<HEADLINE>
IRL POINTS LEADER BUDDY LAZIER TESTING LIMITS AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, it will be damp and 51 degrees and the wind will be
blowing from the north when Buddy Lazier attempts to clinch his
first Indy Racing League driver's championship at Texas Motor
Speedway next month.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, it usually rains any time an IRL race is booked
at TMS, site of the season-ending Excite 500.
</P>
<P>
   So, the sunny and hot and dry conditions under which Lazier and
his Hemelgarn Racing crew labored on Monday at TMS might render all
data collected useless on Oct. 15. But that is the point _ there
are 32 days to go before Lazier, Scott Goodyear and Eddie Cheever
Jr. race for the championship and a $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Time to go testing, and send a subtle message or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing about testing,'' said Lazier, who finally exited
his No. 91 Delta Faucet Dallara/Aurora with a sunburn around his
eyes and nose, and a top speed of approximately 211 mph. ``You'll
hear numbers that are put up, and the numbers that we ran today are
honest, fair numbers. In fact, we'll come back and run faster than
what we ran today next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of gamesmanship and strategy going on here, but
we don't really partake in that. We focus on improving our package
every time we test.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time winner this season, Lazier has built a 38-point lead
over Goodyear and a 41-point advantage over Cheever heading into
qualifying on Oct. 14. Lazier needs a 13th-place finish to clinch
the Indy Racing Northern Light Series title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost ran a full-race distance,'' said Lazier, a
32-year-old resident of Vail, Colo. ``Ran almost 200 laps, in
different segments. Ran almost two mph faster than we ran without a
draft \Rin June\S. And it isn't our updated engine, so we feel like
we made some good gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to retest our spring combination, our shocks. We
realize that this is probably not the temperature we're going to
have four weeks from now, and so this was basically a generic test,
in that we were testing everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Included were the recently repatched portions of Turn 4 and Turn
1 of the 1.5-mile quadoval. Recall that Turn 4 drew the ire of some
IRL drivers during the Casino Magic 500 in mid-June, when a bump at
the bottom of the 24-degree banking upset handling of the
low-slung, open-wheel cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has clearly gotten better,'' said Lazier, referring to the
big black patches in Turn 4 and a lengthy repair between Turns 1
and 2 that sits out of the preferred racing groove. Together, they
present an ugly racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't count 'em, but you can tell there's a large number of
patches,'' Lazier said. ``Turn 4, you still have a little bump
there, and a dip, but it's nothing compared to what we had last
time we raced. And they really smoothed out a couple of the
critical areas. With the improved racing surface, I think it could
be even a closer race now.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be some race, considering that Scott Sharp's victory
over Robby McGehee in the Casino Magic 500 was by 0.059 seconds,
the closest finish in series history and perhaps the greatest
side-by-side race ever.
</P>
<P>
   Lazier previously has raced side-by-side at TMS, logging two
electrifying laps alongside Tony Stewart in the inaugural True
Value 500 night race at TMS in June 1997. Lazier, in fact, started
on the pole here in June en route to a seventh-place result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've led here. But we haven't won here,'' said Lazier, an IRL
original who shared the 1996 Indianapolis 500 victory with affable
team owner Ron Hemelgarn. ``Fact is, we haven't even had a podium
finish here. I really love the racetrack and do have a lot of miles
here, so it's a bit of a frustration for me. It's been like a
thorn. I don't understand why ... I think we have everything that
it takes to have a podium finish and maybe contend for a victory.
And it'd be great to win the championship, and win the last race.
That would be spectacular. There's no reason why we can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, time to go testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our last test here,'' Lazier said. ``But we will test
next week in Kentucky \Rfor Firestone\S, and then we're going to be
down for about three weeks. Normally, you appreciate the time off,
but it really isn't time off. Because we'll be working on all kinds
of stuff on the race car.''
</P>
<P>
   And sending another subtle message or two.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON...
Andretti says CART's limits not enough
Following up on a promise made by interim president/CEO Bobby
Rahal, CART officials have taken the first steps to reduce the warp
speeds of the series' turbocharged open-wheel race cars.
</P>
<P>
   An interim engine formula for the next two seasons was announced
Sunday by Hal Whiteford, president of operations for the
Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Series. Whiteford said engine
suppliers Ford, Honda, Toyota and Mercedes-Benz will reduce maximum
intake manifold (or turbo) pressure from 40 to 37 inches in 2001
and to 34 inches in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are expected to decrease horsepower from the current
900 to approximately 845 next year and to 775 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Bisco, vice president of Cosworth Racing, was among a
handful of Ford executives hailing a change that is expected to
knock approximately 60 horsepower/5 mph off terminal speed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But former series champion Michael Andretti, who drives a
Ford-powered Lola for Newman/Haas Racing, said the rule does not go
far enough for a facility like Texas Motor Speedway. The 1.5-mile
quadoval in Fort Worth is scheduled to play host to the inaugural
Texas 600K on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   With its 24-degree banked turns, CART cars easily would be
expected to click off trap speeds in the 250 mph range without some
sort of boost reduction. At that speed, any sort of accident could
have tragic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they take 50 horsepower away, the engine manufacturers will
find a way to get that back before the season even starts,'' said
Andretti, CART's winningest active driver. ``The biggest thing they
needed to do was to make a bigger move. If they would have taken
200 horsepower away, the engine manufacturers would have gained 100
of it back by midseason. They also need to come down the same
percentage on downforce. That would promote safer racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reduction they have decided on will not be enough to make
a difference, especially at places like Texas that will be very
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz will not be affected by the rules, as the German
manufacturer announced Saturday it was withdrawing technical
support from CART at season's end. But it is likely that Ilmor
Engineering, which builds the Mercedes-Benz CART V-8 engine and
formerly manufactured the engines badged for Chevrolet, will
continue to supply the powerplants to interested teams for at least
another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driving factor was safety and reducing the high speeds,''
Bisco said. ``The perception was that more power creates more
speed, making it more dangerous. I think if we reduce power in an
amicable way for all manufacturers without putting huge costs on
their plate, bearing in mind that we have a rules freeze for two
years, it's a good thing.''
\Nsubheds:PIT STOPS
\Nsubheds:Petty passes on NHIS Long before NASCAR officials opted
to require carburetor restrictor plates for this weekend's Dura
Lube 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway, Kyle Petty
decided not to return this year to the track where his son, Adam,
was killed May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Petty announced in July that he would relinquish the seat in his
Winston Cup No. 44 Hot Wheels Pontiac to drive Adam's No. 45 Sprint
Chevrolet full time in the Busch Grand National Series beginning in
early September.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty, 19, was killed in a crash in Turn 3 at NHIS during
practice. Kyle Petty skipped the Winston Cup series' Jiffy Lube 300
at Loudon, N.H., on July 9, an event run two days after Cup regular
Kenny Irwin Jr., 30, died of injuries suffered in a crash in Turn
3, near where Adam was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle said the decision to stay away was a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it is,'' Petty said. ``I'm going to be honest
and tell you that when I heard the news from Kenny's accident, I
was devastated. I could not believe something transpired like that
again. I thank God I wasn't there ... same place, same time of day;
it was too close to home for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to not have to go there this year and let a year's
worth of time pass, I think it will be easier on myself and my
family.'' \Nsubheds:Gossage to talk CART Eddie Gossage is preparing
to attend his first CART promoter's meetings in Chicago on Tuesday
and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage, the executive vice president and general manager of
Texas Motor Speedway, said he will take notes as the speedway staff
begins integrating the Texas 600K into its 2001 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go and hear what some tracks do that works well, and
what didn't work,'' Gossage said. ``It's good to get together with
other promoters and listen, and I plan to do a whole lot of
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gossage said he does not anticipate the first tests
by any CART teams here until December. Gossage said the 1.5-mile
TMS quadoval is booked every day in September and October, and all
but two days in November. \Nsubheds:Indy F1 a sellout Ticket sales
indicate that the inaugural SAP United States Grand Prix at
Indianapolis, the first Formula One race in the United States since
1991, already is a box office success.
</P>
<P>
   All race-day tickets, reserved and general admission, for the
event at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on Sept. 24 are sold out.
General admission tickets are available for practice Sept. 22 and
qualifications on Sept. 23. But those tickets must be purchased at
the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Single-day general admission tickets are available for $10 on
Sept. 22 and $20 for Sept. 23. \Nsubheds:Last laps Indy Racing
League regular Al Unser Jr. is scheduled for a test, and a news
conference, at Texas Motor Speedway on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte's 158-point lead over Dale Earnhardt
for the Winston Cup championship is the largest of the season, and
greater than the difference between a first and 43rd-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series is scheduled to run at
venerable Darlington Raceway on May 12, 2001. It will be the first
time the series has competed at NASCAR's oldest speedway.
\Nsubheds:The last word ``Any place is a scary place with a stuck
throttle.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dale Jarrett, reigning Winston Cup champion, en route to New
Hampshire
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
