<HEADLINE>
COLORADO COACH BARNETT SHOULD SAVE COACHING TRICKS FOR HUSKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Colorado coach Barnett should save coaching tricks for Huskies 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wily veteran that he is, Colorado coach Gary Barnett provided a
clinic in crisis control this week by blasting Big 12 officials for
force-feeding his beleaguered Buffaloes a ``brutal'' start to the
conference schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Colorado won't begin its three-week march
through league heavyweights Kansas State, Texas A&AMP;M and Texas until
Sept. 30. Never mind that the 2000 schedule was approved in 1997 by
league athletic directors, including the one at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   From Barnett's perspective, this was the perfect time to sound
off for one simple reason: It shifted the focus away from his 0-2
team. Somewhere, Jimmy Johnson _ master of the created controversy
_ must be smiling about Barnett's ploy to shine the spotlight in a
different direction while circling the wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Nice try, Gary.
</P>
<P>
   But we're more interested in how you plan to avoid posting the
first 0-3 start to a Colorado football season since 1986. And we
find it deliciously ironic that your team has reached a crossroads
moment to coincide with Saturday's game against No. 9 Washington in
Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (2-0), lest anyone forget, are coached by Rick
Neuheisel, the man who preceded Barnett at Colorado. Neuheisel's
unexpected departure after the 1998 season, along with his verbal
volleys at school administrators on his way out the door, surely
will be acknowledged by the Folsom Field crowd when the prodigal
coach returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate a lovefest,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   Under different circumstances, Neuheisel's return might be a hot
topic in the Buffs' locker room. But not this week. Barnett's team
faces enough of a challenge in trying to salvage a season that
could gurgle down the drain unless the young Buffs begin receiving
positive feedback. And soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could get worse before it gets better,'' said Barnett, who
lists 18 underclassmen among his 22 starters. ``We can't let these
kids get discouraged ... but when you keep losing tight games, it's
got to take its toll a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, a talented team with a fragile psyche has fallen to
rival Colorado State, 28-24, and to No. 10 Southern California,
17-14. Colorado has disappeared from the Top 25 rankings. The
starting quarterback and kicker were benched Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Players are perplexed, said linebacker Jashon Sykes, because the
Buffs ``don't have 0-2 talent.'' But in college football, you are
only as good as your record. That means Colorado is winless, with
its next four games against teams with a combined mark of 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   To reach a bowl game, much less contend for a Big 12 title, a
confidence-building win is needed Saturday. No one in a Buffs'
uniform wants to risk the emotional scars of carrying an 0-3 mark
into next week's open date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington game is not about Neuheisel. It's a big game
because we're 0-2, and 0-2 is a real strain on everybody,''
linebacker Andy Peeke said. ``It's wearing on us, and you can tell
it's wearing on the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has shown the strain by shifting into crisis-control
mode. He has tried to shift the pre-game focus onto perceived
slights from conference officials rather than ongoing shortcomings
in his players. It's a time-honored coaching trick. But deep down,
Barnett knows the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing two games after you've been in position to win both of
them creates a lot of frustration for the coaches and the
leadership of the team,'' Barnett said. ``We can't afford to get
caught up in any hype about \RNeuheisel's return\S. We need to
concentrate on getting better and taking care of assignments. We're
0-2. And we've got to find a way to turn things around.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ...
\Npcredit:Texas Tech University Defensive end Aaron Hunt has a long
fumble return to his credit this season under Texas Tech's
philosophy to pick it up and run with it.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's scoop mentality makes most of fumbles
Texas Tech defenders have squelched opponent's big plays often
enough that the Red Raiders lead the league in total defense,
allowing just 207.7 yards per game. But coach Mike Leach is just as
pleased by the big plays turned in by a group that is encouraged to
scoop and return loose fumbles rather than merely cover them.
</P>
<P>
   The ``super scooper'' mentality comes from Greg McMackin, Tech's
first-year defensive coordinator. Scoop-and-run drills are part of
Tech's daily practices. And they're paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Through three games, the Red Raiders (3-0) have averaged 39.5
yards on five fumble returns. They've scored two touchdowns. Each
game has featured either a fumble return for a touchdown or a
fumble return in excess of 50 yards. Defensive end Aaron Hunt
returned a fumble 63 yards for a touchdown in a 24-3 victory over
New Mexico on Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's that unusual,'' Leach said of the daily
drills. ``But other teams I've been around tended to be a little
more conservative with it. Greg really stresses it.''
</P>
<P>
   McMackin's scoopers started strong against New Mexico, with Hunt
scoring and cornerback Antwan Alexander adding a 70-yarder.
Linebacker Dorian Pitts scored on a 6-yard return against Utah
State. Hunt had a 2-yard return against North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was cornerback Derrick Briggs' 54-yard return on
what Leach called the craziest play he has ever seen. That was the
deciding play in last week's 13-7 win over North Texas, when free
safety Kevin Curtis popped the ball loose from Eagles receiver
LaDarrin McLane at the Tech 12-yard line after a 50-yard
catch-and-run in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The ball rolled to the 2, where Briggs picked it up and returned
it 54 yards before falling to the turf with 1:44 remaining. In all,
the play covered 114 yards _ 60 in one direction, 54 in the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one hell of a play,'' Leach said. ``Kevin Curtis did
everything you ever coach, teach, preach and beg a player to do
about not quitting on a play and giving second effort. Then, he
pokes it loose and, for a couple of seconds there, I thought
Derrick had a shot to score.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, that's been a recurring feeling about Tech
defenders.
\Nsubheds:QUICK HITS Mission: Threepeat Iowa State quarterback Sage
Rosenfels, a fifth-year senior, said Saturday's game at Iowa holds
special significance for members of his class. Those seniors have a
chance to become the first group of Cyclones in two decades to post
a winning record in their careers against their in-state rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (2-0) has won the past two games between the schools.
Before that, Iowa (0-2) won 15 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean a lot to us if we could finish 3-2 against
them,'' Rosenfels said. ``Our seniors have talked to the
out-of-state guys to ask them to really step it up this week and
treat it like it's the biggest rivalry game they can imagine to
help us out.'' \Nsubheds:Comforting words Texas quarterback Chris
Simms phoned his father's hospital room Sunday morning to wish him
a speedy recovery from an emergency appendectomy. In the process,
he received an uplift as well.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Simms, a former NFL quarterback and now a CBS television
analyst, advised his son to keep his head up despite being pulled
after the first two series in the Longhorns' 52-10 rout of
Louisiana-Lafayette. Simms, the starter, left with Texas facing a
10-0 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Hang in there and be confident. Everything is
going to be all right,''' Simms said. ``He didn't see the game, so
he didn't have any suggestions for me. But that's OK. I know what I
did wrong. I definitely like his input, but it's not a necessity
for me to get better. I'm fairly smart and can figure things out.''
\Nsubheds:Making the adjustment Texas A&AMP;M fullback Ja'Mar Toombs,
the team's leading rusher in 1999, has carried 13 times for 23
yards (1.8 average) this season. As a means of comparison, four
other A&AMP;M backs had 29 or more yards in last week's 51-3 victory
over Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   But coaches said they are more satisfied with Toombs' play now
than a year ago because he has improved his blocking and is
becoming a more well-rounded back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing what most fullbacks do. They don't make a lot of
headlines,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``He's fit into that role,
and we've been pleased with him. He's blocked better and he's in
better shape. He made a couple of key blocks in that \RWyoming\S
game.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Inside the numbers Working overtime Nebraska's 27-24
victory over Notre Dame last week boosted the Big 12's career mark
to 12-11 in overtime games since the extra sessions were approved
for the 1996 season. A breakdown: TEAM OVERTIME RECORD Nebraska 3-0
Missouri 3-2 Texas A&AMP;M 2-0 Oklahoma 1-0 Kansas 1-0 Colorado 1-1
Oklahoma State 1-3 Texas 0-1 Kansas State 0-1 Iowa State 0-1 Baylor
0-2 Texas Tech 0-0
\Nsubheds:BURCH's PICKS Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against the
line) this week's Big 12 games:
</P>
<P>
   Texas at Stanford (plus 13). Pick: Stanford. Longhorns will have
to earn this one against revenge-minded Cardinal to remain
undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   UT-El Paso (plus 24 1/2) at Texas A&AMP;M. Pick: A&AMP;M. Aggies roll
another big number while building confidence in new, improved
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana-Lafayette (plus 32) at Texas Tech. Pick: Tech. Tech's
on-again, off-again offense is due for another ``on'' week.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota at Baylor (plus 8 1/2). Pick: Minnesota. Texas heat
will bother the Gophers, but not as much as Minnesota's superior
talent bothers Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Texas State at Oklahoma State (no line). Pick:
Oklahoma State. Cowboys ride roughshod over outmanned opponent from
Division I-AA.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (plus 3 1/2) at Colorado. Pick: Washington. Rick
Neuheisel makes his former Colorado players the best 0-3 team in
college football.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State at Missouri (plus 11). Pick: Michigan State.
Tigers have fallen and they can't get up.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama-Birmingham (plus 9 1/2) at Kansas. Pick: Kansas. Reeling
Jayhawks circle the wagons, get much-needed victory.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State at Iowa (plus 2 1/2). Pick: Iowa. Sorry, Cyclones.
There will be no ``threepeat'' in this heated rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Ball State (plus 45) at Kansas State. Pick: Kansas State.
Wildcats consume another cupcake while padding stats until the
conference campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 7-2. Season record: 14-7.
nn
</P>
