u p BC-NY-PRIMARY-FORBES-NYT     09-14 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-FORBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY SWITCHER'S FUTURE IS IN DOUBT AFTER PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
  By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLPORT, N.Y. _ When Rep. Michael Forbes of Long Island
switched from Republican to Democrat last year, Republicans put him
at the top of their hit list.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't imagine that a 71-year-old former school
librarian and former garden club vice president, a Democrat who
practices pro bono environmental law in her Bellport home, would
knock him off.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as both parties contemplate what appears to be a 39-vote
victory by Regina Seltzer, a former Brookhaven councilwoman, in
Tuesday's Democratic primary, it is unclear who defeated him: the
Republicans or the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Final results may not be available for several days. But if the
vote holds up _ and Forbes voiced no hope that it would not _ the
result could help the Republicans take back a critical seat in the
fight for control of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   A glum Forbes said Wednesday that a huge Republican effort to
support Seltzer had made the difference in the race. And even many
people who praised Seltzer were skeptical of her chances of
defeating the Republican candidate, Felix J. Grucci Jr., supervisor
of the town of Brookhaven. Grucci also has the support of the
Conservative, Independence and Right to Life parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's excellent,'' said Desmond M. Ryan, a veteran lobbyist
and executive director of the Association for a Better Long Island,
a developers' lobby. ``She's got a background. She's got a history.
She comes across like everybody's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we won't send a grandmother to Washington, but
it's rather difficult for a 71-year-old woman to effectively
conduct a door-to-door campaign against a well-financed, formidably
entrenched opponent.'' He also faulted Forbes for ignoring the
importance of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   In a historically quirky district where Republicans outnumber
Democrats almost two to one, the New York State Republican
Committee fought long and hard against their former congressman.
They sent out eight pieces of glossy campaign literature,
criticizing Forbes' anti-abortion stance and asking voters, among
other things, ``Should buyers at gun shows have to pass a criminal
background check? Congressman Mike Forbes doesn't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes did not release figures on his primary campaign spending.
Seltzer, who keeps her law books in the garage with the Ford Escort
so they don't get moldy in her basement office, spent $40,000 in
campaign contributions and nothing from her own funds, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But without the financial aid she got from the opposing party in
the primary, Seltzer will have an uphill battle in November,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   In a Washington press conference , Forbes said that while he
would ask for a recount, he was not optimistic about its results.
He blamed ``venomous'' Republicans for beating him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a campaign against Michael Forbes, not for Regina
Seltzer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Republicans considered the primary a grudge
match, and a lesson for defectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tempted to ask for a recount, because we were so looking
forward to beating Mike Forbes,'' said Tom Davis, chairman of the
National Republican Congressional Committee. ``But New York
Democrats beat us to it, and in the process destroyed Democrats'
hopes for a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allen, spokesman for the New York State Republican
Committee, said that other Republican groups had organized phone
calls to get out the vote against Forbes, and that his group was
pleased with the results of their mailings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we devoted a substantial amount of resources to assure
that all the families out in Suffolk County knew what kind of
congressman they had,'' said Allen, who would not say how many
pieces of mail were sent to Democrats, or the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Scarrow, a professor of political science at the SUNY
campus in Stonybrook, estimated that the party had spent $100,000
to beat Forbes. He personally received five pieces of anti-Forbes
mail and two or three phone calls about the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the Republicans should be very happy,'' Scarrow said.
``I guess they think Seltzer would be a much easier target for
Grucci than would be Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans accused Forbes of having the same positions on
gun control and abortion and something else as their own candidate,
Grucci. But of course that was beside the point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
