<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BE STARS CENTER MIKE MODANO IS TO BE LUCKIEST GUY AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Today, I'm Mike Modano. Say hello to the luckiest
guy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   I'm 30 years old and single. I'm Hollywood-handsome, I'm rich
and I play hockey for the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   I own that town.
</P>
<P>
   I'm at the top of my game, ranked among the top five players in
the NHL by ``The Hockey News'' recently, and there are those out
there who tell me I'm the best.
</P>
<P>
   They might be right.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't the name of Joe Namath's autobiography, ``I Can't Wait
Until Tomorrow 'Cause I Get Better Looking Every Day?'' Wish I'd
thought of that first.
</P>
<P>
   Today will put a wrap on a great week of training camp. I didn't
miss a day on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   I roll out of the sack in my three-bedroom condo around 8:30
every morning and walk over to the window. The mountains are right
there, almost close enough to reach out and touch, soaring into the
sky like green giants.
</P>
<P>
   The air is as cool and crisp as a fresh apple. The September sun
is so blindingly bright, I'm tempted to shave with my shades on.
</P>
<P>
   Except ... I look in the mirror and I kind of like it when I
don't shave for a day or two. Looks, you know, rugged. Maybe later,
after practice, I'll try the razor. Then again, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   My roommates are Shaun Van Allen, a new center we just signed in
the off-season, and a rookie, Ryan Christie. I've got closer
friends on the team, guys such as Grant Marshall and Brett Hull,
but this is the organization's way of helping everyone get closer,
and Shaun and Ryan are good guys.
</P>
<P>
   That's kind of what camp here is all about; guys hanging around
each other all the time, getting to know each other, eating three
meals a day together, practicing together, playing together a
little bit. I like the time we spend here, especially this year
because they've let the veterans ease up a little, do a little less
scrimmaging, but still work off-ice on conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   After practice _ they only get us three hours a day _ we'll walk
into town for lunch, then head to the golf course. Golf is so great
here. The courses are in terrific shape, everything's so green and
the weather's perfect. That you can hit the ball a mile doesn't
bother me, either.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I can play that game a little bit, too. Another putt drops
here or there, I'm a scratch golfer. I might even try out that
celebrity tour when I quit playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, I'm the luckiest guy going.
</P>
<P>
   People tell me I'm showing a lot more maturity and leadership
qualities. That worries me a little bit. All of a sudden 30 comes
and everybody expects you to be this kind of mentor and all that.
I'm not a rah-rah guy. I just try to keep guys loose and having
fun, especially the young kids.
</P>
<P>
   There's so much pressure and expectations on those guys, and I
was in the same boat not so long ago. I just try to relate to them
and show them you can play in the NHL and still have fun.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything I'm better at than hockey, it's having fun.
When the finals were over last season and we'd lost to New Jersey
in six games, I just cut loose. Sensibly, of course.
</P>
<P>
   July was basically a travel month. I hit Cabo, one of my
favorite hangouts in all the world. I love the mountains, but at
heart, I'm a beach bum.
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of trips to New York with my buddies,
because that's such a fun place to party.
</P>
<P>
   In Vegas, I went to a party that Mavs owner Mark Cuban was
throwing for one of his friends. He'd hired John Cougar Mellencamp
to play in this guy's back yard. How cool was that?
</P>
<P>
   My love life? Not much to tell, really. No, I mean it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, I date a little now and then, play the field, but
there's nothing really hot going romance-wise. That part of my life
is at a stale point right now and that's OK with me.
</P>
<P>
   Honest.
</P>
<P>
   I've found when I get serious in a relationship, I kind of lose
my focus on hockey. So, I've told myself I've got four more years
on my current contract, and I want to have the four best years I
can possibly have.
</P>
<P>
   I really do want to be the best. I'd love to be the league's
MVP. Who knows, if I can play as well all season as I was at the
end of last season, the honors will come.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since a team went to the finals three
years in a row. We can do it and we can win it again.
</P>
<P>
   I shake my head every day at the way my life has turned out. I
would have never thought that my game or my popularity would have
ever gotten to this point.
</P>
<P>
   You don't think about those things when you're 18, 19. You just
want to go and play and enjoy the game, but things happen; the team
plays well and good things start coming your way off-ice, too.
</P>
<P>
   Money. Fame. Women. Everything.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky me.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
