<HEADLINE>
AS YANKS BEAT JAYS, CLEMENS STAKES CLAIM AS THEIR TOP STARTER IN
OCTOBER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unless the Yankees experience a monumental collapse
this month, they will play their first postseason game in 19 days.
Manager Joe Torre has a feel for what his starting lineup will look
like that night. Bernie Williams should be healthy, Chuck Knoblauch
should be easing back at second base and Jose Canseco or Glenallen
Hill could start at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a slight mystery about who will pitch Game 1 of a
potential Division Series, but Roger Clemens continues to make his
case. Clemens tamed and tormented his former team in steering the
Yankees past the Blue Jays, 3-2, on Wednesday night at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had a robust fastball, precise control and growing
confidence as he surrendered eight hits in seven innings and won
his ninth straight decision. Clemens is 9-0 with a 2.21 earned run
average since being activated from the disabled list on July 2. He
has not lost since the Mets battered him on June 9, the night of
the Mike Piazza beaning incident.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Torre said the Yankees would study the matchups and then
determine how to align the starters, he said it would be very
surprising if Clemens were not the No. 1 starter in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``For certain, he's been the most consistent pitcher for us
since the All-Star break,'' Torre said. ``He's been the most
overpowering. He's been everything El Duque has been for the last
year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez led the Yankees with 17 victories last season and
started the first game in all three rounds of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Torre will not make it official until he needs to,
Clemens is also perfectly on target to start the first postseason
game on Oct. 3. Clemens is scheduled to start on Sept. 18, Sept. 23
and Sept. 28 in the regular season and would then have his normal
four days of rest for Game 1 of the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays strung together three straight hits to start the
eighth, ending Clemens' night. Clemens received a thunderous
standing ovation as he sauntered back to the dugout. The cheers
increased as Clemens crossed the foul line and lifted his black
glove to the 29,083 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Yankees were in a tense spot with the potential tying
runs on first and second. Jeff Nelson whiffed Alex Gonzalez and
handed the baseball to Mariano Rivera. After Dave Martinez's bloop
single loaded the bases, Rivera induced Carlos Delgado, the triple
crown threat, to pop to catcher Jorge Posada in foul territory.
Rivera then retired Brad Fullmer on a liner to second. Rivera gave
up a run in the ninth, but left runners on first and third by
getting Gonzalez on a flyout for his 34th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
