<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TO PICK UP OPTION ON HANSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There are questions about where the Los Angeles
Dodgers payroll will stand next season, whether they'll be able to
afford re-signing Darren Dreifort, extending the contract of Chan
Ho Park and signing another free-agent pitcher to round out the
staff.
</P>
<P>
   There's an issue in the bullpen with right-hander Mike Fetters,
eligible for free agency, as is catcher Chad Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   But such should not be the scenario with pinch-hitter Dave
Hansen, who has given the Dodgers one of the game's
most-sought-after yet underrated weapons _ left-handed power off
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, making $500,000 this season, has a club option for 2001
that would play him $550,000. The Dodgers plan to pick that up,
team officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan would be to come back, stay here,'' Hansen said. ``I
like it here. This is my home, a great place to play. I love all
the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen is the most dangerous pinch-hitter in baseball. He set a
major-league record with his seventh pinch-hit homer of the season
Tuesday and he's been the most productive pinch-hitter in baseball
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen is batting .288 with eight homers and 26 RBI in 2000.
Seven of his homers (and six of his pinch-hit homers) have either
tied the score or given the Dodgers the lead. He also has 14 RBI
and is batting .271 as a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's 13 career pinch-hit homers are second to John Vander
Wal among active players and eighth all-time. Cliff Johnson's 20 is
the record.
</P>
<P>
   But an offseason squabble nearly kept him from another season
with the club. Hansen returned from Japan to play with the Dodgers
in 1999, but rather than pick up his club option for 2000, the
Dodgers renegotiated a contract that paid him less than the club
option.
</P>
<P>
   There was also discussion at the end of spring training about
not keeping Hansen on the roster so the Dodgers could carry three
shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven pinch-hit home runs in one season, that's special,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``There was a lot of
conversation in the offseason. People in the organization didn't
want to bring him back. I said we have to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Dodgers center fielder Tom Goodwin extended
his hitting streak to a career-high 14 games with a single to right
on the game's first pitch. . . . Catcher Angel Pena and
right-handers Al Reyes and Mike Judd are expected to join the
Dodgers today from the minor leagues. . . . The Dodgers are poised
to sign a deal to have their Double-A affiliate in Jacksonville,
Fla., after a 24-year relationship with San Antonio of the Texas
League. . . . Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros reached the 100-RBI
mark for the fifth time in his career with a sacrifice fly on
Tuesday. . . . Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek returned to the
lineup after missing one game with a bruised right thumb.
</P>
</TEXT>
