<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-MEMORIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F. ARCHITECTS WIN CONTEST FOR MLK MEMORIAL  &HT;     By CHUCK SQUATRIGLIA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A parklike memorial to Martin Luther King Jr. to
be built in Washington, D.C., will include ``a stone of hope,'' a
winding stream and other features illustrating the metaphors the
slain civil rights leader used in his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial was designed by ROMA Design Group of San Francisco.
The firm bested 870 others Wednesday in an international
competition to design the memorial, which will add King to the
American heroes memorialized on the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, the first accorded a private citizen, is slated
for a four-acre site near the Lincoln Memorial, where King
delivered his ``I Have a Dream'' speech in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited to have the opportunity to work on such an
important project,'' said Boris Dramov, ROMA Design Group
president.
</P>
<P>
   King's widow, Coretta Scott King, attended Wednesday's unveiling
of the winning design in Washington and called it ``uniquely
beautiful and meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   ROMA's design calls for a crescent-shaped memorial park hugging
the shore of the Tidal Basin, a pool formed by the Potomac River. A
20-foot-high profile of King, carved in stone, will gaze toward the
Jefferson Memorial from the center of a plaza lined with oak, pine,
cherry and magnolia trees.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will feature a path lined with niches commemorating
other heroes of the civil rights movement, including Medgar Evers
and four young girls killed in the 1963 firebombing of a church in
Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will enter through two gigantic opposing stones
engraved with excerpts from a speech King delivered in 1963: ``With
this faith, we will be able to hew out of the mountain of despair a
stone of hope. Let justice roll down like waters and righteousness
like a mighty stream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to incorporate into the design notable references
from Dr. King's speeches such as the `mountain of despair' and the
`stone of hope,' '' Dramov said.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of 11 architects, landscape designers and artists from
around the world reviewed entries from 34 countries before
selecting three finalists earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ROMA's design best ``captured the essence'' of King, his message
and the movement he led, said Adrian L. Wallace, president of the
board of the Martin Luther King Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an awesome design,'' Wallace said. ``It is more of an
experience than a memorial. We believe it will speak to the viewer
on many different levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The design must be approved by the National Capital Planning
Commission, the National Capital Memorial Commission and the
Commission of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Construction could begin within three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Martin Luther King Memorial Project Foundation has been
pushing 16 years for a memorial. It took 12 years for the
organization to get Congress to approve the memorial, which was
originally slated for a site at Constitution Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial's cost has not been determined, and its supporters
are launching an aggressive push for corporate and private
donations. Fashion designer Tommy Hilfiger has promised at least $5
million to the project.
</P>
<P>
   ROMA Design Group was recently selected to renovate the San
Francisco Ferry Building. The firm also designed the Embarcadero
Promenade in San Francisco and the Third Street Promenade in Santa
Monica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
