A3908 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-NADER-RIGHTS-SFCHRON &LR;      09-14 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NADER-RIGHTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WOMEN, GAYS SAY NADER NOT DEFENDING THEIR RIGHTS  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With some polls showing the presidential race a
dead heat between Democrat Al Gore and Republican George Bush,
women's and gay rights organizations are more aggressively
targeting a man who could make the crucial difference in the
election _ Green Party candidate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week with The Chronicle, Patricia Ireland,
president of the National Organization for Women, called Nader
``ill-informed about abortion rights,'' and noted his 10-page
candidacy statement ``did not mention any explicitly feminist
issues, not birth control or abortion ... and not violence against
women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just an indifference,'' said Ireland in comments
mirrored in recent mailings by NOW, which has also criticized
Nader's handling of gay and lesbian issues. ``It's an ignorance
that's almost willful.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months before the election, the increasingly contentious
conversation over Nader's liberal credentials comes as the consumer
advocate returns for stumping in California whose 54 electoral
votes are crucial to Gore's campaign for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Nader is scheduled to speak at San Francisco State University
Thursday afternoon, then hold a press conference at Silicon
Valley's Cisco Systems Inc., a company in which he holds at least
$1 million in stock. He is also planning an early evening speech at
San Jose State University.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Amato, the longtime activist who heads Nader's
presidential campaign, says the criticism is unjust and that it
reflects how groups that traditionally back major political parties
are getting nervous about Nader's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're seeing massive turnouts for Ralph on the road, like
the 10,000 people who showed up in Portland, Ore.,'' said Amato.
``Unlike the other two candidates, (this) is a candidate who's
talking about the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Nader's threat appears to be diminishing in
California, with the most recent California Field Poll saying his
support is at 4 percent, down from 7 percent. National polls
routinely put Nader's support at around 3 to 4 percent, and the
race between Bush and Gore at a virtual tie.
</P>
<P>
   While the candidate has emphasized consumer issues, trade and
labor in his campaign, Nader _ in a recent interview with The
Chronicle, argued that there is no real difference between
Republicans and Democrats on the issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference, other than rhetoric?'' he said. ``You
know how many Republicans are telling me it's red meat for their
right wing? They don't want to destroy their party. It's not going
to happen,'' he said of the commonly expressed Democratic belief
that Bush could pick Supreme Court justices who would overturn Roe
vs. Wade. ``I don't buy any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader argued that neither Bush nor Gore would make much of a
difference in protecting a woman's right to choose. ``(It's) all
rhetoric. The pro-choice people in this country do not understand
their power, because it's never been challenged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments infuriate Ireland, who said they misrepresent the
grave danger posed to women's rights in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in Texas, Gov. Bush has signed 18 or 19 restrictive
laws'' affecting reproductive rights and funding, Ireland said.
``It would be one thing to say (Nader) hasn't worked on the issues;
it's another thing to be talking about issues you don't know
anything about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some gay rights advocates are also increasingly vocal about
Nader's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, the
nation's largest gay, lesbian and transgender rights organization,
said the pivotal role Nader could play is one reason why he reminds
gay voters that Nader _ asked his position on abortion and gay
rights in 1996 _ said he wasn't interested in ``gonadal politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we're asked about it, we tell people a vote for Nader
is a vote for Bush,'' said Smith, whose organization endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, the candidate's campaign manager, said she agrees with
Nader that Republicans would not overturn Roe vs. Wade, but argued
that Nader's credentials include ``a four-decade record of reform
and support of issues that women hold near and dear to their
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As consumers, as taxpayers, as shareholders, as voters ...
he's been out there fighting for women,'' she said, adding that
Nader's Web site  &UR; (www.votenader.org)  &LR; details his support for
NOW's agenda. And unlike Gore and Bush, she adds, Nader chose a
woman to be his running mate _ Native American activist Winona
LaDuke.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing that voters, by a 2-to-1 ratio, support the
entry of Nader and Reform candidate Pat Buchanan in the
presidential debates, Nader's California press spokesman, Ross
Mirkarimi, said Nader's best chance of getting his message across
may be if Americans demand his participation so they can hear from
him on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't agree with Ralph, so be it,'' he said. ``The
point is, don't buy into this most anti-democratic behavior. Let
Gore be the man he says he is and debate Ralph Nader,'' Mirkarimi
said. ``It's time to demystify the fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
