<HEADLINE>
KINGS GET TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings flew to Phoenix after
Wednesday's practice and will open the 2000 exhibition season with
a matinee this morning against the Coyotes at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The early game is designed to get kids hooked on hockey, a
promotion the Kings hope to use next season at the Staples Center.
For now, their own youngsters have them excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too early to point out players in particular,'' coach
Andy Murray said. ``But we have stepped up our training camp, made
it much harder, and the players have responded. As a result, we
will use more players than usual in our first exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Against Phoenix, the Kings are expected to hold out veteran
forwards Luc Robitaille, Bryan Smolinski, Glen Murray, Stu Grimson
and Bob Corkum; defensemen Mattias Norstrom, Mathieu Schneider and
Aki Berg and goaltender Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum and Schneider experienced strained hip muscles earlier
this week and did not make the trip. Ian Laperriere and Craig
Johnson also remained in Los Angeles, but they will play Sunday
against the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   With holdout Jozef Stumpel in Slovakia, the Kings will use a
first line of Brad Chartrand, Ziggy Palffy and newcomer Tomas
Vlasak.
</P>
<P>
   Vlasak, 25, was first drafted by the Kings in 1993, but he
played five years in his native Czech Republic and two in Finland.
During the past two seasons, he has scored 54 and 48 goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will go with speed on the second line of Nelson
Emerson, Steven Reinprecht and Jason Blake. If Stumpel returns by
the beginning of the season, Smolinski will play center, with
Emerson and Murray on the wings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Stumpel signed a one-month contract with Bratislava of
the Czech League, putting the Kings' negotiations on the clock. If
Stumpel plays there after the beginning of the NHL regular season,
there is a good chance he could miss the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays with them after the season starts, even if he
signs, he would have to clear waivers and that isn't going to
happen,'' Kings GM Dave Taylor said. ``It is a situation we had
with Aki Berg (during the 1998-99 season).''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will play two exhibition games at the Staples Center:
this Sunday against the Mighty Ducks and Sept. 26 against Phoenix.
They also play San Jose in Bakersfield on Sept. 23 and Colorado
Sept. 30 in Las Vegas. All games will be broadcast on KRLA-AM
(1110). The Sept. 26 game vs. the Coyotes will be televised on Fox
Sports Net.!dlim!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
