<HEADLINE>
L.A. TIMES ABANDONS ITS COMMUNITY NEWS OPERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Acknowledging it failed to attract readers and
advertisers and lost money on the enterprise, the Los Angeles Times
on Wednesday abandoned its community news operation, scuttling 14
Our Times sections and laying off 125 workers, mostly journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Times also eliminated 45 advertising department
jobs from the main newspaper, bringing the total number of job cuts
in one day to 170. It was not immediately clear what prompted the
ad department cuts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a wide-ranging retreat on the local news front and the
latest of several changes since the paper was acquired by Tribune
Co. of Chicago this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Our Times editions ceasing publication covered a huge chunk
of Southern California, from West Ventura County to San Juan
Capistrano in South Orange County. Editions in Santa Clarita,
Sherman Oaks and Simi Valley were closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still cover the major local stories, but we'll leave
the block-by-block coverage of neighborhoods to others,'' said
Editor John S. Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the move as playing to the paper's strength --
coverage of the Southern California region, nation and world. No
additional editorial cuts are planned at this time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll declined to say how much money the community news
operation lost but said the amount was substantial. The editions
were implemented two years ago by former Times Mirror Co. chief
Mark Willes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have practiced community journalism myself and I know it is
difficult to do and I have questioned openly whether a paper on the
scale of the Los Angeles Times can also practice a form of
journalism that deals with communities block by block,'' Carroll
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said extensive changes are planned for the local news section
of the Times in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher John Puerner said the local news cutback was made for
both journalistic and economic reasons. ``Our Times sections were a
two-year effort in community news that was unable to attract the
readership and advertising necessary to make them financially
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Puerner, ``We want to focus on what we do best, which is
covering big regional stories.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of rumors of Our Times' demise, staffers learned
their fate during morning meetings with human resources officials.
They were given until 5 p.m. Wednesday to clean out their desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any idea,'' former Ventura County Our Times
reporter Stacy Brown, an Encino resident, said of the cuts. He said
it was an uncomfortable session and that some workers were upset
that senior editorial department managers were not present.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in a hurry to get out. She didn't want to see us,''
Brown said of the personnel department executive who broke the
news. ``She told us we were no longer needed and our positions were
eliminated as of today. I thought that was kind of bush league, but
what can you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown worked at the company for two years and said his severance
is four weeks' pay plus 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Times will continue to publish the Burbank Leader, Foothill
Leader and Glendale New Press, formerly independent papers that are
operated by the company's community news division. In addition, the
company will continue to publish a six-day-a-week Inland Valley
section and weekly sections in the San Gabriel Valley, South Bay
and Westside areas.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tribune Co. bought the paper, several key executives
have departed or been reassigned and the newspaper has had to
restate its circulation, lowering the average by some 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   It also recently abandoned a deal with the Spanish-language
newspaper La Opinion whereby readers could buy both at a discounted
price after questions about the practice were raised by the Audit
Bureau of Circulations. The Times attributed a gain of 69,559 in
circulation with that deal, according to an earlier filing.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also recently demoted three editors with the
hiring of Dean Baquet, former national editor at The New York
Times, as the paper's managing editor, the No. 2 job in the
newsroom. Baquet formerly worked for the Chicago Tribune. The Times
also replaced the top two editors in its Southern California Living
section.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper industry analyst John Morton noted that changes such
as the folding of Our Times reflects an effort by parent Tribune to
boost profits. ``I just don't think they have found it economical
to do what they have been doing and this is probably the first step
the Tribune Co. is taking to get profit margins up to a comfortable
level.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
