<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WILL PUNT FOR PLAYING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA has been forced to punt on its first
possession against both Alabama and Fresno State. The results: a
71-yard return for a touchdown by Alabama's Freddie Milons and a
mishandled snap by Nate Fikse that handed Fresno State the ball on
the 6-yard line, leading to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Another punt should have ended disastrously, but Fresno State's
Charles Smith, after returning the ball 75 yards, was tripped by a
teammate with no Bruins in sight at the UCLA 7-yard line. The
Bruins' defense rescued them by stopping Fresno State on downs.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, the Bruins, who hadn't allowed a punt return for
a touchdown since Bob Toledo's first game as head coach _ by
Tennessee's Terry Fair in 1996 _ should have given up two in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   If the punt team is in need of a good swift kick, Toledo is
happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   The fullbacks, tight ends and linebackers who comprise most of
the punt team will see their playing time cut on offense and
defense if they don't begin performing better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't play as much on offense and defense if they can't
give me better effort on the punt team,'' said Toledo, no doubt
aware that Michigan punt returner Ronald Bellamy is averaging 14.0
yards per return this season, with a long of 48 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hot, hot, hot: When Michigan comes out to California, the
last thing it figured to have to worry about was the weather. Yet,
the National Weather Service is predicting highs of around 100 in
Pasadena for today and Friday, and Saturday isn't expected to be
much different.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan practiced in much milder conditions Wednesday, with
temperatures in Ann Arbor in the low 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UCLA didn't do any conditioning work Wednesday and
Toledo told the team at the end of practice to begin hydrating
themselves and to get plenty of rest. But there were no plans for
UCLA to wear white jerseys and force Michigan to wear its
heat-absorbing dark blue jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like those baby blue jerseys,'' Toledo said. ``It makes us
look like we're not very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Big House West: A crowd of about 85,000 is expected for
Saturday's game, meaning it could be UCLA's largest home crowd for
a non-USC or Rose Bowl game in school history. The largest was the
1997 Washington game that drew 85,697.
</P>
</TEXT>
