</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY SAYING `GOOD NIGHT,' GEORGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What everyone is missing about the George W. Bush campaign is
that the weird stuff isn't subliminable, it's intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Bush realizes that his only hope for election is to come off as
a guy who will be fun to have around.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know the difference between a billion and a trillion?
Hey, he's one of us!
</P>
<P>
   He forgets that his microphone is live and says a nasty word?
Boy, the guys in the Cabinet meetings are going to razz him
something fierce!
</P>
<P>
   Bush is offering himself as the refreshing antidote to the
overintellectualization of America. Look, I just used a 23-letter
word and put half of my readers to sleep. I almost dozed off
myself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping Americans will decide it would be a hoot to have
a cross between Lucy Ricardo and Gracie Allen running the country.
</P>
<P>
   The roles of Fred and Ethyl Mertz could be played by Madeleine
Albright and Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   BUT I digress. Bush, in playing the ditz card, is on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made of W's vaudevillian verbal pratfalls, but I have
received several items that seem to indicate a move toward
abandoning all the pretentious and nitpicky rules and conventions
of language.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hilltop Mall in Richmond, Kimberly Stigers saw a sign in
front of the Lane Bryant store: ``We sell women sizes 14-26.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that illegal?'' Stigers asks.
</P>
<P>
   On a ``60 Minutes'' segment about education in Gov. Bush's
Texas, W bragged about ``exemplarary'' Texas school tests.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes. Yet in the San Francisco Main Library, where some kind of
contest was in progress, Richard Kales saw this sign: ``Submit your
entrys here.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the Embarcadero Muni station, Kales took out a pen and
fixed a sign that read: ``Take the N Judah to the Giant's game.''
</P>
<P>
   ANONYMOUS caller Old Homeboy says he was watching the Giants on
TV, on KTVU Channel 2, when this message was flashed on the screen:
``If your looking for the news, it's on 36.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for the proper use of ``you're,'' you're
outta luck.
</P>
<P>
   At the Oakland Airport, Paul Giurlanda was struck (figuratively)
by an ad for a new parking lot: ``Park with us once and you will
never park anywhere again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like an offer you can't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   A guy named Larry picked up a bottle of pills for his cat Cleo
at a pharmacy. The label instructions: ``Take two a day until
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Cats have a Dr. Kevorkian?
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Republicans. Anne Cruikshanks attended the
Democratic National Convention as a Louisiana delegate and was
given a packet of buttons to wear with pride, with Louisiana
misspelled.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Anne went to a strategy forum in Rhode Island, where
attendees were given notepads imprinted ``Naval War Colege.''
</P>
<P>
   IN THE NEW spirit of freewheeling plain speech, newspapers make
fun mistakes, too.
</P>
<P>
   The S.F. Examiner has been sold to the Fang family, and the
Fangs are moving the editorial operation into the Fox Warfield
Building at Market and Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   So new security measures have been put in force at the building.
The new rules are posted at the building entrance, and see how many
errors you can spot:
</P>
<P>
   ``Attention to all tenants and clients. Doors are locked after
between 5 P.M. - 8:00 A.M. and all day weekends. Only tenants with
their registered keys can access to the building after hours. All
other client's must contact with the tenant ...''
</P>
<P>
   I count seven mistakes. That's more than I make in an entire
column. Usually.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO sometimes takes itself too seriously, too, but
that can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The Union Square Business Improvement District is holding an
open audition Thursday for Cable Car CASey. The CAS stands for
Clean And Safe.
</P>
<P>
   This delightful character will work the Square, giving
directions, helping old folks cross streets, breaking up
prostitution rings.
</P>
<P>
   The flyer says CASey will, ``with a style and flair that evokes
San Francisco's turn-of-the-century elegance, create a character
that will become a San Francisco icon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I thought that was Willie Brown's job.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE HIMSELF was on the town Tuesday night, he dropped by the
VIP cocktail reception at Frette, the new luxury bed-linen shop on
Geary.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the squeamish of pocketbook, this place. One robe-like
female lounging garment had a price tag of $1,700. And look,
there's the hippest liquid in town _ a quart bottle of scented
ironing water, $20.
</P>
<P>
   George Shultz, with wife Charlotte Mailliard Shultz, obviously
thought the occasion was special. He sent a request to the
three-piece band to play ``Some Enchanted Evening.''
</P>
<P>
   My rule for gauging the VIP-ness of an event is that it is in
inverse proportion to the size of the hors d'oeuvres. Each of
Frette's delicate morsels could easily hide under a postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   City arts czar Stanlee Gatti fell in love with a babe at the
party. It was the 3-week-old child of Summer Tompkins Walker. Gatti
gave the child's cheek a teeny mustache rash, but the wee one
smiled and forgave Uncle Stan.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S UP with public art in the city, by the way?
</P>
<P>
   Gatti says there are no feet, nor any other major public art
projects, on the horizon. It's been Slumpsville for Gatti and his
commission ever since the Board of Supes rejected the proposed
``The Foot'' sculpture for the Embarcadero.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Foot' was a setback,'' Gatti says, ``and so was the vote
to fund the Embarcadero Organ. Those two things undermined the Arts
Commission and the arts community.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody agrees on anything, so everybody gets nothing.
</P>
<P>
   THIS COLUMN was brought to you by the fine folks at Ford and
Firestone _ ``Follow Us! We Know the Shortcuts!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
