<HEADLINE>
FLAME THROWER WRAPS GREAT MEET FOR BAFFERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; DEL MAR, Calif. _ The last order of business at the Del Mar
meeting proved to be a mere formality.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert picked up the rubber stamp and put his name on the
$250,000 Del Mar Futurity again Wednesday, winning California's
biggest 2-year-olds race of the summer for the fifth year in a row,
this time with front-running Flame Thrower and jockey Jerry Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Flame Thrower, the even-money favorite, lost the
lead in midstretch and had to come back along the rail to beat
Street Cry by a head in 1:22 for 7 furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   But the result seemed routine as Baffert became the first
trainer in Del Mar's 64-year history to win the same stakes five
straight years, and capped his fourth consecutive Del Mar training
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also won Wednesday's $77,300 CERF Handicap with Chilukki
and Bailey, and finished the 43-day season with 33 winners, the
most since Farrell Jones' 35 in 1963. Baffert set a Del Mar record
with 13 stakes victories.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had anxious moments during the Futurity. Flame
Thrower, who had barely trailed in winning his first two starts,
had to battle Baffert-trained Arabian Light for the early lead this
time, and their half-mile split was a grueling 44 1/5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they turned for home, I saw 44-and-1 (on the clock), and
I thought, 'Oh, I'm in trouble,' '' Baffert said. ``But this horse
reached down and found something extra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The good ones find a way to win, and this guy did,'' Bailey
said of the winner, a son of Saint Ballado.
</P>
<P>
   Arabian Light held on for third. Glorious Bid, another colt from
Baffert's barn, finished sixth in the field of eight.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up, Street Cry, is trained by Eoin Harty, a former
Baffert assistant. Some thought Baffert would suffer after Harty
left in January to work for Godolphin Racing of Dubai. But Baffert
keeps winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the battle, but we haven't lost the war,'' said Harty,
who's confident Street Cry will have the advantage in longer races.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert compared Flame Thrower to Silver Charm, the 1997
Kentucky Derby winner who was the first of the trainer's five
Futurity champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got guts, you know?'' Baffert said. ``That 'You're not
going to pass me' is what I like about him. You can't really judge
them until they get hooked, and he has the heart to keep running
when he's hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said Flame Thrower, owned by Gary Garber, will use the
Oct. 7 Norfolk Stakes at Santa Anita as his prep for the Nov. 4
Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Victor Espinoza finished with 52 victories and won his
first Del Mar jockey championship by a margin of 20 over Kent
Desormeaux. . . . Bailey's victories with Chilukki and Flame
Thrower were the first at Del Mar in the Hall of Fame jockey's
career. He rode the most famous loser in Del Mar history, 1996
Pacific Classic runner-up Cigar. . . . Pacific Classic winner
Skimming was named Horse of the Meeting in a press-box poll. . . .
Baffert's five consecutive Del Mar Futurity victories did not set a
record for the Southern California circuit. Charlie Whittingham
trained six straight winners of Hollywood Park's Sunset Handicap
(1978-83).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
