<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ TO BE FETED AT FAIR OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; POMONA, Calif. _ The events of a year ago will be on
everybody's minds when the Los Angeles County Fair season begins
with 13 races this afternoon at Fairplex Park.
</P>
<P>
   Leading-rider contenders at the 18-day meet will be competing
for the J.C. Gonzalez Memorial Jockey Award, established after
Gonzalez was killed in a racetrack accident on opening day in 1999.
Gonzalez's memory will also be honored Saturday when his family
joins current and retired jockeys _ including Bill Shoemaker and
Johnny Longden _ for a winner's circle ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the 1998 Fairplex riding champion, was 23 when he died
of head injuries Sept. 9, 1999, after his mount in the fifth race
broke down and fell, throwing the jockey in the path of trailing
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gonzalez's parents filed a wrongful-death suit
against trainer Sandy Shulman, three co-owners and three
veterinarians, alleging that the ill-fated horse, Wolfhunt, was
allowed to race despite serious medical problems, and that
California laws on the reporting of medication use were violated.
</P>
<P>
   First post is set for noon all 18 consecutive days of the fair.
Racetrack admission is free with a $10 fair general admission
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The opening-day card begins with two appaloosa races. The
thoroughbred races include a pair of $50,000 stakes. Matt Garcia
rides favorites Grey Memo in the 6 -furlong Foothill Stakes for
3-year-olds and Sea Reel in the 6 -furlong Bustles and Bows for
2-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Pedroza has 10 scheduled mounts today as he opens defense
of his 1999 riding championship. Mel Stute, Fairplex's all-time
leading trainer, and Paul Aguirre tied for the training title last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
