STRIKING ACTORS TRY A 3RD TIME &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Take 3 of talks in the strike between commercial
actors and advertisers got under way Wednesday with no immediate
breakthroughs as Hollywood stars and union leaders pledged their
support to more than 1,000 striking actors in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the actors' unions and advertising industry
called the first day of negotiations ``businesslike'' but declined
to elaborate at the request of federal mediators who are trying to
end the nearly 5-month-old strike.
</P>
<P>
   Mediator John Muir said the two sides met for seven hours -- ``I
would characterize it as productive'' -- and that the talks should
resume today at the World Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Similar talks have broken down twice before, in June and July,
with each side accusing the other of failing to budge from an
unreasonable position.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both instances we offered modifications and changes and
they refused to take it seriously,'' said Greg Krisman, spokesman
for the Screen Actors Guild, which launched the strike with the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the Association of National Advertisers did not
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is now in its 19th week, affecting 135,000 actors,
about a quarter of them from the San Fernando Valley. It has cost
Los Angeles County's economy an estimated $165 million, said Jack
Kyser, chief economist of the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very crucial day to see what the first blush is
from the negotiations back in New York,'' Kyser said. ``If the
negotiations break down, the reservoir of ill will continues to
build.''
</P>
<P>
   To mark the new round of talks, union leaders staged rallies in
New York, Chicago, Atlanta and elsewhere and picketed around the
country at plants of General Motors, the strike's main target for
repeatedly using nonunion actors during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles rally drew well over 1,000 people to La Brea Tar
Pits for speeches and a show of support from about 30 celebrities
including Tom Hanks, Patricia Arquette, Valerie Harper, Rob
Schneider and Julianna Margulies and Jack Klugman.
</P>
<P>
   With some stars leading the way, striking actors marched along
Wilshire Boulevard to picket outside three advertising agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to choose to use our talent to sell their
products, we only ask they pay us fairly,'' Hanks said. ``We
deserve an honest partner across the negotiating table to help us
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   For those in the crowd who've not seen work since the strike
started May 1, the financial squeeze is beginning to hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Matlock, 41, of Burbank said she had to take catering work
in the interim and forgo a summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about how much these companies and advertisers
make, it's not like we're taking food out of anyone's mouth here
just to make a living,'' Matlock said.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial actors have rejected a proposed contract by
advertisers that would eliminate residuals for ads that run on
network television and instead pay a flat fee, as is now the case
with cable ads.
</P>
<P>
   Actors call that a ``rollback'' that could cut their wages some
50 percent, while advertisers say it would represent a 17 percent
pay increase over the pay-per-play system.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession for Wednesday's talks, union officials said they
are now willing to take less residuals than previously requested
for ads on smaller cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also want jurisdiction over Internet ads.
</P>
<P>
   Full-time commercial actor Michael French, 48, said he is
prepared to hold out until next year, when TV and movie actors and
writers may also go on strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will put a lot of pressure on them if the film and TV
industries would have to shut down,'' French said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has accelerated production in advance of the feared
strike, as partly reflected in the record number of motion picture
and television jobs reported in Los Angeles County in August, Kyser
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strike is gaining momentum and the advertisers have been
impacted more than they're letting on,'' Todd Amorder, chairman of
SAG/AFTRA's member strike committee told the crowd in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He said the strike's impact can be seen in the low quality of
nonunion ads flooding radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
