<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3935 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-SF     09-14 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ENTERTAINMENT LEADERS SPAR WITH SENATORS OVER MARKETING  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The entertainment industry defiantly challenged
charges at a showcase Senate hearing Wednesday that it markets sex
and violence to children.
</P>
<P>
   The reception it received was not warm.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., emerged as Hollywood's lone
defender amid a cast of industry attackers that included Joe
Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential nominee; Lynn Cheney,
wife of Republican vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney; and
members of both parties on the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Amid an intense election-year battle over values and families,
the hearing was a response to a Federal Trade Commission study
issued Monday that said the entertainment industry ``routinely''
targets children for ``violent movies, music and electronic games''
that its own ratings say are inappropriate for children.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties warned that the industry faces a federal crackdown
unless it stops marketing adult material to children.
</P>
<P>
   But industry representatives sharply disputed the FTC findings.
</P>
<P>
   Blasting the study and the hearing, Artemis Records Chief
Executive Officer Danny Goldberg said, ``So-called self-regulation
achieved by political intimidation is the equivalent of
censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg argued that ``gangsta rap'' is the ``direct
descendant'' of the gangster movies of the 1940s, television
Westerns of the 1950s and ``critically acclaimed films such as `The
Godfather.' '' insisting, ``This country will cease to be free the
day one group of parents can tell all other parents how to raise
their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss Zelnick, chief executive officer of record company BMG
Entertainment, said that ``violence is part of the world that
creates, buys and is influenced by our music'' and that ``the
ultimate responsibility for deciding what music our young people
listen to rests with parents in their homes, not public
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our artists legitimately express and comment on the
problems of our society,'' Zelnick said. ``We need to ensure that
their voices are heard ... I stand by our art, just as I stand by
our sense of taste and restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   But such defenses only seemed to elicit pointed comparisons
between the entertainment industry and tobacco company executives,
who in similar Senate hearings once denied marketing cigarettes to
children and disputed the linkage between smoking and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every member of the panel accused the industry of making
billions of dollars selling what Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., called ``the
glorification of killing'' and ``the debasement of virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Defending these market practices does not defend art or free
expression,'' said committee Chairman John McCain, the Arizona
Republican who made his own failed White House bid this year. ``It
defends the bottom line of your corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., agreed. ``It has never been the law
of the land, nor will it ever be, that those engaged in the sale of
a product that harms children will have an unfettered right to
cause that harm,'' Markey testified.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics of hip-hop star Eminem, who recently won two MTV
awards, was of particular focus. Cheney, the former head of the
National Endowment for the Humanities, distributed the misogynistic
lyrics of Eminem's ``Kill You,'' which speak of his raping and
murdering his mother, gays and ``wives, nuns, sluts'' with ``the
machete from O.J.,'' among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., questioned how the executives could defend
such lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg argued that it it would be impossible to impose a
rating system on music, because unlike movie nudity or sex, lyrics
are words that ``are by their nature impressionistic and are often
used symbolically. No one really thought that the words to `killing
me softly with his song' referred to murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating lyrics would be like rating books, Goldberg insisted, and
violate constitutional protection of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney agreed that the First Amendment would make federal
regulation dubious and called instead for ``people of stature'' to
publicly hold industry executives responsible for selling such
material.
</P>
<P>
   In a swipe at her husband's opponents, Cheney added, ``Two
people of stature are Vice President Gore and Sen. Lieberman,''
suggesting they raise the issue at a  &LR; Thursday  &LR; fund-raiser they
are to attend with Miramax Films Co-Chairman Harvey Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, for his part, decried the ``culture of carnage'' in
the entertainment industry and demanded that companies impose ``an
immediate cease-fire in the marketing of adult-rated products to
children.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain blasted movie executives for failing to appear at the
hearing, sending in their place Jack Valenti, president of the
Motion Picture Association of America. McCain said nearly all the
studio executives claimed to be out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti maintained that the line between reasonable and
unacceptable marketing is imprecise. ``We are not dealing with
Euclid's geometry,'' Valenti said. ``We are dealing here with the
irregular passions of subjective judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives strongly challenged the FTC's
conclusion that entertainment companies are targeting children by
advertising adult material on television shows such as ``Xena:
Warrior Princess'' and ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the audiences of the television shows and magazines
cited by the FTC are primarily adult, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this information in the report is misleading,''
said Peter Moore, president of SEGA of America, Inc., a San
Francisco video game maker. ``This type of speculation is
unconscionable in a document that has all the appearance of a
scientific survey.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said his industry uses a game-ratings system by the
independent Entertainment Software Ratings Board and has begun
following advertising guidelines set by the Advertising Review
Council established this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer was the only senator who spoke in the industry's defense,
acknowledging that the FTC report ``makes some very good points''
but questioned whether changing industry practices would ``cure the
violence problem in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Guns are a much bigger problem, Boxer argued, noting that
Detroit, Michigan and Windsor, Canada, are divided by only a river
and get the same movies, television, music and video games, but
Detroit had 354 gun deaths in 1997 while Windsor had just four.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also said they would avoid legislation, but expect the
industry to follow Walt Disney Co., which announced Tuesday that
its ABC television network would refuse advertisements for R-rated
films during prime time and prohibit theaters from showing trailers
for R-rated films before its movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
