u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     09-14 1923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CORRUPT-NATIONS (United Nations) _ Transparency International's
annual index of the most corrupt countries focused this year on how
hard it is for a country to reverse its image once it has been
perceived as deeply corrupt. The end of military rule and a free
election in Nigeria, for instance, does not change the world's
perception of that country. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   WORKER-UNIONS (Geneva) _ A survey by an international labor
union group has found that being a union organizer is a precarious
position to hold all around the world. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Republicans' decision on
Capitol Hill to shift their message to debt reduction and away from
tax cuts in the waning weeks of the session is the latest example
that they are pursuing a campaign strategy independent of Gov.
George W. Bush. While refusing to criticize Bush's large tax plan,
Republican candidates and incumbents on the campaign trail instead
are sticking to a strategy they say has served House Republicans
well this year, emphasizing smaller bite-size tax cuts that target
married couples, small business owners and farmers. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore attended
a Houston dinner in November 1995 to promote a budding relationship
between the Democratic Party and a handful of powerful Texas trial
lawyers. The relationship blossomed, producing $4 million in
donations from the lawyers' firms since 1996. But it also produced
some heavy-handed fund-raising that has recently drawn the scrutiny
of federal campaign finance investigators. Exclusive. By Don Van
Natta Jr. with Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ President Clinton has delayed
new punitive duties on European luxury goods, including Scottish
cashmere, British shortbread and Italian pecorino cheese, because
Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain has shifted his position on
two festering trade issues to help the United States,
administration officials said on Wednesday. Exclusive. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MORGAN (New York) _ On Wall Street, the Chase Manhattan
Corp. has long been considered an investment banking also ran. No
matter how much stock trading or underwriting Chase did, its
competitors continued to disparage it as a declasse commercial
bank. Now, with its proposed purchase of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Company,
Chase hopes that it has finally broken into the club of financial
firms with enduring global clout. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ The immediate verdict by
investors on Chase Manhattan's decision to take over J.P. Morgan
was a resounding hiss; Chase's share price fell 12 percent the last
two days, after rumors of the deal began to spread. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   FIJI-MAHOGANY (Suva, Fiji) _ A coup here a few months ago
toppled the government. Many accounts told of how ethnic tension
had once again exploded. But behind the cries for ethnic solidarity
and native Fijian supremacy was a struggle over land, money and
mahogany, a competition that involved American and British as well
as local business interests. Like diamonds in Sierra Leone and oil
in Nigeria, Fiji's mahogany helped prompt a struggle for political
power, inflicting damage to the nation's economy and political
system well in excess of the riches the commodity once promised. By
Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-COMMERCIALISM (Undated) _ From exclusive soft-drink
contracts to computers displaying continuous advertising, corporate
marketing in public schools is rising sharply, but few states have
laws in place to address the phenomenon. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
