r s BC-OLY-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     09-14 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER, WISER ABORIGINE ABANDONS BITTERNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The dark-skinned men of Aborigine origin are
seated around a wooden table in the middle of Redfern Park, doing
what men do when they've almost finished a case of beer in the
early hours of a sun-glistened afternoon, laughing, joking,
teasing, philosophizing and offering instant remedies for
humankind's ills.
</P>
<P>
   They regard the reporter warily through bleary eyes, and wonder
what he's doing in south Sydney in a faded enclave of low-end
business establishments and mean streets that contrasts
dramatically to the teeming opulence and skyscraper splendor and
spectacular harbor vistas only a few miles away in the middle of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give a damn about the Olympics,'' says Donald Morgan,
the youngest of the group at 22, as he sips a bottle of VB
(Victoria Bitters). ``All I'm going to do is march in the protests.
Why should I care?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Same for me,'' says Mark Wickey, an older man with a gnarled
face and a shock of thick, black hair. ``I'm not planning to watch
the Games. Not me. I'll just come to the park and drink and forget
the way my people have been treated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are all wrong, and I myself am looking forward to the
Olympics,'' says Bruce Ellis, who, at 58, is the oldest person
present and the one who seems to command the greatest respect.
``I'm happy the Games are here. I'm proud the Games are here. I'm
not in support of any of the protests. I wouldn't do anything to
upset this great event. Our problem is not with the rest of the
world. Our problem is only with the Australian government.''
</P>
<P>
   There are murmuring concurrences and loud dissents, as other men
join the impromptu symposium to voice their views.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is aglow at the moment, bursting with civic pride, the
entire city draped in Olympic banners bearing the five rings, signs
and billboards everywhere hyping this Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
   But, as expected in an international event of such stature,
there will be various groups protesting, and the grievances of the
Aborigines have received the greatest coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And in an area known as Redfern, where most of the Aborigines in
Sydney live, there are strong emotions on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him what they did to you, Bruce,'' says Wickey. ``Tell
him how they took you from your parents when you were 4 years old.
Tell him about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ellis shakes his head slowly, and there is a wistful
sadness in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately it's true . . . they took me when I was 4 and
moved me 300 miles away to a home with other Aborigine children,''
says Ellis, referring to a shameful Australian policy of abducting
Aborigine children from their parents to assimilate, as orphans,
into white society. ``I was away when my dad died. I was away from
1949 to 1961. I try not to think of it. I'm not the only one. It
happened to thousands of us. It's just something that happened, and
you just have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, a retired cameraman for the ABC (Australian Broadcasting
Company) doesn't display even a hint of bitterness, even though he
was one of the victims of a ghastly experiment that wasn't
discontinued until 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler got some of his ideas from what was done to the
Aborigine children here,'' Wickey says bitterly. ``The only reason
I wasn't taken is that my grandfather was Scottish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you're kids and your parents say to you, 'The
Boogie Man is going to get you!' Well, when we were kids, our
parents would say, 'The Welfare Man is going to get you!' And we'd
be scared to death. What they were referring to was the Aborigine
Welfare Department, which was responsible for the child
kidnappings.''
</P>
<P>
   Aborigine athlete Cathy Freeman has become an Australian icon,
the most famous Aborigine since Lionel Rose reigned as the world's
bantamweight champion in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm rooting for Jenny Thompson (American swimming
star),'' Ellis says. ``Of course, I want Cathy Freeman to win. But
I'm a big fan of Jenny Thompson.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends shriek protests, but Ellis, a patriarchal figure
with his gray hair, remains adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a free thinker,'' he says. ``I know we've been wronged.
But that doesn't mean I can't root for someone just because they're
white and from another country. I compare what's happened to us
here to what happened to the Indians in America. We were both born
on the land, and then the white man came and kicked us off it. But
that's a long time ago, and now we have to learn to get along.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ellis points to the empty beer bottle he's holding in his
right hand, and that wistful sadness in his eyes suddenly returns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
