<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-HATE-CRIMES-SFCHRON &LR;      09-14 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADER DEFINITION OF `HATE CRIME' CLEARS HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ The House backed legislation Wednesday to expand
the definition of federal hate crimes to include acts of violence
based on a victim's sexual orientation, gender or disability.
<P>
   Though the House vote was non-binding, gay leaders hailed it as
a historic step for what has long been one of their top legislative
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by President Clinton and opposed by Republican
leaders, the measure now faces an uncertain future in a
House-Senate conference committee where legislators will decide its
fate. The Senate passed expanded hate-crimes legislation earlier
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a chance here to reaffirm America at its best,''
Clinton said at a White House event aimed at building support for
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The current law, passed in 1968, allows federal prosecution of
crimes that are based on the victim's race, color, religion or
national origin. The law limits federal involvement to cases in
which the crime is committed on federal property or while the
victim is engaged in a federally protected activity like voting.
</P>
<P>
   The new law would do away with those restrictions. In addition,
it would expand the definition of hate crimes to include violence
based on sexual orientation, gender or disability.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say that more than 10,000 hate crimes
are committed each year, ranging in severity from minor assaults to
murder.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional debate on the House floor, supporters repeatedly
brought up the brutal killing two years ago of Matthew Shepard, a
gay student at the University of Wyoming who was robbed before
being tied to a fence post and beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person is targeted, the assailant intends to send a
message to all members of that community,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi,
D-Calif. ``This is a different type of crime, and it demands a
different type of response.''
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Chairman John Conyers, D-Mich., called
Wednesday's vote the ``most important vote on civil rights in this
session of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that violent crimes should be universally
prosecuted without regard to the motives of the assailant or the
background of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   They said that local authorities do a fine job of going after
criminals motivated by hate, noting that in the Shepard case,
Wyoming authorities have already sentenced one of the attackers to
two consecutive life terms. If the law passes, they warned, some
perpetrators would try conjure a hate-based motive to their crime
in order to avoid local prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a better deal if you can get in the federal system
because you won't face the death penalty,'' said Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., a former prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was endorsed by a comfortable 40-vote margin despite
opposition from Republican House leaders, who refused to bring the
actual legislation before the House for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Democratic supporters attached an amendment to a
defense bill that instructs members of the House-Senate conference
committee to adopt the Senate's hate-crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   If members of the conference committee follow the House's
non-binding instructions, the hate-crimes measure will be a part of
the defense bill that will be before the House for an up-or-down
vote before it adjourns this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters were jubilant after winning support from the
Republican controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it!'' declared David Smith, a spokesman for the Human
Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay lobbying organization.
``If the conference (committee) drops this language, they will be
thwarting the will of the House. It will fall squarely on the
shoulders of the Republican leaders of the House, and they will
have to pay the political price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
