<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYSOC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STARTS STRONGLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia _ After numerous false alarms, the
maturation of U.S. men's soccer might finally be at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Albright and Josh Wolff scored goals as the United States
dominated the Czech Republic but settled for an encouraging 2-2 tie
as soccer play began Wednesday in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer tournament kicks off before the Games officially
open, to allow for 16-nation tournaments to conclude before Closing
Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the U.S. is considered a basketball country and a
gridiron (football) country,'' U.S. coach Clive Charles said. ``I
tell people all the time that we have young players in the United
States who can play well in any arena.''
</P>
<P>
   That arena Wednesday was Bruce Stadium, here in Australia's
capital 200 miles south of Sydney, where the faster and quicker
Yanks created scoring chances by the minute but took a tie when the
Czechs scored on a penalty in the 52nd minute before a well-bundled
capacity crowd of 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys came off the field disappointed, and that's good,
because they expected to win,'' Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   Three over-age players are allowed per team in what is
essentially an Under-23 tournament, and U.S. goalie Brad Friedel,
29, is one of the senior citizens. He also is one of the biggest
boosters of young American soccer talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it to you this way, that Czech team has lost, like,
twice in its last 17 games, and I think at times in the game we
played them off their butts,'' Friedel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I don't think young players in America get enough
credit. A lot of teams in Europe will go sign one of the Czech
players to a contract in Europe with a big club, and not one of our
players. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Friedel, who plays in England for Liverpool, played for the 1992
Olympic team that was ushered out of the tournament after three
matches. He believes American soccer has undergone a sea change in
eight years _ in large part because Major League Soccer gives the
top college-age players a place to hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is better than that team in 1992 in one big way _
we're all professionals here,'' he said. ``You can say what you
want about MLS, good or bad, but the MLS really, really helps
younger players. A lot of these players have played four years of
professional soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were there in '92, I think we had two professionals on
the team. We were all playing in college, and that doesn't compare
at all. So you're going out there and playing against a couple of
players who just got signed by (Italian clubs) and I'm going to go
back to UCLA to play San Diego State, and that doesn't compare.''
</P>
<P>
   Czech coach Karel Bruckner conceded the Americans surprised his
team, favored to win the four-nation Group C.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a wonderful team,'' Bruckner said of the U.S. ``We
had to defend them with all our might. There is much to be admired
_ their fast, counter-attacking offense, the way they closed on
defense. . . . We had to play for an even score.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Albright: ``I think we surprised them with our speed. We
were able to get wide and behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. is now in position to finish first or second in its
group if it can get favorable results vs. Cameroon and Kuwait,
considered inferior competition to the Czechs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men have never advanced to the second round of an
Olympic soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As Friedel noted, the MLS is the biggest change in U.S. Olympic
soccer. Forward Conor Casey, who assisted on Wolf's 44th minute
goal, was the only collegian on the field Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The MLS existed during the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, but it was in
its first season. The lineup Charles used included several players
who contribute significantly on MLS clubs, including Ben Olsen and
Albright of D.C. United, Peter Vagenas and Danny Califf of the
Galaxy, Chad McCarty of Tampa Bay and Wolff of the Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single one of these players who's here has a chance to
become a very, very good player on a very, very good team,''
Friedel said. ``No doubt in my mind. I haven't seen one player who
doesn't belong here. . . . Soccer in the United States for younger
players has gotten a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
