<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GLYNN ABSORBS A POUNDING FROM ORIOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Nothing comes easy for the Rangers in this
season of misery. Even the few bright spots seem to have their
moments when they flare out.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates has been thrilled by Ryan Glynn
since the start of spring training, and one outing hardly changes
that. But Glynn suffered through his worst outing of the season
Wednesday night, giving up seven runs in 3 1/3 innings in the
Rangers' 9-4 loss to the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped Glynn's two-game losing streak. He is now 5-4
with a 4.99 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just couldn't get the ball down,'' Oates said. ``There were
a couple of balls that could have been, should have been, may have
been caught. But as far as Ryan was concerned, he was just a little
bit up.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Glynn and Doug Davis are going to have nights like
this. Davis failed to go five innings in his last outing in Kansas
City. Both games are reminders that the Rangers' two young
pitchers, as excited as Oates has been about them, remain works in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was only Glynn's 23rd major-league start, which
is less than a full season. Davis makes his 11th major-league start
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reality check,'' Glynn said. ``I never took the
approach it was going to be easy. You can even ask \Rcatcher\S Bill
Haselman. Before the game I had great stuff. When I got out there,
I had good stuff and still got hit around.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn didn't help matters by walking the leadoff hitter, Brady
Anderson. Glynn got the next two hitters, but Cal Ripken singled,
Chris Richard] lined a two-run double just over Rusty Greer's glove
in left-center and Brook Fordyce singled up the middle to make it
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Richard added a two-run single in the third, and third baseman
Mike Lamb's throwing error led to two more runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes this happens,'' Glynn said. ``Sometimes you have to
take your spanking, deal with it and come back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates expects that. Rick Helling and Kenny Rogers are still
expected to be the Rangers' No. 1 and No. 2 starters next season
but Glynn and Davis should be No. 4 and No. 5, with Darren Oliver
and/or Justin Thompson fitting in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said there are a lot of teams that would love to have
Davis and Glynn as their No. 4 and No. 5 starters next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the Boston Red Sox,'' Oates said. ``Without Pedro
Martinez and his brother, Ramon, they're 18 games under .500. I'll
be willing to bet you anything Glynn and Davis aren't going to be
18 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rogers and Helling should be 18 games over .500. Glynn and
Davis should be four or five games over .500. But they're going to
get better and better. The biggest disappointment I've had this
season, other than losing, is not seeing \Rinjured center fielder\S
Ruben Mateo grow into a job. The most exciting thing is seeing how
far \RGlynn and Davis\S have come.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates even went so far as to say, ``I can see these guys winning
15 games next year. Who knows. It could be 15-10, it could be
13-12. But these guys have a better-than-average chance of winning
double-figures next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oates offered one caveat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to catch the ball,'' Oates said. ``We weren't too
sharp tonight defensively. We had a couple errors and there were
some balls in the outfield we didn't take good routes on. That's
the way it has been all year. As we finish this season and go into
next year, the one thing we have to do is get better defensively.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
