<HEADLINE>
TCU SOCCER PLAYERS STRIVE FOR THE PERFECT STRIKE AT THE BALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The game is called ``butts up.'' Lose a
series of skills competitions, and your posterior becomes a willing
target for one of TCU midfielder Matt Groves' penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   This is not fun. Groves, a 5-foot-8 senior from Richardson, can
easily bruise one's backside with a soccer ball. His right foot
packs the hardest wallop of any TCU men's player.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Sherry Dick, a 5-10 sophomore forward on the TCU
women's team. At age 10, Dick had a shot timed at nearly 50 mph by
one of those carnival-game radar devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've always had that going for me,'' said Dick, a Sam
Houston High School graduate. ``We talk about it on the bus
sometimes, trying to figure out what makes me kick a ball so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   How can average-sized athletes like Dick and Groves or football
place-kickers strike a ball with such force and momentum? Dick said
it has to do with form that comes naturally with time. Groves, who
has never used weights to improve his leg strength, credits years
of intense running and ball-striking repetition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knock balls at people just for fun,'' Groves said.
``I don't want to take anyone's head off, but you can get
frustrated out there and need to take it out on someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Groves, Dick and TCU men's and women's assistant coach Jay
Fitzgerald were put to a radar-gun test. Fitzgerald, a 6-6,
230-pound former goalkeeper at Creighton, can put some muscle
behind his kick.
</P>
<P>
   All three were asked to estimate how fast they could launch a
soccer ball from the 12-yard penalty spot. Dick guessed 70 miles
per hour. Groves figured in the mid-70s, and Fitzgerald's goal was
80.
</P>
<P>
   Carnac couldn't have guessed better. On their last tries, Dick
topped out at 70 and Groves at 75. Groves also broke a plastic
fastener that held the net and crossbar together.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald hit 80 on his third try before tailing off due to
fatigue. If 70-80 mph doesn't sound fast for a 12-yard soccer shot,
then consider this:
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Chicago Fire goalkeeper Zach Thornton set the Major
League Soccer record for a kicked ball at 86 mph. This season,
Thornton was timed at 81. In three seasons, Matt McKeon of the
Kansas City Wizards (78 mph) has come the closest.
</P>
<P>
   An ability to strike a ball hard can figure into the recruiting
equation, Fitzgerald said. It means a player can choose spots in
the net quickly and precisely, as well as score from longer
distances. In the beginning, Dick's unusual raw power attracted TCU
to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd be hovering around 50,'' said TCU men's defender
Aaron Casey, who watched the experiment. ``I'd be way below
Sherry's kicks. I'd look pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts up.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
