<HEADLINE>
OPTIONS PONDERED FOR DALLAS STARS' NEW CAMP SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ The Stars might be swapping the Eco Challenge for
the I-35 challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations to Dobson Ice Arena likely will prevent the Stars
from returning to Vail for training camp next September, and they
are considering conducting the camp at American Airlines Center in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Heber, who operates Dobson, said construction is scheduled
from April to November.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, in all likelihood, it won't be available
next year,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey said. ``And we'll
have to find somewhere else. ... We've talked about Dallas as a
possibility with the new arena opening, but there is a lot of
variables there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The arena, which the Stars and Mavericks will begin playing in
for the 2001-02 season, needs to guarantee the ice would be ready.
Even if the arena is ready, the Stars haven't settled on Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock likes the effect that getting away has on
his team.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, ``we can tell players, `Well, stick together.' But if
you've got 30 different cars and people that live a long ways away,
they're not going to stick together,'' Hitchcock said. ``This
\Rbeing away\S forces everybody to be on the same page, and forces
everybody to act and behave as a group. At home, it's not \Rabout\S
distractions, it's just that there's no opportunity for chemistry,
because we have to plan it. It's not natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said the Stars considered not returning to Vail this
year, but simply ran out of time. The earliest the Stars are likely
to make a decision is December. \Nsubheds:Muller to see action Talk
about taking one for the team. Stars winger Kirk Muller is taking
60 for the team by playing in tonight's exhibition game against the
Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock hadn't planned on playing any of the 10 veterans, who
didn't scrimmage in camp, in the first two exhibition games. But
the NHL has a rule that each team must play at least 10 players who
played at least 30 games the season before. Without the veterans,
the Stars have nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muller is the 10th,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have specific goals
for all of our older players. When we play them is not as important
as how much we play them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars could have more stars in their lineup Saturday for the
exhibition home-opener against the St. Louis Blues, including
goalie Ed Belfour. They want to play him 240 minutes in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``However we go about that, I'm not sure yet. Really, it's up to
Eddie,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have an obligation to play a good
squad at home, too.'' \Nsubheds:Donato impressive Not a lot of the
veterans have been scrimmaging in training camp, so it's hard not
to notice the ones who are.
</P>
<P>
   But winger Ted Donato has been really good, Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really showing he's a good pro,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's
got speed. He can arrive on pucks that maybe last year we couldn't
arrive on.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato had a dandy goal Wednesday in a scrimmage, but said the
lack of defense probably helped. He had a wide open path to the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure would like one of those in April,'' Donato said. ``I
don't see it happening. I don't think \RColorado defenseman Ray
Bourque\S would bite on that one.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Ken Hitchcock
said defenseman Darryl Sydor, who has been out with an injured
ankle, ``skated very aggressively'' Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Mark Wotton, who had abdominal surgery in the
off-season, has been skating and is set to join the team Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will need to make decisions on some of their younger
players soon on whether they'll be joining their junior teams. One
of the youngsters who could stay a little longer is defenseman Dan
Jancevski. If he stays, Hitchcock said he'll play in some games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
