<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATOR WRESTLING: NO EXPERIENCE NEEDED 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bored with your job? Career going nowhere? Envious of people
with missing digits? Perhaps you should consider becoming an
alligator wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminole Indians are looking for a few good men or women
willing to jump into a swimming pool and wrestle a 7-foot alligator
for the amusement of paying customers. Pay is $12 an hour, plus
health and life insurance. No experience is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The logical question to ask at this point is: What happened to
the previous alligator wrestlers? Did they retire? Were they eaten?
Did they move on to more lucrative careers in e-commerce?
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer is C, according to tribe spokesman Chuck
Malkus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, Seminoles have done this,'' Malkus told the
Associated Press. ``The reason why we have job openings is because
tribe members are now going into banking, communications,
e-commerce and law school. We have a shortage of candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   (Let us pause at this point for a moment and say a silent prayer
for a world populated by lawyers with backgrounds in alligator
wrestling Thank you.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrestling'' is probably not the best word to use in describing
this particular type of alligator/human encounter. There are no
flying drop-kicks, pile-drivers or forearm shivers and a folding
chair almost never figures in the outcome of the contest. The goal
is to simply (or not so simply) drag the gator out of the pool, sit
on its back and pry open its mouth. Those of you with teenagers may
have some familiarity with this procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The next logical question to ask is: Why? I have been in the
(too) near vicinity of alligators on many occasions and not once
did I get the urge to drag it by its tail, sit on its back or pry
open its jaws with my hands. One does not need to be a student of
reptile psychology to suspect that an alligator may not enjoy being
treated in this manner and might even attempt to show its
displeasure by biting off a finger, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Seminole Indian Chief James Billie lost a finger
while wrestling an alligator in front of about 100 tourists in the
Everglades. Billie started wrestling alligators at age 5 but hadn't
tussled with one for the past 10 years. The lesson here,
apparently, is that alligator wrestling is not something you pick
up, put down and pick up again like golf or bridge. Whether the
alligator's skills grow rusty with disuse is a question the
literature has thus far failed to address. My guess is that they do
not.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure I'm right when I say the reason the Seminoles
are having so much trouble finding and keeping alligator wrestlers
is not the irresistible lure of banking and e-commerce but rather
the very real possibility that the wrestler will find himself
suddenly and violently disengaged from one or more body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Looking outside the reservation for people stupid enough to do
this is not the solution. (Though sufficient quantities of stupid
people will certainly be found.) The solution is to ditch alligator
wrestling altogether and replace it with something safer like
alligator debating, alligator admiring or, safest of all, alligator
dreaming. There is no reason to think an alligator would object to
any of these exercises, though in the case of the debate it would
probably be wise to steer clear of topics having to do with
trapping or skinning or things that taste like chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Whether 100 tourists will come to the Everglades to watch
someone dream of alligators, I do not know. It would probably
depend on how vivid the dream was. Either way, having a casino
nearby probably wouldn't be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
