u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-CO     09-14 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE COLUMN
 &HT;    Aunt Bert's shanty house was a haven when dad went to war
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    By Patricia Spork
 &HT;    c. 2000 Special to Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my father went to Vietnam in the '60s for his first tour of
duty, I was only 9 years old. Even at such a young age, I knew the
possible consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Tears and prayer took up many of my waking hours, and it was one
of the worst years of my childhood.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also one of my fondest because of the weekends my
mother, younger brother and I spent at my Aunt Bert's house in
Three Creeks, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Her home was no grand affair. Its peeling paint gave it the look
of a rustic barn. You might even call it a shanty.
</P>
<P>
   Dilapidated front steps leading to a large porch and a torn
screen door greeted us, along with Aunt Bert and my five cousins.
</P>
<P>
   There was no running water. You took a bath in a metal wash tub
with water that had been hauled from the well and heated on the
stove.
</P>
<P>
   A small wooden outhouse sufficed for toilet needs. We considered
ourselves extremely lucky if there was store-bought toilet tissue
in place of the usual pages of newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper had other uses. Crunched tight, it packed many holes
in the walls of that old farm house, helping to keep out red wasps
during summer and keep in the heat during winter.
</P>
<P>
   A stone fireplace in the living room was the only source of
heat. The warmth never ventured from that one room.
</P>
<P>
   Two double beds in my cousins' bedroom slept six of us kids --
three girls in one bed and three boys in another. Homemade quilts
and shared body heat kept us from freezing.
</P>
<P>
   But the house was wonderful in its own special way. Sitting deep
in the country and surrounded by hay fields and dense wood, it was
a child's paradise.
</P>
<P>
   We spent our days trekking across pastures dotted with cow pies,
navigating creek beds, swinging from ropes hung in trees, sliding
down a barn's tin roof onto hay piles and playing hide-'n'-seek
</P>
<P>
   in skeleton cars junked in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Night brought the sing-alongs. My mother and aunt played guitar
and sang gospel tunes such as ``I'll Fly Away'' and honky-tonk hits
like ``Rattlesnakin' Daddy.'' When we ran out of songs, we would
invent new lyrics for the old ones. Christmas carols were sung year
round.
</P>
<P>
   Food only entered our minds when our stomachs started growling.
</P>
<P>
   When we came to visit, mom always brought an ice chest filled
with lunch meat and soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   If we were fortunate, my uncle might have shot down enough
copper wire from electric lines to sell for scrap _ something we
kids were not supposed to know about _ and treat us all to a smoked
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts of sliced turkey fried in butter still make my mouth
water.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all I remember the laughter and glee that filled
that old shanty at each visit.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Bert's house, poor though it was, became my salvation
during my father's absence. I'll always be thankful for the time we
spent there.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Spork lives in Tatum, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 0847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX     09-14 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Candidates need to rethink virtuous stands
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Droppings along the campaign trail:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Of RATS and Men . . .
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complain that the word ``RATS,'' sneaked for 1/30th of
second into a Bush commercial blasting Al Gore, was slimy
subliminal advertising, and there's support for the suspicion from
the ad's own creator.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Castellanos at first denied the charge but, with a
reputation as a political tough and hired because of it,
Castellanos finally couldn't forswear pride of craft. The word was
slipped in, he suggested, to emphasize the word ``bureaucrats'' in
the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly denied being party to any ``subliminable''
advertising. (This campaign must be a daily embarrassment to Yale.)
Which raises an interesting existential question. Can a candidate
be subliminal when it isn't entirely clear that he's even liminal?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Going Hollywood . . .
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole ran against Hollywood four years ago as the Republican
presidential candidate, denouncing wanton movies. The hustle got
him elected poster boy for Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, understand, no longer means just Hollywood. The word
has become political shorthand for any popular entertainment a
politician dislikes. For Republicans, that usually means a
suspicion that someone, somewhere, is making whoopee in a way not
officially sanctioned by the party. Democrats usually don't much
mind the sex stuff (see: Clinton, Bill) but are shocked, shocked at
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Like lions on a gimpy gazelle, Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman have
pounced on a Federal Trade Commission report exposing the
entertainment industry's practice of pitching adult movies, CDs and
video games to teens who are supposedly barred from them by the
industry's own code.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says that if the industry doesn't stop that, he, as
president, will sic the FTC on them with a legal strong arm, a
terrible idea. The industry should live up to its own rules, but
all it would have to do to dodge any federal policing is scrap the
standards, which are voluntary, and the government would have no
constitutional authority to enact its own. And then where would we
be?
</P>
<P>
   We've been told for years by the hell-in-a-handbasket crowd that
Hollywood _ personified by fellow-traveling Clinton _ is leading
the nation and especially its youth to ruin.
</P>
<P>
   How so? Teen pregnancy rates have fallen through the mid-and
late '90s and by last year the teen birth rate was at a 60-year
low, down 20 percent from '91. Teen drug use dropped 21 percent
over the last two years. Major crime rates are at historic lows and
last year's National Crime Victimization survey recorded the
biggest drop in its 25-year history. The lowest abortion rate since
1978 was logged three years ago, the latest figure. Divorce rates
over the last five years are down from 5 in 10 to 4, a 20 percent
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, there's something to be said for virtue, at least in
moderation. (As there is for vice. Without it, virtue wouldn't even
have a name.) But maybe it's time to rethink the glib
cause-and-effect game politicians of both parties play.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 0847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-C     09-14 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE HOLBROOKE FACTOR
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (i) international categories
for release Sunday, Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1996, a friend ran across Madeleine Albright at
the Democratic National Convention as she strolled down Chicago's
Miracle Mile with her security guards in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear you've got a good shot at being secretary of state,''
the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright pressed a finger to her lips. ``Don't talk about it,''
she pleaded. ``It could screw things up.''
</P>
<P>
   That encounter came to mind at a recent dinner party attended by
Richard Holbrooke, Albright's successor as U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations and a leading candidate to succeed her as secretary
should Al Gore move into the White House next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Helms, the crusty Republican chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, kept Holbrooke's nomination dangling
for two years. But in the 13 months since Holbrooke moved to New
York, he has zealously courted Helms, initiating frequent visits
and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   These friendly dealings with Helms are part of a pattern:
Holbrooke treasures a warm letter from Richard Nixon, which Nixon
wrote a few weeks before his death, while Holbrooke was the U.S.
envoy to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Holbrooke pumps plenty of private advice the vice
president's way. In 1996, Gore strongly favored Holbrooke for the
top job at State. But Hillary Clinton believed that Albright, her
fellow Wellesley alumna and globe-trotting companion, should get
the nod.
</P>
<P>
   Among insiders, Holbrooke is known for the brilliance of his
ideas, for his prodigious work habits (he molded the Dayton peace
accords on Bosnia) and for the prickliness of his personality. Ever
since he was a junior staff officer in Vietnam, Holbrooke has also
assiduously courted the press.
</P>
<P>
   Several ideas about all this surfaced at the dinner party, which
marked a face-lift for Foreign Policy magazine, a journal that
Holbrooke had edited briefly during its infancy some 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One was that, if tapped for the post, Holbrooke would be a
dominant figure in the foreign policy arena _ quite a different
sort of political animal than, say, Albright and more in the mold
of Henry Kissinger and the late John Foster Dulles.
</P>
<P>
   Another was that Gore, who is well versed in international
issues, would want to run the show himself. That would mean putting
a lesser figure at State, akin to what President John F. Kennedy
did in 1961 when he chose Dean Rusk, a mild-mannered veteran
foreign service officer from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Among the invited no-shows at the party were Albright (who was
in New York) and Leon Fuerth, Gore's national security adviser.
It's widely presumed that Fuerth would advise Gore to keep a tight
hold on the reins, far from Holbrooke's nimble fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it could be argued that George W. Bush would make a
better foreign policy president than would Gore. Since he knows
less about these issues, he would tend to be more cautious, which
is a good thing. Bush would also rely heavily on his secretary of
state-in-waiting, former Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush should win, Holbrooke would be only too glad to take on
special tasks between his money-making bouts on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
