<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-C     09-14 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE HOLBROOKE FACTOR
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (i) international categories
for release Sunday, Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1996, a friend ran across Madeleine Albright at
the Democratic National Convention as she strolled down Chicago's
Miracle Mile with her security guards in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear you've got a good shot at being secretary of state,''
the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright pressed a finger to her lips. ``Don't talk about it,''
she pleaded. ``It could screw things up.''
</P>
<P>
   That encounter came to mind at a recent dinner party attended by
Richard Holbrooke, Albright's successor as U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations and a leading candidate to succeed her as secretary
should Al Gore move into the White House next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Helms, the crusty Republican chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, kept Holbrooke's nomination dangling
for two years. But in the 13 months since Holbrooke moved to New
York, he has zealously courted Helms, initiating frequent visits
and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   These friendly dealings with Helms are part of a pattern:
Holbrooke treasures a warm letter from Richard Nixon, which Nixon
wrote a few weeks before his death, while Holbrooke was the U.S.
envoy to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Holbrooke pumps plenty of private advice the vice
president's way. In 1996, Gore strongly favored Holbrooke for the
top job at State. But Hillary Clinton believed that Albright, her
fellow Wellesley alumna and globe-trotting companion, should get
the nod.
</P>
<P>
   Among insiders, Holbrooke is known for the brilliance of his
ideas, for his prodigious work habits (he molded the Dayton peace
accords on Bosnia) and for the prickliness of his personality. Ever
since he was a junior staff officer in Vietnam, Holbrooke has also
assiduously courted the press.
</P>
<P>
   Several ideas about all this surfaced at the dinner party, which
marked a face-lift for Foreign Policy magazine, a journal that
Holbrooke had edited briefly during its infancy some 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One was that, if tapped for the post, Holbrooke would be a
dominant figure in the foreign policy arena _ quite a different
sort of political animal than, say, Albright and more in the mold
of Henry Kissinger and the late John Foster Dulles.
</P>
<P>
   Another was that Gore, who is well versed in international
issues, would want to run the show himself. That would mean putting
a lesser figure at State, akin to what President John F. Kennedy
did in 1961 when he chose Dean Rusk, a mild-mannered veteran
foreign service officer from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Among the invited no-shows at the party were Albright (who was
in New York) and Leon Fuerth, Gore's national security adviser.
It's widely presumed that Fuerth would advise Gore to keep a tight
hold on the reins, far from Holbrooke's nimble fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it could be argued that George W. Bush would make a
better foreign policy president than would Gore. Since he knows
less about these issues, he would tend to be more cautious, which
is a good thing. Bush would also rely heavily on his secretary of
state-in-waiting, former Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush should win, Holbrooke would be only too glad to take on
special tasks between his money-making bouts on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
