<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4615 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS &LR;      09-14 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
  
 SLURS NOT ENOUGH TO SILENCE PEDRO
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Shortly after 7 tonight, Pedro Martinez will throw
his first pitch to a Cleveland batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' said Martinez, ``nothing will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the buildup to Martinez's first start at Jacobs Field since
he was suspended for hitting Cleveland's Roberto Alomar April 30
has been electric.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Charlie Manuel disagrees with the common
belief that too much is at stake for the Red Sox and Indians, teams
battling each other for a wild-card berth, for personal feelings to
take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's more likely something will happen just because the
games are so important,'' said Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   In Martinez's mind, though, no scene could be as electric as
when he headed to the Jacobs Field bullpen in the fourth inning of
the fifth and deciding game of the American League playoff series
against the Indians last October. Wednesday, Martinez carefully
described what happened then; the media listened and wrote his
words down in near disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect whatever (tonight),'' Martinez began. ``I remember
being told when I was warming up in the bullpen for the playoff
game that I was going to get shot if I got to the mound. That came
from fans who probably wanted me to just get out of there or go
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   These were new words. Martinez said he had never reported the
death threat, either to the Sox or Major League Baseball. Kevin
Shea, the Sox director of communications, said, ``This is the first
we've heard of it and it's very disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said the Sox will promptly bring Martinez's report of the
threat to MLB security.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez went on. The Indians have never beaten him, and
last October, sore shoulder and all, death threat or no death
threat, Martinez took the mound and pitched six innings of hitless
ball, sending the Indians home for the winter. It was an amazing
performance, even more amazing considering what Martinez said
Wednesday of that night's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The fans) said so many discriminating stuff to me that it
sound unreal,'' Martinez went on. ``They call me `Beaner,' they
say, `Go back to your country' and `You don't belong in America.'
All the things that you have to hear from fans. It was the first
time I had ever heard those things, and I heard them here in
Cleveland. But I understand also that it was a playoff game, and a
lot of people (were) upset because of the success that I had
against this team. They saw their chances were more limited if I
came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Martinez would go out of his way to say this incident
happened in Cleveland, but he did not want to indict the city of
Cleveland. The heart and soul of the Indians, after all, is made up
of Latin players, from pitcher Bartolo Colon to slugger Manny
Ramirez and infielders Roberto Alomar and Omar Vizquel, some of
whom are his friends and all of whom, said Martinez, tell him how
well they are treated in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   And the threat? Perhaps Martinez had taken it too literally, the
Sox pitcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been about baseball, you know, `Shot by the
Cleveland Indians,' '' said Martinez. ``It could have been. Cumby
(Sox bullpen coach John Cumberland) was more upset than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Very true, said Cumberland, who said he heard the slurs but did
not hear a death threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't upset by it. It bothered me more than it bothered
him,'' Cumberland said. ``It started right away once he started
warming up. That was a big game, and they'll do anything to try and
get the opposing pitcher, no matter if it's Pedro or whoever. But
the things that were said were uncalled for. It was personal and it
was racial.''
</P>
<P>
   Cumberland said he was so upset at the small group of fans,
``and especially one guy who was doing most of the shouting,'' that
he did what he shouldn't have done _ shout back at the fans. But,
Cumberland wanted to point out, ``That's not the only city where
you hear this stuff in the bullpen. No matter where you go, New
York and even in the Boston bullpen,'' fans can be vile toward
opposing pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the racial words, Martinez replied, once again,
``They call me `Beaner.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez is Martinez, intelligent and able to weigh all the
emotions that were rampant in Jacobs Field that night 11 months
ago. It was the deciding game of the playoff series, and the
Cleveland fans were fretful and fearful their Indians might give up
a playoff series they once had led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take it personal. It was a playoff game and it meant
a lot to the fans,'' said Martinez. ``I don't know . . . I guess
people forgot about just being fans. They took it personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he hurt by what he heard? ``No . . . no . . . no . . . I
know I don't belong in America,'' said Martinez. ``I'm from Latin
America . . . but that's OK. Like I said, they probably said those
things because they knew I could probably beat the Cleveland
Indians. And they were fans. They were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never do I care what the crowd does _ not here, not in Fenway,
not in Yankee Stadium, nowhere. Fans are out there to have fun and
watch what happens. I am inside the field. And I don't care what
they do and I don't care how they feel, and I just care about my
game and give the fans what they deserve: a good game of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez will take the mound tonight with his reputation set
for his baseball life, he conceded. He's a ``headhunter,'' known to
one and all for throwing inside. But the player he hit, Roberto
Alomar, bears him no grudges, said Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Since that incident, for which Martinez was suspended five games
after throwing close to catcher Einar Diaz and hitting Alomar,
Martinez said his and Alomar's paths have crossed twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Robby at the All-Star Game and we talked like always,''
said Martinez. ``He said it was the right thing to do (hitting him)
when I did it and I did it right. He told me that personally, in
front of some other guys. Then (Tuesday at Jacobs Field), I was in
the weight room and he came over as he always does, and he asked
how I was doing and talked to me for five or six minutes. We hugged
each other, we talked . . . just like always. Robby understands
what I did. There was nothing wrong doing it the way I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the frustrations of Cleveland, all the memories of what
Martinez has done to the Indians _ the win in the fifth game of the
playoffs, the hitting of Alomar, the 3-0 shutout by Martinez of the
Indians at Fenway Park back on June 8 _ all will mesh tonight. The
Indians shouldn't be frustrated, said Martinez. They should take
his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was them, I would be antsy to go out there again against
me,'' said Martinez. ``And again and again and again until I get my
goal. Those guys are some of the best guys in the game, and those
guys know that sometime they can get just lucky and score 20
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland knows if I'm on, then I don't need to hit anybody to
beat them,'' were the next straight-forward but fiery words from
Martinez's lips. ``And I know if they're on, they don't need to do
any type of cheating to beat me, because they're that good. But I'm
going to pitch inside, I'm going to pitch away, I'm going to pitch
up, I'm going to pitch down, I'm going to pitch everywhere I have
to pitch to beat somebody. And It's not just against the Cleveland
Indians, it's against the league. I've done it my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite clearly in Martinez's mind, neither opposing batters,
opposing managers, nor even baseball disciplinarian Frank Robinson
can do anything to change his aggressive style of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't want me to pitch inside,'' said Martinez with
determination, ``if they don't want me to pitch my game the way I
do, then they'll have to kick me out of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   So you're not changing your style, Martinez was asked, no matter
what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I? Would you if you had the results I'm getting?''
answered Martinez. ``If you were the manager of any other team, and
you had me on your team, would you change me? Would you allow me to
change? Then it's obvious. The answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after Martinez's disclosures Wednesday. Even though
he said he heard a death threat, even though he said he heard
racial slurs for the first time, Martinez still came out of that
bullpen and pitched hitless ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody like him,'' said Cumberland. ``He's on
a mission when he takes the mound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
