r k BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN09     09-14 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN0915-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing old but not up
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I'm about to mark another birthday. Note I
didn't say celebrate. It just doesn't seem right that I should
celebrate something that comes along about as often as a full moon.
And besides, I don't feel (unintelligible) years old.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, my wife told me the other day I reminded her of a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what she said was that she wished I'd stop acting like
I was in high school. Indeed, a person older and wiser than I
observed once that the way we act in high school is the way we'll
act through life. So those guys you thought were jerks in high
school are most likely jerks now and will be forever. Same applies
for those who were nice in high school. Nice then; nice forever.
Living right here in the town where I was born and reared, I see a
lot of folks I knew in school. The theory is amazingly accurate.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, I feel the same inside as I did when I was
18. Too bad that teen-ager's soul is trapped in a body that's 100
pounds heavier, more wrinkled and a lot grayer.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, I have my children to keep me young.
</P>
<P>
   While most of my friends are dealing with the empty nest
syndrome, at my house we have a new hatchling. Our young son is 10
months old and yes, thank you very much, I've already done the
math. When he graduates from high school, I'll be ready to draw
Social Security. My concern is that I don't want him to grow up
with an ``old'' dad, because that's what happened to me. My dad was
40 years old when I was born and I spent most of my growing up
years thinking he was so old fashioned and out of date. How little
I knew.
</P>
<P>
   God has a funny way of teaching us lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Here I am, older than my dad was when I was born, bringing a son
into the world. I wouldn't change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of this baby has been one of the greatest joys in my
life. I am both amazed and fascinated by every gurgle and coo. It's
enough to keep me young for years.
</P>
<P>
   But reality has a way of rearing its head.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 on a Monday morning, the baby woke up and decided he
wanted a bottle right then. His crib is in our bedroom and so his
routine is to clutch the siderailing of the bed, jump up and down
and bawl. Being the lighter sleeper, I normally get up, get his
bottle and put him back down.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I decided to see if he would quiet down by himself,
but after a few bellows, my wife got up, got his bottle and soothed
him. When she came back to bed, she put her hand on my back for a
moment and then poked me good with her finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What'd you do that for?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just wanted to make sure sure you weren't dead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday to me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0915-COX     09-14 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Want to talk campaign issues? It'll take more than 30 seconds
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Rats.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago the presidential campaign had been almost
miraculously issues-based. This week it is officially off-base.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the ``issue'' was subliminal rodents. Last week it was a
caught-on-tape vulgarity. And more and more we hear media
recitation/speculation about 30-second jabs.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, people. Hey, press. You've got some substantial policy
differences here. No need for subliminal analysis (debunked as
hokum by reputable research). Just listen to what the candidates
say. Then discuss among yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Take education, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Many people rate it the No. 1 issue. That's an odd ranking,
because Washington's role is small. Federal funds amount to only 6
percent of the total spent on public schools.
</P>
<P>
   However, in this presidential race a federal role is not seen as
small by either major candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore wants to spend an additional $115 billion on education,
including initiatives aimed at universal access to preschool, more
classroom teachers and higher teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush wants to spend $45 billion, including new
after-school programs and education savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   VOUCHERS AS LEVERS
</P>
<P>
   Pricetags aside, it could be argued that Bush's proposal would
entail a greater federal role in public schools than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that case was made by two former state school board
members, Republicans themselves, during the GOP primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promotes local control of decision-making. However, his
proposal to punish low-performing schools by awarding their Title I
money to families as school vouchers portends to affect how every
school district behaves. Obvious questions: How to judge who's
low-performing? A national test? A standard chosen by each state?
If so, how to make state standards comparable?
</P>
<P>
   The choice between Gore and Bush is several national referenda
in one: on abortion rights; on campaign finance reform; on
across-the-board tax cuts. But as much as any issue, it is a
national referendum on school vouchers. What say, America?
</P>
<P>
   Without question, even though rank-in-file Republicans appear to
support vouchers, Bush's proposed federal activism on education
veers from the party line.
</P>
<P>
   Bush prevailed to remove from the national GOP platform a plank
to abolish the Department of Education. Support for that
abolishment, and for a federal hands-off policy on public schools,
has been the party mantra since Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans now find a federal role in schools alluring
if it means realizing such goals as vouchers or sexual abstinence
programs.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESSIONAL RACE
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the District 11 seat in Congress, we have a more
traditional distinction on education. Republican challenger Ramsey
Farley, a former Temple school trustee, said he wants federal aid
to have few or no strings attached. He favors block grants over
targeted programs aimed at specific purposes such as hiring new
teachers. He wants school districts to determine how the money is
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Chet Edwards calls that a ``blank check'' approach.
``There has to be accountability'' when public schools receive
federal funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards supports Title 1, grants targeted at low-achieving
students and weighted heavily toward inner-city schools. He also
supported the Clinton spending initiative to help school districts
hire more classroom teachers. The GOP wants that money parceled
into no-strings block grants.
</P>
<P>
   You see? There are real issues related to real problems. Just
listen to what the candidates say.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
