<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHARP-DRIVING0915-COX     09-14 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's no honeymoon driving a Hummer
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 2,600 miles with a Hummer, the ultimate SUV, I'm
not sure it qualifies as the ultimate ``all-terrain'' vehicle.
Interstate highways are simply not its forte. But who was to know?
</P>
<P>
   When the opportunity arose to take the vehicle on an extended
trip to Dubuque, Iowa, and Minneapolis, my husband and I thought,
``Hey, cool!''
</P>
<P>
   We soon learned that living with a Hummer is in many ways like a
man lusting over a gorgeous woman and finding out after he marries
her that she can't cook.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt in military service, for which it was originally
designed, the Hummer is the ultimate vehicle. It can climb any kind
of steep grade, ford river crossings and pull through the mire and
the muck with the best of them. But don't expect it to cruise down
the interstate and keep up with today's rapid traffic pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Hummer's gearing is such that it is really ``happy'' at a
maximum speed of somewhere between 68 and 70 mph. That meant that
we were a roadblock on today's roadways.
</P>
<P>
   It's really frustrating riding along in a $98,000 vehicle and
being blown away by motorhomes and minivans. The ultimate insult
was the minivan pulling a trailer loaded down with household goods
and flapping bedspreads that roared past us. The four kids waving
out the back window only added insult to injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Hummer is also not a good vehicle for conversation. Look
inside one and you will see a large, flat platform between the
seats. While it serves as a wonderful dining table, it really
houses all of the Hummer's sophisticated four-wheel-drive
mechanism. Combined with the 6.2-liter diesel engine, it creates
quite a noise.
</P>
<P>
   Add two slightly deaf baby boomers, and you have a couple that
rode 2,600 miles with only an occasional yell over the roar.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, for those couples who might not want to
converse with one another, it is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first tank of fuel, our honeymoon with the
idea of using a Hummer was rapidly fading. But everywhere we went,
people just loved it. You'd pull into a fuel station to find a
chorus line of curious gapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much does it cost?'' ``Is it amphibious?'' ``Man, that is
sooo cool!'' ``Can I look inside?'' ``Can I sit in it?'' ``I don't
suppose there is any chance you'd take me for a ride?''
</P>
<P>
   It was an endless barrage of questions. One 14-year-old was so
bold as to ask, ``How about letting me drive it around the parking
lot. I'd be really careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   When the deliveryman dropped off the Hummer at our house, he
said, ``You won't meet yourself coming in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. We didn't see just one other Hummer, in a place
appropriately named Soldiers Grove, Wis., we met a convoy of 44
military Hummers. We did have better paint _ theirs ranged from
conventional camouflage to the Desert Storm variety.
</P>
<P>
   People _ especially guys and kids _ love the look of the Hummer.
We concluded it was because it was a combination of its looks and
because it allows middle-aged men to play GI Joe.
</P>
<P>
   There is an alternative for those who are drawn to playing
either GI Joe or GI Jane but don't want to shell out nearly
$100,000 for an uncomfortable gas-guzzler. General Motors bought
the rights to the name from American General, which builds the
Hummer, to produce a little brother.
</P>
<P>
   GM's H2 will hit the market in 2002 as a 2003 model. For those
of us who don't have the same grit as our fighting men and women in
the armed services, we'll be able to look like it while enjoying
the interior and other amenities one would expect in a well-dressed
Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
