</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HIGHLIGHTS-MYERS0915-     09-14 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHLIGHTS-MYERS0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The man with the answersBy Elizabeth Barchas
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you ask Jack Myers a question, you'll likely
be met with silence. As senior science editor at Highlights for
Children magazine, his job is to answer queries, but he never
purports to know all the answers. Instead, he pauses. Mentally
chews on words, thoughts, ideas. Thinks about what to say, how to
say it, why it's so. And then, just as you think he didn't hear
you, or perhaps doesn't know, he delivers an answer.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it's been for 40 years, when Myers first began
responding to children's science questions in the magazine his
parents, Garry and Caroline Myers, founded. At the time, Myers was
a professor of zoology and botany at the University of Texas with
no experience catering to the under-12 audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pop was of a mind that, `You can do this. You're a
scientist aren't you?' '' Myers said. ``I have to admit that my
first attempts were pretty lousy.''
</P>
<P>
   Years of experience addressing everything from how cats purr to
why snakes flick their tongues honed Myers' skill in writing for
children and taught him some tricks along the way. He uses
analogies to help readers understand a difficult science topic
through something they're already familiar with, and his vocabulary
is a finely tuned kid-friendly without being condescending. When he
talks about an upcoming Highlights article on why there are no
giant insects, for example, Myers becomes especially animated.
``The answer is that an insect doesn't have a very good breathing
mechanism,'' he said. ``It works OK for the little guys, but it
won't work for the big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Replying to children occupied much of Myers' time, but he also
managed to pursue some questions of his own. A renowned expert on
photosynthesis, Myers developed a method of studying algae in a
closed environment that is now used at labs across the world. He
was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1975, and
continues to stay abreast of new advancements by reading several
journals in his office at UT. It was only last year that he finally
gave up his research lab at the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had things in it that I built and made myself and used for
50 years, so that's kind of hard to walk away from,'' he said.
``But it's also true that a university can't provide laboratories
for old guys to play around, so when I wasn't really learning
anything new, it was time for me to fold up, and that's what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   But Myers keeps busy addressing the dozen or so science
questions that come to Highlights each month, and he recently
published his seventh book of short essays about animals, ``What
Happened to the Mammoths?'' (Boyds Mill Press, $17.95). ``Kids deal
in pure curiosity,'' Myers said. ``I know that if you want to grab
them, talk about big, furry animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers responds to every question sent his way and digs into his
memory trove of scientific knowledge and his collection of
textbooks and journals to find the answers. If an explanation is
especially elusive, he'll turn to scientist friends for help,
including Norman Hackerman, who worked with Myers at UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get together over coffee and talk about all kinds of
things,'' Hackerman said. ``Science, world affairs, the heat, where
are you going to park on campus and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at age 87, Myers has no plans to stop writing for the
magazine. He works closely with Andy Boyles, the Highlights science
editor, in approving essay contributions and editing stories, and
he's involved in all major decision with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 40 or 50 years Jack has shaped the way we do
science at Highlights,'' Boyles said. ``If we're ever going to take
a new direction and try something different, we touch base and see
what he thinks about it.'' Boyles said Myers is the most highly
respected member of the company, especially as he continues to
remain so active. ``I know it's hard for me to keep up with him,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Myers has been tackling kids' questions long enough to notice
trends, and while technology and new research continually alter the
fluid scientific world, he says the things that interest children
have remained fairly constant. The most frequent question he
receives is: ``When I take a warm bath, why do my hands crinkle
up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are still taking baths like they did before,'' Myers
said. ``I don't think much has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   WHOLESOME FUN
</P>
<P>
   This could be a theme for the entire Highlights magazine
business. The family-owned corporation has managed to satisfy
generations of children with the same ``wholesome fun'' it used
from the very beginning, like twins Goofus and Gallant who teach
proper manners and Hidden Pictures that require concentration.
</P>
<P>
   The family element has always been important to Highlights,
based in Honesdale, Pa., and Columbus, Ohio. When Garry Myers, a
child psychologist who had written a syndicated newspaper column
about parenting, and Caroline Clark Myers, who had been involved in
family welfare causes, announced they were going to start their own
magazine, their children were ready to help where necessary. They
printed an initial batch of 20,000 copies of Highlights in 1946,
trying to captivate children _ and their parents _ by relying on
fun games and stories with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling magazine was suffering business-wise in 1954, so
Myers' brother, Garry Jr., moved his family to Ohio to help save
Highlights. ``It was the gutsy thing that an engineer would do,''
Myers said. ``You know, engineers figure there isn't any problem
they can't handle.'' In just a few years, Highlights was a
self-supporting entity, and now there are more than 2 million
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the business became a full-fledged success, Garry Jr.
and his wife died when a United Airlines flight collided with
another plane over New York in 1960, leaving their five children
orphaned and the family devastated. With four daughters of their
own, Myers and his wife, Evelyn, welcomed the nephews and nieces,
ranging from ages 8 to 15, into their already full home. ``People
always tell you what a wonderful thing that was to do, but the
facts of life are you just do it because it was something you
needed to do,'' Myers said. ``Every family has its own culture and
putting them together was pretty hard, but we all worked at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong family foundation and common dedication to Highlights
helped keep the Myers clan on track. ``It was a traumatic time in
our lives, but he gave us lots of attention and he was a very good
father figure,'' said Fred Myers, a nephew who was 8 when he came
to live with the family. ``There's a sense of mission about the
magazine in the family and it keeps us all involved.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the current editor of Highlights is Myers' nephew, and
many family members serve on the board of directors. Every year,
they gather in Pennsylvania for a family council meeting to discuss
the magazine. As the oldest living member of the family, Myers'
opinion is highly valued. ``He's definitely the man that everyone
looks up to for advice in the company,'' said Myers' granddaughter
Carrie Holland. ``Whenever I have a question about something he's
the first person I would think to ask because he has such a great
knowledge about things.''
</P>
<P>
   UNCLE JACK
</P>
<P>
   Even nonfamily members in the company regard Myers fondly,
calling him Uncle Jack around the office. ``The editorial staff
here has great respect for Jack as a scientist and an editor and a
writer who speaks to kids in a very honest, forthright way, and we
also have great affection for him,'' said Chris Clark, managing
editor of Highlights. ``He is just a wonderful man, and you always
have the sense that he is going to be very fair with you, even if
it means telling you your judgment's flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   While Myers' research and accomplishments earn respect from
family and friends, what really stands out about him, they say, is
his sense of humor. After raising four daughters he has plenty of
jokes about being outnumbered in a house full of women _ ``It
doesn't take them long to convince you that you have to put the
toilet seat down,'' he said _ and his deep belly laugh completely
envelops listeners. ``Daddy starts every single day with the funny
papers,'' said Myers' oldest daughter, Shirley Wendlandt. ``That's
the first thing he reads, before the news or anything else, and he
almost always finds something to really laugh out loud about.''
</P>
<P>
   This genuine joy for life stems from the fact that he's had a
great one, Myers said. He had such a fulfilling career at UT he
says he often can't understand it when he asks older people how
they stay busy and they say they worked all their lives so they
could retire and do nothing. ``I'm very grateful for being so
lucky,'' Myers said. ``I am grateful that I could be part of a
family endeavor, and that I had 60 years with a great lady who was
my wife. I was able to work as a scientist in an era which I think
was the golden age of science. There was always another challenge
because there was always another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Myers to stop answering them anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
