<HEADER>
A4673 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NY     09-14 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-GORE-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH _ AND A FEW OF GORE'S OTHER FAVORITE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, Sept. 14, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Oprah Winfrey teased a segment on Monday's show by saying
we would soon see a side of Al Gore we'd never seen before, I
cringed.
</P>
<P>
   Did she mean it literally? Was the veep going to give us a rear
view by donning some Lycra bicycle shorts and doing a spin or two
for the benefit of the studio audience and the voters at home?
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't discount such a wacky possibility. Hey, Oprah can get
people to do things on her show that they wouldn't do after six
Cosmpolitans on New Year's Eve at a private party_and Gore for
years has been looking for ways to prove he's the not a Disney
animatronic creation, to wit, smashing ashtrays with David
Letterman in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But when Oprah returned from the commercial break, we found out
we were going to learn more about Gore in a segment that could have
been titled, ``These Are a Few Of Al's Favorite Things.''
</P>
<P>
   (Similar Q-and-A sessions appear in magazines like Vanity Fair.
My favorite question is, ``What are you reading?'' No matter how
dimwitted the sitcom star or monosyllabic the jock, the answer is
always something along the lines of, ``The Evan Thomas biography of
Robert F. Kennedy is awe-inspiring,'' when you know the honest
reply would be, ``Huh? Reading? I just read the room-service menu
and they don't have the egg-white omelette I always order!'')
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we have seen this side of Gore already. Last November,
the New York Times asked Gore to list his favorites in a dozen
categories. For example, Gore told the Times his favorite book was
Stendahl's ``The Red and the Black'' _ a choice he reiterated on
Monday, and a choice I daresay you'll never see trumpeted on
``Oprah's Book Club.''
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned the art of Christo, the wrap-happy environmental
artist who gained some recent pub when Dennis Miller used him as a
punchline on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz greats Thelonius Monk and Miles Davis, country artists
Kathy Mattea and Garth Brooks, ``Les Miserables,'' backyard
barbecues and the TV show ``Futurama'' (for which his daughter
Kristin writes) also garnered plugs from Gore in the New York Times
article.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not as if Oprah's quiz caught Gore by surprise _
although she did toss in a few soft curveballs. Some of the
territory Oprah covered:
</P>
<P>
   Favorite movie: ``Local Hero.'' For suckup points, Gore could
have gone with Oprah-involved efforts such as ``The Color Purple,''
``Beloved'' or even ``Oprah Winfrey Presents 'Tuesdays With
Morrie,''' as the Emmy-award winning mini-series was officially
titled. Had he wanted to demonstrate his self-effacing wit, he
could have blurted, '''Love Story.' It's about me!''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore stuck with the answer he's given before. ``Local Hero''
is a 1983 charmer from writer/director Bill Forsyth about a young
man (Peter Riegert) who is sent to a tiny, eccentric village in
Scotland to secure the rights for an oil refinery. Whimsy and
romance ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder Gore is a fan of this environmentally correct gem,
but I must point out this isn't Riegert's best work, as it cannot
compare to his magnificent performance as Boone in ``Animal
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Meal. ``Chinese,'' said Gore. Get specific, dude!
</P>
<P>
   Cereal. The host and the studio audience were stunned silent by
Gore's first reply: ``Oprah.'' Was he making a joke? Did he have
inside knowledge that the ubiquitous Oprah name would soon be
gracing boxes of breakfast bran?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I said 'favorite cereal,''' Oprah finally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I thought you meant serial like a television serial,''
Gore replied, apparently under the impression that a daytime talk
show falls into the same category as a 1950s soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   He then said ``Wheaties,'' and good for Oprah for expressing her
doubts about that response. God bless Wheaties, but they taste like
... Wheaties. You just know Billy Clinton would have chuckled and
sheepishly said, ``Ah can't help it, Oprah, I still love those
Lucky Charms. They're so magically delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Band. ``The Beatles,'' Gore said. Until recently I would have
concurred, but these days I'd have to go with O-Town. They've won
my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Quote. Do you have a favorite quote you can spout from memory?
Do you know anyone who has a favorite quote? Me neither. But with
barely a hesitation, Gore quoted Bob Dylan: ``Those who are not
busy being born are busy dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone applauded. They might not have known the line is from
Dylan's ``It's Alright, Ma (I'm Only Bleeding),'' a hardcore
protest song about war, government propaganda, commercialism and
``false gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Another line from the song: ``Even the president of the United
States sometimes has to stand naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently this was Clinton's favorite tune as well!
</P>
<P>
   Childhood memory. ``Playing baseball with my dad,'' said the
vice-president, and you could read the sincerity on this face.
</P>
<P>
   I have no joke for that, as I would have said the exact same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper and the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
