<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TOWN-FOR-SALE (Samoa, Calif.) _ This historic company town,
where timber workers and their families once filled all the homes
and traveled by ferry to the ``mainland'' of Eureka, is for sale.
The current owner, Simpson Samoa Co., a subsidiary of the
Seattle-based Simpson Timber Co., has offered the entire town _
including its 98 houses, a well-known restaurant, post office,
playground, restored hostelry and a handful of commercial buildings
_ for sale through a sealed-bid auction that closes Friday. By
EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-EDUCATION (San Antonio) _ Forts Hood in Texas, Benning in
Georgia and Campbell in Kentucky will be the first Army
installations to start a groundbreaking online education program,
according to Army Secretary Louis Caldera. They will serve as the
first three sites for the Army University Access Online education
initiative. The $598 million, six-year program, designed to allow
soldiers to earn degrees while serving at posts in the United
States and overseas, is to begin in January. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-PAINTINGS (San Antonio) _ The Alamo continues to harbor
myriad secrets. Among them are newly discovered frescoes dating to
the Spanish Colonial era. Painstakingly restoration artists Cisi
Jary and Pam Rosser are bringing them to light. By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-PROBE _ A veteran San Francisco Housing Authority
executive denies masterminding a bribery plot and blames the
federal government's politically-connected star witness for the
crimes. By LANCE WILLIAMS and CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-RESCUE (Brownsville, Texas) _ Border Patrol agents are
collecting life vests from undocumented immigrants they encounter
along the banks of the Rio Grande. As immigrants from south of the
U.S.-Mexico border try to thwart hazards that may await them on
their journey north, so, too, are the U.S. Border Patrol and its
counterpart in Mexico, Grupo Beta. Forty members of the two
agencies as well as Mexico's federal police are being trained in
water-rescue techniques. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-MAGAZINE (San Francisco) _ The U.S. Olympic Committee
has dropped its attempt to scrap a magazine's ``Olympics USA''
issue after being assured the publication will be removed from
store shelves Friday. But a committee lawyer says it still plans to
seek damages for violation of its exclusive rights over Olympic
terminology and symbols. The magazine's publisher calls the suit an
unconstitutional interference with freedom of the press. By BOB
EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For the next year at least,
change your mental ``default'' position. Instead of automatically
staying in your job unless you can find a good reason to leave,
plan to quit your job unless you can find a good reason to stay. If
you're talented and willing to learn, this job market is too good
for you to keep rotting away. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDLIFE-LIFEGUARD (Albany, N.Y.) _ Everybody's midlife crisis
takes a different turn. Mine has morphed into dreams of a tall
chair overlooking the beach in Trinidad with sand between my toes
and white stuff on my nose. This summer, I took the Red Cross
lifeguarding course. I had thought, at first, it was going to be
easy. But this is serious business. By MICHAEL VIRTANEN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-OLYMPICS (Undated) _ Some Olympics fans may never come up
from Down Under thanks to the ambitious television coverage of this
year's Summer Games. More hours of the Games than ever before will
be telecast by NBC and its cable networks, MSNBC and CNBC: 441.5
total hours of events from Sydney, Australia _ more than double the
171.5 hours carried on NBC during the Atlanta games of 1996. By
JEANNE JAKLE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PALTROW (Toronto) _ Gwenyth Paltrow talks about her new
karaoke movie ``Duets'' at the Toronto Film Festival. By ERIC
HARRISON.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-APERFECTCIRCLE (Undated) _ How did ``A Perfect Circle''
score the highest debut ever for a new rock band with ``Mer De
Noms?'' We find out from songwriter Billy Howerdel who formed the
band, which also includes Maynard James Keenan, the enigmatic lead
singer of Tool. By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   SOAPS (Undated) _ A look at soaps within movies and TV shows,
including ``Nurse Betty,'' ``28 Days,'' ``Friends'' and ``Soap
Dish.'' By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-SYMPHONY (Houston) _ The Houston Symphony has named
Austrian conductor Hans Graf as its new music director. Graf's
five-year contract will begin with the 2001-2002 season. Graf
succeeds Christoph Eschenbach, who left the post of music director
in May 1999 after 11 seasons. By CHARLES WARD.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEARS (Undated) _ Although they ripen and are harvested the same
time of year, pears have been playing second fiddle to apples since
Eve plucked that fruit in the Garden of Eden. While the apple was
being touted as too inviting to resist, the pear was just another
fruit. Things haven't changed much since Genesis. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   TORTILLAS (San Antonio) _ Tortillas are one of the fastest
growing segments of the baking industry worldwide. In 1998, United
States residents consumed more than 75 billion tortillas. Here is
everything you wanted to know about this popular food. By KAREN
HARAM, JOHN GRIFFIN and BONNIE WALKER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-LAWSUITS (Albany, N.Y.) _ More than 3 million Americans
played golf for the first time last year. So many fledgling
golfers. So many errant shots. So many lawsuits. Doesn't it figure?
Yes, there has been a marked increase in golf course-related
litigation, according to Manhattan-based attorney Robert D. Lang,
who has reviewed cases in New York state. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
