<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MEDIA-DISCOVERS-AMERI     09-14 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-DISCOVERS-AMERICA-SLATE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACK JOURNALISTS DISCOVER 'NEW' AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Slate commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (The following ``separate buy'' article from SLATE, the premier
online magazine of politics and culture, is available from the New
York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Suellentrop writes Slate's ``Pressbox'' column)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY CHRIS SUELLENTROP &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas is no longer dominated by oil rigs, cattle ranches and a
gun-toting, yee-hawing citizenry, the New Republic's Benjamin
Soskis reports. It's a diverse place of suburbs and urban sprawl,
utterly transformed by high-tech industry and out-of-staters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is becoming more like the rest of the nation than
anyone, Texan or non-Texan, wants to admit,'' he marvels in the
cover story now on the newsstands, ``Why Texas Isn't Texas
Anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Soskis isn't the first political reporter to discover the
``new'' character of the provinces beyond the Beltway and
Manhattan. During the 1988 campaign, the Washington Post's Henry
Allen stumbled upon the ``new New Hampshire,'' a state that had
gone ``malltown from milltown.'' The same year, the AP gasped at
New Hampshire's ``high-tech companies'' and ``suburban sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 campaign, The Los Angeles Times' Maria L. LaGanga
was among the first reporters to rely on the ``new'' boilerplate.
The ``New Iowa,'' she wrote, was now home to more high-tech
businesses, more immigrants, and fewer cornfields. Susan Feeney of
The Dallas Morning News offered the ``new New Hampshire'': a
booming high-tech economy dominated by urban sprawl and
out-of-state workers. Feeney put a scholarly gloss on the cliche by
quoting a political scientist who said, ``New Hampshire is becoming
a little bit more like the rest of the country,'' presaging Soskis'
Texas findings.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Eaton of The New York Times and Mark Sappenfield of The
Christian Science Monitor also found Cow Hampshire overrun by
high-tech industry and outsiders. Sappenfield dug up his own
poli-sci expert to say, ``New Hampshire is going to grow closer to
America.''
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign moved to other states, the journalistic pack
detected signs that these places, too, were becoming more like
America. David Von Drehle of The Washington Post wrote that the
``new South Carolina'' was more than ``the old birthplace of the
Confederacy.'' It was a ``showplace for the global economy'' with a
``burgeoning suburbia.'' Steven Thomma of the Knight-Ridder
Washington bureau gaped at South Carolina's ``congested highways,''
``chain stores and malls,'' and ``new suburbs and condos,'' not to
mention the out-of-state newcomers and the concerns about sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popular perception that Michigan elections are still
dominated by legions of auto workers toting lunch pails is as dated
as a Chevrolet Citation,'' wrote The New York Times' Keith
Bradsher. The new Michigan had a ``new economy'' with ``high-tech
professionals,'' many of whom were, you guessed it, newcomers (but
no mention of whether they were concerned about sprawl).
</P>
<P>
   And on and on it has gone, through Virginia and Washington,
through New England and the South on Super Tuesday, until reaching
Texas, where Kenneth T. Walsh of U.S. News &AMP; World Report beat
Soskis to the ``new Texas'' punch in May: More diversity, more
urban residents and, lo and behold, high-tech workers and a booming
economy. ``It used to be that Texas was considered very different
from the rest of the country,'' historian Michael Beschloss told
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these hacks? Why do they insist on filing these ``new''
stories every four years? One possibility is that they're coastal
provincials whose understanding of the flyover territory is so
superficial they don't realize they're debunking long-discredited
stereotypes. Another is that they're just too lazy to bother
checking the archive before writing a story.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, where are their editors, who are supposed to serve
as a publication's institutional memory? They're the ones who
should be telling bored reporters tired of listening to stump
speeches that suburbs and strip malls just aren't newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The real shame is how easy it would be to give these stories the
perspective they lack. As a March Des Moines Register editorial on
Iowa's changing countryside put it: ``There is nothing new about
the New Iowa. Although its cumulative effects are more visible now,
the shift in population from rural to urban areas has been an
inexorable trend for at least a half century.''
</P>
<P>
   Is one sentence of depth too much to ask?
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   Visit Slate on the Web at: http://www.slate.com
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 2000 Slate
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-OLYMPICS-HNS &LR;      09-14 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLYMPICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NBC PLANS MORE COVERAGE FOR SYDNEY GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: All times Eastern unless noted)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEANNE JAKLE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Olympics fans may never come up from Down Under thanks to
the ambitious television coverage of this year's Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   More hours of the Games than ever before will be telecast by NBC
and its cable networks, MSNBC and CNBC: 441.5 total hours of events
from Sydney, Australia _ more than double the 171.5 hours carried
on NBC during the Atlanta games of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The opening ceremony, to be helmed by prime-time Olympics host
Bob Costas and ``Today'' host Katie Couric, airs from 7:30 p.m. to
midnight EDT Friday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Expect pageantry and musical majesty similar to former Olympics
kickoffs. Though the network has tried to keep the surprise element
alive, one detail did escape: Aussie-born Olivia Newton-John of
``Grease'' fame will be among the performers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday through Oct. 1, prime-time and late-night hours as well
as various daytime blocks on NBC will be devoted to the games.
</P>
<P>
   None of the events will be carried live because of the 15-hour
time difference between the East Coast and Sydney; the events will
be presented on tape.
</P>
<P>
   To explain the delay, NBC cites the gymnastics finals, which
will begin at 7 p.m. Sydney time, but at 4 a.m. EDT. In fact, most
finals of the major Olympic sports will happen in the middle of the
night in the United States when, according to NBC, less than 10
percent of the viewing audience is available.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``true fanatics,'' the moniker suggested by NBC Olympics
Executive Producer Dick Ebersol for Olympics junkies, instantaneous
results will be available on the Web at www.nbcolympics.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings for an overseas Olympics such as this one are not
expected to approach the record-breaking 21.6 prime-time rating of
the Games from Atlanta. NBC anticipates a 17.5-18.5 prime-time
rating for the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   However, NBC does predict that total viewership of the Games
will break the 1996 record: 215 million viewers vs. Atlanta's 209
million.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's Olympics host Pat O'Brien, in an interview from Sydney
last week, predicted this could be the greatest Olympics ever based
solely on the dramatic look of the location. ``The Sydney Harbour
has to be the most beautiful harbor in the world,'' he said as an
illustration, adding that NBC will use the sailing competitions to
show that off.
</P>
<P>
   He added that with all the exposure during the games, Sydney
and, really, all of Australia, ``will become a huge star.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyish NBC Sports announcer Costas, a veteran of two previous
Olympics, will act as prime-time host on NBC, weekdays and
weeknights. He'll also host the late-night segments, which will air
from 12:30 p.m. to 2:30 a.m. on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's coverage will focus on a human-interest, storytelling
approach. That way, said David Neal, NBC's head of Olympics
production, the network can make that all-important connection
between the viewer and the athletes. The goal is to make people
care about the competitors, even if the sporting event they're
competing in normally holds no interest for the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That coverage is primarily geared to putting the whole family
in front of the television set,'' Ebersol told a recent news
conference, ``which is, as you know, a rarer and rarer
occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the cable coverage as ``wall-to-wall'' and as
being for the ``pure ... sports fan.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC will concentrate on the major sports of the Olympics:
swimming and diving, track and field, gymnastics, volleyball,
basketball, triathlon and wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's swimming analyst will be Rowdy Gaines, a gold medalist in
that sport. He predicts that ``this Olympics, for swimming, anyway,
will leave a legacy of the greatest in history ... The
USA-vs.-Australia rivalry could be the greatest story of Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said NBC will do its best not to do a cheerleading act
for the Americans by emphasizing every country's strengths. ``We
know back home, viewers will be cheering for Michael Johnson and
Marion Jones, but we're not going to go in for such jingoism.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lampley, a veteran of 10 Olympics, will host MSNBC's
coverage, which will begin each day at 10 a.m. This channel will be
the home of team sports: men's and women's soccer, baseball and
softball.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, a past late-night host of the Winter Games on CBS and
co-anchor of ``Access Hollywood,'' will anchor CNBC's daily
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the latter coverage, which will run from 4 p.m.
to 9 p.m. weekdays (it begins an hour earlier on weekends), will be
two hours of boxing each day. This treat for fight fans wasn't
available before cable channels offered coverage assistance.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien described these events as faster-paced than professional
boxing. ``There's a lot of punching and jabbing,'' he said, adding
that though Cuba seems to have a lock on this sport, viewers may
see some surprises from the United States this go-round.
</P>
<P>
   He said the best thing about the extended cable coverage is that
every sport, from archery to weightlifting, will get its moment in
the sun. ``You'd be surprised how many people like to watch these
little guys lift 5, 6, 800 pounds,'' he said, defending this and
other less-hyped events.
</P>
<P>
   Other signature voices will be aplenty at the Olympics. Andres
Cantor's ``GOOOAL!'' call (which was made famous on the World Cup
broadcasts) will be heard on both women's and men's soccer
telecasts (primarily on MSNBC). Marv Albert will do Olympic boxing
and Tom Hammond will once again do track and field.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of this Olympics that is widely anticipated is
``Twice Born,'' the short film about Muhammad Ali, which is
scheduled to air the second Saturday night of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was generated just one month after the Games in
Atlanta, when Ebersol learned from Ali's kin how the ex-boxer felt
about lighting the Olympic flame. According to Lisa Lax, NBC's
Olympics senior profile producer, Ebersol was told that Ali sat in
his hotel room that night holding his torch and could not sleep a
wink. ``He stayed up the entire night. There were receptions by the
people in the stadium and ultimately by everyone around the world
that were just overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   The film shows, Lax said, ``how he first was introduced to the
world on an international level at the Rome Olympic Games in 1960,
and how he was almost reborn in 1996 when he lit the Olympic flame
in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Jeanne Jakle by email at jjakle(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-ELECTION-$ADV17-     09-14 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ELECTION-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CANDIDATES WOO HIGH-TECH WORLD WITH SIMILAR STANDS
 &HT;    With TECH-ISSUES and TECH-MONEY. Moving in the (w) Washington,
(f) financial and (p) political categories for release Sunday,
Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to high-tech issues, who would make
the better president: George W. Bush or Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   While the race for the White House won't be won by the candidate
who best clears the high technology hurdles, those concerns are
playing an ever-larger role in shaping the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next six years, the U.S. Commerce Department reports,
nearly half the U.S. work force will be employed by makers or users
of information-technology products or services. This sector already
contributes about 35 percent of overall economic growth and about
10 percent of gross domestic output.
</P>
<P>
   An in-depth look at what Bush and Gore have had to say on the
technology front reveals fewer conflicts than similarities.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, however, appears more focused on reaching
out to a wide circle of tech-savvy players, while the vice
president seems more reliant on his long-standing expertise in
these areas. Gore, for example, was deeply involved in the drafting
of a 1997 policy paper that calls for limited government
involvement in Internet e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Key figures helping Bush in the Republican political effort
include fellow Texan Michael Dell, chief executive of Dell Computer
Corp., and Cisco Systems chief executive John Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Republicans have made jokes about Gore saying he
created the Internet, but the fact is that he really believes that
government created the Internet,'' said Floyd Kvamme, a partner at
the Silicon Valley high-tech venture capital firm of Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers and one of California's 324 delegates to
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush,'' Kvamme adds, ``believes the Internet was created by
the entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore cites his long involvement with high-tech issues
and tills the grassroots soil for like-minded community activists,
Bush reaches out to such leading technology industry figures such
as Dell and Kvamme, who act as both his financial backers and
informal advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a much newer figure on the political scene,
so for many months he has been trying to organize key leaders,''
noted Harris Miller, president of the Information Technology
Association of America. While Miller identifies himself as a
Democrat, he says he is pleased with the positions that both the
candidates have taken on key high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of technology executives are in the Bush
camp,'' said William Coleman III, a founder and chief executive of
BEA Systems, a software firm based in San Jose, Calif. Coleman also
participates in the 350-member ``Bush for President High-Tech
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the Gore campaign sought to gather up as
many high-tech business leaders of its own as possible, asking them
to sign a joint letter of support for the Democratic candidate. The
letter is due to be released Monday to coincide with a Silicon
Valley Gore fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporters already include such chief executives as Eric
Schmidt of Novell, Steve Jobs of Apple Computer and Meg Whitman of
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Gore often links technology issues to such broader
themes as the need ``to help American workers beat the foreign
competition to 10 million new high-tech jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   A blurb on the Gore Web site says: ``From early in his
congressional career, Al Gore has focused on the potential of the
information technology age. Al Gore has worked to connect every
classroom in America to the Internet, promoted privacy on-line,
advocated faster Internet connections and he has become a prime
advocate for the development of the Next Generation Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also favors targeted tax cuts aimed at increasing
investment in high-tech research and development, open markets in
cyberspace and better educational opportunities for young people
that would make them fit to assume their place in the ``work force
of tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice the vice president recognizes that high-tech creates
high-paying jobs,'' said Tom Stohler, director of work force policy
for the American Electronics Association. ``But,'' he added, ``it
would take a massive restructuring in the education system and a
tremendous investment in training. We don't have the people to fill
those jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also often uses a wide economic lens to examine the items
that matter most to technology mavens. He stresses his support for
a permanent ban on Internet taxation and the need to offer more
corporate tax credits to enhance technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic platform is silent on the Internet tax,'' says
Tucker Eskew, a senior communications adviser for the Bush campaign
who specializes in technology issues. ``And we view that as our
opponent's lack of commitment to coming down against new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't delved deeply into high-tech at all,'' counters
Dagoberto Vega, a Gore campaign spokesman, referring to Bush's
views. ``They have not addressed any of the 'digital divide'
issues, such as connecting those in disadvantaged areas to the
information highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, has made educational reform a centerpiece of his
campaign, stressing the need to achieve ``the promise of high
standards and accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   To further his goal of ``encouraging continued growth of the New
Economy'' and ensuring that ``all Americans share in its
benefits,'' Bush would dramatically raise the cap of H-1B immigrant
visas; reduce frivolous lawsuits imposed on high-tech companies and
small businesses; strengthen math and science curricula while
creating community technology centers, and provide ``assistive''
technology to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not think of education as a high-tech issue, but it is
the most important issue to high-tech companies,'' said Toni Casey,
the mayor of Los Altos Hills, Calif., who also serves as a
consultant to several Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the candidates, however, has had much to say about
such high-tech-related issues as intellectual property and Internet
copyright law, which has triggered strong judicial pressure against
the Napster music distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   David Foote, the managing partner of an information technology
compensation and workforce research firm in New Canaan, Conn., also
notes that both campaigns have ignored what some industry figures
see as a pressing need for Congress to reform employment-related
labor and tax laws ``that haven't fundamentally (been) changed in
four decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Foote: That's very disturbing (because) these laws will
choke our nation's attempts to field an Information Age work force
to meet the enormous challenges of the New Economy and maintain
America's competitiveness globally.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.algore2000.com; www.georgewbush.com
</P>
