<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-MIGRATION-$ADV17     09-14 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-MIGRATION-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAGEDY AT SEA RENEWS HEATED DEBATE OVER CUBAN IMMIGRATION TO
U.S.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 17
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLON, Cuba - Tears fill Daisy Bueno's(cq) eyes as she opens the
faded greeting card that holds the precious photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Her two handsome sons kneel in one of the pictures, each with a
hand on their beloved boxer, Chester.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy Bueno has only the photographs _ and Chester _ as
reminders of her boys, Juan Carlos, 23, and Alexei(cq), 20.
</P>
<P>
   In early August, the youths became the latest casualties of the
40-year-old cold war between Cuba and the United States. Sneaking
away from home, they boarded a raft along Cuba's north coast and
headed for what they hoped would be new lives of freedom and
opportunity in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, fishermen off Key West spotted their shark-eaten
remains on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understand it,'' said Daisy Bueno, 41. ``They were
such happy boys. Everybody here knew them and liked them. My heart
is broken. I've lost my sons.''
</P>
<P>
   The shocking deaths led to a fresh volley of accusations between
the governments of Cuba and the United States, each blaming the
other for policies they say encourage Cubans like the Bueno
brothers to risk their lives in the treacherous journey across the
Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can calculate just how many have lost their lives this
way, and how many more will do so,'' said a recent editorial in
Granma, the official newspaper of the Cuban Communist Party. The
newspaper has labeled the U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act, which grants
automatic asylum after one year to any Cuban reaching U.S. shores,
``The Killer Law.''
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials say the blame falls at the feet of the Cuban
government. In late August, the State Department sent a blistering
note to the head of the Cuban Interests Section in Washington,
accusing the Cubans of blocking people with visas from leaving the
island, and thus encouraging them to take to the sea in
desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cuban government has consistently failed to take effective
action in response to our continuing and legitimate humanitarian
concerns,'' said the note, which was addressed to Fernando
Remirez(cq), chief of the Cuban diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
   The note specifically mentioned the Bueno brothers, saying their
tragic end ``highlights the growing propensity of Cubans denied the
means to migrate in a safe, orderly and legal fashion to risk their
lives in desperate sea voyages.''
</P>
<P>
   The war of words comes in the wake of a stepped-up campaign by
the government of Cuban leader Fidel Castro to focus world
attention on U.S. immigration policies. Castro began the campaign
during the long-running tug-of-war over 6-year-old Cuban rafter
Elian Gonzalez, who survived a tragic crossing of the Florida
Straits that left his mother and 10 other people dead.
</P>
<P>
   After a tortured court case in the U.S., the boy returned to
Cuba with his father in July, much to the anguish of his relatives
in Miami. It was also a devastating blow to Miami's Cuban exile
community, which for decades had exercised powerful influence over
U.S. policy toward the island.
</P>
<P>
   The willingness of the Cuban exiles to separate Elian from his
father over political beliefs stunned many Americans, bringing
unprecedented attention to U.S.-Cuba relations.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's case is credited with playing a significant role in the
passage of a bill in the U.S. Congress in July that was a major
break with past policy. Although differences in House and Senate
versions of the bill must be resolved in a conference committee
before gaining final approval, it would ease the 40-year-old
embargo against Cuba by allowing the sale of food and medicine to
the island, and would withhold money for enforcing restrictions
barring most U.S. citizens from visiting Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But the angry rhetoric over the immigration issue now appears to
threaten the momentum for a warming of relations.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration has long been the powder keg underlying the
U.S.-Cuba relationship, with several massive waves of Cubans
fleeing by boat triggering crises in the U.S., especially in South
Florida. The most famous exodus, from the Cuban port of Mariel, saw
more than 100,000 Cubans come. The economic crisis sparked by the
fall of Cuba's communist patron, the Soviet Union, prompted a
smaller but longer-running wave in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   After some 38,000 Cubans risked the high seas in 1994 to reach
the United States, the governments reached a new set of agreements
in 1995 that granted 20,000 U.S. entry visas each year to Cubans.
The deal also changed the long-standing U.S. policy of accepting
any Cubans rescued at sea, instead sending them back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But those who reach U.S. soil are still allowed to stay in the
United States, and after the one-year waiting period specified
under the 1966 Cuban Adjustment Act, they are able to win permanent
U.S. residency.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides now say the 1995 agreements are threatened by the
renewed tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The recent State Department note documented 117 cases of Cubans
with U.S. visas who were blocked from leaving the island. The Coast
Guard has also found small but increasing numbers of Cuban rafters
with U.S. visas who said they weren't allowed to leave legally and
finally took to the sea in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans continue to insist it is U.S. policy that encourages
the risky boat trips. Tragedies like that of the Bueno brothers
only give them more ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The two young men were popular in their rural village, which has
not seen a great exodus by raft to Florida, their relatives said.
The farming town is about 150 miles east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Bueno worked at a local radio station as a
technician, while his younger brother Alexei was a carpenter.
Alexei loved to dance, and both youths were popular in town.
</P>
<P>
   Family members shook their heads when asked if they knew the two
were plotting a trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had everything here,'' said their sister, Niobelo
Gonzalez (cq), 27. ``They had jobs, family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bueno family is left with only questions _ and a sense of
loss tinged with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law of the United States encourages people to go to the
sea,'' Gonzalez said. ``If not for that, my brothers would be alive
today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams can be e-mailed at: mikew(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-TECH-ELECTION-$ADV17-     09-14 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ELECTION-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CANDIDATES WOO HIGH-TECH WORLD WITH SIMILAR STANDS
 &HT;    With TECH-ISSUES and TECH-MONEY. Moving in the (w) Washington,
(f) financial and (p) political categories for release Sunday,
Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to high-tech issues, who would make
the better president: George W. Bush or Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   While the race for the White House won't be won by the candidate
who best clears the high technology hurdles, those concerns are
playing an ever-larger role in shaping the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next six years, the U.S. Commerce Department reports,
nearly half the U.S. work force will be employed by makers or users
of information-technology products or services. This sector already
contributes about 35 percent of overall economic growth and about
10 percent of gross domestic output.
</P>
<P>
   An in-depth look at what Bush and Gore have had to say on the
technology front reveals fewer conflicts than similarities.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, however, appears more focused on reaching
out to a wide circle of tech-savvy players, while the vice
president seems more reliant on his long-standing expertise in
these areas. Gore, for example, was deeply involved in the drafting
of a 1997 policy paper that calls for limited government
involvement in Internet e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Key figures helping Bush in the Republican political effort
include fellow Texan Michael Dell, chief executive of Dell Computer
Corp., and Cisco Systems chief executive John Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Republicans have made jokes about Gore saying he
created the Internet, but the fact is that he really believes that
government created the Internet,'' said Floyd Kvamme, a partner at
the Silicon Valley high-tech venture capital firm of Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers and one of California's 324 delegates to
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush,'' Kvamme adds, ``believes the Internet was created by
the entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore cites his long involvement with high-tech issues
and tills the grassroots soil for like-minded community activists,
Bush reaches out to such leading technology industry figures such
as Dell and Kvamme, who act as both his financial backers and
informal advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a much newer figure on the political scene,
so for many months he has been trying to organize key leaders,''
noted Harris Miller, president of the Information Technology
Association of America. While Miller identifies himself as a
Democrat, he says he is pleased with the positions that both the
candidates have taken on key high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of technology executives are in the Bush
camp,'' said William Coleman III, a founder and chief executive of
BEA Systems, a software firm based in San Jose, Calif. Coleman also
participates in the 350-member ``Bush for President High-Tech
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the Gore campaign sought to gather up as
many high-tech business leaders of its own as possible, asking them
to sign a joint letter of support for the Democratic candidate. The
letter is due to be released Monday to coincide with a Silicon
Valley Gore fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporters already include such chief executives as Eric
Schmidt of Novell, Steve Jobs of Apple Computer and Meg Whitman of
eBay.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Gore often links technology issues to such broader
themes as the need ``to help American workers beat the foreign
competition to 10 million new high-tech jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   A blurb on the Gore Web site says: ``From early in his
congressional career, Al Gore has focused on the potential of the
information technology age. Al Gore has worked to connect every
classroom in America to the Internet, promoted privacy on-line,
advocated faster Internet connections and he has become a prime
advocate for the development of the Next Generation Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also favors targeted tax cuts aimed at increasing
investment in high-tech research and development, open markets in
cyberspace and better educational opportunities for young people
that would make them fit to assume their place in the ``work force
of tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice the vice president recognizes that high-tech creates
high-paying jobs,'' said Tom Stohler, director of work force policy
for the American Electronics Association. ``But,'' he added, ``it
would take a massive restructuring in the education system and a
tremendous investment in training. We don't have the people to fill
those jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also often uses a wide economic lens to examine the items
that matter most to technology mavens. He stresses his support for
a permanent ban on Internet taxation and the need to offer more
corporate tax credits to enhance technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic platform is silent on the Internet tax,'' says
Tucker Eskew, a senior communications adviser for the Bush campaign
who specializes in technology issues. ``And we view that as our
opponent's lack of commitment to coming down against new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't delved deeply into high-tech at all,'' counters
Dagoberto Vega, a Gore campaign spokesman, referring to Bush's
views. ``They have not addressed any of the 'digital divide'
issues, such as connecting those in disadvantaged areas to the
information highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, has made educational reform a centerpiece of his
campaign, stressing the need to achieve ``the promise of high
standards and accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   To further his goal of ``encouraging continued growth of the New
Economy'' and ensuring that ``all Americans share in its
benefits,'' Bush would dramatically raise the cap of H-1B immigrant
visas; reduce frivolous lawsuits imposed on high-tech companies and
small businesses; strengthen math and science curricula while
creating community technology centers, and provide ``assistive''
technology to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not think of education as a high-tech issue, but it is
the most important issue to high-tech companies,'' said Toni Casey,
the mayor of Los Altos Hills, Calif., who also serves as a
consultant to several Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the candidates, however, has had much to say about
such high-tech-related issues as intellectual property and Internet
copyright law, which has triggered strong judicial pressure against
the Napster music distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   David Foote, the managing partner of an information technology
compensation and workforce research firm in New Canaan, Conn., also
notes that both campaigns have ignored what some industry figures
see as a pressing need for Congress to reform employment-related
labor and tax laws ``that haven't fundamentally (been) changed in
four decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Foote: That's very disturbing (because) these laws will
choke our nation's attempts to field an Information Age work force
to meet the enormous challenges of the New Economy and maintain
America's competitiveness globally.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.algore2000.com; www.georgewbush.com
</P>
