u p BC-TECH-ISSUES-$ADV17-CO     09-14 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ISSUES-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TECH-ELECTION. Moving in the (w) Washington, (f) financial
and (p) political categories for release Sunday, Sept. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here's a rundown on how the Democratic and
Republican presidential candidates stand on key high-tech issues:
</P>
<P>
   Internet taxation: Both Al Gore and George W. Bush favor
extending the current moratorium. But Bush, citing the problems of
trying to collect sales tax from millions of customers in thousands
of jurisdictions, would make the ban permanent, while Gore favors
an keeping it place ``for at least two more years.'' Gore also
would pursue an international accord making cyberspace ``a
permanent duty-free zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Online privacy: Bush is highly sensitive to privacy concerns,
employing a policy that the campaign will use data provided by
visitors to his campaign Web site only if they ``opt in.'' But many
Republicans in Congress favor allowing business to regulate itself,
which federal regulators argue won't work. Gore often stresses the
need for Internet privacy as part of his broader consumer-oriented
message.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech foreign policy: After a long delay, the Clinton
administration aggressively scaled back export controls, a policy
stance for which Gore takes some credit. Bush distances himself
from both old Cold War hawks and intelligence figures in government
who argue that less regulation carries more security risks. Both
candidates would take further steps to combat piracy of American
ideas and intellectual property and promote the development of
internationally compatible standards for e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   H-1B visas: Both Bush and Gore favor increasing the number of
visas for high skilled foreign workers, which many business leaders
feel are needed to keep U.S. companies from falling behind the rest
of the world in the technology race. But organized labor, a vital
Democrat constituency, opposes any increases.
</P>
<P>
   Tort Reform: Gore is politically tied to the trial lawyers
community, which opposes any changes in current laws, citing the
need to protect the rights of wronged consumer litigants. However,
Gore's running mate, Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut has broken
with party regulars to support for securities litigation reform. As
Texas governor, Bush compiled a strong record on this issue, which
concerns many high-tech entrepreneurs, and can be expected to press
for major reforms as president.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent R&AMP;D tax credits: They are supported strongly by Bush,
by most congressional Republicans and by such ``New Democrats'' as
Lieberman. But a President Gore would likely encounter strong
opposition from tradition-bound Democrats in Congress, who have
blocked all such legislation for research and development subsidies
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Government information reform: Bush favors naming a
government-wide chief information officer and providing a $100
million fund to support interagency information sharing and
electronic procurement initiatives. Gore's vice presidential
``re-inventing government'' effort did not include those
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
