<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-14 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A GOOD SEASON TO THINK ABOUT YOUR FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Getting up and deciding that you're going to
keep the same job you had yesterday is a career decision. Sure, it
might not feel like one because there is no drum roll or blare of
internal trumpets, but if you don't appreciate that you have a
crucial choice in your hands each morning, you might as well be a
lemming.
</P>
<P>
   For the next year at least, change your mental ``default''
position. Instead of automatically staying in your job unless you
can find a good reason to leave, plan to quit your job unless you
can find a good reason to stay. If you're talented and willing to
learn, this job market is too good for you to keep rotting away.
</P>
<P>
   People rarely get into miserable careers because of one stupid
decision, like not going to college or calling a boss a fool or
having an affair with the boss. Usually it's because they make the
same stupid ``little'' decision to go to the same job each day,
even though the job gets a little worse and their options get a
little more limited as each month passes.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the best time of year to quit your job, because
your internal procrastinator could well be in hibernation. Wait a
couple of months and you're close to Thanksgiving and Christmas,
and who wants to be job hunting during the holidays? Summer is out,
because you want to take a family vacation, and spring gets tough
because you're already thinking about the family vacation, and
either a new job or unemployment could spoil those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you could do it after the first of the year, but your
internal procrastinator will gladly point out that the groundhog
just might see his shadow on Feb. 2, and that would lead to six
more weeks of winter. And who wants to be out pounding the street
looking for work when it's so damp and cold, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   So get moving now, before all those falling leaves block your
path.
</P>
<P>
   If you've already made the same little decision 10,000 times or
so in your career, finding the exit door can be so intimidating
that it feels impossible. We were brought up learning that careers
had a logical progression, and that you could have a great career
if you found a quality company and stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   And if you did change jobs, it was part of a logical
progression, too. You landed a promotion or found a more
prestigious company or got a big raise _ sometimes all of the
above. Leaving wasn't all that tough of a decision.
</P>
<P>
   But now it is. Many careers don't offer the kinds of
opportunities they used to, and sometimes the only way you can get
ahead is to make a leap of faith. You might have to change careers
or at least tweak yours, and often that forces you to settle
temporarily for less pay or longer hours or a less prestigious
company.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, too, people are so overwhelmed that they never have
any time to hunt for a job. If you're in that situation and don't
see any logical way out, you might have to make the ultimate leap
of faith: Quit without having anything else lined up.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that sounds incredibly scary. But it's probably not nearly
as scary as you think it is, especially in this market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
