<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-OLYMPICS-MAGAZINE-HNS     09-14 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-MAGAZINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPICS COMMMITTEE TO SEEK DAMAGES FROM MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The U.S. Olympic Committee has dropped its
attempt to scrap a magazine's ``Olympics USA'' issue after being
assured the publication is scheduled to be removed from store
shelves on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But a USOC lawyer said Wednesday the committee still plans to
seek damages for violation of its exclusive rights over Olympic
terminology and symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of the magazine called the lawsuit an
unconstitutional interference with freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   The 76-page magazine was published last month by American Media
Inc., which also publishes the National Enquirer, Globe and Star
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Committee said the magazine's repeated use of the
word ``Olympics,'' along with stylized depictions of the Olympic
torch and medals, violated the trademarks granted to the committee
by federal law.
</P>
<P>
   American Media Inc. said the law does not _ and, under the First
Amendment, could not _ apply to journalistic coverage of the
Olympic Games, which begin Friday in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   At a federal court hearing Wednesday in Oakland, the publisher's
lawyer, Roger Myers, displayed the latest Newsweek cover and an
Olympics section of the New York Times, both of which featured
Olympics words and symbols. He said his client's publication, which
contains a disclaimer of any Olympic sponsorship or official
connection, is no different from more established media and is
equally protected from USOC interference.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Saundra Brown Armstrong seemed unpersuaded.
</P>
<P>
   In the Newsweek and Times editions, she said, ``it's very clear
what the origin of the publication is.'' Although the name ``AMI
Specials'' appears in a corner of the magazine cover, Armstrong
said, the ``Olympics USA'' inscription and photos of athletes are
much larger, giving the USOC a ``legitimate concern'' that it will
be mistaken for an official publication.
</P>
<P>
   USOC lawyer Jeffrey Benz insisted the Olympic Committee was not
trying to interfere with news reporting, only commercial
exploitation of the names and symbols the committee licenses for
revenue to support the U.S. Olympic team. However, Benz withdrew
the request for a restraining order against distribution of the
magazine after Myers said virtually all copies would be taken off
the shelves by Friday, as previously scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Benz said the committee would continue with its damage suit for
trademark violation. The suit contends the magazine harmed the USOC
economically by cheapening its trademarks and encouraging others to
use the names and symbols without paying for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
