<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-KORMAN-2TAKES     09-14 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-KORMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US GYMNASTICS COACH PETER KORMANN HAS THE SPIRIT OF '76 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The house on Elm Street was their screening room, their place to
study, to dream. In the grainy, scratchy, and often-choppy visions
that would come to life on the living room wall in Braintree,
Mass., through the miracle of Super 8mm film, the four friends
would take apart the tumbles and vaults of the world's best
gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the Soviet Union were the powers of the day. Peter
Kormann and his childhood pals knew every athlete by name, envied
their every move, rolled the 8mm frames to and fro until they could
copy every twist and turn of their routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you walked in that house, there were little pieces
of film,'' said Kormann. ``There was nothing like it. We had a
splicing machine and we'd chop the film up to pieces and watch
these guys, day in, day out. We wanted to be the best. We had quite
the study group. I only wish I'd spent that much time on my school
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 44 years old, Kormann is the head coach of the USA men's
Olympic gymnastics squad. His days of cinematic home study are some
30 years behind him, but he is as immersed in the sport today as he
was before and during his years at Braintree High School.
</P>
<P>
   In the Summer Games of '76, inside the Montreal Forum, the
20-year-old Kormann surprised the world when he won a bronze medal
in floor exercise, the first American male to win an Olympic
gymnastics medal since 1932. For the near quarter-century since, he
has not stopped tumbling, although he suspects Sydney will mark the
conclusion of his tour as the head of the men's program with USA
Gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is it for me. My term is up here,'' said Kormann,
just before his squad folded its Olympic training camp in San Diego
and headed to Sydney. ``Maybe I'll go run a gymnastics club.
Ultimately, my goal would be to get back to Massachusetts, but
we'll see where all this leads. Right now, my whole focus is on the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   There is focus, and then there is Kormann focus, nothing short
of riveting when it comes to gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' said longtime pal Kent Anderson, ``loves the sport
like Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, now a veterinarian in rural Orwell, Vt., helped
introduce Kormann to the sport in the mid-1960s when they were
school friends in Braintree. Kormann remembers it as somewhat of
accidental introduction. The boys were awaiting a ride after
swimming lessons at the YMCA. Rather than sit on the sidewalk, they
wandered upstairs to the Y's gymnasium, where instructor Jimmy Hutt
was watching over the pommel horse, rings, and parallel bars.
Anderson was the one who pushed the door open and found the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really knew what gymnastics was,'' said Kormann. ``And
there was this guy (Hutt) standing there, and he says to us, `Hey,
you want to try this, try that? Come over here, try this.' I just
remember doing a handstand on the floor. That was it. If our
parents had been on time to pick us up, who knows, maybe we never
would have done gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutt, who owns and operates a Lakeville, Mass. gymnastics club,
the Gym Hutt, remembers the day the two walked into his gym. It was
not an epiphany. He wasn't aware that a future Olympic medalist had
entered the room. Music didn't play. A ray of sunshine wasn't cast
on Kormann's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't work that way,'' said Hutt. ``I wish it did, but I
can tell you, it doesn't. Peter was one of those rare kids who had
a natural ability _ the ability, right away, to know where he was
when he was upside-down.''
</P>
<P>
   What eventually separated Kormann from a billion and one other
tumblers and vaulters, said Hutt, was an obsessive work ethic. From
that brief introduction in the YMCA gym, Kormann took off down a
path of total, if not addictive, dedication to his sport. Roughly
10 years later, from that standing start in the Quincy (Mass.)
YMCA, Kormann was standing at the top of Olympus, bronze draped
around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of success in gymnastics has something to do with a
burning desire to do something that's crazy,'' said Hutt, who
considers himself the first in a long line of Braintree gymnasts.
``But it's hard work that gets everything done. Peter had it in
him. He wanted it _ really, really bad. And he was willing to work
for it. Hey, there's a lot of people out here with talent. The
problem is, most people sit on it and don't do anything with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kormann wasn't a sitter. In fact, all of Mary and Marty
Kormann's kids seemed born to tumble. Sitting in her living room
recently, Mary Kormann looked out onto Middle Street, laughing as
she recalled the astonished looks on the faces of passersby when
they happened to glance toward the house's large picture window.
</P>
<P>
   ``From out there,'' said Mary, ``all they could see was sets of
feet going by the window in here. It would be Peter and the other
kids walking on their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   By Mary's account, Peter instantly became hooked, ``totally
addicted,'' to the sport. His closest pals all loved it, too. There
were the Ellis brothers, Dave and Rich, over on Elm Street, where
the charter school of gymnastics cinematogrpahy eventually would be
formed. Anderson was just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the four of them ate, drank and, in the rare instance
that fatigue set in, slept the sport. The Ellis brothers _ Dave
some eight years older than Kormann _ built a backyard gymnasium on
Ellis Street. Kormann did the same behind his house. Eventually,
the gymnastics coach at Braintree High, Joe Schuhwerk, retired the
school's old pommel horse, allowing Kormann to make it a carry-home
claimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pommels on it were gone,'' said Schuhwerk, recently
retired as the school' athletic director. ``It was an old beast.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about 4 a.m., recalled Marty Kormann, that he tied that
old pommel horse to the back of the family station wagon and
steered it through Braintree Square. Peter stood with it in back,
making certain it wouldn't tip when they rounded a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went by a cop in the Square,'' said Marty, an ex-Marine,
``and he didn't know what the hell to think.''
</P>
<P>
   All through his high school years, Kormann, along with his three
close friends, made gymnastics the core holding of his life. Dave
Ellis, an accomplished gymnast at Springfield College, took the
boys to countless meets around the country. They traveled to Penn
State. They traveled to Illinois. Dave would get summer jobs at
sports camps, teaching gymnastics, and Kormann, Anderson, and
brother Rick always came along as junior counselors/freeloaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never had to pay,'' said Dave Ellis, who now runs the
Ellis School of Gymnastics in Braintree. ``All of us had a love for
it. It was just a fun, very innocent time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dave Ellis was in the stands at Montreal when Kormann won the
bronze. He says he still gets goosebumps when he thinks of the
``the skinny little kid from Braintree'' standing up on the medal
platform, shoulder to shoulder with Russia's Nikolai Andrianov and
Vladimir Marchenko.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost unbelievable,'' said Ellis. ``Here's a kid from
our hometown, standing there with those guys. I mean, you can't
dream that dream.''
</P>
<P>
   A celebration immediately followed. Kormann and his teammates
headed out on the streets of Montreal. By the time he got back to
the Olympic village, the gates were locked, the tragedy of Munich
four years before forever altering the free spirit surrounding the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, after all those trips to all those camps, Kormann,
the medal around his neck, bunked down in the back of Dave Ellis's
van and slept until the village reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome to be an Olympic medalist,'' said Kormann. ``I
mean, I don't think that much about it anymore, but for that period
of my life . . . I won the first medal for the United States in 44
years, so that was very special for all of us in gymnastics.''
</P>
<P>
   Kormann can't remember the exact whereabouts of the medal today
(``It's in limbo _ somewhere in the house,'' he said), but Steve
Randall, his pal from Southern Connecticut State can recall every
step of Kormann's floor routine in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full in . . . double back,'' said Randall, who now runs the
Maine Academy of Gymnastics in Westbrook, Maine. ``How could I
forget? I used to watch him every day in college. And with each
move, I was in the stands, thinking, `Stick! Stick! Stick!' A
straddle `L' . . . press handstand . . . `Stick! Stick! Stick!'
What a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-KORMANN-2ND &LR;  &UR;      09-14 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-KORMANN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... a performance.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randall made his way to Montreal by car, with legendary Southern
Conn. and Olympic coach Abie Grossfeld at the wheel. In 1973,
Kormann was hoping to go to gymnastic powerhouse Penn State out of
Braintree High, but was dismissed out of hand by Penn State coach
Gene Wettstone. It was Schuhwerk, his high school coach, who
introduced Kormann to Grossfeld and Wettstone the same day,
following a meet at Southern Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abie was great,'' said Kormann. ``He said, `Yeah, we'd love to
have you on our team. We've got no scholarship, but we'd love to
have you.' And Gene, who's a great guy, he says to me, `Yeah, I saw
your scores and I don't think you're Penn State material. We don't
need a floor specialist.'''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Wettstone was the assistant coach on the
men's team when Kormann won the medal .
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great for me,'' said Kormann, refusing an opporutnity
to gloat. ``And I've got to say, during my college years, I always
had my best meets against Penn State.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his freshman year at Southern Conn., during the summer
of '74, Kormann went to Japan to study gymnastics. The Japanese had
powerful teams and Kormann had long studied the best performers at
the Ellis Home Theater. He wrote a blind letter to the College of
Physical Education in Japan, asking the gymnastics coach if he
could train with the nation's elite team in Tokyo over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him in the letter that I'd clean the gym, teach
English, whatever they wanted, I'd do it,'' said Kormann. ``He
wrote back and said I could come.''
</P>
<P>
   For four months, Kormann lived in a near-monastic gymnastics
bubble. A few members of the Japanese squad spoke bits of English,
but virtually all of his communicating for four months was done by
sign language on the gym floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``So four four months, there was nothing else for me to do but
gymnastics,'' said Kormann. ``I couldn't talk to anybody. Total
commitment there was mandatory. I loved every second of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His devotion in those days almost baffles Kormann now. He was so
intent on beginning his college workouts, he left for Southern
Conn. the day after his final class at Braintree High. His BHS
diploma arrived in the mail. The day he packed up for college, he
told his high school sweetheart (and now wife), Linda Nelligan,
``Linda, I'm busy, I won't have time to see you.'' They saw each
other only three times during their college years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't care about anything else in life,'' he said.
``At that time of my life, all I wanted to do was gymnastics. Of
course, I was proud to graduate from high school . . . but I was on
a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The task at hand now is Sydney. The Kormann mission now entails
trotting six Americans to the gym floor, hoping that at least one
of them can head for home with the feeling of accomplishment and
honor that he felt in '76.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be awesome to do it as a coach,'' he said. ``That
would be, in my opinion, more awesome than what happened in '76. To
be honest, I'd feel I worked harder for this. When you train as an
athlete, you just focus on yourself and you work hard and you know
what to do. But as a coach, there are so many variables, so many
things that have to get done. It's a constant process of coming up
with ways to get our guys better.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in Orwell, Vt., Anderson will be paying close attention.
Almost 35 years ago, he was the one who nudged the door open at the
YMCA, discovered the gym, and began the odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a cool thing we had in Braintree,'' said Anderson.
``Guys like Jimmy Hutt, Dave Ellis, Joe Schuhwerk, they took care
of us. We're all like family. Pete made the most of it. He had such
a passion. He threw tricks in high school that no one had ever
done. You need a talent for that, but you also need the hard work
and guts. Peter had all of that. More than anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
