<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-14 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING KIDS WHO ARE HIP TO THE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When advertising honchos gather inside the Grand Hyatt Hotel in
New York this week to bestow the third annual Golden Marble awards
for children's advertising (Best Breakfast Food Commercial, Best
Video Game Commercial, etc.), health-care professionals and
educators will be protesting outside.
</P>
<P>
   They argue there is no such thing as a good advertisement
pitched at a child.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasoning boils down to this: Children are unable to fend
off advertising, making them vulnerable to any marketing aimed at
them. Because so much is aimed at them, the cumulative message they
get is a warped one, that happiness comes from consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Children have been marketing targets since radio days, of
course, but the exposure for previous generations pales in
comparison to the doses our children get, says psychologist Susan
Linn, associate director of the Media Center at the Judge Baker
Children's Center, which is spearheading the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why, she says: Corporations spend $2 billion a year on
print and TV ads aimed at children, 20 times more than 10 years
ago. What's more, she says, that figure swells to $12 billion when
you add in sales promotions and product placement in movies and TV,
as well as increasingly popular in-school advertising. In a report
released earlier this week, the Federal Trade Commission concluded
that Hollywood media systematically target children in advertising
and marketing even when the products in question contain parental
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   From a marketing perspective, aiming ads at children is smart
business. Not only do they spend $8 billion of their own money each
year, but they also weigh in heavily on what their parents buy:
Estimates of children's purchasing influence range from $130-$500
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of many psychologists, aiming ads at
children is unethical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What parents need to know is that the sheer amount of
advertising children are exposed to is emotionally harmful, above
and beyond the impact of any single ad or product or whether the
product is good or bad,'' says psychologist Allen Kanner of
Berkeley, Calif., who studies the impact of advertising on
children. He is calling for the American Psychological Association
to censure psychologists who advise companies on how to market to
children, and is particularly appalled that even babies aren't
off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that companies gear ads to baby viewers per se, but
that they tie products to baby and toddler programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your 15-month-old watches `Teletubbies.' She gets a warm
feeling from it. When she sees the toy, she gets excited: It's
familiar, it's secure,'' says early childhood educator Diane Levin
of Wheelock College, a coorganizer with Linn.
</P>
<P>
   If the toy has a logo on it (and what toy doesn't these days?)
and the logo is shown on the screen, the baby makes the connection.
Voila: ``Brand loyalty even in a 15-month-old because he associates
that familiar logo with that warm, happy feeling,'' says Levin.
</P>
<P>
   It's precisely for that warm feeling that big companies like
Ford advertise in Sports Illustrated for Children. An 8-year-old
can't buy a car, but he can nag dad to buy a Ford, says media
researcher David Walsh. (Indeed, advertisers commonly rate ads on
the ``nag factor,'' the extent to which an ad motivates children to
pester parents.) Meanwhile, by the time a child can buy a car, Ford
feels as safe and comfortable to him as the baby toy did.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that most young children can't tell the
difference between commercials and programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take it all at face value,'' says educator and filmmaker
Jean Kilbourne, whose documentary on advertising, ``Killing Us
Softly,'' is shown around the world.
</P>
<P>
   When a toy that looks giant-size and magical on TV turns out to
be small and boring in real life, it never occurs to a 3-year-old
that there's something wrong with the toy; he doesn't have the
cognitive skills to form that thought. Here's what he's more likely
to think, says Levin:
</P>
<P>
   `` `On TV, kids playing with this toy were happy, so if I'm not
happy, too, there must be something wrong with me.' '' When the
next toy is no better, she says, he moves on to the next and the
next.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this set up consumerism as a positive value, but
it also equates it to happiness and success in a child's mind, says
Linn. A typical 3- to 6-year-old might conclude, for instance, ``I
won't play with you because you don't have that wrestling toy, and
that means we won't have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   As children become older and increasingly anxious to fit in with
peers, advertisers not only feed into insecurities but help create
them, says Kanner, on the faculty at Wright Institute in Berkeley.
One ad that particularly riles him is for Corona beer. He saw it
air in California during Saturday morning cartoons, when viewers
are typically younger than 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows two teens dressed in bikinis carrying a bucket of ice
and beer down the beach to a group of other happy-looking teens.
The message, even to little kids, is clear,'' he says: `` `This is
how to be cool when you grow up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For a child in a have-not family, the constant drumbeat of
consume, consume can fuel inadequacies as well as resentment of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising drives a wedge between parent and child without
parents even realizing it,'' says Walsh. He is president of the
National Institute on Media and the Family, a nonprofit group that
looks at media's effect on children, and author of ``Selling Out
America's Children'' (Fairview Press).
</P>
<P>
   Levin says the wedge first gets lodged in the preschool years:
``A 4-year-old looks at an ad for a toy and says, `This is a toy,
toys are for kids, I want this.' '' When parents say no, she says,
``a child can't see the distinction between a good toy and a bad
one. All she sees is, `You're a mean parent: Can't you see this is
a toy, and toys are for kids?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most disturbing marketing trend is the proliferation
of advertisements in schools. Kilbourne says fiscally strapped
districts are increasingly taking money and equipment from
corporations like Pepsi or Coca-Cola in exchange for ads on school
buses, scoreboards, or book covers, or for exclusive rights to put
soda machines in hallways. So far, about 8 million children are
affected.
</P>
<P>
   For Kilbourne, this is unconscionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is a place for learning, for facts,'' she says. ``An ad
on school property legitimizes the product in a way nothing else
can, making the ad's claim true.'' Kilbourne wrote ``Deadly
Persuasion, Why Women and Girls Must Fight the Addictive Power of
Advertising'' (Free Press).
</P>
<P>
   With the trend obviously toward more advertising, Walsh hopes
protests like the one in New York will raise public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Linn says the group's goal is for a White House conference on
the dangers of marketing to children, as well as legislation to ban
ads for products known to be harmful to children. Kilbourne says
other countries, including Belgium, Norway, and Denmark, outlaw
radio and TV advertisements aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who don't want to wait for legislation, there
are steps we can take at home to insulate our children against
advertising messages, beginning by not leaving the room when
commercials come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay and analyze it, even with a 3- or 4-year-old,'' says
Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Start by defining advertising for her. For instance: ``Do you
know what the job of a commercial is? It's to get us to buy
something that isn't as special as the ad makes it seem or that we
don't really need, even though the ad makes us think we do. Ads use
clever tricks, so the fun is to figure out the trick each ad has.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity endorsements have a lot of power for 5- to
8-year-olds. Ask, ``Do you know why Nike has Michael Jordan wear
their sneakers? Because they want you to think that if you buy
them, you'll play like him. Isn't that silly?'' Be sure to say that
celebrities are paid to make a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are some good ads for good products out there, and
it's fine to acknowledge them when you see them, says Kanner. But
over all, he says, ``The message of consume, consume, is behind
them all. That's what adds up as the over-riding message.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
