<HEADLINE>
MASTER CHEF FOR SISTER'S WEDDING EATS HIS CAKE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE YONAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was up to my ears in corn. Shucking, plunging, boiling,
scraping. Kernels were flying everywhere, and water foamed over the
pots.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I had hours to go before I would be through, I was
already worried about how to get this borrowed kitchen, now flecked
from top to bottom with corn and corn juice, back into condition by
the time its owner came home from work.
</P>
<P>
   The next day was my sister Rebekah's home-grown Maine wedding,
and my gift to her was the food, including a white
chocolate-pistachio wedding cake, for 60 guests. No caterer here.
Twenty-four hours later, the feast would be a success, but not
without glitches, not without help, and not without plenty of
lessons learned for a first-timer like myself.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling off a meal for 60 people requires an extraordinary level
of planning, plenty of advance work, the assistance of as many
skilled friends as you can find, and the flexibility to roll with
the punches when things don't go as planned. Believe me, they
won't.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the wedding, in a borrowed kitchen, as I
struggled alone with 45 ears, stripping them with my cook's knife,
soaking every towel and mitt in sight, and dotting the kitchen with
yellow, the first lesson hit me like corn flying off the cob: Do as
much in advance as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Why hadn't I done all this corn ahead of time, over several
days, freezing the kernels as I went? It would've made much
smoother going on this particular dish, individual corn flans with
a tomato-corn relish. I could have even mixed the custards in
advance. That way, when I left wedding-prep central at my sister's
house in North Berwick, Maine, where my friends were working on
recipes I had left them, I wouldn't be gone long. Instead, I blew
most of the day, alone and covered with corn.
</P>
<P>
   I should've followed the example I had set for myself with the
cake, a creation I designed using recipes adapted from the
Cambridge School of Culinary Arts, from which I graduated last
year. Following Rose Levy Beranbaum's invaluable advice from ``The
Cake Bible,'' I had frozen the layers weeks earlier, so all that
was left was the frosting, assembly, and decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson two: Choose recipes carefully. Take into account not only
taste and presentation but ease of preparation and service. That
means testing the recipes to familiarize yourself with the steps,
then remembering that what is easy for four isn't necessarily easy
for 60.
</P>
<P>
   This one I had down. For such a do-it-yourself wedding in
mid-August, outside a tiny house, I knew I wanted dishes with bold
summer flavors, bright colors, and few ingredients, most of which
would come out of the garden or chicken coop right on the property.
I settled on a collection of recipes gathered from Gourmet
magazine, Boston Globe food pages, Paula Wolfert's ``Mediterranean
Greens and Grains,'' and the recesses of my mind. The lineup: an
appetizer table of smoked fish, cheese, cumin-dried tomatoes, and a
celery Nicoise salad, and a dinner of cold cucumber and avocado
soup, rosemary-grilled chicken, corn flans, Tuscan kale with garlic
and white beans, potato and green bean salad with blue cheese, and
Asian beet salad.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens, raised by the bride and groom, could be cooked on
a large cement-block grill in the outdoor kitchen set up by my
future brother-in-law, Peter Kellman, and almost everything else
could be served cold. After the appetizers, we'd sit for the soup
course; the remainder of the dinner would be buffet-style.
</P>
<P>
   Advance recipe testing proved crucial. Before I settled on the
corn flans, for instance, I wanted to know if they were sturdy
enough to be moved from a serving platter to a plate without
falling apart. I also made sure the flans and the soup could be
held for a day or so without losing flavor or, in the case of the
beautiful light-green soup, without changing color to a
less-appetizing shade.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson three: Get help from experienced friends, and then be
nice to them. Stephen Powell and Edouard Fontenot were my
workhorses. They've worked in catering and at restaurants, and
Stephen was professionally trained at Anne Willan's La Varenne
cooking school. That meant, for example, that he instinctively knew
to ``French'' the green beans, or cut them on an angle, without any
direction from me. And when Edouard was arranging the smoked fish
on a plate, he naturally had a basket of herbs and flowers at the
ready. He beautifully fanned out the pieces of fish and garnished
them with nasturtiums.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson four: When things go wrong, don't be afraid to take
charge, but ask for input and be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   While we were scrambling, one of my friends discovered there
were no small plates for appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slice more bread, and put out more napkins,'' I said. The
guests didn't notice a thing. They ate right off the platters or
put the tomatoes, fish, and cheese on pieces of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson five: Try to enjoy yourself. If possible, arrange for
others to be in charge of such things as table settings and
cleanup. As the proud brother of the bride, I wanted to make sure
that, after the food was finished, I could take my place at the
table and eat, drink, and celebrate with family and friends. That
meant depending on another sister, Teri, to handle such crucial
elements as the table decorations, menu cards, buffet setup, and
cake cutting, and letting others haul away dirty dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if the feast is a success (which this was), it's nice
to be sitting when the bride and groom toast your efforts and the
satisfied guests break into applause (which they did).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Cucumber-Avocado Soup &QL; 
Adapted from Gourmet Magazine, July 2000 &QL; 
Serves 6 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 ripe avocado, peeled, pitted, and diced &QL; 
2 English cucumbers, peeled and diced &QL; 
1 cup whole-milk yogurt &QL; 
6 tablespoons fresh chives, chopped &QL; 
1 teaspoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
1 cup ice cubes &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reserving 1/2 of avocado and 3 tablespoons chives, blend remaining
ingredients in a blender until very smooth and frothy. Serve
immediately, in chilled bowls. Garnish each bowl with a few chunks
of avocado and a large pinch of chives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cumin-Dried Tomatoes &QL; 
Makes 20 &QL; 
 &QL; 
10 ripe tomatoes &QL; 
10 teaspoons cumin seed, toasted and ground &QL; 
1/4 cup olive oil &QL; 
Salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
 &QL; 
Preheat oven to 200 degrees. Slice tomatoes horizontally and place
each half on baking sheet, cut side up. Drizzle with olive oil.
Sprinkle 1 tsp. cumin (be generous!) on each slice, and add salt
and pepper. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Slow roast in oven up to 8 hours, or until tomatoes have shrunk and
caramelized around the edges. Store in airtight container in
refrigerator for up to 2 weeks. &QL;
</P>
