<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S TEAM FEELS AT HOME ON GOLDEN ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ The last Olympic tournament _ the first _ was on
home soil, and it was incredible, they say. Last year's World Cup
was nothing but pressure, right up until Brandi Chastain made The
Kick. This time, all the US women's soccer team has to do is play a
few soccer matches halfway around the world in front of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Australia, it'll be relaxing,'' said forward Tiffeny
Milbrett, whose team will take on nemesis Norway in its Olympic
opener Thursday afternoon at the Melbourne Cricket Ground. ``We
won't have to worry about selling our game or selling tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Just defending its title will be work enough. Though the
Americans are still the clear favorites in the eight-team field,
their top rivals have closed a gap that was never that great to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Though the United States went undefeated at the 1996 Games,
virtually every match was a grinder. In last year's World Cup, the
Americans had to come from behind to beat both Nigeria and Germany
and played 120 scoreless minutes against the Chinese before winning
on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they have a rugged draw (Norway, China, and Nigeria)
and an opener against the only team with a winning record (14-12-2)
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They respect us, but they're not afraid of us. So they'll come
right after us,'' said forward Shannon MacMillan, who scored the
golden goal against the Norwegians that put her mates into the last
Olympic final.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegians, who've shored up their roster around keeper
Bente Nordby, defender Gro Espeseth, midfielder Hege Riise, and
forward Marianne Pettersen since losing, 5-0, to China in the World
Cup semifinals, have defeated the United States three times in six
meetings this year, allowing only one goal in five of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already beaten the USA this year and we are
well-prepared for this tournament,'' said coach Per-Mathias Hogmo.
``The team has spent 60 days together this year. They're in good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have spent nearly nine months together,
crisscrossing the globe while coach April Heinrichs reworked the
roster. Though most of the key faces are the same ones from last
summer's Rose Bowl victory pigpile, there will be a couple of
critical absentees from Thursday's starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Akers, the fierce holding midfielder who'd been with
the team literally since the creation 15 years ago, retired last
month after a decade-long battle with chronic fatigue syndrome,
multiple knee surgeries, and countless concussions. And keeper
Briana Scurry, who blocked the penalty kick that gave Chastain her
victory window in the Cup final, has been scratching for form after
missing most of the year with shin splints and probably will ride
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   That means Siri Mullinix, who wasn't one of the squad's top
three keepers last year, will be making her global debut in a
high-stakes match. Mullinix, a 22-year-old Carolina grad, is a
daring rover who'll roam from end line to the edge of the box and
beyond, looking to squelch danger before it develops.
</P>
<P>
   Defending, though, won't be the Americans' prime concern.
Scoring will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense can be back there stopping goals,'' said
MacMillan, ``but we've got to put the ball in the back of the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Americans could sweep through the tournament
unbeaten, they could also go three-and-out in this top-heavy group
and they understand that.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of them _ Carla Overbeck, Joy Fawcett, Kristine Lilly,
and Mia Hamm _ have been around long enough that this could be
their last global tournament. So going home with only a stuffed
koala is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we come out of this with a gold medal,'' said Milbrett, ``I
can guarantee you that most people who thought they were retiring
won't be retiring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
