<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF THE LAST ENERGY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oil prices are near a 10-year high. No one is sure there will be
enough heating oil this winter. The Europeans are rioting.
Politicians here are looking for someone to blame.
</P>
<P>
   It all brings back memories. We are old enough to remember the
days when the word ``energy'' was inevitably followed by the word
``crisis.'' In fact, we cut our teeth as business reporters in the
days of the energy crisis.
</P>
<P>
   We bring this up, not to wallow in nostalgia or to feel ancient
but to make a point. The energy crisis taught some valuable lessons
that are still applicable _ about how volatile markets can be,
about how difficult it is to predict the future, and about how
expensive it can be when you bet wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Set the ``wayback machine'' for 1973, Sherman. Following the
Arab-Israeli war that fall, the oil-rich countries of the Middle
East vented their anger at the United States by cutting back on oil
production. The price of a barrel of oil, which had hovered around
$3 for more than a decade, shot up to the unheard-of level of $10.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978-'79 the ouster of the Shah of Iran led to another oil
shortage and another spike in prices, this time to more than $30 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Both oil shocks caused recessions. And the second one brought on
a gloom about the future that is hard to imagine in today's can-do
America. Part of that gloom was a belief, broadly accepted, that
higher oil prices were here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 Business Week announced we had entered ``the beginning
of the end of the petroleum age.'' The book ``Energy Future,'' a
well-respected work published the same year, came to a similar
conclusion. ``The days of easy and cheap oil are truly over,'' the
authors said.
</P>
<P>
   We bought into the pessimism too. In the early 1980s, we were
asked to write a story about the economics of the Seabrook nuclear
power plant, then under construction in New Hampshire. Seabrook was
planned to reduce our dependence on ``costly foreign oil.'' To
figure out if Seabrook was worth building, you had to have some
idea how expensive oil would be in the future.
</P>
<P>
   So we asked some experts for advice. They suggested we use two
scenarios to make our comparison: one with oil prices climbing
moderately _ 5 percent per year _ and a second with prices climbing
more steeply, at 10 percent per year. In both cases we used $30 a
barrel as the starting point. Under the first scenario, oil would
have reached $60 a barrel by the mid-1990s; in the second, it would
have topped $100 a barrel. Either way, Seabrook would have been a
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: By the mid-1990s, oil sold for $18 a
barrel. Suffice to say we were a little off target.
</P>
<P>
   But we had plenty of company back then. Consider the fate of our
publisher. He launched a magazine about wood stoves, an industry he
was sure was going to catch fire as consumers scrambled to dump
their oil burners. Like the Internet enterpreneurs of today, he was
universally applauded as bold and far-sighted. The only question
was how rich he would become.
</P>
<P>
   The US government was in the same boat. It proposed spending $15
billion _ real money in those days _ to finance expensive projects
that would extract oil from shale and turn coal into gas.
Continental Illinois, then one of the nation's leading banks, put
40 percent of its loan portfolio into energy projects.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook proved to be a bust, not a bargain. Our publisher's
magazine ultimately failed. The government threw in the towel after
wasting billions on so-called synthetic fuels. Continental Illinois
lost a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit was the same in each case: oil prices. They leveled
off in the early '80s, dropped sharply in the mid-1980s, and since
then have stayed pretty flat at around $18 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high oil prices of the '70s translated into lower demand
and they also spurred more oil production,'' said Joseph Stanislaw,
president of Cambridge Energy Research Associates, a consulting
firm based in Cambridge. Throw in better technology, which made it
easier and cheaper to extract oil from the ground, and the
predicted oil shortages turned into gluts.
</P>
<P>
   Stanislaw expects the current mini-crisis to be short-lived. He
says that by spring oil prices should be significantly lower. We
have no reason to doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   But our experience during the energy crisis days taught us to be
wary of sweeping predictions. Will the Internet change everything?
Will the record companies all be put out of business by Napster? Is
the United States destined to leave its rivals in the dust in the
race to the economic future?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But maybe not. We're still waiting for the end of the
petroleum age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
