u e BC-AUTHOR-BUSHNELL-ART-B     09-14 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-BUSHNELL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CANDACE BUSHNELL: DON'T CONFUSE MY LIFE WITH MY NOVELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's got a millionaire British boyfriend and a new book, yet
Candace Bushnell, author of ``Sex and the City,'' and now, ``4
Blondes,'' is annoyed because people keep mixing fact and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   They think, Bushnell complains, that she and that Carrie
Bradshaw character are the same person. They think she actually
chronicled real-life accounts of her friends' sex lives for her
columns in the New York Observer, which spawned the novel ``Sex and
the City,'' which led to the hit HBO series of the same name. And
they think a lot of what goes on during the show is a reflection of
her own struggles when she was a single woman in her 30s, living in
Manahattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put other people's personal lives in the paper. People
told me stories about things that have happened to them. These are
kind of general stories. Sex and the City (the column) was really
fiction, OK?'' Bushnell, 41, says over lunch as a quick flush of
temper colors her high-boned cheeks. ``The stories would be quite
changed, and I always showed them the stories before they were
published. It's really fiction written as journalism. I want to
clear that up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lecture does not end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really ignorant. And for some reason people don't
seem to be able to understand the concept of fiction anymore.'' Her
new novel _ ``4Blondes'' _ ``is completely fiction. I do get these
questions, `Oh, well, is this person so and so? Or who is this
person based on? They're fictional characters that came out of my
head! And that's it! I happen to be the kind of writer who, I
think, is a good enough writer so when you read it, it feels
real,'' she says, spearing an oyster with a tine. ``That's what an
artist does.''
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't write about sex. And I don't write about the sex act.
It's not very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the word popped up in the title of her column,
book, and TV show, and that explicit sex acts are detailed in ``4
Blondes,'' she demurs. ``I think the kind of sex that people have
informs the characters,'' Bushnell explains.
</P>
<P>
   One problem for this misconception, she observes, is that the
show ``Sex and the City'' features more sex than her writing ever
did. And some nights, she hopes that her parents at home in
Glastonbury, Conn., aren't tuned into HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to push myself away from it in any way. I can't;
the show's part of my life,'' Bushnell says. ``The only thing
that's annoying to me, occasionally, is when people compare my book
to the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, she wants to point out that her first novel is not
about four single women in New York. It's about one: Her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's bound to be more confusion if _ or when _
Universal Studios makes a film based on a vignette in ``4 Blondes''
that explores the life of a regular girl who marries a prince and
practically goes insane from the pressure and publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask if the character is based on Carolyn Bessette Kennedy
or Princess Diana. Fiction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Don't ask &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And don't ask if Hollywood, where she's spending more time
lately, is filled with characters as seemingly shallow as the ones
she writes about in ``4 Blondes,'' including a vapid model who is
determined to sleep with men just so she can spend the summer at
their houses in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's human nature to put down what you don't know
and what makes you insecure,'' she says, bristling at the
suggestion that Los Angeles _ and some New York social circles _
are phony.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Bushnell, who proclaims she's starving, has her
entree of short ribs set before her.
</P>
<P>
   ``God. Like one rib?'' she huffs, her blue eyes directed at the
plate. (But in the end, she didn't finish the Lilliputian portion.)
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turns to her boyfriend, Stephen Morris, and how
he's handling the big kickoff of her two-month book tour and all
this talk about sex. Perhaps even theirs?
</P>
<P>
   ``His sex life isn't out there,'' Bushnell says irritably. ``So
that's not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is the ex-boyfriend of her ex-best friend, Kate Bohnner,
an author and Bushnell's roommate for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Morris saga was chronicled on Page 6 of the New York Post,
which reported in June 1999 that Bohnner was ``devastated to learn
Candace was sleeping'' with him. Apparently, Bushnell and Morris,
then 34, broke the news to her over dinner. ``It was a real
ambush,'' one friend told the tabloid. ``And when Kate went to his
apartment to move her stuff out, Candace's stuff was already
hanging in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bushnell said Bohner and Morris had been broken up
for five weeks before she made a play for him.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse any of this with the last vignette in ``4
Blondes,'' about a New York sex columnist who goes to England and
falls in love with a British businessman on the flight back.
Fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But in real life, Bushnell has also dated former Republican
Senator Al D'Amato, Penthouse heir Bob Guccione Jr., and Michael
Bergin, Bessette Kennedy's ex-boyfriend. However, she does confirm
that the ``Sex and the City'' character Mr. Big is based on the
relationship she had with Ron Galotti, one-time publisher of Vogue
who is now an executive at Talk.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell says she's not sure if marriage with Morris in the
works. And besides, she explains, ``A lot of people say when you
get married, you trade one set of problems for another.''
</P>
<P>
   Would she sign a prenuptialagreement, the way TV character
Charlotte did on a recent episode?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would,'' she says, ``just to protect myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But one gets the sense Bushnell can take care of herself just
fine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scuffed Gucci years &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell grew up in Glastonbury, a town she has dubbed
Glastonboring. It was, in her words, a place devoid of a movie
theater, where people (including herself) loved horses, and where
parents drank gin and tonics at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   For fun, she would write plays and have her two younger sisters
perform in them. After graduating from Glastonbury High School, she
attended Rice University for two years, then moved to New York,
where she enrolled in acting school and went to casting calls for
Coke or Burger King commercials. ``I hated it.''
</P>
<P>
   She also plunged into the social scene and was a regular at
Studio 54, where she did not have to wait in line behind a velvet
rope. ``Like, if you didn't get in right away, you wouldn't get in.
Which is always hard to explain to people from out of town, you
know? I mean there would be, like, 500 people outside the door.
You're like, `You're not. Gonna. Get. In. Go. Hooooome.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell also started writing short interviews for Night, a
publication filled, she says, with pictures of her friends from
Studio 54. She was just 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were like, you should get a job. I was a little
taken aback _ because I thought I could just write novels. My whole
life. But then you start writing for those women's magazines and
that's it. You can't make enough money to stop doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell landed a job at Ladies' Home Journal. ``Believe it or
not,'' she says in an embarrassed, confessional tone.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted a year. She then jumped to Good House Keeping,
writing occasional ``blurbs,'' before becoming a staff writer at
Self covering health and beauty for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   But she found office work restrictive, and searched for
freelance opportunities, which led to writing about relationships
for Mademoiselle. (Next came the New York Observer, where she wrote
profiles, and then the column).
</P>
<P>
   Other assignments at Mademoiselle, she fondly recalls, included
pieces on migrant farm workers and homeless and runaway teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always wearing my beat-up Gucci shoes,'' she says, a
faraway look in her eyes. ``I'd be walking through fields . . .''
Asked if the Guccis were a sound footwear choice for such gritty
reporting, she doesn't skip a beat: ``They were pretty old and beat
up.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Bushnell &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Bushnell cut her teeth on her mother's Vogue
magazines and modeled in the punk scene when she moved to New York
in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   She may be a style maven, but she has nothing to do with the
fashions on the HBO show. ``They comb the city for vintage
things,'' Bushnell says, noting that she rarely wears other
people's used frocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a couple of months ago, I wore a Micheal Kors dress that I
bought 10 years go. And everyone was going vintage! Vintage Michael
Kors! I can't believe I would, like, in my lifetime, have my own
vintage clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kors is one of her favorite designers, although she's partial to
Italian fashion houses Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Gucci, Versace, and Prada.
She's dressed head to toe in Versace, from her
button-all-the-way-down, cinched-at-the-waist dress _ graphically
striped like swirls of mocha and fudge soft-serve ice cream _ to
her caramel-colored shoes with dark heels. On her thin arm hangs a
burgundy Prada bowling bag, the most hyped designer accessory of
the season. Her perfectly tanned legs are bare. And her thong was
only faintly visible from the back.
</P>
<P>
   When she read Vogue as a young girl, she recalls, ``everyone
felt like, if you could wear those glamorous clothes, you could
have that glamorous life.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that she seemingly has both, Bushnell snaps back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasy isn't reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
