<HEADLINE>
FOOD SITE SEEKS PARTNER WITH GREENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Alex Beam's column will now move Tuesdays and Thursdays.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does Skip Gates have that New York Times food writer Molly
O'Neill wants? A deep-pocketed buyer for a special-interest Web
site that isn't really clicking.
</P>
<P>
   The Skipper (a.k.a. Harvard African-American studies impresario
Henry Louis Gates Jr.) managed to unload his africana.com Web
business onto Time-Warner earlier this month for a reported $10
million, even though, as he hilariously admitted, ``the revenue
model was slow to develop.'' Now the O'Neill site, trumpeted in
this space as a potential ``category-killing'' food site, is
looking for a partner, according to O'Neill's husband and business
partner Arthur Samuelson: ``We're trying to figure out how to
survive in an Internet-unfriendly world. We're involved in some
talks that could lead to a merger.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Neill site, initially called At-table.com and then
redubbed Onebigtable.com never really got off the ground. The dream
of creating a soup-to-nuts ``multimedia encyclopedia'' proved to be
punitively expensive. Celebrity chefs, such as Julia Child or Anne
Willan, weren't interested in turning over electronic rights to
their work. The only real celebrity on the demo site is O'Neill,
author of the ``New York Cookbook'' and other best-selling food
books. At its peak, the company had 26 employees. The online
service Inside.com has reported two rounds of layoffs, bringing the
head count down to a skeleton crew of 6.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few deals Onebigtable did pull off was a partnership
with Amazon.com's new Kitchen web site, launched this summer. But
it is a deal that seems to favor only Amazon. The Kitchen site is
like an Internet roach motel: You can click in but you can't click
out. Amazon carries content from O'Neill's site, and from the
successful Brookline-based journal Cook's Illustrated. But the
Seattle-based Amazon provides no direct links to their partners'
own Web sites sites. ``I guess we cut a pretty good deal,'' one
Amazon executive told me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Premature articulation?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Standards are important in journalism, and I intend to enforce
them. Which is why I have decided to mount a campaign of harassment
and intimidation against Sports Illustrated, until they agree to
publish a cover-length retraction of their March 27 cover story,
``Why the Red Sox Will Win the World Series.'' Most of its staff
has run off to Sydney, Australia _ Is something going on there? _
but they can't hide. Spokesman Joe Assad told me that a
cover-length retraction was ``unlikely,'' even though he let slip
that the March story was clearly erroneous. ``The prognostication
business is never an exact science,'' he said. ``The Red Sox were
in it until last weekend.'' He then tried to retract that last
statement, but that's not the retraction I'm looking for.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, I can look forward to telephoning the editors
of TV Guide, and asking them to explain their Sept. 2 cover story,
``Patriots Pride! Why New England Can Win This Year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bring it on
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hate mail is pouring in from WGU _ Wellesley's Greatest
University _ reacting to Wednesday's brief, upbeat profile I wrote
about the college's only resident male student. Let the sputtering
begin. A senior: ``The language used was degrading and
disrespectful to the amazingly brilliant and intelligent women that
(sic) have come here for 125 years as well as their remarkable
achievements.'' A junior: ``You even managed to make a direct
sexist comment, saying _ to paraphrase _ that women don't have an
interest in weight equipment.'' A freshperson: ``You seem to be
painting my new home as some kind of brothel, and I find it rather
rude.'' A recurring theme: We're not lesbians! I don't recall
writing that the students were all lesbians, not that there would
be anything wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
