<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORTILLAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EVERYTHING YOU WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT TORTILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KAREN HARAM,  
 &HT;    JOHN GRIFFIN and BONNIE WALKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   Corn tortillas have no added fat and are more healthful than
flour tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Tortillas are one of the fastest growing segments of the baking
industry worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, United States residents consumed more than 75 billion
tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   If 75 billion tortillas were laid end to end, they would stretch
across the United States 1,178 times, or circle the Earth 338
times.
</P>
<P>
   It's perfectly good manners to roll a tortilla and use it as a
pusher or scooper for food on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Flour tortillas originated in Northern Mexico. In Mexico, flour
tortillas are generally not served with southern Mexican cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Lime (calcium oxide) acts as a preservative in corn tortillas.
The more lime, the yellower the tortilla. If tortillas are ochre,
too much lime was added.
</P>
<P>
   Spain also has a tortilla, but it's similar to a thin omelet.
</P>
<P>
   Homemade masa without preservatives keeps less than six hours
unrefrigerated. Refrigerated, it keeps less than two days.
</P>
<P>
   Variety of uses
</P>
<P>
   Totopos, chilaquiles, tortilla soup and migas are great ways to
use leftover corn tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Leftover flour tortillas can be cut in triangles, fried in hot
oil, and sprinkled with cinnamon and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap sandwiches using flour tortillas have fused U.S., Mexican
and other cultures. Some possibilities: Fill cilantro tortillas
with spicy chicken salad; fill spinach tortillas with sliced
Italian deli meats, cheese and arugula and dress with light Italian
dressing; brush one side of a flour tortilla with mayonnaise and
wrap around bacon, lettuce and tomato; fill a sun-dried tomato
tortilla with goat cheese and black olive tapenade or pesto.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional facts
</P>
<P>
   Flour tortillas are a low-fat food and contain iron along with B
vitamins. A 7-inch tortilla has 115 calories, 3 grams protein, 20
grams carbohydrate, 2.5 grams fat and 44 milligrams calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Corn tortillas do not contain gluten, making them an alternative
for those who are gluten intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Corn tortillas are a low-fat, low-sodium food and contain
calcium, potassium and fiber. A 7- inch tortilla has 60 calories, 1
gram protein, 12 grams carbohydrate, 1 gram fat and 44 milligrams
calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexican cooks believe crisp tortilla halves sprinkled with
salt are good after-dinner digestive aids.
</P>
<P>
   History
</P>
<P>
   Historic evidence says tortillas or similar flatbreads have been
around for 12,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mayan legend, tortillas were invented in ancient
times by a peasant for his hungry king.
</P>
<P>
   The first tortillas, food of the ancient Mayans and Aztecs, were
made of native corn.
</P>
<P>
   In the central highlands and west central Mexico, as well as
parts of New Mexico, you'll find tortillas made of blue corn. The
difference is more in color than taste.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Aztec word for tortilla is tlaxcallim.
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla trends
</P>
<P>
   Flavored tortillas, including spinach, jalapeno, sun-dried
tomato and cinnamon-sugar, offer new tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap sandwiches and hors d' oeuvres made from rolled-up
tortillas are taking the tortilla in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   Tortillas come in all sizes, ranging from silver-dollar
varieties to thin, platter-sized ones, used for cheese crisps and
burritos.
</P>
<P>
   Prep tips
</P>
<P>
   When making your own corn tortillas, butter your hands as you
pat the tortilla to keep it from sticking.
</P>
<P>
   If making tortillas with a press, put the ball of masa in a
plastic bag larger than the press to expedite removal.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave ovens are great for reheating tortillas. Wrap a dozen
tortillas (no more!) in plastic wrap and heat for about a minute.
Turn it over and heat for another 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to use tortillas the day you buy them, they
don't need to be refrigerated. They taste best when freshest. For
longer storage, refrigerate or freeze _ days in the fridge, months
in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Soften tortillas for enchiladas by dipping them quickly in hot
oil. (Fat-gram counters may want to substitute hot broth or sauce
for oil, or warm them quickly in a lightly oiled skillet.)
</P>
<P>
   Warm tortillas on a hot skillet or comal or wrap several at a
time in aluminum foil and heat in a 250- to 325-degree oven for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Mexico: The Hungry Traveler'' by Marita Adair, White
Wings, The Tortilla Industry Association, ``A Cook's Tour of
Mexico'' by Nancy Zaslavsky, ``Authentic Mexican'' by Rick Bayless
with Deann Groen Bayless, ``Mexican Regional Cooking'' and ``The
Art of Mexican Cooking'' by Diana Kennedy, and USDA Handbook 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
