<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD IS BETTER THAN RUBBER FOR GARDEN EDGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The rubber edging I am using in my garden just doesn't work
very well. It is too shallow to stick in the ground properly, and
also tends to work itself out of the ground. I was thinking of
pressure-treated wood, something like a 2-by-4 or 2-by-6. And to
save money, would a 1-by-6 do?
</P>
<P>
   DANIEL O'NEILL, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Any wood board will do, but pressure-treated will last
indefinitely, without affecting what's in the garden. Cedar will
last up to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   For good staying-in-the-ground power, use the deeper boards; a
1-by-6 will be fine. The only disadvantage to long boards is that
they do not turn corners or curve. To do that, use shorter, 2-foot
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara McGurl of Belmont, Mass. called recently with several
questions, which were duly answered, and she came up with this one
for the handyman.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked if she could find any ready-made corner cabinet
of a certain size, the handyman suggested several sources. ``I went
to the Woodworkers Store ... and they sent me to a carpenter who
built the corner cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it pays to check things out, and the handyman is pleased
to put this in his file, for anyone who wants it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wrought-iron furniture is a bit rusted. It is white, and
not peeling. A beloved member of the family wants me to paint it
green. Would that work?
</P>
<P>
   S.D., Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure it would work, but I strongly suggest that you not
change color. If the green starts to peel, revealing the white
underneath, the contrast will be glaring, and shouting to be fixed
in a big hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, stick with white, but you have to remove all the rust
whether you repaint white or green. Sand off the rust with medium
sandpaper. If you cannot get all the rust off by sanding, paint the
remaining rust with Rust Reformer (that and other brands are sold
in paint and building stores). It contains phosphoric acid, which
turns the rust black and makes it paintable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to make a concrete platform for my 8-by-16-foot shed
that I am moving to a new site. Can I mix the concrete myself and
pour it?
</P>
<P>
   LEVON CHORBAJIAN, Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but if you make the slab 4 inches thick, you will be
using more than 3 yards of concrete, which is one heck of a lot of
concrete to mix by hand. You can rent a portable mixer, but even so
you will be handling all that sand, stone, cement, and water
anyway. Concrete weighs more than 3,000 pounds per yard, so you are
going to be handling 9,000 pounds (4 1/2 tons!).
</P>
<P>
   It would be better to have a ready-mix concrete company deliver
it to the forms you will be building for it. If you have the
concrete delivered, be prepared to smooth it out and finish it.
Concrete truck drivers deliver the concrete, but that is all,
unless you get a friendly guy to help. But they don't have to. No
matter how you pour the slab, put reinforcing rods in it. It will
float on the ground but will stay in one piece that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a fine old Boston rocker that was in my cousin's
house, but I can't use it because it reeks of cigarette smoke. I
washed it with Mr. Clean, which helped some, but not enough. What
else can I do? It really reeks.
</P>
<P>
   G.Y., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, it is amazing how smoke of any kind can penetrate so
many things, including finished or painted wood. One thing you can
try is to treat the whole chair, especially the unfinished seat
bottom, with Febreze. Made by Proctor &AMP; Gamble, it's a deodorizer
that oxidizes the smoke residue rather than disguising the odor.
While it was designed to treat fabrics and other soft goods, it can
work on wood and other hard surfaces. It is sold in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't work, you will have to strip it and refinish or
repaint it, including the seat bottom. You might be able to simply
sand it and repaint, but I don't think that is as effective as
stripping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The roofing crew finishing my roof took up a garden hose to
test for leaks and, wouldn't you know, dropped the nozzle, a piece
of brass about 6 inches long, down the vent pipe. They said it is
impossible to retrieve. What can I do? There have been no symptoms
of a blocked vent or sewer pipe since this happened two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   WORRIED, in Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The handyman has been taking in weird and wonderful tales for
34 years now, but this one takes the cake. That's exactly what the
Godfather did with the pistol he killed his first victim with.
Broke it up and dumped it down a vent.
</P>
<P>
   If there have been no symptoms in two weeks, all you can do is
wait. The nozzle is simply a tube, and is unlikely to block the
vent pipe. But if it turns a corner from the vent pipe to drain
line, it could wedge itself in and cause a blockage. Even if it
doesn't, it is unlikely to go far down a gently sloping drain,
pushed by water.
</P>
<P>
   If you get a blockage, start looking for it where the horizontal
drain exits from the vertical vent pipe.
</P>
<P>
   The roofing crew should give you more than just a new nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter C. Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail him at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
