<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-CYBER-CLUTTER-AR     09-14 1925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CYBER-CLUTTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HIDING COMPUTER-WIRE CLUTTER: SOUND PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it cyber clutter. Or messy Web weaving. Or just plain
ugly-wire networking. The wires from computer monitors, keyboards,
speakers, printers, faxes, scanners, and phones that swoop around
rooms, dangle under desks, and loop along desktops in an all-out
scramble to get to the nearest electrical outlet are, for some, a
visual nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   There's no uniform color or girth to them, and they are as prone
to tangling as a mop of wet hair. They also seem to multiply
overnight. There are the big, fat, hose-like ones from the monitor;
the skinnier, more flexible ones from the keyboard and mouse; the
tangled mass of them to and from the CPU (computer power unit); and
the strays from the printer, fax, and surge protector. There are
silver ones, white and grey ones, and black.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, this mess is mysteriously absent from photographs of
computer stations in catalogs, and wires never snake along the rugs
or dangle from desks in furniture showrooms. They seem only to lurk
and lurch around private homes and apartments like a veritable
cyber invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Eben Scanlon, 25, a graduate student at Harvard Business School,
is trying to make his new apartment as wireless as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other apartments, I've hidden wires under sofas and rugs
but I'm planning to be pretty wireless this time by using LAN
(local area network) cards and a Linux box (a piece of computer
equipment) that serves as a (wireless) bridge between my
computers,'' says Scanlon.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has five computers, Scanlon is planning to use only
two in his new digs. What he's most excited about, he says, are the
wireless homes that some friends are building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people I know who are building new houses are putting in
ethernet drops,'' he says. ``That means all the wires are in the
walls and the drop is like a phone jack.''
</P>
<P>
   For those still with old-fashioned exposed wires, however, help
is available. With 60 percent of American homes now equipped with
computers and 70 percent of all home computers purchased by
first-time buyers, according to a recent Microsoft survey, the
furniture, interior-design, and industrial-design industries are
tackling wire management and techno-clutter problems.
</P>
<P>
   According to SoHo Today magazine, an industry trade publication
based in Greensboro, N. C., today's residential computer furniture
industry is one of the fastest-growing segments of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of falling PC prices, ongoing corporate
downsizing, and the growing number of Americans spending time in
their home offices proved to be key ingredients in the recipe for
success enjoyed by the small office/home office segment in 1999,''
according to a recent issue of the magazine. ``Last year, the
Business Industry Furniture Manufacturers Association indicated
that the wholesale demand for domestic office furniture is at
approximately $12.7 billion. This year the group says it expects
that number to reach between $13 billion and $13.5 billion, which
would represent an increase of between 4 percent and 6 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers say that although many clients seem willing to spend
money on space planning and decorating for his, hers, theirs, and
the children's computers, there are still the holdouts who'll pay
thousands for a little-used dining room set but a pittance on
computer stations. This, even though a recent Harris poll found
that of the 63 percent of adults who use computers, 26 percent use
one both at work and at home and the average weekly use is 15
hours, six of which are spent on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One need not hire a decorator or buy an expensive wall unit to
achieve solutions to the wire mess. A few dollars buys a handful of
large cup hooks at the hardware store. Screw them into the back of
the computer desk or table, gather the wires in a bunch and string
them through the hooks, then bring them all straight down to the
outlet. Alternatively, buy a roll of duct tape and tape the bunched
wires along the underside or back of the desk. Or, create neat
bundles by grouping wires together and binding them with nylon ties
or Velcro wraps or ``twisties'' from bread wrappers. Then herd them
toward an inexpensive power strip with four or five outlets.
</P>
<P>
   To hide the wires, try plastic corrugated tubing from a store
like Hold Everything (roughly $16 for 8 feet of flexible tubing).
The tubing comes split down the middle so it can be opened and
wrapped around a set of wires. This gives a one-lane,
all-inclusive, covered-bridge route to an outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Klein, president and chief executive officer of Media
Systems, headquartered in the Boston Design Center, says that when
it comes to wires, ``it's a matter of detail, not budgetry. It's
about dressing and creating harnesses with your wires so that there
is one single run of cable.''
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasizes planning, planning, and more planning when
branching into more expensive home-office setups, armoires, and
high-end desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be fooled by the lovely photos in the catalogs,'' he
says. ``There are never any wires in the pictures. So be careful.
However, most cabinets and desks can be modified to a person's
needs. A home office should have, and can have, the functionality
of a business office.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein's company works on the big picture of prewiring new homes
with the most sophisticated communications systems available. He
also assures that eventually, these wires (and this article) will
be obsolete. The wireless computer is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Kasrel, senior analyst at Forrester Research, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to happen is that networking technology will
allow scanners and printers to communicate with a computer without
being in the same room,'' says Kasrel. ``There will be just one
power cord. Ultimately, there may be no need for even a power cord.
A technology called Bluetooth may someday allow a printer to talk
to a computer without the need for a cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wirelessness, however, will not be available in the next year or
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were building a new home and I was a high-tech person, I
would special-wire the house because that's going to be the best
solution for the next two to five years,'' says Kasrel. ``Within 10
years, we won't need special wiring.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, cleverly housing computers and their wires and
accessories in various rooms has become a top priority in the
design industry, mainly because computers are not relegated to just
one room anymore. A recent Microsoft poll found 33 percent of home
computers are in the playroom, den, or family room; 28 percent are
in the office, library, or study; and 16 percent are in the master
bedroom, followed by the living room, child's bedroom, and other
rooms set aside for cyber working.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Pelissier, an interior designer and owner of Robin's Nest
in Hingham, Mass., custom designs armoires and wall units for
clients but also takes far less expensive routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get decent armoires or desk units in catalogs like
Pottery Barn,'' says Pelissier. ``An armoire is great because it's
a good-looking piece in a room and you can close it up and hide the
computer when you're not using it. Just be careful about the
measurements and that there's a roll-out piece for the keyboard and
spaces below for a fax and speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens are becoming an increasingly popular place for a
computer, designers say, as it tends to be the hub of the house.
This is usually the wife's computer. The husband's, they say, often
remains in the den or library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men like their desks facing the door, they don't like their
backs to the door,'' says Pelissier. ``So I'll put the computer
along the wall behind the desk because you don't want to see a
bunch of wires falling off a desk as you enter a room. A swivel
chair makes everything accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   For children, Pelissier likes to convert a small bedroom closet
into a computer center. She upholsters the inside of the door and
hangs a bulletin board on it, puts a wide piece of wood or a
formica-topped piece on two sawhorses as a desktop for the monitor,
keyboard, and printer, and places the computer in a cabinet
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get an inexpensive cabinet from Home Depot and drill
holes in the back for the wiring,'' says Pelissier. ``If you don't
want a cabinet, drill holes in the formica top, snake the wires
through the holes, and then put them in tubing for a clean look.
You can add bookshelves on the facing wall or put up another
bulletin board. When the child is not using the computer, just
close the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelissier does not always try to hide a computer or large-screen
television, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the computer or television is the most expensive
thing in the room and people want to show off their techiness,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   For a more luxurious look, Charles Spada of Charles Spada
Interiors, also in the Design Center, has custom-built commodes and
buffets with pull-out drawers for monitors, keyboards, and faxes.
Increasingly, clients are asking for ``his and her'' work stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Husbands really don't care what their computer station looks
like,'' says Spada. ``They just want leg room and surface space.
Women want their work space pretty and practical. They don't want
to see a lot of electronics. They want their space free and clean.
They are neatniks. Men are more comfortable with everything at
their fingertips. They don't care if everything is out in the open.
They want to see their toys.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of toys in the Fish house in Weston, Mass.
Ellen Fish said her husband, Ted, who works with Peabody
Construction, ``sometimes works out of the house and needed a room
for a computer, fax, and copy machines, but I didn't want the room
to be a total office. I wanted to be able to sit in there, watch TV
with my son, Eddie, and just relax. I hate the way wires and things
hang off desks. They're so ugly. Some of them are just huge,
especially those big black ones that MediaOne puts in. They make
for a visual disaster. So we tried to hide the wires as much as
possible by putting in plenty of strip outlets placed high enough
off the floor so you don't see them.''
</P>
<P>
   It works. Sitting in the office that Spada designed, a few wires
are visible snaking across the desk area to the wall, but no wires
dangle beneath the desk. They are bunched together and plugged into
the above-knee-level strip outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Glossmann-Smith of Design Creations Inc. in Boston's
North End has made a specialty of custom office design, both
residential and commercial, and often uses inexpensive materials to
keep costs down.
</P>
<P>
   She uses plywood covered with laminate, for example, sometimes
edged in cherry or maple, and attaches the desktop to the wall by
anchoring it on a 2-by-4. To further support the desktop, she puts
filing cabinets underneath. As for the wire problem, she drills
holes or grommets in the laminate, groups and tapes wires
underneath the desktops, then drops them down behind the filing
cabinets to an outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Pelissier says she urges her clients to pick up magazines and
decorating books, and to go on house tours and to show houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I get my ideas,'' she says. ``So why shouldn't my
clients?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
