<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4943 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-14 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO DEEP FOR MOST OF US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's just what I needed _ more Web search results.
</P>
<P>
   As if the thousands of pages turned up during the typical
AltaVista search weren't enough, I now find out that this mighty
search engine is just skimming the surface. The same goes for all
of the other market leaders _ Yahoo, Lycos, Google, Hotbot. These
guys just don't get it _ or at least, not most of it.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't breaking news, of course. I'm looking at a ticker at
www.cyveillance.com, which purports to display the total number of
unique documents online. It was at 2,571,377,000 when I began this
paragraph and 2,571,386,000 when I finished.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest search engines only claim about a billion pages
indexed. So the rest of the Web might as well not even be there,
since nobody can see it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But this seeming ocean of data is little more than a kiddie
pool. Step out a little farther, and you'll sink into ``the deep
Web,'' a Marianas Trench of information that contains 550 billion
documents and counting.
</P>
<P>
   So say the researchers at BrightPlanet.com LLC, a tiny company
in Sioux Falls, S.D., where the workers probably have time to read
every single document. Instead, they've been writing code that does
it for them. For you, too, if you're willing to part with $90.
</P>
<P>
   So what's this deep Web anyway? Well, you've probably taken a
dip now and then. Say you want to buy the (wretched) new Tom Clancy
novel at Amazon.com. Go there and look it up. The Web page you'll
see didn't exist till you asked for it _ at least, not as a Web
page. What you're seeing is a collection of information stored in
databases. When someone asks about the book, software pulls
together the required data, assembles it into a Web page, and sends
it to you. This is called a ``dynamic Web page,'' because it's
created on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that a huge amount of Internet data is handled this
way, because it's so efficient. You write one set of code to
automatically design Web pages. These pages assemble themselves
based on visitor requests and the contents of the database. To
change the site, you need only change the data. No page design
changes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   But since these Web pages don't exist till you specifically ask
for them, they're invisible to standard search engines. If you want
to search the Amazon database, crammed with useful information
about thousands of books, you have to go to Amazon.com, not Yahoo.
And the same is true for thousands of other deep Web databases,
full of good stuff unknown to the computers at AltaVista.
</P>
<P>
   Enter BrightPlanet.com, with its LexiBot software. It's sort of
like Copernic, an old favorite of mine that feeds my queries to a
dozen standard search engines at once. LexiBot goes quite a bit
further. Run a search, and it'll target up to 600 databases, most
of which aren't indexed by the search engines.
</P>
<P>
   Say you want medical information. You might start at Yahoo, but
the information you desire could be hidden in the databases of the
federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. A savvy
searcher would go there directly, and use its search feature.
LexiBot can be programmed to search this database as a matter of
course, and dozens of others besides.
</P>
<P>
   There's a price to be paid, of course _ the aforementioned $90
for the LexiBot client software. There's a 30-day free trial if you
want to dip a toe in first. Company officials admit that they don't
sell many copies of the software, but they don't care. Their main
product is server software that companies can use to do deep
searches of topics that interest them _ finding every single Web
site that mentions Heinz Baked Beans, for instance. The LexiBot
client is mainly a way to give researchers a taste of deep Web
searching, and get them interested in buying their own servers.
</P>
<P>
   That's just as well. Deep Web searching sounds like a fine idea
for corporate researchers and librarians, but I don't see the
concept catching on with consumers. It's not just the price either.
LexiBot doesn't solve the biggest problem of most Web surfers. We
don't want more Internet data; just the data we truly need. We try
to tailor our searches to find the two or three pages that can
really help us. Instead, today's search engines, LexiBot included,
serve up a surfeit of sites, with thousands of times more data than
we have time for. Now we're in for thousands more hits, from
databases we never knew existed. I can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
