<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TONIGHT-ADV18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV18 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Sept. 18, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic telecasts continue on NBC, CNBC and MSNBC today, via
tape delay from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   There's women's water polo in the morning for you early
starters, but evening activity begins at 5 with women's
weight-lifting finals on CNBC. In prime time on NBC, 7 to midnight,
you'll see the equestrian cross-country competition, men's team
gymnastics finals and various swimming finals. First-round boxing
is on CNBC in the 5 to 9 block. In late-night, after your local
news, you'll find canoeing finals and a women's volleyball game.
Bob Costas hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno will host a mini-``Tonight Show'' that lasts six
minutes at 12:35 a.m. and is likely to include a monologue and a
taped comedy bit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dumb &AMP; Dumber,'' Fox at 8: No dummies themselves, the folks at
the Fox network aren't about to waste good shows going up against
the Olympic juggernaut, so they're filling prime time with movies
all week. Tonight that means this tasteless but funny 1994 comedy
with Jim Carrey and Jeff Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: O is for the opposite of
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS at 8:30: Ally's being bullied
at school. A good chance to watch Patricia Heaton's performance as
Ray's wife and see if you think she deserved that Emmy she got last
week. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' CBS at 9: Episode 3. The tribes search for food,
and Stacey gets voted off the island. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football,'' ABC at 9: Dallas Cowboys at
Washington Redskins, which will no doubt allow color commentator
Dennis Miller to deliver arcane wisecracks based on obscure
constitutional provisions and minor characters on ``Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Force More Powerful,'' PBS at 9: A two-part look at the
history of nonviolent action in the 20th century, narrated by Ben
Kingsley. Tonight begins with Gandhi's efforts against the British
in 1930s India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girlfriends,'' UPN at 9:30: This sitcom is a sort of
African-American take on ``Sex and the City,'' as in tonight's
episode, when the question for Joan is whether to have a fling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ''7th Heaven,'' WB at 8: Part one of two finds summer romance
and forgiveness on the agenda for the family. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstory,'' AMC at 8: A look behind the scenes at the making
of ``The Poseidon Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``White Witch Doctor,'' FMC at 8: Susan Hayward and Robert
Mitchum star in this 1953 drama about a nurse and a big game hunter
in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooper,'' TNN at 8: Some good ol' boy action from 1978, as
Burt Reynolds, Sally Field and Jan-Michael Vincent star in a movie
about stuntmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Rules,'' MTV at 9: With the Olympics in Australia, this
show keeps with the theme, as the kids swim with great white
sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stepfather,'' TBS at 10:35: If you're home alone, better
not to watch this genuinely terrifying thriller from 1987 about a
man who keeps looking for the perfect family and is often very,
very disappointed. Terry O'Quinn stars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Bruce Willis.
Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 1:05 a.m.:
Media critic Howard Kurtz. (Note time after football.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: Magician
Lance Burton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL; 
 &UR; For information concerning the above material call (800) 972-3550.
After 5 p.m. contact The New York Times News Service (212)
556-1927. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
