<HEADLINE>
$ADV19 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Aug. 19, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic telecasts continue on NBC, CNBC and MSNBC today, via
tape delay from Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Women's gymnastic team finals, various swimming finals and the
United States vs. Russia men's volleyball game are all likely
highlights of NBC's prime-time coverage from 7-midnight. CNBC
offers boxing and tennis, which could feature sister act Venus and
Serena Williams. Late-night action should focus on the U.S. men's
basketball game, with NBA stars against Italy. Bob Costas hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno will host a mini-``Tonight Show'' that lasts six
minutes at 12:35 a.m., featuring a monologue and perhaps one or two
taped comedy bits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumanji,'' Fox at 8: The Olympics are the elephant in the
living room of this TV week, so Fox is going in another direction,
filling prime time with movies all week. Tonight that means this
entertaining 1995 fantasy starring Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: T is for the time wasted watching
this show, hours you'll never get back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: Regis Philbin
hosts. And it's going to be interesting to see how these ratings do
against the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' WB at 8: Fans of this ordinarily
excellent show were divided by this episode, which features the
heavily symbolic dreams of the Scoobie Gang. To us it appeared the
writers had ended the whole ``Initiative'' story line a week too
early and pounded this puppy out in desperation. This is one Buffy
rerun for devotees only.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Queens,'' CBS at 8:30: Doug's bowling team sponsor
(guest Robert Klein) puts the pressure on them to win more games,
and Doug has to choose between Carrie (who stinks) and the rest of
the team. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel,'' WB at 9: This big May episode finds Angel trying to
save his friends and, of course, the rest of Los Angeles, from the
evil unleashed by the satanic attorneys of Wolfram &AMP; Hart. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' CBS at 9: Episode 4 of the show that's CBS' big
bet against the Olympics. A storm and the ejection of Ramona are
tonight's highlights. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spin City,'' ABC at 10: Two back-to-back episodes give you a
chance to savor Michael J. Fox's Emmy-winning performance. Reruns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen Files: Surviving High School,'' UPN at 8: We're not sure
exactly which high schoolers would take advice from Leeza Gibbons,
who hosts this special, but the round table of California teens who
talk about the problems they face may have some impact. And for
some moms and dads, this could be an eye-opener.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullitt,'' AMC at 9: Steve McQueen, a Mustang fastback and the
coolest car chase in movie history mark this 1968 thriller, set in
a beautiful and somehow threatening San Francisco. Jacqueline
Bisset and Robert Vaughn also star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokedown Palace,'' HBO at 9: Claire Danes and Kate Beckinsale
are young Americans abroad in Southeast Asia who end up facing long
sentences in a hellish prison for drug smuggling. A cautionary tale
from 1999, rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masters Highlights,'' Golf Channel at 9: A review of Tiger
Woods' amazing drive to the title at the 1997 tournament, when he
beat the course by 18 shots and his competitors by 12.
</P>
<P>
