<HEADER>
A4970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TOWN-FOR-SALE-HNS &LR;      09-14 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWN-FOR-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR SALE: LUMBER TOWN AND ALL ITS TRAPPINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EMILY GURNON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAMOA, Calif. _ This historic company town, where timber workers
and their families once filled all the homes and traveled by ferry
to the ``mainland'' of Eureka, is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The current owner, Simpson Samoa Co., a subsidiary of the
Seattle-based Simpson Timber Co., has offered the entire town _
including its 98 houses, a well-known restaurant, post office,
playground, restored hostelry and a handful of commercial buildings
_ for sale through a sealed-bid auction that closes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson has owned the fog-shrouded property since 1998, when the
company bought it and 70,000 acres of redwoods from
Louisiana-Pacific. The 60-acre town came as part of the package and
was not something the company had sought, said Tom Elfers,
controller of Simpson's timber operations in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not our business to run a town,'' Elfers said. ``We're a
timber company. We hope someone can buy it, make an investment,
make it thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Humboldt County officials are optimistic that the sale will
inject new economic juice into the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially, it would be a huge component to the economic
development of the region,'' said Michael Richardson, senior
planner for the county. ``There aren't that many parcels out there
that are suitable for high-intensity development.''
</P>
<P>
   The site boasts one of the few pieces of coastal land in the
area that is neither developed nor protected, Richardson said. It
also features access to roads, a railroad and a water supply.
</P>
<P>
   If it continues to lease the houses and other buildings, the new
owner will collect some $540,000 a year in rental income, according
to the sales brochure.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between the Pacific Ocean and Humboldt Bay on the
North Coast, the narrow peninsula once housed a gas station,
company store, sawmill, shipyard, butcher shop and community
theater.
</P>
<P>
   All those have since closed. The two public schools have been
replaced by one, Peninsula Elementary, whose 90 students in grades
K-8 come from surrounding communities like Eureka, Arcata and
another peninsula town, Manila, as well as Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the town's quaint wood-frame homes, built in the 1920s,
have missing shingles, peeling paint and sagging frames.
</P>
<P>
   But for some of Samoa's 300 residents, about half of whom are
current or former timber workers, this latest change is the most
unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what's going to happen,'' said Rose Rogers, 49,
who moved here with her husband and son 10 years ago. ``It's
wonderful, and I don't want to see it change at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideas for a Samoa of the future include affordable housing, a
new industrial park for technology companies, artists' lofts,
offices and a tourist resort.
</P>
<P>
   The restored Victorian-style hostelry, a beautiful 11-room guest
house built in 1908 for the Vance Redwood Co.'s owner, could become
a bed-and-breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Samoa is already a tourist destination: Visitors fill the long
tables once occupied by lumbermen at the famous Samoa Cookhouse,
which includes a museum and gift shop. These properties are
included in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Since the homes are included in one parcel of land, the new
owner would have to get county supervisors to approve a new
subdivision before selling individual homes, officials said. The
land also would have to be rezoned from industrial to residential
before any new homes could be built.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson has invested a substantial amount of money for
improvements to the town, according to the auction brochure
published by Realty Marketing/Northwest, which is managing the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   About half the homes have fresh paint, new roofs or new doors.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the property has been keen. Since announcing the
auction two months ago, at a minimum bid of $1.75 million for the
town, his company has sent out more than 100 bid packages, and 50
potential buyers have visited, said John Rosenthal, president of
Realty Marketing/Northwest of Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had everything from affordable housing companies to real
estate developers to people representing pension investors,''
Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the residents, ``I'm just taking it one day at a time,''
said Dolores Weatherbee, 70, who has lived in Samoa for 55 years as
the daughter of one lumberman and then the wife of another. ``What
are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   She and others said they hoped the town would stay much as it
is. Residents have long enjoyed the quiet, close-knit atmosphere
and crime-free streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a Neighborhood Watch, but all we do (at the meetings)
is drink coffee and eat cookies,'' Rogers said. ``You can walk
around this town at midnight and be safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
