<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-PEARS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PEARS CAN BE THE APPLE OF YOUR EYE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although they ripen and are harvested the same time of year,
pears have been playing second fiddle to apples since Eve plucked
that fruit in the Garden of Eden. While the apple was being touted
as too inviting to resist, the pear was just another fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't changed much since Genesis.
</P>
<P>
   Americans ate roughly 3.5 pounds of pears per person in 1999,
according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture's National
Agricultural and Statistics Service, but they ate 18.7 pounds of
apples per person in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   While apples have been used for everything from pies to archery
practice to gifts for teachers, it seems like people only do two
things with pears: eat them raw or eat them poached. Maybe that's
because many cookbooks don't include anything other than poached
pear recipes. Or maybe it's because pears are so tasty when eaten
alone that they don't stick around long enough to be used in
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But pears are just as good as apples in many recipes and even
have a few shining uses of their own.
</P>
<P>
   When buying pears of any type, look for firm fruit that is
well-shaped and free of blemishes. Since the color of pears varies
greatly, it is not a good indicator of quality.
</P>
<P>
   The texture of pears will become grainy if allowed to ripen on
the tree; therefore, pears are harvested when mature but unripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pears in stores are usually conditioned to be one to three
days from ripeness, so buy pears about three days before you want
to eat them,'' according to the Fort Valley State University
College of Agriculture in Fort Valley, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   To ripen pears, place them in a paper bag and let them sit at
room temperature, says the USA Pear Bureau. When the pear yields
slightly if you apply gentle thumb pressure near the base of the
stem, it's ready to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett pears are one of the few varieties that signal ripeness
by changing color. Yellow Bartletts, at first green, turn bright
yellow. Red Bartletts change from a dark color to a brighter, more
brilliant red, often with some light vertical striping, according
to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are hundreds of varieties of pears, five are most
commonly found in supermarkets. They are:
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW BARTLETTS:
</P>
<P>
   Available from August through December. Aromatic and perfect for
eating fresh, this pear is very sweet and juicy. It is also
excellent for canning or cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bartletts:
</P>
<P>
   The only difference between the red and yellow versions is the
color. Red Bartletts have the same texture, flavor and uses as the
yellow version.
</P>
<P>
   Green Anjou:
</P>
<P>
   Available from October to June, these have abundant juice and a
sweet flavor. Anjous do not change color as they ripen.
</P>
<P>
   BOSC:
</P>
<P>
   This highly aromatic pear is the one often used for poaching
since it has a classic pear shape and dense flesh that stands up to
cooking. Boscs are the brownish pears, usually available from
August through February.
</P>
<P>
   SECKEL:
</P>
<P>
   These are the little, maroon- and olive-colored gems with a
sweet flavor. They are great to use in children's lunches or as a
garnish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
