<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MEXICO-PHOTOGRAPHY-$A     09-14 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PHOTOGRAPHY-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN MODERN: BACK TO A FUTURE THAT FELL BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 17)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a point between the two world wars when
politics and economics pushed experimental modernism in the visual
arts into a corner or simply squashed it in the Soviet Union,
Germany, Italy and America. For a while in the 1920s the modernist
adventure was still going full throttle. Although many artists in
Europe and the United States pulled back toward stylistic reason
and classicism immediately after the chaos of World War I,
avant-garde experiments like Dada, Suprematism, abstraction and
Surrealism continued to strike sparks in much of Europe and the
USSR in the 1920s and even in the 1930s where dictators did not
forbid them or social causes overshadow them. Mexico was a special
case. Early 20th-century art movements had a negligible influence
there before the 1920s. Just when they began to have an effect, the
Mexican muralist movement spread across the country's walls and by
its artistic power, nationalistic appeal and its very size and
visibility, marginalized the modernist currents pulsing through the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The muralist movement, set in motion by a government plan for
the ``Salvation and Regeneration of Mexico Through Culture'' in
1920, ignored European currents like Cubism and abstraction. Diego
Rivera, who had been a Cubist for several years in Europe before
turning away from it, devised a mural style that combined realism,
primitivism, myth and politics. Neither Jose Clemente Orozco nor
David Alfaro Siqueiros paid any more attention to Cubism or
abstraction than he did.
</P>
<P>
   And yet experimentalism did spring up and never died in Mexico;
it just stayed in the shade. A glimpse of vanguard modernism in
photography, which has been studiously neglected (and probably
largely unknown) by historians, may be caught in the gallery of the
Mexican Cultural Institute on East 39th street, in a quiet and
elegant little show called ``Otras Cosas: Abstract Photography.''
Malin Barth is the curator of this exhibition of 27 images by
Emilio Amero, Lola Alvarez Bravo, Manuel Alvarez Bravo, Augustin
Jimenez and Rosa Covarrubias, most from the late 1920s and early
1930s, a few from the 1950s. A brief catalog is available.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez Bravo, born in 1902 and by far the best known of the
five, is widely recognized as a major player in early modernist
photography as well as a vital influence on Mexican photography.
His most familiar images, taken on the street, distill the
commonplace experiences of a Mexican city into moments pregnant
with potential and resonant with mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Less well known are his modernist experiments with abstraction
and ambiguous details in the 1920s, which first brought him to
public attention in Mexico in 1928. For a series of ``Paper
Games,'' Alvarez Bravo let his adding machine spew out paper tape
that wound itself into unforeseeable shapes, and then photographed
the results close up. In 1931 he won first prize in a contest
sponsored by the Tolteca Cement Co. with a photograph that is at
once a geometric exercise and an index to information about the
subject. A trapezoidal form, actually a cement wall that recedes
too rapidly, stands on a slanted bed of crushed pebbles used for
making cement. The dark background, punctuated by lighter diagonal
lines, is the ceiling of the cement factory. Alvarez Bravo's lens
turns both site and process into spare emblems of modernity.
</P>
<P>
   He taught photography to his first wife, Lola Alvarez Bravo
(1907-1993), and she made a career of it, keeping his name after
they divorced. She is the late comer in this show; though she was
photographing by the mid-1930s, most of her pictures then were
portraits and street work. The selection here is of landscapes
taken in the 1940s and 1950s; they are less devoted to the
principles of abstraction than some of the other images in ``Otras
Cosas,'' though they immerse the viewer in roots and leaves and
branches without horizon, beginning or end.
</P>
<P>
   As a muralist, Emilio Amero (1901-1976) assisted Rivera and
Orozco; later he made experimental films and earned most of his
reputation as a lithographer. In the early 1930s he made
photograms, a cameraless technique thought of as a pre-eminently
modern way to make the familiar strange. Amero experimented with
the process and produced an unusual range of tones by exposing the
paper to light in the darkroom several times _ most photograms are
exposed only once _ and changing the light's intensity. His
rigorously constructed compositions, mostly of mass-manufactured
objects like gears and springs, include cut-out shapes as well as
actual objects placed on the emulsion and proclaim their modernism
by technique, composition and the use of machine parts and
utilitarian products.
</P>
<P>
   Augustin Jimenez's (1901-1974) photographs were shown in America
and London between 1929 and 1931 to good reviews. He subsequently
devoted himself to cinema, collaborating with Sergei Eisenstein and
working with Bunuel as well as making some films on his own. In
this show, his photographs from around 1931 concentrate on
repetitive elements that form patterns when ripped out of context:
The spines of a cactus, a line of rifles on a rack, the open-work
shadows of some sort of umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Covarrubias (1895-1970), wife of the painter and
illustrator Miguel Covarrubias, played with photograms in a manner
so different from Amero's that it might be called _ at risk of
sounding politically incorrect _ feminine modern. Two of her images
begin with drawings of herself in the nude and add emblematic
objects like shells, a sunburst, a Mexican ceramic animal, a goblet
turned upside down to make the outline of a full-skirted dress that
does not obscure her naked body. One photogram of a glass, lace and
a butterfly could certainly have been made by a man, but in the
context of her other work it looks like a riff on feminine
preoccupations. She won third prize in the Tolteca competition,
reportedly with the most abstract composition of all.
</P>
<P>
   Covarrubias was a striking woman even with her clothes on, and
Edward Weston took her portrait more than once. He and Tina
Modotti, who had moved to Mexico together in 1923, taught her
photography. How well she learned the lesson is evident from her
photogram of a halved cabbage, most likely made after Weston had
left Mexico and certainly before his extreme close-up of a halved
artichoke, which it strongly resembles.
</P>
<P>
   All of this work follows modernist dictates, even regarding
experiment, with an air of assurance, suggesting on the basis of
limited material that photographic modernism had a respectable
outpost in Mexico at the time. The surprise is that it exists in
some quantity, since so little of it has been seen here.
</P>
<P>
   Modernism came to Mexico from abroad. In photography, and to
some degree in painting, Weston and Modotti were primary influences
(though Covarrubias probably learned about photograms in Europe in
1926 when she became friends with Man Ray). In the 1920s and 1930s,
several outstanding foreign photographers, including Weston,
Modotti, Paul Strand and Henri Cartier-Bresson (and Eisenstein),
worked for a time in Mexico, and their presence enriched the
culture of that country, if not as greatly as it enriched the
culture of the visitors.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
