<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-CRIME-OF-PAS     09-14 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-CRIME-OF-PASSION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSION SENDS POWERFUL BRAZILIAN NEWSMAN OVER THE EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Wednesday, Sept. 13, or thereafter.) 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's MARTINEZ COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the MARTINEZ COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ 
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People on the streets of Rio de Janeiro or Sao Paulo have more
than once had to ask themselves if they're not living in a soap
opera.
</P>
<P>
   Passion is such common coinage in Brazil that novelists don't
have to invent anything _ real life has already done so.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, crimes of passion in Brazil occur in the
favelas, communities of misery and poverty that surround big
cities, but even the famous are not immune. They, too, can succumb
to the same consuming emotion, because passion recognizes no class.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 p.m. on Sunday, Aug. 20, Antonio Marcos Pimenta Neves,
63, pumped two bullets into Sandra Gomide, 32, killing her
instantly. They both worked for the same company and had been
lovers for three years.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Sandra had been trying to break off the affair but
the obsessive Pimenta, distraught with jealousy and desperation,
would not let go.
</P>
<P>
   His consuming suspicion was that she was seeing someone else. To
find out, he started going through e-mail on her computer, and as
she walked down the street he'd follow her, blind with jealousy, in
his car, crashing into things along the way. At night he took to
watching the shadows in the windows of her house for hours, just
like James Stewart in ``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   Described like this, this crime seems much like any other of the
many that happen every day. But it is not. Pimenta Neves, whom I
met briefly at a luncheon in 1996, was one of the most powerful
newspapermen in Brazil. A prudent, serious and reflective man, no
one could possibly imagine he'd be capable of violent passion.
</P>
<P>
   When I met him at a restaurant in Sao Paulo, we discovered we
had been film critics during the same era and that we had loved the
same movies. At the time, Pimenta had just returned from
Washington, where he'd served as an adviser at the World Bank, and
had become editor of Gazeta Mercantil, Brazil's most prestigious
financial daily.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that his twin daughters, born in 1972, lived in
Washington with their mother, and that loneliness at times engulfed
him. The year after our meeting, he was named editor of O Estado de
Sao Paulo, and thereafter I lost track of him. So the man I met was
a very different Pimenta.
</P>
<P>
   At some point during 1997 Pimenta fell in love with Sandra
Gomide, business editor at Gazeta Mercantil, and when he moved to O
Estado, he took her with him.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, Sandra soared to dizzying heights at the
newspaper. Her $1,000 monthly salary as a special reporter rose
nearly fivefold. A striking and sensual woman, she was, it seemed,
amazingly intelligent. Returning to postgraduate studies for her
Master's at Sao Paolo's Research Institute, her articles early this
year on aviation mergers in Brazil were a must-read for anyone in
business or media.
</P>
<P>
   But something started going wrong between the two lovers. Two
months ago, during an editors' meeting at O Estado, Pimenta
complained that Sandra was neglecting her work and that he had
asked for her resignation. Then he was seen going through Sandra's
private mail on her computer to check for messages from an
Ecuadorian businessman with whom Pimenta suspected she was in love.
</P>
<P>
   This story is not all that different from other famous tales of
fiction, such as that of Carmen in Prosper Merimee's novel of the
same name, or that of Lola Lola or Rosa in Heinrich Mann's ``The
Blue Angel.'' But Brazilian crimes are moved by more complex
passions. Sometimes it's a matter of wounded pride, self-respect or
honor, but most times it's all about possessiveness.
</P>
<P>
   There are countless examples and some are still alive in
people's memories today, like the unforgetable murder of writer
Euclides da Cunha, author of the Brazilian classic ``Os Serties.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1906, Da Cunha was a member of the Brazilian Academy
of Letters, supervisor of Public Works and one of the most
distinguished figures in the country. He had just come back from a
14-month trip on the Amazon, to find his wife Saninha pregnant.
Rather than disowning her, he decided to adopt the baby. A year
later another boy was born _ again, not his _ and he also accepted
him without reproach. He only reacted strongly when Saninha left
him to live with her lover of all those years, Dilermando de Assis.
</P>
<P>
   Da Cunha, who had accepted adultery, could not accept
abandonment. He went to his rival's house and, after shooting in
the air, he pointed the gun at Saninha. But Dilermando, national
rifle champion, was quicker on the draw and shot Da Cunha clean
through the chest. Da Cunha's death was a national tragedy and
Brazil decreed an official three-day mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Pimenta, too, could not accept Sandra leaving him. He'd appear
at her apartment at any hour of the day or night, with a variety of
excuses, and sometimes he even hit her. Sandra reported him to the
police on charges of ``forced entry and battery,'' but nothing came
of it. The police just thought it was a mere quarrel between an
immensely powerful man and his lover.
</P>
<P>
   At daybreak, Aug. 20, Pimenta left for the outskirts of Sao
Paulo where he often rode to release his tension and where Sandra's
family kept two horses. He knew that she would appear at any
moment, as she did every Sunday. He waited for her till 2:30 in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw her arrive, he took out his gun and said he was
going to kill her _ and himself _ if she insisted on leaving him.
Sandra cried, ``No, Pimenta! Don't do it!''
</P>
<P>
   Two shots were heard. The first bullet hit her in the chest,
puncturing a lung, the second bullet caught her in the head, just
above the left ear, as she fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Pimenta soberly gathered up the spent shells and fled in his
car. For hours he drove aimlessly around nearby rural Ibiuna until
finally he decided to seek refuge at a friend's house. On the
Tuesday afternoon he wrote a farewell letter to his daughters,
saying he had lost all interest in living. He took a huge dose of
barbituates and lay down to die. He was found unconscious two hours
later and paramedics were able to resuscitate him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Pimenta has turned the tables and become the
accuser, charging that the dead woman had ``personally and
professionally'' deceived him, ridiculed his honor and given him a
venereal disease.
</P>
<P>
   Was the crime, then, an act of blind passion, or vengeance, or
the destruction of a woman by a sick man who could no longer
possess her? Two of Brazil's most intelligent women, novelist
Nelida Pinon and sociologist Rosiska Darcy de Oliveira believe that
violence continues to be the macho's only way of expression in
response to wounded pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society itself is an accomplice,'' says Darcy de Oliveira.
``The Penal Code doesn't prescribe any form of punishment for a man
who beats a woman. And from there to murder is only a small step.''
</P>
<P>
   Confined to a rest home, Pimenta has shown no remorse and has
self-confidently assumed the role of victim. He is conscious only
of living in a soap opera. What he doesn't know is that those
condemned to that hell can never leave.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------- &QL;
