<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ALMOSTFAMOUS-TEX     09-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ALMOSTFAMOUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERON CROWE'S ROCK-NOSTALGIA PIECE IS UNFOCUSED AND TOO ADMIRING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a beautiful scene about halfway through Cameron Crowe's
``Almost Famous'' that finds Stillwater, the fictional 1970s rock
band at the center of the film, aboard the tour bus on a sunburnt
morning out of Kansas. In the front of the bus, the magnetic
guitarist Russell Hammond (Billy Crudup) recovers from an evening
of drugs and booze; his bandmates lounge around bored and tired,
groupies at their sides; and in the back, William Miller (Patrick
Fugit), the 15-year-old rock journalist covering the group for
Rolling Stone magazine, sits next to Penny Lane (Kate Hudson), a
groupie he's fast falling in love with, but who is in love with
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   A song comes on the radio _ ``Tiny Dancer,'' one of Elton John's
soaring early-'70s anthems of heartbreak; one of the band members
begins to sing along. And then, one by one, everyone else rises
from their hazy slumber to join in _ quickly building to a
crescendo that's both exultant and, in its brevity and elusiveness,
oddly, unavoidably melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Famous'' is a memory piece _ writer-director Cameron
Crowe (''Jerry Maguire'') based the screenplay on his experiences
as a boy-wonder rock journalist _ but what makes it such a
frustrating experience is that this scene is one of the few that
come through with any degree of emotional clarity. Crowe locates an
underlying theme here _ namely, the way popular music creates
powerful, yet ephemeral, links between its listeners _ and he
brings it to the fore with a quiet, unforced eloquence. But for so
much of the rest of the film, he seems to be remembering
experiences that he doesn't have a hold on, and emotions that he's
never completely sorted out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost Famous'' is certainly in need of an editor (it's at
least 15 minutes too long, and it has a half-dozen characters too
many), but what it seems most in need of is a psychotherapist _
someone who can help Crowe give his adolescence a meaning and a
focus.
</P>
<P>
   The Crowe stand-in is William, a precocious San Diego teen-ager
who has already skipped two grades in school. His overprotective
mother (Frances McDormand) abhors rock music, driving older sister
Anita (Zooey Deschanel) out of the house with her rants against sex
and drugs. But William has been writing music reviews for a local
underground paper and sending his work to Creem magazine editor
Lester Bangs (Philip Seymour Hoffman) and to the editors at Rolling
Stone magazine. Eventually, he's awarded a major assignment _
following Stillwater, a struggling band on the brink of a
breakthrough, on tour.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe has a loose narrative thread running through the movie _
William keeps trying to get a one-on-one interview with Russell _
but the screenplay is mostly anecdotal. Russell attends a party and
drops too much acid; the band has petty squabbles over whether
Russell is trying to steal the spotlight; the groupies decide to
help William lose his virginity. Along the way, a love triangle
develops, also: William wants Penny, Penny wants Russell, and
Russell wants to sleep with Penny without his steady girlfriend
back in New York ever finding out.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't with the episodic structure. I think if Crowe
had decided to play these episodes out with a more relaxed whimsy,
he might have had a low-key sleeper. But instead, in scene after
scene, you feel him trying for meaning that the material can't
support _ or meaning that remains too deeply embedded in his brain
to make any sense to the viewer. After a while, the film loses its
center. Is it William's story? Penny and Russell's? Stillwater's? I
don't quite understand the exact nature of William's journey,
either. Are we supposed to root for him to win Penny's heart _ or
to be the one who finally brings Penny and Russell together? Is he
supposed to become a great journalist _ or realize that journalists
are gadflies who have no friends?
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of problems aren't uncommon for autobiographical
works; there are periods of many people's lives that remain too
emotionally complicated for them to ever come to terms with, much
less shape into a coherent 120-minute film. And there are things
here, it should be said, that are as good as anything Crowe has
ever done. Always showing a gentle touch with his actors, he works
particular wonders with his ensemble, especially McDormand, who
finds depths of humanity in her broadly written, too-small part,
and Hoffman, who captures the real-life Bangs' crinkly edges with
surprising warmth.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, ``Almost Famous'' feels at once
overdeliberated and too thin _ very much made by (and for) a
middle-aged white guy on the road to his first midlife crisis and
in desperate need of validation. And while Crowe may be clinging to
his self-image as a progressive hipster, a lot of his formulations
also seem terribly old-school. He tries to do right by the women in
the film _ at one point, William calls the groupies the purest kind
of fans _ but they still come off as slutty, hangers-on cliches.
Meanwhile, the soundtrack, which features Led Zeppelin , Deep
Purple and The Who, among many others, feels a bit too worshipful
of these (mostly white) '70s rock gods to have much resonance for
today's hip-hop-weaned teen-agers. Crowe deserves credit for his
ambition and heart-felt sincerity. But as much as you may want to
like it, ``Almost Famous'' simply refuses to sing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Almost Famous''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Cameron Crowe
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Billy Crudup, Kate Hudson, Patrick Fugit
</P>
<P>
   Length: 122 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, drug use and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _ .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
