<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-MIDLIFE-LIFEGUARD-HNS     09-14 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDLIFE-LIFEGUARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TURNING A MIDLIFE CRISIS INTO A BIG SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL VIRTANEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``I-I-I wanna be a lifeguard
</P>
<P>
   ``I-I-I wanna guard your life
</P>
<P>
   I-I-I wanna be a lifeguard
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardly any clothes
</P>
<P>
   ``Sand between my toes
</P>
<P>
   ``White stuff on my nose''
</P>
<P>
   (From ``I Wanna Be a Lifeguard'' by Broadway Blotto)
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The 250-pound man is floating face-down in the
deep end of the pool, so you jump in with a rescue tube and swim.
You hook him under the arms, tilting his back onto the tube, and
then start kicking. Only this guy isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, you've traveled maybe five feet. Two minutes of
exerting like mad, finally you cover the 15 feet to poolside.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's midlife crisis takes a different turn. Mine has
morphed into dreams of a tall chair overlooking the beach in
Trinidad. Sand between my toes. White stuff on my nose.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, I took the Red Cross lifeguarding course. I had
thought, at first, it was going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, you just about had to be Johnny Weismuller to
be a lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   You had to be able to outswim a school of piranha, and you had
to be able to wrestle a giant crocodile into submission, and then
you had to haul that monster to shore by yourself, using only a
cross-chest hold and a modified sidestroke.
</P>
<P>
   Even for Weismuller, who did this in Tarzan movies, it wasn't
easy. He'd been an Olympic swimmer, and he could do just about
anything with large animals and water.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Cross began offering lifeguard training in 1914, it
never actually involved crocodiles. But you had to be able to swim
far, tread water for a long time and rescue struggling victims
without any equipment, using various grappling techniques to get
the upper hand, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The burly Commodore Wilbert E. Longfellow founded the program to
end what was a mounting toll from drownings. In old photographs, he
looks like he could have done the job single-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you didn't have to be Johnny Weismuller. But you had to be
Jack LaLanne or Buster Crabbe, or a member of the UCLA water polo
team, just about. It wasn't for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the whole business has evolved _ the result of
technology and more astute observation about how people actually
drown.
</P>
<P>
   Now that struggling victim would be classified in the Red Cross
manual as ``a distressed swimmer.'' If you couldn't reach out to
him from poolside, you'd jump in and pass him one end of the rescue
tube, keeping him away from you and afloat, and drag him back.
</P>
<P>
   If he progressed to ``active drowning victim,'' he'd probably be
incapable of grabbing the tube, and his few gasping movements would
be limited to what the Red Cross calls the ``instinctive drowning
response'' (the one that makes you wonder how the human race
survived long enough to learn to dog paddle).
</P>
<P>
   Then you hook him from behind, using the tube to keep you both
afloat, and start kicking. I did that with a 250-pound ``victim.''
It took two minutes to move him 15 feet, and I only swallowed water
twice.
</P>
<P>
   But I passed the Red Cross tests, which proves it doesn't take
an Olympian anymore.
</P>
<P>
   You have to swim 500 yards (20 pool lengths); tread water for
two minutes (no hands); retrieve a rubber brick from the bottom of
the pool; retrieve a human from the bottom of the pool; spend about
40 hours of class time; read two books; pass multiple-choice tests
on first-aid, safety and rescue; and certify in CPR. It cost $70.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part was being a 45-year-old among 15-year-olds (15
is the minimum age), who were polite but not entirely enthusiastic
about having a geezer in the class. And you could see bystanders
wondering why the old guy was hanging around the kids.
</P>
<P>
   The best part was being three times the age of the other
students _ who didn't really want you to be their victim. At the
Glen Hills Club, outdoors on a cool evening in late summer, you
don't want to be the one feigning spinal injury, the one that
they're taking 10 minutes or so to strap onto a backboard and pull
out of the diving well.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the practical point for a middle-aged man? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, who's also 15, made $5.50 and $6.25 an hour this
summer in her two, part-time guarding jobs. On her last scheduled
workday, I asked if she'd let me come out there and sit in the
chair for a few minutes with her whistle and the rescue tube. Being
all certified now. No, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually a serious business, done around here mostly by
teen-agers at cement pools. Preventing spinal cord injuries and
drownings. Keeping little kids from bobbing around where they can't
touch bottom and can't get out. Keeping knuckleheads from diving
head first into the shallow end.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'70s, a film came out titled ``Lifeguard'' in which
Sam Elliott portrayed a guy attending his 15-year high school
reunion. He was still a lifeguard, and everybody looked at him like
he was a loser. Now there's ``Baywatch'' on TV, making it appear
more glamorous as a career option.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported this summer that some Northeastern
beaches, facing a lifeguard shortage, recruited middle-aged
executives to come back on weekends and moonlight at the jobs
they'd held 20 years ago. They said it recalled the best times of
their youth.
</P>
<P>
   But to work at the ocean, you need a separate certification,
which is supposed to be more rigorous, on account of the surf.
</P>
<P>
   Volusia County, Fla., where lifeguards make approximately 3,000
ocean rescues a year, requires taking its course, annually swimming
500 meters, emergency medical technician certification, and ability
to tolerate ``inclement weather'' and ocean temperatures as low as
50 F. For entry-level seasonal work, it starts at $6.50 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Volusia Beach Patrol's senior lifeguard positions pay up to
$13.80, but you're also sworn in as a law-enforcement officer and
have to swim 500 meters in less than 10 minutes. A little too close
to Weismuller territory.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's Trinidad. Warmer water than Daytona. And maybe
they think geezer guards aren't bad for tourism. Make the
vacationers feel youthful.
</P>
<P>
   And if not? Dream about a beach chair, get out the sunblock, and
hum a few bars of the Blotto song.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HUMANRESOURCES-T     09-14 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HUMANRESOURCES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOVIE OF MANY `RESOURCES'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American movies so rarely have anything substantive to say about
people's work (Steven Soderbergh's wonderful ``Erin Brockovich'' is
perhaps the year's only exception) that foreign viewers might
simply assume that ours is a nation of leisure. But that's not the
case for the French, who, with movies like ``A Single Girl'' (about
a day in the life of a chambermaid) and ``Post Coitum'' (about a
book editor's obsessive relationship with one of her writers) have
shown a probing interest in the ways by which everyday folks earn
their keep.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Cantet's ``Human Resources'' is both a welcome addition
to the genre and a vivid, moving reminder of that central role that
work plays in our lives. Jalil Lespert plays Franck, a Parisian
college student who returns home for a summer internship in the
management offices of the factory where his father has toiled for
30 years. The bosses are busy trying to implement a 35-hour
workweek _ which will mean less overtime and money for the workers,
who oppose the plan. Franck wants to involve the workers in the
labor negotiations, but the bosses seem more intent on using his
plan for a referendum to justify more firings.
</P>
<P>
   You'll figure out quickly where the story is headed (hint:
Franck's dad is only five years from retirement age), but Cantet
has made a film of real purpose and intelligence, with his crisp
shooting style and complicated characterizations of everyone from
the ready-to-fight union representative to the middle manager
fearful that Franck is trying to usurp his power to the younger
worker coming to terms with the soul-deadening nature of his work.
Indeed, what a refreshing, simple pleasure just to hear characters
talk about what it is they do for a living and how it makes them
feel.
</P>
<P>
   I do wish the director hadn't ultimately decided to paint
Franck's conflict in such black-and-white, ``workers
good''/''management bad'' terms. The sequence in which Franck joins
with the union to strike against the company is moving, but it
doesn't tell us much about how this soulful idealist will ever find
his own place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cantet has brought a whole range of fascinating ideas to
the table _ about the gulf that develops between uneducated parents
and their educated children; and about how corporate culture is
often defined by an unwillingness on the part of all employees to
listen to one another. Lespert, too, is a major find. The French
cinema has never been in short supply of brooding, brown-eyed,
hunky intellectual types, but he captures Franck's shifts from
haughtiness to empathy, and from ambition to self-disgust, with a
control and authority that suggests his own career is going to be a
long one.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Human Resources''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Laurent Cantet
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jalil Lespert, Jean-Claude Vallod
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Not rated: Adult themes make it unsuitable for children
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Kelly is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
