<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-LEE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno says she is
``comfortable'' with the handling of the Wen Ho Lee case and
refuses to apologize to the freed nuclear scientist for his
nine-month detention on charges of security violations. Her remarks
come after a federal judge said the government's investigation had
``embarrassed the entire nation.'' By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ George W. Bush accuses Al Gore of
``potential misuse of the White House'' for allegedly soliciting a
1995 campaign donation from a Texas trial lawyer after President
Clinton vetoed a bill, which the lawyer opposed, that would have
limited liability lawsuits. A Gore aide says the vice president did
not solicit the donation. Bush battles to overcome Gore's lead in
California by emphasizing his support for public education while
Gore presses his own education plan in Manchester, N.H. By STEWART
M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   POLL-INDEPENDENTS (Washington) _ A new poll, contradicting other
recent surveys, finds independent voters evenly divided between Al
Gore and George W. Bush. It reports that one in three such voters
who have committed to one candidate now say they might change their
minds. Independents are one part of the so-called swing-voter bloc
that likes Bush's personality but prefers Gore's stand on the
issues. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Editors: Marianne Means is off work today. Her next MEANS-COLUMN
will be filed Monday, Sept. 18 in the COMMENTARY (``k'') category.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   MOYNIHAN-INTERVIEW (Washington) _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
the former Harvard professor known for his sharp intellect, is
savoring his last days on Capitol Hill before returning to academic
life. The lanky New York Democrat, who has served 24 years, says in
an interview that ``there comes a time when it's time to go and to
let other people have a crack at it.'' By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE-POLICE (Washington) _ Gourmands, beware! Angel-hair pasta
with tangy Parmesan cheese grated over basil marinara sauce will
never be the same if the federal government has its way. The Food
and Drug Administration is considering a rule that, in effect,
would ban the manufacture and import of unpasteurized cheeses
because it believes they may pose a health risk. If the ban is
imposed, say goodbye to those tasty, pungent favorites that you
make or eat at restaurants. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
