<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ARMY-EDUCATION-HNS &LR;      09-14 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARMY HOPES ON-LINE UNIVERSITY WILL HELP KEEP RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Ga., Ky., Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Army Secretary Louis Caldera, rolling out a new
incentive to keep recruits in the military, says a groundbreaking
on-line education program will allow soldiers to earn degrees while
serving at posts in the United States and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Benning, Ga.; Fort Campbell, Ky.; and Fort Hood, Texas,
will serve as the first three sites for the Army University Access
Online education initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The $598 million, six-year program is to begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest way the services have thought of education is as a
benefit for departing soldiers, the GI Bill model,'' Caldera said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different model which says that instead
of giving it as a benefit for people who served in the military,
make it an incentive for people to join and stay in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled by Caldera two months ago, the program is one of
several Army initiatives designed to help counter a generally
downward slide in enlistment and retention.
</P>
<P>
   Though Army retention has risen over the past year and the
service also has met its recruiting goals, signing up 80,000 new
soldiers, Caldera said he believes that many of those leaving are
using educational incentives earned during their enlistment to
complete college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, he said, is taking the lead in creating an on-line
university system and taking its commitment to in-service education
``to a whole new level.'' The program will offer soldiers the
opportunity to earn two-year, four-year and post-graduate degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime military observers, among them the University of
Maryland's David Segal and former Pentagon leader Sara Lister, see
the move as a bold step.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think it's raising the ramp significantly,'' said Segal,
director of the Center for Research on Military Organization, a
think tank. ``There have been small initiatives in the past, and
the Army is saying, `Let's get more bang for the buck out of this,'
and I think they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister, former assistant secretary of the Army for manpower and
reserve affairs, said soldiers like to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of soldiers who have bachelor's degrees,
master's degrees. There are undoubtedly some with Ph.D.s, and what
(Caldera has) done has been very sensible and also very clever, and
it certainly should help retention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has traditionally offered education benefits to draw
recruits into the service, but has had trouble keeping veteran
soldiers because many of them have left to complete their
education, Segal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only recently, I think, that the services have explicitly
realized that the real competition is not McDonald's, it's the
college down the street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern University sociologist Charles Moskos, the author
of ``The Postmodern Military: Armed Forces After the Cold War,''
said soldiers he met earlier this month in Kosovo complained they
didn't have time to answer e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Moskos said, ``I'm cautiously optimistic. It's worth the
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sig Christenson by e-mail at sigc(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
