<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURVEYORS OF VULGARITY AND VIOLENCE ARE DOING US NO FAVORS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the F-word was heard in a movie or over the radio, there
was the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Before simulated coitus was allowed on movie or television
screens, there was the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Before the blood and gore of the gangster movies and video
games, there was the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Long live the First Amendment. May it ever provide creative
artists and pretenders to that vocation the freedom to make and
distribute their creations. As Americans protected by that
provision of the Constitution, filmmakers, music producers and
video game manufacturers have the right to dispense products using
the most extreme vocabularies of sex and violence if they choose to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, that is their right. That does not mean, however,
that it is right for them to do it. And one can make a strong case
that, by doing so, they are wronging society and jeopardizing their
freedom and everyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans who are still ambulatory and alert can remember
the days when some novels now considered to be classics were banned
in all or certain parts of this country because they contained a
few words or scenes that today would be considered quite tame.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, anything _ with a few exceptions of time and
place _ goes. And that near-total license has led to a spiraling
degradation of cultural and aesthetic standards. The profusion of
protected vulgarity has contributed to a pervasive mediocrity in
popular entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Comedians don't have to be funny anymore. They have only to yell
obscenities. The same holds true in much of what passes for music
for the masses. Rhythmic noise overlaid with offensive language,
violent or sexually degrading images and fractured rhymes drowns
out popular music that evidences talent.
</P>
<P>
   Variations of the F-word predominate in what passes for dialogue
in the preponderance of movies that elevate violence and special
effects above imaginative plotting and insightful characterization.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it is easier to do that. Moreover, the entertainment
industry has conditioned much of the public into thinking that this
is what it really wants. The truth, of course, is that the public
comes to want what the entertainment industry gives it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the wholly unscrupulous marketing of killing games
that pander to the basest instincts of children and adults alike.
The cumulative effect of prolonged and persistent participation in
such games is to reduce the players' sensitivity to the value of
life. The subconscious mind, after all, can't distinguish between
real and virtual murder.
</P>
<P>
   This diatribe obviously was triggered by the Federal Trade
Commission report that accuses some filmmakers, music producers and
video game manufacturers of surreptitiously marketing entertainment
products to children that are labeled for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential candidates, predictably, have seized upon the
FTC report as a rationale for calling upon the entertainment
industry to cease and desist from the egregious practice. And just
as predictably, entertainment industry moguls have denied doing it.
</P>
<P>
   This makes for good political theater. But the politicians and
entertainment sellers are all skirting the real issue. It's not
enough for the movie, music and game folks to correct their
marketing practices. They really need to cut back on making the
worthless, distasteful and dangerous junk and foisting it off on
the defenseless public.
</P>
<P>
   They can do better, because they have the talent and resources
to move to a higher plane. Unfortunately, there is so much money to
be made in adhering to the easier low road that there is little
room to hope that they will clean up their act of their own
volition.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, no one who really values the freedom guaranteed to
all Americans by the First Amendment wants to see government force
the industry to change its entirely mercenary ways. If, however,
the entertainment industry continues to abuse the protection
afforded by the First Amendment, that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   There still are powerful groups in this country that would like
to take us back to the days when ``Lady Chatterley's Lover'' and
``Ulysses'' were banned and when Lenny Bruce was jailed for saying
the F-word in a nightclub to an audience of adults.
</P>
<P>
   Those groups have a very narrow slant on the First Amendment.
And those who are abusing that precious protection today are
playing into their hands.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a former Fort Worth Star-Telegram columnist
and editorial writer. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
