<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DUETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NOTES IN `DUETS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Paltrow doesn't have a whole lot on his resume since
beginning his producing career in 1973, the year his daughter,
Gwyneth, was born. Perhaps that explains why his new directorial
effort, ``Duets,'' looks a little like an early '70s TV-movie: a
lost, well-meaning artifact about ``looking for America'' that you
stumbled across during a late-night channel-surf.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that most of ``Duets' '' cast wasn't around in
the early '70s. Nor was karaoke, the movie's unifying topic. But
the movie echoes so many movies from that era and later that it's
like the elder Paltrow's cinematic version of karaoke _ he's
filming along to the oldies.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers not to onstage performances, but to the motley
duos that make up the movie's three interlocking story lines. These
uneasy riders include a karaoke hustler (Huey Lewis) and his
estranged daughter (Gwyneth Paltrow), who insists that he act like
a dad now that her mother's dead; a midlife-runaway salesman (Paul
Giamatti) and a not-as-harmless-as-he-seems hitchhiker (Andre
Braugher); and a disenchanted gypsy-cab driver (Scott Speedman) and
a karaoke thrush (Maria Bello) who sleeps her way into the best
hotel rooms, much to the cabdriver's dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone pairs up on the way to the National Karaoke Finals in
Omaha, Neb., but it's not the climax _ which is kinda abrupt and
bizarre _ that matters here, so much as the bonding that takes
place on the road. Unfortunately, only one of the stories _ the
Giamatti-Braugher arc _ is at all developed.
</P>
<P>
   The father-daughter story is underdrawn, and for some reason,
director Bruce stuck daughter Gwyneth with the movie's most
stilted, hoary speech, about how her dad should act like a dad. And
although Bello probably gives the best performance, it's difficult
to tell just what screenwriter John Byrum is trying to do with her
and Speedman's characters.
</P>
<P>
   It's an oddball movie, and your enjoyment depends on how much it
breaks down your resistance: To Gwyneth Paltrow singing (less
painful than you'd think); to Huey Lewis acting (he seems
uncomfortable and jittery, except when he's singing); to the
soundtrack of warhorse rock and soul songs chirped by people who
were never meant to sing them in public; to the idea of karaoke
itself, which seldom sounds as good as it does in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But if Paltrow and Byrum are trying to get at the conscience of
America today, and at the rush that onstage singing can give you,
they don't succeed. It doesn't mean that ``Duets'' won't grab you
if you're in the right mood, but in the current box-office climate,
it seems likely that most people will just plug their ears to its
uneven charms.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Duets''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bruce Paltrow
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Paul Giamatti, Andre Braugher, Gwyneth Paltrow
</P>
<P>
   Length: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, brief nudity, sexual situations and
violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
