<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BORDER-RESCUE-HNS &LR;      09-14 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-RESCUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BORDER AGENTS GET A LESSON IN WATER SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Border Patrol agent Cecilio Bauelos pulled
a stack of nearly new life jackets _ including a tiny one for a
baby _ from the stowage area of a patrol boat moored to the banks
of the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, they've only been used once,'' Bauelos said.
</P>
<P>
   The life vests apparently were used by people who risked the
dangerous crossing to get from Mexico to the United States. And
just as these illegal immigrants are taking steps to avoid the
hazards of the river, so, too, are the agents of the U.S. Border
Patrol and its Mexican counterpart, Grupo Beta.
</P>
<P>
   Bauelos watched Wednesday as 40 members of the Border Patrol,
Grupo Beta and Mexico's federal police trained in water-rescue
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Rain dappled the river as animated agents in swimming trunks
gathered on a wooden dock along with life preservers, buoys and
other water-rescue devices. One officer dived from the dock into
the murky river, and Bauelos flinched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's dangerous!'' said Bauelos, who was trained in water
safety while in the U.S. Coast Guard. ``You should never dive in
head-first. Sometimes there are concrete blocks on the bottom of
the river. Did that guy come up?''
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   As thunderstorms rolled overhead, agents tossed life preservers
or towed to safety ``drowning'' companions who struggled in the
river's thick water hyacinth lilies.
</P>
<P>
   Some agents with Mexico's Grupo Beta don't know how to swim, but
that won't be an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Garza, head of the McAllen Border Patrol Sector, which is
hosting the $10,000 training program, said agents will be taught
that jumping in to perform a rescue is only a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to use the equipment they have at hand to perform
the rescue,'' he said. ``We want them to be able to do their jobs
better, but we're not going to demand that they jump in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to become victims, too, is not what we have in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fletemeyer, a nationally acclaimed water-safety instructor
helping to train the officers, said statistics show 90 percent of
all water-related accidents occur between 10 and 20 feet from the
shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, there's seldom any need for a person ... to
actually go into the water to effect a rescue,'' he told his
students. ``I'm here to train members of the Border Patrol not to
be lifeguards, but to be lifesavers.''
</P>
<P>
   The water-safety training is a part of the Border Safety
Initiative launched by the United States and Mexico in 1998, said
Renee Harris, associate chief of the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, which received almost $500,000 in U.S. funding
this year and also is underwritten by the Mexican government,
focuses on preventing immigrant deaths, search and rescue
operations, identification of dead immigrants and tracking of
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1998, immigrant safety was not a significant part of the
Border Patrol's activities, and statistics about their well-being
were sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, however, figures kept by the agency have shown
drowning to be the leading cause of death for immigrants who
illegally cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   In both 1998 and 1999, the Border Patrol documented the drowning
deaths of 89 immigrants along the Southwest border.
</P>
<P>
   In June, two Mexican men drowned while trying to cross the river
from Matamoros to Brownsville. A Mexican TV crew captured images of
the deaths, along with footage of the Grupo Beta, apparently
looking on helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the water-safety training program is not a result of
those highly publicized deaths, but the decision to place it in
Brownsville was.
</P>
<P>
   A similar training program, conducted by a Border Patrol agent
certified in swift-water rescue, recently was held in El Paso,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take the best practices from both areas and share
them,'' she said. ``In the future, officers on both sides of the
border will be able to teach this class to others.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Alison Gregor by e-mail at agregor(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
