<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-US-KOREA-BUSINESS-BOS     09-14 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOREA-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ELMENTAL CHANGE FOR US, KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (f and i coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Magnesium is about as friendly as an element gets. From homey
laxatives like grandma's milk of magnesia, to furnaces for making
steel, to the very latest in environmental technology, most all its
uses are benign.
</P>
<P>
   Now it may become the element that opens normal trading
relations between the United States and North Korea after 50 years
of war, distrust, and a tough US embargo.
</P>
<P>
   An alliance of businessmen and academics has put together the
first joint venture between US and North Korean interests _ a deal
struck quietly in Pyongyang in late August to produce and export
magnesia, a processed form of the mineral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real importance of this is it is a first step in
confidence building,'' said Greyson Bryan, a California-based Asia
Society official and specialist on North Korean business law.
``Confidence for North Korea that it can benefit from closer
relations with the rest of world, and for the rest of world that
there is something worth investing in in North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal is significant for several reasons: It marks the
apparent beginning of a special zone for US investment in North
Korean mines, south of Korea's Rajin-Sonbong free trade zone, and
it provides a striking illustration of how private citizens, rather
than government, are leading the United States into better
relations with the North.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture is no sure thing. Nowhere in international
politics and business are the commitments less certain than in US
dealings with what generations of American diplomats have demonized
as the world's most isolated Stalinist regime, and a significant
part of the US partners' obligation is to recruit investment to
modernize North Korea's magnesium industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the US partners _ a Harvard-based specialist in business
law, a Korean War veteran who made millions in gold mining, and a
scholar who serves as a go-between for the United States and Korea
_ are as interested in geopolitics as in profit. All have an
abiding interest in northeast Asia, and all believe US policy often
has heightened tensions in a region where Chinese, Korean, Russian,
Japanese, and American interests easily can come into conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korea, its people, and its 10 million divided families are the
unfortunate victims of a US policy dominated by Cold War
thinking,'' said Robin Radin, 58, who joined Harvard Law School's
international law program in 1996 after nearly a decade as a top
corporate executive in Japan and China. ``I want to make a positive
change in relations between the United States and North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   Birl Worley, 69, who became a mining executive after serving in
the Korean War, put it more gruffly. ``I was one of those nice
people who helped make a mess of China and North Korea,'' he said.
``I thought I'd make a little amends.''
</P>
<P>
   The third US partner is K.A. Namkung, a China-born Korean,
raised in Japan, educated and naturalized in the United States. He
refuses to discuss the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The deal targets an emerging market in North America and Japan
for environmentally benign methods for disposing of the nasty
byproducts of mines and coal-burning power plants. Magnesium
products are coming into use in place of lime to absorb the sulphur
and carbon compounds produced in these industries. The resulting
magnesium sulphate is non-caustic and easy to handle compared to
the gooey, unusable gypsum that results from using lime on
sulphur-polluted mine water. And magnesium sulphate can be used as
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to create a door-opening venture with North Korean
interests grew out of the friendship Namkung and Radin formed in
the late 1960s, when they were graduate students in Asian and
Japanese history at the University of California-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   They fell out of touch for nearly 20 years, reconnecting by
chance just before Radin moved to Tokyo as a Morgan Stanley
executive. Their business dealings became frequent, and Namkung
became deeply involved in back-channel communications between
Pyongyang and Washington _ which led to the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Namkung and former President Jimmy Carter were key players in
the prolonged crisis in 1994 over allegations that North Korea was
developing the capacity to manufacture nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After the crisis was defused, to the fury of Clinton
administration officials who had advocated a new round of sanctions
against the North, relations among countries with interests in
northeast Asia gradually warmed, despite setbacks over North
Korea's missile development and testing, and ``in 1996, Tony
(Namkung) advised me that his contacts in North Korea had an
interest in attracting US investment, particularly in the mining
sector,'' Radin said.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed that the moment to realize their ambition to improve
North Korea's relations with the world was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, both participated in the first exchange between US and
North Korean legal experts; during the meetings, the Koreans
broached the idea of creating investment opportunities for US
investors in the Danchon mining region.
</P>
<P>
   But when the idea was pitched to the US mining industry,
``interest was tepid, to say the least,'' as Radin put it. So he
and Namkung organized a second trip in spring 1998 in an attempt to
persuade mining experts to join them in a venture.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Worley, president of Golden Cycle Gold Corp.,
one of the oldest gold mining companies in the United States. After
retiring from Golden Cycle last year, he co-founded of Aurora
Partners Ltd. to undertake the joint venture. When US sanctions on
North Korea were partially lifted this summer, the trip that led to
the magnesium deal was arranged.
</P>
<P>
   Still, much can go wrong, particularly in the financing. Because
the United States still considers North Korea a terrorist nation,
conventional access to international capital is barred.
</P>
<P>
   ``North Korea is no pasture to bring your cash cows into,''
Worley said. ``But if somebody doesn't lead the way, nobody will
follow. . . . One of the main reasons we're there is to show it can
be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
