<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEXUS IS300 IS SNEAKY FAST ENOUGH TO SLIP INTO SEDAN CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The answer: 2001 Lexus IS300.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Is there a Toyota product that can appeal to
young, aggressive drivers for whom the Camry or the Echo just
aren't enough, image-wise and zippy-wise?
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Toyota will tell you they've been struggling to
come up with a car that will appeal to younger drivers. The Camry
is a fine car, but you don't find it tricked out the way you do
Honda Accords and Civics. The Echo doesn't seem to have created any
youthful buzz, and the ad campaign for this low-end Toyota is being
revamped in the shadow of highly successful ads for the Ford Focus,
which has youthful buzz all about it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lexus _ out of Toyota's luxury division _ is not a car
most 18-year-olds will be able to afford (at $30,000-plus), but
given the number of 25-40-somethings with good incomes in this
high-tech economy, the IS300 may be just the rig to challenge BMW,
Saab, and Audi in the compact sport sedan class.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great-looking car, from its gaping fascia, up over its
steeply sloped front, big windshield, solid roofline and down to
its short, chopped rear deck. It's downright Saablike.
</P>
<P>
   But if the outside says Sweden, the inside says Switzerland, as
in fine watches. Especially cool is the chronograph watch style of
the center gauge. Its circumference is toothed like a gear and
inside it sit the tachometer, speedometer, and smaller gauges for
temperature and fuel readings.
</P>
<P>
   And you get downright German with drilled aluminum pedals,
aluminum doorsills, and a sculpted aluminum shift knob. It's billed
as a five-passenger, but realistically, it will hold four adults.
</P>
<P>
   The leather front bucket seats on the test model were firm and
gripped especially well at the sides of the thighs and up the back
during hard cornering. A small steering wheel added that certain
race car feel that young drivers (and crazy older ones) seem to
crave.
</P>
<P>
   But looks, of course, won't fool many people who know what they
want in a sports sedan. You've got to show them performance.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Lexus has equipped the IS300 with an in-line six,
3.0-liter engine that delivers 215 horsepower. It's not as powerful
as the 300-horsepower plant introduced three years ago for the
GS400, but this is a smaller, lighter car, and this engine propels
it around just fine, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is a sneaky fast car. You stomp the gas, expecting
to hear some sign of surge: a roar, a burble, a guttural gush. You
get none of that. But then you look at the speedometer and realize
you have leaped forward and are rapidly gaining speed. The Lexus
engine is that quiet. So quiet, in fact, that you pick up tire
noise instead of engine sounds as you roll down the highway. In a
week of driving, the IS300 got about 21 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it comes only with an automatic, electronic, five-speed
transmission. It does a good job of shifting up _ for an automatic
_ as you accelerate. A manual option _ buttons on the steering
wheel a la Porsche _ lets you take over the shifting, but only to a
point. Use the manual option and try to run the car close to red
line and it won't let you. The automatic takes over and shifts up
for you. I hope they offer this with a good five-speed manual as
soon as they can come up with one.
</P>
<P>
   So how's it handle?
</P>
<P>
   Just the way a good sports sedan should.
</P>
<P>
   On the highway, it's nimble and firm, moving in and out of
traffic with a solid feel from the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   On corners, it flat out carves turns and there is virtually no
sense of weight being thrown around or body roll. That, no doubt,
owes to a sport-tuned suspension that has upper and lower control
arms, coil springs, and anti-roll bars front and rear.
</P>
<P>
   The price you pay, of course, is stiffness on rough roads, but
even here it's not a cowl-shudder tremor that ripples through the
cockpit as you get in some tight sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   It's got ABS operating four-wheel disc brakes that bring the
IS300 to confident, quick stops _ though I'd like a little more
feel from the brake pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to the manual transmission I long for _ and there
again, you'd get more feel for the car _ and you'd have an almost
perfect compact sports sedan, something the folks at Toyota have
been striving for in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The tuck-and-roll look of the leather-coated dashboard. Hey,
it's a fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --They did such a great job designing that chronograph gauge
setup. Too bad they didn't encircle the dash knobs with the same
thing: geared real metal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
