   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of FRIDAY, Sept.
15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WATCH-TARANTINO-WESTERNS (Hollywood) _ When Quentin Tarantino,
champion of everything from B-grade 1950s genres to '70s black
exploitation to life as a bitter and ironic cocktail, was asked
what film he wanted to watch, he said, ``The Golden Stallion'' _ a
1949 minifeature by a now all-but-forgotten journeyman director
named William Witney from the days of the Saturday morning cowboy
serials. This is the premiere of an occasional series featuring
accomplished filmmakers, actors, screenwriters or cinematographers
watching a movie that has some special resonance for them. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-CALLIGRAPHY (New York) _ As ``The Embodied Image:
Chinese Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott Collection,'' at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, demonstrates, in China, where words are
images, writing has traditionally been the highest art form of all,
and a source of profound political and emotional power. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   CLAUDE-LORRAIN (New York) _ On the current show of Claude
Lorrain's work, which features nearly 40 drawings and eight
etchings by the French expatriate artist who spent most of his life
in Rome at the Pierpont Morgan Library. By John Russell.
</P>
<P>
   PIERRE-GILLES-PHOTOS (New York) _ The New Museum of Contemporary
Art in SoHo presents a long overdue introduction in the United
States of the French photo team known as Pierre et Gilles. It is a
must-see for anyone interested in the intertwining histories of
postmodern (especially set-up) photography, fashion photography,
commercial illustration, the male nude in art and the emergence of
a gay sensibility. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   GIRARD-DESIGN (New York) _ ``The Opulent Eye of Alexander
Girard,'' at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum, is the first
comprehensive show devoted to Girard, who seems to have lacked the
recognition accorded his colleagues Eero Saarinen, Charles and Ray
Eames, and George Nelson. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   TALMUD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``The Talmud and the
Internet,'' Jonathan Rosen notes that one rabbinical term for the
Talmud means sea, and that the Hebrew word for its chapters means,
literally, webbing. Reviewed by Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ELIAN-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Elian Gonzalez Story'' has the
political heft of a Disney cartoon, the dramatic tension of
``Saturday Night Live'' and is so upbeat it should have been called
``Everybody Loves Elian.'' By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   DUETS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Duets,'' Bruce Paltrow's new
musical, features his daughter, Gwyneth, in its impressive ensemble
cast. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In addition to its title, there
are a few other things about ``Crime and Punishment in Suburbia,''
directed by Rob Schmidt, that might lead you to believe it has
something to do with Dostoyevsky. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   GOYA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Carlos Saura's visual knockout of a
film, ``Goya in Bordeaux,'' forcefully conjures up the spirit of
Goya, who died in exile in Bordeaux (France), portraying him as an
unstoppable bull of a man and an artistic visionary whose greatest
work fearlessly locked horns with the darkest human truths.
Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Into the Arms of Strangers,'' a
new documentary by Mark Jonathan Harris, tells the story of a group
of Jewish children from Germany, Austria and Czechoslovakia who
were fortunate enough to escape, thanks to the Kindertransport,
which took 10,000 children to the safety of England in the late
1930s. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   DREAM-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Clacking freight trains
silhouetted against a fading late autumn sunset, the peripheral
blur of trees speeding by a moving boxcar, the hollow glare of
anonymous gas stations and bus depots, and the desolation of shabby
bars and luncheonettes on the wrong side of the tracks: these are
some of the recurrent images that lend Ed Radtke's melancholy road
film ``The Dream Catcher'' an enveloping sadness. Reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   BAIT-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In the comic action thriller
``Bait,'' Alvin Sanders (Jamie Foxx), a paroled thief, and a
partner are caught red-handed stealing $2,000 worth of prawns from
a Brooklyn warehouse. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ One way of looking at Jon Shear's
harrowing and indelible film ``Urbania'' is to think of it as ``Sex
and the City'' turned inside out. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   CLEO-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ In 1964, the British singer Dame
Cleo Laine recorded a groundbreaking album, ``Shakespeare and All
That Jazz,'' that featured settings of Shakespeare's poetry by her
husband, John Dankworth. At Tuesday's opening night show of a
two-week engagement in New York, Laine and a quartet led by
Dankworth brought back four of them. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   ART-NOTES (Undated) _ News from the art world. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (New York) _ On Qing porcelain, an often
neglected stepchild in the family of Chinese porcelains. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NOTES (New York) _ Notes on Broadway. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ The Home Video column. By Peter M.
Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Undated) _ News from Hollywood. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Brief reviews by New York Times
critics of current movies
</P>
<P>
   ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK (Undated) _ The Album of the Week: Everclear:
``Songs From an American Movie, Volume I: Learning How to Smile''
(Capitol). By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-JAYS (New York) _ Bluejays at Yankees, 7:05 p.m. EDT.
By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-EXPOS-METS (Montreal) _ Mets at Expos, 7:00 p.m. EDT. By
