<P>
   &UR; OLYMPICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN (Sydney) _ The sun is setting on fading
empires. Gerontocracies are going out of style. The Olympic
movement is starting to resemble the Soviet Union in its final
days, just before people attacked the Berlin Wall with
sledgehammers. In this case, the cracks are appearing from within.
By George Vecsey. (With photo NYT 10)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-OPENING (Sydney) _ A beleaguered Olympic movement sought to
sustain its viability and to shift its focus toward the
possibilities of international brotherhood and the achievements of
the world's greatest athletes as the 27th Summer Games opened in
what is late winter in the Southern Hemisphere. By Jere Longman.
(With photos NYT 1, 2, 4)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-U.S. (Sydney) _ The United States dominated Norway, its
most intractable rival, by 2-0 in the opening women's match of the
Olympic soccer tournament. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIM (Sydney) _ Advance on the swimming competition, a
highly anticipated tournament in a swimming-crazed country. By
Christopher Clarey. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-NOTEBOOK (Sydney) _ Reporters' notebook. (Staff bylines to
come)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-MELBOURNE (Melbourne) _ It has been a bittersweet week for
Australia's other Olympic city. While Sydney was gussying itself up
for the opening ceremony and basking in the world's attention,
Melbourne, which hosted Australia's first Olympics in 1956, watched
from the sidelines. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RUN-CLARK (Undated) _ Feature on the Clark family _ sisters
Joetta and Hazel and sister-in-law Jearl _ who will be the only
runners representing the United States in the women's 800 meters.
The women finished first, second and third at the U.S. trials. By
Kelly Crow.  &UR;
