<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-U.S.-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN DEFEAT THEIR NEMESIS, NORWAY, 2-0, IN OLYMPIC SOCCER
OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ She delivered the winning goal in the
1996 Summer Olympics and led the Americans in scoring during the
1999 Women's World Cup, yet Tiffeny Milbrett has always felt
something of an outsider _ in the middle of many important
victories, yet in a sense always apart.
</P>
<P>
   She did not play collegiately at North Carolina, which has
essentially been a farm system for the national team. She clashed
with Tony DiCicco, the former national team coach, whom she felt
was too rigid. For Milbrett, soccer is a form of jazz, something
that must be felt rather than instructed.
</P>
<P>
   April Heinrichs, the new coach of the national team, has given
Milbrett the freedom she craved, and she responded Thursday night
with one goal and nearly three others as the United States
dominated Norway, its most intractable rival, by 2-0 in the opening
women's match of the Olympic soccer tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett hit for the cycle, scoring on a brilliant counterattack
in the 18th minute and slammed three other balls off the left post,
the right post and the crossbar. Mia Hamm added the second goal in
the 24th minute. The Americans smothered Norway in midfield and
played most of the game in the opponent's end on a cold, blustery
evening.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Summer Games, but it is late winter in the
Southern Hemisphere. Having grown up in Hillsboro, Ore., and having
played at the University of Portland, Milbrett was more than
accustomed to the chill and a field made slick by a late afternoon
rain. Benefitting from o her speed and agility, the Americans are
in excellent position to advance to the semifinals, with group
matches remaining against China on Sunday and Nigeria on Wednesday.
China defeated Nigeria 3-1 Thursday night in Canberra on a pair of
goals by Sun Wen, the most valuable player in the 1999 Women's
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Norway was the only team with a winning record against the
Americans (14-13-2), and had defeated the United States three times
in six previous matches this year. Thursday night, however, the
sluggish Norwegians appeared as soggy as the turf. Milbrett
repeatedly exploited seams in the flat-back four defense, turning
and shooting with insistent, unobstructed determination.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Milbrett had seemed tense and hesitant in the
opening match of the World Cup. Thursday night, she felt free,
unrestricted, dancing in the locker room before the match. Then she
played with her own dazzling, improvisational rhythm, even if it
felt like performing in an echo chamber with only 16,043 spectators
in the 95,000 seats at the Melbourne Cricket Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you've got to quit listening to coaches,'' Milbrett
said. ``I don't mean that in a bad way. You're the one out there
playing the game. You got yourself to this level. If you forget
that, sometimes you start struggling. In the past, I was worried
about what my coaches and teammates thought. I got the point where
I said, `It's time to get back to listening to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th minute, goalkeeper Siri Mullinix played with the
assertive roaming that has come to characterize her style, racing
to the top of the penalty box and clearing a ball 60 yards
downfield to a sprinting Milbrett. This was Mullinix's first start
in a major tournament, and she sometimes appeared overly aggressive
in straying off her line, but she did collect her 14th shutout of
the year, a team record. And, on the first goal, she placed the
ball with such distance and precision that Milbrett ran onto it at
full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the ball forward, Milbrett rushed past two defenders and
punched a shot at the Norwegian goalkeeper, Bente Nordby, who could
not control the rebound, leaving Milbrett with an unencumbered
finish and a 1-0 lead. Norway left huge gaps through which Milbrett
knifed with her searing first step, change of direction and
spontaneity. At 5 feet, 2 inches, she and China's Sun move more
expertly in tight spaces than any players in the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her agility and change of direction and change of speed and
control of her body, I liken it to a point guard in basketball,''
Heinrichs said.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL MATERIAL BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Milbrett felt shackled by DiCicco's more structured
style, even though it brought the Americans an Olympic gold medal
and a world championship. DiCicco, on the other hand, felt that
Milbrett did not possess a sufficient level of fitness. Heinrichs,
a former star forward on the national team, does not yell from the
sideline and she does not insist on any unbending plan of attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``April said, `Do whatever you want, I'm not going to yell, just
get the ball on frame,''' said the defender Kate Sobrero.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL MATERIAL
</P>
<P>
   Hamm beat the offside trap for the second goal, taking a chip
pass from Kristine Lilly and driving it beneath Nordby's futile
dive for her 126th international goal, unsurpassed by any man or
woman. It has been Hamm's history to score in early matches of
major tournaments, then to have difficulty continuing to put the
ball into the net. Without the pressure of playing at home as the
Americans did in the 1996 Olympics and the 1999 World Cup, perhaps
she will be able to sustain her goal production throughout the
tournament.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If she just plays for herself and doesn't worry about what
anyone else is saying, she'll be fine,'' Milbrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it is Milbrett who appears to be on the verge of a
breakthrough tournament and a chance to gain widespread attention,
as well as a sense of true belonging on the American team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't hurt if we come home with a gold medal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
