<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5185 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BAIT-TEX     09-14 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BAIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN TALENTED JAMIE FOXX ISN'T A KEEPER IN WEAK ACTION FLICK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRISTOPHER KELLY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years working on the pop-culture periphery in his own TV
show on UPN and in the inspired (and hugely underrated) sex farce
``Booty Call,'' Jamie Foxx scored a major breakthrough last year in
Oliver Stone's football drama ``Any Given Sunday.'' The film itself
was a muddle, but Stone recognized Foxx's best quality _ his
mixture of relaxed comic playfulness and an almost venomous-seeming
sexual energy _ and framed Foxx's character accordingly. The
resulting performance was similar to watching Will Smith in ``Six
Degrees of Separation'' _ a lightweight teen heartthrob suddenly
showing a gravity that no one could have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   So it makes a lot of sense for Foxx to take the next step _ up
to a Will Smith-style action crossover superstar role. It's sad
that he chose a script that is essentially a dumbed-down remake of
Smith's ``Enemy of the State,'' a handicap only exacerbated by a
director, Antoine Fuqua, who seems to take all of his visual
inspiration from the movie ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is apparent from the first sequence, a gold heist in
New York that goes awry. The film's sniveling bad guy (Doug
Hutchison) is swindled out of his share of the take by his partner
(Robert Pastorelli). A bang-'em-up car chase between the Feds and
the sniveler ensues, but Fuqua dispenses with establishing shots
and instead serves up, in rapid fire, one cut after another of
mayhem and crunching metal. This may be fun to watch, but good luck
making a shred of sense out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Foxx's Alvin Sanders who, for reasons never quite
explained, is across town robbing a fish warehouse. He ends up at
Riker's Island, sharing a cell with the sniveler's partner _ who
managed to bury the gold in a secret location, but who was picked
up for drunken driving on his way home. It gets worse. The robber
also turns out to have a heart problem, and he dies after not
taking his pills. Flash-forward 18 months: In an effort to capture
the sniveler who got away, the Feds knock Alvin unconscious,
secretly plant a tracking device in his skull, and let him out of
prison _ with the hope that the sniveling bad guy will think Alvin
knows were the gold is and come after him.
</P>
<P>
   If this all sounds senseless, well, wait until you see where
they buried the gold! The screenplay, by Andrew and Adam Schienman
and Tony Gilroy, barely qualifies as a first draft _ it piles one
ludicrous plot twist atop another and bothers not a whit with
logic. This might not have mattered much if the action sequences
came off. But in addition to being visually incoherent, the set
pieces are jaw-droppingly stupid (the climax, featuring Foxx on a
racehorse riding in the opposite direction of a race that's being
run, is like something out of a Marx Brothers movie, only here it's
played straight). As for Foxx, he toggles between dithering
stand-up comic shtick and serious ``paranoid guy'' poses _ which
only further contributes to the make-it-up-as-we-go-along spirit of
the whole movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bait'' probably won't do much damage to Foxx's rising star _
he's an immensely compelling on-screen presence and has built up
enough good will with audiences that they'll forget this turkey
fast. But he needs to learn that a successful acting career is as
much about making good choices in projects as it is about anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Bait''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Antoine Fuqua
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jamie Foxx, David Morse
</P>
<P>
   Length: 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, strong language and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Christopher Kelly is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
