<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ELIAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-14 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ELIAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ELIAN GONZALEZ STORY': LITTLE ELIAN, HAPPY AT LAST? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has the political heft of a Disney cartoon, the dramatic
tension of ``Saturday Night Live'' and is so upbeat it should have
been called ``Everybody Loves Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Fox Family Channel movie ``The Elian Gonzalez Story''
is significant merely because it exists. The little boy had hardly
set foot on Florida's shore before the course of his life became
inseparable from the television circus around him. This
simple-minded film, the latest turn in the media extravaganza,
displays how television shapes and reshapes events.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seems the story has been around much longer, it was
only last Thanksgiving when Elian was found floating in an inner
tube, having survived a flight from Cuba in a crowded boat that
claimed his mother's life. Almost at once, television news helped
make the battle over Elian's custody an international incident.
</P>
<P>
   When his relatives in Miami refused to return him to his father
in Cuba, their campaign was fought with photo ops and sound bites
as much as with the law. Television viewers became accustomed to
seeing crowds of Cuban-Americans gathered outside the house in
Little Havana, Elian's cousin Marisleysis emotional and sometimes
hysterical on-camera appearances and a happy-looking Elian paraded
before the cameras. Elian's life became a virtual gallery of iconic
moments, culminating with the still photograph of a federal agent
in riot gear taking the boy at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   If the cable news channels puffed the story up, this movie
re-enacts those scenes as bland caricatures. Trying to change a
complex political battle into entertainment for the largest
possible audience, the film creates a fantasy in which there are
only heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, Juan Miguel (Esai Morales, in a cardboard role),
loves his son and believes in Castro's Cuba. Most of the film,
though, assumes the point of view of the Miami relatives. If they
are guilty of anything, it is loving the little boy too much, as
television-movie characters so often do. Their fictional images
here stray far from the news clips that created such divided
opinions about them.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Great-Uncle Lazaro, in reality an angry presence with a
striking pompadour of black hair, is played by Miguel Sandoval as a
warm, balding teddy bear. The fictional Marisleysis (Laura Elena
Harding) is more rational than the actual one and is given demure
brown hair, a small but telling detail. Replacing her artificial
brassy color has the instant effect of raising her social class
without saying a word. Any hard-nosed calculations from either the
Cuban-American community in Miami or American politicians _
calculations that so coldly exploited the child in reality _ have
been smoothed away.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to think any other network would have done
things much differently. As early as last spring, CBS had a deal in
place to create its own Elian movie, a project the network is still
developing with Craig Anderson, the producer of its romanticized
mini-series ``Sally Hemings.'' First as news and now as fiction,
the Elian story reveals television's knee-jerk tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   But the relatively new Fox Family Channel (one of Fox's cable
channels, not to be confused with the broadcast network, of ``The
Simpsons'' and ``X-Files'' fame) apparently wants to out-Disney
Disney, so this film goes as far as possible in stripping the Elian
tale of any hint of controversy. Fox's own press material spells
out what the film intends to do: ``Behind the headlines. Beyond the
politics. The story of a family torn apart.''
</P>
<P>
   After you recover from the sugar-shock of those cloying lines,
you can see that they unwittingly point to what is bogus about the
movie. It can't get behind the headlines if it refuses to deal with
complex motives. The idea of going beyond politics is absurd
because politics is what made the story a public rather than a
private matter in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the film's approach brings to mind the singsong way
Conan O'Brien used to call the boy ``Leetle Ay-lian,'' mocking the
sappy news reports. This movie even begins with a cliched vision of
sunny Cuba, with Che posters plastered on buildings, colorful
laundry hanging across alleys, Elian kicking a soccer ball with
friends. Juan Miguel calls Elian home. It is time for him to return
to his mother, who tells her ex-husband that she is taking their
son to Havana for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd dramatic turn, the disaster at sea is saved for later,
in a few flashbacks. We cut to the Gonzalez family in Miami
watching the Thanksgiving parade on television and being called to
get their young relative. Soon Lazaro, in a phone conversation with
his nephew Juan Miguel, blurts out, ``For his own good, I think
Elian should stay here.'' He tells his family about the decision:
``I didn't plan it. I hadn't even thought about it.'' It's hard to
complain that we don't share Lazaro's thoughts when the script has
so clearly decided not to give him any.
</P>
<P>
   The central scene comes when Lazaro tells why he is determined
to keep the boy. In one of a handful of skittish references the
script chooses not to explore, Lazaro tells his advisers that while
they may want to use Elian for political reasons, he has different
reasons. His eyes welling with tears, he says, ``I want to keep him
here 'cause I would miss him so damn much if he left. It would
break my heart if he left.'' We're meant to sympathize, but such
lines inadvertently depict Lazaro as a selfish airhead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Marisleysis believes Elian is a miracle child
delivered to them by God, making ``The Elian Gonzalez Story'' sound
like ``Touched by an Angel.'' No wonder the film dashes through a
tough scene it cannot ignore. Marisleysis assumes a tone of sad
necessity when she creates a home video of Elian telling his father
he wants to stay in Miami. In this brief re-creation, Elian (Alec
Roberts) is not nearly as angry as he was in that real tape, which
was so unsettling it quickly became known as ``the hostage video.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few other times when the film takes a similar
hit-and-run approach to deeper issues. Everything about the
family's relations with their Cuban-American political advisers,
the real untold story, is even murkier in the film. Armando
Guttierrez (Tony Amendola), the Gonzalez family's spokesman,
appears out of nowhere offering help with legal affairs and public
relations. He is seen in the office of a group called Democracy
Movement, in reality a Cuban-American organization behind many of
the vigils in Little Havana, though that is not explained either.
</P>
<P>
   The film is most laughable when it resorts to caricatures of
Janet Reno, Fidel Castro and Donato Dalrymple, the fisherman who
said he pulled Elian from the sea but is shown here watching from
the boat, then claiming credit for heroism. When James Quattochi
imitates Dalrymple's hoarse, hysterical voice on the morning the
federal agents take Elian, the film plunges into pure,
unintentional comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Even that most iconic moment, when the agents arrive, is
softened here with Cuban music playing in the background. The scene
quickly shifts to Elian happily reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken less than three months for the television seesaw to
transform a complex political event into this pablum, which is all
too typical of how television recycles its own excesses. As recent
news films of Elian going to his first day of school in Cuba
showed, the story is still here. All we can hope is that we are
spared a sequel, ``Little Elian Goes to Therapy.''  &QL; 
BROADCAST NOTES: &QL; 
`THE ELIAN GONZALEZ STORY'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on Fox Family Channel
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Christopher Leitch; produced by Leanne Moore; Lance
H. Robbins and Brad Krevoy, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Alec Roberts (Elian Gonzalez), Esai Morales (Juan Miguel
Gonzalez), Laura Haring (Marisleysis Gonzalez), Alan Rachins
(Spencer Eig), Miguel Sandoval (Lazaro Gonzalez), Tony Amendola
(Armando Guttierrez) and James Quattochi (Donato Dalrymple). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
