<P>
   FIDELITY-FUTURE (Undated) _ Much has changed since Fidelity, the
mutual fund giant lost its aura of invincibility a few years ago.
In 1996, the firm's top money manager led its flagship Magellan
fund to the bottom of industry rankings after a disastrous bet on
bonds, and only a handful of Fidelity's funds were beating the
Standard &AMP; Poors 500-stock index. Today, With its performance
ebbing, Fidelity has decided to compete by spending big on
technology and service. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MERIWETHER (Undated) _ Two years ago, the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York convened an extraordinary meeting of the heads of the
major Wall Street banks. After rancorous debate, the bankers agreed
to invest $3.65 billion in Long-Term Capital Management, an obscure
hedge fund, to save it from imminent collapse. Only then did the
world learn what still seems implausible today: That this tiny
bond-trading firm, virtually unknown, had panicked financial
markets around the globe. Two years after the fall of Long Term
Capital Management, John Meriwether and his friends are investing,
small-time, and the market has changed around them. By Peter
Lowenstein.
</P>
