<P>
   BIZ-WAGES (Undated) _ Despite all the talk about prosperity in
this digital age, tax return data indicates that the rising tide of
bits and bytes is lifting the yachts a lot more than the rowboats.
From 1986 through 1997, the average income of the richest 1 percent
of Americans soared 89 percent. In 1997, the average income for the
bottom 90 percent was $23,815, up a scant $364 or 1.6 percent from
1986. By David Cay Johnston.
