<HEADER>
A5200 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-LAWSUITS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LAWSUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEE TIME HAS ITS HADICAPS, EVEN IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ More than 3 million Americans played golf for the
first time last year, which has sometimes made public courses and
country clubs across the land almost as crowded as the freeway
during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   So many fledgling golfers, so many errant shots.
</P>
<P>
   So many lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't it figure, just as predictably as night follows day?
Yes, indeed there has been a marked increase in golf course-related
litigation, according to Manhattan-based attorney Robert D. Lang,
who has reviewed cases in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those who have tried to receive compensation for
injuries on the links is long and varied. It includes spectators at
tournaments, caddies struck while on the job, homeowners whose
property borders a golf course, a motorist who had the misfortune
to be driving down a highway alongside a golf course when a poorly
hit ball whacked his car, even a golfer whose errant shot whacked a
yardage marker, ricocheted and plunked him.
</P>
<P>
   There is a silver lining for the person with a bad slice,
however. Even if your fellow golfer is not very understanding, the
courts usually are.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits based on golfing accidents rarely result in judgments
against the defendant, Lang says. Golf course accidents are a
given, justices and juries have declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurors don't tend to like those types of cases, thinking
anyone who's engaged in something like golf tends to get what's
coming to them,'' Lang said. ``Some jurors view golf as an elitist
sport, and they're particularly unsympathetic to these sorts of
lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits, however frivolous, are not amusing when they involve
you. Professionals at public and private clubs are reluctant to
discuss litigation stemming from incidents at their courses.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs attorney Matthew Jones, a lawyer in Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., said that golf course lawsuits are on the rise
despite the fact that the courts are reluctant to penalize the
golfer. Jones, who played on the University of Vermont golf team 30
years ago, finds some of the litigation laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read these cases, they almost always talk in terms of
negligence, saying that the shot did not go exactly where the
golfer intended it to go. Well, no kidding!'' Jones said. ``This is
golf, where to slice is human, and to hit long and straight
divine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang believes there is a simple reason why so many men, women
and children are now being drawn to golf for the first time: Tiger
Woods. Golf has never been more popular, thanks largely to Woods,
the pro superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings are at an all-time high whenever Woods is in
the hunt for another championship, prompting more and more people
to give the game a try. And putting more folks potentially in the
way of errant shots on the links.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most golfers have been witness to at least one incident where
someone has been hit by a golf ball,'' Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the equation, notes Lang, a personal injury and
casualty specialist at the firm D'Amato &AMP; Lynch, is that we are
living in an increasingly litigious society. ``If someone has an
injury,'' he noted, ``the first thing they want is to have someone
else pay for their medical bills and injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang is a self-described mediocre golfer who says he's never
been sued for a golf shot gone awry, but has represented several
clients who have sought compensation for injuries that occurred on
the links. (He advises friends to be sure to have an umbrella
policy to guard against all sorts of unforeseen mishaps, including
those that are golf course-related.)
</P>
<P>
   The attorney reviewed more than a dozen lawsuits in an article
he wrote for the July/August issue of the New York State Bar
Journal. In his research for the story, titled ``Lawsuits on the
Links: Golfers Must Exercise Ordinary Care to Avoid Slices, Shanks
and Hooks,'' Lang found that in every suit he studied the case was
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Jenks vs. McGranaghan, the defendant drove a golf
ball without warning from the eighth tee and hit a player at the
ninth tee, which was adjacent to the eighth fairway. The ball
struck the player in the eye, causing blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the defendant's group had shouted ``fore,'' but the
plaintiff did not hear.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the defendant was preparing to drive, the plaintiff
was behind the protective fence where he had left his golf bag,
walking out just at the time the defendant drove the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Court of Appeals wrote that a ``golfer cannot be
expected to break his concentration while addressing the ball the
instant before he hits to look up and see if someone has just
stepped into the danger zone,'' and concluded that there was
therefore no duty to yell ``fore'' before hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Lang advises that the basic rule imposes no duty on the golfer
to warn people who are not in the intended line of the ball's
flight, and that spectators, in general, assume the risk that even
the best golfers cannot avoid an occasional hook or slice.
</P>
<P>
   When a suit is filed, he concluded, the crux of the inquiry is
likely to be whether ``the harm to the defendant was reasonably
foreseeable, with the onus on the player taking the shot to take
reasonable precaution to protect those in the intended line of
flight of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Said lawyer and golfer Jones: ``What it comes down to, I think
the courts are saying, is common sense prevails on the golf course.
I think that's the theme. If you hit a ball toward some people, you
should yell and let them know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
