<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACE IS FORSAKING SOHO FOR CHELSEA AND GETTING LOTS OF COMPANY;
TEXAS MUSEUM ANNOUNCES THE ACQUISITION OF A RENAISSANCE
MASTERPIECE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, Britain, Italy, France)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Jan. 10, PaceWildenstein plans to close its
10-year-old gallery at 142 Greene St. in SoHo and migrate to
Chelsea, opening in mid-March at 534 W. 25th St. While Pace will
keep its sleek 57th Street space, its new downtown location will be
something of an artwork. Arne Glimcher, chairman of
PaceWildenstein, has commissioned the California artist Robert
Irwin to design the space.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, whom Pace has represented since 1966, is the design
consultant to the Dia Center for the Arts' new branch in Beacon,
N.Y. ``We've been watching Bob's drawings of Beacon, and thought
he'd be perfect to design our new gallery,'' Glimcher said.
``Nobody understands light the way Irwin does.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he stressed that he is first and foremost an artist,
Irwin has put on a design hat before, helping with the design of
places like the Museum of Contemporary Art in San Diego. ``I looked
at other galleries in Chelsea, those swept-out spaces each with
elaborate architectural statements,'' he said. ``I'm a fan of
modernism, but here it seemed out of character.'' He plans to
conceive a design that he feels is more appropriate to the
neighborhood, with its warehouse buildings and garages dating from
the early years of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving some vestiges of the old building _ a pair of
garages _ like the wood beam ceiling,'' he said. He also plans to
put in vertical windows with brick columns between them. ``At first
it will look symmetrical,'' Irwin said, ``But they're actually
asymmetrical.''
</P>
<P>
   CHELSEA HOT SPOTS
</P>
<P>
   PaceWildenstein is just one of a number of dealers moving to
Chelsea. Some have just opened; others, like Pace, are in the
throes of renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Like PaceWildenstein, Mary Boone is keeping her uptown gallery
but plans to open in Chelsea on Nov. 4. Her new gallery, at 541 W.
24th St., is in a space that virtually backs up to PaceWildenstein.
Charles Cowles, a SoHo dealer who has temporarily taken space at 74
Grand St. after moving out of 420 West Broadway, will be her
neighbor. His new gallery, at 537 W. 24th St., is expected to open
the first week in January.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot spot is 535 W. 22nd St., where seven dealers _ six
from SoHo _ have leased space from Dia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 1917 warehouse building, which Dia bought in 1992 to
show our permanent collection, but once our new museum in Beacon
got under way we decided to rent it,'' said Michael Govan, director
of Dia. The contemporary-art center is attempting by its example to
try to ensure that the neighborhood will not be taken over by
high-style shops: the leases stipulate that all tenants must be art
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The six SoHo dealers that will occupy the building are Friedrich
Petzel, who opened on the ground floor last week; Marianne Boesky,
who opened last week on the second floor; Yancey Richardson, who
plans to open on Nov. 11 on the third floor; CRG Gallery, also
scheduled to open Nov. 11 on the third floor; Frederieke
Taylor/Tz'art Gallery, opening on Oct. 21 on the sixth floor; and
Julie Saul, also planning to open on Oct. 21 on the sixth floor.
Leslie Tonkonow Artworks Projects, which was at 601 W. 26th St.,
hopes to open on the sixth floor in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 years in the Fuller Building on 57th Street, ACA
expects to open in mid-October on the fifth floor of 529 W. 20th
St. It will be joined by Paul Rodgers9W, opening next Friday on the
ninth floor. Howard Scott opened last Thursday on the seventh
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Three old-time artist cooperatives _ Bowery Gallery, Prince
Street and Blue Mountain _ will be leaving their SoHo space on Dec.
1 after 10 years and moving to 530 W. 25th St. They hope to reopen
in March.
</P>
<P>
   KIMBELL BUYS RARITY
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, Texas, has announced its
latest purchase: a gilt bronze statue of St. John the Baptist,
recently identified as a lost masterpiece by the Florentine
sculptor and architect Michelozzo di Bartolommeo. The sculpture, 22
5/8 inches high, was commissioned by Piero de Medici around 1450
for the Church of Santa Maria dei Servi (known as the Santissima
Annunziata) in Florence around 1450.
</P>
<P>
   The only known works by Michelozzo outside Italy are two
fragmentary marble angels in the Victoria and Albert Museum in
London. ``There has not been a more important Renaissance discovery
than this in a generation,'' said Timothy Potts, director of the
Kimbell. ``It's one of the first free-standing sculptures in the
Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell bought the sculpture, which depicts St. John the
Baptist in his camel-pelt undergarment, a year ago but delayed the
announcement while the work was being cleaned by conservators at
the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Jack Soultanian, the conservator
responsible for European sculpture at the Met, calls the statue ``a
masterpiece.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heavily cast, and the detailing of the surface is
beautifully finished,'' Soultanian said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Kimbell declined to say what the museum paid
for the sculpture, but art experts put the price at just under $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture was originally above a baptismal stoup in the
entrance to the church and was thought to have been removed during
renovations in the 18th century. It was later sold, and then it
disappeared. The work surfaced, unidentified, in the collection of
Jean-Georges Rueff, a French dealer and decorator, who had owned it
for decades. In 1995 he sold it to an unidentified Swiss collector
through a dealer living in England; at that point an Italian
scholar, Giancarlo Gentilini, identified it as a Michelozzo. The
same dealer sold it to the Kimbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was contacted by a dealer living in London who knew we were
looking for great things,'' Potts said. He declined to give the
dealer's name. Experts would only say the dealer is Russian-born
and lived in Venice until he moved to England recently. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
