<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DREAM CATCHER:' RECKLESS ISN'T GLAMOROUS, JIMMY DEAN, JIMMY
DEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Clacking freight trains silhouetted against a fading
late autumn sunset, the peripheral blur of trees speeding by a
moving boxcar, the hollow glare of anonymous gas stations and bus
depots, and the desolation of shabby bars and luncheonettes on the
wrong side of the tracks: These are some of the recurrent images
that lend Ed Radtke's melancholy road film ``The Dream Catcher'' an
enveloping sadness.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opens a one-week engagement Friday at the
Walter Reade Theater as part of the Film Society of Lincoln
Center's Independent Feature Project, follows the odyssey of two
runaway teen-age boys scrounging their way across the country, each
on his own vaguely defined personal quest. Freddy (Maurice Compte),
a handsome, stony-faced brooder, is fleeing a pregnant girlfriend
in Philadelphia while searching for the father he barely remembers.
Albert (Paddy Connor), who attaches himself to Freddy early in the
trip is a voluble, smart-aleck prankster from Dayton, Ohio, headed
for Reno to reunite with a mother he hasn't seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dream Catcher'' could be described as a ``lost boy'' film
as well as a road movie, and the scenes in which the characters
poignantly press their noses to the glass of an adult
self-sufficiency that seems as unreachable as the stars, will put a
lump in your throat. What grown man doesn't remember having been
gripped as an adolescent by a sinking feeling when finding himself
in a strange situation with only pocket change and no parents
hovering nearby? ``The Dream Catcher'' conjures those moments of
choked-back anxiety and the strategies for disguising it that range
from displays of phony bravado to an impenetrable withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's greatest assets are Compte's and (especially)
Connor's performances. Compte deftly deglamorizes a sullen movie
stereotype that dates back to James Dean. Connor's Albert, by turns
charming and infuriating, is an impetuous boy-child with a wild
streak that grows more reckless as the journey continues. The two
actors beautifully evoke the establishment of a fragile fraternal
bond that is continually tested by Albert's impulsive acts of
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dream Catcher,'' like almost every other road movie, is a
schematic patchwork of episodes that wants to piece together an
offbeat mosaic of American life. Its gallery of characters includes
a Bible-thumping couple of mixed race, the kindly Indian caretaker
of a church in which the boys spend the night (Patrick Shining
Elk), a raving gun nut, and a divorced nurse (Jeanne Heaton) who
takes the boys under her wing late in their odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   But as one vignette folds into the next, the storytelling often
seems forced. Recurrent symbolic images of a white bird furiously
beating its wings inside a cage strike a pretentiously false note.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the film, Freddy visits his ailing, hospital-bound
uncle (Larry John Meyers) who informs him that his father, recently
discharged from prison, is living in Oklahoma City. Freddy doggedly
tracks him down. But when he faces his dad, a gruff, hard-boiled
ticket taker in a parking garage, Freddy's volatile reaction
doesn't quite ring true. Nor do Albert's antics with a gun he
somehow succeeds in stealing from the glove compartment of a hunter
who gives the boys a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its small glitches, ``The Dream Catcher'' sustains a
mood of aimless adolescent angst, and its vision of the road is
uncompromisingly bleak. The dreams luring these teen-age drifters
into the Wild West are leftover childhood illusions. In the end,
there's nothing out there.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DREAM CATCHER'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ed Radtke; written by Radtke and M.S. Nieson;
director of photography, Terry Stacey; edited by James Klein; music
by Georgiana Gomez; production designer, Sally Petersen; produced
by Julia Reichert, Steven Bognar and Radtke; released by Redeemable
Features.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 99 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Maurice Compte (Freddy), Paddy Connor (Albert), Jeanne
Heaton (Katherine), Joseph F. Arthur (Freddy's Father), Patrick
Shining Elk (Caretaker) and Larry John Meyers (Freddy's Uncle).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
