<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-14 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: GAMES NEED NEW BLOOD TO SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The sun is setting on fading empires.
Gerontocracies are going out of style. The Olympic movement is
starting to resemble the Soviet Union in its final days, just
before people attacked the Berlin Wall with sledgehammers. In this
case, the cracks are appearing from within.
</P>
<P>
   The newest set of Summer Games are beginning this weekend,
following an opening ceremony both touching and spectacular. But
there are a lot of extravaganzas in the world, a lot of sporting
jamborees, and there is no guarantee that people are going to buy
this retro act much longer.
</P>
<P>
   The world is getting smaller. The Sydney Morning Herald this
week ran photographs of Darryl Strawberry and the Monday night
football game.
</P>
<P>
   To love the Olympics for the next two weeks, you have to go
along with the program _ gold medals, old-fashioned amateur sport,
sound mind and sound body, fair play. The old ideals don't work
with the world snickering in the background.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sadness of Juan Antonio Samaranch that he stayed on
too long. He knows it. The look of weariness is on his face. He no
longer makes any pretense at having fun with this business. It's
over. The real question is where the International Olympic
Committee goes from here. Can it hold Games in Athens in 2004 and
in some undesignated city in 2008 with the guaranteed full
obeisance of the host city? Those days may be over.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first shuttlecock is fired in anger here, the powers
that be have already spent a week that would have embarrassed the
average elected public official.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch and his Politburo were seen agitating over missing
brethren, a boxing fixer from Uzbekistan and a basketball officer
from Hong Kong who were denied entry by the Australian government
on the grounds of questionable activities. The IOC also seemed
highly perturbed about the legal troubles of an Indonesian
colleague known for razing the rain forest and supporting an old
dictatorship back home. With friends like these ... as the saying
goes.
</P>
<P>
   It was extremely bad timing for the Olympic movement to have the
next two sets of Games already assigned to cheeky former colonies.
People in Australia generally like to hoot at pomposity, and they
have surely enjoyed watching the IOC fumble around this week.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the ongoing spectacle from Salt Lake City, where
two former big shots are set up to take the hit for the rich
burghers they served. The IOC heavies are furious that documents
from Salt Lake City organizers would be accessible in potential
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you just burn everything like our esteemed
colleagues in Nagano did?'' the IOC honchos seemed to be shrieking,
while a few Yanks tried to explain that the laws of the land allow
distribution of evidence. Peculiar place, this America.
</P>
<P>
   It's all going bad. Thursday, Samaranch held his quadrennial
news conference before the opening of the Games. As if the mood
around the IOC were not operatic enough, somebody chose to pipe in
the sounds of Pavarotti singing ``Nessun Dorma'' from Turandot
while the world press awaited the entrance of the dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said little in a few languages, demonstrating all the
blandness of latter-day Soviet Union presidents like Brezhnev,
Andropov, Chernenko.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of the ``enhanced role of women on our executive
board,'' noted the inclusion of contemporary athletes, praised
alleged advances in testing for drugs, alluded to healing gestures
between the two Koreas, between Bosnia and Herzegovina, the
inclusion of athletes from East Timor. He made it all seem so
banal.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked if Samaranch planned to go to Salt Lake City in
2002, and he answered: ``If I am invited. I am awaiting an
invitation.'' Lawyers will be on call. The future of the Olympic
movement is in the hands of the U.S. Justice Department. If the
Games survive, the United States won't be the host for a century or
three.
</P>
<P>
   While Samaranch presided over this exercise in ostensible
democracy, he was flanked by younger IOC officials undoubtedly
still hoping for their turn. Have they been tainted by the blatant
associations with hustlers from outposts like Uzbekistan and Salt
Lake City? Quite possibly.
</P>
<P>
   What the IOC may need is to go out and hire a chief executive
officer who knows how to handle money, handle the law, handle the
public, handle the press. It needs a David Stern of the National
Basketball Association, a Dick Ebersol of the National Broadcasting
Co., a David D'Alessandro of the John Hancock Co., just to mention
three skilled and personable Yanks who just might be able to save
the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   There are cracks in the Lausanne Wall. A few more snickers from
the colonies, and the walls come tumbling down.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
