u w BC-LEE-RELEASE-CLINTON-N     09-14 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-RELEASE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE IS `TROUBLED' BY HANDLING OF SCIENTIST'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday he was ``quite
troubled'' by how the government handled the prosecution of Dr. Wen
Ho Lee. The president's remarks came just hours after Attorney
General Janet Reno defended the Justice Department's conduct in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in light of a plea agreement reached Wednesday that
set free Lee, the former Los Alamos scientist originally accused of
espionage, the government could not justify the way it had treated
him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge James Parker apologized to Lee, 60,
Wednesday after accepting his guilty plea to one count of
mishandling nuclear secrets. Parker said the government should not
have held him in solitary confinement, prohibiting him from talking
to his family, save for an hour each week. Parker said the
executive branch's conduct had ``embarrassed the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters on the south lawn of the White House,
Clinton said he and his aides had taken prosecutors at their word
that Lee should not be freed and was a danger to national security.
But Clinton said he personally had doubts about the government's
stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had reservations about the claims that were being
made denying him bail,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that , in light of the plea deal, the case against
Lee was not as strong or wide ranging as prosecutors had suggested
initially. He said that given that the Justice Department was
willing to let Lee walk free as part of the plea agreement, it was
difficult to justify their earlier demands that he be kept in
solidary confinement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden they reach a plea agreement which will, if
anything, make his alleged offense look modest compared to the
claims that were made against him,'' Clinton said. ``So the whole
thing was quite troubling to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks were at odds with Reno's position that the
government had acted correctly. Reno defended the government's
conduct in the Wen Ho Lee case Wednesday, saying she had no regrets
about it personally, and that Lee deserved no apology.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was peppered with questions at her regular weekly briefing
about the case, in which the former Los Alamos scientist was freed
on Wednesday after pleading guilty to a single charge of
mishandling nuclear secrets. But Reno refused to budge Thursday
from the government's long-standing position that Lee brought his
troubles on himself (and potentially on his country) by downloading
and mishandling nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a great respect for Judge Parker,'' Reno said, ``and I
regret that he feels that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general chose her words carefully and delivered
them in an even tone, as is her custom, but there was no mistaking
her feelings. ``We went over the evidence. We looked at the law. We
made the best decision we could, based on the evidence and the law,
and I feel very comfortable about that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's case against Lee, which was never officially an
``espionage'' case as such, unraveled in recent weeks, so much so
that dozens of felony counts went by the wayside and the defendant
admitted to only a single count before being released.
</P>
<P>
   Does Lee deserve an apology, as the judge said?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lee had the opportunity from the beginning to resolve this
matter, and he chose not to,'' Reno said, ``and I think he must
look to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, she elaborated: ``With respect to issues of
whether apologies are out of the question or who, what should have
been done differently, I with all my heart and soul wish that Lee
had come forward, said, ``This is what I did with the information,
this is what I did with the tapes.'''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said she and her staff had been guided only
by concerns for national security and the necessity of finding out
just what the scientist had done with the sensitive material he
mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   And she said there was nothing to the accusation, made by some
of Lee's supporters, that Lee was mistreated because he is of
Chinese descent. ``There was no racial bias in anything we did,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     09-14 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `BLESS THE CHILD'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kim Basinger, Rufus Sewell and Jimmy Smits. Directed by
Chuck Russell. (R, 115 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A runny supernatural soap opera _ the first thriller of the
``Touched by an Angel'' era _ that tries for the elegant calm of
``The Sixth Sense'' but fails. It is too often overcome by its
flamboyantly cheesy reflexes. Basinger is the protector aunt of a
child (the gifted Holliston Coleman) whose heavenly powers make her
the target of an evil cult leader (Sewell, chewing his English
accent as if it were sunflower seeds). He means to kill her before
Easter; you may feel the need to leave long before then. ``Bless
the Child'' seems derivative of so many other movies that you're
surprised it doesn't have to credit its sources the way hip-hop
artists do when they sample songs. With Smits as an FBI agent and
Ian Holm as a priest who does a laughable steal from ``The Usual
Suspects'' (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `BRING IT ON'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirsten Dunst, Jesse Bradford and Eliza Dushku.
Directed by Peyton Reed (PG-13, 110 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Even though it does feature young women bouncing around in
skimpy outfits, this cheerleader comedy directed with giddy,
sometimes sloppy pep-rally intensity by Reed from a brisk, slangy
script by Jessica Bendinger is more than a low-minded appeal to
male lechery. Though bound by the conventions of the sports movie
and the teen-age romantic comedy, ``Bring It On'' has a fine
satirical edge, and at least glances at some serious issues of race
and sexuality. It's also a vehicle for the vibrant comic talents of
Dunst, ably supported by Bradford as her cute, nonconformist love
interest, and Dushku as his sister (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CELL'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Lopez, Vincent D'Onofrio and Vince Vaughn.
Directed by Tarsem Singh (R, 110 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A serial killer named Stargher ( D'Onofrio), who abducts women
and imprisons them in a Plexiglas cell that slowly fills with
water, has a seizure and goes into a coma. His latest victim is
trapped in his cell, and she has to be found before the automated
torture takes her life. An FBI agent (Vaughn) talks a child
psychologist (Lopez) into using an experimental technique to enter
the killer's subconscious. Singh's talents haven't quite jelled
into storytelling yet. He folds this tale over and over on itself,
working with a script that blends elements of ``The Silence of the
Lambs,'' ``Manhunter,'' ``The Matrix,'' ``Seven,'' ``Dreamscape''
and ``Spellbound'' with the stop-motion animation of the brothers
Quay (``Street of Crocodiles''), the moody photography of Matt
Mahurin, the paintings of Francis Bacon and so many other things
that there's no there there (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CREW'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Richard Dreyfuss, Burt Reynolds, Dan Hedaya and Seymour
Cassel. Directed by Michael Dinner (PG-13, 88 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This sloppy, cliche-ridden comedy about four aging mobsters
blundering their way through a series of unlikely capers has
moments of wit provided by Barry Fanaro's overplotted script and
Hedaya's priceless goofing. But the picture, with no clear idea of
what it wants to do, lurches between slapstick and sentimentality,
wasting the talents of Dreyfuss, Cassel and Lainie Kazan. Reynolds,
meanwhile, absurdly cast as a New Jersey mafioso, looks as bored
and grouchy as the audience will be after 88 minutes of this mess
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `IT ALL STARTS TODAY'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Philippe Torreton. Directed by Bertrand Tavernier (not
rated, 117 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Filmed with unassuming realism, beautiful to look at even as it
avoids any suggestion of stylishness, Tavernier's latest film is a
passionate and relentless look at how chronic unemployment _ with
the usual side effects of alcoholism, domestic abuse and pervasive
despair _ menaces the lives of children. Torreton plays the
director of a preschool in a town where the coal mines have been
shut down, and the film chronicles his daily battles with
bureaucrats, parents and his own pessimism. The film avoids both
sentimentality and cynical despair; Torreton's character refuses to
succumb to hopelessness, but he also refuses to rule it out
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `MADADAYO'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tatsuo Matsumura. Directed by Akira Kurosawa (not
rated, 134 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his long career, Kurosawa, who died in 1998,
made a number of great movies. His last film, ``Madadayo,''
released in Japan in 1993, lacks the narrative intensity of
emotional range to be considered among his masterpieces, but within
its own modest proportions it achieves a kind of perfection. The
story is not much: a retired professor in postwar Tokyo lives out
his twilight years in the glow of his former students' devotion and
declares his unreadiness to say farewell to the life he lives with
humor and gusto. But Kurosawa's absolute assurance as a filmmaker
and his unabashed affection for his characters make ``Madadayo'' a
richly, and in a way inexplicably, satisfying movie (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `NURSE BETTY'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Morgan Freeman, Renee Zellweger, Chris Rock and Greg
Kinnear. Directed by Neil LaBute (R, 112 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Alternately hilarious, poignant and gory, this modern fairy tale
that follows an aspiring nurse (Zellweger), suffering from
traumatic amnesia, to Los Angeles to win the love of her favorite
soap-opera character is a contemporary ``Wizard of Oz.'' Hollywood
is the Emerald City. Kinnear is the self-centered actor who plays
her heart's desire on television. Freeman and Rock are a sadly
introspective hit man and his hot-headed protege who follow her
across the country with intention to do harm. This may be the
deepest and funniest American comedy since David O. Russell's
``Flirting With Disaster'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `THE ORIGINAL KINGS OF COMEDY'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer and
Bernie Mac. Directed by Spike Lee (R, 117 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Filmed before a live audience on two nights in February in
Charlotte, N.C., the self-proclaimed Kings of Comedy swagger across
the stage, urban legends in resplendent outfits. Until a couple of
years ago the comedians' exposure was limited mostly to cable
television. Here their comedy gives audiences that have never seen
anything like it a hilarious window on a new world. They display
their chops when they talk about family, specifically
African-American family with roots in the South (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE REPLACEMENTS'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves and Gene Hackman. Directed by Howard
Deutch (PG-13, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This negligible jock comedy, about a group of misfit macho
clowns who suit up for pro football during a players' strike, just
wants to be loved: Is that so wrong? This rehashed and desperate
picture stars Reeves as the honorable, stoic fill-in quarterback.
(He glides through.) Hackman musters his requisite command as the
honorable, stoic fill-in coach in a wardrobe from the Tom Landry
Collection, mouthing dialogue from ``Hoosiers'' and old United
Airlines commercials. The unvaried ragtag scab players include a
pair of violent bodyguard brothers (Faison Love and Michael
Taliferro), a violent cop (Jon Favreau) and a violent felon on loan
to the league (Michael Jace). Brooke Langton is the cheerleader who
resolves not to date players and dates Reeves anyway. It's a
peculiarity from L.A., a union town: a film that celebrates
anti-union activity (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``SAVING GRACE'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brenda Blethyn and Craig Ferguson. Directed by Nigel
Cole (R, 93 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This innocuous piece of comic Anglophilia features the usual
cast of lovable British eccentrics plopped down in a picturesque
seaside spot, in this case a Cornish village. Blethyn is Grace, a
widow whose husband committed suicide, leaving her $450,000 in debt
and in danger of losing her lovely stone house. She and her
resourceful gardener (Ferguson, who also wrote the screenplay)
convert her greenhouse into a marijuana farm, and the resulting
high jinks resemble a twee hybrid of ``The Full Monty'' and the
lesser works of Cheech and Chong (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `SOLAS'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Maria Galiana and Ana Fernandez. Written and directed
by Benito Zambrano (not rated, 98 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   When a simple Spanish woman ( Galiana) makes a rare journey to
the city to be with her husband, who is having surgery, she stays
with her embittered, alcoholic daughter ( Fernandez) who works for
a cleaning service. Galiana's eloquent, utterly unsentimental
portrayal of a woman who expects little of life is an
extraordinarily moving portrait of unconditional love gradually
working its wonders (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SPACE COWBOYS'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland and
James Garner. Directed by Eastwood. (PG-13, 105 minutes)
</P>
<P>
   The second half of Eastwood's new movie is a pleasant reworking
of the standard trouble-in-space movie, with Eastwood himself
leading a heroic team of astronauts that also includes Jones,
Sutherland and Garner. But the first half, which consists of the
comic, tough-old-guy interplay among these four sublime actors, is
a boisterous, easygoing tribute to manhood and maturity. Sutherland
and Jones are in especially fine form, as are Marcia Gay Harden,
playing a NASA engineer, and James Cromwell as (once again) the
villainous bureaucrat who tries to deny the old-timers their shot
at celestial glory (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE TAO OF STEVE,' starring Donal Logue and Greer Goodman.
Directed by Jenniphr Goodman (R, 87 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Steve'' in the title refers to the spiritual embodiment of
cool as exemplified by Steve McQueen, Steve McGarrett (``Hawaii
Five-O'') and Steve Austin (``The Six Million Dollar Man''), a goal
to which the blobby and amiable Dex aspires. In this
light-as-a-marshmallow romantic comedy, Dex (Logue) has lined up
quotes from Heidegger, Thomas Aquinas and ``Don Giovanni'' to
rationalize his aimless pleasure-seeking in this rather aimless
movie. Logue's performance as a nice-guy player _ his weight
doesn't keep him from scoring with the ladies _ makes the movie
glide. Dex has a cherub's glee over what he gets away with. The
movie becomes a lot less interesting when it rolls around to the
inevitable quest for a steady relationship with a woman (Goodman)
whose feelings were trampled in Dex's compulsive fox hunting.
``Tao'' can't redeem the moves to its predictable end, but its
protagonist has a great time getting there (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WATCHER'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves, James Spader and Marisa Tomei. Directed
by Joe Charbanic (R, 93 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Reeves enunciates, Spader frets and Tomei just looks tired in
this pretentious, incoherent compilation of serial-killer cliches
and warmed-over MTV-style visual flourishes. Reeves is a sadistic,
diabolically intelligent strangler, Spader the FBI agent whose
psychic torment is the killer's real turn-on, and Tomei is the
agent's kindly therapist (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WAY OF THE GUN'
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del Toro and Juliette Lewis.
Written and directed by Christopher McQuarrie (R, 120 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This film feels like a more violent and grim version of a Coen
brothers film; it could be Quentin Tarantino's ``Raising Arizona.''
Its lead characters are small-time criminals who tend to speak in
ambitious and hilariously orotund turns of phrase. The two, um,
heroes, while visiting a sperm bank, hatch a plan to kidnap a young
woman doing surrogate mother duty for a wealthy couple. ``Gun'' is
a stylish and intelligent film noir built around the feelings
adults have about babies, climaxing with a childbirth and a lengthy
gunfight and standoff (Mitchell).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
