<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHISH0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catching Phish an epiphany phor this phan
 &HT;    By Sara Pharr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE IN VERMONT _ Eight years of my life have been spent
following the Burlington, Vt., jam-rock band Phish, at least on
some level.
</P>
<P>
   From the very first song I heard at age 16 to now, at 24, I've
been a Phish fan. I can remember my first show like it was
yesterday _ I still have the ticket stub _ and I can remember that
when ``Farmhouse'' was released a few weeks ago, it was the first
time I didn't rush out and buy it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Phish was a virtual ``introduction to music'' class. The group
led me to seek out new and exciting music, such as Colonel Bruce
Hampton and the Aquarium Rescue Unit, Bela Fleck and the Flecktones
and Miles Davis. Through reading about the band and its influences,
I became exposed to eclectic acts from Sun Ra's Arkestra to Frank
Zappa.
</P>
<P>
   Though I never got fully into the touring lifestyle (college and
a full-time job precluded that idea, which proves I was never a
neo-hippie), I did make sure to go to every Phish show in Dayton
and a few outside the area as well. My philosophy was: ``Hey, if
Phish is in Dayton or nearby, I ought to go see what they're up
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Often people ask, ``How can you follow one band around so
much?'' For every fan of the Grateful Dead, the Allman Brothers or
even Bruce Springsteen, the answer is obvious: Because you never
know what to expect. Every time Phish plays a show, there's
something different. With a vast catalog of songs, every set list
is different. Being there when the band jumps into a cover of a
song it's never played _ unannounced _ is something special indeed.
Being part of the Phish ``phamily'' is another bonus _ bonded
together by a love of the music, young adults from across the
country meet and swap stories about a band that becomes a metaphor
for life.
</P>
<P>
   All of this helps explain why Phish has become one of the top
touring acts in the world despite receiving minimal airplay (and
even that is mostly on college radio stations). However, the world
seems to be catching on: Rolling Stone, Spin, Alternative Press,
Entertainment Weekly _ Phish has recently been ``discovered'' by
every mainstream music magazine. The band has videos on MTV, M2 and
VH1. The phenomenon of Phish has been unmasked for all to see and
hear. Is it a good thing? Is it a bad thing? That's open to
speculation, but in the meantime, Phish is busy doing its thing _
putting out records, pleasing the fans and playing hundreds of
shows.
</P>
<P>
   BASIC PHISH PHACTS
</P>
<P>
   Band members: Page McConnell (keyboards), Mike Gordon (bass),
Trey Anastasio (guitar) and Jon Fishman (drums).
</P>
<P>
   _ Phirst gig: Halloween 1983, at an ROTC dance at the University
of Vermont. Booed off stage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phormed in: Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Home'' venue: Nectar's, Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phish newsletter: Doniac Schvice.
</P>
<P>
   PHISH IN PRINT
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phish Book'' by Phish and arranged and edited by Richard
Gehr (the first and only authorized book about the band).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Go Phish'' by Dave Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Phishing Manual: A Compendium to the Music of Phish'' by
Dean Budnick.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Story of the Ghost'' Guitar Tablature (official band
release).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Billy Breathes'' Guitar Tablature (official band release).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hoist'' Guitar Tablature (official band release).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mike's Corner ``(collection of anecdotes and
stream-of-consciousness from Phish bassist Mike Gordon).
</P>
<P>
   OPHISHAL DISCOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to list every release. The band has way too many
imports, live bootlegs and random side project releases. If you're
a hard-core Phish Head, you can find it by accessing one of the
myriad Phish tape-trading sites on the Internet (refer to section
of this article called ``Everyone's Must-Have Phish Internet
Sites''). So, what we have here is a list of readily available
(either through Phish's label, Elektra, or the official Phish Web
site)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Farmhouse'' (2000)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hampton Comes Alive,'' six-CD box set (1999)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Siket Disc'' (1999)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Story of the Ghost'' (1998)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Slip, Stich and Pass'' (1997)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Billy Breathes'' (1996)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Live One,'' two-CD set (1995)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hoist''(1994)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Rift'' (1993)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Picture of Nectar'' (1992)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Lawn Boy ``(1990)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Junta'' (1988)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Phish: The White Tape ``CD (1986)
</P>
<P>
   PHISH ON PHILM
</P>
<P>
   According to Boston Globe music critic Steve Morse, the new
Phish documentary, ``Bittersweet Motel,'' resembles the Bob Dylan
documentary, ``Don't Look Back.'' The film includes concert
footage, backstage interviews and ``stupid band member tricks.''
Directed by Todd Phillips, who also did a documentary on freak-out
punk rocker G.G. Allin, the movie will be released in all major
North American markets; theater runs for the film began Aug. 25
(Dayton was not among them).
</P>
<P>
   _ Phish bassist Mike Gordon also released the ``Tracking
Video,'' a behind-the-scenes look at the recording of ``Hoist.''
</P>
