<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ROUPS CALL FOR REFORM OF U.S. ARMY CORPS OF ENGINEERS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of environmental and taxpayer organizations
Thursday called on the Clinton administration and Congress to
reform the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers by imposing greater
civilian control over the agency and requiring independent reviews
of major projects.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations claimed the Corps often pursues projects which
benefit private interests, but waste taxpayer money and could harm
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army should not be at war with nature,'' David R. Conrad,
water resources specialist for the National Wildlife Federation,
said at a news conference. ``Reform is needed to bring this
out-of-control agency back in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless reforms are included in the pending Water Resources
Development Act, the groups said they would prefer to see the bill
die when Congress adjourns next month.
</P>
<P>
   The water bill includes authorization of the $7.8 billion
Everglades restoration project, but spokesmen for the groups said
they were hopeful the Everglades project could be approved
separately.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference came as the Senate Environment and Public
Works Committee held a hearing on the nomination of Maj. Gen.
Robert Flowers to be chief of engineers, the Corps' top military
post.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers told the committee he planned to continue the Corps'
mission ``of maintaining its vast inventory of existing public
improvements and pursuing new projects that develop, conserve,
preserve and protect our aquatic resources,'' but he said such
efforts could be done ``in an environmentally responsible manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Westphal, the assistant secretary of the Army who
oversees the Corps, said in an interview that the Clinton
administration is ``committed to civilian control. ... We have
never really lost that, but there have been questions about how
effective it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said Flowers' nomination, if confirmed ``gives us an
opportunity to restore confidence and to take a closer look at
shaping the mission of the Corps,'' including reviewing criticisms
that the Corps' has improperly tried to broaden its duties.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 10-point reforms the groups hope to see adopted would
be creation of an Office of Independent Review within the Corps
that would appoint expert panels to study projects costing $25
million or more, or which have become controversial.
</P>
<P>
   A bill proposed by Rep. Ron Kind, D-Wis., would require the
Corps to establish such an office.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress scheduled to adjourn next month, group leaders
agreed prospects for reform this session were slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, Congress's addiction to pork has made them blind
to the need to reform the Corps of Engineers,'' said Steve Ellis,
director of water resources for Taxpayers for Common Sense.
</P>
<P>
   The other groups in the coalition are American Rivers,
Earthjustice(cq) Legal Defense Fund, Environmental Defense, Friends
of the Earth, Mississippi River Basin Alliance, and the Sierra
Club.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   National Wildlife Federation: www.nwf.org
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers for Common Sense: www.taxpayer.net
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Corps of Engineers: www.usace.army.mil/
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
