<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     09-14 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DISPENSES SUGGESTIONS ON HOW TO GRAB POWER, MONEY, FAME AND
SEX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Power Money Fame Sex: A User's Guide''
</P>
<P>
   By Gretchen Craft Rubin
</P>
<P>
   Pocket Books, $25.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Few books have been titled better to grab the attention of a
potential buyer than Gretchen Craft Rubin's ``Power Money Fame
Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the human cravings they represent, each word taken in
isolation would be enough to incite reader interest. Together their
allure is almost irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Once she has hooked readers, Rubin reels them into a net of
interlocking themes that makes the book hard to put down. It is not
so much that Rubin dispenses any wealth of new truths. It is the
way she organizes knowledge that most adults believe they already
possess.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin commences her treatise with power, although she could have
begun with any of the other three themes. She, of course, ends it
with sex. The organizational structure is designed to hold the
reader until the end, although the reader could skip ahead to the
section in which he or she is most interested and read the others
randomly.
</P>
<P>
   She defines power quite simply as the capacity to express one's
will and have others execute it. But she emphasizes that before one
can exert power over others, one must seize control of one's own
situation, take on the responsibilities of decision-making within
one's own orbit and make one's time one's own.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential, Rubin writes, to decide whether one wants to
exercise power either directly or indirectly. In her case, as a law
school professor and author of a book that she hopes will be
influential, Rubin is taking the indirect approach to the exercise
of power by seeking to influence the thinking of future lawyers and
judges and by enhancing public understanding of the uses and abuses
of power, money, fame and sex.
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer engaged in trying to win cases for clients and
causes, a businessman seeking to sell a product and compete
successfully against other companies or a politician winning an
office and passing legislation is pursuing power directly.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin identifies eight pillars of power. They include maximizing
the power of one's institutional position, using other people to
gain power, controlling information, exploiting the attraction of
special abilities, exploiting the attraction of nearness to power,
using one's money to gain power, making the most of one's fame and
making the most of one's sexual assets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the subsets of those pillars are networking, sycophantism,
footwashing adoration, proximity to the powerful, exclusivity,
surrogacy and charisma. Rubin makes a clear distinction between
charisma and charm. You either have the former or you don't. It
can't be developed. But with hard work, you can acquire a useful
degree of charm. But you must not convey the impression that you
are making an extraordinary effort to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has a word for such seemingly effortless performance. She
calls it ``sprezzatura.'' It is a continuing motif of the book.
Whether demonstrating power, flaunting wealth, enjoying fame or
exhibiting sexual attraction, you must convey an air of
nonchalance, of accepting the extraordinary as ordinary, of never
letting them see you sweat.
</P>
<P>
   As with power, Rubin poses different reasons for wanting money.
People want it, she says, to signal others about their social
status, for self-gratification, to satisfy a lust for material
objects, for sheer miserly love of accumulating it and to purchase
power.
</P>
<P>
   Her chapters on money constitute a guide on what to buy, where
to go, how to act and with whom to associate to make one's money
grow, how to win status and influence and how to acquire the best
things that money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are what you buy,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things many successful men buy, Rubin points out, is
a trophy wife. Although trophy wives are often thought of as sex
trophies, their principal function is really to supervise the
couple's status signaling. She controls the decisions about the
house, entertaining, civic activities, vacations and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first wife was no help _ she was preoccupied with the
children with vivid memories of humbler days; she was unskilled in
the new parties, the right shops, the stylish activities that her
husband's position now, he believes, merits,'' Rubin writes.
</P>
<P>
   She cites this as a true rule: ``A first wife marries for better
or for worse. A trophy wife marries for better.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's sections on fame focus on how to get it and how to use
it once you have it. But first, as with power and money, she makes
distinctions between the kinds of fame different people want. She
divides fame seekers into those who want to be a big fish in a
small pond, a household name, a star or an icon.
</P>
<P>
   She presents six ways to get fame. Rubin advises the fame seeker
to practice fame frottage, i.e., rub up against someone who is
famous; attain a prominent position; accomplish a notable
achievement in one's field; achieve ubiniquity, i.e., do something
scandalous; buy it; or cultivate a reputation for colorfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Once having achieved fame, Rubin writes, you can use it to
acquire greater fame, to boost your power, to make money or for
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the consequences of fame is the adoring fans _ the
admirer who hands the screen idol a propositioning note or the
groupie who shows up outside the rock star's hotel room late at
night,'' she writes. ``Fame oils the way for sexual adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the use of fame to obtain sexual favors is touched upon
in Rubin's sections on sex, her emphasis is upon the more
sophisticated uses of sex to acquire money, power and fame, as well
as the use of sex to signal that one is wealthy, powerful or
famous.
</P>
<P>
   She points out, for example, that Henry Kissinger attained the
reputation of being something of a playboy because he was
frequently seen at social gatherings in the company of beautiful
and sometimes famous women. But it was mostly show. Kissinger
seldom if ever attempted to engage in actual sex with any of those
women.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of his macho display was to send signals about his
power. In his own words: ``I think that my playboy reputation has
been and still is useful because it served and still serves to
reassure people. To show them that I am not a museum piece.''
</P>
<P>
   The late John F. Kennedy used his celebrity quite differently in
that regard. Rubin writes that JFK once said that if he didn't
sleep with a different woman every day he'd have a migraine
headache.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, of course, dwells at some length on President Clinton,
but not in a self-righteous, condemning way. She uses Clinton to
illustrate how using power and celebrity to get sex can prove
disastrous. She also points out that many other politicians have
been caught with their pants down in that regard and have paid a
high price for their indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in particular are susceptible to such mistakes, she
said, noting that it was Kissinger who first said, ``Power is the
ultimate aphrodisiac.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sex section concludes with analyses of how women use sex to
gain power, fame or money, including outright prostitution,
trapping rich or famous men in child support situations, marrying
wealthy and powerful men or being kept mistresses of such men. She
dwells at some length on the phenomenon of the Washington mistress
as a prime example of using sex to gain money and power.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's book is aptly subtitled ``A User's Guide,'' because it
is about people using other people to satisfy their cravings for
power, money, fame and sex. The book can be used, she says, both to
help one pursue, exhibit or exploit those assets, as well to defend
oneself against being caught unaware by such users.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
