<P>
   HURRICANE FLOYD ANNIVERSAY
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-ANNIVERSARY _ A look back a year after North Carolina's
most expensive natural disaster, Hurricane Floyd. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-RESCUE _ Floyd tested emergency responders' ability to
handle a disaster of such proportions. They had to rely on
assistance from the state, the military and grassroots volunteer
efforts helped them rescue victims, provide relief and maintain
order. The logistics involved in coordinating such disparate
agencies led to separated families and a confused and angered
public who were unable to reach supplies and/or banned from
returning to their homes. How will emergency managers handle things
differently next time. (Greenville Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-SHELTERS _ Sheltering thousands of flood victims for weeks
on end tested officials with the Department of Social Services and
the Red Cross. Until Floyd, the system had never sheltered more
than a few hundred people for just a day or two. Things were
particularly bad in first week. Food and other supplies were short
north of the river and conditions were cramped all over. Grassroots
efforts based in Grifton and Bethel sustained victims and helped
bail out authorities. What did they learn from the experience and
how will they handle it differently next time? (Greenville Daily
Reflector).
</P>
