<P>
   PEST-INDUSTRY _ Complaints about termite inspections resound
nationwide. Accusations about various firms regularly failing to
perform adequate inspections -- even forging customer signatures on
reinspection tickets -- have cropped up in Florida, Alabama and
other states. As such charges of misbehavior persist the
pest-control industry battles a chronic credibility problem. Other
improprieties, regulators and consumers say, include applying
insufficient amounts of chemicals in termite treatments and
misleading customers on warranties. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 43. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PEST-WEAPON _ The hot new weapon in the battle against America's
termites looks low-tech, resembling a footlong plastic screw.
Inside its hollow cylinder is placed a bait -- pieces of pine or
other wood. A dozen or more of these bait stations are planted in
the ground around a house. If termites start to nibble on the pine,
a chemical is put in the cavity, and the termites carry this poison
back to the colony. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 28.
</P>
<P>
   PEST-TIPS _ Consumer tips on pest control. (Miller, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
