<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5261 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BUDGET-ENDGAME-NNS &LR;      09-14 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ENDGAME-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE BUDGET DEAL PROMPTS POLITICAL, SPENDING WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, Sept. 13, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 By BILL CAHIR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans have one last battle to
fight this fall: determining how much money to spend on education
and other social programs.
</P>
<P>
   If they are not confident of a substantive or political victory,
it is because GOP leaders must wage the battle with President
Clinton, a creature of compromise who nonetheless demands every
last dollar he can get for his own priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats generally are delighted that the GOP Congress has
passed only two of 13 appropriations bills for the budget year that
begins Oct. 1, providing the president with added veto leverage
now.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, caution their rivals to refrain from
popping any champagne corks. Bringing Clinton back into the
political limelight through spending negotiations, they argue,
isn't necessarily good news for Vice President Gore, who has soared
while separating himself from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   If there is political danger for both sides, however, there is
also the likelihood that any final deal will significantly drive up
federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Republicans have agreed, through endgame
budget deals and emergency legislation, to increase discretionary
spending to $619.2 billion this year, far beyond the $564 billion
cap envisioned by the 1997 Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Only the budget surplus, a swelling financial windfall that no
one fully understands, keeps the federal ledger in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to the American people,'' said U.S. Rep. Pat
Toomey, R-Pa. ``The president is going to say, `OK guys, you want
to go home? It's going to cost you $30 billion.' And I'm afraid
he's going to get most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is virtually assured that Congress will vote to increase
spending dramatically to get out of town and avert political
disaster, such as a government shutdown or a stalemate that lasts
until mid-October. Incumbents for a third year straight have
entered a realm where they get to leave Washington only if they
provide more money for everyone's programs, making sure everyone is
satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   There is no brake on the process, save time.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has met with House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to begin initial talks.
Before the meeting on Tuesday, Clinton held a news conference to
talk about his goals and, possibly, to remind the GOP that spending
talks have been his strong point.
</P>
<P>
   ``American students in schools are making steady gains in almost
every category,'' the president said. ``I urge Congress to invest
more in the priorities that work well for our students: in smaller
classes, good teachers, modern schools, more after-school programs
and pre-school programs, and accountability for results.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton this year asked Congress to provide $1.3 billion for
emergency repairs in schools. Republicans generally claim that
building and repairing schools is a state and local responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., said if the GOP is forced to
give up the money, he would propose directing it to asbestos
removal and disability-access projects, two obligations imposed on
schools by the federal government. ``We do have some responsibility
in those areas, so that's what we would try to push in school
construction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the House Education and the Work Force Committee,
Goodling also expects to negotiate some provisions related to any
increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   And he plans to fight for language that would bar the U.S. Labor
Department from regulating the treatment of ergonomic, or
repetitive stress, injuries people suffer at work. The GOP usually
includes such language in its labor spending bill, and the Clinton
administration always tries to strike it.
</P>
<P>
   The $106.2 billion labor, health and education spending bill
written by congressional Republicans illustrates how the
last-minute process creates incentives to spend more money than any
lawmaker would care to admit.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to throw up his hands and accept the GOP bill as
written, it would increase discretionary spending by $8.93 billion,
or 9.2 percent. The president, however, would veto that bill, says
Joel Packer, lobbyist for the National Education Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get way more than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While generous, the GOP bill fails to provide $2 billion in
school funding that Clinton requested. It includes funds for
class-size reduction or urgent school repairs, but would let school
districts decide how to use the money.
</P>
<P>
   If the budget process poses a political opportunity for
Democrats, it also poses a risk, according to some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does reintroduce Bill Clinton front and center back into
the political equation,'' said U.S. Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., chairman
of the National Republican Congressional Committee. ``If you're Al
Gore, you've got to wonder how many kisses it takes to make up for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added that the end-of-session budget fracas poses a
``tough'' dilemma for the congressional wing of the GOP. If
Republicans too willingly submit to the president's spending
demands, he said, they will be seen by their own base as abandoning
their fiscal principles.
</P>
<P>
   The moment seems to favor Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   By writing a compromise bill to fund the federal labor, health
and education agencies, the Labor-HHS spending bill, Republicans
have painted themselves into a corner. Clinton can accept the
spending hikes Republicans have proposed for their own priorities,
such as special education. And then he can demand more money for
his own ideas, such as repairing run-down school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The blueprint suggests the final bill will boost domestic
spending more than anyone dreamed at the outset. It is a fiscal
conservative's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a new approach. Adding money is the way
congressional appropriators have worked in recent years. The U.S.
Education Department's budget has gone up 55 percent since fiscal
1996. And that's when Republicans took over the congressional purse
strings.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Toomey lamented the likelihood that lawmakers would include more
pork-barrel projects in a final budget deal, larding up any
catchall compromise with pet projects that one lawmaker couldn't
possibly identify or kill before a vote. He said he wished the
Republican Senate had passed more spending bills,like the House,
and forced Clinton to deal with them one by one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to veto them, let him veto them. Then we can
negotiate where we need to end up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Rep. Robert Andrews, D-N.J., seemed to relish the
moment. Andrews held out the possibility that Democrats would
strike a deal to include managed care reforms, such as the right to
sue an employer-provided health plan, in the last-minute
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., wants to see if Clinton really
would veto the GOP's generous proposal for labor, health and
education programs, even if the measure doesn't comply with all of
the president's policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference would be to send the Labor-HHS bill to the
president,'' said Specter, chairman of a key appropriations
subcommittee. ``I believe we have a good bill there. He sent over a
request for $106 billion, and after a lot of effort, we've gotten
the Republican caucus to go along with that. ... We have the high
ground. If we could undertake a public debate with him on this
subject, I think we'd get a lot of public support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
