<P>
   GARZA-COMMUTE (Washington) _ President Clinton is weighing
whether to commute the death sentence of Juan Raul Garza who is
scheduled to be the first person executed under federal death
penalty laws in 37 years. Garza's attorney asked the president to
change the sentence to life without the possibility of parole. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEE (Washington) _ President Clinton says he was ``quite
troubled'' by the handling of the Wen Ho Lee case, saying that
Justice Department prosecutors could not justify the nine-month
detention of the former Los Alamos laboratory scientist. The
president's remarks came only hours after Attorney General Janet
Reno said she was ``comfortable'' with the handling of the case
despite a blistering condemnation of her department and the
administration by a federal judge. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ The Senate is expected to approve
legislation to normalize trade relations with China after turning
back efforts to attach amendments dealing with human rights and
weapons proliferation. By KAREN MASTERSON.
</P>
