<SLUG> BC-FILM-CAMERONCROWE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE CROWE SIGHS: SUCCESS NO REMEDY FOR DIRECTOR'S ANXIETY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies FILM-ROCK JOURNALISM)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1973, when ``Almost Famous'' writer-director Cameron Crowe
was 16 years old, he got his first assignment from Rolling Stone
magazine: Go out on the road with the Allman Brothers. Discover the
soul of the popular Southern band. Dig into how twin tragedies _
the traffic-accident deaths of guitarist Duane Allman and bassist
Berry Oakley _ in the preceding years had affected the surviving
members.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like an enviable assignment for a teen-age rock fan:
Spend two weeks tagging along with a million-selling band. And all
was fine, until Gregg Allman woke Crowe with a late-night phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a vision,'' Allman said, ``and I think you might be a
cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Allman demanded that the young journalist turn over all his
tapes, and that he produce ID immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still hard to talk about, in a way,'' Crowe says during a
phone interview. ``I was scared to death. And I left my tapes with
him, and within a week, they had been sent back to me, and Phil
Walden, who was the head of Capricorn (Records), called me and
said, `Oh, Gregg, he woke up the next day and didn't even remember
why he had those tapes, and you just know that the Brothers really
loved you, and write yourself a great story, nobody got the kind of
access you got.'''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe never told the editors at Rolling Stone, but the incident
dented his confidence. Until then, the stakes had been low, because
he considered rock writing a hobby that wouldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the truth is, I thought that was the end,'' Crowe said.
``I thought, `This is life saying, ``You have no idea what you're
doing. You're in an adult forum here, and you do not belong.''' And
I got through it, and that was the first big test. So it was not
the easiest thing in the world, and it became harder after that.
But the beginning was all about, `Hell, this is fun!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe, best-known for writing and directing ``Jerry Maguire,''
recaptures those days in ``Almost Famous,'' his
semi-autobiographical movie. The movie sees Crowe's salad days
through the eyes of alter-ego William Miller (Patrick Fugit), a
15-year-old rock journalist who befriends groupies and becomes
enmeshed in an unrequited-love triangle as he travels with
Stillwater, a fictional composite of several bands, most notably
the Allmans and Led Zeppelin. Miller spends much of the movie
trying to snare an interview with Russell Hammond (Billy Crudup),
the group's elusive lead guitarist _ who, yes, accuses Miller at
one point of being a cop.
</P>
<P>
   Although some facts and names have been changed, Crowe's movie
is easily his most personal; like the reporter he was, he's used to
observing, whether it be the student antics of ``Fast Times at
Ridgemont High,'' the teen romance and parental conflicts of ``Say
Anything ... '', or the grunge-era Seattle scene of ``Singles.''
Here, he observes as well _ but puts himself and his family in the
middle of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's many plot threads involves Miller's mother
(Frances McDormand), a college professor who mistrusts rock 'n'
roll _ she condemns Simon &AMP; Garfunkel's mellow and comparatively
innocuous ``Bookends'' as ``drug music'' _ and wants her son to
become a lawyer. But she indulges his passion enough that she
drives him to a Black Sabbath concert, and drops him off _ yelling,
``Don't do drugs!'' to her embarrassed son as bemused bystanders
look on. It almost looks like a caricature, but Crowe says it's
pretty close to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was there for a little bit of the time we were filming
it, which was truly weird and strange and somewhat difficult,''
Crowe says. ``But we're very close, and when my dad passed away, we
got closer to kind of make up for the hole that was left. She's
like one of my best editors. I'll send her a script and she'll say,
`You know what? You've gotta dig deeper.' Or, `This is funny, don't
touch it.' Or something like that. She's very much like Frances'
character in the movie. She's a teacher; she always has to teach.
Even when she's taking your head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Crowe's passion for the music remained, he didn't keep
the journalism gig. In the late '70s, when he was in his early 20s,
he went undercover at a Los Angeles high school to find out what
teen culture was about. That resulted in the magazine article
``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' which became a book, and then an
Amy Heckerling-directed movie that's often credited with starting
the '80s teen-movie craze.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Crowe made his directorial debut with 1989's
``Say Anything ... '', though, that he became what he calls a
``film geek'' _ a guy who's now so into it that last year he
published a book called ``Conversations With Billy Wilder,'' a
series of interviews with the multi-Oscar-winning director. But in
a climate where directors often churn out a movie a year, Crowe is
hardly prolific _ ``Almost Famous'' is his fourth directing effort
in 11 years behind the camera. For him, every movie is an anxiety
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``You start the long journey and you forget all the tough
stuff and soon you slam into the wall of realizing that bringing
this stuff to life is the greatest joy and the greatest anxiety
attack ever, because you're bringing so many people along on your
anxiety attack,'' he says. ``Particularly on this movie, it was
weird, because every time I'd go to six or seven takes I could feel
people behind my back going, `Isn't therapy a little cheaper? And a
lot less public?' And I'm happy I did it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
