<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-IDIOTS15-COX     09-14 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IDIOTS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing with exhibitionism
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danish director Lars von Trier (``Breaking the Waves'')
continues his role as provocateur with a movie about provocateurs,
``The Idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not about comedians. The mob of performers in question
are a houseful of dropouts (including a doctor and an advertising
grunt) who ride around in a short bus and try to upset the nearby
townsfolk with elaborate displays of ``spazzing.'' Pretending to be
mentally retarded, they wander like children through the public,
and cry, and drool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You poke fun,'' says Karen (Bodil Jorgensen), a fragile
mid-30s waif who gets swept up by the group during one of their
public outings. ``They're the ones who make fun,'' counters Stoffer
(Jens Albinus), the charismatic but possibly unstable leader of the
group. His main goal is to upset what he sees as the hypocritical
values of society.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least, that seems to be his goal. Stoffer never really
gives a plausible reason for this group's rude merrymaking. Neither
does the movie. It proposes that this brand of acting out
represents freedom, an escape from the shackles of polite society.
Whatever. The idea doesn't really hold water, and von Trier doesn't
spend too much time trying to state a thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the movie is primarily a series of comic scenes that
show the characters getting under the middle-class skins of
selected victims. They include a woman interested in buying the
house (it belongs to Stoffer's uncle) and a concerned member of
city hall. Driven by the actors' performances, ``The Idiots''
increasingly feels less like a movie than an extensive actors'
experiment, a work of exhibitionism egged on by the director. (This
movie, ``Breaking the Waves'' and next month's ``Dancer in the
Dark'' all show von Trier wringing extreme emotional performances
out of very thin material.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots'' adheres to the director's no-frills Dogma 95
aesthetic. The film is shot with hand-held cameras (queasy viewers,
beware). In fact, crew members and boom mikes accidentally appear
onscreen from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   You'll mind these intrusions less than the ridiculous black
rectangles that are used to cover up glimpses of male nudity.
Apparently that was the compromise USA Films made to get the movie
an R rating instead of the dreaded NC-17. It's a bad choice, even
worse than the digital cover-ups in ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' The
director and his actors obviously understood the ways that nudity,
even more than inappropriate behavior, can be one of the most
provocative weapons. The blotted-out images of this censored
version are instead unintentionally comical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idiots''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jens Albinus and Bodil Jorgensen. Rated R for strong
sexuality and nudity and profanity. In Dutch with English
subtitles. 1 hour, 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: More provocation from the bad boy of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
