<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-SOLOMON15-COX     09-14 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SOLOMON15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wistful Welsh romance gone awry
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After hiding the fact that he's Jewish from his Christian
girlfriend for weeks, Solomon (Ioan Gruffudd) finally explains to
her, ``I just couldn't see how to put the pieces together.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the star-crossed melodrama ``Solomon &AMP; Gaenor''
puts its pieces together too predictably. Set in a gloomy Welsh
village in 1911, it tells of the forbidden love between Solomon,
son of Jewish merchants, and Gaenor (Nia Roberts), daughter of a
churchgoing family of miners.
</P>
<P>
   They meet one afternoon when Solomon is traveling door to door,
selling cloth samples. Instantly smitten, Solomon is soon paying
formal visits to her family, including her father, Idris (William
Thomas), and gruff, menacing brother Crad (Mark Lewis Jones).
There's just one catch. He tells them his name is Sam. And en route
to Gaenor's home, he stashes his tallit (prayer shawl) in the
chinks of a stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, soon after Solomon and Gaenor have started
sneaking off to make love in a (distractingly overlit) stable,
trouble breaks around them. Gaenor's family are anti-Semitic, but
Solomon's kin are no better: They let him know he will be
dispossessed if he takes up with a shiksa.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Paul Morrison gives his film a poetic kind of
gravity. But he never throws any narrative curveballs that might
have made the story more than a misty, damp echo of ``Romeo and
Juliet.'' Gruffudd and Roberts are attractive performers, but they
never make their characters seem like much more than plot devices.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of plot devices, Solomon's masquerade as a Christian
seems unlikely, given the way that the townsfolk are depicted as
such a xenophobic, tight-knit community. In the suspicious world
Morrison shows us, it doesn't seem that any secret is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solomon &AMP; Gaenor''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ioan Gruffudd and Nia Roberts. Rated R for sexuality
and a scene of violence. In English, Welsh and Yiddish, with
subtitles. 1 hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A star-crossed love affair that seems too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
