<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, Sept. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIETNAM (Washington) _ The White House said Thursday
that President Clinton would visit Vietnam shortly after the
November elections, becoming the first president to step on
Vietnamese soil since the end of the war that took 58,000 American
lives, and completing a rapprochement with the communist government
that has unfolded over most of Clinton's time in office. By David
E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-RELEASE-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton said
Thursday that he was ``quite troubled'' by the government's conduct
in the Wen Ho Lee case one day after a U.S. district court judge in
New Mexico harshly criticized federal authorities for tactics he
said were unfair and abusive. The government's abandonment of the
case that it had once compared to nuclear espionage shattered an
uneasy calm that had settled over the Justice Department and the
FBI in the waning months of the Clinton presidency. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEMS-ISSUES (Washington) _ Faced with a Democratic edge on
high-profile domestic issues, Gov. George W. Bush is not trying to
change the subject. Instead, he has confronted this vulnerability
head on, mounting a drive to change public perception by drawing
daily contrasts between his policies and those of Vice President Al
Gore. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FUNDRAISER (New York) _ Vice President Al Gore and his
running mate, Joseph Lieberman, headlined a star-spangled musical
benefit for their party Thursday night, highlighting a spree of
aggressive fund raising that Republicans said had undermined this
week's Democratic crusade against the entertainment industry's
marketing practices. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-DEBATE (New York) _ In the debate Wednesday night
between Rep. Rick A. Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton, the parrying
and thrusting over many of the issues discussed _ from cuts in
government health programs to the environment to soft money _
obscured a more complicated reality. To begin with, while Clinton
and Lazio both insist that they favor a ban on soft money, they
cannot even agree on what soft money is. By Clifford J. Levy.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ A federal appeals court case that
offers the strongest challenge in 60 years to the foundation of the
nation's gun-control laws, could well be resolved by a bitter
academic battle over whether Americans have a constitutional right
to own firearms. By William Glaberson.
</P>
