<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-AR     09-14 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE GOES ON FOR MRS. CLINTON AND LAZIO AS THEY RETURN TO
CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULTON, N.Y. _ The New York Senate candidates hit the stump
Thursday, a day after a contentious first debate, with both Rep.
Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton claiming the high road but
firing off barbs aimed at tactics and issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who embarked on a four-stop swing through western and
central New York state, defended his challenge to Clinton to sign a
document that he said was an agreement to refrain from using
unregulated campaign contributions known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   That image _ of Lazio approaching Clinton with paper in hand _
was repeated on television news programs and newspaper front pages
after the debate, and Clinton on Thursday called it a ``stunt'' and
something that reminded her of the sort of tricks her little
brothers used to play on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that probably prepared me best in dealing with
things like that was having two younger brothers,'' she said in a
campaign stop in Buffalo. She derided Lazio's debate appearance as
``a performance without a lot of substance.'' She said, ``He had a
script and he followed his script.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio kept up his aggressive posture Thursday, saying New York
needed the ``plain talk'' he had delivered in the debate. His
campaign also sent a letter Thursday to Clinton's campaign manager
saying Lazio had written to independent groups telling them he
would demand they forsake any political activity on behalf of the
candidates once Clinton signs his pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am writing in hopes that you and Clinton will reconsider our
campaign's pledge to ban soft money from this race,'' William Dal
Col, Lazio's campaign manager, wrote to Bill de Blasio, Clinton's
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made no apologies for his tactics in the debate, brushing
aside complaints from NBC, which broadcast the debate, that he
violated a rule using props.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who violated the rules was Clinton, by not
agreeing to what she said she was going to do _ a ban on soft
money,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect plain talk,'' Lazio told reporters as he
embarked on the tour. ``And you can't take the high horse and then
take the low road. If you fire at me, you're going to have to
expect to get fired back at.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been a major beneficiary of soft money, raising
almost $22 million for her campaign from both those unregulated
contributions and direct contributions. Lazio has gathered about
$19 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not established soft-money fund-raising committees on
his behalf but has benefited from spending by independent
committees. The first lady has said that she is willing to renounce
the use of soft money, providing that Lazio obtains ``signed
agreements'' from those committees promising not to advertise in
New York or from those sending ``mean mail'' solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, even children, it seemed, paid notice to his
aggressiveness. During a visit to a charter school in Rochester, a
second grade pupil asked, ``Why were you fighting against Mrs.
Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio replied, ``Last night, we were on TV and we were talking
about different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Fagan, a second-grader who said she had watched the
debate with her father, asked, ``Did you expect her to sign that
paper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really, really did,'' Lazio replied, seated on a pupil's
chair and leaning toward his questioner, ``and I still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, both campaigns declared victory Thursday. The
Clinton campaign sent out a synopsis of news reports that it said
backed up its claim of a Hillary Clinton victory.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio took the opportunity during the hour-long debate to hammer
Clinton continually, questioning her trustworthiness and repeating
one of his campaign's major themes: that Clinton is seeking to
serve as a senator from a state where she has never before lived.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, for her part, sought throughout to tie her
opponent to the policies of former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and
attacked what she described as his ``reckless'' plan to cut taxes
by at least $770 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, the Lazio campaign said he received the
endorsement of three Erie County Latino groups. In the evening,
Clinton was due to attend a Democratic fund-raising concert at
Radio City Music Hall in Manhattan with Vice President Al Gore and
his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lieberman plan to campaign together in New York City
on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
