<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-LUXURY-GOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUXURY-PRODUCTS MAKERS IN EUROPE REPORTING RISING PROFITS AND
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As booming economies around the world fuel the
consumption of luxury goods, some of Europe's largest luxury goods
retailers are reporting strongly improved sales and profits in the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The world's leading luxury goods retailer, LVMH-Moett Hennessy
Louis Vuitton of France, reported Thursday that operating profit in
the first half rose 31 percent, to 762 million euros, or $655
million, on a 40 percent increase in sales to 5.03 billion euros.
</P>
<P>
   The group attributed the strong result to particularly big
increases in sales of leather goods and perfumes, including
Christian Dior's J'Adore, which was launched earlier this year in
the United States. But it said that ``global economic growth has
certainly contributed to these developments.'' Net profit rose 21
percent in the first half to 374 million euros.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another of Europe's biggest specialty
retailers, Pinault-Printemps-Redoute of France, said first half
operating profit had risen 35 percent, to 791.1 million euros, on
an 8 percent increase in revenue, to 11.3 billion euros, borne
aloft by strong consumer buying in France and the good performance
of Gucci Group, in which Pinault owns a 42 percent share. Pinault
said net income rose 23 percent to 20.6 million euros.
</P>
<P>
   Pinault, which is controlled by the French billionaire Francois
Pinault, entered the luxury business in a big way last year, after
winning a drawn out battle with Vuitton for control of Gucci.
Vuitton, which is controlled by another French billionaire, Bernard
Arnault, a kind of archrival of Pinault, owns a 20 percent share of
Gucci, but management control rests with Pinault. Since the
acquisition, Gucci has used the purchase price pocketed from
Pinualt of roughly $3 billion to launch a campaign of high profile
acquisitions that have included the French fashion house Yves Saint
Laurent and Sergio Rossi, an Italian maker of shoes for the
well-heeled.
</P>
<P>
   Vuitton's strong results were also reflected in the return to
profitability of DFS Group, which is 61 percent controlled by
Vuitton. DFS operates duty free shops at major airports and had
suffered badly following the Asian economic crisis when usually
free-spending travelers from Japan and other East Asian countries
cut back their airport shopping. Vuitton said DFS was ``benefiting
from increasing tourism in the Asia-Pacific region.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor reaction to the news was mixed. After initial strong
gains, the share price in both companies fell back and registered
only slight gains at the end of the day. Pinault's share price rose
by a little more than 1 percent, to 207.10 euros; Vuitton 0.7
percent, to 88.65 euros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
