<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-EDEN15-COX     09-14 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-EDEN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breezy `Eden' like a breath of fresh air
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Piece of Eden'' isn't exactly heavenly. But in a multiplex
landscape dominated by R-rated flicks, this little family-friendly
movie is a bit of an oasis for viewers trying to see something
without guns, sex jokes or rapid-fire vulgarities.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by veteran John Hancock (``Bang the Drum Slowly''),
``Eden'' gets off to a shaky start as it introduces New York
celebrity publicist Bob Tredici (Marc Grapey) and his new
assistant, Happy (Rebecca Harrell), a sweet space-case who can't
answer the phone without stumbling over her own tongue.
</P>
<P>
   When Bob learns that his father, Franco (Robert Breuler), has
landed in the hospital, leaving the family's sprawling Indiana farm
in the hands of Bob's scheming cousin Greg (Jeff Puckett), he
returns home hoping to run the farm himself. But Franco distrusts
his citified, girl-chasing ways, so Bob has to pretend he's
settling down and has even gotten married.
</P>
<P>
   You guessed it: He brings Happy along, masquerading as his wife.
And while Bob starts modernizing the farm, what do you bet they
start to make googly eyes at each other (culminating in a messy
food fight involving gallons of fresh honey).
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Tristan's screenplay tries to evoke generational weight,
giving us flashbacks to the Tredicis' origins in Corsica and
throwing in a few magic-realist touches like the amiable
appearances of grandpa Tredici's mandolin-playing ghost. At its
best, ``Eden'' strives to be a Midwestern ``Moonstruck'' but
doesn't have the romantic spark (or John Patrick Shanley's zing
with dialogue).
</P>
<P>
   Still, its good-natured charm sneaks up on you. Grapey,
unfortunately, is never quite the adorable rascal he's obviously
supposed to be. Harrell (who played the little girl in Hancock's
``Prancer'' back in 1989) has an appealing girl-next-door spunk.
But the movie is pretty much stolen by Tyne Daly, as Bob's sensible
Aunt Aurelia, and Irma St. Paule, as his superstitious (and
melodramatic) grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Piece of Eden''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Marc Grapey and Rebecca Harrell. Unrated, but it's a
family-friendly movie. 1 hour, 46 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An uninspired but perfectly decent family comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      09-14 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERROGATING THE DETECTIVE; INTERVIEWING THE DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Morgan Freeman knows how to give people the fisheye.
When you say something a little unexpected or maybe even a little
silly (as people sometimes do when in the presence of, say, a
celebrity or one of the country's finest actors), he will cock his
head slightly and look at you out of the corner of his eye. Like:
Say what? And then, if you're lucky, he'll break into a broad
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman was sitting in the bar at the Four Seasons Hotel in Los
Angeles one recent afternoon, doing interviews for the two films he
has coming out this month and nudging along his dream project of
making a big-budget adaptation of Arthur C. Clarke's ``Rendezvous
With Rama,'' a project that has attracted the interest of the
director David Fincher.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman is already in theaters as the principled hit man chasing
Renee Zellweger in ``Nurse Betty.'' But he is even more eager to
talk about ``Under Suspicion,'' a small film, set for limited
release next Friday, that comes out of his own production company.
He will be paired, once again, with one of his ``Unforgiven''
co-stars, Gene Hackman.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on ``Garde a Vue,'' a 1981 police thriller by
Claude Miller that was critically and financially successful in
France, where it is regarded as a minor classic. In it, a police
detective spends a long night interrogating a very successful local
lawyer who may or may not be a murderer. It's all bluff and mind
games and steely eyes contemplating one another in the harsh glare
of an interrogation room. Freeman plays the detective, Hackman the
prosperous suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened right here, in this hotel,'' Freeman said. ``I
bumped into Gene in the lobby, and he told me he had this project
he was interested in and that he had a tape he wanted to show me. I
said sure, and he sent me the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Claude Miller film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked later and he asked me if I was interested, and I
said yes, and then he asked which part I wanted to play,'' Freeman
said. ``I told him, oh, I wanted to play the detective, and he said
that's good because he wanted to play the lawyer. Sometimes it
works out.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Freeman said, is that it was a small movie. ``And
in this town, right now, you cannot go to a big studio with a small
movie,'' he said. ``All they want to make are big movies. Summer
blockbusters. No mayhem, no money.''
</P>
<P>
   So Freeman decided to take on the project for his own fledgling
production company, Revelations Entertainment, raise the money
himself, hire a director (Stephen Hopkins), shoot it and then find
a distributor, which is just what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said he was particularly gratified when the film was
shown at the Cannes International Film Festival this year and
Miller appeared at the post-screening news conference and said he
considered it a better film than his. ``I don't think it's a better
film, personally,'' Freeman said. ``I think it's a different film.
I have a big thing about remakes. I don't think they're worth
anything unless you give them something new, unless you make them
different. Otherwise, it's just another pillaging of French cinema
by Hollywood hacks.''
</P>
<P>
   AGAINST THE ODDS
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Cohen sees himself as a success story of independent
filmmaking, someone whose story should give hope and encouragement
to other young filmmakers out there flying on a wing and a credit
card. But he's afraid that, with one thing and another, that's not
how his story is coming across.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen produced, wrote and directed a movie called ``Whipped,''
which opened over Labor Day weekend on about 1,500 screens. It
stars Amanda Peet as the object of affection, if that's the word,
of a group of not altogether admirable Manhattan men. The movie
drew some fairly harsh reviews and earned only $2.7 million in its
opening weekend, not even finishing in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say the box office wasn't disheartening, compared to
the marketing, but I am still proud,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   What people don't seem to realize, he said, since the movie all
but vanished in an eye-blink, is that it wasn't the studio film
that it might have appeared from its marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total cost to make this movie was $180,000,'' Cohen said.
``That's it. I raised the money myself from 36 private equity
investors. My whole hope was not so much to get released as to just
go to some festivals, get a little attention, maybe get myself an
agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen made the movie as ``kind of a hobby''; his full-time job
is as a producer with a major Manhattan advertising agency. ``Most
of the characters were first-time actors, high school or college
friends of mine,'' he said. ``If you gave me $1,000, you got to be
in the movie; you got to walk through the frame.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never intended to be a Hollywood film, he said:
``Originally, it was going to be a short. It only grew into a
feature as we were making it. It was always supposed to be a
character-driven piece more than a plot-driven piece. It was never
supposed to be more than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot it in 15 days in Manhattan and tried to get it into the
Sundance Film Festival in January, but it wasn't accepted. So
rather than continuing to try to interest festivals, Cohen and his
new agent decided to do some distributor screenings in Los Angeles
_ to show the movie directly to studios and independent
distributors in hopes of making a direct sale. The odds against
this are great, but they showed the movie around Hollywood, and a
week later Destination Films made an offer for the domestic rights
and Intermedia for the foreign rights.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he said, it was a Hollywood film.
</P>
<P>
   Destination mounted an aggressive marketing campaign, and the
movie went out over Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   And died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Cohen said. ``I was actually happy. I mean,
they told me the movie had made $2.7 million. This is a movie that
cost me $180,000 to make. This was just me and a bunch of my
friends running around New York with a camera. I thought, `This is
great.'''
</P>
<P>
   But in the reality of Hollywood perceptions, with bad reviews
and a disappointing box office ($2.7 million is not great for 1,500
screens, no matter how much the movie cost), he is worried that
``Whipped'' will never be seen as anything positive. It bugs him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be an inspirational story,'' Cohen said. ``The guy
who came from nowhere and decided to make a movie, and it ended up
on 1,500 screens. But it's not being seen that way. I don't know.
I'm still proud. I made something from nothing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
