<SLUG> BC-US-OLY-SWIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SWIMMERS WILL FACE STIFF CHALLENGES IN QUEST OF OLYMPIC
SUPREMACY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ There are more than 100 municipal pools in
this sprawling city where Dawn Fraser and Ian Thorpe learned how to
swim astonishingly fast. On any given day in any season, you can
find someone doing laps with a sense of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Head to Bondi Beach in the winter where members of the Iceberg
Club ignore their chattering teeth and plunge in a seaside
saltwater pool. Head to an aquatics center in late summer when
hordes of teen-agers covered in colorful grease paint race in
school carnivals that resemble fraternity initiation rites.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Saturday, though, all eyes will be on just one pool
in Sydney: The Olympic pool at Homebush Bay. If the pundits are
correct, the thousands watching in person and the millions viewing
around the world could be treated to the most compelling swim meet
in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks that way,'' said Michael Klim, one of
several Australians hoping to win gold medals over the next eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   No nation is more passionate about competitive swimming than
Australia, where the majority of people live within a short drive
of the ocean. Nearly all Australians learn to swim early and those
who excel receive considerable positive reinforcement from a
society where the best swimmers are in the spotlight every year,
not just every four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that Australia is like swimming heaven,'' said
Jenny Thompson, an American who has trained here extensively in the
last year. ``Because I think it's the country that gives the most
respect to the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australians, led by the otherworldly 17-year-old Thorpe and
the veteran Susie O'Neill, appear to have their strongest Olympic
team since 1956, when the team featuring Fraser and Murray Rose
took full advantage of the home-pool advantage to win 8 of the 12
gold medals contested in Melbourne. This time, the Australians are
clear favorites in seven events, but the program has expanded
greatly in 44 years, which means that there are now 25 events in
which they are not clear favorites.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian men should challenge the American men and the
remarkable backstroker Lenny Krayzelburg for medal supremacy, but
the Australian women are merely one element in a balanced field.
Female swimmers from Japan could win three individual gold medals
and Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands could win three all by
herself in the 50-meter and 100-meter freestyle and 100-meter
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in for one of the most exciting Olympics in
history, because it's going to be a world competition; it seems to
me about nine or 10 countries have a chance to win Olympic gold,''
said the American women's coach, Richard Quick. Only two of the
American women swimmers _ Brooke Bennett in the 800-meter freestyle
and Megan Quann in the 100-meter breaststroke _ have the year's
fastest time in their events.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, de Bruijn already has broken world records eight times
this year and displaced Thompson as the favorite in the 100-meter
freestyle and 100-meter butterfly. But her stunning times,
remarkable for both their quality and quantity, have been greeted
with skepticism by competitors in a sport where systematic doping
by East German swimmers in the 1970s and 1980s and by the Chinese
in the 1990s contributed to a climate of perpetual suspicion
regarding excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Michelle Smith further poisoned the atmosphere.
Smith, an Irish swimmer who like de Bruijn did not peak until her
mid-20s, won three gold medals in the Atlanta Olympics in 1996.
Smith has since been banned from the sport for four years for
manipulating a urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, O'Neill, the veteran Australian swimmer,
called de Bruijn's records ``pretty suss,'' slang for suspect and
then sent de Bruijn an apologetic e-mail message. De Bruijn has
denied cheating, attributing her huge improvements to several
factors: A new training regime under the respected American coach,
Paul Sterkel; increased motivation after missing the Atlanta Games,
and to the lift provided by a new body suit.
</P>
<P>
   The new generation of suits, which along with de Bruijn have
been the most pressing and polarizing poolside topic this year,
will be worn by the vast majority of competitors in Sydney. One
exception could be Aleksandr Popov, the most successful men's
Olympic swimmer of the 1990s. Popov, a Russian who trains with Klim
in Australia under coach Gennadi Touretsky, became the first man to
sweep the 50-meter and 100-meter freestyle in consecutive Olympic
Games when he defended both titles in Atlanta. After losing races
and his aura of dominance last year, he has roared back this season
to break the world record in the 50-meter freestyle and threaten
his own world record in the 100-meter. He will be the favorite in
both events in Sydney and has said that he plans to compete in his
own skin here, not a high-tech suit.
</P>
<P>
   Popov should be pushed very hard in the 50-meter by Americans
Anthony Ervin and Gary Hall Jr. And in the 100-meter, Popov will
face Klim and Pieter van den Hoogenband of the Netherlands, who won
six gold medals at last year's European championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the hardest meet of my life,'' said Popov, who at
28 plans to make it his last Olympic meet.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight is still considered an advanced age for a swimming
star, but age is no longer the same barrier it once was. Dara
Torres, 33, became the oldest woman to qualify for the American
swim team after an improbable comeback, which came after a
seven-year layoff. She will compete with de Bruijn in three
individual events.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the age spectrum is 16-year-old Megan Quann,
an American who has every intention of ending world-record holder
Penny Heyns' Olympic reign in the 100-meter breaststroke. This
should be one of many duels to remember in the Sydney Aquatic
Centre, the 17,500-seat arena that will be sold out for every
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that in our country we are way down the
ladder of popularity,'' said Tom Dolan, an American who is the
world-record holder in the 400-meter individual medley. ``So it's
fun to come here and read the papers and see that swimming is not
only on the cover of the sports section, but on the cover of the
paper. It's helped us to get motivated.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
