<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-JOURNAL-$ADV17     09-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNAL-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOREIGN JOURNAL: TODAY'S RUSSIA NO SUPERPOWER, BUT PATRIOTISM
REIGNS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 17 
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In recent months, while terrorist bombs exploded in the
heart of the capital and more than 100 sailors perished in a
nuclear submarine accident, many Russians retreated to the dim
safety of their local cinemas to watch the country's most popular
summer movie _ a slick shoot-em-up that features good-guy Russians
venturing to America to avenge a comrade's death.
</P>
<P>
   Many of my Russian friends adore the film, ``Brat 2,'' for its
thumping soundtrack. But what they especially love is the climax of
a fight scene on the streets of Chicago. The only American left
standing asks fearfully, ``Are you all gangsters?'' In reply, one
of the stars of the Russian-made film deadpans: ``No, we're
Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   While signs of Russia's deteriorating condition pile on one
another with alarming frequency _ if it's not the Kursk submarine
disaster, it's the army's shellacking in Chechnya, the country's
decrepit roads or the alarming drop in life span due to poverty and
alcoholism _ patriotism is on the rise here.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not their grandfather's patriotism. In place of the
infamous Cold War superpower boast that ``We will bury you,''
today's slogan might more aptly be: ``We haven't been buried yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the young generation of Russians born after the Cold War
views the Soviet past like a fairy tale. Their adulation in today's
Russia is reserved not for generals and cosmonauts, but for
home-grown rock stars and athletes such as Murat Safin, who
recently won the U.S. Open tennis tournament. But, they are as
proud of their country as their elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been practicing democracy longer than we have, so you
have a better standard of living. But we have things you don't. We
have 1,000 years of history and literature,'' 15-year-old Nikita
Volkov told me when I asked him in the chatter-filled hallway of
Moscow Public School No. 57 what he loved about his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is the biggest and richest country in the world,'' is a
favorite saying of my friend Andrei Kazakov, who comes from a
distinguished military family that traces its roots to the glorious
battle in 1812 when the Russian army decimated Napoleon's forces at
Moscow's doorstep and forced the French emperor's retreat. One of
Andrei's proudest possessions is his grandfather's Order of Lenin
decoration, the highest military honor bestowed on World War II
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gold, we have diamonds, we have oil. We have the most
beautiful landscape. We have the highest standards of education and
the best mathematical minds. We should be number one,'' Andrei
says.
</P>
<P>
   For Andrei, those words are not bragging or a sign of Russian
expansionist designs on the West. They are a simple statement of
fact. But do they mean that he thinks Russia is still a superpower?
The answer is an unequivocal ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   What the government thinks about Russia's role in the world,
however, is more murky.
</P>
<P>
   During the rare times the question about the country's
superpower status has been raised on a national level, ministers,
educators and commentators have run into a problem. While the
country's image has changed among Russians since the end of the
Cold War, the lexicon to describe national pride remains stuck in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Just the word ``patriotism'' in Russian is soaked in military
nuance and wrapped in a nostalgic respect for a past where millions
of their countrymen sacrificed their lives and millions more were
killed in the name of furthering Soviet goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism is a cliche for army victories. All our national
holidays except New Year's Eve commemorate a military battle,''
said Yevgeny Bunimovich, the Moscow City legislator in charge of
education and culture. ``Our views of ourselves have evolved, but
we don't have a consensus on how to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin himself exhibits a split personality on
the issue. Much of his public rhetoric suggests that Russia remains
capable using its military to play a Soviet-era global role. He's
continued to insist on Russia's seat at meetings of the G-8, where
leaders of the world's leading industrialized nations gather. Yet
Russia's economy is only as big as that of Belgium, a non-member.
</P>
<P>
   Putin even signed a decree ordering mandatory classes this year
where ``national pride'' and ``defense of the Fatherland'' are
taught _ classes that harken back to Soviet times where children
had compulsory lessons on how to assemble a Kalashnikov rifle and
march in drill formation. However, the president did not offer a
definition about what he thinks patriotism means, or how exactly
the curriculum should be altered.
</P>
<P>
   With confusion at the top, many Russians agree with Andrei's
views of what national pride should be.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Brat 2,'' the literature-quoting, gun-toting characters are
hard-drinking ladies men who never give up and never leave one of
their own behind. In other words, they're ``muzhiki,'' or real men.
</P>
<P>
   For Boris Davidovich, the vice principal at Moscow's Public
School No. 57, this code _ minus the drinking, of course _ seems a
decent one to raise his kids by. Putin's decree, he says, is
ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't teach patriotism by standing up in front of a flag
every morning and singing the national anthem. Even if you could,
in Russia it's impossible. Our national anthem doesn't have
words,'' said a laughing gray-bearded Davidovich, who has been
teaching math for close to 30 years at this high school just a
short walk from the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``To instill respect for your country, you have to have respect
for yourself. You have to understand what friendship means. That's
what I try to teach. The government doesn't understand that, but
they don't have any control over us and our ideology anymore,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For kids like Nikita, the answer to whether Russia can regain
its superpower status is easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These adults don't understand us,'' he said. ``Wait until we
get a little older. We'll start to run the show, and then you
watch. You won't know Russia anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's e-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
