<SLUG> BC-CHINA-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S WEB WORLD SHRINKS AS SOHU.COM PURCHASES RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ One of China's leading Internet companies
announced the purchase of a smaller rival Thursday, setting the
stage for what is expected to be a sweeping consolidation of
China's fledgling Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sohu.com, which went public on the Nasdaq market in July, said
it would buy ChinaRen.com for 4.4 million shares, or about 12.5
percent of Sohu.com's outstanding shares. The deal values
ChinaRen.com, an operator of information and e-commerce web sites
popular among Chinese college students, at about $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   China's Internet industry, jammed with thousands of
under-funded, money-losing Web sites, has been surviving largely on
foreign investment capital since the industry appeared almost
overnight about two years ago. But that money has become
increasingly scarce since Western investor appetite for Internet
companies ebbed suddenly earlier this year. China does not yet
allow start-up companies to sell shares to its public, and
regulatory obstacles have kept all but four major Chinese Internet
content providers from going public abroad.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many Chinese Internet companies are running near
empty. Some smaller companies have already closed their doors. The
rest have begun a mad scramble to find shelter with the few
companies that were able to accumulate cash while the investment
dollars were flowing. Sohu.com is one.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists say the consolidation, while occurring
earlier than expected in the industry's development, is healthy
because few of China's Internet companies have innovative
technology or original business plans that give them a competitive
edge in the global industry. Instead, China's Internet industry is
all about size: With so little differentiation between companies,
only a few big players are likely to attract enough traffic to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Sohu.com's purchase of China.Ren.com gives it the largest
audience of Internet users of any Chinese Internet company. By
Sohu.com's count, its sites will have 44 million page views a day
and 7.8 million registered users. Independent tallies put the
number of users closer to 4.5 million, but that is still more than
either of the company's next closest rivals, Netease.com and
Sina.com, both of which are listed on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   China has about 17 million Internet users, though that number is
climbing daily and could increase fivefold by 2003, the year that
Sohu.com expects to start turning a profit.
</P>
<P>
   With Sohu.com now clearly in the lead, rivals Netease.com and
Sina.com are expected to announce similar acquisitions soon.
Neither company could be reached for comment, but both are believed
to have looked at ChinaRen.com, which received bids from other
prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely prompt these other companies to rethink
their acquisition strategies,'' said Sohu.com's chief executive,
Charles Wang, speaking by telephone from Beijing. ``Things will
happen at an accelerated speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang met ChinaRen.com's founder, Joseph Chen, when they were
both students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He said
he first approached Chen about a merger earlier this year, but the
two couldn't agree on the valuations of their respective companies.
When they spoke again after Sohu.com's public offering, the company
was sitting on $80 million in cash and ChinaRen.com was reportedly
running short of funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides got more realistic,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still possible for us to go it on our own, but there
were many elements that were uncertain,'' Chen said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' web sites will continue operating after the
merger, but will share some features and link users between the
two. Wang said the company will stop promoting ChinaRen.com,
however. He said the merger would not affect the company's
timetable for profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Chen will stay on as head of Sohu.com's strategic planning and
both men said there may be more acquisitions in the future. Because
the currency of the deal is stock, Sohu.com still has plenty of
cash for shopping.
</P>
</TEXT>
