u e BC-DUET-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-14 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUET-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DUETS': HARK, HERALD ANGELS SING! OR IS IT KARAOKE DUETS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most bad movies _ and there is no shortage _ are content to
amble along the well-trodden path of mediocrity hoping, at best, to
remind their audiences of other, better pictures. About such movies
there is little to say. But every so often a movie comes along
that's bad in such original and unexpected ways that it inspires an
almost admiring fascination. You leave the theater in a state of
amazement, and say to yourself, ``Well, I've certainly never seen
anything like that before,'' a response that's not unrelated to the
thrill you feel after having seen something truly wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duets,'' Bruce Paltrow's new musical, which features his
daughter, Gwyneth, in its impressive ensemble cast, is such a
movie. It's not quite ``Ishtar'' or ``Showgirls'' _ it lacks both
the perverse integrity and the epic ambition that made those films
touchstones of bad movie sublimity _ but it will probably, as those
films have, inspire a devoted video cult. Best to see it now _ I
can't imagine you'll have much time _ and reserve yourself a
charter membership.
</P>
<P>
   How can you resist seeing Paltrow, in a pink outfit that looks
as if it was stitched together out of old ladies' bathing caps,
singing ``Bette Davis Eyes''? Or Huey Lewis doing Joe Cocker?
</P>
<P>
   The film explores an odd, out-of-the-way subculture: the world
of die-hard, competitive karaoke enthusiasts who, if John Byrum's
script is to be believed, travel across the country from bar to
bar, belting out the pop hits of yesteryear for prize money and for
the thrill, as one character puts it, of being ``a star for three
minutes.'' Karaoke is no mere drunken pastime, but rather, we're
repeatedly told, ``a way of life.'' For the purposes of this movie,
it's a way of life that unites six unhappy people, who make their
errant way to Omaha, Neb., lured by the promise of glory and a
$5,000 purse.
</P>
<P>
   Their chance pairings _ the duets of the title _ have a
carefully arranged unlikeliness. A saintly Cincinnati cabdriver
(Scott Speedman) is thrown together with a steely, manic
ex-waitress (Maria Bello) who has the voice of an angel and who
dispenses sexual favors the way other people use credit cards.
Meanwhile, a sleazy karaoke hustler (Huey Lewis) is reluctantly
reunited with his daughter, a third-generation Vegas showgirl (
Paltrow) with the speech patterns of a 12-year-old and the voice of
an angel.
</P>
<P>
   The odd couple whose adventures merit the most screen time
consists of a miserable sales executive (Paul Giamatti) on the run
from the prison of his empty middle-class life, and an ex-convict
(Andre Braugher) with the voice of . . . but you get the idea. (All
the actors, with the exception of Braugher, do their own angelic
singing. Bello, it must be said, does a mean Annie Lennox.)
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, the release of ``Duets'' was held up by a dispute
between Paltrow and Disney about how it should be edited, and the
argument seems to have been settled with a blunt ax and a staple
gun. Lacking any narrative rhythm, the film flops around like a
carp on the kitchen floor, jumping from scene to scene, from
musical number to emotional confrontation, before you can figure
out what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its chaotic sprawl yields some moments of indelible
brilliance. ``You have these hidden corners,'' the
downward-spiraling salesman cackles to his solemn jailbird friend,
and so does the film. It intermittently reveals a dimension of
loneliness and vulnerability in the lives of its characters, and
suggests that their desperate drift is the symptom of a larger
cultural disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Giamatti's character spends the early part of the movie
wandering in a fugue state through a landscape of indistinguishable
hotels and airports, and when he falls into karaoke his inchoate
sadness turns into a vivid, life-affirming rage. Giammati, who has
won admiration in a series of comic character parts, careers
through ``Duets'' like the Tasmanian devil in the Warner Brothers'
cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   At its best _ in Giamatti's performance and in some of Lewis'
early scenes _ the movie has a tang of gamy alienation that recalls
the downbeat, existential black comedies of the early '70s.
Unfortunately, the maudlin habits Paltrow acquired working on
dramatic television series like ``The White Shadow'' and ``St.
Elsewhere'' wreck the film's tough, satiric possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The tearful, conflict-resolving speeches _ in which people say
things like ``You feel sorry for me? Well I feel sorry for you.'';
``you're right, I am the loser'' and so forth _ arrive punctually,
as if timed around commercial breaks. Relationships that had seemed
risky and interesting collapse into conventional sentiment.
Braugher, it turns out, has been cast in the role of sacrificial
black man, whose job is to assist in the spiritual education of his
privileged white companion. All credit to this fine actor for
bringing a measure of wit and dignity to this hoariest of
liberal-racist Hollywood archetypes.
</P>
<P>
   After a bizarre climax _ involving a shoot-out and an a cappella
version of ``Free Bird'' _ the characters (or do I mean the cast?)
wander around looking dazed, as if blinking through the haze of a
severe collective hangover and trying to remember just what
happened the night before. As I stumbled out of the theater, I had
a similar sensation _ not an altogether unpleasant one, I must
admit. We could use more bad movies like this.
</P>
<P>
   Duets is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian). It includes brief nudity, sexual references, gunplay and
the brutal murder of two classic Motown songs.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DUETS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bruce Paltrow; written by John Byrum; director of
photography, Paul Sarossy; edited by Jerry Greenberg; music by
David Newman; production designer, Sharon Seymour; produced by
Kevin Jones, Paltrow and Byrum; released by Hollywood Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 113 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Maria Bello (Suzi Loomis), Andre Braugher (Reggie Kane),
Paul Giamatti (Todd Woods), Huey Lewis (Ricky Dean), Gwyneth
Paltrow (Liv) and Scott Speedman (Billy).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
