<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINESE-CALLIGRAPHY-2     09-14 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-CALLIGRAPHY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITING ON THE WALL, AND ON THE SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By image-obsessed Western standards, one picture is
worth, absolute minimum, a thousand paltry words. But in China,
where words are images, writing has traditionally been the highest
art form of all, and a source of profound political and emotional
power.
</P>
<P>
   To see this power art in action, check out ``The Embodied Image:
Chinese Calligraphy From the John B. Elliott Collection,'' the
grand survey of calligraphic material that opens Friday at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art here. Head straight to the middle of the
show, the long room in the Chinese painting galleries devoted to
the Ming dynasty (1368-1644). Look around, and just see what you
see.
</P>
<P>
   What you won't see are landscapes or still lifes or figure
paintings, at least not more than a few. In their place are dozens
of scrolls, vertical and horizontal, covered with handwritten
words, that collectively suggest a gathering of vivid personalities
and radiate the equivalent of cocktail party conversational buzz.
</P>
<P>
   A smallish hand scroll with a fastidious ink-and-brush script,
for example, brings to mind visions of an uptight court
functionary. A larger scroll with gangly, tumbling-about
characters, seems self-confident, and very ``on,'' maybe a little
high on something. A hanging scroll in the corner, with columns of
loops and smears, seems to be giving off agitated vibes. You can
almost hear the mutterings of righteous defiance and dashed hope in
a voice veering out of control.
</P>
<P>
   One can project meanings on practically anything of course. But
control _ as in, you need to have it to lose it _ really is the
binding ingredient in this extraordinary visual talk-a-thon. Almost
every specimen here is the product of arduous training. Each
written character is infused with the energy of generations of
writers physically shaping language to gain personal fame, to link
up with the past and above all to say what they want to say.
</P>
<P>
   What they say must remain somewhat conjectural to anyone who
doesn't read Chinese _ the Met supplies translations for only a few
of the texts _ which is why viewers are often encouraged to think
of calligraphy primarily in formal terms, as a kind of Asian
version of American postwar ``action painting,'' in which the
artist's stroke was assumed to reveal his psyche. If this analogy
gets you into the calligraphic groove, great. While you're there,
go back to the show's opening gallery for a chronological view of
how this phenomenon came to be.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ritual inscriptions going back to the Shang
dynasty (16th to 11th centuries B.C.) writing seems to have been a
tool of social dominance in the hands of an elite. After the
invention of paper the ancient seal and clerical scripts were
joined by styles known as running and cursive, which caught the
movement of the individual hand. The emphasis on touch brought
strict standards of virtuosity, and writing as art was born,
replete with an exclusionary mystique, a market, a
still-flourishing trade in forgeries and a lineage of geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   The first and most enduring of these was Wang Xizhi (A.D.
303-361), routinely referred to in textbooks as one of the most
influential Chinese artist who ever lived. The running script he
developed, poised but springy and personable, provided a template
for most of what followed. Writers defined themselves as much by
rejecting his example as by adhering to it, and his ``Preface to
the Orchid Pavilion'' was endlessly copied.
</P>
<P>
   None of his original works are known to survive. His writing
does, in the form of ink rubbings lifted from stones, and a tiny
number of paper tracings, one of which is a centerpiece of the
show. Titled ``Ritual to Pray for Good Harvest,'' it's just a scrap
of a letter mounted on a scroll, but it has the aura of a relic.
Seals of owners and admirers float over its surface. The two
columns of Wang's traced script are flanked by proprietary comments
by one long-winded emperor and the renowned Ming artist Dong
Qichang. The work itself is now part of the John B. Elliott
collection at Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   If Wang was the canonized founder of the classical writing
tradition, it reached an aesthetic peak in the Song dynasty
(960-1279). Entries from this period _ an exquisite transcription
of a Buddhist sutras, a fan inscribed with a poem by the emperor
Gaozong, masterpiece hand scrolls _ are the exhibition's high
points.
</P>
<P>
   The inventive artist Huang Tingjian is represented by two superb
scrolls. In one he kvetches about his health _ his stomach aches,
his feet hurt _ though the quavers in his ink strokes are the
result of his adamant brush technique rather than infirmity. In the
other, ``Biographies of Lian Pou and Lin Xiangru,'' he works in a
fleet, airy, improvisatory style known as ``wild cursive,''
inspired by a famous eighth-century model by the monk-artist Huaisu
that Huang actually saw early in his career, and which traveled to
the Met two years ago in ``Splendors of Imperial China.''
</P>
<P>
   The other luminary here is Mi Fu, a live-wire artist and
antiquarian referred to as Crazy Mi in his day. Examples of his
writing are rare, and the Met owns a gem in ``Poem Written in a
Boat on the Wu River,'' an autobiographical travelogue enlivened by
calligraphic special effects.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative bops along in jazzy, syncopated cursive rhythms up
to the point where Mi's boat runs aground, and he hires a gang of
laborers to haul it back to deep water. He compares the shout they
give, when they finally dislodge it, to a battle cry, and he turns
the character for battle into a space-clearing wiry snarl that
punctuates the text like a Roy Lichtenstein ``Blam!''
</P>
<P>
   Although both Huang and Mi played daringly with the sacrosanct
Wang model, orthodoxy reasserted itself during the the Yuan dynasty
(1260-1368) in the person of Zhao Mengfu, an artist who ended up
having almost as much long-term clout as Wang himself.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao arrived at a tense moment. China was under Mongol rule.
Many artists, adhering to a Confucian ethos of imperial loyalty,
retreated from public view. Zhao, who was related to the defeated
Song royal family, chose to work for his new overlords, which
infuriated many of his peers but did wonders for the continuing
history of Chinese art.
</P>
<P>
   He represented an ideal version of the art-for-art's-sake
scholar-painter, and different facets of his complex achievements
and personality flash out in the show. His transcription of a
monastic history is an official document, meant to be copied as a
stele carving. It's written in a stately version of standard script
created by Zhao and adopted by the Yuan court as its house style.
</P>
<P>
   Another scroll nearby finds him in the role of art historian
with a retelling of anecdotes from the life of Wang Xizhi that
affectionately channel that master's spirit. In a private letter to
his Buddhist spiritual adviser, Zhao writes in a tremulous hand
about his crushing grief at his wife's death. Together, these
documents do more than flesh out a brilliant career; they suggest
the public and private ends to which calligraphy can be turned.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   In the adjoining gallery that Ming party is still in full swing.
Like many fledgling dynasties, the Ming asserted political
legitimacy by supporting time-honored tradition, and it was very
calligraphy-friendly at first. But this was a hybrid, promiscuous
age, much like our own. Social and cultural categories were
blurring, art of all kinds was in circulation, from high-polish
dandified fluff to agitprop.
</P>
<P>
   Political discontent gained force with the rise of the Qing
dynasty (1644-1912), and one senses it in a hanging scroll by the
Ming loyalist Fu Shan. A doctor by profession, he refused to deal
with the Manchu government and, as a ``left-over citizen,'' he
donned the robes of a Daoist priest. His ``Poem on the Heavenly
Emperor,'' done in ink on satin, suggests a fantastic, neurotic
aria of wishful thinking, incorporating bits and pieces of archaic
script into a baroque play of graphic trills and runs.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out the Manchus adored China, everything about it,
especially its art. The proprietary imperial colophons on ``Ritual
to Pray for Good Harvest'' were written by a Qing emperor, and the
dynasty sponsored extensive archaeological digs to recover ancient
stones and bronzes. As a result archaic scripts had a major
revival, and their presence in the last scrolls that conclude the
show, a few of them produced in the early 20th century, brings the
calligraphic saga full circle.
</P>
<P>
   The story isn't over. True, the repressions of the Cultural
Revolution and the global spread of digital technology have given
calligraphy the status of a left-over art in China today. It is
still practiced in its traditional form, and young, innovative
artists are both deconstructing and, perhaps, reclaiming it, as one
saw in ``Inside Out: New Chinese Art'' at the Asia Society in
Manhattan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Calligraphy was everywhere in that show, though in offbeat
guises. For example Xu Bing, who now lives in New York, cooked up a
customized East-West script through computer programming. Another
emigre in New York, Gu Wenda, ``wrote'' a pseudo-seal script in
strands of human hair. Wu Shan Zhuan, now living in Europe, covered
a room with quotations from classical poetry, Buddhist scripture,
Maoist tracts and advertising, so that competing spiritual and
social orthodoxies canceled one another out. Finally the Beijing
Conceptualist Qiu Zhijie copied Wang's ``Orchid Pavilion Preface''
1,000 times, but on a single sheet of paper, so the hallowed text
ended up a solid mass of black ink.
</P>
<P>
   Their work has little chance of finding its way into a
mainstream survey like ``The Embodied Image,'' which was organized
by Cary Y. Liu and Robert E. Harrist for the Art Museum at
Princeton University last year and has been expanded to twice its
original size in New York by Maxwell K. Hearn, curator of Asian art
at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the very fact that such art is being made suggests that the
polarities that have propelled calligraphy all along _ conservatism
and innovation, political manipulation and personal expression _
are still in play. This amazing art form may still feel a bit
unapproachable to the Western viewer. Any attempt to get to know it
is well worth the effort, and the Met makes persuasive
introductions in this stimulating icebreaker of a show. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
