<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAIT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BAIT': FROM PRAWNS TO A PAWN, A THIEF'S BUMBLING JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the running jokes (or what passes for a joke) in the
numbingly incoherent comic action thriller ``Bait'' has to do with
the distinction between prawns and shrimp. You see, when Alvin
Sanders (Jamie Foxx), a paroled thief, and a partner are caught
red-handed stealing $2,000 worth of prawns from a Brooklyn
warehouse, everyone, including the police, insists on calling them
shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin is beside himself that people can't get the difference
straight and points out more than once that prawns are larger than
shrimp. But then, while Alvin may know his way around a fish store,
he isn't the brightest light on the planet. While he is fiercely
denying any involvement in the robbery, an interrogating officer
reaches behind his ear, and what does he find tucked there? Why, a
stray shrimp (oops, prawn), of course. At that moment the jig is
up.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between prawns and shrimp, incidentally, has no
relevance whatsoever to ``Bait'' beyond providing some tedious,
high-pitched verbal filler for its motor-mouthed star. Although
Foxx, his eyes gleaming, tries to pump up such inanities with his
characteristic bleats of mischievous hysteria, not even this
talented comic actor can levitate them.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question concerning ``Bait'' is why, oh, why Foxx,
who was so impressive in ``Any Given Sunday,'' chose to make a
movie so boring and idiotic that it barely meets minimal standards
of lowest-common-denominator entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The story finds poor Alvin sharing a cell with one of the
perpetrators of a $42 million heist of gold bricks from the Federal
Reserve System. When his cellmate suddenly dies of a heart attack,
Alvin is plucked from prison, implanted with a satellite-controlled
radio device that continually broadcasts his location and is used
as bait by a ruthless treasury investigator (David Morse) to flush
out the mastermind of the ``heist of the decade.'' Because his
cellmate buried the treasure, the reasoning goes, he may have left
Alvin a deathbed clue of its whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The ploy succeeds, and before long, Bristol (Doug Hutchison), a
villainous computer wizard who talks as if he is a robotic
caricature of John Malkovich in his monster mode, is menacing
Alvin's girlfriend, Lisa (Kimberly Elise), and their baby son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bait,'' directed by Antoine Fuqua from a screenplay by Andrew
and Adam Scheinman and Tony Gilroy, is so frenetically choppy that
its action sequences are impossible to follow. As a result, the
movie's chases and demolition derbies have no continuity or
visceral charge. After a while you begin to wonder if the director
cheated and, instead of actually filming whole action sequences,
shot bits and pieces and spliced them together. The result is an
odoriferous helping of cinematic seafood whose pungency suggests
that it has been sitting on the kitchen counter for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bait'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes sexual situations and some gory
violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BAIT'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Antoine Fuqua; written by Tony Gilroy, Andrew
Scheinman and Adam Scheinman; director of photography, Tobias
Schleissler; edited by Alan Edward Bell; music by Mark Mancina;
production designer, Peter Jamison; produced by Sean Ryerson;
released by Castle Rock Entertainment/Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 120 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jamie Foxx (Alvin Sanders), David Morse (Edgar Clenteen),
Doug Hutchison (Bristol), Kimberly Elise (Lisa), David Paymer
(Wooly), Mike Epps (Stevie), Robert Pastorelli (Jaster), Jamie
Kennedy (Blum) and Nestor Serrano (Boyle). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
