<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOB-KNIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN KNIGHT AND THE DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Deep thoughts about shallow subjects, shallow
thoughts about shallow subjects and shallow thoughts about deep
subjects:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hey, Knight, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   According to Bob Knight, those words are enough to drive a
reasonable man to distraction _ and from his job.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, then let's do our part to make the sports
world a better place:
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Patrick) Ewing, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Albert) Belle, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Mike) Tyson, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Daniel) Snyder, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Jerry) Jones, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Dick) Vitale, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Brent) Musburger, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Stuart) Scott, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Donald) Fehr, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, (Jerry) Tarkanian, what's up?
</P>
<P>
   _ Well, at least Knight didn't go down in a blaze of Woody Hayes
ignominy. There were no television cameras to capture the episode
that banished Knight into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Yet.
</P>
<P>
   Because Knight insists he isn't finished as a coach. Which means
that Knight will be back somewhere, doing the same boorish,
obnoxious, unnecessarily belittling things again. Anger management?
He needs a course in ogre management.
</P>
<P>
   Some school administration is going to sell out and hire Knight.
Didn't Tarkanian find work again? And Knight has never gotten a
school in probation, because the NCAA has never treated boorishness
as a prosecutable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to coach in the worst way,'' Knight said. Why not? He
already behaves in that manner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knight insisted there was nothing wrong with the hands-on
confrontation he had with freshman Indiana University student Kent
Harvey. Never mind that Knight admitted that the ``Hey, Knight,
what's up?'' greeting likely came out of nothing more sinister than
being flustered by an unexpected encounter with the most powerful
man in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did was simply try to teach him something about
manners,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight lecturing somebody about civility is like Madonna holding
court about chastity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knight was his usual blustering, bullying self Wednesday night
during his ESPN interview with Jeremy Schaap. He sidestepped
questions, played semantic games, rambled on almost nonsensically
and refused to take responsibility for any of his actions. When
Schaap tried to press the coach on specifics or cut off
self-serving filibusters, Knight trotted out his tiresome tactics
of intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Knight tried to throw off Schaap by saying:
``You've got a long way to go to be as good as your dad (long-time
writer and broadcaster Dick Schaap). ``You better keep that in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, a certain coach with ill-fitting sweaters has got a long
way to go before he passes muster as any sort of Knight in shining
armor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't buy into the spin that Knight galvanizes people into
love-him-or-hate-him postures. That implies that anybody who
disapproves of Knight does so irrationally, out of hate. Just
because Knight has done a lot of wonderful things during his career
doesn't excuse his wretched excesses. He didn't invent the concept
of winning games and positively influencing players. Plenty of
coaches do those things without the spite and meanness.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I Love You, Ronnie,'' reveals the contents of several of the
love letters that Ronald Reagan sent to his wife Nancy. The new
book paints a portrait of a love almost as intense as the one
between Keyshawn Johnson and Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keyshawn hasn't come across as bitter and petty about the New
York Jets trading him to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. He has been
bitter and petty, accusing Jets management of hidden agendas and
not wanting to win.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Jets are just as 2-0 as the Buccaneers. The lack of a
go-to receiver of Johnson's ilk didn't hinder the Jets from pulling
out an unlikely comeback victory against the New England Patriots
on Monday night. Dedrick Ward and Wayne (The Mascot) Chrebet both
made big-time catches during the winning drive. Johnson's nemesis,
Chrebet, caught two late touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the record, Johnson has contributed nine catches for 96
yards and a touchdown this season. Ward (nine for 204) and Chrebet
(nine for 118, two touchdowns) both have been more productive in
the season's first two weeks. The plot will truly thicken in 10
days, when the Jets play at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scary: St. Louis Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, the reigning
NFL Player of the Year, has put up 827 passing yards and 78 points
in the first two games. Scarier: This Sunday the Rams face a San
Francisco 49ers defense allowing 35 points and 314 passing yards
per game against quarterbacks not named Kurt Warner. Scariest: ``I
definitely believe I can play better,'' Warner said, ``than I did
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Warner said he's shooting for ``that perfect game.'' Maybe he
should re-think his goals. Look what a perfect game did for David
Cone's career.
</P>
<P>
   _ First, Snyder tried to turn the Washington Redskins into The
Beat Team That Money Can Buy. Then, Snyder started charging fans to
watch the training camp workouts. Then, the Redskins split their
first two games, giving them the same record as the Arizona
Cardinals and Philadelphia Eagles. Meanwhile, Jones' Cowboys are
winless, with hopeless in clear sight.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy justice _ fleeting as it may be _ when you see it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
