<HEADLINE>
`URBANIA': FIRST URBAN LEGENDS, THEN REAL DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way of looking at Jon Shear's harrowing and indelible film
``Urbania'' is to think of it as ``Sex and the City'' turned inside
out. This menacing erotic fantasy, set in Manhattan on the evening
of the switch from daylight saving to standard time, adding an
extra hour to the night, suggests a surreal cinematic answer to one
of Lou Reed's rock 'n' roll walks on the wild side.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its characters, instead of looking for love, are hunting
for sex on the streets and in the bars of a neighborhood that
resembles the downscale environs of Chelsea and the West Village
near the Hudson River. One of the kicks of cruising the streets
after midnight, the movie reminds us, is the thrill of the unknown
and its undertone of danger, which ``Urbania'' portrays as
palpably, frighteningly real.
</P>
<P>
   The central character, Charlie (Dan Futterman), is an angry,
grief-stricken gay man whose lover, Chris (Matt Keeslar), seen in
flashbacks, has mysteriously disappeared and is probably dead.
Charlie is obsessed with Chris to the point that he repeatedly
dials his number and leaves messages that he knows his absent
friend will never get.
</P>
<P>
   The story darkens as it develops, and it becomes increasingly
clear that the normally unprepossessing Charlie is ritualistically
psyching himself up to commit an act of violence. One preparatory
rite is to ponder scary urban legends, which the movie brings to
life with a haunting mixture of realism and horror. There's the one
about a man who picks up a woman, is drugged and wakes up in a
bathtub covered with blood to discover that one of his kidneys has
been removed. There's the one about a man who has unprotected sex
with a woman; the next morning he finds her gone and the message
``Welcome to the world of AIDS'' scrawled in lipstick on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Burrowing deeply into the threatening mood of these and other
horror stories, Charlie begins playing sadistic mind games with
people he meets in a neighborhood bar. He charms, then humiliates
an arrogant jock and his bimbo girlfriend. In his nastiest prank,
he picks up a vain bisexual soap-opera actor, goes home with him
and pretends to be a violent sociopath. The movie's portraits of
these narcissists have a scalding accuracy that even a show as
observant and up to date as ``Sex and the City'' rarely equals.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie's adventures in mental cruelty are only rehearsals for
the creation and acting out of his own urban myth before the night
is over. By the time he attaches himself to Dean (Samuel Ball), a
homophobic punk who has been prowling the neighborhood, Charlie's
vengeful agenda is painfully apparent.
</P>
<P>
   If the intense, edgy performances and urban ambience lend each
vignette a gripping fascination, ``Urbania'' sometimes pushes too
hard. It is also infuriatingly coy in its withholding of crucial
information. Once the facts have finally been revealed, ``Urbania''
turns briefly and uncomfortably mawkish with a scene set either in
heaven or in one of its anterooms, in which Charlie and Chris have
a sad, mystical conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Futterman, familiar from the television series ``Judging Amy,''
delivers a remarkably subtle and shaded portrait of a peaceful man
driven by overwhelming personal grief and rage to exorcise his
personal demons through a kind of violence that doesn't come to him
as naturally as it does to the macho men he confronts. The extent
to which he forces himself to ignore his more humane impulses makes
his situation all the more excruciating. It's the psychic
equivalent of being a vegetarian whose survival depends on
cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urbania'' is as technically innovative as it is emotionally
unsettling. Shot in super 16-millimeter film and digitally blown up
to 35-millimeter, it has a remarkably rich (and dark) visual
palette that matches its moody turbulence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Urbania'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes graphic sex and gory violence.. . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `URBANIA`
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jon Shear; written by Shear and Daniel Reitz;
director of photography, Shane Kelly; edited by Randolph K. Bricker
and Ed Marx; music by Marc Anthony Thompson; production designer,
Karyl Newman; produced by Shear, Stephanie Golden and J. Todd
Harris; released by Unapix Films. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Dan Futterman (Charlie), Alan Cumming (Brett), Matt
Keeslar (Chris), Josh Hamilton (Matt), Lothaire Bluteau (Bill),
Bill Sage (Chuck), Paige Turco (Cassandra), Samuel Ball (Dean) and
Barbara Sukowa (Clara). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 103 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is rated R.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
