<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     09-14 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUM OF THE WEEK: `SONGS FROM AN AMERICAN MOVIE' BY EVERCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERCLEAR: ``Songs From an American Movie, Volume I: Learning
How to Smile'' (Capitol).
</P>
<P>
   What are memories for? Art P. Alexakis of Everclear ponders that
question on ``Songs From an American Movie, Volume I.'' Alexakis,
38, isn't afraid to admit he has a long past, and he seesaws
between weighing what he has done and trying to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   In the album's single, ``AM Radio,'' he borrows the strutting
riff from Jean Knight's `` Big Stuff'' to rap-sing fond
reminiscences of the 1970s. But in ``Here We Go Again,'' he fends
off a new girlfriend's questions, saying, ``I do not want you to
know me the way I used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs'' is a post-divorce album. Alexakis observes the
collapsing marriage, hurls his final barbs and worries about the
effects on the child. He pins his hopes on a new love, vowing not
to make the old mistakes. And with ``Unemployed Boyfriend,'' he
comes up with the perfect modern come-on.
</P>
<P>
   The album started as a solo project for Alexakis, and it moves
away from Everclear's usual punky, guitar-charged rock toward
AM-radio music he remembers: country-rock, the Beach Boys, the
string-laden pop of Electric Light Orchestra. Despite some overdone
moments, like the remake of Van Morrison's ``Brown-Eyed Girl,''
most of the album turns Alexakis' ups and downs into tuneful,
broad-shouldered rock.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
