<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-LEE-HNS &LR;      09-14 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON FINDS HANDLING OF LEE CASE `QUITE TROUBLING' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday he found the
government's handling of the Wen Ho Lee case ``quite troubling,''
saying that Justice Department prosecutors could not justify their
treatment of the former Los Alamos laboratory scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had been concerned for some time about the
denial of bail for Lee, 60, who was freed Wednesday after agreeing
to plead guilty to one felony count of inappropriately downloading
nuclear weapons secrets at Los Alamos National Laboratory in Los
Alamos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Following Lee's release, the case's presiding judge said the
government's conduct had ``embarrassed the entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing was quite troubling to me,'' said Clinton,
whose remarks came only hours after Attorney General Janet Reno
said she was ``comfortable'' with the handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Lee was indicted on 59 counts alleging that the
scientist compromised some of the most sensitive codes in the
nuclear weapons arsenal by removing them from classified areas of
the lab from 1993 to 1997. Lee downloaded the codes onto 10
computer tapes, seven of which remain missing.
</P>
<P>
   The president questioned why government prosecutors would agree
to set free a person who, as recently as a week ago, they argued
was a potential national security threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day he's a terrible risk to the national security, and the
next day they're making a plea agreement for an offense far more
modest than what had been alleged,'' Clinton said, speaking to
reporters outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can justify in retrospect keeping a person
in jail without bail when you're prepared to make that kind of
agreement,'' he said. ``It just can't be justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Reno blamed the scientist's incarceration on
Lee himself. She said that she ``wished with all her heart and soul
that Mr. Lee had come forward'' immediately with information about
the seven missing computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dr. Lee had the opportunity from the beginning to
resolve this matter, and he chose not to, and I think he must look
to himself,'' she said at her weekly news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also said the Justice Department handled the case
appropriately. ``We made the best decision we could, based on the
evidence and the law, and I feel very comfortable about that,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, U.S. District Court Judge James Parker,
speaking from the bench after approving the plea agreement, told a
packed courtroom that ``the top decision-makers in the executive
branch, especially the Department of Justice and Department of
Energy, have embarrassed the entire nation and each of us who is a
citizen in it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Parker did not exonerate Lee in his remarks, saying the
scientist had pleaded guilty to a ``serious crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a felony offense. For that you need to be punished,'' he
said before sentencing Lee to the 278 days he has already served
while awaiting trail.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker, a Republican appointed by former President Ronald
Reagan, said the manner in which Lee was held _ without bail and
often in solitary confinement _ was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, you've been punished harshly,'' the judge said,
adding that citizens usually are entitled to be released until they
are tried and convicted. ``You lost valuable rights as a citizen. I
am sad that I was induced in December to order your detention.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Reno said Lee's punishment was equal to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even (Judge Parker) recognized that Dr. Lee had violated
criminal law in this instance, evidence was taken off a secured
computer, downloaded, put into an unsecured computer, which people
could have access to,'' she said. ``I think in that situation, you
have to look at the consequences of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   At his Wednesday hearing, Lee admitted that in 1994 he had
unauthorized possession of documents related to national defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used an unsecure computer to download a document related to
national defense,'' Lee said. ``I knew at the time that my position
was unauthorized and that under the Los Alamos National Laboratory
directives I was not permitted'' to have the documents outside of
the secured perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also acknowledged that the government had national security
reasons for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The felony conviction carries a maximum penalty of 10 years'
imprisonment, a fine of $250,000 and up to three years of
supervised release. The scientist instead was credited with the 278
days he already served.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea agreement, Lee, a Taiwanese-born naturalized
citizen, will have to undergo as much as 60 hours of intense
interrogation from federal agents over the fate of the seven tapes.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to tell prosecutors how, when and where the copies
of the data were made and the manner in which they were disposed
of. He also has submitted a written declaration that he never
shared, nor had any intention of sharing, the information with any
other source.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions will begin Sept. 26 and will run for six hours a
day for 10 days. Lee also will make himself available for further
debriefing sessions, if necessary. And he will allow authorities to
search his home or any other storage spaces, such as safe deposit
becomes, if questioning leads to that. The deal further stipulates
that Lee may have to take polygraph exams on issues related to
national security.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
