<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-CLARK-870&AMP;ADD     09-14 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-CLARK-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARKS HOPING TO KEEP OLYMPIC MEDALS IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY CROW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hazel Clark is a Clark, which means many things, but mostly that
she is a runner. Her father ran cross-country in high school, and
her half-brother and half-sister have forged distinguished track
careers for themselves, particularly in the 800 meters. Her
sister-in-law even has an Olympic gold medal for a relay and holds
the American record in the 800: two laps in 1 minute, 56.04
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When Hazel Clark was not much more than a toddler, though, she
decided two things: That she idolized her older and then-distant
half-sister, Joetta, and that she would never follow Joetta onto
the track. Instead, Hazel spent years at the fence railing, content
to watch with hands clasped together while Joetta flew past in a
blur of legs and accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was really young, I would get really nervous when she'd
run,'' Hazel said, ``and I'd root for her and pray to give her all
my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet today, Hazel Clark at 22 is one of America's top
800-meter runners. In March, she won the USA Indoor Track &AMP; Field
Championships, and in July, she took first place at the U.S.
Olympic trials. Following right behind her in that race were her
sister-in-law, Jearl Miles-Clark, and her sister, Joetta Clark
Diggs. Her brother, J.J. Clark, was their coach, and watching from
the sidelines was the family patriarch, Joe Clark, better known
from his ``Lean on Me'' days as a hard-nosed Paterson, N.J., high
school principal.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark women made headlines and history as the first family
to sweep a track-and-field event in an Olympic trials. When track
competition begins Sept. 22 at the Summer Games in Sydney, it will
be Hazel's first time on an Olympic team, Jearl's third, and
Joetta's fourth and final. As far as the 800 goes, the Clarks are
America's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two sisters coached by a brother who is married to one of
their competitors _ it's a story even Hollywood couldn't make up,''
said Craig Masback of USA Track &AMP; Field, the organization that
oversees more than 4,000 track events a year. ``Jearl has to be the
favorite, Hazel has the most untapped potential, and Joetta has
more experience than anyone. Each has an opportunity to make it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to join Team Clark, though, Hazel first had to find
herself among her famous family of runners. She who would not run
had to figure out why she was so intimidated and then decide what
to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   There is an undeniable pressure that comes with taking on
another's legacy. You must somehow validate their successes and
further their dreams without losing your own. When Hazel eventually
became a runner, she constantly worried about letting Joetta and
the rest of the family down.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Hazel decided to race her sister and her
sister-in-law for the first time at the Goodwill Games in New
Orleans. Jearl finished first, Joetta second and Hazel fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point,'' Hazel said, ``I guess I was still caught in
that little sister routine, where I was so used to looking up to
Joetta and she had been everything to me for so long that I didn't
really race her.''
</P>
<P>
   But something in Hazel had changed by the Olympic trials in
Sacramento on July 23. ``This time,'' she said, ``I felt like I was
going to race her _ not cut in behind her, not let myself be beaten
by my big sister, not make excuses because I was young or not
supposed to be at the top _ no, I went for it.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, Hazel Clark left the railing for good.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, Joetta Clark Diggs has watched her sister
for years now with the bemused pride and frustration of a drill
sergeant. Hazel, or ``Peachy,'' as the family calls her, is
Joetta's project as much as her sister.
</P>
<P>
   When Hazel was born, though, Joetta was already 16 and a senior
in high school. She was not keen about the prospect of
baby-sitting. The baby was welcome, Joetta said, but she was closer
to J.J., who was only two years younger. Joetta and J.J. had grown
up together in Newark, N.J. They had adjusted to their parents'
divorce and to their father's remarriage. They had discovered the
family talent for running track, although their father forbade them
from becoming sprinters because he wanted to combat the stereotype
that black people could not run distances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing that roadwork is very, very lonely,'' Joe said recently,
``but it builds character.''
</P>
<P>
   In matters of character, Joetta is her father's daughter. She is
aggressive and serious, well read and business savvy. Even as a
teen-ager, she thrived on the discipline of all-day workouts, and
for a long time she had little time for Hazel. Joetta was running
the 800 at 12 and missing her high school graduation at 17 because
she was at her first Olympic trials. Before Sydney, she was on
three other Olympic teams, with her best finish a seventh place in
the 800 meters in 1992. She's been ranked in the national Top 10
every year for the last 20 years, and in 1998, she was ranked
fourth in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot mentally to come back and train and race year
after year, to stay that intense over that many years,'' said Mark
Young, the assistant coach overseeing America's 800-meter runners
in Sydney. ``She's the consummate professional.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She is also 38 years old now, a veteran in a sport filled with
sprightly twentysomethings like Hazel, who makes time to shop and
talk about boys and go to dance clubs and the beach. Hazel never
had to fight for the college scholarships or the big-money shoe
deals that now give professional sports so much gloss. If Joetta is
intense, she said she has had to be to survive in her sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was Hazel's age, I was more focused,'' Joetta said,
``but it was a different generation. Women during my time were
trying to establish themselves in the career world, and at 21, I
was trying to prove that as a black woman I was educated. Now it's
a whole different game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like as an athlete, she thinks that there were always nice
tracks and nice weight rooms and nice equipment, and everyone
always had planes to fly on to go to all their meets. She doesn't
understand life before Title IX, when women couldn't do the same
things as men, didn't have the budget. So she's more into the
enjoyment of it, just having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true. Hazel Clark is having fun on the track these days,
relishing the Olympics with the giddiness of a spectator and taking
along several suitcases for the trip. Joetta packed one.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Hazel's childhood promise never to be a runner?
She kept it for a time, becoming a dancer and then a figure skater.
But by 16, she was 5 feet, 9 inches tall _ long-legged for a skater
_ and she quit the sport after suffering a serious fall on the ice.
Only then did she give in to the pleadings of her siblings, who saw
potential in Hazel's long stride.
</P>
<P>
   She begrudgingly became a runner. She even attended the
University of Florida in Gainesville where her brother is an
assistant track coach, and she trained with J.J.'s wife, Jearl.
Joetta stayed in New Jersey, but regularly flew down to train.
</P>
<P>
   Jearl, 34, said she had watched Joetta mellow and Hazel mature,
but she added, ``I didn't know it for a long time, but Hazel still
felt she had a lot to live up to. She wanted so much to be her own
person.''
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly six years for Hazel to deal with her demons of
inferiority and finally fall in love with the sport that she felt
belonged to her sister. Late last year the three Clarks started
training for the Olympics. Somewhere in all those early-morning
workouts and summer track meets, Hazel got to know Joetta. Hazel
came to know her not as a record-setter or a reputation but as a
sister, someone who loves to cook and hates to lose and reminds her
so much of their father that it's eerie. And one day after a long
workout, it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stopped and thought, `You're supposed to be up there.
You've worked hard, and Joetta will be proud of you. She won't take
anything from you,''' Hazel said. ``It felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right. Joetta said, ``She's a good kid. She still has to
prove herself a lot, but she's going to have some good years. She's
so talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that workout, Hazel said she no longer minds carrying on
the Clark legacy. She has chosen to love the sport on her own
terms, and now she wants nothing more than to race alongside her
sister and sister-in-law one last time in Sydney. After the
Olympics, Joetta will retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is make-or-break time,'' Hazel said, ``and it's my first,
but it's her last. But now we're motivating each other, and I think
that's why we all made the team. We get to the finals, and we're
going to make some more history.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
