<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFSNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIAN REVERSAL ON MOBILE PHONES
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government suspended a decision to seize frequencies
of the country's two biggest mobile phone providers in a move that
investors said shows the government has not lost sight of
protecting Russia's property rights. The two companies, Vimpelcom
and Mobile Telesystems, were told last week by the Ministry of
Telecommunications to relinquish frequencies they had already been
awarded, which drove their stock prices down by as much as 24
percent. Though the government did not explain why it had recalled
the frequencies, analysts said Moscow's third mobile phone
provider, Sonic Duo, which is owned partly by a
government-controlled company, would have been the most likely
recipient. Frequency space is tight in Moscow's crowded mobile
phone market, which is expected to double in subscribers by the end
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   STRONG RESULTS AT CAP GEMINI
</P>
<P>
   Shares in one of Europe's biggest computer service groups, Cap
Gemini of France, rose sharply after the company announced strong
sales and profit growth in the first half and said results were
lifted by a tax credit related to its $11.1 billion acquisition
earlier this year of the consulting practice of Ernst &AMP; Young. Cap
Gemini's chief financial officer, Frederic Lemoine, said Cap Gemini
would benefit from the deductibility over 15 years of as much as
1.6 billion euros, or $1.3 billion, from U.S. taxes as a result of
goodwill amortization related to the Ernst &AMP; Young acquisition. Cap
Gemini shares rose almost 5 percent, to 219.50 euros, on the news.
</P>
<P>
   POTENTIAL DEAL FOR DHL
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Post AG, the postal and logistics company controlled by
the German government, is in talks to gain control of DHL
International by substantially increasing its 25 percent stake in
the courier company that has operations in the United States,
people close to the negotiations said. The deal would value
Brussels-based DHL at about 11 billion euros or $9.4 billion, far
less than what has been speculated.DHL would give Deutsche Post,
which is planning to go public in November, a global delivery
network and pit it against FedEx Corp. of Memphis, Tenn., and
United Parcel Service Inc., of Atlanta. Japan Airlines, Lufthansa
AG and a group of DHL senior managers and members of the founders'
family control DHL in nearly equal parts.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY LOSSES AT NUCLEAR FUEL MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Britain's ill-starred, state-owned nuclear fuel company, BNFL,
reported disastrous losses for a year marked by scandal over the
falsification of quality control data on shipments of nuclear fuel.
In what the company called ``poor results'' for the year to March
31, pretax profit fell from 218 million pounds, or about $307
million, to a loss of 337 million pounds. BNFL, which has contracts
for a range of nuclear decommissioning projects in the United
States through its Westinghouse subsidiary, said it was unlikely to
proceed with plans for a partial privatization until late 2002.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE CONTRACTOR EARNINGS FALL
</P>
<P>
   Shares in BAE Systems PLC, Britain's leading defense contractor
and the world's third biggest, slipped by up to 8.7 percent to
363.25 pence after the company said first-half profit fell 3.3
percent because of higher taxes and cuts in government military
spending. The company said net income slid to (PS)87 million, or
about $123 million, from (PS)90 million one year earlier. The
results reflect BAE's purchase of Marconi Electronics last
December, but the company declined to say how the acquisition had
affected its first-half performance.
</P>
<P>
   RESPITE IN CANADIAN INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   Canada's annual inflation rate fell to 2.5 percent in August
from 3 percent in June, as the rise in energy prices abated.
Economists had expected less than the half-point drop in the
Consumer Price Index for August, but warned that the latest jump in
oil prices will push it higher again for September. Excluding
energy, Canada's inflation rate was 1.7 percent in August, up
slightly from 1.5 percent in July. Energy costs are 11.9 per cent
higher than a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5395 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-SELLING-ON-WEB-HARVAR     09-14 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELLING-ON-WEB-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALL-IN-ONE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Mon., Sept. 11, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from a recent issue of
HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of information on the
art and science of business and management. For information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or about The
Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL PUBLISHING _
contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives
listed at the end of the text.) 
 By PAUL NUNES, DIANE WILSON and AJIT KAMBIL  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies have always wrestled with two questions in tandem:
what to sell and how to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to sell is a big one, because in choosing
one way, sellers almost always foreclose other possibilities.
Commodity dealers selling on spot markets, for example, do not also
offer continuous replenishment programs. Mass merchandisers with
fixed prices do not invite negotiation. And auction houses do not
sell through mail order.
</P>
<P>
   Companies know that by limiting themselves to one main selling
mechanism, they sacrifice a lot of potential customers and leave a
lot of money lying on the table. But they've had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the same things in different ways has traditionally been
too complex and has required radically different physical setups.
How, for instance, can a mail retailer bring together enough
interested buyers to run a reasonable auction?
</P>
<P>
   PROLIFERATING CHOICES
</P>
<P>
   All that has changed in the age of the Internet, where business
is increasingly unconstrained by the laws and limitations of the
physical world.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the many different ways one could purchase a ticket on
American Airlines' Web site. Travelers can book tickets through
Sabre, the company's traditional reservation system; choose from a
limited number of deeply discounted fares using NetSAAvers; secure
special fares based on membership in one of a number of affinity
programs, such as Senior TrAAvelers; arrange customized trips based
on a personal profile stored in Personal AAccess; or select
vacation packages, purchasing air tickets as part of a bundled
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, someone who goes to Dell's Web site can buy a
customized computer using the company's famous online system
configurator or bid in an auction for a popular setup. LandsEnd.com
augments its fixed-price catalog with a Dutch auction for
overstocks. Streamline.com offers buyers basic grocery ordering as
well as a continuous replenishment option for staple items.
</P>
<P>
   All these sites are early examples of all-in-one markets _
markets that offer, side by side, alternative ways for buyers and
sellers to transact business.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why companies are moving quickly to offer more
ways to buy. They recognize that the same buyer may want different
transaction mechanisms under different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   A clotheshorse may love certain purchasing methods when bargain
hunting for basics, yet shun them when shopping for an outfit for a
special occasion. A person may not care about ticket prices when
traveling for business, but he may be the king of the cherry
pickers when it comes time to plan a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to offer multiple transaction approaches allows
companies to win a larger share of existing customers' business as
well as bring new types of buyers into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   A THREE-STAGE EVOLUTION
</P>
<P>
   All-in-one markets have evolved in three stages. Stage one saw a
great deal of innovation in online transaction mechanisms. Many
companies experimented with mechanisms that had previously been
unknown in their industries.
</P>
<P>
   For example, iBeauty.com introduced continuous replenishment to
the online health and beauty business, enabling automatic
reordering of fragrances and cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies pioneered entirely new transaction mechanisms.
Priceline.com, for example, introduced the world to the ``demand
collection system'' _ where buyers post the price they are willing
to pay and invite sellers to either accept or decline the business.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata pioneered electronic group buying. It allows individuals
to gather into buying blocks, leveraging their combined purchasing
power to drive prices down.
</P>
<P>
   In stage two, companies rushed to combine transaction approaches
on their Web sites. Of the 320 leading e-commerce sites we studied,
two-thirds already employ multiple transaction mechanisms, and 30
percent support three or more mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the growing availability of off-the-shelf software
for handling Web transactions, such as OpenSite's auction package,
these numbers are sure to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're entering stage three: the aggregation of many sellers
onto the sites that already feature more than one selling
mechanism. An early leader in this trend is Travelocity.com.
</P>
<P>
   Like the American Airlines site, Travelocity combines several
transaction mechanisms. But unlike American Airlines, it provides
access to travel services from a range of airlines, hotels and
rental car agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of all-in-one markets was inevitable. By enabling
frictionless movement among ways of doing business, they benefit
both buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this trend runs counter to the conventional wisdom
about e-commerce. Many observers predicted that the wide reach and
low transaction costs of the Internet would push all transactions
toward a single mechanism _ open-market price competition. It seems
that the ultimate market for e-commerce isn't one for all. it's all
in one.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Nunes and Ajit Kambil are research fellows at Andersen
Consulting's Institute for Strategic Change. Diane Wilson is a
partner in charge of Andersen Consulting's new Dot-Com Launch
Centre in Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
