<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Sept. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A band of locally heavy rain will precede a cold front as it
sweeps across New England Friday. In the wake of the front, winds
from the northwest will deliver sharply cooler air from central
Canada into the Middle West and Northeast. Showers and a few
rumbles of thunder will occur in the chilly air from the eastern
Great Lakes to the central Appalachians. The autumnal air mass will
envelop the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states throughout the
weekend, keeping temperatures far below normal.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and noticeably less humid air will reach most of the
Southeast as a cold front moves toward the Gulf of Mexico. Sultry
air and a few thundershowers will linger across central and
southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, high pressure will keep most areas from the Plains
states to the West Coast dry and tranquil.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FUNNEL CLOUDS
</P>
<P>
   A funnel cloud swirled briefly near Brownsville, Texas, on
Wednesday as scattered showers moved across the area. Later Friday
and Saturday, funnel clouds may be seen near the eastern Great
Lakes. In general, funnel clouds are a result of atmospheric
instability, a condition that arises when a layer of cold air
overlies a layer of warm, moist air. The air above the Great Lakes
will be chilly this weekend, while the lake waters retain summer's
warmth. At Brownsville, the air aloft was not very cold, but
low-level Gulf of Mexico air was very warm and humid. In both
cases, the atmosphere was unstable.
</P>
</TEXT>
