<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PIERRE-GILLES-PHOTOS-     09-14 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIERRE-GILLES-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HISTORY AND ARTIFICE MATE IN A HOTHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may almost be too late for the French photo team
known as Pierre et Gilles to get the credit they deserve in the
United States. The cross-pollination between high and popular
culture that they exemplify has accelerated so dizzyingly over the
last decade that their exquisitely hand-finished photographs of
impossibly, sometimes scarily, beautiful men and women seem oddly
creaky and routine. At the same time, it may also be too soon to
know just what credit Pierre et Gilles are owed.
</P>
<P>
   The team's 56-work retrospective at the New Museum of
Contemporary Art in SoHo is a long overdue introduction. It's their
first major museum show in the United States, coming a decade after
a single gallery show, at Hirschl &AMP; Adler Modern in 1990. Organized
by Dan Cameron, senior curator at the New Museum, it is a must-see
for anyone interested in the intertwining histories of postmodern
(especially set-up) photography, fashion photography, commercial
illustration, the male nude in art and the emergence of a gay
sensibility _ histories in which Pierre et Gilles figure to a
greater or lesser degree, depending on who is talking.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that this show is too small to account for the
activities of this prolific duo, who are now in their 40s and have
been a couple and a collaborative team since 1976. (While they plan
the images and their often elaborate stagings together, Pierre, who
trained as a photographer, takes the pictures, while Gilles,
trained as a painter, applies the painted highlights; contrary to
appearances there is no digital work involved.) Over the last
quarter-century they have applied their peculiar mix of media, and
of camp and kitsch and sacred and erotic, to an ecumenical range of
media: album and magazine covers, fashion photography, commercial
illustration and celebrity portraiture.
</P>
<P>
   They have given us Catherine Deneuve as a fairy princess with a
painted-on tiara, Iggy Pop as a foppish visionary with a pancake
complexion and crazed blue eyes. They have portrayed friends,
models and stars as biblical and mythological characters ranging
from Adam and Eve to Medusa.
</P>
<P>
   They have revisited academic painting genres (the exotic beggar
boy, for example) and raided non-Western cultures _ the Indian
movie poster, for one. Repeatedly they have provided lavish updates
on the beefcake tradition, bringing an unusual mix of blatant
seductiveness and innocence to images of beautiful young men cast
as Roman centurions, Greek sea gods, hustlers, sailors and cowboys.
Throughout, they have had a thriving gallery career, at least in
Europe: however widely reproduced, their photographs are always one
of a kind and encased in elaborate, often glitzy custom-made
frames.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to another problem: this exhibition's seeming
intent to present the artists as avatars of the avant-garde and the
somewhat isolated atmosphere that results. Pierre et Gilles are
stars in France and Europe because of their fairly constant
presence in the mass media. But there is no sense of the media, of
the street, in this exhibition, even though some of the images on
view have appeared on magazine and album covers. It might have
helped if the catalog or the installation had provided a fuller,
messier sense of the context in which their work habitually
appears.
</P>
<P>
   The clean, lean installation certainly enables the visitor to
savor the peculiar hothouse intensity of the images, and until a
larger show comes along, to form a few opinions, not all of which
may be completely reconcilable.
</P>
<P>
   One opinion is that Pierre et Gilles, rather than being
avant-garde artists, are the sole occupants of a category of their
own devising, a hermetically sealed, time-warped middle ground
between high art and popular culture. From this vantage point they
have ignored both, pursuing a vision of otherworldly beauty steeped
in artifice and historical consciousness and charged with an erotic
current that is often but not always explicitly gay.
</P>
<P>
   They share concerns and characteristics with many other artists
of the 1970s and '80s, including Gilbert and George, Robert
Mapplethorpe, Annie Liebovitz, Yasumasa Morimura, Cindy Sherman and
Jeff Koons. Their elaborately staged images also stand as
precedents for younger photo artists like Gregory Crewdson,
Catherine Opie, Matthew Barney and Mariko Mori. Their emphasis on
idealized images of beautiful young men has undoubtedly influenced
the increased visibility of the male body in fashion photography.
</P>
<P>
   These connections don't alter their basic isolation. For one
thing, their work seems protected by a not-so-invisible shield of
artistic conservatism; it is deliberately, almost exultantly retro,
which may account for its popularity. Its retrievals don't so much
parody or revitalize forms like the hand-tinted photograph or
mass-produced images of saints as pay heartfelt homage to them or
simply embalm them. There is not, for example, a shred of irony in
the beatific, softly lighted image of a slim black man in a monk's
habit who portrays St. Martin, even though some of the animals
gathered around him look as though they came from the taxidermist.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at this show becomes a process of seeking out the works
that, like St. Martin, have escaped the embalming process for one
reason or another and managed to breathe as art objects. Sometimes
survival is mostly due to the subject's force of personality, as
with the imperious glare of Eliane Pine Caringhton, an artist who
stands before a deep orange wall draped in pearls, looking like
Coco Chanel on a good jewel day despite his 5 o'clock shadow. In
other instances the painting seems to take over completely. A
jaundiced Medusa backed by greenish feather-boa clouds achieves a
classic aura of evil because it is so thoroughly overpainted that
it resembles a lithograph and not a photograph of a real person at
all.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, a large recent image of a melancholy male nude in a
rocky grotto is effective because the mist that gives the image
such mysterious depth is clearly painted and stands out against the
photographic quality of the rest of the image. This sense of the
techniques of painting and photography being pulled far enough
apart that a perceptible gap exists between them also animates
``Dans le Port du Havre'' This image, which is hands down the
show's best, features an angelic young sailor up to his chest in
water rich with gleaming bubbles and the harbor lights and a florid
night sky behind him. Like the grotto image, it dates from 1998,
and it takes the indefatigable Pierre et Gilles into new territory
that they would do well to explore.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
