<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f BC-ART-OF-PERSUASION-AND     09-14 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-OF-PERSUASION-AND-MORE-HARVARD-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The following articles constitute this
week's transmission HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, one of two news
services that will carry content from Harvard Business School
Publishing. Both services are distributed by The New York Times
Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text.
</P>
<P>
   The articles have been sent to the ``f'' (financial) category
code.
</P>
<P>
   MASTERING THE ART OF PERSUASION
</P>
<P>
   ART-OF-PERSUASION-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ Are you a Donald Trump
or a Mahatma Gandhi? Both have reputations as highly persuasive
leaders, but display very different operating styles. Once you know
whether you're more Gandhi or Trump, there are specific things you
can do that will set you on the path of effective leadership and
mastery of the art of persuasion. By the editorial staff of the
Harvard Management Communication Letter.
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSONS OF `FAILING FORWARD'
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING-FROM-FAILURE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ Management theory
underscores the virtues of taking risks and learning from failure.
However, management practice is behind the curve. The dynamics of
failure are poorly understood. Recently, professors Amy Edmondson
and Dorothy Leonard of Harvard Business School and Mark Cannon of
Vanderbilt University developed a concept they call ``failing
forward.'' Drawing from a study of 51 work groups in a midsized
manufacturing company, they explain that failing forward is ``the
ability to fail intelligently and respond constructively to failure
so that the potential learning is captured.'' It includes four
essential activities, described in this article. By the editorial
staff of the Harvard Management Update.
</P>
