<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-COSTAS15-COX     09-14 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-COSTAS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bob Costas: Pumped, prepped and at the helm
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Costas, bright-eyed and bearing tons of useful and
not-so-useful information, will bound kangaroolike into our living
rooms for a two-week visit beginning tonight.
</P>
<P>
   As anchor of NBC's prime-time telecasts of the Summer Olympics,
Costas will spend 162 1/2 hours on the air, starting with tonight's
4 1/2-hour coverage of the Opening Ceremony in Sydney. This is his
fourth Olympics for NBC and third as prime-time host. It would not
be stretching the truth to say he enjoys these assignments quite a
lot. His first love may be baseball, but the Olympic Games get his
blood pumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the appeal of the Olympics,'' Costas said in a recent
teleconference, ``is that it's an international adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas is legendary for his Olympics preparation. In
anticipation of the Atlanta Games, he pored through hundreds of
books, profiles and interviews. He's done the same thing this time,
prepping himself for an event that is equal parts sports
competition, human drama and travelogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The setting is always important,'' Costas said. ``To an
American audience, there's absolutely no intrigue about showing
scenes from Atlanta. But in Barcelona in '92, there was a
travelogue element. ... It was almost impossible to show an event
in Barcelona without the backdrop looking like a picture
postcard.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas' boss, NBC sports executive producer Dick Ebersol, calls
Sydney ``the best place the Olympics have ever been.'' The natural
beauty of the land Down Under, coupled with the intimacy of the
various venues, make for another potentially ``picture postcard''
setting. Americans are keenly interested in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the No. 1 destination for American tourist travelers,''
said coordinating producer Lisa Lax, ``and we're going to make sure
we show off the country.''
</P>
<P>
   `Our mantra is storytelling'
</P>
<P>
   The goal of NBC's Olympics coverage, as always, is to connect
viewers, especially those who may not be sports fiends, with
athletes from all over the world. ABC perfected the art with the
``Up Close and Personals'' created by sports producing genius Roone
Arledge and delivered by avuncular host Jim McKay in the 1960s and
'70s, and the tradition has continued ever since from year to year
and network to network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mantra is storytelling, and we do that primarily through
telling these unique, individual stories,'' Lax said.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles are now part of the Olympics experience because
they are such a big part of the TV experience. The theory is that
to know the athletes is to love them, and to love them is to want
to watch them _ whether they're racing around a track, spiking a
volleyball or pressing a few hundred pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be aware that 95 percent of the competitors who
come to an Olympic Games are not aspiring professionals who will
become fabulously wealthy,'' said Costas, 48, and still oozing
boyish charm and enthusiasm. ``This is their be-all and end-all.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas has had a happy, healthy career covering professional
baseball, basketball, football and hockey _ team sports that
function on yearly cycles, often with the same participants
returning from year to year. Famous folks, popular sports. For most
Olympic athletes, the once-in-a-lifetime experience raises the
competition to a heightened level that Costas finds thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the preparation, the sacrifice and the anticipation
that go into that moment,'' Costas said, nearly breathless at the
prospect. ``And the nature of many events is that they are very
quick _ boom, it's over in 10, 20 seconds. Those moments have such
clarity, and knowing that the world is watching brings everything
to a peak. That's tremendous sports drama.''
</P>
<P>
   And although American viewers may have never heard of athletes
from other countries, sometimes these lesser-knowns have a greater
impact than our home-grown stars such as Michael Johnson and Marion
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``An athlete, such as a runner from Ethiopia, can lift the whole
country's spirit,'' Costas said. ``That's the way it works at the
Olympics, and I find that compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours and hours of coverage
</P>
<P>
   NBC's prime-time coverage is being touted by the network as the
``traditional family coverage,'' featuring premiere events such as
track and field, gymnastics, swimming and diving. And lots of
profiles. NBC's cable outlets, MSNBC and CNBC, are targeting more
ardent sports enthusiasts with a total of 279 hours of
wall-to-wall, start-to-finish coverage of team sports and boxing.
And for the total sports fanatic, there's NBCOlympics.com, which
will be laden with statistics and other insider sports stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the Complete Olympics,'' Costas said of the
whopping 441 total hours planned on the Peacock's broadcast, cable
and Internet empire.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 15- to 18-hour time difference between Australia
and the United States, all of NBC's coverage will be tape-delayed.
The network figured very few viewers would watch the main events at
3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Games are the first of five Olympics that NBC won the
rights to televise with a bid of $5 billion for the package, $705
million for the 2000 Summer Olympiad. Unless a koala kidnaps him in
Australia, we can probably expect to see Costas at the helm of at
least a couple more.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Diane Holloway at dholloway(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
