A5430 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-LEARNING-FROM-FAILURE     09-14 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-FROM-FAILURE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LESSONS OF `FAILING FORWARD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Sept. 12, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Management theory underscores the virtues of taking risks and
learning from failure. Management practice is behind the curve. The
dynamics of failure are poorly understood. Nobody likes to fail,
and nobody seems to learn much from it.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, professors Amy Edmondson and Dorothy Leonard of
Harvard Business School and Mark Cannon of Vanderbilt University
developed a concept they call ``failing forward.'' Drawing from a
study of 51 work groups in a midsized manufacturing company, they
explain that failing forward is ``the ability to fail intelligently
and respond constructively to failure so that the potential
learning is captured.'' It includes four essential activities:
</P>
<P>
   DELIBERATE EXPERIMENTATION
</P>
<P>
   ``Organizations that are not experiencing small failures on a
regular basis are probably not experimenting enough and not
learning enough,'' write Edmondson and Cannon in an as-yet
unpublished paper. Effective experimentation tests a variety of
hypotheses.
</P>
<P>
   BMW and other auto companies, for instance, use simulation
technology to test cars' crashworthiness. They can thereby
experiment with a wider range of risks than if they used expensive
cars and dummies for every test.
</P>
<P>
   ENGAGING IN `CREATIVE ABRASION'
</P>
<P>
   This concept, developed by Leonard, takes people with a mix of
differences _ in expertise, training, education, background and
cognitive preferences _ and engages them in a constructive thought
process that maximizes those differences. When an experiment
``fails,'' an intellectually diverse group can frame and analyze
the outcome in ways that wring value from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   EXPOSING FAILURE
</P>
<P>
   You can't learn anything when failures ``are either covered up
or never materialize in the first place because people have not put
their ideas to a test,'' Edmonson and Cannon write. What's more,
``errors must be surfaced before they are compounded, incorporated
into larger systems, and become irrevocable.''
</P>
<P>
   Try to identify the failure as early and efficiently as
possible. ``The sooner a failure is identified, the sooner the
potential learning ... can take place and the less investment goes
toward an unproductive end.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYZING FAILURE THOROUGHLY
</P>
<P>
   High quality ``arises from an organizational system that
actively seeks out problems and determines how they may be avoided
in the future,'' the two researchers observe. Avoid placing blame.
Rather, create a system that discovers the causes of the errors and
prevents them from recurring.
</P>
<P>
   The theory may be straightforward, but it's difficult to
implement. Most organizations are allergic to failure and tend to
penalize employees associated with it. Little wonder that employees
are loathe to ask the difficult questions at the beginning of a
project or conduct a comprehensive post-project review. The risks
to their careers are too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore,'' Edmondson observes, ``they tend to play not to
lose instead of playing to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Can things be different? Yes, according to Edmonson, provided
``managers learn how to be more concrete and less abstract than
people typically are in the way they ask questions and give
direction.'' For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Demonstrate the kind of openness you'd like to see. Employees
may engage in constructive criticism of a project _ or even admit
their own mistakes _ when they see a manager do the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create ``practice fields.'' Peter Senge, author of the
best-selling book ``The Fifth Discipline,'' observes that
management is the only profession that affords no opportunity for
practice or rehearsal _ it's 100 percent live performance. Try to
create situations in which employees can experiment, whether it's
through computer-based simulations or offsite seminars.
</P>
<P>
   When managers create the psychological conditions that ease
employees' fear of failure, the potential for learning increases
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of nursing teams in a major hospital, for example,
Edmondson found that when the nurse manager was open, encouraging
and respected, the entire team was more open to exploring the
possibility of errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance,'' she explains, ``the results looked as
though the teams with the more respected nurse managers were making
more errors. But they were only reporting more errors: They had a
higher intercept rate, which meant they were catching more errors
and therefore averting more potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, these teams discovered systematic errors
occurring with a particular type of intravenous pump. This
discovery led the hospital to order a different kind of pump.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
