<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Put away welcome mat for opossums
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We live in the country and are having a
problem with an opossum eating our cat's food and drinking his
water. He is about the size of a full-grown cat. My question is,
does he pose any health concerns if he and our cat share the same
water bowl or food bowl? Should I provide him with his own bowls?
The cat has had a few run-ins with him also.
</P>
<P>
   _ K.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opossums do have some parasites, but transmission does not
occur at the food bowls,'' notes Texas A&AMP;M veterinarian David
Phalen. What should concern you is the chance your cat could be
bitten by the opossum, he warns. Opossums dine on dead things, and
their bite may transmit bacteria, leaving your cat with an infected
wound.
</P>
<P>
   Reconsider making the opossum so welcome. Can you feed the cat
inside?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you help me procure the address of film great Steven
Spielberg? This is business-related, not personal.
</P>
<P>
   _ L.C.S.
</P>
<P>
   A:Spielberg and his famous partners, Jeffrey Katzenberg and
David Geffen, own equal portions, but Microsoft's co-founder, Paul
Allen, is the largest single investor in DreamWorks, SKG. The
company has produced ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Antz.''
Addresses for DreamWorks? The studio facilities, DreamWorks SKG,
100 Universal Plaza, No. 601, Universal City, CA 91608 and the
administrative offices, 1000 Flower St., Glendale, CA 91201.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We were given a piece of Texas pink granite as a gift from a
man in Marble Falls to use as a countertop in our kitchen. It has a
smooth, shiny surface, but it still has lots of natural cracks and
indentations. Do we need to do anything before we use it? Do we
just set it as is on top of the laminate countertop? Also, do we
need to wax the surface to fill in those indentations? Use special
cleaners? Can we slice, dice, chop and scrub on this surface _ or
do we need to be careful?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jane U. &AMP; Jim D.
</P>
<P>
   A:You are going to love this countertop! Safely slice, dice and
set pots directly from the stove on it. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Stone Works' Myrna Gonzalez advises removing the current
laminate and placing the granite directly on the counter supports.
Use Liquid Nails to secure the top and caulk the edges. Use a
standard sealer on the surface. The nicks and cracks give the
granite character. Simple soap and water keeps granite countertops
in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   Granite's enemy? Grease. If you do spill grease, wipe it up
promptly before it soaks into this natural stone.
Upshot/Update/Uproar:Cleaning out your closet? The Boys and Girls
Clubs of the Capital Area would love to have your old men's shirts
_ short or long sleeve. Any color. Any size. The clubs' fine arts
classes need these old shirts to use as smocks. While you are
cleaning out the closet, consider donating any art supplies _ clay,
paintbrushes, etc. Drop donations off at 303 W. Johanna St. or
contact fine arts director Alyx Kellington at 444-7199. Who knows?
You may be sparking the career of the next Auguste Rodin or Mary
Cassatt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
