<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New VHS and DVD editions of ``This is Spinal Tap,'' Rob Reiner's
1984 parody of a rock documentary, were released on Tuesday, but
some of the better entertainment issued this week can be found in
two new series from the silent era: ``First Ladies: Early Women
Filmmakers 1915-25'' from Kino and ``Equal Time: The Women of
Cinema'' from Milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Good silent films hold surprises, not least the people who made
them. In the earliest days strong women frequently produced and
directed what they also wrote and starred in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were allowed to work because there weren't great profits
to be made yet in that industry,'' said Dennis Doros, president of
Milestone, a distributor of classic films.
</P>
<P>
   Once the money got better in the 1930s, men asserted themselves
and professional life became more complicated for women like
Dorothy Davenport Reid, the producer and co-director of ``The Red
Kimona'' (1925), about a young girl who is tricked into becoming a
prostitute in New Orleans and murders her pimp.
</P>
<P>
   The Kino series includes five films, all of them preserved by
the motion picture department at the Library of Congress. The four
others are ``The Ocean Waif'' by Alice Guy-Blache, one of the first
directors of either sex, who had made more than 700 shorts and
features by 1916; ``49-17,'' a western satire by Ruth Ann Baldwin;
``Eleanor's Catch'' (1916), a two-reeler by Cleo Madison about
still another young woman done in by a lowdown man; and
``Hypocrites'' (1915), written, directed and produced by Lois
Weber.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague of Guy-Blache, Weber was known for her moral
crusades. In ``Hypocrites'' the subject was ``the naked truth'' as
envisioned by a hand-wringing religious ascetic and sculptor who,
inspired by a woman scampering in the buff, renders a nude statue
of same. On its unveiling, the good citizens, all cheats and
perverts, to judge by Weber's interpretation, are shocked.
</P>
<P>
   Notes on the cassette box call the film ``amazingly complex.''
Bizarre, too. ``Definitely off the wall,'' said Jessica Rosner of
Kino. ``That's real nudity. If you look closely, you can see
everything.'' In Boston, clothes had to be painted on the woman
before the film was distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The Milestone series moves on to the talkies with ``The Gay
Desperado'' (1936), starring Ida Lupino, and Mervyn LeRoy's
``Tonight or Never'' (1931), with Gloria Swanson as an opera diva
who has lost the passion for her work. But there are also Frances
Marion's silent ``Love Light'' (1921), with Mary Pickford as a
betrayed wife, a role intended to change her her little-girl image,
and two silent films by Nell Shipman, ``Back to God's Country''
(1919) and ``Something New'' (1920).
</P>
<P>
   Shipman, a conservationist, set her two films in northern Canada
and the Mojave desert, respectively. ``She did action films,''
Doros said. In ``Something New'' the heroine (Shipman), her
boyfriend and her collie, Laddie, escape mounted bandits across
rocky terrain in a Maxwell sedan, a forerunner of the sport utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the Milestone series, call (800) 603-1104.
For the Kino tapes, call (800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   HIGH FIDELITY
</P>
<P>
   As the manager of Championship Vinyl, a Chicago record store,
Rob (John Cusack) is so immersed in pop culture that he gives the
most important events in his life hit-parade rankings. At No. 5 in
his former-girlfriend ratings, Laura (Iben Hjejle) joins a string
of vibrant women (Shannon Stillo, Joelle Carter, Catherine
Zeta-Jones and Lili Taylor) in Stephen Frears' fine-tuned
adaptation of Nick Hornsby's novel. ``Even more than the book,''
Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times, ``the movie evokes the
turmoil of urban single life with a quirky mixture of confessional
poignancy and dry, self-deflating humor.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000. Touchstone. $107.37; DVD, $32.99. 113 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   28 DAYS
</P>
<P>
   A New York writer (of what we're never told), Gwen Cummings
(Sandra Bullock) lives fast and drunkenly until a car crash lands
her in a rehabilitation center called Serenity Glen. Deprived of
alcohol and her Vicodin, Gwen gets mighty cranky with her counselor
(Steve Buscemi), but later settles into her four-week stay with a
choppy series of seriocomic bits that lurch between sitcom-y
silliness and soap-opera schmaltz. Before long a film that starts
with promise ``skids out of control and begins to weave around as
unsteadily as its central character does'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 103 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ME MYSELF I
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a fairy godmotherly intercession, Pamela Drury (Rachel
Griffiths), a lonely single woman approaching 40, gets to live the
life she might have pursued as the wife of Robert Dickson (David
Roberts), the true love she left 13 years earlier. Yes, those three
demanding children are hers now, as is all the dirty laundry. Sex
with Robert is fine and another love interest appears for Pamela,
played by Griffiths with a fine, high-strung intelligence. But
while Pip Karmel's film maintains a comfortable balance between
fantasy and realism, it ``isn't much more than a Cosmo girl's
daydream'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.99. 104 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   A MAP OF THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   One day a beleaguered school nurse and farm wife named Alice
Goodwin (Sigourney Weaver) loses track of a friend's child who
drowns in a pond on the Goodwin land. Without dwelling on tragedy,
the story turns to the rogue self-destructiveness it unleashes in
Alice, who eventually ends up in jail and turns coldly critical of
her own life with her husband (David Strathairn). But Scott
Elliott's film, adapted from Jane Hamilton's novel, ``would have
been better had it clung to that toughness, rather than showing how
Alice's stay in jail makes jail a better place'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. USA. $56.49; DVD, $24.95. 125 minutes. R. Release date:
Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   BEST RENTALS
</P>
<P>
   Video's current top three renters, ``Erin Brockovich,'' ``The
Cider House Rules'' and ``Reindeer Games,'' played on thousands of
theater screens. Here are a few examples from Video Business
magazine's list of best renters among films that played on 475
screens or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   TITUS. Julie Taymor's film turns Shakespeare's bloody tale into
a fluid time-traveling fantasia of violence and revenge that has
the look of a sophisticated video game. 1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD,
$34.98. 160 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS DON'T CRY. A best renter since April, Kimberly Pierce's
film stars Hilary Swank as Teena Brandon, a lanky high school girl
who turns her name around and becomes a boy in the small town of
Falls City, Neb. 1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. R.
</P>
<P>
   GUN SHY. Ever since the federal agent Charlie Mayo (Liam Neeson)
was tortured face down in a pile of watermelon, he has been trying
to get his nerve back. 2000. Hollywood. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 102
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRAIGHT STORY. The elderly Alvin Straight (Richard
Farnsworth) decides to drive his lawn mower from Iowa to Wisconsin
to see his estranged brother (Harry Dean Stanton). Directed by
David Lynch, believe it or not. 1999. Disney. $104.16. 111 minutes.
Closed captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   HOLY SMOKE. The headstrong Ruth Barron (Kate Winslet) proves
more than a match for the ``cult exiter'' (Harvey Keitel) hired by
her family to break her away from her Indian guru. 1999. Miramax.
$104.16; DVD, $29.99. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   MANSFIELD PARK. Treated like a poor relation, Fanny Price
(Frances O'Connor) makes her mark on the estate of the pompous
slave trader Sir Thomas Bertram (Harold Pinter). 1999. Miramax.
$104.16; DVD, $29.99. 110 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
