A5445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      09-14 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO SAYS PLAYS DON'T PAY? ITEMS ON `THE UNEXPECTED MAN,' `THE
DINNER PARTY,'   `THE BEST MAN,' `THE TALE OF THE ALLERGIST'S
WIFE,' `SEUSSICAL,' `REFERENCES TO SALVADOR DALI MAKE ME HOT,'
`JESUS HOPPED THE A TRAIN,' AND `COBB.' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE MCKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing a winning streak from last year, when the
plays ``Copenhagen,'' ``Dirty Blonde,'' and ``True West'' all did
big business, two new dramatic entries were ringing up impressive
numbers at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   The first was the Off Broadway production of ``The Unexpected
Man,'' at the Promenade Theater. The play, by Yasmina Reza, author
of the Broadway hit ``Art,'' racked up some $55,000 on Monday, its
first full day of sales. Tuesday's take was $63,000. By Wednesday
the daily tally topped $75,000, all before the show has run a
single advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   All of which left the show's producers as happy _ and bewildered
_ as lottery winners. ``If I could tell you with confidence why
these things happen,'' said Ben Sprecher, one of the producers, ``I
would only produce shows where this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot ticket could be attributed to the popularity of ``Art,''
or to the appeal of the play's two stars, Eileen Atkins and Alan
Bates, who play strangers on a train. Whatever the reason, the
early take will surely help mitigate some of the expense from the
production's elaborate design, which includes some four tons of
gravel and a suspended glass floor. The sales will also probably
fan speculation that ``Man'' might jump to Broadway if the 399-seat
Promenade proves too small to accommodate audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man'' wasn't the only play that got out of the gate quickly
this week. ``The Dinner Party,'' the new comedy from Neil Simon,
also posted impressive first-day sales, taking in more than
$100,000 on Monday. It joins two other Broadway plays with good to
great sales: ``The Best Man,'' whose producers say has a $1.2
million advance, and ``The Tale of the Allergist's Wife,'' which is
nearing the $2 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, none of the productions _ except ``Tale,'' which had
an acclaimed Off Broadway run last spring _ have met the New York
critics, and advances can evaporate as quickly as they came, if new
sales don't materialize to refill the till.
</P>
<P>
   THING 1 AND THING 2
</P>
<P>
   Revisions of the forthcoming Broadway musical ``Seussical'' were
under way in Boston this week, with a wide range of tweaks and
structural changes, primarily in the second act and primarily to
clarify the musical's story.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Weissler, one of the show's producers, said revamping was
commonplace for a new musical. ``I've never done a show out of town
that didn't require changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the changes were being mulled well before Boston critics
gave the show mixed notices last week. Two of next week's
performances were canceled to allow time for rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Weissler dismissed rumors that David Shiner, who plays the Cat
in the Hat, would be replaced, though he said some of Shiner's
blocking had been altered to gel with the show's overall tone.
``David brings an edge to the show,'' Weissler said, ``and a
certain artistic danger.''
</P>
<P>
   `I'M A BIG GIRL'
</P>
<P>
   When producers first began to call Rosie Perez several years ago
to offer her roles onstage, her reaction wasn't exactly what they
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' she said. ``I felt I was nowhere near ready.''
</P>
<P>
   But last spring George C. Wolfe, the artistic director of the
Public Theater, found a part for which he felt Perez might be
perfect. His only worry was it might be ``too weird'' for her.
Again her response was something of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Don't insult my intelligence, George,''' Perez
recalled, with a laugh. ``I'm a big girl.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Perez will appear next spring in the premiere of
``References to Salvador Dali Make Me Hot,'' a surreal-sounding
play by Jose Rivera that features actors in the characters of the
moon and a coyote. Perez will play an unhappy wife opposite John
Ortiz, the rising actor who will also be seen this fall in ``Jesus
Hopped the A Train.'' (See below.) Performances for ``Dali'' are to
begin in March.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 36, a Brooklyn native whose only other New York stage
experience was a short stint in ``The Vagina Monologues,'' said she
was still nervous about her debut. But she added that acting in New
York was what she wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do L.A., but I have too little patience,'' she
said, ``and too much attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOORAY FOR HOLLYWOOD  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Off Off Broadway companies are learning how nice it
can be to have well-known, and well-connected, friends.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the Melting Pot theater, which confirmed this week
that its production of ``Cobb,'' the 1989 Lee Blessing drama about
Ty Cobb, would move to a commercial run at the Lucille Lortel
Theater in Greenwich Village. Performances begin in late October.
</P>
<P>
   The move is being financed largely by Kevin Spacey, who saw the
show last May then paid for a two-week extension for the production
and urged other producers to take a look. He had originally come to
see ``Cobb'' because it starred Matthew Mabe, who was an understudy
last year in ``The Iceman Cometh,'' in which Spacey played the
central role.
</P>
<P>
   Across town the Labyrinth Theater Company was also preparing for
its first commercial transfer: ``Jesus Hopped the A Train,'' the
prison drama by Stephen Adly Guirgis about a pair of Rikers Island
thugs.
</P>
<P>
   The production had short run over the summer but has since been
optioned by two commercial producers, Ron Kastner and Roy Gabay,
who have a professional connection to the show's director, Philip
Seymour Hoffman. Kastner was the lead producer of last spring's
runaway hit ``True West,'' in which Hoffman received a Tony
nomination for his performance. Gabay was that show's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial run is to begin previews on Nov. 21 and open a
week later at the East 13th Street Theater in the East Village, the
home of the Classic Stage Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, 33, joined that company about five years ago after
doing a production of ``The Merchant of Venice'' with Ortiz in
Chicago. Last year he directed ``In Arabia, We'd All Be Kings,''
also by Guirgis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his writing has gotten a lot stronger,'' Hoffman said.
``And as he matures, I think the whole company matures. And I think
it's a great kind of evolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
