<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISNEY-WEB-NYT &LR;      09-14 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TO INTRODUCE A REVAMPED GO.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go.Com is starting up again after a nine-month pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   Go, which was Walt Disney Co.'s attempt to build an Internet
portal to take on the likes of Yahoo, will start testing a new
design starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For users, it's a much leaner model, focused almost entirely on
searching, rather than the complex, all-purpose vehicle of Go's
previous design. As a business, think NASCAR, not Formula One, as
the site is covered with more and bigger ads than any of its
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Go.Com _ and the broader concept of the Go Network linking all
of Disney's online efforts _ was started with great fanfare in
December 1998. Disney owned ESPN.Com, the top-rated sports side;
Disney.com, the No. 1 site for children; ABCNews.com, the No. 3
news site; and a controlling interest in Infoseek, a popular search
engine and portal.
</P>
<P>
   Disney figured that all of its content, combined with promotion
on ABC television network and other properties, would give Go a
lift that Yahoo and the others did not have. Although Go vaulted to
No. 6 in the ratings it has lost audience share as Yahoo, America
Online and Microsoft's MSN have grown briskly.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is hardly alone in finding the portal business to be
difficult. Next Month, NBC's internet affiliate is expected to
introduce its new redesigned portal, NBCi.Com, with a focus on
automatically filtering information from the Internet to meet each
user's interests.
</P>
<P>
   For Disney, one of the biggest changes is that its various sites
are not trying as hard to promote their corporate cousins. No
longer will every page of every service have links to Disney.com,
ESPN.Com, and so on. Nor will promotions on television for, say
ABC.com, refer to it as part of the Go Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Go Network is not something that resonated with
consumers,'' said Steve Bornstein, the longtime president of the
ESPN cable network that Disney assigned last year to run its
Internet Group. That approach, moreover, had made Go's competitors,
like Yahoo and America Online, reluctant to provide links to
Disney's sports, news and kids sites.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there has been a focus on creating new formats for
advertising that are more effective than the rectangular ad banners
that dominate most web sites. Banner prices have been falling
sharply, as advertisers find their effectiveness to be modest.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has created a rectangular unit, much the same shape as a
television screen, that has 30 percent greater area than a banner
and will be placed at the top of the front screen of Go.Com and its
other services.
</P>
<P>
   The Go.Com service itself has been streamlined to eliminate vast
sections of the site including ``channels'' about a wide range of
topics and de-emphasize other features like chat rooms. Instead,
the vast bulk of the site will be focused delivering answers for
queries typed into the web search box.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in addition to a banner advertisement, there are three
new bigger advertisements with technology that let the ad be more
interactive and related to the user's search. On a search for ski
resorts, for example, L.L. Bean could offer links to it's three
hottest selling sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   Disney hopes advertisers will pay $65 to $85 per thousand
impressions for these units, compared to $10 per thousand for its
current banners. And of course it hopes revenue will rise even more
than that because it has far more advertisements on a page than it
used to.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors say this strategy may not be all it's cracked up
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may sell six ads but that doesn't mean that people click
on any more of them,'' said George Bell, chief executive of Excite
(at)Home. He said his company's Excite portal tried pages with more
advertising, but all it did was reduce the average number of
responses each advertiser received. ``We sold more units, but the
advertisers were displeased,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
