<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DOCUDRAMAS15-COX     09-14 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCUDRAMAS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox Family's Elian movie Sunday night
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like only last month that Elian Gonzalez was big news.
Actually, it was 11 weeks ago that the boy and his father returned
to Cuba, effectively ending the saturation news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven weeks may be a long time by CNN or Internet standards,
but it's blazingly fast for filming and editing a two-hour movie.
On Sunday, Fox Family Channel runs a new TV movie, ``The Elian
Gonzalez Story'' (8 p.m., 487630).
</P>
<P>
   Elian doesn't hold the record, though. That goes to the Amy
Fisher trifecta of docudramas in 1993 and ``Ambush in Waco,'' both
of which ran within about a month of the news events. And it's hard
to measure how fast CBS moved on its JonBenet Ramsey four-hour
movie in February, which aired even though her murder remains
unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some major news events and how fast they became
TV movies:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Elian Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   Start: November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   End: June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   TV movies: ``The Elian Gonzalez Story,'' (left) Sunday on Fox
Family Channel. CBS has its own version in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Three months (Fox); five months (CBS).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O.J. Simpson
</P>
<P>
   Start: Nicole Brown and Ron Goldman murdered June 1994.
</P>
<P>
   End: It will never be over; Simpson was found not guilty October
1995.
</P>
<P>
   TV movies: Fox aired ``The O.J. Simpson Story'' in January 1995
while his criminal trial was just beginning. Another movie, ``An
American Tragedy,'' is in production for November on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Seven months (Fox, from time of murder); five years, 10
months (CBS, from time of verdict).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  David Koresh
</P>
<P>
   and the FBI standoff
</P>
<P>
   with the Branch Davidians
</P>
<P>
   Start: The stand-off began in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
   End: April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   TV movie: ``Ambush in Waco,'' NBC, May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Time: One month.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JonBenet Ramsey
</P>
<P>
   murder case
</P>
<P>
   Start: December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   End: None yet.
</P>
<P>
   TV movie: ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,'' February 2000 on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Three years, two months (from time of murder).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tonya Harding
</P>
<P>
   vs. Nancy Kerrigan
</P>
<P>
   Start: Harding associates attacked Kerrigan in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   End: Kerrigan won silver medal, Harding self-destructed at
February 1994 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   TV movie: ``Tonya and Nancy: The Inside Story,'' April 1994 on
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Two months.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Atlanta Child Murders
</P>
<P>
   Start: 1979.
</P>
<P>
   End: Wayne Williams was convicted in February 1982.
</P>
<P>
   TV movies: February 1985 on CBS and July 2000 on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Three years (CBS) and 18 years, five months (Showtime).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amy Fisher,
</P>
<P>
   the ``Long Island Lolita''
</P>
<P>
   Start: Fisher shot Mary Jo Buttafuoco May 1991.
</P>
<P>
   End: Pleaded guilty December 1992.
</P>
<P>
   TV movies: Three network movies within one week in January 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Less than a month
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Preppy Murder
</P>
<P>
   Start: Robert Chambers killed Jennifer Levin in Central Park in
August 1986.
</P>
<P>
   End: Chambers pleaded guilty to manslaughter March 1988.
</P>
<P>
   TV movie: ``The Preppy Murder,'' September 1989 on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Time: 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Baby Jessica in the well
</P>
<P>
   Start and end: October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   TV movie: ``The Baby Jessica Story,'' May 1989 on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Time: One year, seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
