<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5450 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GAY-BLOOD-DONORS15-CO     09-14 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-BLOOD-DONORS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hearings to decide if gays can give blood
 &HT;    By Gracie Bonds Staples
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For as long as he could remember, Jim Marks had made it his
civic duty to donate blood at least once a year. Then the rules
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that gay men were not allowed to give blood no matter
what their HIV status was, so it became less of a priority for me
then,'' Marks said this week.
</P>
<P>
   But with the development of improved AIDS tests and a recent
rise in HIV cases among heterosexuals, federal officials will
consider today whether to modify the lifetime ban on blood
donations from gay men.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration's blood products advisory
committee will hear testimony and discuss recommendations. There is
no timetable on when members will vote. The committee concluded in
December 1997 that the ban should be relaxed, but it was dissuaded
by federal blood experts urging caution.
</P>
<P>
   Gay men have been forbidden from donating blood if they have had
sex with a male since 1977, once considered the starting date of
the deadly virus. The FDA imposed the ban in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, deputy director of AID Atlanta, a nonprofit organization
that serves HIV and AIDS clients, and others say that no one knew
enough about the AIDS virus then, so the ban served a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it first went into effect it made sense,'' said Philip
Rafshoon,owner of the Outwrite Bookstore and Coffee House in
Atlanta. ``But times have changed, medical knowledge has changed
and the policy should reflect that. Today there are plenty of
screening tests they can do so there's really no reason to have
this antiquated policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue becomes especially important because demand for blood
is outpacing donations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some blood banks remain cautious about modifying the ban.
Officials estimate that blood donations would increase by only 1
percent if the ban were relaxed, but the small number of
HIV-infected donations entering blood banks could rise by 1,200
units. That would put more pressure on tests to catch bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued Thursday by the American Red Cross, said the
organization ``cannot change its procedures in a way that would
result in increased numbers of infectious donations in our blood
supply. If the Public Health Service could assure the American Red
Cross that introducing previously deferred donors into the donor
pool could be accommodated without increasing risk, we would
support appropriate actions to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Blood Banks has urged the FDA to
lift the ban on gay males who have not had sex within a year of
their donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest window we know to detect the virus is a year,''
said Karen Shoos Lipton, the association's chief executive. ``The
science is there.''
</P>
<P>
   And The Committee of 10,000, a group for hemophiliacs who
contracted HIV through blood donations, has also abandoned support
for the lifetime ban. The group now favors a five-year ban.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Gair, chief operating officer of LifeSouth Community
Blood Centers based in Gainesville, Fla., said he has not yet seen
anything that would support loosening the restriction. LifeSouth
has 10 regional collection centers, including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say that that might not come forth (at the
committee hearing),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gair added that while he doesn't feel the industry discriminates
against any group, it does discriminate against anyone who might be
in a high risk group .
</P>
<P>
   ``You might be deferred and deemed ineligible as a donor for any
number of reasons, not just your sexual orientation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before donating, a potential donor must answer a battery of
questions. Men are asked whether they have had sex with a male
since 1977, to determine if the donor might pose a risk for
infectious disease. If the donor answers yes, he is sent home and
entered on a national ``deferral'' database of people banned for
life from donating. The same is true for other high risk groups
such as intravenous drug users, prostitutes and people with
hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed, however, is HIV rates among gay men have
declined. Heterosexuals now make up more than half of new HIV
cases. Blood tests also have become more precise, allowing for
detection of the virus' genetic material after as little as 20
days. A decade ago, tests looked for antibodies to HIV, which could
develop months after infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that while gay men continue to account for the
majority of AIDS cases in the U.S., the numbers among women and
heterosexuals is rising dramatically and, in particularly, among
minorities,'' said Peter Velasco, director of communications for
the National Minority AIDS Council. ``We feel to exclude gay men
not only discriminates but also creates a false sense of
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Graham, executive director of the AIDS Survival Project, a
nonprofit AIDS advocacy organization in Atlanta, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time, science has clearly proven that sexual
orientation has nothing whatsoever to do with HIV transmission,''
said Graham. ``As an HIV-negative gay man, I personally feel that
it is my civic duty to donate blood and I have not been able to do
that my entire adult life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists across the country say the ban should be lifted
completely. They note that the FDA imposes only a one-year ban on
women who have had sex with gay men and on men who have had sex
with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``But yet we're being told we can't donate blood because of our
sexual orientation,'' said Marks. ``It's like saying you can't give
blood because you have red hair.''
</P>
<P>
   As of June 2000, 311 people in Georgia had contracted the virus
through blood, or 1.4 percent of the 22,011 reported AIDS cases in
the state. Nationally, an estimated 18 pints of HIV-infected blood
are transfused into patients every year, which works out to a risk
of one in 675,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short as we are on blood, we want to include as many people as
we can safely include, but at the same time we need to ... satisfy
the recipient that we've done everything we can to ensure the
safety of the blood,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Lennox, associate professor
of medicine in the division of infectious disease at Emory
University School of Medicine. ``That's a delicate balancing act.''
</P>
<P>
   He has mixed feelings about changing the ban. The issue, Lennox
said, is how likely is someone to be carrying an undetected viral
infection that would harm the blood recipient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee will have to decide if they want to single out
certain groups to be at greater risk based solely on their sexual
preference or whether behavior is a more reasonable marker for
risk,'' he said. ``If you want maximum safety of blood supply,
you'd want people who are not IV drug users and who are not
promiscuous. To me those criteria would not rule out many gay
men.''
</P>
<P>
   News services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: Food and Drug Administration: www.fda.gov
</P>
<P>
   Gracie Bonds Staples writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
