<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIRARD-DESIGN-REVIEW-     09-14 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRARD-DESIGN-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOWMAN WHO TURNED INTERIORS INTO ATMOSPHERES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ind., Ill., N. M., Italy, Sweden)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and NYT12 moved on 9/13 with GIRARD-DESIGN
to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRACE GLUECK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ebullient architect and designer Alexander Girard
(1907-1993) once declared himself more interested in atmospheres
than in buildings. Atmospheres are what his work is about. A
designer of fabrics, graphics, interiors, furniture, tableware,
radio cabinets and much else, he brought to his creations a vivid
sense of civilized living with more than a touch of panache.
</P>
<P>
   He devised a home of elegant yet inviting spaces for the J.
Irwin Miller family in Columbus, Ind. (1955-58), served up a
brilliant medley of Latin American motifs for the New York
restaurant La Fonda del Sol (1961) and from the 1950s to the early
70s designed more than 300 fabrics and wallpapers for the textile
division of the Herman Miller (no relation to J. Irwin) Furniture
Co. that pulse with color and rhythmic patterns. His whimsical,
sometimes flamboyant sensibility permeated everything he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Opulent Eye of Alexander Girard,'' at the Cooper-Hewitt
National Design Museum through March 18, is the first comprehensive
show devoted to Girard, who seems to have lacked the recognition
accorded his colleagues Eero Saarinen, Charles and Ray Eames and
George Nelson. It can be argued that Girard was basically a
middlebrow designer, less a theorist and inventor than they were,
and more involved with showmanship. His forte was fabrics and
interiors, domestic and commercial. The few pieces of furniture he
designed for the airport waiting rooms of Braniff International
Airways in 1966 seem timorous and derivative.
</P>
<P>
   But spontaneity and joy were hallmarks of his work, and there is
no denying that over all it has had an influence, even among
present-day practitioners. ``He has urged each of us toward a more
personal and expressive way of life,'' wrote the fabric designer
Jack Lenor Larsen in Design Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   Well organized by Donald Albrecht, adjunct curator for special
projects, the show is a packed but lively installation. It displays
fabrics, sketches, collages, interiors, exteriors, furnishings,
tableware, graphic designs and other Girardiana, including a group
of rather kitschy dolls he designed. Here, too, are photographs and
films on his work, along with many examples of the folk art he
collected that often served as inspiration, as the show makes
clear.
</P>
<P>
   With modernism as his core belief, Girard _ known to colleagues
as Sandro _ saw himself as ``a reasonable and sane functionalist
tempered by irrational frivolity.'' He wanted home decor to be
accessible, affordable and personal. His contribution to
contemporary design was a freedom of approach that encompassed all
sorts of visual stimuli, from Italian stage sets to Mexican folk
art to motifs from modern technology. He made use of color,
pattern, texture and ornament with a vibrancy that seemed to catch
the beat of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   He pushed for convenience and informality by combining different
kinds of furnishings, accessories and tableware that avoided the
deadly matched look; devising walls for storage and display that
looked into other spaces; and inventing a cozy semienclosure known
as the ``conversation pit,'' a cushiony retreat that encouraged
sit-down talk in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Girard was very good at public areas, too, particularly
restaurants. The show presents examples of his interior done in Op
Art and Art Deco styles _ fabrics and furnishings in glorious black
and white, including tables in the form of petalled flowers _ for
L'Etoile'' (1965), a very smart but short-lived restaurant that
once inhabited the Sherry-Netherland Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But his greatest extravaganza was La Fonda del Sol, the Latin
American dining complex installed by Restaurant Associates in the
old Time and Life Building. Girard saluted its banquet of Latin
American foods with folk art and themes from the same culture. As
he did for L'Etoile, he designed La Fonda's total environment, from
the room's canopy, festooned with embroidered Colombian skirts, to
the folk dolls used as decoration, to the geometrically patterned
buttons on the waiters' jackets. The leitmotif, shown here, was a
great golden sun of hammered brass and antique glass that
majestically shone down on diners.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition devotes a good deal of space to Girard's fabric
designs, with an entire room for the textiles he did for Herman
Miller. Always abstract, to avoid the distortion that occurs when
representational images are subjected to the folds of hanging
cloth, the designs, often geometric, are sometimes derived from
folk art motifs. In their freshness of color and pattern they
exuberantly push the envelope of middle-class taste.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of his fabric designs are ``Manhattan''
(1958), a bouncy image of the skyline at night, and the intricate
``Cut-Out'' (1954-57), a drapery for the master bedroom of the
Miller house in Indiana. Although ``Cut-Out'' is flat, it combines
color and black shadow to give it the three-dimensional look of
sculpture. A more famous one is ``Feathers'' (1957), an overall
pattern of small diamonds in blue and mustard colors derived from
the plumage used in Peruvian and Hawaiian ceremonial cloaks.
</P>
<P>
   Girard's love of folkways and of theater apparently surfaced in
his childhood, with a fascination for Christmas nativity creches.
(An early acquisition is in the show.) Born in New York to an
American mother and an Italian father, he grew up in Italy and was
trained as an architect. He practiced in Rome for a while, but it
was a stint as a designer for the Nordiska department store in
Stockholm that put him in touch with the craft-based modernism
underlying his own style.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932 he returned to New York, where he did domestic interiors
and restaurants in a retro rococo mode, as several drawings in the
show attest. Five years later he and his wife, Susan, moved to
Detroit, then a budding design center, where they stayed for some
15 years before permanently settling into a historic adobe house in
Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1950s Girard's thinking in newer terms was bringing
him recognition. He packaged two of the influential ``Good Design''
exhibitions for the Museum of Modern Art and the Merchandise Mart
in Chicago, and a backlighted photograph of silhouetted objects he
arranged in the 1953 show makes a stunning wall in the exhibition.
In 1958 he did a spectacular showroom for Herman Miller in San
Francisco, using gold leaf, garish paint, a mirrored carousel and
theatrical lighting to highlight the Victorian excesses of the
building as a setting for displays of supercool '50s Miller
furniture, designed by others.
</P>
<P>
   Textiles and Objects, the Herman Miller showroom in Manhattan
that Girard designed in 1961, is on view in a specially
commissioned three-dimensional model. It displayed more than 100 of
his fabric designs, surrounded by bright arrangements of folkish
figures (designed by Girard's brother Tunsi, and others), mirrors,
pillows and other domestic accessories.
</P>
<P>
   If Girard was not one of the real heavyweights in American
design, he was one of its liveliest figures, as this show happily
affirms. A nice endpiece to the exhibition, incidentally, is the
Cooper-Hewitt's tiny Design Museum Cafe, adorned with overhead
placards bearing quotes about Girard from colleagues and friends.
They were designed in a playful spirit by the graphic artist
Deborah Sussman, a colleague and longtime friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
