<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SPORTS, ALL THE TIME, A WORLD AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ This really is the other side of the world. Been here
for four days and not one person has asked about Bernard Gilkey,
Rico Brogna, or Tebucky Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 2000 Olympics, where the buses aren't running on
time and cab drivers are upset that there's not much business
(Atlanta redux). Drug allegations, fat cat kickbacks, ticket
fiascos, and political protests still dog the International Olympic
Committee (Atlanta again), but the good people of Sydney plan to
enjoy themselves for these Games.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be 110,000 at Olympic Stadium Friday night and more
than 3.5 billion folks around the globe will watch the Parade of
Nations fill an infield wide enough to accommodate four supersonic
aircraft. Aussie basketball star Andrew Gaze (who played at Seton
Hall) will carry the flag for the 600-strong local team and we're
bound to see Olivia Newton-John sometime during the night.
</P>
<P>
   What will be the signature moment of these Olympics? Will it be
Marion Jones's fifth gold medal or a heroic vault by a pixie
gymnast with a wounded foot? Will there be a Beamonesque leap into
history or a tragic dropped baton? Will the US men's basketball
team finally get a game and survive a scare? Will any Cubans
defect?
</P>
<P>
   The questions will all be answered between now and Oct. 1, and
let the record state that the locals have done everything possible
to accommodate visitors from afar. They've even painted ``look
right'' at busy corners and crosswalks so that Americans won't be
run over by vehicles driving on the ``wrong side'' of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong side.'' There I go again. Ugly American that I am, it's
traditional to view anything different as incorrect. In an effort
to compensate for this skewered thinking, I've been wondering about
the whole Down Under thing. A Foster's beer ad claims that the
world is round and that Australia is actually on top. And why not?
Who decided what constitutes the top and bottom of a round object?
Are there not viewing areas in outer space from which Los Angeles
would appear to be an east coast city in South America in the
Southern Hemisphere?
</P>
<P>
   These are the things one thinks about during a 26-hour flight.
Most American athletes left the US weeks ago to compensate for jet
lag and time change. It takes a few days to adjust and woe is the
competitor who makes no allowance.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Boston Saturday afternoon, I set my watch 15 hours ahead
to Sydney time _ Sunday morning. Conveniently enough, I had the
bulldog edition of the Sunday Globe (which is printed early
Saturday) in my lap. So there I was, a modern time traveler, flying
out of Logan on Saturday, reading a Sunday newspaper, bound for a
place where it was already Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will take advantage of this time difference by furnishing no
live coverage of the Games. Everything you watch happened Thursday.
These are the Memorex Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney in 2000 so far reminds me a little of America during the
Eisenhower administration. You see kids in caps pushing barrels
that have upside-down pushbrooms attached. There's the usual
Olympic security (no trash bins at the Olympic train station _
probably a response to the Atlanta bombing), but folks are not
gripped with the fear of terrorism that has haunted other Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Melbourne Olympics of 1956 (Bill Russell and K.C. Jones won
gold) were held in December, which is the beginning of Australian
summer. These Games come at the end of winter and beginning of
Australian spring. The weather has been sunny, dry, cool at night,
and generally spectacular, though high winds may impact some
events.
</P>
<P>
   The pool is the place to be in these early days. We wait to see
if American Gary Hall can win his duel with Russian Alexander
Popov, while Australian teen sensation Ian Thorpe threatens to
change the sport. The swimming venue seats 17,500 and has a low
ceiling that will hold the considerable noise.
</P>
<P>
   Know this: when they drain the Sydney International Aquatic
Centre, the water will flow clockwise (I checked this already in my
hotel bathtub). It's the Coriolis effect, another reminder that
we're in the other half of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
