<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH15-COX     09-14 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ngoma's days of glory are upon him
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ He was 12 years old and living in Lukasa,
Zambia, during the 1992 Olympics, but that spectacle from the
Summer Games of Barcelona left an indelible mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sitting in front of a television set and watching a
broadcast of the Olympics,'' Wright State University swimmer and
Olympian Leonard Ngoma said. ``I didn't understand much of what the
announcer said _ it was in English _ but I remember I kept hearing
`16 Days of Glory.' It sounded magical. And I started thinking I
wanted that. I wasn't quite sure how, but one day I wanted to be
part of the `16 Days of Glory.'''
</P>
<P>
   As the years went by and those flickering TV images faded, they
were eclipsed by a reality that Ngoma understood only too well.
Instead of 16 Days of Glory, he had four years of hurt and
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, both of Ngoma's parents died of malaria. Soon after, he
left his home and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really was nothing for me,'' he said. ``I wanted
something more, but I didn't know where to turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee _ which has a program to
nurture Olympians in underdeveloped nations _ soon provided a road
map. Ngoma was a junior swimmer of some note in Zambia, and the IOC
provided the initial funds to send him to the United States. He
joined the high school swim team at Jacksonville's Bolles School,
one of the premier high school programs in the nation, and from
there _ thanks to an assistant coach with ties to Wright State _
Ngoma ended up with an invitation to join coach Matt Liddy's swim
program at WSU last season.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was contingent on Zambia _ as required by the IOC _
funding part of the college costs. Just when things were looking up
_ Ngoma had swum an Olympic qualifying time at the All-Africa
Championships in Johannesburg, South Africa _ he was hit with what
seemed to be a final KO punch.
</P>
<P>
   Zambia _ where the economy is in a downward spiral thanks in
part to the decline in the country's copper mining _ had no money
to spare. Because Liddy already had distributed his scholarships,
it looked as if Ngoma might be headed back home _ his finances
gone, his dream dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then out of the blue, he found a guardian angel in the City of
Dayton, which just so happens to have a developmental partnership
with Lukasa.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Valerie Lemme _ after some conversations with Liddy
_ knew what Ngoma could achieve with some help. More importantly,
she knew what he'd go back to if no one stepped in. She's been to
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very difficult there,'' Lemme said. ``Some 80 to 90
percent of the people live in abject poverty. Schooling from grades
K through 12 is not free. Many people live in overcrowded homes
without water or electricity. A lot of traffic is actually by foot.
For a lot of young people, there just isn't much opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Lemme convinced various charitable
organizations to help fund Ngoma's stay at Wright State. The
20-year-old completed his freshman season with the Raiders last
year, got modest results and that kept his Olympic opportunity
alive. Since Zambia hadn't paid for his schooling, it was able to
come up with the $1,800 airfare to get him to Sydney, where Tuesday
_ when he dives into the pool for the 200-meter breaststroke _
he'll become his nation's first Olympic swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, he will be on the global stage, when he and seven other
Zambian athletes in their green blazers march into the massive
Olympic Stadium for the Opening Ceremonies of the 2000 Olympic
Games. In so doing, he'll join 11 other athletes with Miami Valley
ties who are competing in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Best known in Dayton is Tonja Buford-Bailey, the Meadowdale High
School graduate who will compete in her third straight Olympics.
She won a bronze medal in the 400 meter hurdles in Atlanta, the
same race Central State graduate Deon Hemmings _ who will compete
for her native Jamaica again these Games _ won gold.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other athletes linked to CSU also will be here. Former
Marauder basketball stars Maty M'Bengue and Marieme Lo, who now
works in the athletics department at WSU 0 will play basketball for
Senegal. CSU graduates Catherine Scott-Pomales and Beverly Grant
will run track for Jamaica, while current Marauder Vida Nsiah will
run sprints for Ghana. Former CSU sprinter Sayon Cooper will do the
same for Liberia, Neil De Silva will represent Trinidad and Tobago
and Ronald Promesse runs for St. Lucia.
</P>
<P>
   Sion Brinn, the newly hired Wright State assistant swim coach,
will be competing in his second Olympics. He's swimming relays for
Great Britain at these Games. Because of dual citizenship, he
competed for Jamaica in the 1996 Olympics and finished 12th in the
200 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Brinn's presence in Sydney is a plus for Ngoma. Because Zambia
has no swimming coach, Brinn has taken Ngoma under his wing here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if you'll find another college coach and one of his
athletes competing in the same sport at the Olympics,'' Liddy said.
``Imagine the two of them together on the pool deck in Sydney.
Wouldn't that make a good cover to our media guide?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Willy, the swim coach at Bolles when Ngoma arrived and
now a coach at the University of Florida, said the Zambian swimmer
is a boon to any swim program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team needs a Leonard Ngoma as a reality check,'' Willy
said. ``These days, you hear so much about athletes being pampered.
... But he's come from a place where there weren't many facilities
and he hadn't gotten a lot of instruction. For a while, he'd even
coached himself. It's good for (the other swimmers) to see someone
doing something positive, even though he's had things a whole lot
worse. Leonard's an inspiration to anyone who knows his story.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemme knows and agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our partnership with Zambia, we consider him one of
our own,'' Lemme said. ``We're proud of him for the way he's
overcome tremendous odds to get an education and advance his
swimming. He's really done something special.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Ngoma managed to make his own magic. He took four years
of hurt and uncertainty and managed to turn them into 16 Days of
Glory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
