<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-COVERAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NBC, DELAYED AIRING WILL ADD UP TO PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's simple math.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way anyone would spend $705 million for the rights to
the Summer Olympic Games and have them air live between 1 a.m. and
6 a.m., when only 9 percent of the nation's televisions are on.
</P>
<P>
   The taped versus live debate is not new, and frankly NBC Sports
chairman Dick Ebersol, whose network is covering the Sydney Games,
sounded tired of answering the same old question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the height of ugly Americanism to suggest that the
Olympics should revolve around the prime-time schedule in the
United States,'' Ebersol said during a recent teleconference. ``We
told everyone back in May that all of our coverage would be taped
because of the 15-hour time difference and our need to reach the
largest possible audience. We won't have any plausibly live
coverage or virtually live coverage. It's all taped.''
</P>
<P>
   All 441 1/2 hours spread over NBC and its two cable networks,
CNBC and MSNBC. The 279 hours of cable coverage, including 30
gold-medal finals, represent the first time the Olympics have been
televised on basic cable. Ebersol has predicted an average of about
17 million households watching all or part of the Olympic telecast
each night. In addition, NBCOlympics.com projects 10 million
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   On paper at least, the taped coverage, filled with athletes'
personal stories _ more than half from foreign countries for those
keeping track of network jingoism _ and features on Australian
life, coupled with a staggering amount of information on NBC's Web
site, is a perfect marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've chosen not to treat the Internet as an enemy, but
instead to embrace it,'' said David Neal, NBC's head of production.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for instance, NBCOlympics.com updated users with
the score of the American men's soccer team's game against the
Czech Republic. The fact that some knew before the game aired that
it ended in a 2-2 tie was not a bad thing. MSNBC showed the game
Wednesday night to kick off the network's coverage. Ebersol said
the game may get more viewers knowing the Americans put up a good
showing.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol, a passionate Olympics fan, said the Games are unlike
any other sporting event because viewers are, of course, interested
in the results, but they are also interested in the stories. ``The
journey is equally as compelling as the result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol learned his up close and personal style from pioneer
Roone Arledge during ABC's coverage of the 1972 Winter Games in
Innsbruck, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fundamental reason why we do it this way,'' Ebersol
said. ``The Olympics bring families together for a shared viewing
experience. That is a rarer and rarer occurrence today. But there
is a gap of knowledge about most Olympic sports and the people who
are competing in them. That's why when you broadcast these sports
outside of the Olympics, you're lucky to get a 3 rating. We aim to
get the largest possible audience. That means doing some
storytelling, and putting the Games on when it's convenient for the
viewers, which is certainly not in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Olympics, MSNBC's daily coverage will be from 10
a.m.-5 p.m. and CNBC's coverage from 5-9 p.m. On weekends, MSNBC's
coverage will be from 10 a.m.-4 p.m. and CNBC's from 4-9 p.m.
MSNBC's coverage is hosted by Jim Lampley and will focus on team
sports, including soccer, baseball, softball, and basketball. CNBC
has most of the boxing and will be hosted by Pat O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in coverage from anything that's ever preceded
it either here at NBC or on any other network is staggering,''
Ebersol said. ``We have more than double the total amount of
coverage we had in '96 and the most prime-time coverage _ 84 1/2
hours _ of any Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't mention the Canadian Broadcasting Company to Ebersol. CBC
is showing the Games live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coverage is better than theirs,'' Ebersol said. ``We have
more resources, more coverage, richer stories, and much more of a
commitment of showing viewers who the athletes are and the impact
they have had in their home countries. But people are certainly
free to wake up at 5 a.m. to watch CBC.''
</P>
<P>
   A true testament to the drawing power of the Olympics is the
fact that rival networks delayed the release of their new fall
shows until after the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate test, however, is whether professional football and
baseball will cut into NBC's expected Olympic ratings.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure, NBC reports it has sold $900 million in
advertising, all but assuring the network of earning a profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
