<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0915-COX     09-14 2548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Trial lawyer money to Democrats reviewed
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A trial lawyer at the center of a dispute with Texas over
tobacco litigation has given hundreds of thousands of dollars from
his law firm to the Democratic Party over the last four years since
Al Gore was asked to call him to seek a six-figure check. A Gore
aide said the vice president never made the phone call to Texas
trial lawyer Walter Umphrey. Gore was asked to make the call in
1995 by Democratic Party chairman Don Fowler at a time when they
were concerned with Republican legislation that would have put
limits on lawsuit awards. Democratic call sheets that recently have
been scrutinized by Justice Department investigators suggest Gore
and Fowler were asked to solicit Umphrey for contributions
beginning in late 1995.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH CRITICIZES GORE'S ALLEGED FUND-RAISING CALL
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush criticized Al Gore today over what he called
misuse of the White House to secure campaign contributions in 1995.
Bush said voters should elect a new administration to ``restore
honor and dignity'' to the Oval Office. Addressing a crowd of
National Guard members in Newport Beach, Calif., Bush also
criticized the Clinton administration for running down the
military. Bush also planned to visit schools, take in a county fair
and hobnob with donors during his 2 1/2-day visit to California _
his 15th in a year and the third since the GOP national convention
last month.
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S TIES TO VIOLENT-MOVIE PRODUCER DEFENDED
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign is defending his raising of millions of
dollars with the help of celebrities and movie moguls who put out
the kind of films he and running mate Joe Lieberman have
criticized. Republicans seized on his close association with movie
mogul Harvey Weinstein, whose company, Miramax, has released
violent films like ``Reservoir Dogs'' and ``Pulp Fiction.'' The
Democratic ticket has threatened new federal legislation or rules
against the entertainment industry within six months if it doesn't
stop marketing violent and sexual products to young people.
Nonetheless, Gore was to attend a fund-raiser tonight at New York's
Radio City Music Hall that Weinstein helped organize, capping a
week of fund-raising reaching $9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   GORE COMPUTERS STOLEN _ QUESTION IS WHY
</P>
<P>
   Someone broke into Al Gore's Midtown Manhattan campaign
headquarters and stole several computers containing confidential
information, according to WABC-TV and the ABC News Web site. The
question for investigators is whether the thief was interested only
in stealing pricey computers, or was someone looking for the
information they contained? The burglary took place on the 19th
floor of Number Two Penn Plaza. Campaign workers told New York City
detectives that three laptops and a Palm Pilot were stolen sometime
between 4 a.m. and 8 a.m. Wednesday. Investigators say the
computers contain detailed financial information about Gore's gala
fund-raiser at Radio City Music Hall tonight. ABC News said some of
it included personal details about contributors to the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   GORE HAMMERS AGAIN ON EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore spoke at a Manchester, N.H., middle school today,
continuing his focus on education. He said education issues provide
``one of the biggest differences in this election'' as he capped a
week of drawing contrasts with George W. Bush. Gore has argued
repeatedly that Bush would use up too much of a projected federal
surplus on tax cuts, leaving no money for bolstering schools. ``We
can't reform education with half an agenda,'' he said. ``We can't
make education our top priority if huge tax cuts for the wealthy
are already the first, second and third priority.'' Gore, who
revels in detailed policy talk, has focused on a specific aspect of
his education policy each day this week, and he presented the
entire package in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   OVERNIGHT STAYS FOR HILLARY CLINTON SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will soon release a list of overnight
guests at the White House and the Camp David presidential retreat
in response to suggestions that Hillary Clinton traded visits for
contributions to her Senate campaign, the White House said today.
``As soon as that list is ready and I have a chance to review it, I
will make it available,'' said White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart. Reporters sought the list to compare it to rosters of the
first lady's political supporters. Said Clinton: ``We have friends
and supporters come and spend time with us and spend the night with
us that we are getting to know and who like spending time with us.
I don't see what's news about that.''
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE MEETING AND MYSTERY PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the two presidential campaigns were meeting
today with the Commission on Presidential Debates to iron out
details for fall debates. And meanwhile, the FBI is reviewing a
package received by Tom Downey, an ex-congressman from New York who
has been helping Al Gore prepare for debates against George W.
Bush. Downey said the package contained documents and a videotape
apparently related to Bush's debate preparations. The commission
meeting got under way at midday today. Taking part for Gore were
campaign chairman William Daley, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman and
adviser Jim Johnson, while Bush was represented by campaign
chairman Don Evans, campaign manager Joe Allbaugh and adviser
Andrew Card.
</P>
<P>
   SPLIT DECISION IN NEW YORK DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton bested her opponent, Rick Lazio, 49 percent to
36 percent in their stormy New York Senate debate in Buffalo,
according to a quickie poll conducted for WCBS and the New York
Daily News. However, the newspaper's own panel of media experts
gave Lazio the edge, 57-50 percent, in a grading system based on
the candidates' presentations. In the debate, he called her
``Clintonesque,'' she linked him to Newt Gingrich, and both
candidates accused the other of having ``chutzpah.'' Afterward,
Lazio boasted to supporters, ``We New Yorkers don't back down from
a fight.'' Clinton told her backers she was relieved: ``It was my
first debate, and I feel like I survived.''
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN A LITTLE CLOSER TO THE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan inched closer to getting a $12.6 million check for
his Reform Party presidential campaign. The Federal Election
Commission rubber-stamped its decision to award Buchanan the
federal campaign funds at its meeting today, authorizing the
Treasury to issue a check. ``I'm feeling rich,'' said Buchanan's
sister and campaign chairwoman, Bay Buchanan. ``We're thrilled.
It's been a long time coming, but we're ready to get this campaign
kick-started.'' John Hagelin, who also had sought the money,
dropped his plans to appeal the FEC decision.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE BANS HAGELIN FROM PARTY NAME
</P>
<P>
   California Superior Court Judge James Wright has declared Pat
Buchanan the Reform Party's true presidential candidate, and
ordered Buchanan's Reform Party rival, John Hagelin, to stop
campaigning as the party's nominee. His supporters must also stop
promoting Hagelin as such, collecting and spending donations, and
operating its Web site. Hagelin said he'd honor that ruling, both
in California and nationwide. In the meantime, his lawyer said he
would seek to delay the force of the ruling while appealing it.
Hagelin said he'll continue to campaign as the Natural Law Party
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A NIXON COMES OUT FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Among the supporters who greeted George W. Bush in Monroe,
Wash., was Edward Nixon, younger brother of the late President
Richard Nixon. ``He's going to do fine,'' Nixon said of Bush, who
has been slipping in recent polls. ``My brother always said you
don't want to peak too early. Bush and his people have the means to
bring this thing together.'' Nixon, 70, is a retired geologist and
Navy veteran living in Lynnwood, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL TV STATIONS THE BIG ELECTION WINNER
</P>
<P>
   Political advertising may annoy some voters, but it's a cash cow
for local TV stations, which are expected to take in up to $1
billion from sale of political ads this year. That's double the
haul from 1996, said the Alliance for Better Campaigns, which
argues that all that money compels broadcasters to provide
candidates free time to talk about issues. ``The broadcasters don't
own the airwaves; the public does,'' said Walter Cronkite, former
CBS News anchor and honorary co-chairman of the Alliance. The group
advocates five minutes of candidate discourse a day in the 30 days
before Election Day. A study earlier this year found there to be
less than one minute.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN COVERAGE BLASTED
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney lashed out at news reporters. Speaking to a business
club during a swing through western Michigan, Cheney said the need
to produce stories for a growing number of Internet-based news
sites and 24-hour cable TV news channels apparently has changed the
way campaigns are covered. ``So you end up with absolutely trivial
issues dominating an entire (news) cycle or maybe two cycles _ an
entire 24 or 48 hours _ that really have nothing to do with the
election or the fate of America or how the campaign ought to be
decided,'' he said. ``The way that works serves to distract
everybody and to take the focus off the basic issues that we ought
to be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   A CHANGING FLORIDA NOW RATED A TOSS-UP
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is scrambling to salvage his campaign for 25
electoral votes in Florida, a Republican-trending state where he
once led comfortably, but is now in a dead heat with Al Gore. The
two are competing in a Florida that has changed dramatically in the
last decade. The population in the nation's fourth largest state
has become older, more independent and more Hispanic. A new
Mason-Dixon poll confirmed the belief of both campaigns that the
race is tightening. The poll put Bush at 45 percent and Al Gore at
43_ a statistical dead heat. That same poll had given Bush an
8-point edge _ 47 percent to Gore's 39 percent _ in June.
</P>
<P>
   WON OVER ON ENDANGERED BIRDS, BUSH SAYS
</P>
<P>
   They don't have salmon in Texas, George W. Bush told local
conservationists at a campaign stop highlighting local
save-the-salmon efforts in rural Washington state. But Bush said
he's done his part to save the golden cheeked warbler, an
endangered bird found only in Texas that nests in cedar trees found
on his own 1,600-acre ranch in Crawford, Texas. ``A man from the
federal government came down to see me,'' Bush said. ``I was a
little suspicious frankly.'' The man _ Bush didn't say what agency
he was with _ told Bush that the government wanted to protect the
cedar trees to help save the birds. A strong advocate of property
rights, Bush nonetheless decided that preserving the fate of a
5-inch songbird species outweighed his concerns about intrusive
federal government practices. ``I agreed after listening to the
man,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   IN-HOUSE FUND-RAISING BY DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   With Election Day less than two months away, House Democratic
leaders have asked their colleagues for $5 million more to help
finance the fall campaign. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
(Mo.) and Rep. Patrick Kennedy (R.I.), chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, have received $1 million since
they began asking members a week ago, said DCCC spokesman Erik
Smith. The new effort is in addition to an earlier drive that
brought in $4.5 million from lawmakers. The House Democrats had
about $15 million more money in the bank as of June 30 than their
Republican counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDACY AS A DOOR-OPENER
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman told prominent Jewish leaders that he hopes his
candidacy opens doors for people from all walks of life. ``I'm here
for a principle _ the principle of inclusiveness and opportunity,''
he said at a fund-raiser in Brookline, Mass., near Boston.
Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, made his remarks at a $10,000-a-plate
fund-raising event at the home of Ahron Solomont, brother of former
Democratic National Committee finance chairman Alan Solomont.
Lieberman paraphrased John Kennedy, the first Roman Catholic
elected president, saying he hoped no one would vote for or against
him because of his religion.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH EXPANDS MESSAGE TEAM
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has added a Washington-based Republican
consultant, Ed Gillespie, to his communications team to help
sharpen his campaign message. Gillespie, 39, has been senior
adviser to House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, director of
policy and communications for the House Republican Conference, and
a senior staff member at the Republican National Committee. He was
one of six Washington advisers named by the Bush campaign earlier
this year when national Republicans complained that the
Austin-based Bush campaign was too insular.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-FORD REUNION
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney paid a call Wednesday on his old boss, former
President Gerald Ford, in a campaign swing through Grand Rapids,
Mich. Twenty-five years ago, Cheney, then 34, became Ford's White
House chief of staff. Warmly greeted by Ford and his wife, Betty,
outside the Gerald R. Ford Museum, on the banks of the Grand River,
Cheney said, ``It's fun just to come back and spend some time with
the president, get words of wisdom from somebody who has been where
I'm trying to go, as vice president.'' Cheney added that Ford was
``looking much better'' since his minor stroke last month at the
Republican convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   PAPA BUSH CHATS UP WITH IMUS
</P>
<P>
   Ex-President George Bush made a surprise call to the ``Imus in
the Morning'' radio show in New York where Don Imus has turned his
full satirical guns on Bush's son, George W., in recent weeks.
Calling from Kennebunkport, Maine, the elder Bush told Imus he had
just received a jar of the radio host's personal salsa. ``I haven't
felt that way since I threw up on the Japanese prime minister,''
Bush deadpanned. The former president invited Imus to his vacation
home for a horseback ride. Imus was seriously injured this summer
when a horse threw him. The horse's name, Bush said, is Subliminal.
Imus had a big laugh, and said later the ex-president ``was pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   FINAL DEBATE IN WASHINGTON STATE
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the Democratic nomination for senator
from Washington clashed at their final scheduled debate before next
Tuesday's primary. Speaking before the Rotary Club of Seattle,
state Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn and former Rep. Maria
Cantwell traded barbs over their records, Internet privacy issues
and Cantwell's largely self-financed and more lavish campaign
spending. But they also spent time criticizing the record of the
Republican incumbent, Slade Gorton, whom the primary winner will
take on in November. Senn identified protecting prescription drug
coverage for older Americans as her top legislative priority, while
Cantwell, a millionaire high-tech executive, singled out campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
