<SLUG> BC-MASKED-ADVOCACY-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME? IT DEPENDS ON WHICH GROUP IS WEARING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, Sept. 14, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 Art Advisory: With photo illustration (NNS5) For more information
about purchasing these photos call 202-383-7824. 
 By JENNIFER SCOTT CIMPERMAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) When the group Americans for Balanced Energy Choices
issued a news release last month, its prediction was a gloomy one:
potential electricity shortages, higher prices, a slowing economy.
</P>
<P>
   It said working families were canceling vacation plans because
of high gasoline costs. It said the high cost of electricity had
prompted large industrial facilities to limit production and lay
off workers.
</P>
<P>
   And the situation would get worse without improved national
energy policies, without ...
</P>
<P>
   Coal.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Americans'' in Americans for Balanced Energy Choices are
not what the name seems to imply _ regular folks who depend on
energy to earn a living and keep a family together. Rather, they
are large corporate interests: the U.S. coal industry, the
railroads that haul coal and the electric utilities that burn coal
to make electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ABEC, launched in April, is among the newest entrants in an
already crowded field of business groups using names with
``Americans,'' ``customers'' or ``coalition'' in an effort to
appear populist and reach consumers wary of corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   Such groups include Consumers' Voice, a group known for bashing
Ameritech Corp. (the Midwest Baby Bell that now is part of giant
SBC Communications Inc.). Consumers' Voice lists mostly community
organizations as members; it takes a call to its Indianapolis
office to learn that financial backing comes from long-distance
phone leviathan AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Customer Choice, another telephone industry
group, notes that its members are companies, although its news
releases don't specifically mention AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom Inc. and
other phone and cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say such groups can mislead consumers by failing to
disclose their financial interests in the issues they present.
</P>
<P>
   ``By putting in the word `consumer,' it makes them appear that
they are representing consumers rather than an industry group,''
said Roger Blackwell, professor of marketing at Ohio State
University and a marketing consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the word `American' is like waving the flag and hoping
that people stand up and salute. It would almost (appear) to be
un-American to be opposed to these organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Lucas, spokesman for Alexandria, Va.-based Americans for
Balanced Energy Choices, said the group's name accurately reflects
its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a group of Americans talking about an important issue _
balancing America's growing demand for electricity while protecting
the environment,'' Lucas said. ``It was a name for the group that
was truly at the heart of (its) mission.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hughes, who heads the environmental and consumer group
Citizen Power Inc., said groups like ABEC engage in
``greenwashing'' _ putting out only facts that support their
arguments while ignoring those that don't.
</P>
<P>
   He said the strong presence of environmental groups like Citizen
Power, which often appeared at Ohio legislative hearings last year
to support electricity deregulation, spurred the creation of
corporate-funded ``consumer'' groups in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   As the environmental movement gained strength in the last 10 to
15 years, target industries ``started getting more creative in how
to offset its influence,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Sierra Club spent almost $6 million on its
Environmental Public Education campaign last year, Lucas said
Americans for Balanced Energy Choices this year also plans to spend
``millions'' of dollars advertising its message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks may not like it, but they're looking through their
own political beliefs,'' Lucas said. ``This is an honest dialogue
with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, corporate coalitions gather to fight one specific issue,
for example electricity deregulation laws, then disband.
</P>
<P>
   United, group members can share the costs of advertising and
legal assistance, a must when fighting proposed legislation or
other regulations. While most companies already have their own
lobbyists who meet with politicians and other decision-makers
individually to push corporate causes, a large group of businesses
may pack more punch.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``The message becomes clearer the more groups you get to agree
on certain things,'' said Larry Stelzer, general counsel for the
Ohio Council of Retail Merchants and a former member of the
now-defunct Coalition for Choice in Electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus-based group fought for business-friendly provisions
in Ohio's electricity deregulation laws, passed last summer. The
group was open about its corporate membership, and Stelzer said
some lawmakers appreciated the ability to go to one business source
with questions rather than calling the CCE's 51 members _ mostly
trade groups _ individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real value is information,'' Stelzer said. ``You need
lawyers, consultants to bring evidence and information forward to
bolster your arguments. To that degree, it can be an expensive
proposition. (But) in the end, it gave us a better product for
legislators to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, not consumers, are the ultimate target of corporate
coalitions, said Mark Cooper of the Consumer Federation of America,
a group made up of state and federal consumer groups. He said
corporate-funded coalitions work to change public opinion so that
lawmakers won't feel sheepish when pressed to vote in companies'
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumers are not the ones the (groups) are trying to
mislead,'' said Cooper, CFA research director. ``It's policy
making. This is part of politics in 21st century America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some municipal and consumer groups have joined corporate-funded
``consumer'' coalitions, recognizing that businesses and consumers
can have compatible interests.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Affordable Electricity, which works for cheaper
wholesale electric rates for mostly corporate members, also
includes the National Association of Neighborhoods and the National
School Boards Association; lower wholesale rates could mean cheaper
heating or lighting bills for such groups.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' Voice, the AT&AMP;T-funded group, includes the Salvation
Army of Oklahoma and a homeless advocate as members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone should always ask where (groups') funding comes
from,'' Consumers' Voice Executive Director Robert K. Johnson said.
``At the same time, I don't think that's reason to discount the
message or the consumers that support us.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Balanced Energy Choices includes a low-income
housing advocate in St. Louis and ``people from all walks of
life,'' spokesman Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are always some folks who are going to be
skeptical,'' Lucas said. But ``it's just the facts, ma'am _
providing facts based clearly on government statistics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
