   ``The consumers are not the ones the (groups) are trying to
mislead,'' said Cooper, CFA research director. ``It's policy
making. This is part of politics in 21st century America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some municipal and consumer groups have joined corporate-funded
``consumer'' coalitions, recognizing that businesses and consumers
can have compatible interests.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Affordable Electricity, which works for cheaper
wholesale electric rates for mostly corporate members, also
includes the National Association of Neighborhoods and the National
School Boards Association; lower wholesale rates could mean cheaper
heating or lighting bills for such groups.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' Voice, the AT&AMP;T-funded group, includes the Salvation
Army of Oklahoma and a homeless advocate as members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone should always ask where (groups') funding comes
from,'' Consumers' Voice Executive Director Robert K. Johnson said.
``At the same time, I don't think that's reason to discount the
message or the consumers that support us.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Balanced Energy Choices includes a low-income
housing advocate in St. Louis and ``people from all walks of
life,'' spokesman Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are always some folks who are going to be
skeptical,'' Lucas said. But ``it's just the facts, ma'am _
providing facts based clearly on government statistics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
