A5465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PHILIPPINES-ECON-NYT &LR;      09-14 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINES FINANCIAL MARKETS TUMBLE AMID WORRIES ABOUT ECONOMY,
REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerns about rising unemployment, inflation and lawlessness in
the southern islands of the Philippines badly hurt the country's
financial markets Thursday, sending the value of its currency to
the lowest level since the depths of the Asian financial crisis of
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   As the government contemplates whether to use force against
Muslim rebels who this week conducted a second raid on a Malaysian
resort in search of people to kidnap, investors seem to be losing
their remaining faith in the ability of President Joseph Estrada's
administration to ensure economic security. The benchmark stock
index fell Thursday to a five-week low, and the Philippine peso
dropped at one point to its weakest level against the dollar in 32
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's low confidence in the system,'' said Gary del Rosario,
research chief at Salomon Smith Barney in Manila. ``It's getting
out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is building on the nation's central bank to halt the
peso's slide and keep inflation in check. Bank policy-makers plan
to meet on Friday to decide whether to raise interest rates a
second time in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and economists worry that further rate increases
may only dampen growth. Some are urging the bank to strengthen the
currency's value by buying Philippine pesos with the nation's
dollar reserves. The central bank governor, Rafael Buenaventura,
denied rumors Thursday that the bank was in fact selling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists remain confident that increasing exports will
keep Philippine growth intact and that the latest pieces of bad
news are not the beginning of a wider crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are more skeptical. Also among their concerns is
swelling government debt, with many expecting the government to
report on Friday that it has already exceeded its deficit target
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the National Statistics Office reported Thursday
that despite continued economic growth, unemployment rose in July
to 11.1 percent, up sharply from 8.4 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Manila residents say gloom surrounds the economy, and rising oil
prices, are making matters worse. Buenaventura warned this week
that higher prices for fuel and energy could stoke inflation and
keep the country from meeting its target for economic growth this
year of 4 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in what could lead to a repetition of events in Europe, a
militant group Thursday threatened to blockade the country's three
main refiners to protest rising gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Manila's investment climate has also been undermined by
persistent complaints of official corruption, including a still
unresolved insider-trading scandal implicating a friend of
President Estrada. In the latest ``corruption perceptions index''
compiled by an independent group, Transparency International, the
Philippines ranked 69th of 90, behind India and China.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors are choosing to pull out of the Philippines. The
central bank said on Wednesday that foreign investors had withdrawn
more than $390 million from Philippine financial markets this
year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
