<HEADER>
A5472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-POLL-INDEPENDENTS-HNS     09-14 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-INDEPENDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INDEPENDENT VOTERS SPLIT ON GORE, BUSH, NOW POLL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent voters are evenly split between Vice
President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and 15 percent of
them have not made up their minds yet, according to a new poll
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the survey by the Pew Research Center for the
People &AMP; the Press differ sharply from another poll this week
showing Gore far ahead of Bush among voters in the crucial
unaligned bloc.
</P>
<P>
   That poll, by the Utica, N.Y.-based John Zogby, showed Gore over
Bush 43 percent to 32 percent among independents. But a New York
Times poll, also out this week, showed Bush with 36 percent of the
independent vote and Gore with 35 percent _ a statistical dead
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Pew poll showed Gore with 39 percent and Bush
with 38 percent of the independents. Last June a Pew poll found
Bush with 40 percent of independents and Gore with 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen percent of the independents surveyed said they had not
decided whom to vote for. That figure compares with 3 percent of
Democrats and 5 percent of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Pew survey polled 1,999 registered voters between
Aug. 24 and Sept. 10. The margin of error was plus or minus 2
percentage points. Of the total sample, 547 said they were
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Pew research center director Andrew Kohut said at a news
conference where the results were released that ``whoever wins the
independents wins the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall in the Pew poll, Gore led Bush 47 percent to 41 percent
among registered voters. But the gap narrowed to 48 percent to 43
percent among the 1,495 in the sample who said they were likely to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey differs from other polls in that it attempts to
dissect the electorate and divide it up into sociological
categories of voting types.
</P>
<P>
   For example, among the unaffiliated voters are ``new prosperity
independents'' _ affluent, business-oriented and well educated _
and ``disaffected independents'' _ those who are less educated,
distrustful of government and less likely to have prospered
financially in the boom economy. Both groups favor Bush by wide
margins, as do another group, called ``conservative-oriented
independents.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``liberal-oriented independents'' like Gore, yielding a
dead-heat in the poll among unattached voters.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
