<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CHEESE-POLICE-$ADV17-     09-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEESE-POLICE-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHEESE GOURMETS FEAR FDA POLICY COULD LEAVE A BAD TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 17)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gourmets, beware! Angel hair pasta with cheese
grated over basil marinara sauce will never be the same if the
federal government has its way.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is considering new rules that
either would ban or drastically limit the manufacture and import of
raw milk, or unpasteurized, cheeses. The FDA has commissioned
scientific studies out of concern that the cheeses may pose a
health risk by carrying potentially deadly bacteria such as E.
coli, listeria and salmonella.
</P>
<P>
   For the gastronomically inclined, who dispute the health risk
claim, such a ruling would be the equivalent of the apocalypse. If
the FDA wins, say goodbye to such tasty and pungent favorites as
Parmigiano-Reggiano, a favorite on pasta, and Gruyere, which is
used in fondue.
</P>
<P>
   Other unpasteurized cheeses that are in the federal cross hairs
include Swiss Emmental and Appenzell; French Vigneron and Comte;
certain Vermont and English cheddars; and Spanish Idiazabal and
Manchego.
</P>
<P>
   Raw cheeses account for only a small portion of the cheese sold
in the United States, perhaps 10 percent, and most are imported,
according to industry estimates. But they are arguably among the
best tasting and most sought after by cheese sophisticates.
</P>
<P>
   Gourmets say the pasteurization process, in which the milk is
heated to high temperatures, destroys flavor. While some of these
raw-milk cheeses have less flavorful pasteurized cousins, others
such as Comte, rarely if ever are made from pasteurized milk.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 50 years, the government has allowed raw-milk cheeses
to be sold here provided that they are aged at least 60 days. The
belief had been that the aging process, along with a minimum amount
of heating of the milk, killed most bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   As a comparison, most European nations have no such rule. If a
raw cheese is made in the morning, it can go to market in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. David Armstrong, associate director for research with
the FDA and the National Center for Food Safety and Technology in
Chicago, said the agency is justified in taking a new look at the
60-day rule, especially, given the virulence of modern day
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been reports in scientific literature that
pathogens such as E. coli 0157 and salmonella may survive the
60-day aging process,'' Armstrong said. ``We are conducting
research to assess the adequacy of the 60-day aging process.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has flatly warned that raw-milk cheeses are ``potential
food safety concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, a United Nations panel that influences rules about
the international shipment of foods is considering whether to limit
the availability of raw-milk cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA argues that while there have been no recent recalls of
raw-milk cheeses, there have been cases of illness linked to some
of the cheeses in California and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Dun Gifford, of the Cheese of Choice Coalition to defend
raw-milk cheeses, questions the claim, although he concedes that
two people in California became ill after consuming Mexican-style
raw-milk cheese. ``Hamburger and poultry are killing people but
nobody's is dying from this cheese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese coalition was founded by the Wisconsin-based American
Cheese Society, which represents artisan cheese makers, and
Cambridge, Mass.-based Oldways Preservation and Exchange Trust,
which promotes traditional foods. The coalition has hired a
lobbyist here to defend the cheeses before the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the organization gathered some 1,500
signatures at 10 stores around the country in protest of possible
FDA action. The group plans a more extensive petition in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The future of raw cheese in this country in large part will fall
or rise on the results of ongoing tests conducted by Armstrong's
staff at FDA labs. In one key study, scientists are injecting
raw-milk cheeses with a cocktail of pathogens as part of an
extensive assessment of whether the cheeses are dangerous to public
health. Armstrong said that scientists likely will have preliminary
results by early next year. The agency is spending some $60,000 on
the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford's group is attacking the methodology, arguing that
because the tests use abnormally high levels of bacteria, they are
skewed toward linking the cheeses with illness.
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA opts to take action, a decision likely wouldn't come
for a year or more. But the gamut of possible options runs from
requiring blanket pasteurization of all cheese sold in the United
States, to requiring producers to age raw-milk cheeses up to 180
days instead of 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, cheese aficionados say, the result would be the
same. ``It would mean that those (raw) cheeses would go the way of
the Studabaker,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Zepos, a cheese consultant in San Francisco, said any
change to the current 60-day rule would have ``huge repercussions''
for raw-milk cheese lovers and manufacturers. If the FDA took the
less dramatic option of increasing the 60-day rule to 180 days,
requiring manufacturers to age raw-milk cheese six months before
sale, it would eliminate from the market a great deal of raw-milk
cheese, she said. Most raw-milk cheeses are four to six months old
when they are at their best, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans, meanwhile, are watching the cheese battle unfold with
bemusement. ``They laugh at the Americans,'' said Gifford. ``They
say, `The great American cowboy has a bad stomach and can't handle
cheeses.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-OLY-BIOPURE-BOS &LR;      09-14 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BIOPURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOPURE TO OFFER ATHLETES TEST FOR PERFORMANCE DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Responding to reports that Olympic athletes may be using two of
its products to enhance performance, Biopure Corp. said Thursday it
will make available a laboratory test to detect the presence of the
drugs in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. company said it decided to release the test
after media reports suggested athletes were using Hemopure and
Oxyglobin instead of better-known performance-enhancing drugs
because the two products can not be detected by commercially
available tests.
</P>
<P>
   The company is developing Hemopure as a potential subsitute for
blood transfusions. The product, in late stages of human clinical
trials, is not yet commercially available. Oxyglobin, a similar
drug used to treat anemia in dogs, is sold in the United States and
approved for use in Europe. It has not been tested in humans and is
not intended for use in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Both drugs increase the amount of oxygen in the bloodstream and
would give competitors in endurance sports such as cycling,
running, and swimming an enormous advantage. Although the use of
Hemopure and Oxyglobin by athletes has not been confirmed, coaches
and physicians associated with the Olympics say they believe it is
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not condone the use of our products by anyone other than
licensed practitioners for approved purposes,'' said Carl Rausch,
Biopure's chairman and chief executive. ``If this news gives those
athletes pause, then all the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Hemopure and Oxyglobin are designed to take immediate
effect, athletes would most likely inject the drugs shortly before
a race. The products have been shown to have an effect on oxygen
levels in the blood even in small doses.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of articles in recent weeks, including one in Time
magazine and another in the London Times newspaper, have reported
that athletes are turning to drugs as their cheating supplements of
choice. Canadian track coach Dan Pfaff has said that he believes
many athletes switched to Hemopure after the introduction of a
viable test for EPO, a drug developed to treat anemia in patients
with kidney disease. EPO, well-known for its use by athletes, is
banned by the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure also received calls from three IOC-accredited
laboratories about the availability of a test to detect the use of
Hemopure and Oxyglobin. Maria Gawryl, Biopure's senior vice
president of research and development, said the company is in
discussions with an IOC-accredited lab in Sydney. But, she said,
she does not know whether that means athletes will be tested during
this summer's Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   Rausch said it makes sense that athletes would try to misuse the
drugs. But he thinks it is highly unlikely that they could get
their hands on Hemopure. The company tracks every unit of the drug
sent to its testing sites in accordance with strict regulatory
requirements. But with more than 60,000 units of Oxyglobin in the
market, Rausch said, the veterinary version may be available
through ``unapproved channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Biopure plans to begin marketing Oxyglobin in Europe later this
year and to apply for regulatory approval next year to begin
marketing Hemopure in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company developed its test to monitor how the body
metabolizes the hemoglobin-based drugs and to evaluate the
products' efficacy in treating animals and people. Since Biopure is
not in the business of testing for the illegal use of drugs, the
company decided to make its testing technology available through
licensing agreements to commercial labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the test available because this is only going
to build in the future as the commercialization of these products
extends,'' Rausch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-OLY-ADVERTISING-BOS &LR;      09-14 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ADVERTISING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS GEAR UP FOR OLYMPIC EXTRAVAGANZA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympics begin Friday night, but other than companies paying
big sponsorship fees, are many Americans paying attention yet?
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the Atlanta summer games started in July, and for
Americans, the viewing was easy.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance this year's games in Sydney 15 time zones away
shape up as much more of a marketing challenge, but such is the
global power of the Olympic brand that corporate sponsors still
think they will get their money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic rings give you instant credibility all over the
world,'' says vice president Steve Burgay of John Hancock Financial
Services Inc. of Boston, a worldwide Olympic sponsor. ``There's a
halo effect that enhances and differentiates your brand.''
</P>
<P>
   As befitting a world event, the Olympics are a moveable feast,
and to accommodate the late Australian summer, the 17-day games in
Sydney are beginning about two months later than the 1996 games did
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Up against summer reruns, July Olympics tend to score high US
ratings. But a September start means Sydney will compete for the
attention of busy Americans with baseball pennant races, a new
football season, a new fall TV season, and a new school year. And
the 15-hour time difference could make it even harder for American
viewers to get excited about the Olympics this year.
</P>
<P>
   Will a fan opt to watch the Red Sox in real time or the delayed
coverage of an hours-old shotput contest won by some large and
obscure athlete from Tajikistan?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Salt Lake City bribery scandal, which at one
point had Hancock hinting that it might withdraw its sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   But despite scandals, time differences, and busy fall schedules,
marketers remain bullish about Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Over its current four-year budget cycle, the International
Olympic Committee says it could rake in $3.5 billion, in part
because big companies such as Hancock, Eastman Kodak Co., and Xerox
are willing to pony up big bucks to link some of their marketing
efforts to the fabled Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   Among companies with some Olympic ties are Monster.com of
Maynard, Mass., which operates a job-search and career-management
Web site, and Reebok International Ltd. of Canton, Mass., a maker
of athletic footwear and apparel.
</P>
<P>
   As the games unfold and heroes emerge, the Olympics should once
again win over Americans, but a sense of anticipation seemed
lacking as the opening cermony drew nigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so conditioned to the Olympics in July that beating the
drum in September'' seems odd, says Larry Moulter, a prime mover in
the building of the FleetCenter in Boston and someone who's devoted
much of his professional career to sports marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of three teenagers, the Moulter household
is so far immune to Olympics fever; its more preoccupied by school,
baseball, and a new football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, it's hard to get mind-share,'' says Moulter,
chief marketing officer of Mirror Image Internet Inc. of Woburn,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But he's quick to note that such a perspective is
``America-centric.'' For a corporation seeking global reach, he
says, ``The Olympics are the biggest footprint you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Looked at this way, the $40 million to $65 million that some top
sponsors are paying for four years of Olympic marketing rights
could well turn out to be a shrewd investment.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hancock, worldwide sponsors include Coca-Cola Co.,
McDonald's Corp., and IBM. The 11 top sponsors paid a total of $605
million, up 51 percent from the amount collected for the Atlanta
games, according to IEG Sponsorship Report.
</P>
<P>
   If the scandals had involved athletes, sponsors might have
reason to fear a fan backlash and a drop-off in TV viewership.
</P>
<P>
   But few fans are likely to tune out Sydney because some
officials took bribes to pick Salt Lake City as the site for the
2002 winter games, says IEG managing editor Sean Brenner.
</P>
<P>
   Already Syndey seems a good bet for the NBC network, which has
sold $900 million worth of air time to advertisers after paying
$705 million for the US television rights, according to Advertising
Age. NBC plans to parcel out coverage between itself and its two
cable sister stations, CNBC and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Past Olympics have drawn audiences of upscale US viewers who
normally don't watch a lot of TV. The games are also something that
families watch together, a phenomenon that has become more rare in
an age of three- and four-TV households with cable access to 40
different channels. For US advertisers, this big audience makes the
Olympics highly desirable.
</P>
<P>
   To a fan, the games are 17 days of sports, but to a corporate
sponsor, the Olympics are about long-term benefits that can't
always be seen on TV or measured in ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, for example, has invited about 500 top sales agents to
Sydney, both as a reward and for retraining. Mornings will be
devoted to business, the rest of the day to fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsorship offers other benefits. In a country where a company
is unknown, the Olympic rings can be a calling card.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock recently received permission to operate in China, Burgay
says. If Beijing wins its bid to host the games in 2008, Hancock
stands to reap a marketing bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   For a company with a global perspective, this may be the
ultimate payoff, says marketing guru Moulter. Keep something in
mind, he says: ``We're never going to see what McDonald's does with
its Olympic promotions in Italy or Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   As a new sponsor of the US Olympic Committee, Monster.com is
looking ahead to Salt Lake City and the 2002 winter games.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers expect Olympic sponsors to be more than mere
advertisers, says Monster.com vice president Peter Blacklow;
consumers expect sponsors to contribute something to the games.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Monster plans to offer online training to the
25,000 volunteers who will help stage the Salt Lake City games.
When the games end, Monster plans to help athletes find jobs. Not
only should such programs generate good will, but they should also
build awareness around what Monster does.
</P>
<P>
   Sneaker-maker Reebok won't have as a big a presence in Sydney as
it has had in some past Olympics. Looking to re-energize its brand,
Reebok has decided not to run TV ads during the games.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has been testing other marketing initiatives,
including a successful tie-in to the ``Survivor'' TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Reebok will have a big ``on-field presence;'' more than
2,500 Sydney athletes or officials will wear its gear, says Denise
Kaigler, senior director of public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several local ad agencies have produced ads that are
scheduled to air during the games.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston has some new ads for
Hancock. Mullen of Wenham has done a spot for Monster. And Boston's
Arnold Communications plans to air new work for Volkswagen of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet is ``globalizing commerce'' and forcing
companies to enter new foreign markets, marketing guru Moulter
thinks that Olympic sponsorships can only gain in value.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, the Olympic rings have emerged as one of the
few marketing icons that have worldwide currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about global commerce and the Internet revolution,''
he says. ``It used to be the global village. Now it's the village
laptop. And the Olympic rings gives you a marketing tool you can
take to any part of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
