<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIDING THE INFORMATION HIGHWAY
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of 10 Internet-enabled taxis hit the streets of New York
on Thursday in a venture between Yahoo, Team Systems, a large taxi
fleet operator, and Medallion Financial, which provides loans for
taxi operators. The purple and yellow, purple-upholstered taxis are
equipped with Palm hand-held computers, offering passengers access
to the Internet at no extra cost. ``This will be a great
opportunity for taxi passengers to stay on top of their business
and personal lives while riding in the comfort of a taxicab,'' said
Andrew Murstein, president of Medallion Financial. The initiative,
which follows a similar effort by Yahoo in San Francisco, is part
of a trend by many companies to deliver Internet content on
wireless devices in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT-PACKARD BUYS STAKE IN INDIGO
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to extend its business from office printers to
business publishing, Hewlett-Packard said Thursday that it would
invest $100 million in Indigo, a Dutch maker of digital color
printing systems. The move, which a company vice president said was
the largest single investment that Hewlett's printing division has
made in at least 18 months, sent Indigo's American depository
receipts soaring $1.156, or 17.6 percent, to $7.7188. Hewlett
shares gained $1.25, to $106.25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH SOFTWARE MAKER ACQUIRED
</P>
<P>
   The Irish security software company Baltimore Technologies
acquired Content Technologies Holdings, a London-based developer of
e-mail security products, in an all-stock transaction valued at
702.5 million pounds ($992 million). The deal increases Baltimore's
North American presence, through Content Technologies' four United
States offices. Content Technologies' MIMEsweeper software, which
protects against junk e-mail and computer viruses, has an installed
base of 6 million users at 6,000 customer sites, and is
particularly popular among medium-sized companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT INVESTMENT IN INDIA
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will invest an additional $50 million over the next
three years in the company's development facility in Hyderabad in
Andhra Pradesh, said chairman Bill Gates on Thursday. ``I am
impressed with the talent we have in our Indian development center
and the quality of software that they are developing,'' Gates said
in New Delhi, India. He also announced an alliance with India's
emerging information technology giant, Infosays Technologies, for
developing a portfolio of business solutions to be delivered on the
Microsoft .Net platform. ``Together, we can deliver world-class
e-business solutions to our existing and future customers,'' Gates
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `GARAGE SALE' MODEL FOR WEB SALES
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to mimic the deals available at yard sales, where prices
tend to decline as the afternoon wears on, the online trading site
WebSwap.com introduced a new ``Garage Sale'' service Thursday
through which prices of goods for sale decline over time. Sellers
set starting and minimum prices for an item, and the service
automatically decreases the price by a set amount every hour over
the course of seven days _ or until someone snaps up whatever is
being offered for sale. WebSwap.com also offers a regular listing
service where sellers can post an item for sale at a set price,
without charge for 30 days or, for a 25-cent fee, for 90 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
