<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-1980-0915-COX     09-14 1827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-1980-0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Olympic team that wasn't
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Randy Ableman has been dreaming the same
dream for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   He's climbing the ladder to the 3-meter springboard for his last
dive. The meet is on the line and Ableman hasn't practiced. He's
out of shape. He's terrified he's about to launch into a big, fat
belly-flop with 10,000 eyes glued to his every move.
</P>
<P>
   And then the dream ends.
</P>
<P>
   If his subconscious had any sense of proportion he'd nail the
dive and wake up happy. Ableman is, after all, a former Olympian
and a collegiate champion. Now a diving coach at the University of
Miami, he has been named NCAA coach of the year nine of the last 11
years.
</P>
<P>
   But the dream mirrors his fate. Ableman had the misfortune of
reaching his athletic peak in 1980. The year the Soviets invaded
Afghanistan. The year the hostage crisis in Iran was making
President Carter look like a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   And the year America boycotted the Olympic Games in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Just like in his recurring dream, Ableman never got to make the
biggest dive of his life.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, he wasn't favored to win a gold medal that year. He
was slated to compete against the legendary Greg Louganis, who made
four Olympic teams and dominated American diving for almost two
decades. But Ableman was 21 years old, confident, 40 pounds slimmer
and cheerily optimistic. ``I had a shot,'' he said. ``I've seen
divers that have nailed a dive for years suddenly miss it in big
meets. You never know how you'll respond in a situation like that
and in our sport there is nothing like the Olympics. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As the nation winds up for the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney and
the worldwide media machine starts recounting glorious moments from
Olympics past, about 400 members of the 1980 U.S. Olympic team are
taking deep breaths and trying to keep some old ghosts at bay.
</P>
<P>
   These Olympians from that forgotten team have moved on with
their lives. They've become lawyers, brokers, coaches and
psychologists. But even after two decades, flashes of disgust and
even despair spark when they talk about what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Marshall Duane. Duane could be a poster boy for Merrill
Lynch, where he's worked almost since the boycott. With his
impeccable manners, country-club tan and corner office, he exudes
the confidence you might expect from someone who handles other
people's money. But when he talks about the Games, about what
should have been, his blue eyes narrow ever so slightly.
</P>
<P>
   As a former member of the U.S. Olympic sailing team, Duane _
like all Olympians _ still gets first crack at Olympic tickets
every four years. But when the Games were held in Atlanta in 1996,
he said he just couldn't bring himself to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been there eating my heart out,'' he said.
``Maybe that's a terrible way to think about it, but I'm extremely
competitive. It happens every four years. I think that somehow that
should have been me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ableman missed the 1984 U.S. Olympic Diving Team by three spots.
Duane, training with a wife and a child to support, could muster
only a half-hearted attempt at the sailing trials. He wasn't close.
</P>
<P>
   They are left to wonder about the shot they did have in 1980.
They are left to wonder: What if?
</P>
<P>
   BOYCOTT THWARTS LIFETIME GOAL
</P>
<P>
   Doug Brown is the head coach of the track and cross-country
teams at the University of Florida. On the wall in his office are
photos from his athletic career. Among them: a shot of the 1980
U.S. Olympic track and field team. ``It was a good one,'' Brown
says.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has something to compare it to. The 48-year-old
represented the United States in the steeplechase on the 1972 and
1976 Olympic teams as well. In neither Games did he run as well as
he'd hoped. Steeplechasers _ who leap over hurdles and water
ditches along a 3,000-yard course _ don't typically peak until
their late twenties, so he took aim at the Moscow Games. He wanted
one more chance to reach his lifelong goal of an Olympic medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my life on hold,'' he said. ``I put off kids, I put off
a career.''
</P>
<P>
   To support himself and his wife, Brown sold lumber part time in
Eugene, Ore., while he trained four hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   He had one of the fastest times in the world and was in the best
shape of his life when the trials were run in June. He qualified
easily. And even though President Carter had threatened to boycott
the Games in January and the United States Olympic Committee had
voted to boycott in April, Brown said he didn't believe it would
actually come to that by the time the teams were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make sense,'' he said. ``There were too many other
alternatives there that could have worked.''
</P>
<P>
   President Carter felt otherwise. Convinced that the world map
could be drastically altered if the free world ignored Soviet
aggression, the president dispatched Vice President Walter Mondale
to Colorado where Olympic committee delegates were meeting. Mondale
called the boycott vote ``truly a referendum on freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake is no less than the future security of the
civilized world. . . if we and our allies and friends fail to use
every single peaceful means available to preserve the peace, what
hope is there that peace will be long preserved?''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC voted by a 2-to-1 margin to boycott the Games.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate the athletes for the sacrifice, Carter had the
entire U.S. Olympic Team to the White House for a reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was honoring the office, not the man,'' said Brown, who did
not race at the next trials because he had children and a full-time
job with Nike and was too busy to train. ``To this day I tell
people I was a member of Jimmy Carter's Special Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The boycott had no immediate discernible effect on the Soviets
and many believed it accomplished nothing at all. The
Soviet-installed government in Afghanistan remained in place until
1992 when it was overthrown by Islamic resistance groups.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Henry Kissinger, the Secretary of State under
President Nixon, said that although he favored the boycott at the
time, ``in retrospect, I think it was a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get angry when I think about it how dumb it was, how
short-sighted,'' says Brown. ``It didn't have any impact on the
world of politics but it had a lot of impact on the young Americans
that Carter was supposed to represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hogshead-Makar, who made the U.S. Olympic Swimming Team in
1980 and again in 1984, said she supported the boycott at the time.
``I got suckered into the rhetoric of the day which was 'You
Olympians are going to save us from World War III,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing years, she came to believe Carter had used the
Olympics as political tool. ``I think he backed himself into a
corner and couldn't get out of it,'' Hogshead-Makar said from
Jacksonville, where she is now an attorney. ``We had the hostage
crisis and he was getting crucified every day, he was seen as
inept. Here was something he could do operatively . . . as I got
older I realized I had been a sap.''
</P>
<P>
   From Hogshead-Makar's perspective the boycott cost not only her
_ she would have been tremendously marketable if she had gone into
the Los Angeles Games in 1984 with a few gold medals under her belt
_ but an entire generation of athletes, particularly women.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, women were believed to peak athletically by their
late teens and they had few role models or opportunities to prove
otherwise. The Olympics were one of the few events that turned
girls on to sports.
</P>
<P>
   While she got a chance to compete in the 1984 Games, she said
she sympathizes with the athletes who were shut out of the Games
altogether. ``I've been to pretty much every sporting event in the
world, the Tour de France, the Super Bowl, the World Series, the
World Cup, the Kentucky Derby, you name it. Either as a commentator
or a spectator I've been there, and there is nothing like the
Olympics. There's a spirit of wonder and of humanity that's there
that I just haven't found anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Potter knew enough about that spirit to know what she
was missing in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   An Olympian in 1972 and 1976, she had been an elite diver for
almost a decade and won the Olympic bronze medal in 1976. She came
out of retirement to give the 1980 games one last shot.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare, she took a leave of absence from her job and moved
to Texas where the trials were to be held so she could train full
time. For six months she practiced twice a day, lifted weights, ran
and stretched.
</P>
<P>
   When she heard the boycott was for real she remembers thinking
it was a bad a joke. ``I thought, he's got to be kidding. (The
situation in Afghanistan) has nothing to do with me.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later she was driving north on Highway 75 in Texas and
she broke down in tears. ``I still had not dealt with it and all
that anger was ruining my life,'' Potter said. She sought
counseling and has since come to look at the boycott as a sort of
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think it was a good decision but it was an
opportunity to learn about ourselves. About how we could accept
hard truths and not hold onto resentment or bitterness.'' Potter
will be in Sydney this year working for NBC as a commentator for
diving.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Neyer was another member of the women's 1980 Olympic Diving
Team and she has had to go through her own grieving process because
of the boycott which, she says, is reintroduced every time the
subject comes up. The conversation almost always goes the same way,
she says. She tells people she was an Olympian. They ask if she won
a medal and she tells them she was on the team that didn't get to
compete. They say something like 'Oh that stinks,' and change the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Vietnam vets,'' said Neyer. ``I don't want that
analogy to be misunderstood, but from a public perception
standpoint we did something really stupid so we don't want to talk
about it and people don't know what to do with it. And this
generation of kids who weren't even alive during the Cold War, to
them it sounds so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Neyer was favored to lead the 1984 Olympic women's diving team
but missed a dive and did not qualify for the team. She quit diving
for a year but came back and finished her career at the University
of Florida, where she went on to win her eighth consecutive NCAA
diving title.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Neyer went on to get her Ph.D. in sports psychology.
She practices today in Atlanta, part of her speciality is helping
athletes leave athletics and enter different fields.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her own ``what if's,'' she takes some solace in her one
encounter with the Russian diver who won the 1980 Olympic gold
medal in Moscow. The two competed in 1982 at the world diving
championships in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' Neyer said. ``I kicked her ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
