<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      09-14 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 3 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (2-0) at Jets (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   The Jets seek their first 3-0 start since 1966. That's almost 40
years of history working against them. But this team has courage.
The Jets were completely outplayed by New England until the final
six minutes Monday night and still won. If they play that poorly
against the Bills, New York will lose. The Jets should play much
better, however, and win a close one.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Jets, 21-17
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (1-1) at Carolina (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons looked awful last week against Denver. They were
slow, ragged and disorganized. The games between these two teams
are usually close and high scoring, which means Atlanta will likely
play better. The difference maker is Carolina quarterback Steve
Beuerlein, who is first in the conference with a 116.1 passer
rating. Atlanta's defense gets torched for 300 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Panthers, 28-24
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati (0-2) at Jacksonville (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Mark Brunell, for one of the first times in his
career, has spent the early part of this season as a classic
dropback passer. Brunell loves to roll out and play loose, so the
fact he has stayed in the pocket and is playing well, is a good
omen for the Jaguars. Not to mention that against Cincinnati,
Brunell is 3-0 with a passer rating of 113.2.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Jaguars, 25-10
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (1-1) at Green Bay (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   Winning at Lambeau Field is not as difficult as it used to be.
The Jets did it in the season opener and the Eagles are capable.
After running back Duce Staley (11 yards) was shut down by the
Giants, he will rebound against a weak Green Bay defense. The
Packers are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Eagles, 17-14
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (0-1) at Cleveland (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kent Graham injured his throwing hand during
practice this week after banging it on teammate's helmet. He will
likely start but there is no question his throwing motion will be
affected. Backup Kordell Stewart had a touchdown pass and run in
last game against Cleveland last season. The Browns showed a spark
last week against Cincinnati but the Steelers have a much better
defense than the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Steelers, 18-14
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco (0-2) at St. Louis (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   How good are the Rams? Their defense has allowed 382 yards a
game and they are still undefeated. How bad are the 49ers? They
give up 404.5 yards a game. When Rams coaches were looking at game
film, they were shocked at just how far San Francisco's defense has
fallen. The Rams will score so many points the wide receivers will
need track shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Rams, 40-17
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (2-0) at Detroit (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more intriguing games of the week, mainly
because both teams have outstanding defenses. Tampa Bay is one of
the fastest, most well coached defensive units of the past decade.
Surprisingly, the Lions also have a solid unit, allowing just 292.5
yards of offense in the first two games, second best in the
conference. The better defense will win this one, and it belongs to
Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Buccaneers, 13-9
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES:
</P>
<P>
   Denver (1-1) at Oakland (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   Broncos' quarterback Brian Griese is first in the league with a
quarterback rating of 120, so Denver has found its replacement for
John Elway. The Raiders are a surprising 2-0 because of _ guess
who? _ Tyrone Wheatley, the Giants' castoff. Whenever the Raiders
venture inside the 20-yard line Wheatley is a major weapon with his
bull rush up the middle or his sprinter speed to the outside. These
games are always close and Oakland wins in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Raiders, 24-21
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (0-2) at Kansas City (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   Coach Gunther Cunningham hasn't talked about quitting the past
few days, so other than the Chiefs' poor start, everything is fine
in Kansas City. Actually, it's disastrous, because the Chiefs have
had two extremely brutal close losses, the last one coming to
Tennessee in overtime. Those losses are still eating at the Chiefs
and will prove too great a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Chargers, 20-17
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (2-0) at New England (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   Rookie quarterback Daunte Culpepper was supposed to be in over
his head, but he has performed more proficiently than that of his
Pro Bowl counterpart, Drew Bledsoe. The Patriots have an excellent
secondary overall, but few teams can stop Randy Moss and Cris
Carter, and Minnesota's defense is playing extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Vikings, 20-10
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (1-1) at Seattle (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   The Saints finally have a decent offense mainly because
quarterback Jeff Blake has added the long pass to the arsenal. The
Seahawks are in total disarray. General manager and coach Mike
Holmgren is discovering that doing both jobs is much harder than it
appears.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Saints, 35-28
</P>
<P>
   Giants (2-0) at Chicago (0-2)
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have an offense for the first time since Phil Simms
was the quarterback. The defense is playing inspired because for
the first time in years those players can actually have a break,
and not go right back on the field after stopping an opposing
offense. Michael Strahan manhandled Philadelphia offensive tackle
Jon Runyan, linebacker Jessie Armstead is again playing at a Pro
Bowl level and cornerback Jason Sehorn is blanketing receivers.
This game will be tough because the Bears know if they lose any
playoff hopes are all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Giants, 27-16
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Night
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (2-0) at Miami (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Tony Banks has to be considered one of the hotter quarterbacks
in the game, mainly because he has demonstrated poise and great arm
strength. The offense, surprisingly, is carrying this team, when
its defense is clearly the better half. When Baltimore's defense
does catch its breath, the team will be that much better.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Ravens, 20-6
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY 9 P.M.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (0-2) at Washington (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the Washington organization is waiting for impatient
owner Daniel Snyder to go on one of his firing binges, beginning
with Coach Norv Turner. One day Snyder will go off, but not this
week. He knows there is no reason to panic _ the Cowboys are not
very good. The team is old and quarterback Troy Aikman, because of
numerous concussions, is becoming more frail as each season passes.
Washington's defense is playing well and will shut down what little
offense the Cowboys possess.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction; Redskins, 28-12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
