<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT     09-14 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT ORDERS SUHARTO TO BE EXAMINED BY INDEPENDENT MEDICAL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (No byline)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A court in Jakarta ordered an independent
medical team Thursday to determine whether the former President
Suharto was fit to stand trial for corruption after he again
declined a summons to appear in court, citing ill health. Suharto
failed to appear when the trial opened on Aug. 31, forcing a
two-week delay.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing Thursday opened just hours after a powerful car bomb
exploded at the Jakarta Stock Exchange building on Wednesday,
killing 15 people.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's continued absence and the intensifying violence in
Jakarta at each stage of the case have increased pressure on the
government to show that it has the will to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   The police acknowledged that the latest explosion might be
linked to bombings in recent weeks that had been blamed on
supporters of Suharto. Senior government officials have accused
military and political extremists linked to him of trying to derail
both the corruption trial and investigations into human rights
abuses during his 32-year regime.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Reuters, Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
said: ``There is a perception that any time the government raises
the pressure on Mr. Suharto or any of his cronies, then these
things happen in Jakarta or in the regions. I think there are
elements connected to the military establishment who make these
incidents possible, rogue elements, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, 79, is accused of stealing $571 million from the state
and funneling the money into the businesses of his family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers deny the charges and insist that he does not have
the mental capacity to stand trial because strokes last year left
him with brain damage _ a defense that has been compared to that of
the former Chilean dictator, Augusto Pinochet, who fought an
extradition battle in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lalu Mariyun, chief of the South Jakarta District Court,
ordered physicians from the Indonesian Doctors Association and from
three prominent universities to ``conduct a comprehensive medical
checkup'' on Suharto and report to the judges at a hearing on Sept.
28.
</P>
<P>
   The government has so far declined to escort the former leader
forcibly to court from his villa in Jakarta, where he lives under
house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant's chair sat empty Thursday while the panel of five
judges heard medical testimony from the prosecution and defense for
three hours. More than 400 uniformed police officers stood guard
outside the auditorium in South Jakarta where the trial is being
held.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's entire medical team of 23 doctors, wearing white
hospital coats, appeared in the courtroom to testify about his
ailments, which they said included hypertension, kidney stones and
heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   His chief doctor, Teguh Ranakusuma, and two colleagues presented
Suharto's health history, projecting images of his brain on a large
screen. They said Suharto had suffered three strokes last year, and
warned that forcing him to attend the trial could trigger a fourth
and fatal one.
</P>
<P>
   A state-appointed medical team examined Suharto three times in
the past six months, and although they conceded that he had trouble
communicating, they determined that he could stand trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1851EDT &QL; 
