<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      09-14 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR GOVERNMENT BEARS BRUNT OF FUEL-CRISIS ANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As Britain's fuel crisis began to recede Thursday, the
nation's most popular government in recent history was pondering
how it so badly misread public opinion by steadfastly refusing to
cut the highest fuel tax in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel deliveries rose to levels unseen in a week as most
demonstrators ended their blockades of refineries, officials said
it could be two weeks before supplies return to normal.
</P>
<P>
   At Stanlow refinery, where the uprising began last week, protest
leader Brynle Williams, a farmer, said the demonstrators _ urging
an end to the tax _ should quit while they still enjoyed the
support of most Britons and before widespread hardship was caused.
</P>
<P>
   For the third day in a row, a chastened Prime Minister Tony
Blair faced reporters after spending the day twisting the arms of
oil executives. Blair blames the industry for the crisis, saying it
did not do enough to force its drivers to defy the relatively small
number of protesters who congregated at the gates of the nation's
nine main refineries.
</P>
<P>
   But polls suggest the vast majority of British people blame not
the protesters or the oil companies, but the government. There is
widespread anger with the government for setting the fuel tax at
what most Britons consider too high, and for not being more
creative in finding a way to defuse the protests that led to panic
buying of gas and food, causing shortages and chaos.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly $5 a gallon, with 76 percent of that price going to
taxes, gasoline in Britain is the most expensive and most-taxed in
Europe. For many Britons, living in a nation that produces oil, and
which is enjoying what even Blair calls a golden period of economic
growth and low unemployment, such prices seem unfair, the product
of a greedy government.
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis deepened, Gordon Brown, chancellor of the
Exchequer, reminded Britons that their income taxes are among the
lowest in Europe, and that for nearly two decades important
services such as health and education have been subsidized by the
more than $50 billion the gas tax raises each year.
</P>
<P>
   Most British people don't want to hear it. They look east and
see that the Irish, who are enjoying record budget surpluses, pay a
third less for their gasoline, while only 58 percent of the price
the Irish pay at the pump is tax. Britons look west and see that
the French pay 20 percent less for gasoline, but enjoy a national
health service that is superior to Britain's. Britons don't accept
that the Germans, Dutch and Belgians can pay less for fuel, and are
hardly mollified by the fact that there are growing protest
movements against the fuel tax in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bill Clinton, Tony Blair moved his left-wing party to the
center and in 1997 won a landslide victory, ending 18 years of
Conservative rule. In doing so, he secured the largest
parliamentary majority in nearly two centuries, and has pretty much
had his own way legislatively. But the bloom is coming off the
rose, which is the Labor Party's symbol.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, there was a series of embarrassing leaks of
memos in which Blair and top aides openly questioned whether they
were losing touch with the public. Andrew Marr, the BBC's political
editor, said the widespread public support for the fuel tax
protest, which was confirmed in a BBC poll, is the first emperical
evidence that Labor is out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the rebirth of the opposition,'' said Marr.
</P>
<P>
   That opposition, however, is hampered in its attempts to make
the fuel tax the key issue in the next general election, which
could come as early as next year and must be held by May 2002. The
Conservatives instituted the current fuel tax, which besides
raising revenue for the government is aimed at forcing people to
drive less and rely more on public transportation. While
Conservative leader William Hague has tried to use the fuel crisis
as a stick to beat Blair with, he refused to promise to cut the tax
if the Conservatives win the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Hague's deputy, Michael Portillo, predicted Labor will eventully
be done in by what he called a ``taxpayer revolt.''
</P>
<P>
   As the foot soldiers in that revolt, the truckers and farmers
and self-employed business people, pulled back from the barricades
Thursday, Blair and his braintrust were left to pick over the
debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a kicking,'' admitted one Downing Street official,
speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``We've got to sit down and
look at all this and try to find the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   They have time. They won't be driving much the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of The Boston Globe London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LONDON-EXCHANGE-NYT &LR;      09-14 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-EXCHANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-MORTEM AT LONDON STOCK EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Senior members of the London Stock Exchange's board
managed to hang on to their jobs Thursday during a heated
shareholder meeting, but the exchange is back to Square One in its
goal of forming a pan-European market for trading stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the London Stock Exchange abandoned plans to
merge with the Deutsche Boerse in Frankfurt to form what would have
been Europe's first over-arching stock exchange. The plan for the
merged market, to be called iX, had been facing increased
opposition from both retail brokers and large institutions who were
uncertain how the regulations, technology, and clearing and
settlement systems of the two exchanges would meld. The situation
was further complicated by a hostile bid for the London exchange
from OM Gruppen, a Swedish technology group that runs the Stockholm
stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right to explore iX, and it was right to abandon it,''
Don Cruickshank, the London exchange's chairman, said as he faced a
barrage of criticism, mainly from retail brokers who feared the
merger plan would hurt their livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   Cruickshank and Michael Marks, executive chairman of Merrill
Lynch, the London exchange's adviser on its plan to form iX, were
both re-elected during a show of hands at the tense meeting held in
the gilded ballroom of the Hotel Inter-Continental. Marks has been
under pressure ever since a report commissioned by Merrill Lynch
that was highly critical of the iX plan leaked last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive Gavin Casey was voted out during the show of
hands, but he was reinstated by a narrow margin during a secret
ballot later Thursday afternoon. (In a secret ballot, a
shareholder's vote is proportional to the the number of shares
held, whereas in a show of hands each shareholder has one vote.)
</P>
<P>
   Several retail brokers took the opportunity to express
disappointment with the leadership provided by the exchange's
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had iX gone to a vote, it would not have succeeded,'' said
Michael Spencer, chief executive of Garban Intercapital, who had
called for Cruickshank's removal in a piece published in The London
Times over the weekend. ``Doesn't that raise questions about the
competence of the board?''
</P>
<P>
   The board must now focus on how best to achieve a pan-European
exchange, and decide whether such a strategy is even viable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
