<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS STRUGGLE TO REDUCE MISTAKES, INCREASE CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Everyone's looking for the silver lining, the
bright side, the ray of hope _ something that would make one
believe that the power of positive thinking can be applied to
Patriots football. Thursday talk of ``constant improvement''
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Henry Thomas gave it some thought, then mowed
the notion down like a patch of tall weeds beneath a John Deere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that improvement thing; that's a nice concept,'' he
said. ``But we want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, or some variation thereof, became a refrain in the
Patriots locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to win,'' said defensive back Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 0-2, and it ain't great,'' said wide receiver and
specialist Troy Brown, when asked about being off to a good start
personally. Twice afterward, when asked about his personal
achievements, he uttered the same answer.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team in need of a win. A convincing win. An ugly win.
A controversial win. Right now, the Patriots merely want to walk
off the field with more points than the adversary. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win would get things going,'' said Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you do until then? How do you keep team morale up
between now and that first triumph of the season, particularly when
it's coming off two games it could have won and has a tough stretch
ahead (home against Minnesota on Sunday, then at Miami, at Denver,
and home against Indianapolis)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way. My approach isn't, `Well, everything
is going to be fine. Don't worry about it,' '' said first-year
coach Bill Belichick. ``You know, we're 0-2, and we need to address
the things that made us 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really where my focus is _ to explain to the players
what we need to do to make a difference in a few close games.
That's what I tried to do. Whether it's a morale thing, a coaching
thing, a strategy thing, call it whatever you want to call it.
You're trying to get your team ready to play another opponent, a
good one.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. Minnesota (2-0), which will be playing its first road
game this weekend, is second in the NFC in total offense (265.5
yards per game) and is averaging 6.54 yards on first down, tops in
the conference. The Vikings beat Chicago, 30-27, in their opener,
and edged Miami, 13-7, last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are coming off a disheartening 20-19 Monday night
loss to AFC East rival New York, which was outplayed by New England
most of the game before rallying with two touchdowns in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Couple that with the 21-16 season-opening debacle against Tampa
Bay and you have a team that says it needs a win, one that has
given up 12 sacks in two games yet had chances to win both in the
closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustrating loss (on Monday) but it's time to put that behind
us now and move on to Minnesota,'' said Brown. ``We had one in the
bag and let it get away, and we had a chance to win the Tampa game
going down the stretch. It didn't work out, but now we have to go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Belichick said talk of low morale is exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like it's gloom and doom; it is what it is,'' he
said. ``It's not like we've been beaten, 58-0, in the past two
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether victories beget positive thinking or vice versa, the
Patriots know they need to cut down on their mistakes in order to
enjoy either. Thomas admitted the team is making progress while
adjusting to the new staff.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, save the sack total, the Patriots have been
statistically similar to their opponents. For instance, while New
England has struggled running the ball (188 yards, 55 carries, 3.4
average), the opposition hasn't fared much better (199 yards, 55
carries, 3.6 average).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting better, performing better, especially the
defense,'' Thomas said. ``We're playing together better, starting
to understand things better. We have a long way to go but we have
begun to minimize mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
