<HEADER>
A5516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MICKEY'S-CLOSET0915-C     09-14 1783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICKEY'S-CLOSET0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The cast gets costumes, but Mickey's the star
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What does the well-dressed mouse wear to
receive royalty?
</P>
<P>
   If he's Mickey Mouse shaking paws with the late King Hussein of
Jordan, he dons kaffiyeh and galabiyya, the headdress and flowing
white robes of a sheik. Custom-fitted to his truly one-of-a-kind
mouse physique.
</P>
<P>
   And what does the chipper rodent sport when he wants to go
incognito in the Magic Kingdom? The tourist's uniform of Hawaiian
shirt and comfy sneakers, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Call Mickey the mouse that hoards. His clothes closet holds more
than 500 different outfits, one for any possible Disney World
occasion _ business meeting, wedding, parade, party.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Mickey au courant are the 250 employees of the Creative
Costuming department, which designs and develops all aspects of
wardrobes for Walt Disney World Resort.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to almost 1,000 ensembles for Mickey and Minnie
alone, they stitch enough costumes to outfit an army 50,000 strong.
</P>
<P>
   They keep parking-lot attendants cool and comfortable, yet
neat-looking. They dress dancing girls in costumes with kick. They
even provide Audio-Animatronic presidents with suits that can be
donned without the robotic heads of state moving a single limb
(Velcro is key).
</P>
<P>
   But the star of the show, with the accompanying headliner's
wardrobe, is Mickey Mouse, whose costumes are cataloged in a fat
three-ring binder.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday morning, Mickey paid a visit to Creative
Costuming, which is headquartered behind a nondescript fence inside
the Disney-MGM Studios theme park.
</P>
<P>
   The Creative Costuming folks had hung a couple dozen of Mickey's
outfits in their conference room. Dressed in his standard costume
of red pants, white shirt and black tails, the Mouse looked over a
pair of lederhosen and modeled his Uncle Sam hat. New outfits are
designed for Mickey whenever a party, show or visiting dignitary
dictates a special ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   He then retired to a dressing room, with a human assistant, to
don his China costume. With matching hat, Mickey's China ensemble
is aswirl with color. A dragon breathes satin fire on the front,
and the lizard's vivid tail wraps around Mickey's back. The pants
and jackets are richly appliqued and decorated with Swarovski
crystals. Only the best for Disney's master of ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   When the Disney design team creates a costume with national
flavor, they try to keep it authentic, referring to a library of
reference and travel books. (Concessions have to be made for
Mickey's special shape and the fact that the outfits need regular
laundering.)
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, aesthetic concerns override safety. Creative
Costuming was asked to sew Mickey a scuba outfit so he could dive
in the Living Seas exhibit. They chose a cheery lemon hue. But when
the Living Seas team saw it, they said, ``Uh-oh, yum-yum yellow,''
so-called because the color makes sharks hungry. ``So Mickey
decided to feed the sharks before he got in the pool,'' said Pamela
Carver, costume design manager.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his mariachi, Beefeater and Boy Scout costumes,
Mickey has an outfit made of black satin and kente cloth, created
for his appearance at an African-American beauty pageant. The
pattern and colors of the cloth symbolize royalty, Carver said.
``People of a very high stature would wear this cloth, and Mickey's
as high as he could get here. He's tops.''
</P>
<P>
   Carver estimated that 90 percent of Mickey's costumes are period
attire (such as his Colonial America white knickers, red coat and
cream ascot), and in general, Mickey doesn't follow trends. You
won't see him wearing cargo pants and a guyabera shirt over a white
T. ``He's classic,'' she said. ``We don't want to keep changing''
his image.
</P>
<P>
   But they're happy to change his clothes, again and again and
again . .
</P>
<P>
   MOUSE OF A MILLION FACES
</P>
<P>
   An astronaut, for the opening of Space Mountain. He wore
bubble-shaped headgear, a spacesuit and silver gloves.
</P>
<P>
   _ A '50s sock hopper, for an Eisenhower-era-themed party. Yellow
pants, green letter sweater.
</P>
<P>
   _ An artist, for a visit to France in Epcot. White smock, red
beret, black trousers.
</P>
<P>
   _ George Washington, for a Fourth of July show. Three-cornered
hat, white wig, knickers.
</P>
<P>
   _ A doctor, for a convention of physicians. Lab coat,
stethoscope, medical bag.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ghost, a scarecrow, a sorcerer.
</P>
<P>
   _ A farmer, a football player, a mailman.
</P>
<P>
   _ A chef, a movie director, a pirate, a member of the press. . .
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY BEAT THE FLORIDA HEAT
</P>
<P>
   In the South Florida version of summer, you can break a sweat
simply walking from house to car.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine spending the season of swelter in a Goofy suit.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping cast members cool is a priority for Disney costume
designers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``that's our No. 1 consideration,'' says Pamela Carver,
costume design manager. ``Except for the Audio-Animatronics. We can
make (their clothes) any way we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ways Disney helps its employees chill:
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding ways to let off steam.
</P>
<P>
   The designers look for ways to allow air-flow through costumes.
Most hats have holes poked in the tops so that hot air can escape,
and a new line of hats for Disney security guards has tops made of
mesh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Relying on the touch, the feel of cotton.
</P>
<P>
   The costuming department tries to make sure that only cotton
touches the bodies of cast members. To decrease the number of hours
spent ironing, they use polyester fibers wrapped in cotton. They've
also started using CoolMax, a DuPont fabric that pulls moisture
away from the body and helps speed its evaporation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bending the dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Every effort is made to shade those wearing long dresses, and to
give dancing-and-singing entertainers longer and more frequent
breaks than their stationary counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of the summer, those who operate the Haunted
Mansion, for example, are allowed to remove their long jackets, and
others get permission to roll up their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Faking it.
</P>
<P>
   Synthetic hairpieces keep dancers looking tidy and uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``You use a real-hair wig, and it does the same thing that real
hair does in Florida,'' Carver says. ``It flops.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone exception: The stationary fellas in the Hall of
Presidents are coiffed with human locks, for they never leave
air-conditioned comfort.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY'S LAUNDRY ROOM: NO SMALL WORLD
</P>
<P>
   How huge is Disney's costume operation?
</P>
<P>
   Much bigger than a certain mouse's oversized ears.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mickey alone can choose from more than 500 different
ensembles, from Boy Scout to Beefeater. Minnie needs to hit the
mall to catch up with her male counterpart. Her closet is stocked
with more than 450 different outfits, including cheerleader skirts
and ballgowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Walt Disney World Resort has to outfit close to 55,000
employees, making it the largest single-site employer in the United
States. Roughly 90 percent of those workers are in costume. To
simplify, costumers try to keep as many of them in the same black
pants while theming them very specifically from the waist up _ the
part of the body that guests see most often.
</P>
<P>
   _ An example of outfitting a single department: To make sure the
resort's 800-driver bus division is adequately covered, costuming
keeps on hand 6,400 pairs of pants and 6,400 shirts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Each day, Disney uses Ecolab products to clean an average of
240,000 pounds of clothes. If you were to wash and dry one load of
laundry every day for 44 years, you'd clean as much as the Disney
laundry department in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   _ You think you've got dry-cleaning bills? Between 30,000 and
32,000 Disney garments are dry-cleaned daily.
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL KINGDOM
</P>
<P>
   `Vogue' and `Harper's Bazaar' are touting animal prints for
fall. At Disney's Animal Kingdom, they're always in style:
</P>
<P>
   _ The 2,500 cast members _ who man gift shops, serve snacks and
drinks, sing and dance in shows, and act as ``safari guides'' _
wear 62 different designs. In all, more than 61,000 items of
apparel are required.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twenty percent of the costumes are made with lyocell, a fiber
made from wood pulp harvested from trees grown specifically for the
production of fabrics. It has the absorbency of cotton and the
strength and versatility of a synthetic fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cast members in Safari Village wear tunics in which the colors
are shaded gradually from a deep coral to pink, orange, yellow,
green, blue and purple. Each band of color contains a menagerie _
turtles, flamingos and fish on one blouse, crabs, frogs and
alligators on another, and beetles and lady bugs on a third.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employees who work the Kilimanjaro Safari wear safari and
game-warden attire in bronze and khaki with patch pockets and
national park-style emblems sewn on sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Festival of the Lion King'' stage show alone requires
136 costumes, inspired by authentic tribal attire. They include an
aerialist dressed like a chartreuse-and-yellow bird, trampolinists
in monkey costumes, and a storytelling tribal chief in an amber
headdress, leather tunic and lion-mane cape. Other members of the
tribe are dressed to portray a gazelle, a snake, a crocodile and a
sandy-colored leopard.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``student paleontologists'' who dig at DinoLand U.S.A.
wear green, rust and blue jeans with lime green or yellow Henley
T-shirts and baseballs caps bearing the Dino Institute logo. Some
outfits are accessorized with tool belts and bandanas.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the high-energy ``Tarzan Rocks!'' show, in-line skating
performers are dressed to resemble members of the ape family. Their
costumes are made of painted spandex, which allows them to skate
through the theater with the greatest of ease. The only fur used in
Animal Kingdom attire is faux.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tribal costumes from the Ivory Coast to Nigeria to Kenya
inspired the Harambe costumes, which feature bright colors, beaded
trim and geometric designs. Both men and women wear tunic tops
bearing Swahili greetings and knee-length trousers with
drape-effects sewn into them. The outfits are topped off with
matching headscarves and turbans, beaded belts and leather panels.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Animal Kingdom Lodge will open next spring, and the
costume department recently held a fashion show to preview the
staff's uniforms, which were all based on designs indigenous to
Africa. Many of Disney's employees from foreign countries brought
examples of traditional costuming from their homelands, but they
had to be adapted to the Orlando sun. Turns out it's hotter in
Florida than in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
