<HEADER>
A5519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH-CRAIG15-COX     09-14 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-CRAIG15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boxing always had been good for Dion Craig
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The dream supposedly went like this:
</P>
<P>
   Mary Craig was up in heaven. Her son, Dion, was down in
Cincinnati. They were talking by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing Dion said he asked Mom was if she'd gotten her
wings yet,'' his brother, Dante Craig said. ``Mom told him no, that
getting your wings takes a while. He started to ask her something
else about them and that's when she told him, 'Stop! Now listen to
me. Get Dante back in boxing. Get your brother back in the ring.'''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat here on this Sydney afternoon wearing his red, white
and blue Olympic warm-up jacket, the Cincinnati welterweight retold
his brother's dream in almost reverential tones. Not that it was
always like that. When Dante first heard about the Pearly Gates'
plea, he didn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming a Junior Olympics champ in 1994 and then winning
the National Golden Gloves title the following year, he thought
he'd certainly make the 1996 Olympic team. Instead, he was beaten
in the Olympic Trials and the loss devastated him.
</P>
<P>
   He quit his sport and got a job pressing pants at Teasdale
Cleaners in Cincinnati. After a year, he was earning $8 an hour and
making a name for himself with the steam set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could press 70 pair of pants an hour,'' he said so proudly
that his grin soon revealed the golden caps he wears on two teeth.
``Nobody else could press 70 pair. I was the best they had.''
</P>
<P>
   While he worked for the cash, he also used his job as an escape
from all that had gone wrong. First, he'd left boxing, then he'd
lost his mother, who died of breast cancer in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Dion told me his dream, he begged me,'' Dante said. ``He
said, 'Oh man, give it one more shot.' I told him, 'No, I'm making
$400 a week. I'm not giving that up.' But the more he explained how
the dream went, the more I said, 'Dawg, you're right. That had to
be Mom talking. It sounded like her. It sounded so real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dion was working for TV Guide and he told me he'd give me $200
a week, if I quit my job and just trained. The dream felt real to
him. And pretty soon it felt real to me. too.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxing always had been good for him. Back when he was going to
Crest Hills Middle School in Cincinnati, schoolyard bullies began
forcing him to give up the weekly $10 his mom gave him for meal
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Daddy didn't want me to get picked on anymore, so he took
me to the Findlay Street Neighborhood House,'' Dante said of the
Over-the-Rhine fight club. ``I ended up doing pretty good and soon
I was winning tournaments. Back then, my mom was my biggest fan.
Maybe that's why when I dream of her now, I don't hear what she
says. I'm always too busy hugging her and kissing her like she's
still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He figured since he doesn't listen, she had to talk to someone
else. That got the message across. The Woodward High School
graduate returned to the gym last year, won his second National
Golden Glove title and once again was invited to the Olympic
Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed to be working out perfectly, until _ just
three weeks before the Trials _ he got a frantic phone call just
before he was to get into the ring at the 2000 U.S. Championships
in Colorado Springs. The call was from Evelyn DeLoach, the mother
of their 1-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She said Dante Jr. had been having some respiratory problems for
a couple of days and then all of a sudden, he'd just stopped
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called 9-1-1 and then she revived him herself with CPR,''
Dante said. ``I rushed home...but by the time I got there, he was
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I wanted nothing to do with boxing. But my Daddy
wouldn't hear of it thought. He said, 'C'mon you've earned that
spot. You've lost so much already, don't lose this too.'''
</P>
<P>
   After first getting a large tattoo on his right biceps _ one
that features the names of his mother and son with a rose and a
cross _ he went to the Trials that year and was beaten 15-5 by
Larry Mosely, the nation's top ranked boxer at 67 kilograms (147
pounds). The only way Dante, ranked eighth, still could make the
Olympic team was to turn the tables dramatically at the box-offs.
And that's just what he did, beating Mosely twice in three days.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there was one last hurdle. He had to qualify
internationally. After losing to an Argentine boxer in March, he
went to Tijuana the next month and overwhelmed Dominican boxer
Yovanny Lorenzo, 16-3.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been the case too often for him, triumph was followed
by tough times. It turned out he had torn ligaments and a chipped
bone in his right hand during those bouts in Mexico. He had
immediate surgery, wore a cast for eight weeks and wasn't cleared
to begin punching again until Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   That layoff _ along with the fact that he's only had six
international bouts _ have most people writing him off in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   While he should get by Egypt's Fadel Showban Showban in
Saturday's Olympic opener, his division features Oleg Saitov, the
Russian who won gold at the Atlanta Games and Dorel Simion, the
Romanian world champion at 139 pounds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind that, I'm bringing out the dog here,'' said Dante,
who now points his right arm skyward and places his padded left
mitt across his tattoo just before the opening bell. ``For these
fights here, I'm bringing out everything I got. And sometimes that
surprises me. When I see myself fight on video or see pictures of
myself, it's like 'Dawg...You've got real anger in your eyes.' I
got so much built up in me, I scare myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's times when I get to the last rounds and I think I
don't have any energy. Then all of a sudden I feel something
pushing me on. It's energy out of nowhere. I figure it's got to be
my mom. And I figure she'll be in there with me at these Games.
She's the only reason I'm back, the reason I finally made it to the
Olympics. That says a lot about her.''
</P>
<P>
   It says that while she may not have gotten those wings, she's
still managed to get her son soaring higher than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
