<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-REVIEW-BAIT15-COX     09-14 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BAIT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Bait'' review: It's just not that good
 &HT;    By Richard O. Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was going to begin this review of ``Bait'' by saying that
Jamie Foxx's cheap one-liners marred an otherwise fine paranoia
action thriller.
</P>
<P>
   But then, I started thinking about the paranoia action thriller
and realized that there wasn't much there to ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's a good movie buried in there somewhere. But it would
take some serious re-thinking to smooth out the improbabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Foxx is small-time crook Alvin Sanders who gets busted for
stealing seafood. Prawns. It becomes a running joke that someone
will ridicule him for stealing shrimp when he really stole prawns.
Bigger than shrimp. That's the joke. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   He gets put in a cell with Robert Pastorelli, who stole
something even bigger _ $42 million in gold bullion _ but is in
jail for drunken driving. He ditched Bristol, (Doug Hutchison) his
maliciously evil partner, at the scene of the crime, hid the gold
and then got hammered. By the time the feds catch up with him for
the gold, he's had a heart attack and dropped dead.
</P>
<P>
   But not before he gives Alvin clues to the gold's whereabouts,
asking him to tell his wife. Alvin and the feds scour a
preposterous hiding place, thinking the gold is there because
Pastorelli's character was a heavy equipment operator. It's not
where they think it is, however, and the real hiding place, when it
is finally revealed, is even more preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   David Morse stars as U.S. Treasury investigator Clenteen, the
kind of hard-edged guy who takes his job so seriously that he rants
and scowls at any opportunity, especially when someone on the team
tries to make a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Morse is a fine actor, but this is a one-note performance, and
the drone gets to you after a while.
</P>
<P>
   Clenteen gets the bright idea to draw out Bristol by planting
hints that Alvin knows where the gold is. In order to keep track of
Alvin, they plant a combination global positioning device and
microphone in his jaw. The rest of the movie concerns the feds
trying to stay close enough to Alvin to nab
</P>
<P>
   Bristol but without giving themselves away. It would have made
more sense to let Alvin in on the deal. If a man is desperate
enough to steal seafood, surely he would be desperate enough to
actually work with the investigators if they paid him to - which
they do anyway. They let him ``find'' money so
</P>
<P>
   that he won't commit any crimes and get in trouble before they
can catch the
</P>
<P>
   bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few funny moments in ``Bait,'' and I enjoyed the
climactic scene at the race track even though the sequence was
lifted straight from ``The Screenwriter's Idea Book'' (how many
movies feature a bomb on a timer with big red numbers?).
</P>
<P>
   It might have been better if they paid more attention to the
story and characters and less on trying to make it funny. A movie
like ``Enemy of the State'' works much better by allowing the star
(Will Smith in that case) work his charm in the context of a
coherent script. It's a balancing act in any case. It just doesn't
work here. Fans of Jamie Foxx's television show may relish the
chance to see him in a
</P>
<P>
   big-budget, big-screen caper, but the rest of us might wait
until it plays on video or cable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
