<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACK15-COX     09-14 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tucker grad gets a tuneup
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ A day after settling into the Olympic Village, Tucker
High grad Dwight Phillips won the long jump at an informal meet
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, second at the Olympic trials, took just two jumps and
won with a best of 25 feet, 8 inches. ``I haven't competed much
since the trials, so it was a good little practice,'' Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the meet from the stands were Southwest DeKalb products
Terrence Trammell and Angelo Taylor, neither of whom elected to
compete. Taylor and Phillips are roommates here, and both stood out
in the crowd wearing their Atlanta Braves caps.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he's motivated to perform well at the Games after
Australian long jumper Jai Taurima referred to the American jumpers
as ``dark athletes'' and suggested they wouldn't fare well in the
cool Sydney conditions. In addition to his racial remarks, Taurima
dimissed Phillips, Melvin Lister and Savante Stringfellow as a
``bunch of dribblers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely motivates me more than ever,'' Phillips said.
``At the Games, it's going to add a couple inches, maybe a foot,
because of that comment. I hope it's 30 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Taurima didn't show at Thursday's competition, and hasn't
approached the Americans since his remarks last month. ``I guess
he's dodging us,'' Phillips cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had his own side issue to address, saying he'd be
disappointed if U.S. coaches don't have him run the 1,600-meter
relay final. The coaches have said they won't finalize the relay
teams until after the athletes finish competing in their individual
events, with Taylor being a gold medal favorite in the 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   However, assistant coach Bubba Thornton, who handles the 1,600
relay, spoke of Taylor as something of a luxury: ``We know he's
sitting there if we need to go that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring injury, three relay spots appear set with open 400
runners Michael Johnson, Antonio Pettigrew and Alvin Harrison.
Taylor has beaten the other Americans when he's run the open 400
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I should be able to run the relay,'' said Taylor,
who earned a gold medal on the relay at last summer's World
Championships. ``I've beaten these guys in the 400. A lot of guys
can only run from behind. I've proven I can run out front, and
that's important because we're probably going to have the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
