<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATE0915-COX     09-14 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Debate debate is over,' Bush agrees to proposed scheduleBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ Eleven days after he drew a line in the sand
about a debate schedule, Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday walked
across it and signed on to the plan demanded by Democratic foe Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the capitulation marked another strategy-gone-bad in a
campaign that has taken him from frontrunner to self-proclaimed
underdog. Bush has gotten little traction with a tax-cut plan that
is a campaign centerpiece, and, according to polls, now trails Gore
on all major issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, still blaming Gore for the debate impasse,
said it had gained a more free-flowing format by not agreeing to a
schedule set earlier by a bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates agreed Thursday to square off Oct. 3 in Boston,
Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C. and Oct. 17 in St. Louis. Each
debate, sponsored by the Presidential Debates commission, will last
90 minutes in a format yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidential candidates Dick Cheney and Joe Lieberman will
debate Oct. 5 in Danville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased that the campaigns have agreed to these
plans,'' the commission said after meeting with Gore and Bush
campaign officials in Washington. ``The American public can look
forward to four substantive discussions of the issues central to
this general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said a campaign
attorney had confirmed that a videotape anonymously mailed to the
Gore campaign was a tape of a Bush practice debate. Gore supporter
Tom Downey had turned the tape over to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said there was still no word on who sent the tape and
related materials to Downey. She said she had no way to know
whether Bush's debate effort would be compromised by the purloined
tape.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, then it would mark another setback in what has been
a troublesome three weeks for the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Recent state-by-state surveys, for the first time, indicate Gore
has solid leads in states with electoral votes approaching 270, the
number needed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The polls show Gore leading in 15 states plus the District of
Columbia with a total 224 electoral votes. Bush led in 21 states
with 171 electoral votes. Another 14 states and 143 electoral votes
are toss ups.
</P>
<P>
   The debates that could go a long way to determining the race
have been a sticking point for several weeks, with each camp
blaming the other for the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the debate schedule intensified on Sept. 3, when
Bush was firm in opposing the commission's proposed schedule. He
said he would accept only a three-debate schedule including
appearances on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and CNN's ``Larry King
Live'' and the St. Louis debate proposed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our final answer,'' Bush campaign chairman Don Evans
said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, that answer turned out to be semi-final for Bush,
who is trailing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is very eager to debate,'' Evans said after a
meeting in Washington with Gore Chairman William Daley and
commission officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the GOP nominee has gained a lot by initially
rejecting the commission debate schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were arguing for all along is what we are now
succeeding with, which was a more unstructured, more free-flowing
format which we think serves the American public much better than
which candidate can best memorize a 30-second response,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk, a commission co-chairman and former Democratic
National Committee chairman, did not want to talk about who had won
or lost in the battle over the joint appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major thing is that the debate debate is over,'' said
Kirk.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had rejected Bush's proposed schedule, criticizing it as an
effort to reduce the audience by limiting two of the debates to
single-network coverage. Bush tried to shift the blame to Gore,
noting the Democrat had promised to debate ``anytime, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As late as Wednesday, Bush was still trying to blame Gore for
the debate imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the debates, if the man will show up,'' Bush
told a rally in Westminster, Cal.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, before the agreement was announced, Bush, in a Los
Angeles television interview, was defending his earlier plan to
include two debates that probably would have been carried by a
single broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the thing,'' Bush said, ``if people want to watch the
debates there will be plenty of outlets for them to watch the
debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's efforts to blame Gore, a CBS/New York Times poll
completed this week showed the GOP nominee was losing the debate on
debates. Seventy percent of the respondents said they believed Gore
truly wants to debate. Only 59 percent said they believe Bush wants
debates.
</P>
<P>
   GOP strategist Scott Reed, campaign manager for Bob Dole's 1996
presidential bid, said Bush's position was untenable for a
candidate trailing in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get the debate schedule set sooner rather than
later and begin to focus on the first debate,'' said Reed. ``It
appears to me that the race is frozen until the first debate and
that all this campaigning is just background noise.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush on Thursday, all this campaigning included pitching his
military message in a speech beamed to the National Guard
Association convention in New Jersey, and his education message in
an appearance at Santa Ana High School.
</P>
<P>
   The military speech included a shot at Gore, based on a New York
Times report concerning Documents being reviewed by the Justice
Department indicating Gore was asked to make a fund-raising phone
call in 1995 to a trial lawyer Walter Umphrey of Beaumont involved
in tobacco industry litigation. Umphrey and his firm later gave
$790,000 to the Democratic Party after President Clinton vetoed a
bill to limit liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore aide said the vice president never made the phone call.
But Bush pounced on the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll restore the bond of trust between a president and all
Americans,'' Bush said near the end of the speech. ``Just today
there are new revelations about the potential misuse of the White
House for fundraising purposes. New evidence that my opponent may
have crossed a serious line, solicitation of campaign contributions
linked to a presidential veto.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has tried to make character an issue, drew applause
when he said, ``The appearance is really disturbing. Americans are
tired of investigations and scandal and the best way to get rid of
them is to elect a new President who will bring a new
administration who will restore honor and dignity to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
