<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-HALLIBURTON15-COX     09-14 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HALLIBURTON15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Was Hodges Mitchell the best player for the UT?
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question made Hodges Mitchell pause. He rubbed his head for
several moments, then wiped the sweat off his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to ask that question to someone else,''
Mitchell said, obviously uncomfortable with the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The question?
</P>
<P>
   Was Hodges Mitchell, pound for pound, the best player for the
University of Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell deferred to a higher authority, anyone other than
himself. He really is one of those humble team guys.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll say what others should be saying. Mitchell, all 5 feet 6
1/2 inches and 181 pounds of him, is the best and most reliable
player the Longhorns have on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   He wins top player because of his versatility and his ability to
prove others wrong. He is the smallest Longhorn starter, yet he can
run, catch and block like he's 6-0 and 220, the size he wishes
genetics had assigned him. He even is returning punts this year,
knowing that some kamikaze special teams player, running at him
with a full head of steam, could ruin his season with a single
spear.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell didn't start his season last Saturday with
headline-making numbers. With the Longhorns choosing to hurry up on
offense against Louisiana-Lafayette, Mitchell carried only eight
times for 31 yards. But he returned five punts for an average of
8.6 yards and caught two passes for 30. Statistics don't show the
number of blocks he made to protect quarterbacks Major Applewhite
and Chris Simms.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Mitchell walked out of the locker room with a
broad smile on his face and a bounce in his step. He only had UT's
52-10 victory on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 thing with Hodges is if we win,'' said UT running
backs coach Bruce Chambers. ``That's all he cares about. If he ran
for a million yards, and we lose, he's not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about Hodges is he's so versatile. He can run
back punts and kicks. Heck, he can go out and play wide receiver,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers coached against Mitchell when the tailback was playing
for Skyline High School in Dallas and Chambers was at nearby
Carter. Chambers jokingly tells Mitchell that he hasn't forgiven
him for going to Skyline, a magnet school in the Dallas Independent
School District, rather than staying close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to coach Hodges Mitchell,'' Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell lived only a five-minute drive from powerhouse Carter,
yet it was Skyline that benefited from Mitchell's 5,005 career
rushing yards and 65 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   When Mitchell first arrived at Texas in 1997, he knew he was
there to be the chief backup to Ricky Williams. That was the season
Williams, the future Heisman Trophy winner, started playing
tailback after spending his first two years at UT as a fullback.
Early in 1997, then-Coach John Mackovic actually found himself
answering questions as to why he wouldn't move Williams back to
fullback to allow Mitchell to see more action at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   So it was Mitchell who had the misfortune of following Williams'
historic presence in the Longhorns' backfield last season. He
responded the best way possible, with an All-Big 12 Conference
year, rushing for 1,343 yards, the fifth-best single-season
performance in UT history.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing a lot of people don't know about Hodges is that he's
so strong,'' said UT defensive tackle Casey Hampton. ``He can run
over you. It's hard for one person to bring him down. He's so
short, he's got more leverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's like really quick and real shifty.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the off-season, it was a common topic in the media, on
radio talk shows and in internet chat rooms that the Longhorns'
running game was the offense's weak link. A running back who can
put up those kind of numbers shouldn't be subject to such
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard all that talk, too,'' Mitchell said earlier this week.
``I listened to it, but I didn't let it bother me. Everybody got
spoiled with Ricky Williams. They've got to adjust to a new running
back now.''
</P>
<P>
   The pros have noticed Mitchell as well, although NFL scouts are
well aware of Mitchell's less than intimidating physique. The
National Football Scouting Service, based out of Tulsa, Okla.,
graded Mitchell at 4.8 on an 8.0 scale after evaluating him in the
spring. His grade classifies him as a priority free agent for next
April's draft. It says Mitchell can improve on that score with a
nice senior season and move into the draft's mid-to-late rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The scouts like his speed and the fact that he can catch. His
skills at returning punts also will be scrutinized this fall, which
could move him out of the category of third-down back.
</P>
<P>
   If Mitchell is looking at the pros, he isn't saying. He is set
to earn his degree in business next summer. His grade point average
is 3.1 on a 4.0 scale, which is as impressive, given his course
load, as his accomplishments last season.
</P>
<P>
   But the one thing Mitchell has yet to handle is public praise.
It makes him squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not deserving of any hype,'' he says. ``I'm just trying to
be a team player. The team deserves the hype, not me. I do believe
in myself, I'm just not cocky.''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Suzanne Halliburton at
shalliburton(at)statesman.com
</P>
