<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.15.00
 &HT;    Compiled by Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   UPS, Delta among most Net-savvy
</P>
<P>
   B of A uses Web to add ATM services
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. taxis to put e-mail in riders' reach
</P>
<P>
   NET-SAVVY: United Parcel Service and Delta Air Lines are two of
corporate America's most Net-savvy businesses, according to the
latest edition of BusinessWeek magazine. In a special e.biz section
in its Sept. 18 edition, the magazine praises the two Atlanta-based
companies and 48 others among the ``nifty-fifty'' for having a
knack for using the Web to gain a competitive edge. UPS, through
its online logistics services, helps companies manage everything
from inventory control to tracking shipments. The company has
generated $1.4 billion in revenue and commands 55 percent of the
e-business-related shipping market. Delta, the nation's
third-largest carrier and the largest one operating at Hartsfield
International Airport, also gets a nod from the magazine for using
the Web to automate ticketing, offer wireless network links at its
gates and offer its employees free Internet access and subsidized
computers. BusinessWeek said all of the companies are using the Web
to ``set new standards for speed, efficiency and service.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peralte C. Paul
</P>
<P>
   www.ups.com and www.delta.com
</P>
<P>
   BANKING ON THE NET: Bank of America will link 10 of its Atlanta
ATMs to the Internet this year as part of a plan to create
full-service banking centers. Eventually all of its 14,300 ATMs
across the country will be ``Web-enabled.'' Transactions on the
high-tech cash machines should be faster, officials say. That's the
only immediate difference customers should expect. The machines
won't have access to e-mail accounts, for example. But in the
future, customers may be able to view images of checks, send
messages to the bank, monitor investments and buy goods and
services. Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. debuted its Internet ATMs in May.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christine Van Dusen
</P>
<P>
   YOU'VE GOT C-MAIL: Assuming you're lucky enough to hail one,
many New York taxicabs soon may come equipped with hand-held Palm
VII computers for riders who want to check their e-mail or surf the
Net while zig-zagging through Manhattan. Yahoo and Medallion
Financial Corp. are teaming up to put the Palms in 1,000 cabs
across the nation over the next year, starting with 10 that will
make their debut in the Big Apple today. The Palms will be built
into the partition separating driver and passenger.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   TIGHTENING PURSE STRINGS: A new report from PC Data Online shows
consumers pulled back on online spending last month. While
Amazon.com remained the No.1 online retail destination with 1.6
million buyers, that was down from 1.8 million in July.
Ticketmaster.com remained No. 2 with an estimated 595,000 buyers,
followed by buy.com (466,000) and CDnow.com (441,000). Clothing
retailer J.Crew posted the largest gain, jumping from No. 47 in
July to No. 18 in August. The sample included 120,000 home Internet
users.
</P>
<P>
   HOT/COLD NET STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Conexant Systems (ticker symbol CNXT), up 40 percent at $51.94.
The firm plans to spin off its Internet infrastructure business
into a separate company. Several analysts also upgraded the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com (BNBN), up 10 percent at $4.81. The online
bookseller plans to acquire technology and business bookseller
Fatbrain.com for $64 million in stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   EBay (EBAY), up 9 percent at $67.84. Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
analyst Anthony Noto recommended investors buy the auctioneer and
Amazon.com before their executives meet with analysts next week.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia Network (STRM), down 14 percent at $9.91. The online
network, which targets Latin America, said it will cut 15 percent
of its work force. The company, which expects to be profitable in
the fourth quarter of 2001, also said top executives sold shares
last month.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.15.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   MedCareer launches health care job site
</P>
<P>
   MedCareers Inc., an Atlanta-based health care career network,
has launched a new Web site that targets government health care job
seekers and employers.
</P>
<P>
   www.govmedcareers.com
</P>
<P>
   EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS CONFERENCE: Replays of Friedman, Billings, Ramsey
Group's recent two-day 7th Annual Investor Conference in Washington
are available. The conference attracted 220 companies and more than
1,000 institutional investors, portfolio managers, analysts, and
executives.
</P>
<P>
   www.fbr.com; available on-demand for 60 days.
</P>
