<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ORKIN-VERDICT0915-COX     09-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORKIN-VERDICT0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rollins to appeal Ala. verdict
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Rollins Inc. said that a recent $80.8
million verdict in Alabama against its Orkin Exterminating unit
will have ''a material adverse impact'' on the company if the award
is not reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins will appeal the award, said the company's filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, dated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a jury in Macon County, Ala., found that Orkin
breached a longtime termite contract with Artie Mae Jeter of
Tuskegee and committed fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter and her lawyers had alleged that Orkin hid extensive
termite damage to her home for at least 15 years. Orkin employees
propped the house up on cinder blocks and jacks to conceal the
damage, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Jeter's family $800,000 in compensatory damages
and $80 million in punitive damages. Jeter died in December at age
88.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the company's position that it complied with its
contractual obligations and that it did not attempt to conceal
alleged misconduct or suppress material facts,'' Rollins said in
the SEC filing. Orkin spokeswoman Martha May said Thursday that the
Rollins filing was voluntary, designed ''to inform shareholders
that this event has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   If the award is upheld, May said, ''it would affect the
profitability of the company, which would affect the stock.'' But
Orkin believes the award will be reduced upon appeal, she said.
``Historically, Alabama juries will award enormous verdicts against
companies,'' May said. ``Almost every single one of them has been
reduced substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin is also the defendant in a class-action lawsuit in Alabama
that alleges the company skipped annual termite reinspections and
forged customers' names on inspection tickets. A similar suit seeks
class-action status in Florida, with homeowners claiming thousands
of dollars each in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Orkin denies the charges in each case.
</P>
<P>
   The pest-control industry, meanwhile, is drawing increased
scrutiny from government officials in several states. Questionable
termite practices have sparked a multistate investigation of the
industry, in conjunction with a Federal Trade Commission inquiry.
And according to Florida Assistant Attorney General Bob Buchner,
Florida and five other states are investigating Orkin. Georgia is
not among them.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeter lawsuit, filed in 1999, grew out of the Alabama class
action after a memo from an Orkin branch manager surfaced,
describing Jeter's termite damage. That 1988 memo, said Jeter
co-counsel Jock Smith, was ''by far, the most compelling evidence
in the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, Branch Manager Bill Maxwell wrote to Orkin District
Manager Jim Turner that Jeter ''feels people have taken advantage
of her over the years, and she is tired of being ripped off. My
personal observation of work done to her home indicates this is a
true statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell, a co-defendant, added, ``To my knowledge, no one has
really told her the true extent to which her house is infested. We
sold her a termite treatment in Sept. 1977 and a moisture and jack
job in Dec. 1984. Nothing has ever been graphed or documented as to
termite damage in her house. We took her money and never really
told her the truth about the serious termite problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo discussed Orkin's treatment choices, with Maxwell
saying it would be cheaper and faster to build Jeter a new house
than repair her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can spend $5,000 now and have her put in small claims over
the years until she dies and her children sell the house, or if any
attorney gets involved, we will probably buy her a new house,
thousands in punitive damages and attorney fees,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Maxwell nor Turner is still with Orkin, May said
Thursday. The memo, she said, was intended to urge an Orkin vice
president to pay termite claims.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins, in its SEC filing, said the company made $23,000 in
repairs to Jeter's home.
</P>
<P>
   May said the house had termite damage prior to Jeter's first
contract with Orkin, in 1977. The jacks and cinder blocks, she
added, addressed structural problems in the house, not the termite
damage.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter co-counsel Steve Etheredge of Dothan said that ''from
1977 up until 1998, in each of the annual reinspections of this
property, Orkin indicated to her no evidence had been found of
subterranean termites.'' Orkin did the repairs to ''conceal the
fact the house was totally destroyed,'' Etheredge added.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's son Robert, also of Tuskegee, said Thursday, ``I wish my
mother had lived to see the outcome of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury sent a message to Orkin to get their act together,''
Jeter said. ``You don't ruin people's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, internal memos written by Orkin executives in
Florida, Georgia and Texas showed that company employees falsified
reinspections of homes for termite damage. The memos, written in
April 1996 after an internal company audit, said many Orkin
customers are ''being charged for services not rendered.''
</P>
<P>
   The memos, which surfaced in connection with the Florida
lawsuit, told Orkin branch managers to stop practices of ''fraud,
theft and forgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Orkin acknowledges a problem with reinspections and forgeries in
Georgia and Florida, though it says it was not an extensive
practice. Orkin has cleaned up the reinspection problems, company
spokeswoman May said.
</P>
<P>
   Orkin is the No. 2 pest-control company in revenues behind
Terminix. Rollins, which reported 1999 revenue of $586.6 million,
has its headquarters on Piedmont Road in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins shares rose 13 cents to close at $15 Thursday in New
York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
