</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-SCHOOL-ART-NYT     09-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SCHOOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY CHILDREN IN TURKEY DON'T GET AN OPPORTUNITY TO GO TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YENIDOGAN, Turkey _ Murat Kilic summoned forth all the bravado a
14-year-old could muster, shook his head back and forth vigorously
and said he never liked school anyway and he was proud to be
working to help support his family.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as he watched his friends clowning around nearby, his
facade collapsed in a deep shrug of his frail shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard and dirty work,'' he said, displaying the scars and
calluses on his hands from toiling in a metal-fabrication shop 10
hours a day for $200 a month. ``I'm there _ and they are learning
something in school.''
</P>
<P>
   About 14 million children started the new school year across
Turkey this week, donning uniforms and filling overcrowded
classrooms. But a million other children were not there. Instead,
most were working in factories, fields, shops and the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Like Murat, many of these children dropped out of school at the
end of the fifth grade before the government raised compulsory
attendance to eighth grade two years ago. Thousands of other
children never start school.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reasons are the same as in other developing
countries. Many children are needed to earn money for their
families, or they stay at home and take care of siblings while
their parents work. Others come from families that do not value
formal education.
</P>
<P>
   But other factors have shut the school door for large segments
of the Turkish population. A new report by the World Bank said most
of the country's 30,000 villages do not have a school that goes
beyond fifth grade. To continue their education, students must
commute by bus to another town or go to a boarding school. Both
options are often too expensive for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis also found that girls, particularly those from poor
rural families, are twice as likely as boys to drop out before
finishing eighth grade. Nearly half the women are illiterate in
southeastern Turkey, the poorest region, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in richer urban areas like Istanbul or Ankara, poor people
who want to send their children to school face difficulties. The
uniforms that are mandatory at most public schools cost $75 or $80,
and families must pay at least as much for textbooks and other
basic supplies because schools do not get enough money from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   On top of those costs, parents who want their children to attend
good public schools are often required to pay $200 to $300 a year
under the table for each child for additional expenses that are not
covered by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The schools themselves are overcrowded and teachers are
underpaid. The average class size is 64 pupils, and Turkey's
525,000 teachers earn an average of about $300 a month, according
to statistics from the education workers union. That is barely
above the country's per capita income of $3,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey needs 190,000 more teachers and 106,000 more classrooms
and only then can we have 30 kids to a class,'' said Alaattin
Dincer, president of the education union.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of increasing, the percentage of government budgets
spent for education has declined steadily in the last decade to a
level below the standard of countries with comparable income, the
World Bank analysis said.
</P>
<P>
   The national government, which provides the money for education,
has been increasing military defense spending instead, although the
Ministry of Education said that 152,000 new teachers had been hired
in the last four years in an attempt to reduce overcrowding and
that there were plans to hire more next year.
</P>
<P>
   While Germany spends $817 per student annually and Greece $240,
Turkey spends only $90.
</P>
<P>
   No one understands those statistics more clearly than Mehmet
Kapuca, the principal of the elementary school in this poor
village.
</P>
<P>
   When the doors of Huseyin Tolgacan Sipahi Elementary School
opened this week, he was confronted by 1,876 pupils in eight
grades. They are deployed in double shifts, with half starting at
7:30 a.m.and the others at 12:50 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowded classrooms defy most prescriptions for good
learning. The older pupils are jammed 80 to a classroom, with a
single teacher. Even in the smallest classroom, for 50 first
graders, three children share each desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard job to teach here and to go to school here,''
Kapuca said as he rifled through drawings for a badly needed new
school, something that was promised years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Yenidogan's 5,000 or so residents fled rural areas for
this extended suburb about 20 miles southeast of Istanbul. They
live in half-finished houses and struggle to find the money to send
their children to school.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a stack of textbooks in his office, Kapuca said
donations had provided some books for the poorest children, and
collections are taken up for their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Murat Kilic would have been wearing the tie and blazer of an
eighth grader at Huseyin Tolgacan Sipahi had he not left to help
support three brothers and sisters. Instead of rising before dawn
to accompany his father to the metal shop where they work side by
side, he would have been sitting alongside his friends, snickering
at slides of the human body or struggling to understand a math
problem.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had never liked school and does not miss it, but he
pretended to be sick Monday and Tuesday to skip work and hang out
with his friends after they finished classes. And when they put
their bags on the dirty field to play, he admonished them to be
more careful with the books inside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
