<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SAFE-KIDS15-COX     09-14 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFE-KIDS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conference to to focus on strong families
 &HT;    By Mary Lolli
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Ohio _ Country music star Barbara Mandrell is helping
Butler County commissioners launch what they hope will be an annual
conference focused on building strong families and keeping children
safe in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``Safe Kids, Strong Families Conference,'' Mandrell
will be keynote speaker for the forum's kickoff event Monday at
Lakota East High School.
</P>
<P>
   Mandrell, twice-named Mother of the Year, will talk about
family, parenting and her life experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Mandrell in the kickoff event will be Ohio First Lady
Hope Taft and musician Todd Snyder. The conference coincides with
Ohio's Parents Week observation, designated by Gov. Bob Taft.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the conference will be held at the Harry T.
Wilks Conference Center and Parrish Auditorium at Miami
University's Hamilton campus.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, to run through Sept. 21, is designed to create a
forum to engage community groups as agents in building strong
families and to promote safety for children, according to
conference coordinator Katie Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to participate are people involved with
family and social service organizations and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something commissioners had been thinking about doing
for a while,'' Weber said. ``And with all the problems that cropped
up recently with (Butler County) Children Services issues and the
duplication of efforts among different county agencies, the time
was right to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said the conference is a vehicle for initiating
discussions between families and the professional agencies that
serve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The professionals need to hear what the families have to say,
and the families need to hear what the professionals can offer
them,'' Weber said. ``They need to start to listen to each other
and learn what works in making families stronger and keeping kids
safe. It's kind of a combination. We're hitting the issues from
both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Each day of the conference will include general sessions with
keynote speakers covering a range of topics such as ``Ethics,
Confidentiality and the Courts'' and ``Help Create a World Where
All Children Are Safe and Happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference also includes smaller breakout sessions on
narrower topics such as intervention, diversity, violence, signs of
child abuse, learning disabilities and parenting after a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mandrell, others who will be giving keynote
addresses include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Adele Faber, who co-wrote the book, ``How To Talk So Kids Will
Listen and Listen So Kids Will Talk.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lonise Bias, mother of University of Maryland basketball star
and Boston Celtics recruit Len Bias, whose drug-related death
stunned the sports world in 1986. Four years later, the Bias family
lost another son, Jay, in a drive-by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thom Hartmann, an internationally known psychologist who will
share his unique perspective on learning, living and parenting in
today's society and discuss the myths of attention deficit
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   n Joanne McDaniel, associate director of the Center for the
Prevention of School Violence, who will talk about creating schools
that are safe and secure.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the kickoff featuring Mandrell and other evening
sessions are $10. Tickets for the workshops and seminars are $25
each day. Tickets and registration will be available the day of
each event or may be purchased in advance. For more information,
call (513) 785-5957.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
