<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-BOS &LR;      09-14 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK TARGETS CONSERVATIVE RELIGIOUS PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak has made a bid for
political survival by mounting a direct challenge to the power of
Israel's conservative religious parties.
</P>
<P>
   But observers said it remains to be seen if Barak's move will
prove to be a genuine new direction for his government or political
ploy to turn the tables on the religious parties that provided key
support in forming his coalition government last year only to
mutiny this July.
</P>
<P>
   Saying Barak had gone too far in making concessions to
Palestinians in the failed peace talks at Camp David, the powerful
ultra-Orthodox Shas party broke from Barak's now fractured
coalition Thursday and vowed to join other conservative parties to
topple his government when the parliament convenes in October.
</P>
<P>
   The plan outlined by Barak would redraw the lines between
religious and secular life in Israel by dismantling the powerful
Religious Affairs Ministry, establishing civil marriage outside the
control of Ultra Orthodox rabbis, and permiting planes and expanded
bus lines to operate on the Jewish sabbath. It would also impose a
national service requirement on religious Yeshiva students who are
currently exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary plans also call for completing a constitution
that would, after more than a half century, define the Israeli
democracy in terms that make room for Palestinian Muslims and
Christians and other non-Jewish citizens who live within it.
</P>
<P>
   After an impassioned debate Thursday, 100 leaders of Barak's
Labor Party voted overwhelmingly to confront the religious parties
head-on and unanimously adopted Barak's platform for a ``civil
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli media dubbed the plan ``a civil revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   By confronting the religious parties on the issues that matter
to them most, Barak seemed to recognize the hemorrhaging of secular
voters from his traditionally liberal Labor Party. Many of them
objected to Barak's failed partnership with Shas, an increasingly
powerful party whose base is the ``sephardim,'' immigrant Jews
predominantly from North African countries such as Morroco.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an attempt to extend a hand to the predominantly
secular Russian immigrants of Natan Sharansky's Yisrael ba-Aliya
party, which also broke with Barak's coalition and vowed to join
Shas in an effort to call for early elections when the parliament,
or Knesset, reconvenes next month.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's dramatic change in direction _ away from Shas and
back to his traditional secular supporters _ made even ardent
supporters of civil reform nervous. Barak is regarded as solidly
secular at his core, but many felt that he unforgiveably betrayed
that core by siding with Shas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost his way. It seems like he is panicking,'' said
Shulamit Aloni, the gray eminence of the civil reform movement and
one of the founders of the Meretz Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked all my life for these reforms, but I can't take this
proposal seriously. He lost his credibility,'' added Aloni, 70, who
retired in 1997 after 30 years in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak is very smart. But ultimately he is a commando who works
with secrecy, undercover tactics, and anything it takes to get the
mission accomplished,'' she said. ``Unfortunately, you can't
achieve peace that way. You can't achieve civil revolution either.
To do that you have to act like a prime minister, like a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is has been struggling to break the deadlock in the peace
talks and clinch a final agreement with the Palestinians just as
the move to topple him is taking hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we conclude conditions are not ripe for a (final peace)
agreement, then the civil agenda will come center stage,'' said
Barak in his speech at the storied Labor Party Headquarters,
beneath huge portraits of Israel's founding father David Ben Gurion
and assassinated prime minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and some party officials said Barak's reversal was a
designed to assemble a new political base that would allow him to
survive politically if there is no peace deal by extending a hand
to the strongly secular constituencies within the conservative
Likud and Russian immigrant parties.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of his plan platform could be enacted immediately by
executive fiat, Labor officials said, including the dismantling of
the Religious Affairs Ministry. Critics have charged that it has
become a huge patronage mill for Shas and other religious parties.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals would require another vote next Thursday by the
Labor Party's 2,600-member Central Council, and would then need the
approval of the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Although Israeli politics are famous for fractious coalitions,
passionate rhetoric, deep divisions, and elaborate political ploys,
there is no more powerfully emotional fault line than the one that
cuts between the secular and the religious. It is a divide that has
everything to do with how the Jewish state defines itself.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including some of Barak's supporters, called Barak's
criss-crossing of this line a cynical and potentially dangerous
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Menachem Friedman, professor of sociology at Bar Ilan
University, a modern Orthodox believer, and a respected analyst of
the growing power of the ultra-Orthodox, said he was worried about
launching a political debate that would pit the secular against the
religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli society has the seeds within to even have a civil
war on this issue. And I say that not as an exaggeration, but as a
truth,'' said Friedman. ``It pulls the country apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a maneuver, a tactic to win by putting together a
secular agenda. But Barak has a problem: It doesn't look real.
People do not take him seriously. They don't know who he is, and
Israelis don't like that. They like to know who they are dealing
with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
