<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-RECOVERY0915-CO     09-14 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-RECOVERY0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road to recovery after the flood is rough
 &HT;    By Chad Dunbar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ For Beanie and Jeff Collins, the roughest
part wasn't watching floodwaters ruin their family home. It wasn't
throwing away heirlooms and cherrywood furniture pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to start all over again _ that's the toughest part,''
Beanie Collins said. ``It takes so much to start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   As with scores of others across Eastern North Carolina, the
Collinses have waited all these months after the water receded for
life to approach normal _ but still a full recovery seems distant.
</P>
<P>
   The Collinses doled out money in December to buy a home on
higher ground, and now they await their day in the buyout program.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration still is evident everywhere one year after Hurricane
Floyd. With recovery programs in cities, towns and wide spots in
the road after the historic storm, it is hard to see much progress.
Although it is one year after the flood, hard-hit areas are just
now receiving money and gearing up recovery projects.
</P>
<P>
   The behemoth storm pinwheeled up the East Coast last September,
putting communities in 66 Eastern North Carolina counties under the
largest swath of flooding in state history. Entire neighborhoods
now are abandoned, people still live in travel trailers and nearly
$850 million is set aside for disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Mount Mayor Fred Turnage said the Twin Counties _ one of
the hardest-hit areas _ has traveled the roughest part of the road
to recovery. The treetop rescues and evacuations are over, and the
city is focusing its efforts on buying ruined homes and moving
residents into higher homes, well away from the threat of future
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge is not being able to see an end in
sight,'' Turnage said. ``It will be a number of years until we
really realize the impact of Hurricane Floyd.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's buyout program is the largest disaster recovery
program in the history of the United States, and it promises to
last through 2001. State leaders were not prepared for such a
widespread natural disaster, not to mention recover from one. For
months, people complained about the slow trickle of money and the
wall of red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we've never done this before,'' said Leza
Aycock, director of the N.C. Hurricane Floyd Redevelopment Center.
``We had to start from scratch, develop programs and implement
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, just finding and contacting all the flood victims was
difficult. Most called the Federal Emergency Management Agency's
toll-free number to register for federal disaster assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, FEMA is not permitted by federal law to release
those names to the state,'' she said. ``FEMA's been great in
cooperating with us, and they've done a lotoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question in Grand Forks is `When is it going to be like it
was before the flood?''' said Kevin Dean, Grand Forks disaster
recovery center spokesman. ``They want the whole idea of recovery
behind them. But I don't think we will ever be normal like it was
before the flood.''
</P>
<P>
   The flood's scars remain evident in the Twin Counties. The
water-stained shell of Tarrytown Mall, the first mall built in
Eastern North Carolina, stands as a glaring example of the ill
effects Floyd left on Twin Counties business.
</P>
<P>
   The main business corridors in Rocky Mount soaked for days in
several feet of brown water. Now, a majority of flood-torn
businesses have reopened, paving the way for an explosion in
ribbon-cutting ceremonies in the last six months. But getting to
that point has placed a heavy financial burden on the business
owners' shoulders, said Charlie Glazener, president of the Rocky
Mount Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the businesses have to pay off 30-year loans,''
Glazener said. ``We still have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The flood discouraged Twin Counties leaders. Rivers and creeks
surged over their banks and stayed that way, in some places, for
weeks. Decades of work spent building the communities washed away
in a single event.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Mount's arts center, a children's museum, swimming pools
and bridges - all were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Steve Raper didn't tour the city until the chaos
settled six days after Floyd - and the sights of destruction hit
him like a knockout punch. The city's recovery effort, he said, is
well ahead of other communities in the state, but there are miles
of road left until recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even one year later, we have a lot of accomplishments, and
there's still a lot of stuff left to do,'' Raper said. ``Getting
everyone back to where they were is a long-term effort. The people
in Grand Forks said we will come back bigger and better than ever,
and I believe that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has set up a full-scale hazard mitigation office to
lead its recovery effort, concentrating efforts on rebuilding homes
and businesses and preventing future flood catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout program, the city's biggest project, will move 400
homes built in the floodplain. Houses will be bulldozed to the
ground and acres of land will be cleared, never to be developed for
residents again.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have several land-use options. The leveled land
can simply lie barren, or the city could use it for additional
parks space, adding hiking trails and picnic tables. But the city
is far away from such an endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of things that can be done,'' Raper said,
``and that's what we are going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The city could follow in the footsteps of its flood-disaster
predecessor, Grand Forks. Residents there have become experts on
the rigors to recovery. Dean said some of the same hurdles lie
ahead for Eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what it is like,'' Dean said. ``It has taken longer
than any of us ever expected. It's something that has impacted
people so completely and permanently that no one's lives will be
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
