u p BC-NY-LAZIO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFRONTATIONAL LAZIO GIVES HILLARY CLINTON A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robin Gelburd is one of those people who have long
confounded Hillary Clinton _ a white, liberal, professional woman
in New York's suburbs who agrees with the First Lady on the issues
but is reluctant to vote her into the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But while watching the New York senate candidates' debate
Wednesday night, Gelburd started shifting her view. ``I think I can
look beyond the things I don't like about her personally,'' she
said Thursday. ``I probably will vote for her.''
</P>
<P>
   What got to her was the intensity of the attacks on Clinton by
her opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, he showed a lot of spunk in confronting her
directly,'' Gelburd said. ``On the other hand, I saw for the first
time a slight chink in her armor. To see her in the rough and
tumble, I could feel for her as a human being. Lazio came close to
crossing the line of a schoolyard bully.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, too early to gauge the effects of the debate.
But Gelburd's response raises some questions that go beyond the
reactions of many professional commentators.
</P>
<P>
   One typical comment, going into the debate, was that the
boyish-looking Lazio would win marks just by showing he could hold
his own with the worldly Clinton. He certainly accomplished that
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazio didn't get run out of the room and that's what he had to
worry about,'' Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College
Polling Institute, said after the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a draw _ and if it's a draw, give the win to Lazio,''
pollster John Zogby agreed.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Lazio scored his best points when he _ or the
debate's aggressive moderator, Tim Russert _ had Clinton on the
run, especially when discussing her 1993 health-care plan and the
whole complex of issues involving, as Lazio put it, ``trust and
character.''
</P>
<P>
   This could only have boosted Lazio's standing with his core
constituency _ those who support him precisely because they so
dislike Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But what about those in the middle, those who have problems with
Clinton but are waiting for Lazio to give them a strong reason to
vote for him?
</P>
<P>
   Women like Gelburd are in this grey area. So are many in one of
New York's critical constituencies _ Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dov Hikind is an outspoken conservative state assemblyman from
Brooklyn who has a lot of contacts and influence in the Orthodox
Jewish community, and he did not like Lazio's approach at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazio did himself a tremendous disservice with all those
personal attacks,'' Hikind said Thursday. ``I've talked with a lot
of conservative people and without exception, they felt he was
nasty. This is not the way a senator should handle himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind plans on publicly endorsing one candidate or another in
the next couple weeks. Though he would not say which way he is
leaning, he said he was ``considering Hillary Clinton _ and that
alone surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Lazio's campaign were not returned Thursday. It is not
known whether, buoyed by his own feistiness, Lazio will continue
the assault on Clinton when the two meet at their next debate, in
New York City on Oct. 8 _ or whether, having made the point that he
can stand in the same ring with her, he will tone things down.
</P>
<P>
   One well-placed New York Republican thought he would keep up the
punching. ``The people around Lazio,'' this Republican said,
``really think Hillary Clinton is evil personified, that she's
actively corrupt and motivated solely by ambition. To them, this is
war.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, when Lazio threw her his attack-lines _ calling
some of her statements ``beyond shameless,'' ``more evasions,'' and
``positively Clinton-esque'' _ he had two things in mind.
</P>
<P>
   First, as a tactical matter, he felt he needed to show he hold
his own with Hillary Clinton. But second, he meant what he said: He
really does hold her in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts thought the debate was a wash. Hank Sheinkopf,
a Democratic consultant, spoke for many when he said, ``I don't
think it's going to cause much movement in either direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they agree that, whatever the debate's net effect, Lazio
cannot have done himself any good with those who at least claim to
like their politics more dignified.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls, taken before the debate, show Clinton's favor
rising among two such groups that she has had trouble attracting _
white women like Gelburd and conservative Jews like Hikind.
</P>
<P>
   An instant-poll by the Daily News and WCBS-TV _ a telephone
survey of 274 voters taken right after the debate _ showed Clinton
judged the winner, by 49-36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, its significance is unclear, given the very small
sample. Four statewide polls, taken in the week leading up to the
debate, all showed the two candidates virtually tied, with Clinton
leading but by a margin smaller than the statistical margin of
error.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
