<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-MILESTONE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Habitat celebrates victory at home
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICUS, ,Ga. _ After 24 years of righteous sweat, there are no
more shacks in Habitat for Humanity's home county.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a weeklong, home-building blitz led by longtime
Habitat volunteer former President Jimmy Carter, the Americus-based
nonprofit organization declared the virtual elimination of poverty
housing in Sumter County.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration comes as Habitat also marks international growth
that has totalled 100,000 homes, mostly for people who otherwise
could only have dreamed of home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done is provide housing for everyone we could
locate who needed a house,'' Carter said. The victory claim means
that virtually everyone in Sumter County who desires to leave
substandard housing can do so, he said. Joined by his wife,
Rosalynn, Carter helped put the final touches Thursday to five new
homes outside Plains. The houses were built on land where his
family used to grow cotton, corn and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   He worked through the late-morning heat and gnat swarms, pausing
briefly to track down a trowel that someone had borrowed from his
toolbox.
</P>
<P>
   The victory celebration is perhaps sweetest for 50-year-old Vera
Thomas, owner of the Habitat home in Americus designated as the
``Victory Home.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending her youth picking cotton on a Sumter County farm,
and the last 20 years caring for Alzheimer's patients as a nursing
assistant, Thomas and three of her four children will soon move
into their first real home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come a mighty long way,'' Thomas said. But, she added,
she might never have been able to step up to a home of her own if
she'd had to qualify for a regular bank loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I can plant me some flowers,'' she said. ``And maybe I
can rest better.''
</P>
<P>
   The cadre of strangers who built her house have become ``like
family,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers were part of the corps of approximately 1,200
workers who came to Sumter County for the housebuilding blitz,
which consists of 30 new homes in Americus, five in Plains and more
than 120 in other locations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The group is a mixture of experts, idealists and everyday people
who want to use their spare time to help someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Brandon, a New York-based senior editor of This Old House
magazine, was putting into practice the topics she features. ``Now,
I really understand what I'm talking about,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon said the Habitat homes are built to standards equal to
those of some of the most demanding construction tradespeople she
routinely works with. ``It's amazing how exacting everyone is,''
she said. ``If we don't do something right, we do it over.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brandon and the other volunteers, the biggest rewards for
their labor are the emotional ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a lot of good things for others, but this is
something that abslutely changes someone's life,'' said Carol Tebo,
of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Tebo and her husband Larry have been full-time construction
volunteers for the past five years. They sold their home and most
of their possessions, bought a recreational vechicle, and travel
around the country to various work sites.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat For Humanity has flourished in a time when other
non-profits are struggling, said Millard Fuller, Habitat's founder.
While it took the organization 24 years to build its first 100,000
homes, it expects to reach 200,000 in about five years from now, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the expansion, he said, is that Habitat taps into
the philosophy preached at practically every church: love one
another. ``You can't express love just by talking; we give people
an opportunity to put what they hear in church into practice,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And those who move into the Habitat houses are challenged to
give in return, Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not charity,'' Fuller said. ``The only thing we give
away is an opportunity to help someone else.'' The mortgage
payments for each new Habitat home are put into the fund that is
used to build more homes, so the new homeowner knows that each
payment he or she makes is directly helping someone else, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A house is to a family what good soil is to a plant,'' Fuller
said. ``A good place to live enhances a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
