<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS &LR;      09-14 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH ATTACKS GORE FUND-RAISING AFTER AGREEING TO DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush on Thursday ended an impasse with
Democrat Al Gore over their debates by accepting Gore's position.
Then, going on the offensive after several campaign setbacks, Bush
charged that the vice president may have solicited an illegal
campaign donation in 1995 from a Texas trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's moves came on a day that he and Gore showcased their
rival plans to strengthen public education and four nationwide
polls showed Gore leading Bush by margins of 3 percentage points to
7 percentage points in the popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of arguing over the timing and format for
presidential debates, Bush had his campaign lieutenants agree with
Gore counterparts in Washington, D.C., on four campaign debates
sponsored by the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush abandoned his earlier insistence that he and Gore appear on
two interview-style broadcasts and hold only one formal
commission-sponsored debate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement Bush and Gore will debate on nationwide
television on Oct. 3, 11 and 17, and the vice presidential
candidates, Republican Dick Cheney and Democrat Joe Lieberman, will
face off on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also raised questions about Gore's fund-raising in 1995
after documents leaked from a Justice Department task force showing
a ``call sheet'' that the Democratic Party prepared for Gore's use
during a planned telephone solicitation of campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Jim Kennedy said records show the vice president
never made the requested solicitation to a Beaumont, Texas, trial
lawyer named Walter Umphrey.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer and his firm have donated $790,000 to the party
over the last four years since President Clinton in 1996 vetoed a
GOP-sponsored bill, opposed by trial lawyers, that would have
capped damages in liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Justice Department's recent opening of a
preliminary probe of the alleged solicitation, Bush said,
``Americans are tired of investigations and scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to 3,000 National Guard officers and defense industry
representatives in a satellite address from California, the Texan
said, ``The best way to get rid of them is to elect a new president
who will restore honor and dignity to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the allegations provide ``new evidence that my
opponent may have crossed a serious line _ solicitation of campaign
contributions linked to a presidential veto.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Kennedy said both the Justice Department and
Republicans in Congress have ``had these documents for more than
1,000 days, and nobody found it interesting until 1,000 hours
before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has refused to name a special
prosecutor to investigate Clinton-Gore fund-raising tactics, said
of the new charge, ``I'm going to approach it with respect to
anybody concerned, based on the evidence and the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's criticisms of Gore came after two Republican Party ads
came under attack as unfair and were withdrawn. Also, a microphone
at a campaign event picked up Bush's use of a barnyard epithet to
describe a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush allies, led by GOP chairman Jim Nicholson, also attacked
the vice president's participation in a $5 million fund-raiser at
Radio City Music Hall in New York City Thursday night that was
organized by Miramax Co-chairman Harvey Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein released a film, ``Kids,'' about adolescents using
drugs and having sex in 1995 and underwrote the violent film ``Pulp
Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson criticized Gore for accepting campaign donations from
the ``Hollywood elite'' after criticizing them for marketing
violent films, music and video games to children.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at the fund-raiser, Gore told a school audience
in Manchester, N.H., that he would ``demand more restraint and
responsibility'' from Hollywood, adding: ``Parents should not have
to battle to protect their kids from a culture that glorifies
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Mark Fabiani rejected suggestions that Gore was
being hypocritical. Democrats ``aren't afraid to tell their friends
when they think those friends are wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, meantime, belittled Bush's $47 billion
education plan, saying that it would be financed with the budget
leftovers after a $1.3 trillion across-the-board tax cut that the
governor has proposed. Gore highlighted his own $170 billion
10-year plan for education improvements at a campaign appearance in
Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't make education our top priority if huge tax cuts for
the wealthy are already the first, second and third priority,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, hoping to counter Bush's emphasis on the
popular education issue, said his rival's education plan stands as
``one of the biggest differences in this election'' between Bush
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush calls for the use of state-created standardized tests to
assess schools' performance and the diversion of federal education
funds to parents in the form of $1,500 vouchers to pay for private
schools or tutors if the public schools fail for three years in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan calls for a wider federal role in assisting local
school disricts by providing 100,000 new teachers to bring down
class sizes and repairs on 25,000 dilapidated schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also took part in New York City in an internet broadcast
chat with 11 young adults ranging in age from 18 to 28 that had
been organized by his oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, 27.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, hoping to boost turnout among the 26.5 million potential
voters aged 18 to 24, vowed to boost college attendance by
college-age Americans to 75 percent by 2010 by providing a tax
break for the first $10,000 of annual college tuition expenses.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
