u s BC-OLY-WOMEN-SOCCER0915-     09-14 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-SOCCER0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prelude ceremonies
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ By the time Tiffeny Milbrett had
completed her woodwork hat trick early in the second half on
Thursday, an eerie silence enveloped the cavernous Melbourne
Cricket Ground.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the U.S. had sewn up a persuasive 2-0 win over Norway
in its first Olympic group match, a crowd of 16,043 roused only
when Milbrett cracked shots against both posts and the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Swirling around in the chilly, early-spring breeze was a flock
of seagulls, whose numbers grew as the temperatures dipped deeper
into the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean fans waiting for their men's team to play Morocco in the
following match were providing the only authentic soccer
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It did not feel like the Olympics, even though the MCG was the
main stadium for the 1956 Melbourne Games. The Australian Gallery
of Sport and Olympic Museum, adjoining the main entrance, boasts of
such past Aussie Olympic heroes as Betty Cuthbert and such current
hopefuls as Cathy Freeman, who call Melbourne their home.
</P>
<P>
   Because Olympic soccer is contested at various sites around the
host nation, soccer players often feel left out at the beginning of
the Games. But the U.S. women, who took part in Opening Ceremonies
in Atlanta four years ago, will be in Sydney today and will march
into Stadium Australia with their fellow American athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an important match on Sunday against China, which got
two goals from Sun Wen to beat Nigeria 3-1 in the other women's
game Thursday, a first-hand glimpse of the central Olympic venue is
important enough for the team to hop a 90-minute flight from
Melbourne, spend the night and return on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Denmark in its first 1996 Olympic game in Orlando,
the Americans flew to Atlanta. It was their only visit there,
because the medal round was contested in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the U.S. might not get back to Sydney unless it
reaches the gold-medal match.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, it was such a huge factor for us,'' midfielder Julie
Foudy said about the ceremonies. ``It's such an emotional boost. We
decided that we wanted to be a part of it again. It's worth the
travel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have all three of its group matches scheduled for
the 92,000-seat MCG.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach April Heinrichs said she decided three months ago to
let her players attend the Opening Ceremonies. She re-evaluated
after the team got its tough draw. Medal contenders Norway and
China were lumped in with the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Foudy and captain Carla Overbeck conducted another vote, and the
decision was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very good self-motivators,'' Heinrichs said. ``They're
well-traveled and know how to pace themselves after doing this for
as long as they have. What we get is a great Olympic experience.''
</P>
<P>
   IN MEN'S GAMES The second day of men's competition saw gold
medal contender Spain defeat South Korea 3-0. Japan, with a late
goal, rallied for a 2-1 victory over South Africa; Brazil beat
Slovakia 3-1; and Chile beat Morocco 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
