<HEADLINE>
CHINESE FORMER POLICE OFFICIAL ARRESTED FOR CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese prosecutors announced Thursday that they had
arrested a former senior national police official in connection
with the government's continuing investigation of corruption and
smuggling in the southern port city of Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the highest-level arrest so far in the billion-dollar
smuggling scandal surrounding the Yuanhua Corp. Several trials of
lower-level officials implicated in the same scheme began earlier
this week in five cities in the southern province of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
   Li Jizhou, a former vice minister of Public Security, was
arrested late last year for taking ``huge bribes'' in connection
with the Yuanhua smuggling case, Zhao Dengju, deputy chief of the
national prosecutor's office told Chinese journalists at a news
conference Thursday. He added that Li had also been charged with
taking bribes in two other smuggling cases, both in Guangdong
province, according to the state-run China Radio International.
</P>
<P>
   Until a recent government crackdown on graft, vast smuggling
rings in southern China _ generally working in collaboration with
government officials _ made huge profits by illegally importing a
wide range of goods, including fuel, cars, cigarettes and
electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the same crackdown, the former vice chairman of
China's parliament, Cheng Kejie, was executed Thursday for taking
$5 million in bribes and kickbacks. Cheng, who was sentenced to
death last July, is the highest-ranking official executed for
corruption since the Communists took power in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no place for corrupt elements to hide in the Party,''
said a commentary in People's Daily, the main Communist Party
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is widespread at virtually all levels of China's
government, a fact that has greatly tarnished the party's image.
China's leaders and, according to opinion surveys, ordinary
citizens both point to corruption as the country's greatest
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The central government began a major campaign late last year to
clean up government, led by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji. As part of
that effort, hundreds of investigators were dispatched to Xiamen to
delve in to the smuggling empire of the Yuanhua Corp. and its
collusion with dozens of local officials.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have complained that the investigations tended to
focus too much on low and mid-level officials and that the
government's enthusiasm for public arrests went cold when the trail
led to officials closer to the top. When it seemed like government
investigators were poised to implicate the wife of Beijing's
Communist Party chief, Jia Qinglin, a protege of President Jiang
Zemin, in the Yuanhua case, a central government press office took
the offensive to clear the couple's name.
</P>
<P>
   The exact extent of the crackdown is unclear, since most
high-level investigations are kept under wraps. But over the past
six months, the arrests have slowly moved somewhat further up the
chain of command and have become somewhat more public _ presumably
in part to satisfy public demands for more action.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the arrest of Li took place at the end of last year,
Zhao, the prosecutor, said. But it was only announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's relatively candid discussion of some aspects of
the Yuanhua case also marks a change from the general secrecy that
has surrounded the investigation. Zhao said that from January to
August of this year, the national prosecutor's office had
investigated four officials at the rank of minister or provincial
governor as well as 100 officials at the rank of bureau head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
