<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TRIATHALON0915-CO     09-14 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIATHALON0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Triathlete sets a new course
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Sheila Taormina makes triathlon look easy. Barely two
years after taking up the sport, the swimming gold medalist made a
smooth transition onto another Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a classic overachiever,'' said Jack Bauerle, Taormina's
college coach at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The women's triathlon opens the Games here Saturday morning on a
picturesque course centered around the Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of funny,'' said Taormina, who won the Olympic
triathlon trials and is ranked No. 43 in the world, ``to think
maybe I shouldn't have been a swimmer all those years, I should
have been a triathlete.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old from Livonia, Mich., wasn't sure what she was
supposed to be when her eligibility ran out at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of typical college female issues,'' said Taormina,
who is now a motivational speaker with her own company. ``Your head
just screws up what your body is capable of doing. Girls, we can
make such a big deal out of little things.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of eight kids, Taormina was homesick, often tired
because of the tough Bulldogs program and admittedly scared of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember sitting with Harvey (Humphries, the Lady Bulldogs'
assistant coach) and saying, `I don't really want to live, I don't
like my life a whole lot,'' Taormina said. ``I wasn't suicidal, but
I remember thinking if my car slipped off the road and crashed into
a tree, that wouldn't be so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no reason I should have felt that way, other than
that I was a hormonal female.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphries counseled Taormina, who had gotten her MBA, to get a
job and move on with her life. She joined an auto industry supplier
near her family, but couldn't leave swimming behind. When she was
rejected by the U.S. Swimming Resident Program in Colorado Springs,
Colo., Taormina began training with an age-group club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing was she found a way to enjoy the
journey a little bit,'' Bauerle said.
</P>
<P>
   For Taormina, making the Olympic squad in 1996 was just as
unexpected as it is now. She swam the third leg on the winning
800-meter freestyle relay and met President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for two years after the Games, she didn't train for any
sports. ``I wanted to just be a normal person,'' said Taormina,
``who could go to bed at midnight, instead of always falling asleep
at 9 o'clock. I didn't want to always eat healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   She got a small-business loan and traveled the country in a
camper, giving swimming clinics, and gained 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed being in shape,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Taormina, who is a commissioner for the city of Livonia's Parks
and Recreation Department, decided to enter a local triathlon with
her brother in the summer of 1998. She was already a swimmer and
runner, and thought, ``How hard can the bike be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it, and I won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The race director, Lew Kidder, sensing her potential, quickly
offered to coach her.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the best thing about Olympic triathlon compared to
swimming? No tickets required.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's key,'' said Taormina, who spent about $4,000 on tickets
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
