<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bear attacks two hunters in Colorado
 &HT;    By Dave Buchanan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Two archery hunters from Missouri
suffered minor injuries Wednesday during an attack by a black bear
on Grand Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, a father and son duo whose names were not released,
surprised the bear while walking in dense brush along Buzzard Creek
east of Vega Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   According to DOW spokesman Todd Malmsbury, the attack occurred
around 11 a.m. Wednesday. The two hunters walked out of the woods
and were treated for minor injuries at at local hospital and then
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hunters apparently were hunting big game and working this
draw when a 'big black bear' come out of the brush and attacked the
25 year old son, biting him on the buttocks,'' said Malmsbury.
``The father was carrying a .44 (caliber) revolver but was unable
to cock it and ended up throwing it at the bear, which in turn
attacked the father and bit him on the left thigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Malmsbury said a third member of the hunting party managed to
fire the revolver at the bear and chased it away.
</P>
<P>
   According to Division of Wildlife regulations, any bear that
attacks humans must be destroyed and checked for disease,
particularly rabies. Officers from the Wildlife Services division
of the federal Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service are
searching for the bear, Malmsbury said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first such attack reported by the Colorado Division
of Wildlife in four years. At that time, a hunter was attacked and
injured when he surprised a bear. That bear was killed by the
hunter's companion.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 1, 130 bears have been killed outside of the
permitted hunting seasons. Rick Kahn, the DOW's state big game
supervisor, said 78 of the kills have been by private landowners
trying to solve predation problems. Another 25 have been killed by
DOW officers and eight have been killed by Wildlife Services
(formerly known as Animal Damage Control).
</P>
<P>
   In additions, 19 bears have been reported killed by other means,
including roadkills and unidentified causes.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has a limited September rifle bear hunting season.
Approximately 2,000 September licenses were issued during the
limited license drawing in May.
</P>
<P>
   Unlimited muzzleloading and archery seasons overlap the limited
September rifle season. Deer and elk hunters also may purchase an
over-the-counter bear license for use during the deer or elk
hunting season.
</P>
<P>
   Over-the-counter bear tags are valid for either sex and may be
purchased at any license agency or DOW office in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, hunters killed 847 bears.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Buchanan can be reached via e-mail at
dbuchanan(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
