<HEADLINE>
BUSH PREFERS ABSTINENCE, INSTRUCTION ON TEEN SEX, PREGNANCY &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. _ George W. Bush's teen-age questioner was
persistent, but the Republican presidential nominee stuck to his
message on sex education. He still prefers instruction that
stresses abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age sex and pregnancy were among several issues tossed at
the Texas governor on Thursday during a 20-minute exchange with
several dozen Santa Ana High School students and teachers on a
campaign swing through southern California.
</P>
<P>
   There also were questions about illegal immigrants, teachers'
pay, gun control and rebuilding the military. But the first
questions were about sex education.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Nguyen, a 17-year-old senior, not only got to ask the
presidential candidate a question but also squeezed in three
follow-up questions or comments as well, more than most reporters
get to throw at Bush at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best sex education takes place at home. I think schools
ought to be focused on reading and writing and adding and
subtracting,'' Bush responded to her first question, asking what he
thought about sex education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Her second question was inaudible to reporters at the back of
the room, but Bush replied, ``If the sex education course includes
abstinence, that's the kind of thing as a parent I would support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to believe a full education course that teaches
children right from wrong will include abstinence education as
well, something in our state of Texas we've tried to encourage,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen then tried a third question, pointing out that many
teen-agers are sexually active.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer to that is I wish people would understand the
consequences of the decisions they make in life,'' the governor
replied. ``One of the things we've got to do is have character
education in our schools, early in a child's career, the difference
between right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's patience obviously neared its limit when the
young woman offered a fourth question or comment, which was
inaudible to most onlookers, but his message didn't change.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who opposes abortion, has consistently stressed abstinence
as a component of sex education. His position is that federal
funding for sex education should include at least as much money for
teaching abstinence as for teen contraceptive programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance at the high school was generally well-received
by his audience, but Nguyen wasn't pleased with her dialogue with
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abstinence is great, but what about the other teens who don't
practice abstinence? Over 50 percent of the students don't practice
abstinence,'' she told reporters later.
</P>
<P>
   She said she believed that Bush was ``kind of ruffled'' by their
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that he was saying that sex was wrong,'' she added.
``We're curious. It's only natural that we want to explore.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen said the only sex education she had received at any
school was in the sixth grade, ``when you have sex ed and they
teach you about the female parts and stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the same appearance at Santa Ana High School, a teacher's
aide asked Bush about teen-age pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about it because a cause of poverty is a child
born out of wedlock,'' Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would provide federal funding for ``character
education'' classes ``so that young children understand there are
right decisions to make and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make it clear to people that having a baby out of
wedlock will make it awfully difficult for the baby and the mom.
And we've got to make it clear to the men of society that the
definition of a man is not somebody who fathers a child and walks
away,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Bush toured the Los Angeles County Fair and
attended Republican fund-raisers in San Diego. Bush also planned to
campaign in San Diego Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, he will have spent one full day and
parts of two others in southern California, although polls indicate
that Democratic nominee Al Gore has a strong lead here.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has vowed to fight for California's treasure trove of
54 electoral votes and plans to return to the state later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident we can carry California,'' Bush said at a GOP
fund-raiser in Irvine Wednesday evening. ``I know that goes against
conventional wisdom, but this is a state that wants change.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said at the fund-raiser that he's sticking to his
proposal for a
</P>
<P>
   $1.3 trillion tax cut, despite reports that Republicans in
Congress are now more favorably inclined to paying down the
national debt with federal budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to yield on this issue,'' Bush said. ``We are
on the right side.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
