<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTES0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gymnast times arrival perfectly
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Born two months premature, 15-year-old U.S. gymnast
Tasha Schwikert gained a chance to become an Olympian. Because she
turns 16 this year (Nov. 21), she is eligible for the Games. A
child of Las Vegas whose parents are both craps dealers at Caesar's
Palace, Schwikert knew the odds were long to make the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   She was ninth in the team selection process, then was named the
second alternate. But Schwikert was added to the squad when Morgan
White suffered a stress fracture on her left foot and selectors
bypassed first alternate Alyssa Beckerman. Schwikert, the second
African-American to make the team (the other is Dominique Dawes),
outperformed Beckerman at some mock meets.
</P>
<P>
   National team coordinator Bela Karolyi calls Schwikert, who is
excelling in floor exercise, an ``up-and-coming, very, very strong
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Joy Schwikert, was a professional tennis player in
the 1970s, who competed at Wimbledon with her twin sister, Jill.
Tasha doesn't know how they did, but offered, ``I could ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwikert's mother wanted Tasha and her 13-year-old sister,
Jordan, to take up tennis, but Schwikert said, ``Being 3 years old,
it's really hard to hold a racket, so she put us in gymnastics for
something to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a year ago, she said, ``I would not even think I
would be here right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But she felt bad for White. ``That kid has been working so hard
her whole life for this,'' Schwikert said, ``and it's pretty
devastating for her. I'm dedicating whatever I do here to her.''
</P>
<P>
   In another injury development, Jamie Dantzscher rolled her ankle
at podium training Thursday, but she and her coaches said it was
minor.
</P>
<P>
   ATHLETES GET TOP BILLING
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Baldwin, vice president of the USOC, said the alignment in
which the United States will march into the Opening Ceremonies will
be different for the first time since 1896.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a clear protocol,'' she said, ``the flag bearer, the
president, officials and so on. . . . Well, we're going to change
that. And the executive committee and athletes agreed 100 percent.
This year, it will be the flag bearer, the team captains and the
athletes _ with the (Olympic) officials on the side (of the
athletes).
</P>
<P>
   ``For the athletes, this is saying that it's their Games. We
don't need to see a bunch of `old fogies' leading the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   PEREZ APPEALING RULING
</P>
<P>
   Mike Moran, the U.S. Olympic Committee's managing director, said
an arbitrator's ruling against an appeal allowing kayaker Angel
Perez to compete with Team USA will not deter the USOC from
exhausting ``everything legally and morally in our power'' to get
the decision reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, born in Mexico, has been disallowed from competing with
the United States although he fits the three-year rule as a
national, Moran said. ``Since 1993, he has been a national,'' Moran
said. ``He's paid his taxes, had jobs, gotten married, had
children. We're not out of bullets yet.''
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPORTATION SLIPUPS
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said the city's troubles with bus service have not been
limited to the media. She said athletes have had similar troubles.
``Anytime you try an endeavor this big. . . .'' she said. ``It was
the same thing in Atlanta, where they hired drivers from all over
the country who didn't know their way around. Here, we've had bus
drivers who've gotten lost and athletes standing on the streets
waiting for buses. But we'll get it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the U.S. women's water polo team missed a
scrimmage Thursday because the bus driver went to the wrong venue.
</P>
<P>
   NEVER TOO OLD TO ENTERTAIN
</P>
<P>
   Still a showman at age 103, Hal Haig ``Harry'' Prieste drew a
crowd Thursday at Darling Harbor by doing wheelchair calisthenics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get this,'' the New Jersey centenarian said to photographers,
standing up and bracing himself on the arms of his chair.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste, the oldest living Olympic medalist, won the bronze in
platform diving at the 1920 Antwerp Olympics. He journeyed to
Sydney to return to the International Olympic Committee the first
flag to bear the Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste had shinnied up a flagpole to grab the banner on a dare
from swimmer Duke Kahanamoku, who is known in Australia as the man
who popularized surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'm not going to be around much longer _ it's no
good in a suitcase,'' Prieste said when he handed over the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Prieste was one of the original Keystone Kops, then a star of
vaudeville, the circus and in the Ice Follies, where he did a
comedy routine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Curtis Bunn and Karen Rosen contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B: Get the news and events www.accessatlanta.com/
shared/sports/olympics/
</P>
