<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-PRIMER15-COX     09-14 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PRIMER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Things Australian, from A to Z
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _Australian crawl. Not what happens after happy hour. The
basic freestyle swimming stroke was popularized a century ago by
Australian Richard Cavill, who adapted the technique from Solomon
Islanders. Those sleek Speedo swimsuits come from Australia, too _
although they weren't very speedy in the beginning. An early woolen
model from the 1920s weighed 10 pounds and formed air pockets that
actually slowed swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Bligh. One of the first governors of the Sydney penal colony was
none other than William Bligh of HMS Bounty infamy. The tyrannical
captain fared no better in Australia than he had on the South Seas.
In 1806, naval officers in the colony mutinied and toppled Bligh in
what became known as the Rum Rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola. The boss man is an Aussie. Douglas Daft, who became
chairman of Atlanta's signature business this year, grew up 80
miles north of Sydney near the coal mining town of Cessnock.
</P>
<P>
   Didgeridoo. The long, wooden wind instrument creates weird
vibrations that, under the right conditions, can open clogged
sinuses. Usually heard at Aboriginal ceremonies and souvenir shops,
where clerks just love to pronounce that word, which rhymes with
Dippety-do.
</P>
<P>
   Errol. As in Flynn, one of the many Hollywood stars who came
from Australia. The list includes Cate Blanchett, Russell Crowe,
Mel Gibson, Nicole Kidman and Geoffrey Rush. Many Australians no
longer claim Paul Hogan, but the facts don't lie.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's. Not Australian for beer _ not in Australia, anyway.
The quickest way to brand yourself a tourist in Sydney is to step
up to the bar and order Foster's. Though it's a popular brand,
locals are as likely to call for something Americans have never
seen on the telly, like Cooper's, XXXX (Four-ex) or VB (Victoria
Bitter).
</P>
<P>
   Gays. Twenty years ago, Sydney police cracked down on a gay
pride parade and started a riot. Now the cops have a float in the
Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras parade, which draws hundreds of
thousands of spectators and is broadcast on national TV. Sydney
Olympic planners have even invited drag queens to take part in the
Closing Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, Harold. Imagine what would happen if a U.S. president
simply vanished. It happened in Oz. In 1967, Prime Minister Holt
went for a swim on the beach in Victoria and disappeared without a
trace. Melbourne built a memorial for him _ a municipal swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Insects. Australia is famous for them. The Outback swarms with
termites that build man-sized mounds and bush flies that'll suck
the moisture off your eyes. The Sydney suburbs are home to the
funnel web spider, the deadliest on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Jet lag. Australia is the Timbuktu of continents, so far and
isolated that natives have a phrase for it: ``the tyranny of
distance.'' Americans visiting for the Olympics will understand
what that means after a 20-hour trip that may not end until two
days after it began, thanks to the international date line.
</P>
<P>
   Kookaburra. Still sitting in the old gum tree _ and, now, on
souvenir shelves. The kingfisher with the cackling call is one of
three official mascots of the Sydney Games. They're Olly the
Kookaburra, Syd the Platypus and Millie the Echidna (a
quill-covered anteater that resembles a porcupine). Unlike
Atlanta's computer-generated Izzy, Sydney's troika of mascots have
real-life antecedents and have drawn little ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Laughs. Speaking of cackling birds, Australians are renowned for
their irreverent sense of humor. They've even made a satirical TV
show based on the travails of the Olympic organizers. One episode
of ``The Games'' was about a bloke who ticked off the Ollies by
copyrighting his new legal name: Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Melbourne. Remember the 1956 Summer Olympics? Not likely. That's
Melbourne's problem: People seem to have forgotten the city that
Sydney passed in population and replaced as the capital of
Australian culture and business. Melbourne, you may recall, bid for
the '96 Games and lost to Atlanta. Now that its old rival Sydney
has the prize, Melbourne is plowing its energies into a festival
for next year's centennial of the Australian commonwealth. Sounds
like a silver medal.
</P>
<P>
   Newton-John, Olivia. The Aussie thrush will be one of the stars
in the Opening Ceremonies, part of a lineup that has been
criticized for being bland, unimaginative and unrepresentative of
the nation's cultural variety. It could have been worse. As one
letter writer said in the Sydney Morning Herald, ``At least Ernie
Dingo isn't going to play the didgeridoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Outback. The fast-growing steakhouse chain began in Tampa, not
Australia, and was inspired by the ``Crocodile Dundee'' movies. The
company is opening its first Australian franchise in Sydney this
December. Maybe it will do better than Hooters, the Atlanta chain,
which brought jiggly waitresses to Sydney three years ago. It
bombed _ perhaps because you can see that kind of stuff for free at
Bondi Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Pokies. Sydney loves to gamble on everything from rugby to
horses to the poker machines that beckon inside every pub. The city
is said to have more gamblers per capita than any place outside
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Queenie. Almost a century after it became an independent nation,
Australia is still a commonwealth of the United Kingdom, and
Elizabeth Rex is still the official head of state. Last year
Australians had a chance to end this vestige of colonialism and
declare their country a republic. In a decision ripe for
psychoanalysis, they elected to stay with Mum.
</P>
<P>
   Roots. At every Olympics, Australians smirk when they see
Canadian athletes wearing gear made by Roots, the Toronto sporting
goods company. The reason? In Ozspeak, rooting doesn't mean pulling
for the home team; it's a bawdy term for doin' the nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Strange place names. The Australian map is sprinkled with words
amusingly transliterated from Aboriginal tongues. Some favorites:
Tittybong, Cocklebiddy, Knockibitoo, Wee Waa and the possibly
related Wangi Wangi.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Town. Sydney, on the other hand, was named for a British
politician, Secretary of State Thomas Townsend, who also went by
the title first Viscount Sydney. Robert Morley once said he would
have liked Sydney better if it had a more regular-guy name like
Bert.
</P>
<P>
   Utzon, Joern. The Danish architect who designed the Sydney Opera
House angrily resigned from the job in 1966, with the project
running years behind schedule and millions of dollars over budget.
He has never returned to see his masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Voting. Australians take it seriously. Not only did they pioneer
the secret ballot (first used in Victoria in 1855), but they've
made electoral apathy a crime. Every citizen must vote or be fined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waltzing Matilda.'' Some people think Australia's unofficial
national anthem is a children's song about dancing with a kangaroo.
It's actually a folk song about vagabonds wandering (waltzing) the
countryside with their bedrolls and knapsacks (matildas) over their
shoulders. The odd lyrics were written in the 1890s by the oddly
named poet Banjo Paterson.
</P>
<P>
   X Files: The Case of the Hungry Cod. A 97-pound fish caught off
the Great Barrier Reef last month revealed a grisly secret. When it
was gutted at a processing plant, a remarkably intact human head
rolled out. Enjoy the triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Yanks. The Brits colonized Australia, but a couple of American
natives shaped its capital. King O'Malley, an American-born
politician, led the movement to establish an independent nation in
1901. And Walter Burley Griffin, an Illinois architect, laid out
the broad boulevards and parks of the new seat of government,
Canberra, which was built from scratch midway between Sydney and
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Zero. The amount of debt Georgia taxpayers had to pick up after
the Atlanta Games. New South Wales taxpayers have spent $1.5
billion and may end up getting stuck for far more. Remember that if
the pundits start saying these Olympics are better than the last
one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
