<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-14 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN AFFAIRS: GIVE A LITTLE, GET A LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was a reporter covering Lebanon's civil war there were
mornings when the fighting was so bad I just wanted to write a
one-line story: ``Lebanon ended today _ period, paragraph,
goodbye.'' But the Lebanese people's indefatigable quest for a
normal life always proved me wrong. I've been reminded of that
reading all the recent doom-and-gloom stories about how the
Palestinian-Israeli peace process is over _ period, paragraph,
goodbye. How many times do we have to bury this thing for people to
realize that if you think it's over _ you don't understand it?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is a very tough juncture, but it is not
insurmountable. We are dealing now with the most sensitive issues:
who should control the spiritual heart of Jerusalem _ what Jews
call the Temple Mount, where the ancient Jewish Temple once stood,
and what Arabs call the Haram as-Sharif, where two of Islam's
holiest mosques now stand _ and what will happen to the Palestinian
refugees outside of Israel and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1967 Israel has occupied and claimed sovereignty over the
Temple Mount. But out of respect for Muslim sensibilities _ and
because most rabbis ban Jewish prayer on the Temple Mount for fear
that Jews might be treading on the ancient Temple below _ Israel
has voluntarily granted Palestinians administrative control there.
But the Palestinians are now demanding full sovereignty for any
final peace.
</P>
<P>
   Quite shockingly, though, both Palestinian and Arab leaders have
been scoffing at Jewish claims that the ruins of the ancient Jewish
Temple are under the Temple Mount. Yasser Arafat and several other
Arab leaders have told U.S. officials that this was a story the
Jews just recently invented to justify their hold on Jerusalem. (If
Israelis heard the insultingly ignorant things Arafat has said in
private about Jewish claims to Jerusalem, the peace process would
really be over.) This is no way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most effective way for the Arabs to limit Israeli claims
to the Temple Mount is not by denying them, but by acknowledging
them and assuring Israelis that they will be respected, so Israelis
would feel comfortable enough to limit themselves,'' argued Stephen
Cohen, a Middle East expert at the Israel Policy Forum. ``But this
sort of recognition of the Israeli narrative by Arab leaders would
be a huge step. It would mean acknowledging that Israelis are in
Jerusalem, and in the Holy Land, not just because the Arabs could
not defeat them, not just because they were driven there by the
Holocaust, but because the Jewish people have a deep historical
connection to this place.''
</P>
<P>
   But the same is true for Israel regarding Palestinian refugees.
Israel refuses to acknowledge any role in the creation of the
refugee problem. Yet Israel wants Palestinian refugees to limit
their demands for any right of return to Israel. That is going to
be a very hard sell for Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Israel doesn't have to assume explicit responsibility, but it
should be generous in saying to Palestinians that they have
suffered a historical injustice and have a moral right to return to
their original homes _ but that as a practical matter Israel cannot
allow more than a symbolic number to return to Israel proper, and
the others will either have to reside in the West Bank or accept
generous compensation. For Palestinians to limit themselves they
need to feel that their narrative as a dispossessed people
struggling to recover their homeland is also affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is a certain symmetry in these two issues of
Jerusalem and refugees, there is no symmetry now between Arafat and
Ehud Barak, Israel's prime minister. Barak may have bungled his
relationship with Arafat, but within his own political context
Barak has shown a willingness to offer unprecedented compromises,
re-educate his own people and stake his whole political career on
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has not gone that far _ yet. Some worry that the
Palestinian leader, now that he is shedding his revolutionary
cloak, is turning out to be an unreconstructed, provincial tribal
chief who may not be up to a grand compromise or running a modern
state.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, this struggle will end. Too many people now want it over.
But whether it is Arafat who seals the deal is still an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
