<SLUG> BC-PLUMBERS-IN-SPACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTIS `PLUMBERS' READY SPACE STATION WITH RUSSIAN POTTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The visiting Atlantis astronauts equipped the
international space station with a Russian ``zero gravity'' version
of the household toilet on Thursday _ a strong indication the
orbital outpost can soon be staffed full-time.
</P>
<P>
   The toilet's installation was the latest in a flurry of home
improvements the shuttle's five American astronauts and two Russian
cosmonauts have engaged in this week as they prepare the station
for the arrival of its first resident crew in early November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are plumbers, carpenters, electricians _ you name it,''
joked astronaut Dan Burbank, who assisted cosmonaut Yuri
Malenchenko with the hook-up of the toilet's waste holding tank,
air and fluid hoses.
</P>
<P>
   Worried the privy might leak once the Atlantis crew departs this
weekend, mission control asked the astronauts to refrain from
engaging in a full fledged test of their handiwork. The honor has
been bestowed on Bill Shepherd, Yuri Malenchenko and Sergei
Krikalev who are preparing to move aboard for a four-month stay
within two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic systems are installed, but we will leave that for
later crews,'' said Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Since docking with the 143-foot-long collection of early station
modules last Sunday, the shuttle crew has spent most of its time
bolstering the electrical power distribution system. Before they
return to Earth, the astronauts will assemble air generation and
recycling systems, an exercise bicycle and treadmill, a laptop
computer network and install fire extinguishers.
</P>
<P>
   Like the toilet, most of the new gear will be installed in the
station's latest addition, the Russian-built Zvezda crew habit
module. With its living and working quarters, the 43-foot-long
module's arrival in late July made the station habitable for the
first time since the first components were joined in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still far from fully assembled, the growing outpost is
nonetheless impressive, said Atlantis commander Terry Wilcutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful facility,'' he said. ``It's the equivalent of
a 13-story building right now. It's incredibly spacious and well
lit. I think all of us (astronauts) hope to spend some time up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of gravity, the new station toilet relies on a
forceful flow of air rather than water to flush human wastes.
</P>
<P>
   Malenchenko and Burbank connected the toilet's waste storage
tank with fluid hoses and filled a reservoir with a sanitizing
chemical fluid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The installations are important because they will minimize the
amount of work the first crew has to do and make the station much
more habitable,'' said NASA's Kirk Shireman, the station's Russian
components manager. ``The toilet in particular is something that is
really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian economic problems slowed Zvezda's launching by two years
and stalled other major assembly work as well. When Zvezda did lift
off, the module was much too heavy to carry all of its live support
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the missing equipment including the toilet was launched
in August aboard an unmanned Russian Progress cargo capsule. The
shuttle brought more of the still needed gear as well as the
personnel to install it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Thursday, Russian ground controllers evaluated a
potential difficulty with one of the Zvezda module's eight power
storage batteries. The module was launched with just five in place.
It was equipped with three more by the shuttle crew earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five original batteries is having difficulty
charging, according to NASA's Mark Ferring, the station's lead
flight director.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on the ground hope to find a remedy.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't, Zvezda can draw adequate power with as few as six
batteries. Another loss would force control teams to impose
conservation measures.
</P>
<P>
   The batteries store power generated by solar arrays as the
station circles the Earth in sunlight. When the outpost slips into
darkness, the batteries discharge enough current to keep the life
support, communications and computer systems running.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
