A5643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-WEATHER0915-COX     09-14 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WEATHER0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's chilly Down Under
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Welcome to the Summer Games _ Down Under. The winter
just turned to spring, and the weather is more like early March in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all bad if you're a basketball Dream Teamer or you're
going for gold in the boxing ring or swimming the pool. But if
you're out in the elements, it could get dicey.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat could give way to shivers at what might go down as the
Windbreaker Games. The weather could play a role in everything from
baseball and archery to beach volleyball and cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Cool temperatures aren't ideal for world-record performances,
especially in the track-and-field sprints that grab prime-time
television exposure. Track athletes already are complaining about
swirling, turbulent winds in the 110,000-seat Olympic Stadium. Most
finals are booked for evenings, after the sun goes down and when
the mercury hovers around 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   And Sydney organizers, along with International Olympic
Committee boss Juan Antonio Samaranch, have voiced concern whether
Mother Nature might rain on the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Their fears were heightened last September when thunderstorms
washed out a women's Olympic field-hockey qualifier in Sydney
Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, three days of torrential rains fell during a
late-September developmental-track camp in Sydney. ``If this kind
of weather hits, it'll be miserable,'' said Loren Seagrave, then a
consultant to the Australian track federation.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, athletes are of the mind-set to deal with it _ and
clear blue skies have been the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the same for everybody,'' said track star Marion
Jones, who is trying to make Olympic history by winning five gold
medals. ``It's not just going to be windy in my lane. I'd love for
it to be 90 degrees, but it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in the Raleigh area, I've experienced everything from
15 inches of snow to 98 degrees and 80 percent humidity,'' Jones
said. ``If anybody can handle various degrees in temperature, I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters are predicting at least traces of rain on five of
the 17 days of competition _ but it probably will be a typical
September, with total accumulation of 1/10th of an inch. The
average daily high temperature is forecast to be 68 degrees with a
low around 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the rain will be at night when no one really cares,''
said Elly Spark, manager of the Olympic Games weather service. ``It
won't be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, Sydney officials debuted weather-tracking radar
last month to assist in detecting any freak severe storms. Weather
reports detailing temperature, rainfall, humidity and, most
important, wind, will be issued every three hours at the venues,
with sailing receiving hourly reports for conditions in the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Weather talk fueled ill winds recently when Aussie long-jumper
Jai Taurima dismissed his American rivals, all three of whom are
black, by saying: ``You can pretty much knock out all the dark
athletes'' because of the cool conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, sprinters and jumpers tend not to perform as well in
cool temperatures, which is the opposite for distance runners.
Athletes in the speed events also are more prone to muscle pulls
when temperatures dip.
</P>
<P>
   It should be interesting to see whether world-record holders
Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene, both of whom pulled up lame in
near-100-degree heat in the Olympic Trials, hold up in the chill.
</P>
<P>
   But fast times in the sprints? ``If the wind is in their face,''
U.S. coach John Chaplin said, ``you won't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
