<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BOWS TO GORE'S DEBATE DEMANDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush bowed to most of his
presidential opponent's debate demands Thursday as he and Vice
President Al Gore agreed to participate in three debates sponsored
by a bipartisan commission.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting for more than four hours, top advisers to Gore and
Bush announced the deal that also will include one face-off between
their running mates. The first presidential debate will be Oct. 3
at the University of Massachusetts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement marks a turnaround for Bush, who earlier had
rejected most of the recommendations by the Commission on
Presidential Debates and instead proposed alternative forums.
</P>
<P>
   But with Gore pulling slightly ahead or even in the polls, Bush
now appears eager to engage his opponent in nationally televised
events that have the potential to shake up the race.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with commission officials, Bush campaign chairman
Don Evans said, ``We have agreed to the sites. We've agreed to the
time. The governor is very eager to debate. He's looking forward to
a free-flowing, substantive, real and genuine discussion of the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore previously had embraced the commission's recommendations
and rejected Bush's insistence on face-offs on a special edition of
NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign chairman Bill Daley, who led the debate
negotiations for the vice president, praised the progress in the
debate talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good because the American people want to hear from
these people in formal settings that give them the opportunity to
express what they will do as the next president of the United
States,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will return Friday to hash out other details,
including the exact format of the 90-minute debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the governor has
been pressing for a more ``unstructured free-flowing format.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that the Bush campaign had agreed to accept the
commission's dates and times with the expectation that they would
win concessions on format.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Boston debate, the presidential candidates will meet
at Wake Forest University in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Oct. 11 and at
Washington University in St. Louis on Oct. 17. The
vice-presidential debate between Democrat Joseph Lieberman and
Republican Dick Cheney will be held at Centre College in Danville,
Ky. on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to hold the first debate at the University of
Massachusetts is particularly striking since Bush strategists had
been adamant that they did not want to meet in such a staunchly
Democratic city at a site across from the John F. Kennedy Library _
which honors the Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   But political analyst Stuart Rothenberg said the Bush campaign
has had to change strategy after a string of disappointing weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow there is a different perspective when you are 12
points ahead than when you are five or six points behind,''
Rothenberg said. ``Now Bush needs the debates. He needs as many as
he can get and needs to cross his fingers and hope they help him.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, the FBI is continuing its probe of a
mysterious package of Bush debate preparation material that was
mailed to a Gore ally who was helping the Democrat prepare for the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Rep.Tom Downey immediately turned the package over
to authorities. It included a videotape of a practice debate
between Bush and Sen. Judd Gregg, playing the role of Gore. The
package was postmarked Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said the governor's lawyer has
examined the tape and determined that it is either the original or
copy of an authentic tape. She also said the package included
``copies of legitimate debate documents.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the mock debate took place at the governor's ranch
in Crawford, Texas, and that only a handful of senior staff would
have had access to the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distribution was very, very small,'' she said. Those
members include Hughes, campaign manager Joe Allbaugh and advisers
Karl Rove and Mark McKinnon.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that whoever obtained it and sent it to the Gore
campaign did so ``in an unethical way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the FBI had asked to talk with members of the
campaign about the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gladly cooperating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter Clay Robison contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
