<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE ARE EIGHT TV STORYLINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympic Games are underway. Andres Cantor has already blown
a lung with his elongated ``Goooooooalll!'' call on U.S. soccer and
NBC Sports President Dick Ebersol was seen at a Sydney pub boasting
that Olympic fans will see what he wants and when he wants it, and
tough if they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   These are half-truths, of course, kind of like NBC's plausibly
live coverage of the 1996 Olympics from Atlanta. The network
promises no semantics games this time, just no live coverage. That
noted once again, here are eight storylines to follow regarding the
Olympic TV coverage:
</P>
<P>
   1. NBC's ratings. The last time an Olympic Games was televised
from a time zone similar to Sydney, Australia, was NBC's coverage
of the 1988 Olympics from Seoul. Coming off a prime time Nielsen
average of 23.2 for the '84 Games in L.A., NBC was disappointed
with a 17.9 average.
</P>
<P>
   NBC promised advertisers a 17.5-to-18.0 average for the 2000
Games, which is notably modest. But with the media landscape having
changed dramatically in the last five years, much less the last 12,
it wouldn't be shocking if there was some audience erosion.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will once again hit a handful of sports hard -- swimming,
gymnastics, track and diving, with a touch of beach volleyball. It
is by design, too, that female athletes are featured in four of
those five sports, all the better to attract female viewers, who
traditionally aren't sports mad.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cable ratings. This marks the first Summer Olympics cable
coverage. In past Winter Games, cable carriers were able to earn
ratings of 3.0 for events like the bobsled, luge and ski jumping.
</P>
<P>
   This time, CNBC and MSNBC will offer full game coverage of teams
sports like baseball, water polo, softball and soccer, events that
got short-sheeted in Atlanta. But watching delayed telecasts of
team sports is anathema to most American sports fans. Will anyone
watch Mia Hamm and friends on tape if they know the soccer team won
its game?
</P>
<P>
   3. Bob Costas will wax eloquently. This is his fourth Olympics
and his third as prime time anchor host, and only Jim McKay has
ever done it better, and McKay never had to deal with 84 hours of
prime time air time.
</P>
<P>
   Costas took a few hits in Atlanta because of NBC's plausibly
live snafu, but he's always prepared and knows how to advance a
story and conduct an interview. He'll also have to play the role of
travel guide, since NBC plans a lot of Aussie beauty shots.
</P>
<P>
   4. No John Tesh. The broadcaster/composer is a very nice guy who
was out of his element as gymnastics play-by-play man four years
ago. A born gusher, he even managed to offend those viewers who
consider gymnastics an art form more than a sport. The competent Al
Trautwig replaces him.
</P>
<P>
   5. Not so dreamy. The one-sided nature of Olympic competition
since the berth of the Dream Team has led NBC to reconsider its
schedule. Of the first five games for the men's team, one will be
carried by CNBC and three will be televised in the late night
(12:41 a.m.) slot.
</P>
<P>
   6. Too close and way too personal. NBC has cut the number of
features it has prepared about 30 percent from 1996, mostly because
critics and viewers complained they got in the way of event
coverage. But even with that cut, one can expect between four and
five of them per prime time show.
</P>
<P>
   7. Programming changes. NBC has a game plan, but the network
will adjust its plans according to news value. Look for a cycling
event or two on NBC, like the road race that features Tour de
France champ Lance Armstrong, and for either of the gold medal
singles tennis games to pop up on NBC if an American, like Venus
Williams and Lindsay Davenport, gets to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   8. Goal. Andres Cantor is the Telemundo soccer announcer whose
work in Spanish on previous World Cups has earned him a cult
following. NBC hired him to do U.S. soccer games in English.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his first language, but he's more than adequate,
especially with the naturally enthusiastic Alexi Lalas as his
partner. The only question is the health of his vocal chords. The
first goal by the U.S. men's team in Wednesday's game earned four
load ``goal'' calls, a stiff pace. &QL; 
Changing channels
</P>
<P>
   Schaap at Knight: Jeremy Schaap, the son of longtime
sportswriter/sportscaster Dick Schaap, got the plum (or punk)
assignment of interviewing Bobby Knight live Tuesday night in his
first major response to his firing.
</P>
<P>
   Schaap acquitted himself nicely. Knight repeatedly would answer
a question by going off on a tangent, and Schaap repeatedly stepped
in to try and bring Knight back to the question and topic. The
ex-Indiana coach didn't like being interrupted, but Schaap's
mandate for a live interview was to keep him on topic.
</P>
<P>
   Knight obviously wanted to make his own points, like what a
great program he ran, how IU administrators never explained zero
tolerance, and how hard this was on his son, Pat. Schaap allowed
him to, but only for a short time before getting back on issue,
like how he could possibly misinterpret zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Nick at Knight: Nickelodeon was the only network that didn't
prepare a Knight-related show this week. The best of the bunch was
Keith Olbermann's treatment on his Sunday night ``Evening News''
show on Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann had four satellite interviews with particulars in the
case, including the sportscaster whose son was confronted by
Knight, the IU president, and an Indiana professor who has long
been a critic. One came away from the telecast having been treated
to a comprehensive look at all sides of the issue, with Olbermann
often playing devil's advocate to cover every angle of the story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
