<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-WATER0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas man's persistence brings much-needed well to his Sudanese
homelandBy Mark Lisheron
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The unquenchable loyalty of an Austin man to his
family and friends is bringing fresh water to a village in northern
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Awad Abdelgadir persuaded Rotary International to donate the
bulk of $42,000 to build a water system for his ancestral village
of Kolomiseed, on the west bank of the Nile River about 200 miles
south of the Egyptian border.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the well and pipes that will bring pure water to
about 3,000 people is expected to start within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelgadir raised $6,000 by forming a company, Nile Valley Herbs
Inc. The company has sold Sudanese hibiscus mint tea for five years
to stores such as Whole Foods and Central Market in Austin and San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel privileged to work with Awad on this project to bring a
much needed well to his people in the Sudan,'' said Jason Osborn,
matching grants coordinator for Rotary International in Evanston,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he left the Sudan 13 years ago, Abdelgadir has
devoted himself to the betterment of life in a village that draws
its drinking water directly from the Nile.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelgadir came to Austin for the similar climate and to get a
master's degree in education, which he received in 1990 from
Southwest Texas State University. His birthdate, Jan. 1, 1954, was
given to him by the U.S. government because he and the people of
his village do not concern themselves with those anniversaries,
Abdelgadir says.
</P>
<P>
   While teaching Arabic culture and language sporadically in
independent school districts and most recently Arabic language at
the University of Texas, Abdelgadir began devising ways to help
Kolomiseed.
</P>
<P>
   With the help and encouragement of a local group, Expanding
Cultural Horizons and Options, Abdelgadir raised money to install
solar panels to light and cool the village's community center.
</P>
<P>
   Next, in about 1995, he offered his old adobe home in the
village for expansion and renovation for a new school. Abdelgadir
returned to Kolomiseed and directed volunteer laborers from the
village and completed the 11-room school for about $6,000, most of
it raised through donations in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   His most ambitious project, to combat disease by providing a
safe water source for the village, required Abdelgadir to generate
more money than he could earn as a teacher. His inability to find
his favorite hibiscus-mint tea and the burgeoning market for herbal
beverages and remedies in Austin convinced him to start Nile Valley
Herbs.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Abdelgadir joined the South Austin Rotary Club. He
says the club embraced the water project with his pledge to raise
some of the money himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of sales of tea, which have been good,
and donations through ECHO at local restaurants, we were able to
raise $6,000,'' Abdelgadir says. ``South Austin Rotary offered to
raise $18,000 and Rotary International agreed to match it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
