<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIETNAM-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO VISIT VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Ariz., Neb.)   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House said Thursday that President
Clinton would visit Vietnam shortly after the November elections,
becoming the first president to step onto Vietnamese soil since the
end of the war that took 58,000 American lives, and completing a
reconciliation with the Communist government that has unfolded over
the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   In what may well turn out to be the last and one of the most
dramatic foreign trips of his presidency, Clinton will make a state
visit to Hanoi, the country's capital, which has been almost
entirely rebuilt since U.S. aircraft once conducted daily bombing
runs.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip will also take him through cities and countryside
that were burned into the American consciousness more than a
generation ago _ Ho Chi Minh City, formerly known as Saigon, and
some locations in the country's center, where much of the heaviest
fighting took place, perhaps including Hue or the port of Da Nang.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan to visit Vietnam has been widely discussed at the
White House for months. But his chief of staff, John Podesta, and
aides to Vice President Gore all said that the visit could not
occur until after the election was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too fraught with complex issues,'' one of Clinton's
top advisers said recently, recalling the accusations in the 1992
presidential campaign that Clinton dodged the draft while at Oxford
University in England. ``Gore's people, understandably, did not
want reminders of Clinton's past distracting from the messages of
the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   So 25 years after the last U.S. helicopter completed a panicked
evacuation from Saigon, Clinton will spend some of his waning
moments as commander in chief in the country that defined the
political crises of his youth. Clinton will likely strike the
themes he has when visiting other one-time U.S. adversaries:
Talking about using trade as an instrument of democratization, and
perhaps declaring that the two countries have found more common
ground as the imperatives of economic globalization have
overshadowed the divisions of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said that the
agenda of the trip will include commerce, the search for the bodies
of American soldiers who are still listed as missing in action, and
studies of the effects of the Agent Orange defoliant that was used
throughout the war. But, he added, the real importance of the trip
was the arrival of an American president on what was once enemy
soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just very much symbolic value in the president
visiting and going actually to visit the country,'' Lockhart said.
Under the current plan Clinton will not visit neighboring Cambodia,
whose suffering began during what its people called ``the American
war'' to differentiate it from so many conflicts that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional reaction reflected the divisions about Vietnam
that linger to this day. Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., and longtime
critic of Clinton, snapped: ``He should have gone 30 years ago.`
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was applauded Thursday by the Republican and
Democratic veterans of the Vietnam War who provided Clinton with
political cover as he lifted the embargo on the country in 1994,
restored diplomatic relations in 1995 and concluded a broad trade
deal two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who spent 5 1/2 years as a prisoner
of war in the jail that became known as the ``Hanoi Hilton'' _ a
spot Clinton will constantly be circling in central Hanoi _ said
the president was making the right move. But he added, ``I
respectfully declined the president's invitation to join the trip
because I was just there in April and see no need to go back so
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., called the end of Clinton's term ``an
appropriate time in the history between our two countries for an
American president to visit Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said: ``The president has been very
brave on Vietnam. He's led and done the right thing. God bless him
for going.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will append the trip to his last summit meeting with
Asian leaders, which this year will take place in tiny, oil-rich
Brunei on Nov. 15 and 16. He will stay in Vietnam for ``several
days,'' a senior official said Thursday. ``We want to give him a
lot of opportunity to visit with the Vietnamese people,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Vietnam War, President Johnson and then President
Nixon visited the country. Johnson went twice, to see troops
stationed at Cam Ranh Bay in October 1966 and December 1967. Nixon
met with the South Vietnamese president, Nguyen Van Thieu, in
Saigon in July 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese leaders have asked Clinton to come for many years,
starting when Warren Christopher, then the secretary of state,
arrived in Hanoi in the summer of 1995 to open diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   But the movement gathered steam this summer when, after five
years, the two countries concluded a trade agreement. It must still
be approved by Congress, with the vote probably next year, after
which Vietnam would receive ``normal trade status,'' meaning it can
export its products to the United States under favorable terms.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Veterans' groups are also largely in favor of the trip, though
officials of some organizations, including the American Legion,
have expressed fears that Clinton's economic message will drown out
his remembrances of the U.S. casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are happy that the president is visiting Vietnam,'' said
Scott Campbell, a spokesman for the Vietnam Veterans of America.
``His highest priority _ regarding our organization _ is bringing
closure to POW-MIA issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
