<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CONEY-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-14 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSION' TO NOWHERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actor Jon Cryer and his writing-producing partner, Richard
Schenkman, have &QL;
</P>
<P>
   followed up their first movie, ``The Pompatus of Love,'' with
``Went to Coney Island on a Mission From God ... Be Back By Five.''
The new film proves they have a talent for unusual-sounding titles,
if little else.
</P>
<P>
   The new film is, obviously, a New York buddy comedy, complete
with ironic voice-over narration, gritty yet unmistakably
nostalgia-tinged growing-up reveries and a whole lot of arrested
development. The movie itself tries to be street smart yet
ingratiating, specifically observant yet universally relatable, but
in the process it mostly displays arrested artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an annoying inability to clearly express his thoughts,
Cryer's Daniel is the storyteller and best-adjusted adult of the
film's central trio, even though he works a nowhere-bound, pawnshop
assistant gig alongside a sort-of girlfriend whom he tries to
impress with his nice guy but business unsavvy generosity. He's a
pillar of maturity, however, compared to Stan (newcomer Rick
Stear), his boyhood best friend. A self-destructive gambler and
ambition-deficient alcoholic, Stan's problems are simplistically
traced back to a childhood operation that left him in a leg brace.
Despite his unreliability, though, Stan has a good, long-devoted
gal, Ione Skye's Gabby, whom the idiot refuses to commit to.
</P>
<P>
   One winter day, Stan characteristically slacks off from his
pizza parlor job, grabs Daniel and heads out to the Brooklyn beach
on the title holy quest. Seems he's gotten wind that their
long-lost friend Richie (Rafael Baez) has been spotted among the
homeless living under the boardwalk and has gone totally nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Stan and Daniel spend the chilly afternoon searching the nearly
empty carnival grounds, meeting a few off-season eccentrics (Frank
Whaley has a nice bit as the world's most irritating skee-ball
clerk), reminiscing and reluctantly facing the fact that their own
lives have taken terribly wrong turns.
</P>
<P>
   With dialogue that's often too cute to ring honestly or
eloquently, let alone rattle or move, and epiphanies that are so
predictable from the start that they make the friends seem like
dolts for not realizing them sooner, ``Mission'' strenuously tries
but never succeeds in making us care about its wayward
protagonists. The ``colorful'' Coney characters, who include a
cranky waitress and a dramatizing gay couple, aren't very
interesting either. And Richie's big, mind-altering secret manages
to be both trite and florid, not to mention beside the point once
the full extent of his condition is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in some of the murkiest, ugliest cinematography ever lensed
and a muddy sound mix, and you've got a feature film that indicates
this team's future lies in creating title sequences. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
``WENT TO CONEY ISLAND ON A MISSION FROM GOD ... BE BACK BY FIVE''
(R; language, drug use, violence). &QL; 
-The stars: Jon Cryer, Rick Stear, Rafael Baez, Ione Skye. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Directed by Richard Schenkman. Written and
produced by Schenkman and Jon Cryer. Released by Phaedra Cinema. &QL; 
-Running time: One hour, 30 minutes. &QL; 
-Our rating: 1 star
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
