 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.15.00
 &HT;    Compiled by John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   The final answer: Enhanced TV use soars 39 percent
</P>
<P>
   Washington's diaries tell no lies but reveal self-doubts
</P>
<P>
   Author adds voice as novel unfolds online weeknights
</P>
<P>
   ENHANCED TUBE: Blame it on Regis, ``Survivor'' and all your
rowdy friends at ``Monday Night Football.'' Some 25 million U.S.
households log on to the Internet while they're watching
television, a 39 percent increase from last year, says a study
commissioned by Showtime Networks. Bottom line: Internet/TV
multitaskers could be ready for even more enhanced TV. In recent
weeks, TBS has put its Wednesday night lineup on the interactive
map; CBS has inked a deal with WebTV to augment dramas, comedies
and other Eye Network shows; and the just-wrapped Emmy Awards were
interactive for the first time. The study found that news, sitcoms
and sports accounted for nearly all the simultaneous viewing. Also:
Viewers are brewing homemade enhanced TV, getting content from
other sites to augment what they're watching.
</P>
<P>
   BY GEORGE: The diaries of the original George ``Dubya'' _
Washington _ go online today. The Library of Congress is posting
2,300 personal logs the Founding Father kept since age 16.
Included: bedbug encounters, farm woes and entries that The Weather
Channel would love (e.g., the snowy conditions on Dec. 13, 1799,
the day before his death). A rare look inward came on April 16,
1789, after his election as president: ``About 10 o'clock I bade
adieu to Mount Vernon, to private life and to domestic felicity;
and with a mind oppressed with more anxious and painful sensations
than I have words to express, set out for New York . . . with the
best disposition to render service to my country in obedience to
its call, but with less hope of answering its expectations.''
Vintage sound bite?
</P>
<P>
   www.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   NIGHTLY LISTEN: Some authors, including Stephen King, are
releasing their new books chapter-by-chapter online. Novelist
Armistead Maupin is taking it one step further at Salon. He's
reading serialized takes from his latest, ``The Night Listener,''
every weeknight through Sept. 29 in streaming-audio format. The
book is about a cult-hit radio talk show host who befriends a
13-year-old abuse victim after reading proofs of his memoir. Also:
The downloadable version of ``Listener'' is set for release Monday.
A separate chat with the author, best known for ``Tales of the
City,'' is set for Oct. 4 from 10 to 11 p.m. at www.netlibrary.com.
(See other events below.)
</P>
<P>
   Weeknights at www.salon.com
</P>
