<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WIND-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-14 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIND-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEST, BEAUTIFUL MESSAGE CARRIED BY STRONG `WIND'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iranian director Abbas Kiarostami has been lauded by cineastes
as one of the &QL;
</P>
<P>
   world's greatest filmmakers, a visionary whose minimalist,
painterly style represents cinema at its purest. ``The Wind Will
Carry Us'' will undoubtedly play to this audience, but newcomers to
Kiarostami's work may scratch their heads and wonder what all the
noise is about. This is a movie that takes the director's
anti-narrative ideas to the extreme; even Hercule Poirot would have
a difficult time solving the puzzle of a plot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even to general audiences, the film has much to
recommend. As with all of Kiarostami's work, the movie is gorgeous
and full of perfectly composed shots that turn the Iranian
countryside into a land of poetic beauty. The pace is glacial, but
ideally calibrated to the story (yes, there is one) and message
that Kiarostami wants to impart.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens on a winding dirt road in an almost otherworldly
corner of sun-baked Iran. The landscape, particularly with its
towering lone tree, will be familiar to anyone who saw Kiarostami's
last film, ``Taste of Cherry,'' as will the general obliqueness of
what is to follow.
</P>
<P>
   A group of men are taking that winding road to go to Siah Dareh,
a tiny Kurdish village that is nestled, pueblo-style, into the
mountains. Throughout the film, we only meet one of the men, a
character known only as the ``engineer'' (Behzad Dourani). These
men seem to have come to the village to witness a local mourning
ceremony; in order for that to happen, an old woman must die. But
that seemingly certain death doesn't happen. If anything, the
100-year-old woman seems to improving in health.
</P>
<P>
   While he waits, the engineer explores the amazing village where
form beautifully follows function. He befriends a young boy, Farzad
(played, like all the other villagers, by actual inhabitants of
Siah Dareh) in order to obtain updates on the old woman's
condition. He talks to the locals, drinks tea and waits.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer's daily routine is frequently interrupted by calls
to his cell phone. In order to establish a clear connection and
answer the calls, he must drive up to the local hillside. This
becomes the film's ritual; the engineer must make the trip a dozen
times during the film. After he answers the calls (which come from
a mysterious Mrs. Godazi, who always asks about the old woman's
health), the engineer engages in metaphysical conversations with an
unseen ditch digger.
</P>
<P>
   And that's about it. The film's denouement comes slowly, but
come it does, and it's more or less stated by an old doctor, who
tells the impatient engineer that ``death is what happens when you
close your eyes to the world.'' And that's what the engineer, with
his set agendas and rut-like approach to life, has been doing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a modest message contained in a beautiful film. Just don't
go expecting something profound. &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``The Wind Will Carry Us'' (Unrated; suitable for all ages).
</P>
<P>
   --The stars: Behzad Dourani.
</P>
<P>
   --Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Abbas Kiarostami.
Released by New Yorker Films.
</P>
<P>
   --Running time: One hour, 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   --Our rating: 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
