<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWLTIP-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIVE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Bowl has attracted some Very Important Performers
over the years, but one of its headliners this weekend surely is
some kind of coup. Composer Sergei Rachmaninoff will ``perform''
the second movement of his Piano Concerto No. 2 backed by the
Hollywood Bowl Orchestra -- 57 years after his death. From 1919 to
1928 Rachmaninoff made piano rolls of his own pieces on equipment
that used electrical impulses to capture the pianist's keystrokes,
velocities, pedalwork and other nuances. His 1919 rendition of the
No. 2 concerto will be brought to life on a Yamaha disklavier.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Bowl program -- its ``almost-end-of-season''
fireworks finale -- also includes the still very lively Debbie
Reynolds and, in their Bowl debuts, actor B.D. Wong and eclectic
band Pink Martini. Reynolds isn't announcing her musical selections
yet, but Wong's set includes ``Half as Big as Life'' from Burt
Bachrach's ``Promises, Promises'' and ``The Impossible Dream'' from
``Man of La Mancha.'' Pink Martini plans to perform Maurice Ravel's
``Bolero,'' which made movie history in ``10.''
</P>
<P>
   The shows will end with a big bang to the tune of ``Hooray for
Hollywood.'' Showtime is 8:30 p.m. tonight and Saturday, and 7:30
p.m. Sunday. Tickets range from $3 to $85 and are available at the
Bowl box office, at Ticketmaster outlets or by calling (213)
480-3232, or online at www.hollywoodbowl.org. For more information,
call (323) 850-2000.
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-URBANIA-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-14 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBANIA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-BUDGET PROJECT A STANDOUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to decide which is more impressive: the storytelling
daring of the &QL;
</P>
<P>
   unique new movie ``Urbania'' or the fact that first-time feature
director Jon Shear made such a rich, compelling work with an
experimental process, in a mere 18 days and for only $225,000.
</P>
<P>
   Guess both achievements are about equal. Especially since, like
all good films, ``Urbania's'' form and content are intricately,
happily married in the most intimate ways.
</P>
<P>
   The film's protagonist, Charlie (Dan Futterman of TV's ``Judging
Amy''), is not married, but he's obviously upset about it in the
most intricately intimate ways. Clearly depressed about a
mysteriously lost lover (Matt Keeslar), he wanders Greenwich
Village, visiting former gay friends and rivals, testing out a
pickup or two (they don't work out), behaving with increasing
obnoxiousness and obsessing over Samuel Bell's Dean, some rough
trade type whom Charlie's seen on the street but (or so he says)
has never spoken to.
</P>
<P>
   All of the issues the superficially mild-mannered Charlie is
wrestling with come very slowly into rapier-sharp focus. This is
partially because ``Urbania'' is a multipronged mystery, equal
parts whodunit (and who done what?) and psychological thriller. But
for a story that works some very dire themes indeed, the picture is
also unusually playful. Based on co-screenwriter Daniel Reitz's
play ``Urban Folk Tales,'' the film is constantly inserting
recitations and even stagings of those woo-woo myths into the path
of Charlie's mysterious quest.
</P>
<P>
   So we see some women seduce a guy only to drug him and steal a
kidney, a wet poodle gets microwaved, etc., usually in concert with
somebody insisting ``This one really happened.'' What Shear and
Reitz seem to be aiming for here is the creation of a whole new
urban legend, one that viscerally responds to the evil of
gay-bashing in something a bit more enlightened than kind.
</P>
<P>
   Shear, whose background is in stage acting (both he and
Futterman were in ``Angels in America''), juggles the film's
goofy/angry tonal shifts adroitly, even if his slightly surreal,
sometimes mystical presentation of the material gets too tricky for
anyone's good at times.
</P>
<P>
   The fast cutting that many of these effects require, however, is
astoundingly well-done, and was achieved by editing the film
footage, which was shot on easily damaged Super 16, digitally.
``Urbania'' is the first film since the last ``Star Wars'' episode
to be edited this way, and it's great to see that the process can
even more effectively explore the knottiest human motives than some
fantasy world far, far away. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
``URBANIA'' (R; violence, sex, language, drug use.) &QL; 
-The stars: Dan Futterman, Alan Cumming, Matt Keeslar, Josh
Hamilton, Samuel Ball. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Directed by Jon Shear. Written by Shear and
Daniel Reitz, based on Reitz's play ``Urban Folk Tales.'' Produced
by Shear, Stephanie Golden and J. Todd Harris. Released by Lions
Gate Films. &QL; 
-Running time: One hour, 45 minutes. &QL; 
-Our rating: 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-KIDS-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      09-14 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOUT HARRY POTTER IN ONE BOOK
</HEADLINE>
  For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By NANCY HEWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you are one of the folks not overly saturated with
Harry Potter, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   a book devoted to the idiosyncrasies of the young character and
his adventures is hitting the market today.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural edition of ``Beacham's Sourcebooks for Teaching
Young Adult Fiction'' focuses on the delightful character brought
to life in the four J.K. Rowling books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exploring Harry Potter,'' by historian and children's literary
expert Elizabeth D. Schafer, is a 478-page compendium of everything
you could ever want to know about Harry Potter, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer admits to be being a Harry Potter fan. ``I read them
(the first four volumes) the first time for fun,'' she recalls.
``Then I discovered how rich they are. I really got into them.''
</P>
<P>
   And getting into them meant lots of research on things such as
alchemy, history, mythology, literature and other subjects
referenced in the novels.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer maintains that the Harry Potter books appeal to all
ages. ``Harry is a moral mentor,'' she says. ``He teaches kids to
help others. The books help with school work, with ways of
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Harry Potter books are so popular, it (this book) will
help kids realize that all of literature has these themes,''
Schafer says.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer also shares references and parallels to legends, fairy
tales and more. For example, there is a lightning bolt branded on
Harry's forehead that has a mythical origin. The lightning bolt is
a symbol of the Greek god Zeus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another feature of Schafer's book is discovering the origins
and meanings of Rowling's clever character names. For example,
Argus Filch, Hogwart's caretaker, is named after a mythic Greek
watchman who was covered with eyes. Then there is Hedwig, Harry's
snowy white owl, that is named for a medieval saint.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer is working on a source book based on L. Frank Baum's Oz
books. The second volume of the Beacham series is being done by
another author, and it will focus on C.S. Lewis' Chronicles of
Narnia series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beacham's Sourcebooks for Teaching Young Adult Fiction:
Exploring Harry Potter'' is available beginning today at local
booksellers or online at www.beachampublishing.com. Suggested
retail price of the book is $24.95. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Acceptance and friendship &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Young sleuths Christopher, Korina and Alex go searching for a
number of pets that have mysteriously disappeared. While on the
trail, they discover that they may have misjudged people they have
seen in a negative light in ``The Puzzle Club Pet-Napping
Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   During the program, parents will be given a toll-free phone
number to call where they can obtain a free copy of the storybook
``The Puzzle Club Pet-Napping Mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   The program airs at 11:30 a.m. Sunday on KCOP (Channel 13). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Attention designers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are in kindergarten through sixth grade, then the folks
at Puffs Facial Tissues are interested in seeing what you can draw!
</P>
<P>
   The company is sponsoring a contest called ``What I Like Best
About School.'' Kids across the country are being asked to
illustrate any aspect of school they like and submit it to win
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Each entry must be on an 8 1/2 by 11-inch sheet of paper. The
child's name, address and grade at time of entry must be hand
printed on the back of the design. A second sheet of paper should
include the child's complete name, address and phone number; the
school's name and complete address and child's grade at time of
entry. This entry must also be hand printed.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize winner will receive a $25,000 savings bond for
college, a Gateway personal computer, a digital camera for his or
her classroom, as well as having his or her artwork displayed on
store shelves across the United States on boxes of Puffs Facial
Tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Three first place winners from each grade category _
kindergarten and first, second through fourth, and fifth and sixth
_ will receive Gateway personal computers. All winners will receive
a year's supply of Puffs Facial Tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Mail entries to: Puffs Back-to-School Design Contest, P.O. Box
4572, Blair, Neb. 68009-4572. All entries must be received by Dec.
1, 2000. For additional information, call: (800) 777-8337 or visit
the company's Web site: www.Puffs.com.
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
