<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OPEN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ceremonies celebrate Australia
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Today's Opening Ceremonies of the 27th Olympiad are a
celebration of the fantastical Australian landscape and a
procession of the athletes who've journeyed from around the world
to compete.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast of 12,700, performing on the 4 1/2-acre floor of the
Olympic Stadium for a global audience of about 4 billion, it's a
show that seems as big as the continent itself. The theatrical
first half combines elements of Cirque du Soleil, the films of
Busby Berkley and a canned score that runs the gamut _ candy-coated
pop, classical warhorses, even house music. There's a narrative,
albeit a loose one, that might remind you of ``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for these elliptical descriptions is that the press
has been sworn to secrecy, but after seeing a Wednesday night dress
rehearsal, we can report that the show meets all expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The final revelation, of course, is the lighting of the caldron.
Who will do it? And how? Some names on the short list have been
Dawn Fraser, the former swimmer who won a chest of medals for
Australia, and Betty Cuthbert, another home-grown champion.
Cuthbert suffers from multiple sclerosis and uses a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the U.S. Olympic Committee announced that sprint
kayaker Cliff Meidl will be the flagbearer for the American team.
For the first time in history, the teams of North and South Korea
will march behind a single flag. Chelsea Clinton, who was a big fan
of the Atlanta Games, will attend the ceremony. This is a
production that has been handled with politically correct gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not this show captures the soul of Australia is an
open question, one that will be exhaustively debated over the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the 2,000-member marching band, which includes kids
from Fayette County and around the world, it's an all-Aussie
entertainment lineup. Olivia Newton-John is the one face Americans
may recognize. She'll do a duet with John Farnham called ``Dare to
Dream.'' Tina Arena will sing ``The Flame,'' and Vanessa Amorosi
will perform ``Heroes Live Forever.'' These are all new songs, and
they will be recorded on a commemorative CD.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet there won't be any references to the nation's
penal-colony origins or kangaroos. To some degree, the Aboriginal
myth of dreaming _ which refers to the bridge of time that brought
them across the water _ is a springboard for the beautiful and
evocative opening fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the parade of athletes and some of the requisite
pomp and circumstance, will be the time when most of the world
visits the loo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
