<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OLY-STOCK15-COX     09-14 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-STOCK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Games sponsors aren't guaranteed winners
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you beat the market by investing in companies that sponsor
the Olympic Games, companies with global visibility and world-class
products? Yes. And no.
</P>
<P>
   Two of six big Georgia-based companies that spent big bucks on
the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta are well ahead of the market as
the 2000 summer games begin in Sydney. Scientific-Atlanta and Home
Depot have posted big, market-beating gains since the Atlanta games
ended on Aug. 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the other four are up, but well below the 95.4 percent
rise in the Dow Jones industrial average, the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500's rise of 124.3 percent and the 249.2 percent increase in the
high-tech Nasdaq composite.
</P>
<P>
   One Georgia-based sponsor, United Parcel Service, was not
publicly traded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A check of 10 other large 1996 sponsors found only one
market-beater _ International Business Machines, which is up 364.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The shares of three 1996 sponsors have declined: Xerox, by 40
percent, Eastman Kodak by 18 percent and Bausch &AMP; Lomb by 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say if there is a connection between the Olympics and
the stock market, it's something bigger than the Games themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have conjectured that the intensive media coverage
associated with the Olympics ought to benefit the stocks of
sponsoring companies, not to mention the added visibility of their
products.
</P>
<P>
   That idea prompted analysts at Robinson-Humphrey to cite the
Olympics as a potential factor in their 1996 investment forecast,
which said, ``The spotlight shines on the Southeast in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bloomberg News put together an Olympics index in 1996,
consisting of 24 companies that paid $40 million apiece to sponsor
the games. Bloomberg didn't duplicate the effort this year.
</P>
<P>
   The connection between the Olympics and the market is probably
indirect. If the sponsors' shares do well over time, it's because
only successful companies with strong track records have the kind
of money to be an Olympic sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Olympics is not big enough to change Wall Street's
ways, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   If there should have been a clear winner from the 1996 games, it
was Coca-Cola, which bought $60 million worth of commercial TV time
and was most closely associated with Atlanta and the Games.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola is not, and its problems have nothing to do with
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
