<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-DEBATE-ART-     09-14 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-DEBATE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WITHDRAWS OBJECTIONS TO DEBATE SCHEDULE PROPOSED BY
COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 3rd graf to make clear that Bush was seeking shortening of
some debates, not all)  
(With BUSH-GORE-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT6,8,9,15,19,22 _ are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday withdrew all his objections to a
bipartisan commission's debate schedule, agreeing to three
90-minute prime-time encounters with Vice President Al Gore next
month on college campuses in Boston, Winston-Salem, N.C., and St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced after a four-hour meeting in Washington
of top officials of the Bush and Gore campaigns and representatives
of the Commission on Presidential Debates, means that Bush and Gore
will debate under all the original conditions laid out months ago
by the panel, which has organized the nationally televised forums
in every presidential election since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The accord amounted to a wholesale retreat by the Bush campaign
from its efforts over the last two weeks to impose its own
schedule, moving some of the debates from campuses to television
studios, shortening some of them from 90 minutes to 60 minutes, and
designating moderators like Larry King and Tim Russert.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, in the face of mounting criticism from fellow
Republicans and a growing sense that the issue was becoming a
distraction, aides to Bush announced they were dropping the plans
to seek an alternative series of debates. But they continued to
insist they were opposed to aspects of the commission plan, like
staging the first debate in Boston, near the John F. Kennedy
Library, because it commemorated a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Bush campaign conceded even those points. Under
the agreement, the candidates are to meet at the University of
Massachusetts in Boston on Oct. 3; Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem on Oct. 11 and Washington University in St. Louis on
Oct. 17. The vice-presidential contenders are to debate for 90
minutes at Centre College in Danville, Ky., on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The terms, precisely those the commission spelled out when it
unveiled the debate locations in January, were accepted months ago
by the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major thing is that the debate debate is over,'' said Paul
G. Kirk Jr., the former head of the Democratic Party who is
co-chairman of the debate commission. Kirk told reporters after the
meeting, which was held in the offices of the panel's legal
counsel, that the session had been without rancor. But he added
that ``some things we were not flexible on,'' like the notion of
moving any of the sites of the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's four and a half hours in a long campaign,'' Kirk said,
referring to the length of the three presidential debates. ``And we
didn't think it was asking too much,'' he said, ``particularly at a
time when the electorate is paying more attention than they have
been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides professed to be pleased with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have agreed to the sites; we have agreed to the times,''
Donald L. Evans, Bush's campaign chairman, said. ``The governor is
very eager to debate. He is looking forward to a free-flowing,
substantive, real and genuine discussion of all the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   William M. Daley, the chairman of Gore's campaign, concurred.
``This is good because the American people want to hear from these
people in formal settings that give them the opportunity to express
what they will do as the next president of the United States,''
Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bush officials sought to portray the outcome as less than
a setback, saying they were pleased that the commission was still
considering the kind of informal formats for the debates Bush had
sought. Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications director, said the
governor had always thought the public would be better served by
more casual discussions than by ``the canned and stilted formats
that have been the case in past presidential debates.'' About
Bush's pledge to participate in three debates, she added, ``He has
kept his commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political professionals wondered whether the Bush
campaign had badly miscalculated by offering a counterproposal and
trying to make it appear that Gore was the reluctant debater when
he refused to agree to Bush's terms. The Bush campaign even ran a
television commercial taunting the vice president on the issue
after Bush unveiled his debate plan on Sept. 3. In addition to
60-minute debates of CNN's ``Larry King Live'' and ``Meet the Press
on NBC,'' the Bush plan called for participation in one commission
forum, in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does raise questions about the tactics here,'' said
a Democratic official. ``Who in the world was going to think that
Al Gore does not want to have debates?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who attended the meeting said it was not
contentious at all. In fact, they said, the two sides had agreed
quickly to the items that had been the subject of the dispute, like
the locations and lengths of the debates.
</P>
<P>
   What consumed most of the session, they said, was working out
the details; for instance, the question of how members of the
audience might be chosen if a town-meeting arrangement were used
for one of the debates.
</P>
<P>
   The formats and moderators for the debates are still up in the
air, though it was agreed that there will be one moderator for each
forum, participants said. Kirk said he believed that many of the
remaining issues could be resolved over the next day or two.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The resolution came as a relief not only to the commission, but
also to the hosts of the debates. One of the panel's central
missions is to involve young people in the process, and that is why
the debates have come to be held on college campuses. This year's
sites were chosen from dozens of colleges and universities that had
submitted proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic that we'll be the first presidential debate for
2000,'' said Annemarie Lewis-Kerwin, a spokeswoman for the
University of Massachusetts in Boston, the site to which the Bush
campaign raised its most serious objections.
</P>
<P>
   The school has had to raise about $2 million from corporate
sponsors and the state Legislature to stage the event, Lewis-Kerwin
said, and it had already spent about $300,000 when Bush's proposed
a plan that threatened to scuttle the Boston debate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the commission's guidelines, formal invitations are to be
sent to the candidates several days before each debate. To qualify,
a candidate must have on the date of invitation the support of an
average of at least 15 percent of those polled in five national
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   This standard has been criticized by Ralph Nader and Pat
Buchanan, third-party candidates who say the threshold is
impossible for them to meet. Many political observers say that
third-party candidates could hope to register that level in the
polls only after an appearance on a nationally televised debate.
</P>
<P>
   Jamin B. Raskin, a professor of constitutional law at American
University who represented Ross Perot in 1996 in an unsuccessful
effort to be included in the presidential debates, said a less
arbitrary standard would be 5 percent, the threshold required by
federal law for a candidate to qualify for public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The co-chairmen of the Commission on Presidential Debates go
around saying they are not in the business of propping up
third-party candidates,'' Raskin said. ``They're in the business of
killing third-party candidates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
