<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: ECONOMY BRIGHTENS
</P>
<P>
   A healthier economy, lucrative oil exports and more effective
tax collection increased government revenues for the first half of
2000 to their highest level since the collapse of the Soviet Union,
Prime Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said. The government said it took
in $18.3 billion, nearly two-thirds of its anticipated revenue for
the entire year, and predicted a further increase in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: RIGHTISTS BANNED
</P>
<P>
   The government banned the far-right group Blood and Honor for
spreading neo-Nazi propaganda and breaching the Constitution. Its
so-called White Youth wing was also outlawed. ``Germany is the
first nation to fight this organization this way,'' Interior
Minister Otto Schily said. The group, which was founded in Britain
and spread to Germany in 1994, has ties to the larger far-right
German National Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: CARDINAL CALLED RACIST
</P>
<P>
   A leading cardinal has set off a political furor by suggesting
that Italy favor Catholic immigrants over Muslims to ``preserve the
identity of the nation.'' Many center-left government ministers
condemned Cardinal Giacomo Biffi's pastoral letter to his Bologna
archdiocese as dangerous and racist. But some center-right
politicians agreed with his proposal and the opposition leader
Silvio Berlusconi said the cardinal's ideas ``were deemed worthy of
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: TORY CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   In the latest blow to Canada's shrinking Tory party, the party
president resigned, only two days after two Tory members of
Parliament defected to the Liberals. Peter Van Loan, a Toronto
lawyer was an effective fund raiser, and his loss will hurt the
heavily indebted party.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CHARGED IN MURDERS
</P>
<P>
   The accused leader of one of Mexico's most powerful drug cartels
was charged in a United States federal indictment in El Paso,
Texas, with 10 counts of murder, including the killings of seven
people whose bodies were found last fall on ranches near Juarez.
Justice Department officials believe Vicente Carillo Fuentes, who
is a fugitive, ordered the murders to silence those who might have
given information to law enforcement agents.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MISSILE SYSTEM TESTED
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Arrow II antiballistic missile system was successfully
tested, intercepting a simulated missile similar to the Scuds fired
at Israel in the gulf war in 1991, the defense ministry said. It
was the seventh of eight tests that proved successful for the
system, which is heavily financed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: POLICE RAID OPPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Movement for Democratic Change said four party
officials were detained after its offices were raided by police
officers who said they were conducting an investigation into a
grenade blast this week outside the party's headquarters. No one
was hurt in the explosion, and the officers and intelligence agents
arrived at the offices with warrants allowing them to search for
firearms and explosives. They apparently found none.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: 4,435 SLAVES BOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss aid group said it bought the freedom of 4,435 slaves in
southern Sudan this month, bringing the total freed to 38,000.
Christian Solidarity International has been criticized by the
United Nations and rights groups, who say buying slaves encourages
captors to seize more people. The group said it paid $33 for each
slave.
</P>
</TEXT>
