<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GAMES WITHIN THE SYDNEY GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Well, let the Olympic fun begin, along with
the doping, the scalping, the ghastly boxing decisions, the
politically-motivated gymnastic scoring, the shameless corporate
shilling and whatever shenanigans Juan Antonio Samaranch and his
IOC minions dispense during the next 16 days.
</P>
<P>
   The 11,000 participating athletes will go through that garish
flag-waving show of international solidarity tonight the
globalization wonks hyperventilate over the opening ceremonies at
the 110,000-seat Stadium Australia.
</P>
<P>
   And then Saturday the volleyballs and softballs and arrows and
shuttlecocks and handballs and even swords and live ammunition will
be employed by those hardy souls attempting to earn gold medals for
themselves in the upcoming days.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there will be jocks in subsequent days who will
depend more on their speed do I hear Marion Jones, Maurice Greene
and Michael Johnson? or leaping ability what about Vince Carter and
Kevin Garnett? or durability how about Morroco's incredible
distance runner Hicham El Guerrouj? when pursuing their artistry.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure what will happen during the remainder of
this month, except it's as much of a certainty as Juan Antonio
Samaranch dissembling during press conferences that some athletes
from countries you've never heard of and some from countries you
have will be kicked out of the Olympics for failing drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for sure, the American basketball team will win the gold,
and I'm willing to bet anyone a princely sum that Venus Williams
and Serena Williams will do the same in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, none of the 60,000 people expected to descend on this
picturesque city or even the 100,000 expected to come from other
parts of Australia will be able to bet on any event unless they're
able to find an illegal bookmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The myriad TAB (Totalizer Agency Board) sports book outlets
around town, which usually take action on everything including NFL
games will not be posting lines on any Olympic events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will cost us millions,'' said one of the clerks at the
sports book at Star City, the biggest casino in town. ``The
decision came down from the government a couple of weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's in the hallowed IOC by-laws that legalized
gambling on the Games is forbidden in the host city.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Juan Antonio Samaranch, Generalissimo Franco's old
crony in Spain whose IOC organization is such a beacon of
righteousness, went bananas, demanding that SOCOG (Sydney
Organizing Committee of the Games) pressure the Australian
politicians into keeping his beloved Games pure and honest.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the fact that two members of Samaranch's Olympic family
earlier in the week were refused entry into this country because of
their ties to organized crime, or that many of Samaranch's top
aides have been accused of accepting bribes, or that most of his
media session Thursday was centered around the rampant corruption
allegedly afflicting his organization.
</P>
<P>
   No way Samaranch would want his sterling event polluted by
tourists easily able to lay bets on the outcome of that
much-anticipated 400-meter duel at least it is around here between
national idol Cathy Freeman and France's Marie-Jose Perec.
</P>
<P>
   And so TAB was forbidden by the Australian government recently
to post Olympic bets an easy chore since TAB is a government agency
and Samaranch will at least not have to worry about gambling
scandals being added to all the other IOC scandals. ...
</P>
<P>
   --In the grand and glorious history of Olympic press
conferences, the one staged by Juan Antonio Samaranch Thursday
might ranks as the most camp. The arrogant, pretentious Juan
Antonio affected the comically-serious aura of a Third World
dictator shorn of his raiment.
</P>
<P>
   Before it even started, his earphones weren't operating,
creating pure havoc at the podium as aides frantically scurried
around trying to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Once they did, Samaranch went into a spiel so tedious and
meaningless I momentarily swore I was listening to Dennis Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget that the athletes are an important part
of the International Olympics,'' was one of Samaranch's more
cornball statements.
</P>
<P>
   But not nearly as important as Samaranch's mighty organization,
which pockets untold millions from the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time for the international press to start grilling
Samaranch about the IOC's recent spate of unsavory incidents, he
either would respond he didn't understand the question and his PR
toady hurriedly would go on to the next interrogator or he would
give a vague answer that made no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who takes himself seriously, too seriously, was
visibly agitated by the negative tone of the journalists.
</P>
<P>
   But, as they say, he'll be laughing all the way to the bank, or
wherever he's been stuffing all those IOC profits. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how successful the Sydney Olympics will be 1.2
million tickets remained unsold as of Wednesday but I do know the
thousands of volunteers are the friendliest and nicest and most
helpful I've ever been around at any major athletic event. ...
</P>
<P>
   --It's a pleasure to be in a city where there are almost no SUVs
disrupting the scene. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The 18-hour time change it'll be Saturday morning here when
you read this conspires to make the jet lag lag far too long. ...
</P>
<P>
   --I know anything can happen Hicham El Guerrouj tripped over
himself in the Atlanta Olympics in 1996 and finished last in the
1,500 meters but Marion Jones should be the dominant figure in
these Games. ...
</P>
<P>
   Unless she trips over herself. ...
</P>
<P>
   --I still can't get accustomed to calling Tom Lasorda manager of
the U.S. Olympic team instead of manager of the Los Angeles
Dodgers. ...
</P>
<P>
   --With its beautiful harbors and coves and inlets and beaches,
Sydney reminds me of a cross between Seattle and San Francisco,
with a large pinch of Southern California. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Isn't it only fitting that they stuck the media in a sprawling
compound that once was Sydney's largest mental hospital? ...
</P>
<P>
   --San Fernando Valley public relations mogul Steve Brener is
here for the duration spreading propaganda for Speedo. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Venerable boxing PR guy Bill ``Bozo'' Caplan arrives next week
to hustle amateur fighters for promoter Bob Arum. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Jerry &AMP; Karen West of Bel Air will attend the Games. In case
you're wondering, West once worked for the Lakers. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The Australia team's top big man is Luc Longley, which means
the Australia team isn't destined to unseat the Americans. ...
</P>
<P>
   --OK, there has to be an unfriendly Aussie somewhere, or at
least one who doesn't smile. It's just I haven't yet come across
such a person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
