<SLUG> BC-TREK-FREAKYLINKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREAKYLINKS' COMES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and black-and-white photo of Ethan Embry
and Karim Prince in a scene from ``Freakylinks.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) &QC;
<P>
   Adam Barnes is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Or so his twin brother thought, until he switched on his
computer and fresh images of Adam flashed on the screen. Already
immersed in exploring the bizarre and purportedly paranormal via
his underground website, Freakylinks.com, Derek now must dig deeper
into the inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the wild world of ``Freakylinks,'' a new television
series that Fox will unveil on Oct. 6. Joining Derek Barnes (Ethan
Embry) on his adventures will be webmaster Lan (Lizette Carrion),
partner Jason Tatum (Karim Prince) and Adam's former fiancee, Chloe
(Lisa Sheridan). They'll also have to deal with the creepy presence
of Vince Elsing (Dennis Christopher), a psychiatric-ward patient
who seems to know more than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot clearly shows you that Derek will be tracking down
the mystery of his brother, and you'll have that backstory and that
lore,'' says David Simkins, the show's executive producer, whose
credits include ``The Adventures of Brisco County, Jr.'' and the
sci-fi saga ``Mercy Point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll deal with that, but not as often as was originally
intended in the initial conception of the show,'' he adds. ``We'll
probably tap into those stories every four or five episodes. Those
shows will have a slightly different flavor, a more foreboding
tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other episodes will be more fun,'' Simkins says. ``There
is some comedy here. We want each episode to be just slightly
different from the one before it, so the audience is not quite sure
what they'll be getting every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Simkins' ascension to the executive producer's seat came with
enough intrigue to confound Mulder and Scully, much less Derek
Barnes. ``Blair Witch Project'' producer Gregg Hale and ``Blade''
scribe David Goyer co-created ``Freakylinks,'' which began life as
``Fearsum,'' and Tommy Thompson of ``SeaQuest DSV'' and ``Quantum
Leap'' fame started as its executive producer and day-to-day
showrunner. Fox liked the pilot and greenlit ``Freakylinks'' as a
series, but insisted on a name change and a lighter tone for
subsequent episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, with those subsequent episodes still in the
process of being written, Thompson left the show, citing creative
differences with the network. Simkins, already a co-executive
producer, took over. A few weeks later, Fox announced that Hale and
Goyer likewise had severed their links with the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what Fox was asking for,'' Simkins says. ``I think I
do. I hope I do. No, I'm sure I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tommy's fear was that the network was asking for, in a
sense, a dumbing-down of the show,'' he says. ``I don't believe
that's true. I don't think the network would intentionally ask for
that, and I don't think that's what we are going to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale, it should be noted, was more involved with Fox's
interactive website _ freakylinks.com _ than with the show's daily
production. And though Hale's gone, the familiar ``Blair Witch''
shaky camerawork will remain part and parcel of ``Freakylinks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our actors walking around the sets (cameras in
hand), making their own discoveries,'' Simkins says. ``So we're
looking forward to using that immediacy of raw footage to tell a
visual story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The video aspect is completely in context with the show we're
doing,'' he adds. ``We can shoot more. We can get more coverage. We
can get deeper into the story and use that extra footage online, as
the show airs on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet aspect is freeing us up in quite a big way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, ``Freakylinks'' is a dash of sci-fi, a touch of
horror and a dollop of the Web. It's a left turn from ``The
X-Files'' and a right turn from reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all of that,'' Simkins says. ``What we really are
focusing on is a sense of reality. These characters are us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds so lame and everybody says that,'' he admits,
``but these guys are not professionals. They're in it because it's
interesting to them and because it's fun, and 10 times out of 10
they'll get into situations they had no idea were lurking in the
shadows. They'll just walk into stuff that can be sci-fi, that can
be supernatural, that can be of a psychic nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we want `Freakylinks' to be, it can be.''
 &UR; c.2000 Ian Spelling &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Freakylinks,'' consult the
official Web site at www.freakylinks.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
