<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ENERGY-ART-50     09-14 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ENERGY-ART-505(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFSHORE GAS DEPOSITS MAY FORGE ECONOMIC BOND BETWEEN ISRAEL AND
PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT34 and 35 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE SOUTHERN CROSS, off Gaza _ Drilling deep below the seas
off Israel and the Gaza Strip, foreign energy companies are
discovering gas reserves that could both lift the Palestinian
economy and give Israel its first taste of energy independence.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts, including those on this giant platform, say
the Palestinians and Israelis will both profit if they can work
together in a high-stakes partnership. They need each other for the
efficient development of these offshore reserves, since neither
side alone can fully afford the billion-dollar investment in
pipelines and pumping facilities that is being sketched out, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians and Israelis shy away from discussing a
collaboration, and territorial issues and long-lasting hostilities
could easily intrude. But both sides speak optimistically of the
potential bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important to the Palestinian economy because we will
not be permanently dependent on foreign aid,'' said Nabil Shaath,
the Palestinian planning minister, who expects gas deposits here to
supply all local electricity needs within three years, with a lot
left over for exports.
</P>
<P>
   Yehezkeel Druckman, Israel's petroleum commissioner, who
supervises the offshore explorations from a tiny two-room office in
the Ministry of National Infrastructures, is also optimistic. He
recently calculated that Israel now has some 3 trillion to 5
trillion cubic feet of proven gas reserves. That is a tenth the
size of Egypt's reserves, which are among the world's largest. But
it is enough to supply Israel's current electricity network for 25
years, Druckman estimated. ``And there may be more,'' he said this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Systematic exploration began this year, and Israeli officials
are encouraged because already large deposits have been identified,
though the ultimate quantity _ and quality _ cannot be known until
the gas starts flowing, and many things can go awry before a
profitable production.
</P>
<P>
   But for Israel, a country that never had energy reserves of its
own, and that for political reasons has been forced to import
almost all its fuel from far beyond the Middle East, the
discoveries are stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis used to joke about how Moses wandered in the desert
for 40 years and ended up in the one place that had no energy,''
said Leonard Coburn, the ranking Middle East specialist at the
Energy Department in Washington. ``All of a sudden, they have
energy. It is an extraordinary change.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, just months after sinking its diamond-tipped bit into a gas
find near the Israeli coast, this drilling platform has moved to
anchor 19 miles off the Gaza Strip, in 1,900 feet of water, poised
to complete the first exploration project in Palestinian waters.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Southern Cross bored into the seabed here,
industry executives were confidently anticipating reserves larger
than the Palestinians can profitably absorb _ but that could
readily be sold to Israel to supplement its own newly discovered
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else are we going to do with commercial quantities of
gas?'' said Said Khoury, co-owner of Consolidated Contractors Co.,
the Palestinian minority partner in the enterprise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Outside narrow industry circles and the upper echelons of both
governments, there is little awareness still of the scope of the
exploration or the dimensions of the projected reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government, now working on a strategy for a
long-term conversion to gas, has yet to publish its internal
estimates of its deposits, and appears reluctant to advertise its
collaboration with what could be a parallel gas bonanza for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office declined to comment on the
issue, though Defense Ministry officials said Barak ordered the
Israeli Navy not to interfere with the Gaza drilling. On the
Palestinian side officials are also close-mouthed, declining even
to reveal the terms of their exploration agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Without recent advances in deep-water drilling and with
sonogram-like geological scanning, it would not have been
technically or financially feasible to pinpoint these deposits, say
executives at BG Group, the giant British energy company that has
an exclusive 25-year concession in Gazan waters and licenses for
another 1,500 square miles off Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has already spent $25 million on the joint
exploration effort and will spend ``hundreds of millions'' more
within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Peering through a microscope at the first core sample unearthed
from Gaza Marine l, the geologists on board the Southern Cross
liked what they saw: distinct crystals packed just evenly and
densely enough to trap natural gas. ``Good porosity,'' pronounced
Hugh Miller, an Alabaman industry veteran who heads BG's operations
in Israel and the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, burly roustabouts wrestled fresh lengths of pipe onto
the milelong drill, now just 600 feet away from its target
reservoir of what BG believes are gas-saturated sands. ``Just like
a big Black &AMP; Decker'' drill, shouted Anthony Clark, the rig's
chief drilling engineer, as it drove deeper into the ancient
sediment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the seas here are smooth and the weather benign, BG Group
_ the $25 billion successor to the former British Gas, with energy
ventures throughout the world _ says the politics of the operation
are as daunting as any it has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, BG became the first big international energy company
to bid for an exploration concession in Israel's history,
effectively ending what Israelis had long denounced as a tacit
boycott of their country by the oil and gas majors. But when Yasser
Arafat, as president of the Palestinian Authority, then signed a
deal in London in November granting BG an exclusive 25-year
concession to explore for oil and gas off Gaza, the company knew it
was embarking on legally uncharted waters.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, it was not clear if there was such a thing as
Palestinian territorial waters, given the Authority's nonsovereign
status. The Oslo accords assigned the Palestinians a 20-by-20-mile
swath of sea for limited ``fishing, recreation, and economic
activity,'' but said nothing about resources beneath the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   But by default, the Authority and BG reasoned, the area between
Egypt's eastern maritime boundary and Israel's self-identified
exploration zone was Palestinian. Though Israel could restrict
shipping off Gaza for security reasons, it never claimed economic
rights there.
</P>
<P>
   With Barak's quiet assent, BG negotiated an agreement with the
Palestinians to spend up to $500 million of its own money on
natural gas development off Gaza. Under still undisclosed terms,
the Palestinian Authority will get a share of the production and
can tax the business. (In Israel, the government collects 12.5
percent of any gas discovered, plus a 36 percent tax on profits.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work this play as much as possible without
boundaries, because the rocks don't have boundaries,'' Miller said.
``The endgame here is to have Palestinian gas in the Israeli
market, which has to be good for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the gas business seems in better shape than the peace
process. The Israelis and Palestinians are both respecting the
unofficial division of coastal exploration rights, despite angry
objections from Israeli rightists and some local energy companies,
who are suing in Israeli courts to stop the Gaza drilling.
</P>
<P>
   But in a warning that a different Israeli government could stop
this venture cold, Danny Naveh, a leader of the opposition Likud
Party, charged that Barak could not authorize Palestinian
exploitation of what he termed ``Israeli territory'' without
parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating matters, gas has been located in at least
two large structures straddling the fuzzily demarcated line between
Israeli and Palestinian waters. The two sides must decide how to
allocate those reserves, which could have a production life of 10
to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   To efficiently develop these reserves, Israel and the
Palestinians would have to work together. Neither can afford
entirely separate plants and pipelines for pumping the gas to their
respective markets _ an investment that if undertaken jointly would
still approach $1 billion, Miller and other industry experts say.
</P>
<P>
   But the crux of this partnership, say officials on both sides,
should be a new Palestinian role as an energy supplier to Israel,
where electricity demand is 10 times greater than the Palestinians'
and growing by 7 percent yearly. In addition to Israel, Sha'ath,
the Palestinian planning minister, suggested, other potential
markets for surplus Palestinian gas include Jordan and, in time,
Turkish or European customers of a planned Egyptian pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the discoveries could provide not just energy to
Israelis and Palestinians, but fresh water, too. Natural gas would
make desalination plants an affordable adjunct to power plants
serving the densely populated Gaza and Israeli seacoast, helping to
resolve an acute potable water scarcity that is one of the region's
most difficult diplomatic and environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even with offshore gas, though, Israelis and Palestinians will
be importing oil for most of their transportation needs, experts
predict.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Palestinians, local gas would bring a welcome sense
of energy independence from Israel, which now supplies all
electricity in the Palestinian territories, at some of the region's
highest prices. The Palestinians already plan to use the offshore
gas at three new power stations they are building; the first, near
Gaza City, will be ready this year, followed by plants in Nablus
and Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will definitely save money,'' Sha'ath said.
</P>
<P>
   For the economically robust Israelis, whose gas will start
flowing first, the impact of this unexpected resource could be as
much psychological as financial.
</P>
<P>
   Because it had no choice, Israel has always relied on fuel from
far outside the Arab world: it now ships in coal from Australia,
Colombia and South Africa, and crude oil from Norway, Britain and
Mexico. Its one brief experience as an energy producer was after
the 1973 war in the occupied oil fields of the Sinai Desert, handed
back to Egypt in a 1979 treaty. Having its own gas reserves _ plus
access to nearby Palestinian deposits _ should make it easier for
Israel to buy additional gas from Egypt, which is now building a
gas pipeline to the Israeli border, analysts say. Israel's
objection to Egyptian gas was fear of dependence on a single Arab
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Meiman, an Israeli businessman whose company proposed an
undersea piping of Egyptian gas to Israel's coastal power plants,
expects Israel and the Palestinians to develop an integrated gas
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a geostrategic interest here,'' Meiman said. ``If you
want to live in a region where people are not throwing stones at
one another, the best way of doing it is by creating mutual
dependency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
