<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SPRAWL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Areas chied for uncontrolled growth
 &HT;    By Michael D. Pitman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASON, Ohio _ Mason and Deerfield Township are among the
nation's worst examples of uncontrolled commercial growth and
suburban sprawl, according to a Sierra Club report released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental group's members also said that additional
shopping malls proposed for the area in southern Warren County, on
the border with Hamilton County, should not be permitted because
they argue that Mason and Deerfield Township are too congested.
</P>
<P>
   A township government official responsible for development
issues disagreed with the Sierra Club's call for the development of
offices instead of retail shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Mason and Deerfield Township already have the largest
populations in the state's second-fastest growing county. The
Sierra Club report described the growth as out of control,
especially along Fields-Ertel Road. Malls planned at the two farms
on the corner of Irwin Simpson and Mason-Montgomery roads will only
worsen the congestion in the area, according to the report, ``Smart
Choices or Sprawling Growth: A 50-State Survey of Development''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart growth development can help rejuvenate downtowns and
main streets, create transportation alternatives, build walkable
communities, protect open space, better balance jobs, shops and
housing,'' said Glen Brand, the Sierra Club's midwest conservation
organizer. ``The question now is whether we have the courage and
vision to follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand said the traffic congestion on Fields-Ertel Road will move
north if the mall projects happen.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from Balance, a citizens' group whose members
want to preserve green space and control growth, and Deerfield
Township Residents for Controlled Growth, also voiced concerns
about the potential traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Deerfield Township's administrator of economic development,
Dan Theno, said said the residents and the Sierra Club report make
no new arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more logical to have an upscale mall than more office
buildings,'' Theno said.
</P>
<P>
   Total population of Warren County, as of July 1,
</P>
<P>
   1999, was 153,292 _ an increase of 5 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   A mall spreads out the traffic, whereas office buildings would
add to the morning traffic problems and to early evening traffic,
Theno said.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club members said the impact of suburban sprawl like that
experienced in Warren County is higher pollution, more access roads
and highways could be needed, higher taxes, a potential threat on
area schools, and potential problems with the natural aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can grow smarter,'' Brand said. ``We're not anti-growth or
anti-development. We're pro-smart growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club report includes a state-by-state description of
examples of what its members said are good and bad ways for
communities to grow. The only other Ohio city mentioned is
Cleveland, where the
</P>
<P>
   the proposed EcoVillage is intended to be an environmentally
friendly village within the larger city.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of EcoVillage's most innovative aspects is its commitment
to creating an urban oasis. Plans call for creating parks with
trails and bike routes, restoring environmentally degraded urban
habitats and enhancing open space. Residents, as well as wildlife
in the area, are sure to enjoy the tree-lined streets and plentiful
green space,'' according to the Sierra Club report.
</P>
<P>
   ``By locating housing next to an existing light-rail station,
the developers will be able to provide location-efficient
mortgages, giving homebuyers credit for reduced transportation
costs. Residents will have access via walking, biking or public
transportation to shops, markets and other resources within the
neighborhood. Many of the developments will also use passive solar
energy for heating and cooling.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
