<SLUG> BC-IVOR-SALLY-FIELD-DIRECTS-BEAUTIFUL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIDGET GROWS UP: SALLY FIELD STEPS BEHIND THE CAMERA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 ART NOTE: Includes two color slides of Sally Field directing
``Beautiful.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 c.2000 Ivor Davis 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Sally Field, still familiar in reruns as the bouncy star of
``Gidget'' and as the bubbly ``Flying Nun,'' isn't what comes to
mind when you hear the word ``grandmother.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, the two-time Oscar-winner is fiercely proud of the
fact that her son Peter has presented her with a 2-year-old
granddaughter _ even if, clad in a simple black dress worn with
flat shoes and a purple sweater knotted around her shoulders, she
hardly seems old enough to be a grandmother.
 &HT;    The 5-foot-2-inch actress, who will turn 54 in November, is
slender, girlish and little changed from the perpetually befuddled
teen-ager we knew way back then. But Field has grown up _ not only
to win her spurs as a dramatic actress but also to embark upon a
new chapter in her life: Sally Field, movie director.
 &HT;    Her first feature film as a director, ``Beautiful,'' will open
Sept. 29 and stars British actress Minnie Driver as the wildly
ambitious Mona Hibbard, clawing her way out of an unloving family
into the bright lights and dubious glamor of the beauty-contest
circuit.
 &HT;    She pursues her goal with such narcissistic passion that there's
no room in her world for her adorable, smart and illegitimate
daughter, Vanessa (Hallie Kate Eisenberg). Never having experienced
parental love, Mona doesn't know how to give it.
 &HT;    The tone of the film _ over-the-top satirical comedy meets
sentimental, feel-good family bonding _ would pose challenges for
any director, let alone one whose experience is limited to two
television outings: the ABC movie ``The Christmas Tree'' (1996) and
the astronauts'-wives episode of the highly acclaimed l998 HBO
series, ``From the Earth to the Moon.''
 &HT;    Field admits to having some qualms about the project, and
especially about the world of beauty pageants.
 &HT;    ``On one hand, it still seems incredible to me that in this day
and age we're still rating women on their physical appearance,''
she says. ``On the other hand, a lot of young women I talked to
while preparing to shoot this film told me that they were able to
find new opportunities in life through the pageants. They were able
to break out of impoverished backgrounds and get an education,
because the weird and wonderful and ironic part about pageants is
that they're still the largest scholastic organization for women's
education.''
 &HT;    While Field herself never marched down a runway in a swimsuit,
her experience as an actress left her knowing only too well what it
feels like to be scrutinized and judged by strangers.
 &HT;    The actress was only 18 when, in 1965, she was cast as the
boy-crazy Gidget after auditioning on a lark. The show lasted for
only a year, but she was promptly cast as the
pure-as-the-driven-snow ``Flying Nun,'' a role she played from l967
to 1970.
 &HT;    It took more than a decade for Field to convince Hollywood that
she was more than a lightweight television comedian, but she got
the job done, winning Best Actress honors for ``Norma Rae'' (l980)
and ``Places in the Heart'' (l985). She also proved that she could
handle big-screen comedy in films such as ``Steel Magnolias''
(l989) and ``Soapdish'' (l991).
 &HT;    Along the way the actress married twice and had three sons:
30-year-old Peter, 28-year-old Elijah and 12-year-old Sam. The
challenges of sustaining a family life while remaining active in
Hollywood were considerable, and Field says she brought that
experience to ``Beautiful.''
 &HT;    ``I didn't experience anything like Minnie's character in our
film,'' she says. ``but certainly the pull is something that I
completely identify with. Every working mother will tell you there
are times she'd like to pick her kids up and throw them out. Mostly
you spend your life being ripped to shreds, especially when you
support your family and you need to go out and earn a living and
also be there for your children.''
 &HT;    Field knew about single motherhood beforehand _ her mother and
father divorced when Field was 4, and her mother raised her _ so
she was glad to have her mother on hand to help out with her own
boys.
 &HT;    ``There were probably moments where I was just focused on my
work,'' she admits. ``But if any of my children needed me, that
would become the most important.''
 &HT;    Being a film actress is a plus, she says, in that it provides
all the household help that money can buy. At the same time, it's a
demanding job that takes its toll on parenthood.
 &HT;    ``You're away on location for long periods,'' she recalls, ``and
you've got to figure out how to get your children there as well as
to school. But there were long periods when I'd be at home and be
completely and utterly the mother. So I was always out of balance.
 &HT;    ``But I guess if you want balance you should join the circus.''
 &HT;    While she agrees with many of her contemporaries, 50-something
actresses who complain that the Hollywood studios' ``Boys Club''
attitude makes it tougher for actresses of a certain age to land
decent roles, she points out that it's nothing new.
 &HT;    ``It's always been harder for women,'' she says. ``If you read
Virginia Woolf's 'A Room of One's Own,' she was really talking
about women having a voice in literature. But you could certainly
apply that to women in film. A hundred years ago, women were not
allowed to have an education in this country. So would we expect
women by now to have caught up? No.
 &HT;    ``The lack of roles for women is a reverberation of history and
tradition,'' Field says. ``The movie industry tells us that
audiences aren't there for older actresses, but that's not really
true. If the product is there to bring the audience, things will
change.''
 &HT;    The actress began planning her big-screen directorial debut a
full five years ago, after having written and directed ``The
Christmas Tree.'' It took her a while, because she is still intent
on maintaining a career as an actress as well, most recently
playing Ashley Judd's biker mother in ``Where the Heart Is''
(2000).
 &HT;    This fall she'll return to the small screen to appear in six
episodes of ``ER,'' playing the estranged mother of medical student
Abby Lockhart (Maura Tierney). The producers are hoping she'll give
the show the kind of ratings boost that it got from Alan Alda's
appearance last year.
 &HT;    But the best sign that Field is happy with where she is has to
be a recent television commercial for a stock brokerage in which
she spoofs her much-maligned 1985 Oscar acceptance speech, with its
widely mimicked ``You really like me.'' Not that long ago, Field
would icily refuse to discuss that night at the Oscars.
 &HT;    ``Do you understand how tired I get of explaining this
question?'' she says, sounding a little peeved even now. But she
sips a glass of water and wades into one more round of explanation.
 &HT;    It all started with the 1980 Oscars, she says, when she won a
Best Actress award for ``Norma Rae.'' So stunned was she, so
dazzled by the magnitude of the event, that all she could do was
grab the statue, mutter some thank-yous and get offstage. She
didn't enjoy the moment at all.
 &HT;    ``It was all a blur,'' she recalls, ``like I was in a trance.''
 &HT;    Next time, she was determined, things would be different.
 &HT;    ``In this industry you face hurtful things, because of rejection
and because you just didn't do well,'' she explains, choosing her
words carefully. ``You feel those moments so acutely, and you allow
them to injure you like a bad blow. So you'd be a fool if you
weren't able to take the good, like the standing ovation. and say,
'I will feel this, goddam it, no matter how big the Academy Awards
are and how much pressure is on you to get offstage!'
 &HT;    ``So you cut to the chase, which is `I can't deny for this
moment that the work worked and you like me,''' she concludes.
``That's what it was about _ not, as it's been interpreted for
years, that somehow I thought I wasn't likable.''
 &HT;    Got it? Good, because Sally Field, actress and director, is
ready to move on.
 &HT;    And she hopes you are, too.
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Beautiful,'' consult the
official Web site at www.beautifulthemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
