<SLUG> BC-NASA-AUTHORIZATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    EDS: sent to ``a'' wire, resending to Washington wire
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Congress moves to cap NASA's share of space station
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOHN C. HENRY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress took steps Thursday to cap NASA's share of
space station development costs at $25 billion and clear the way
for the controversial Triana satellite proposed by Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are part of legislation approved by the House
outlining spending priorities and policies for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which faces a final vote in the Senate, authorizes the
space agency to spend $14.1 billion in 2001 and $14.6 billion in
2002. Both amounts are slightly higher than requested by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The measure _ which sets policy for the agency through 2002 _ is
the first NASA reauthorization bill on which the House and Senate
have reached agreement since 1992. Since then, funding and policy
guidelines have been written year-by-year and included in annual
appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's budget for the 2001 fiscal year _ which begins Oct. 1 _
is still being debated in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sticking points in yearlong negotiations over the
authorization bill has been House Republicans' objections to NASA's
Triana Earth-observation satellite.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by Gore, who says the idea came to him on a
sleepness night in the late 1990s, the camera-equipped satellite
would be parked halfway to the sun and provide a real-time view of
the Earth. Images would be available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, who derided the project as an expensive
computer ``screen-saver,'' yielded to Senate negotiators and $221
million _ four times the original cost estimates _ was written into
NASA's Earth science budget.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and the White House have argued that the satellite would
provide scientists with valuable data on the Earth's climate, cloud
and wind patterns, and solar flares.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans also backed away from their outright
opposition to NASA's involvement in developing an inflatable but
rugged three-story facility, called TransHab, to house engineers
aboard the space station.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bars NASA from using money to buy or design the
structure, but allows the agency to lease a privately developed
TransHab.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of about $2.5 million, engineers at Johnson Space
Center south of Houston have constructed a TransHab prototype. The
agency is looking for a private-sector partner to develop and build
a larger facility for use on the space station and, someday, on
missions to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional negotiators finalized their agreement on the NASA
authorization bill Tuesday as a crew of five Americans and two
Russians prepared the space station for its first residents, who
are due to reach the orbiting outpost in November.
</P>
<P>
   The authorization bill, which cleared the House 399-17 on
Thursday, includes a $17.7 billion cap for NASA shuttle missions to
assemble the space station, which eventually will be operated by 16
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials said the limits being imposed by Congress are
not out of line. ``We can work with those numbers. We're not real
happy with them, but when we get direction from the Hill we try to
follow it,'' said Kathy Nado, of NASA's Office of Space Flight.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with unforeseen problems, lawmakers agreed to set up
contingency funds for emergencies over the next two years _ $5
billion for the space station and $3.5 billion for the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kevin Brady, R-The Woodlands, said the compromise signals
Congress's support for NASA's mission. ``We were able to overcome a
fairly difficult year that included two preventable losses of Mars
vehicles and the emotional debate that followed over NASA's
philosophy of `better, cheaper, faster''' space exploration, Brady
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the estimated cost of developing the space station was
$17.4 billion. Current estimates put the cost somewhere between $24
billion and $26 billion. NASA blames the overruns on delays by
Russia's space agency, which failed to stay on schedule for
building, then launching, the space station's service module.
</P>
<P>
   One section of the NASA authorization bill requires the agency
to obtain assurances from Russia that it puts a higher priority on
completion of the international project than on keeping its aging
Mir space station in orbit. Earlier this year, Russia diverted
three space missions _ each originally intended for the space
station _ to help keep Mir aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Government accountants estimate that the total U.S. cost of the
space station _ from initial planning during the Reagan
administration through development, assembly, occupation and the
expected 20-year life of the facility _ is expected to reach $100
billion.
</P>
