<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN     09-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S GYMNASTICS TEAM BRACES FOR FOR THE WORST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Bela Karolyi couldn't seem to remember
anyone's name. Which seemed fair considering U.S. Olympic Committee
officials misspelled his on the placard in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Dawes picked at her fingernails. Kristen Maloney
looked as comfortable as someone awaiting a dental procedure. Tasha
Schwikert appeared terrified. Elise Ray had that frozen,
deer-in-headlights stare. Amy Chow seemed to be wondering how she
got mixed up with this crew.
</P>
<P>
   And Palmdale's Jamie Dantzscher watched the festivities with her
sprained right ankle heavily wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Say hello, America, to your U.S. women's Sydney Olympics
gymnastics team, such as it is, presented for the media's
observation at a press conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   These are the successors to the Maginificent Seven of Atlanta,
and they have morphed into a rather motley crew of six athletes and
three coaches who appear to be bracing themselves for disaster
rather than getting ready for a victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   The team activity Thursday night?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to watch `Titanic,' &UR;  &LR; '' Dantzscher said.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Nothing like preparing for a disaster by watching one.
What's on tap Friday night, a showing of ``Armageddon''?
</P>
<P>
   We love our Olympics gymnasts. We love to watch them perform. We
love to watch them win medals.
</P>
<P>
   Would you settle for two out of three this time around?
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Miller, Kerri Strug and the gang won team gold (and a
nation's love) at Atlanta in 1996. Then they all retired, or quit
practicing. Bela Karolyi, architect of the victory, retired as
well.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. women's gymnastics fell like a stone. Or like an
amateur off the balance beam.
</P>
<P>
   The female Yanks were a distant sixth in world team competition
in both 1998 and 1999. It was after the latter disaster that the
U.S. gymnastics federation went riding down to Houston to summon
Karolyi out of retirement to see if he could scrounge up something
resembling a world-class squad in time for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Bela and the posse arrived too late, it would seem.
</P>
<P>
   If body language, palpable tension and things said and left
unsaid tell us anything about athletes on the eve of competition,
this crew is headed for the bottom of the Atlantic. Or the Tasman
Sea, in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The team is alternately too young (Schwiker), too old (Dawes,
Chow), too internationally inexperienced (Maloney, Ray) or too
nicked up (Dantzscher) to do much damage.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the women seem to think Schwiker shouldn't even be
on the team (a controversial injury replacement over the
higher-ranked Alyssa Beckerman). And team unity?
</P>
<P>
   Said Dawes, in a less-than-enthusiastic outburst: ``We all get
along, you know, fairly well.''
</P>
<P>
   United we stand. Divided, you know, we fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Karolyi, who could teach Don King a thing or two about
bombast, could come up with a coherent reason to like this team.
They are experienced, young, powerful, brave, eager, fresh and do
an excellent job choosing professional hair-care products.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bela settled on ``most -balanced team,'' which in
this case seemed to mean they are equally inadequate in every area.
</P>
<P>
   If Karolyi had his druthers, Miller would be on this team.
Perhaps Dominique Moceanu, as well. But both sustained injuries
while attempting comebacks, and Dawes and Chow are the only Olympic
vets here.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan White was supposed to be here, too, but she's hurt. And
now Dantzscher has that sprained ankle she was trying to ignore
Thursday. We don't know how your sprained ankles go, but ours
usually preclude vigorous tumbling for a month or two.
</P>
<P>
   Women's gymnastics competition begins Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what to expect from this team, Karolyi was evasive.
We will fight on the mats, we will fight on the beaches, we shall
never surrender ... and if any of these girls gets a medal I'll do
a cartwheel right over the victory podium.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically? Ray has a shot in the all-around. Maloney could
medal in floor exercise if everything breaks right. And Chow has a
chance in the bars.
</P>
<P>
   Any medal would be a pleasant surprise. And by the looks of the
U.S. women's gymnastics team Thursday, they seemed to believe
``pleasant surprises'' are not on the Sydney itinerary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
