<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-DIVERSITY-IN-FLA-UNIVERSITIES-BUSH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY ENROLLMENT IN FLORIDA'S UNIVERSITIES INCREASES
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    (New York Times OpEd for Friday, September 15, and
thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JEB BUSH  
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. __ As college students around the nation began
classes earlier this month, the incoming class at Florida's 10
public universities made headlines just by showing up. In the first
year that Florida universities stopped using race as a factor in
admissions decisions, minority enrollment increased by 12 percent
for students entering the system for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, I proposed replacing traditional affirmative
action policies with race-neutral and legally defensible strategies
to expand diversity and opportunity in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, traditional affirmative action has been under
attack because it has lost public support and become legally
suspect: Ballot initiatives in California and Washington state have
eliminated affirmative action policies, and federal courts in
Georgia and Texas have ruled such practices unconstitutional as
applied to state university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   We have seen how diversity suffers in state universities where
policy-makers wait until a ballot initiative or court order
eliminates affirmative action and we know who has paid the price:
racial and ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, we saw the writing on the wall, and did not want to
be captive to ballot initiatives and court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   First, we have replaced race and ethnicity with other admissions
criteria that will promote diversity and preserve equal access to
state colleges. These include a student's socioeconomic background,
geographic diversity, and whether the student comes from a
low-performing public school or is a first-generation college
student.
</P>
<P>
   Second, we have increased capacity in the state universities so
that we can guarantee admission to every Florida student who
graduates in the top 20 percent of his or her high school class.
</P>
<P>
   Third, we have provided a 43 percent increase in need-based
financial aid, an expansion that will make our state colleges far
more accessible to low-income students.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and perhaps most important, we are devoting
unprecedented resources and attention to our lowest performing
primary and secondary schools, where 85 percent of students are
African American, Hispanic or other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Among other changes, we are making the PSAT available free of
charge to all Florida 10th graders. We will also provide free SAT
prep courses at the lowest-performing schools, and guarantee
students at those schools access to Advance Placement coursework.
In addition, every college in the state will be required to
establish alliances with low-performing high schools to improve
achievement and college preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   This plan, called One Florida, can be a model for other states
because its goal is to transcend the increasingly tired debate
about affirmative action. We intend to prove that government can be
race-neutral in its decision-making without turning a blind eye to
equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   While we have moved beyond traditional policies, we have
succeeded in increasing the number of minorities enrolled in
college. In fact, the freshman class at state universities is the
most diverse in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the practical benefits of such an approach are the
intangible, yet significant moral benefits that occur when
diversity is achieved with fairness. Every student entering
Florida's university system can be confident that achievement, not
skin color or ethnic background, is the measure of merit.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeb Bush is governor of Florida.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
