<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-TIRES-405&AMP;ADD-NY     09-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-TIRES-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD CHAIRMAN DEFENDS COMPANY PRESIDENT'S MORE VISIBLE ROLE ON
TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIRE-RECALL) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ During his first news conference since
Bridgestone/Firestone announced the recall of 6.5 million tires
used mainly on Ford Explorers, William C. Ford Jr., Ford Motor's
chairman, Thursday defended his decision to let the company's
president, Jacques Nasser, handle all public appearances concerning
the tire problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it was Nasser's responsibility as the head of Ford
Motor's management team to respond to the initial recall, and once
the recall became a much larger public relations and regulatory
issue it would have been confusing to change.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is the great-grandson of Henry Ford and his mother is a
daughter of Harvey Firestone, the tire maker's founder and a friend
of Henry Ford. But Ford said Thursday that his family relationships
had not prompted him to recuse himself in any way from the tire
issue.
</P>
<P>
   He was sharply critical of Firestone, which was purchased by
Bridgestone Corp. of Japan in 1988, saying that, ``It hurts to see
a family name and a family heritage tarnished so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor also announced Thursday that it would buy back $5
billion worth of stock, and Ford defended that decision to
distribute cash to stockholders in the middle of a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said the move would not interfere with Ford Motor's
handling of the tire issue and represented a reward to shareholders
for not selling their stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is very much a tire issue, not a Ford issue,''
he said at the news conference, which was held Thursday afternoon
after Ford Motor's board had met to review the tire problems. He
spoke on a conference call with reporters instead of at Ford
Motor's briefing center, a move that made it impossible for
television cameras to film him.
</P>
<P>
   The moves by Ford Motor came as congressional investigators are
focusing on whether Ford Motor and Firestone chose too low a
pressure for the inflation of the tires _ 26 pounds per square inch
_ and whether the tires were adequately tested at that pressure
before being put on Explorers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., the chairman of the House Commerce
Subcommittee for Consumer Protection, scheduled a hearing next
Thursday morning on the companies' choice and testing of the tire
pressure. Tauzin has demanded that both companies provide all of
their test data to his subcommittee and the House Commerce
Subcommittee for Oversight and Investigation by Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   C. Tab Turner, a lawyer in Little Rock, Ark., who specializes in
tire failure and vehicle rollover cases and who has filed some of
the many lawsuits against Ford Motor and Firestone, said that he
had seen during litigation many of the Firestone test results that
Tauzin is now demanding.
</P>
<P>
   The recalled tire models suffered tread separations _ the type
of tire problem now blamed in dozens of fatal crashes _ in 600 to
700 of the roughly 1,000 tests that Firestone conducted over the
last decade, he said. Many of the tests were designed to push the
tires to their limit to determine when tread separation occurred,
but the sheer number of tests shows that Firestone suspected a
problem, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone officials did not return calls for comment Thursday
but have said repeatedly that the tire maker's safety staff only
became aware of a problem at the beginning of August, just before
the recall was announced on Aug. 9. But the company's financial
records show that the company's accountants had identified a
problem at least by 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vaughn, a Ford Motor spokesman, said the company had
tested the tires at 26 pounds per square inch by driving Explorers
with the tires at 100 miles per hour for a distance of 200 miles on
a test track in Arizona. No problems were detected, he said. Ford
Motor proceeded Thursday with the buyback despite concerns raised
even by some Wall Street analysts that returning money now to
shareholders might be viewed as insensitive given the nearly 100
deaths linked to the failure of Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Henry D.G. Wallace, Ford Motor's chief financial officer, said
the stock buyback represented a continuation of the company's plan,
announced last April, to distribute to shareholders $10 billion of
the automaker's cash reserves. The company set up a plan in April
to give stockholders a choice of cash or additional shares, but so
many chose the additional shares that the company only ended up
distributing $5.3 billion of the planned $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin declined to comment on the buyback. Joan Claybrook, the
president of Public Citizen, a consumer advocacy group, said that
she was not concerned as long as the buyback did not affect the
recall.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts applauded Ford Motor's move even while noting
the awkward timing. ``You can be a little surprised they did it in
the face of the tire fiasco,'' said Ron Tadross, an analyst at
Credit Suisse First Boston. ``The tire issue is a completely
separate issue and this doesn't restrict at all Ford's ability to
deal with the recall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor shares rose 69 cents, to $25.94.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said that Ford Motor had $20 billion in cash now, so
disbursing $5 billion would have no effect on the company's
financial soundness or ability to handle the recall. William C.
Ford Jr., who took control of the company back from professional
managers when he became chairman at the beginning of last year,
also said that the tire issue would not prevent him from trying to
position Ford Motor as the auto industry's leader in safety and
environmental issues, although he acknowledged that the tire
problems had hurt that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a flavor of the month, it's a flavor of a lifetime,
it's a flavor of a career,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
