<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN0915-COX     09-14 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old allies lament Lieberman shift
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Joe Lieberman was sharing the stage with Al Gore
last month when he joked that the way to halt his support for
school voucher programs was to elect him vice president.
</P>
<P>
   As the loyal soldier to Gore, Lieberman would follow the
president's agenda, not his own. And Gore has been an outspoken
opponent of using federal money to help pay for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Schwartz, the general counsel to the American Tort Reform
Association, was not joking when he made essentially the same point
on another issue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been the Senate's leading Democratic proponent of
efforts to limit Americans' right to sue and cap jury awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore wins, then you get rid of him,'' Schwartz said,
lamenting Lieberman's potential exit from the Senate. ``On some
issues, maybe, Gore will listen to him, but not this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not favor reining in trial lawyers. In fact, trial
lawyers have contributed nearly $5 million to Gore's campaign,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the month since Democrats nominated him as their vice
presidential candidate, Lieberman has effectively silenced some
Democrats who worried about his stands on a number of key issues,
including affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman began embracing Gore's positions even before the end
of the Democratic convention. And in its aftermath, as the
Democratic ticket has risen in the polls, Lieberman has been widely
portrayed by Democrats as a boon to Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the earlier concern has been muted, if not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Face it, he's no longer so much `Joe Lieberman, the guy who
all conservatives like,' '' said David Bositis, who studies
African-American voting trends at the Joint Center for Political
and Economic Studies in Washington. ``He seems to have become more
of a populist, like Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   On affirmative action, for instance, Lieberman stood before the
Democratic convention and said he supports the ``mend it, don't end
it'' policy that President Clinton adopted in 1995 in the wake of
court decisions that said some affirmative action programs ran
afoul of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Gore have been very reassuring about affirmative
action,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   And Lieberman's staff has worked hard to suggest to reporters
that on some of these issues, Lieberman's shift has not been
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gerstein, the senator's spokesman, pointed to three
instances in the past five years in which Lieberman opposed
Republican efforts to end racial preferences in federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   But days after Clinton announced the administration's position
in 1995, Lieberman said he favored ending most mandatory preference
programs. ``We have come to a different conclusion, respectfully,
than the President did,'' Lieberman said then.
</P>
<P>
   Much more recently, in the months before he vaulted to
prominence as Gore's running mate, Lieberman signed the Hyde Park
Declaration drafted by the Democratic Leadership Council, a group
of moderate Democrats that Lieberman chairs.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a call to ``resist an `identity politics' that
confers rights and entitlements on groups.'' And the document also
sets as a goal for 2010 to ``shift the emphasis of affirmative
action strategies from group preferences to economic empowerment of
all disadvantaged citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   On tort reform, Lieberman has been an unambiguous ally of
insurers and manufacturers in Senate battles over limiting
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   He has been one of a handful of Democrats to regularly join
Republicans in seeking to cap industry liability, once even voting
to shield gun makers from lawsuits by crime victims who had been
shot. Lieberman is a strong proponent of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   His support of insurance companies and their desire to limit
payouts to people who successfully sue businesses stems as much
from political philosophy as from the fact that Connecticut is home
to 36 insurance companies that employ 50,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, Lieberman has not changed his views publicly, but
he has had little to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's shift on some issues since his selection may not be
surprising, given the necessity of falling in line with the
presidential candidate. But Schwartz said, ``There is a pattern
that saddens me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman did not come to his views on limiting lawsuits and
jury awards or on affirmative action overnight, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bositis, who supports affirmative action programs, described
Lieberman's opposition as ``principled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just view it as doing what he had to do, to the
chagrin of conservatives,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman campaign media aides did not return calls for this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Gore picked Lieberman, the Bush campaign and
the Republican National Committee began a steady stream of releases
that pointed up differences between the two Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans hit especially hard on school choice, personal
retirement accounts and managed care reform. On those issues,
Lieberman's rhetoric and voting record had somewhat resembled
Bush's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 31, for instance, a Bush campaign release said that
Lieberman last year ``blasted'' a Gore-supported Democratic managed
care reform bill because it allowed limitless legal assaults on
health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up the system to the unlimited right to sue and
creates the same prospect for the lotteries that have been going on
elsewhere in the tort system,'' Lieberman said on the Senate floor,
as quoted by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on discrepancies has dissipated in recent weeks, but
Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett said it would intensify again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's credibility is an issue. Using Joe Lieberman's
voting record is a good way to show that,'' Bartlett said. ``One
place you'll definitely see it invoked is in the debates.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
