<HEADER>
A5755 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LEE-RELEASE-ASSESS-NY     09-14 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-RELEASE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: 2 HEARINGS APPEAR TO HAVE PLAYED CRUCIAL ROLE IN JUDGE'S
STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With LEE-RELEASE-CLINTON) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Last December, Judge James A. Parker of the
Federal District Court here had two crucial encounters with John
Kelly, then the U.S. attorney for New Mexico, in hearings in the
case of Wen Ho Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of Parker's startling denunciation of the government's
tactics in the case, delivered on Wednesday before Lee was released
after pleading guilty to mishandling nuclear secrets, may have been
sown at those hearings. That is when, the judge appears to have
felt, he was misled by government officials driven by questionable
motives.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hearing, Kelly, who had not previously appeared in
the case, stood up in court and argued that if the judge agreed to
release Lee to home detention on bail _ something the judge was
clearly leaning toward _ the conditions would require so much time
and supervision that it would amount to the creation of a ``private
jail'' at Lee's home.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's message was clear: if Parker released Lee it would form
the basis of an appeal that would overturn the order, something
judges tend to avoid. Kelly's personal presence made it clear that
the full weight of the federal government would lie be behind any
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the second and more important encounter, Parker met with the
two sides privately in a closed hearing. According to lawyers
familiar with the meeting, Kelly and a senior agent of the FBI,
Robert Messemer, vigorously warned the judge that enemy
intelligence agents were poised to search out and possibly capture
the nuclear secrets that Lee had improperly downloaded. They
saidthat if Lee, who they claimed had engaged in a pattern of
deceptions, were released even to closely supervised home
detention, the nation would be vulnerable to a catastrophic loss of
information.
</P>
<P>
   Parker agreed with the government and, for nine months, Lee, 60,
was held under conditions reserved for the most violent,
threatening defendants. For several months, the lights were kept on
in his cell without pause and every one of his actions was watched.
He has said he was underfed and constantly hungry. When he
exercised, one hour a day, five days a week, he was shackled. For
the one hour a week that he could meet with his wife and children,
an officer was at his side.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Parker apologized to Lee for those conditions,
said he was wrong in sending him to jail, and launched a scathing
attack on the government, and Kelly in particular, for misleading
him into making what he said was a faulty decision.
</P>
<P>
   While he criticized several aspects of the government's case,
Parker's most acid remarks focused on the lengths the prosecutors
went to keep Lee in prison. And though the judge was not specific,
previous comments he has made in the case suggest that he felt
misled to the point of betrayal by the warnings the officials made
at the closed hearing last December, which have not been previously
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell you with great sadness that I feel I was led astray
last December by the executive branch of our government through the
Department of Justice, by its Federal Bureau of Investigation and
by the United States Attorney for the District of New Mexico, who
held office at that time,'' the judge said in court.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly resigned from his office in January, just days after the
bail hearing, and is now running for Congress from New Mexico as a
Democrat. He said in an interview on Monday that he felt the plea
agreement was a good result for the government.
</P>
<P>
   It received little notice at the time, but several weeks ago,
when Parker delivered a blow to the government and decided to
finally release Lee on bail, he took note of the fact that the
threats of enemy efforts to snatch up the nuclear secrets Lee
downloaded had proven hollow.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Parker himself asked Messemer, when he was testifying
on the witness stand, if a big increase in enemy intelligence
activity had materialized. Messemer quietly responded that it had
not. During the same hearing, Messemer also acknowledged that he
had provided misleading testimony last December in several other
critical issues.
</P>
<P>
   He had said Lee lied to a colleague to gain access to a
computer, then recanted. In addition, he had said Lee had sent
letters to a number of foreign scientific institutes seeking a job,
suggesting that Lee may have downloaded all the secrets in an
effort to enhance his job prospects. But during his latest
testimony Messemer recanted again, saying the FBI had no knowledge
that any such letters had ever been sent.
</P>
<P>
   Parker clearly had such events in mind when he read his
withering criticisms in court on Wednesday, which amounted to his
judgment and sentence of the government's actions. But one other
thing was clear, a touch of frustration that, with the criminal
case closed, there would be no further opportunities, in his
courtroom at least, to find out why the government had acted in
this way, or why it had singled out Lee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the judge's most important rulings for the defense was an
order several weeks ago that the government hand over to him a huge
volume of classified documents so he could decide whether there was
evidence that Lee had been unfairly singled out for prosecution.
The material he ordered was due this Friday, a deadline that was
lifted with the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Parker noted Wednesday that the government's sudden change of
heart in its willingness to release Lee ``occurred shortly before
the executive branch was to have produced, for my review in camera,
a large volume of information that I previously ordered it to
produce.''
</P>
<P>
   He later said he was troubled that he did not know why the
government acted so irresponsibly, and he remarked, pointedly, ``We
will not learn why because the plea agreement shields the executive
branch from disclosing a lot of information that it was under oath
to produce that might have supplied the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker was careful to explain to Lee in his remarks the
differences between the three branches of government. What he did
not explain, but seemed to know others in Washington would
understand, is that one of the products of this distinction is
that, even though the courts no longer have the right to those
government documents, it is well within the right of Congress to
subpoena them. The judge's remarks were as close to an invitation
and road map as the Congress is likely to get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-SECT-NYT &LR;      09-14 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA RELEASES DETAILS OF RAPE CHARGES AGAINST LEADER OF HEALING
SECT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese officials released details Thursday
surrounding the rape charges that have been filed here against the
leader of a besieged healing sect who sneaked onto U.S. territory
in January and is seeking political asylum in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The asylum request of Zhang Hongbao, founder of a large
spiritual and healing movement called Zhong Gong, has posed a
difficult choice for the U.S. immigration service. The United
States wants to foster the mutual extradition of criminals with
China, and failure to turn over Zhang _ who arrived in Guam with a
phony Chinese passport and is accused of raping some of his
followers _ would be deeply resented by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhang insists that he is a victim of political persecution
and U.S. officials know that, given Beijing's campaign to crush his
organization, he is extremely unlikely to receive a fair trial.
They also know that charges of rape or other criminal activities
have sometimes been trumped up by Chinese authorities to silence
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, 46, is currently in detention in Guam, awaiting the
delayed decision of an immigration court, expected to come this
month. Thursday, in an apparent effort to bolster their case,
officials here took the unusual step of providing copies to a small
number of journalists of what they said were statements by rape
victims, the victims' photographs (with eyes blacked out), arrest
warrants and other documents. These were a portion of the evidence
given to the U. S. government, a Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
   The materials were provided on condition that the alleged rape
victims not be fully identified, and that the office providing them
also be concealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to repatriate Zhang Hongbao because he broke the law,
not because of his work with Zhong Gong,'' said the official. The
crackdown on Zhong Gong and other independently organized
``qigong'' societies, devoted to the cultivation of cosmic energies
to enhance physical and moral well-being, started last year after
one such group, Falun Gong, held illegal demonstrations and then
was outlawed as an ``evil cult.''
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown in recent months of hundreds of Zhong Gong
businesses and the arrests of several leaders, the official
insisted, were because of tax fraud and other illegal business
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Zhong Gong _ its full name translates as China Health Care and
Wisdom Enhancement Practice _ is one of the largest of many groups
that arose in the last two decades using traditional concepts of
qi, or energy, in gong, or ritual exercises, to promote health and
enlightenment. Its Web site is www.ZGZG.net.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang founded Zhong Gong in 1988, four years before the start of
Falun Gong, and by the early 1990s it claimed tens of millions of
followers. Zhang was from the beginning controversial as he set
himself up as the ``master'' and made extravagant claims that his
followers could attain supernatural powers.
</P>
<P>
   As his organization and related businesses grew _ outside the
control of the Communist Party _ it clashed with local authorities
in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents provided Thursday, the authenticity of
which could not be verified, back in 1990, a Ms. Li accused Zhang
of raping her on June 26 of that year in his Beijing office, where
he had lured her for what he said would be a special healing.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1991, the materials indicate, Beijing police issued a
``notice of detention'' for Zhang. But he was never picked up,
according to the account, in part because he moved and began using
a pseudonym and forged identity documents, copies of which were
pro- vided.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ensuing years, Zhang also set up a large, well-known
healing center in Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
   The two other signed testimonies provided Thursday _ from a Ms.
Guo and a Ms. Zhang describing events that allegedly occurred in
Sichuan in 1994 _ were recorded by police only in November and
December of 1999, according to the documents. This was after the
campaign to destroy Zhong Gong was underway and Zhang Hongbao had
gone into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Guo's statement says Zhang Hongbao had her come alone into his
office , where he hugged her and ``forced me to touch and play with
his penis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhang alleges that Zhang Hongbao raped her in that same
location, claiming that ``men and women had to complement each
other, like Yin and Yang, to cure disease.'' Her testimony
describes features of Zhang's penis, his pubic hair and other
intimate details.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Hongbao was formally charged with rape, and a warrant was
issued for his arrest, on June 7, 2000 _ five months after he had
arrived in Guam seeking asylum.
</P>
</TEXT>
