<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wide spreads tarnish divisional matchups
 &HT;    By Ken Seguira
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In college football, the cries would be deafening.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is St. Louis doing playing San Francisco?'' ``Why did
Jacksonville schedule a cupcake like Cincinnati?'' ``I have only
one thing to say about the Washington-Dallas game: BCS.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the NFL. Not only are these teams playing each other,
they play again later in the season because they are in the same
divisions. All three games have double-digit point spreads,
uncommon in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The consolation is that some good games are on the schedule. In
addition, the spread doesn't always hold. The two games with the
widest point spreads last week _ Kansas City-Tennessee and St.
Louis-Seattle _ both were decided by a field goal, and the Titans
won in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Three games will decide first place. Denver (1-1) will be at
rival Oakland (2-0) to decide early-season primacy in the AFC West.
In the AFC East, Buffalo and the New York Jets are 2-0 and a game
ahead of the Dolphins and the preseason favorite Colts. The NFC
Central lead is at stake in the Silverdome between Detroit and
Tampa Bay, both 2-0. The Buccaneers have lost five of six in the
Silverdome.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-Oakland game might come down to a Broncos field-goal
attempt. The Raiders cut Joe Nedney after they drafted Sebastian
Janikowski, but they waited through preseason to let him go because
they were trying to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City was rumored to have been interested, but Nedney said
the Raiders wouldn't deal because they didn't want to trade him to
a team in the same division. So they let him go, and after Broncos
kicker Jason Elam hurt his back, Nedney joins the Broncos, also in
the same division as Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   GRUDGE MATCH: A week after Falcons coach Dan Reeves returned to
Denver, where he had his first head-coaching job, Broncos coach
Mike Shanahan goes back to Oakland, where he first was a head coach
before he was fired after a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   UPSET OPPORTUNITY: We go back to Oakland, where the Raiders have
lost four of their five games against the Broncos since moving back
from Los Angeles. The Raiders, favored by a field goal, will have
to outplay Denver by a lot to win.
</P>
<P>
   DIVISIONAL MATCHUP: San Diego will be at Kansas City in a game
both teams need desperately. The loser will fall to 0-3 and can
abandon hope for the season.
</P>
<P>
   INDIVIDUAL MATCHUP: Minnesota quarterback Daunte Culpepper ran
for three touchdowns the first week and then threw for 355 yards
last Sunday. New England coach Bill Belichick, the so-called
defensive genius, will try to work up a scheme to harness Culpepper
and his purple band.
</P>
<P>
   FANTASY PLAY: New York Giants receivers Ike Hilliard and Amani
Toomer must be drooling at the prospect of playing the Bears, who
have given up 71 points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
