<SLUG> BC-REBECCA-LIEBERMAN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman's daughter a good campaigner
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Rebecca Lieberman has never been elected
anything, never even run for anything. But during her third day on
the campaign trail, Joseph Lieberman's second child handled the
crowd, the press and the local pols with the aplomb, of well, a
senator's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   She tackled sticky questions about her parents' divorce and her
departure from her dad's strict religious practices without so much
as a hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the risk of believing in my dad. I can tell you without a
doubt, it's warranted,'' Lieberman told an audience of mostly 18-
to-22-year-olds at Florida Atlantic University on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very personable,'' said Rhanda Wynds, a 23 year-old
business student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personable,'' agreed Robyn Faust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, very genuine,'' said senior Marshal Klaven.
</P>
<P>
   To about 50 students, Lieberman called her father ``a good and
caring and judicious man ... who's open minded and really
listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, 31, stumped at the University of Florida in
Gainesville on Wednesday then swung through the Boca Raton
Elementary School Thursday morning before meeting student leaders
and local media at FAU.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with the earnestness of a grade school teacher,
Lieberman touched on health care, affordable housing and education
and managed a few jabs at what she called Bush's tax cuts for the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, she described her father in almost
reverential terms. He and her mother, Betty Haas, married young and
grew apart, she said.They called it quits when she was 12. After
the divorce, Rebecca and her older brother would stay at their
mother's house for half the week and their father's house the other
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a very good packer,'' Lieberman joked. ``My parents
did an incredible job of getting divorced, which is a strange thing
to say, but they have always agreed on how to parent my brother and
I.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Lieberman said, she has her father's ear on politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, after the Senator announced he would vote to confirm
Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court, Lieberman, then 22, lobbied
him to vote against Thomas. She told him a Thomas nomination would
send a message that sexual harassment is not to be taken seriously,
according to a 1992 story in The Hartford Courant.
</P>
<P>
   When President Bush urged the senator to vote for Thomas, he
told the president of his daughter's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to say to him, 'You know it's totally plausible
that these things that she's saying happened, happened,'' Lieberman
said Thursday. ``It's inconceivable to you dad, because you're a
certain kind of man to whom these things are completely
unimaginable. But I know from being a woman in the world that every
man isn't like that...''
</P>
<P>
   The senator voted against Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who works part-time for the New York Board of
Education and lives in Manhattan, does not observe Jewish laws
nearly as rigorously as her father, whose strict observance has
made headlines ever since he joined Al Gore on the Democratic
ticket. But, she said, her father respects her choices.
</P>
<P>
   The respect has, so far at least, extended to the men she dates.
Are they a little bit intimidated when they meet the senior senator
from Connecticut?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a regular guy and he really works hard to make
people feel comfortable and I think the people I've dated have felt
that. And yeah, I think they're also a little bit intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
