<SLUG> BC-LAWYERFUNDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush brings up 1996 DNC allegation in contest of character with
Gore
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON and PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Striving to turn the presidential race back into a contest of
character, Republican George W. Bush expressed outrage that
Democratic officials may have asked for a $100,000 campaign
contribution in 1996 from a Beaumont trial lawyer with the promise
that President Clinton would veto tort reform legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by satellite hook-up to the National Guard Association
of the United States, Bush accused his Democratic presidential
rival, Vice President Al Gore, of being involved in the
solicitation of money from attorney Walter Umphrey. While Gore had
been scheduled to make the fund-raising call, it actually was
placed by then-Democratic National Committee Chairman Don Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just today, there are new revelations about the potential
misuse of the White House for fund-raising purposes, new evidence
that my opponent may have crossed a serious line in solicitation of
campaign contributions linked to a presidential veto,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said questions about the contribution and veto are ``really
disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are tired of investigations and scandal and the best
way to get rid of them is to elect a new president who will bring a
new administration, who will restore honor and dignity to the White
House,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign has been trying to turn the election back to
Gore's character, as the vice president's surge in the polls
suggests renewed voter trust in him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign responded that Gore was not involved in the
fund-raising incident, and that the document that raised the
questions has been available to congressional and justice
department investigators for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is old news,'' said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
``Everyone agrees the vice president did not call Mr. Umphrey. What
this represents, really, is just recycled Republican attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said Bush's comment on the matter Thursday ``sounds like
a desperate candidate, with a desperate campaign using desperate
words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's reverting to the one-play Republican play book,'' Lehane
said. ``Attack, attack, attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported in Thursday editions that the DNC
had tried to use Gore in 1995 to make a fund-raising telephone call
to Umphrey at a time when tort reform legislation was pending in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would have set strict limits in both state and
federal courts on punitive damages _ the money that can be awarded
to injured parties beyond compensation for their actual losses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not talk to Umphrey, but a memo shows Fowler called
Umphrey on Dec. 15, 1995. The call sheet _ something like a script
for the caller _ suggested Fowler tell Umphrey: ``Sorry you missed
the vice president. I know (sic) will give $100K when the president
vetoes tort reform, but we really need it now. Please send ASAP if
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Fowler told the paper he does not recall making any such
statement to Umphrey. Umphrey's lawyer, Michael Tigar, said no
contributions were made in exchange for a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation in question did not pass Congress until March
1996. It was vetoed by Clinton on May 2, 1996, almost five months
after Fowler's call.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported that in the months after Clinton's veto,
Umphrey's firm gave $40,000 to the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before Clinton's veto, business organizations ran
television commercials in key swing states urging Clinton not to
veto the legislation. Democrats accused the business organizations
of serving as fronts for Republican Bob Dole's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The tort reform legislation, opposed by trial lawyers across the
United States, was supported by many business organizations and the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey's firm and four others made about $3.3 billion
representing Texas in its lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey was controversial after the 1990 governor's race when he
put $300,000 into Democrat Ann Richards winning campaign. She later
named him to the Parks and Wildlife Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey this year has put $300,000 in to a state political
committee called the Constitutional Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston Chronicle study in 1999 found Umphrey and the other
tobacco lawyers had poured $5.7 million into Democratic political
funds since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey did not take calls from the Houston Chronicle on
Thursday. A spokesman, who asked not to be named, said Umphrey
never talked to Gore and gave no money in direct connection to
Clinton's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter R.G. Ratcliffe contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
