<SLUG> BC-UZBEKISTAN-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PUTS UZBEK GROUP ON ITS TERROR LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has added the Islamic Movement of
Uzbekistan to its list of foreign terrorist organizations, saying
that the group has ties to the Saudi financier Osama bin Laden,
administration officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision reflects the administration's determination to
isolate groups that it believes sponsor or abet international
terrorism, especially those that American officials identify as
part of a global network sponsored by bin Laden. Last year the
United States placed bin Laden's group al Qaeda on the list,
accusing him and his organization of blowing up two American
Embassies in Africa in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Addition of the Islamic Movement to the list of 28 foreign
groups that Washington now accuses of sponsoring terrorism means
that American citizens and residents are legally barred from
contributing money or ``material support'' to the group. It also
means that Islamic Movement members can be denied visas to, or
deported from, the United States. And it enables the Treasury
Department to seize assets held by the group or its members in
American banks and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Treasury had already asked the
nation's financial institutions to identify any assets that the
Uzbek group or its members control, though they said they doubted
that the group kept or raised money in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the designation sends a signal to other states
that the United States considers the group dangerous, hoping that
they too will try to restrict its activities.
</P>
<P>
   The agency reviews groups every two years, as required by
Congress. This is the first time, said Michael Sheehan, the State
Department's coordinator for counterterrorism, that it has not
waited for that review to add a group.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said adding the Islamic Movement to the terrorist list
was intended to encourage it ``and all organizations to eschew
terrorism as an instrument for their political goals.'' The move,
he said, was not a signal that the United States ``is against
opposition forces to governments around the world, including
Islamic groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're against is their use of terrorism as an
instrument,'' he said, adding that if the group or any other stops
using terrorism, ``we will drop them from the list.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The stated goal of the Islamic Movement, a coalition of several
thousand Islamic militants from Uzbekistan and other Central Asian
states, is to overthrow the secular government in Uzbekistan and
establish a Taliban-style Islamic state there and in other former
Soviet republics of Central Asia, whose population is about 85
percent Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report on terrorism issued this summer, the State
Department called the Islamic Movement terrorist and criticized the
group for its ``anti-Western and anti-Israeli rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   One administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said there had been growing evidence in recent months that bin
Laden had been shifting his focus from the Middle East and North
Africa to Central Asia. Several of its former Soviet republics are
being de-stabilized by a resurgence of militant Islam and a
flourishing regional drug trade. The Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan
has received financial support from bin Laden, American and Uzbek
officials said, as well as from groups and individuals in Pakistan,
Turkey, Saudi Arabia and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Most of its members are said to live in Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan
and Afghanistan. Its recruits have been trained in bin Laden's
Afghan camps as well as in Pakistan, whose weak military government
faces its own militant Islamic pressures. Training has also taken
place in Uzbekistan's conservative Ferghana Valley, where poverty
and high unemployment have given Islamic militants considerable
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Uzbek government holds the Islamic Movement responsible for
instigating five car bombings in Tashkent in February 1999.
Uzbekistan claims that the group was trying to kill President Islam
Karimov, who has banned religious political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Movement claimed responsibility for the fall 1999
kidnapping of four Japanese and eight Kyrgyzstanis. Last month it
also kidnapped several American hikers, but they escaped. Uzbek
officials said that in August, Islamic Movement guerrillas
operating from bases in Tajikistan staged several incursions into a
remote mountainous region on the Kyrgyz-Uzbek border. According to
unconfirmed government reports, at least 30 soldiers from both
countries were killed in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
   Sodiq Safaev, Uzbekistan's ambassador to Washington, called the
administration's decision to add the group to its list of foreign
terrorist groups ``extremely positive.'' ``It shows that these are
not freedom fighters, as they claim,'' he said, ``but skillful,
well-financed, well-trained and well-armed killers.'' Uzbekistan is
very happy, he added, that Washington ``now has a clear stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright pledged $3
million in new military assistance for Uzbekistan and a total of
nearly $10 million to help Central Asian governments fight
terrorism and narcotics trafficking. But she also called upon
governments in the region to establish greater respect for human
rights and civil liberties. The State Department's most recent
rights report calls Uzbekistan an ``authoritarian'' state whose
police officers torture prisoners.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
