<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-MEMORIES0915-CO     09-14 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-MEMORIES0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Learning to live again after Hurricane Floyd
 &HT;    By Bobby Burns
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ New brick and vinyl skins cover most of the
wooden skeletons that lined North Eastern Street after Hurricane
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   People park their cars there every day, go inside, eat dinner
and lay down to rest.
</P>
<P>
   The muddy river that Floyd's rains swelled flows by just a
stone's throw away, oblivious to the homes it stripped and the
lives it altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stays in the back of your mind,'' said Tony Siano, an East
Carolina University student who helped dry out and refurbish the
three bedroom ranch home he owns with his parents. ``I watch the
weather in fear now. I don't want to see another hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd forever changed Siano's little neighborhood, an enclave of
15 cozy homes in Greenville's university district. The waist-high
weeds growing in front of empty shells that remain remind him and
his neighbors that recovery is far from complete. A year after the
storm hit, the people there and all over Pitt County are still
learning how to rebuild their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part was not knowing,'' said Kendall Quinn, who
rooms with Siano at 112 N. Eastern St. ``There was no planning. It
was just, 'here it is, deal with it.' I don't think anybody could
understand unless they live through it.''
</P>
<P>
   ADDING IT UP
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in Pitt County lived through it, officials said.
The flood damaged more than 4,000 homes, offices and other
buildings here. Damage estimates countywide topped $280 million in
agricultural, public and private property losses.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,600 people, business and agencies applied for some
form of state and federal assistance for aid topping $165 million.
Church groups and nonprofit agencies pumped millions more into the
area providing clothes, food and labor. The N.C. Baptist Men
Association has mustered hundreds of volunteers to rebuild 145
houses in Grifton alone.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency shelters housed, fed or helped more than 15,000 flood
victims from Sept. 15, when Floyd hit, to Oct. 10. About 440
families have cycled through camper and mobile home sites set up by
the state to house flood victims since then. About 260 families
remain at those sites.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who remain homeless, living with friends,
relatives, apartments or even hotels is not available. Neither is a
good accounting of how much aid has trickled into the hands of
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of millions of dollars have, but legislative and
bureaucratic holdups on the state and federal level have stranded a
portion the aid, and only about 65 of 575 people enrolled in the
buyout process have received funds.
</P>
<P>
   If the neighborhood on North Eastern Street is a microcosm of
the county at large, flood victims have made their own recovery,
supplementing what aid they received from the government and
charity with their own cash and sweat.
</P>
<P>
   RIDING THE STORM OUT
</P>
<P>
   North Eastern Street was a place where ``you got up, you washed
your dishes, you got out, it you wanted to have lunch, you went,''
said Lillian Jenkins, who lived there 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the flood, retirees like Jenkins populated the
middle-class neighborhood along with young couples, professionals
and college students.
</P>
<P>
   Modest brick and wood homes lined both sides of the lane,
climbing south up the hill from the Tar River to Willow Street.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, whose home was closest to the river, had already left
to stay with her son when Floyd began pummeling Pitt County on
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Siano and Quinn, who lived next door to Jenkins, were enjoying
what they expected to be just another hurricane party.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, Doug Schrade, a general contractor, and his
wife cared for their newborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, the storm had passed. Three doors up from
Schrade, newlyweds Tim and Kelley Matthews picked up sticks and
branches and raked the debris from their yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually went to bed Thursday night,'' said Matthews, a
sales representative. Neighbors pounding on their door woke them up
about midnight and the water was at their property line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got up and just started packing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Matthews and their neighbors followed similar routines.
Photos, computers, clothes, books _ anything small enough with real
or sentimental value _ went up into the attics.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m. Friday the Matthews had done all they could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking it would probably flood, but I thought we'd
have more time,'' he said. ``There was no need to be in a panic,
just pack it up ... It wasn't fun by any means. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the neighbors could do is look out for each other.
Jenkins said Schrade helped ferry her furniture to dry land in his
fishing boat. Schrade said everyone pitched in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met a lot of people during the flood, neighbors who we
didn't normally deal with,'' he said. ``Everybody helped everybody
out. That was one of the nice things that did come out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   THE LONG ROAD HOME
</P>
<P>
   The river continued rising for five days. It crested at 29.74
feet on Sept. 21. Current rolled through nine of the 15 houses on
North Eastern Street.
</P>
<P>
   Another week passed before most of the people who lived there
could return.
</P>
<P>
   The flood drove several thousand people from their homes. Some
of them ended up in shelters, then in campers and trailers provided
by the Federal Emergency Management Agency and the state.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people on North Eastern had taken refuge with family
or friends.
</P>
<P>
   Siano and Quinn evacuated all the way to Raleigh. Jenkins and
her family were in a hotel because her son's home had burned the
month before.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually most of them found apartments and pondered their
options.
</P>
<P>
   All of the flooded homes were within the 100-year floodplain and
eligible for the buyout. However, the buyout takes time, and time
is money.
</P>
<P>
   Tim and Kelley Matthews had little of either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't wait,'' he said. ``We considered it (the buyout)
strongly. We couldn't just up and put a down payment on a house.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple could have tried to secure a low-interest Small
Business Administration loan and paid it off when and if the buyout
came through.
</P>
<P>
   They decided their best option was to use their flood insurance,
a small FEMA grant and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance did not cover all the costs, he said. The policy
devalued furniture and other contents, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The grant helped make a small dent in the difference. ``Then you
just tough it out,'' Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   Schrade and the Siano family faced similar choices. They all
rebuilt. So did Frances Allen, who lives across from the Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Three other homes sit empty, while their owners await the
buyout.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth was purchased recently by a property development
partnership that has purchased more than 20 houses in the area
since the flood.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is repairing the homes and renting them.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins also sold to the group. She was one of the first to make
that choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw what it (the damage) was all about, I just didn't
want to have anything to do with it,'' she said. ``We just decided
to go on and get what we could get for it and get out.''
</P>
<P>
   AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Matthews had just renovated his home prior to the flood. So they
renovated it again.
</P>
<P>
   Siano's parents wanted to keep their house so Tony's younger
brother and sister have a place to live when they attend ECU.
</P>
<P>
   Schrade moved to the top of the hill. He now rents out part of
it and uses part for an office.
</P>
<P>
   They all say the once-flooded homes are in better condition now
than they were before the Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   They hope the open green space created by the buyout will add to
the value of their homes. They are anxious for the government to
complete the process and destroy the empty homes.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of another flood concerns them, but they figure the
risk is acceptable considering the other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do,'' Matthews said. ``We have flood insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins now has a brick patio home in a new development miles
away from the old neighborhood. Large windows allow sunlight to
bath her vaulted living room.
</P>
<P>
   The big, bright room contains little more than the Victorian
couch and chairs rescued by Schrade, her son and grandson.
</P>
<P>
   She had yet to spend the night there as of Tuesday. She couldn't
remember when she started moving in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you the truth, it did something to you,'' she said of
the flood. ``A lot of it I don't even remember. It feels like your
in a daze or something. I don't even know how to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she thinks she will adjust to her new home in time,
even though she thought the one on North Eastern Street would be
her last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be home,'' she said. ``It might be nice.
It might be new. It might be everything. But it's not going to be
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
