<SLUG> BC-GARZA-COMMUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Amid bias, lawyers ask Clinton to give Texan on death row life
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will review a request to spare
the life of Texas killer Juan Raul Garza in light of new Justice
Department data indicating that the federal death-penalty system is
biased against Hispanics and other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But White House spokesman Joe Lockhart Thursday gave no
indication as to whether Clinton would grant Garza clemency or even
when a decision would be made, saying only that the review process
is ``now under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza's lawyers, in an effort to convince Clinton to spare the
killer's life, have seized on Justice Department data showing that
minorities accounted for 80.4 percent of the 682 defendants charged
with federal crimes punishable by death since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the study, released Tuesday, also showed federal prosecutors
sought the death penalty in 38.3 percent of the cases involving a
white defendant compared to only 24.7 percent of cases involving a
black defendant and 20 percent of the cases involving a Hispanic
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fundamentally unjust, unfair and unwarranted to
carry out a death sentence that is a product of a system in which
arbitrary results are produced by long-standing racial bias and
geographic disparity,'' the defense lawyers wrote in a clemency
petition filed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of such profound doubts and uncertainties about
the fundamental fairness of the federal death penalty, Mr. Garza's
application for clemency should be granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense attorneys, Greg Wiercioch of Houston and Bruce
Gilchrist of Washington, are urging Clinton to commute Garza's
death sentence to life in prison without the possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   If his scheduled Dec. 12 execution goes forward, Garza, 43,
would become the first federal prisoner put to death since 1963. A
Brownsville federal jury in 1993 convicted Garza, who was a major
South Texas drug dealer, of killing three associates to further his
illegal business. The Supreme Court refused to hear Garza's appeal
in November 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In the clemency petition, Garza's lawyers cited the Justice
Department's report in deriding the federal criminal process as
``plagued by systemic bias, disparity and arbitrariness.'' The
attorneys argued that the data cry out for further study to examine
the extent of racial bias at all stages of the criminal justice
system from the time a police officer decides to stop a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, who moved more than 7,000 pounds of marijuana through
South Texas from 1982 to 1992, killed Erasmo de la Fuente, whom
Garza blamed for losing a marijuana shipment, and de la Fuente's
associate Gilberto Matos. The year after those 1990 slayings, Garza
killed Thomas Albert Rumbo when he agreed to assist law enforcement
after being caught shipping marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Garza was sentenced to death under the federal 1988 Anti-Drug
Abuse Act, which lets prosecutors seek the death penalty against
``drug kingpins'' who use murder as a stock in trade.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, who sits on death row in Terre Haute, Ind., is one of 19
condemned federal prisoners, including Oklahoma City bomber Timothy
McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
