<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   More video coming to NBA sites
</P>
<P>
   Fanball.com ranks No. 1 in 'stickiness'
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and urls in this column are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   HOOP SCOOP: The NBA will team with Intel to expand video
offerings on its Web sites. When the season begins, fans can expect
highlights packages and some archival footage on the league's
network of sites, NBA commissioner David Stern said. Later, the
venture will sell access to video archives and statistics, though
the league has not determined how fans will be charged. The
ultimate goal is to let fans create game feeds from multiple camera
locations.
</P>
<P>
   www.nba.com
</P>
<P>
   STICKY SITE: The fantasy sport site Fanball.com ranked as the
No. 1 ``stickiest'' sports site in PC Data Online's August report.
Stickiness refers to the amount of time a visitor spends using a
particular site. From Aug. 1-31, the average visitor spent more
than three hours, 10 minutes at the site. It attracted more than
185 million page views, second for sports sites behind ESPN.com,
and had more than 530,000 users. For more fantasy news and links,
see Fantasy Land below.
</P>
