<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ADVANCE15-COX     09-14 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ADVANCE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ They're back, four years and nearly 10,000 miles
removed from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Olympics begin anew this weekend in Australia _
bigger than ever, maybe better, with the usual mix of familiar
stars and fresh ones, plus a certain medals spike for the host
nation.
</P>
<P>
   After tonight's Opening Ceremonies, the spotlight swings
Saturday toward the athletes, and a wider one it is. Some 10,200 of
them from 199 countries partake in a 31-sport schedule so jammed
that it had to begin two days before the Games' official start.
</P>
<P>
   The first medals will be presented Saturday to women in the new
Olympic sport of triathlon, which consists here of running, cycling
and eluding sharks in the occasionally infested harbor waters; no
feedings are anticipated. Aussies are projected for gold, perhaps
silver as well, which would whoosh them to the top of the medals
tables and send their rabid mates into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   They will not wind up as the host with the most. Still, the
Aussies expect to increase a 41-medal take in Atlanta by about 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds here will be worth 12 to 15 medals alone,'' U.S.
Olympic Committee spokesman Mike Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. knows well the Olympic home-field, -court, water bonus.
In 1996, the U.S. team won 44 gold, 18 more than runner-up Russia,
and 101 in all, 36 better than second-fiddle Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The medals gap probably will narrow but not enough for the U.S.
to relinquish global superiority. Australian officials say, not too
loudly, that fourth place would be fine behind the superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the U.S., Moran said, ``Our hopes would be to do in the
neighborhood of what we did in Atlanta. Everyone would be thrilled
if we could do in the 100-medals range, but the question is, 'Can
anybody win 100 anymore?' ``
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Year of the Woman, a label informally attached to
Atlanta, has taken on a more formal ring here. It can only aid the
U.S. records show that the Americans strike quickly in first-time
female sports. The Sydney debutantes include water polo, taekwondo
and weightlifting, with strongwoman Cheryl Haworth of Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Medal threats from Georgia abound. The ripest of the Peach State
athletes are in track and field (hurdlers Gail Devers and Angelo
Taylor, shot putter Adam Nelson), basketball (Shareef Abdul-Rahim
and Teresa Edwards), shooting (Thomas Tamas and Cindy Gentry) and
canoe-kayak (Scott Shipley).
</P>
<P>
   The potentially transcendant performer is track-and-field terror
Marion Jones, who has been bumping world leaders off magazine
covers. She eyes gold in five events _ two individual sprints, two
relays and the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
