<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIR-DELAYS15-COX     09-14 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-DELAYS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials vow to improve air travel
 &HT;    By Melanie Eversley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For those who have dealt with the crowds, delays
and hassles that air travel has become, relief may be on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials and airline executives told a Senate panel on
Thursday that that they are trying to ease the travel trauma at the
nation's airports.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Mullin, president of Delta Air Lines, told the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee that his company,
whose hub is in Atlanta, is trying to ease the load by adding
regional flights to smaller communities.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater told Sen. Max Cleland
(D-Ga.) and other panel members that he has directed his agency to
explore the problem and come up with answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if the Wright brothers could put man into flight ...
we can deal with the ground-level and even the air-level challenges
that we face to insure improved services to the American people,''
Slater said.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said that among his initiatives is a task force that will
probe the nature of traffic delays and come up with plan to deal
with them within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic comments came amid a three-hour hearing that
overall was not so upbeat. Figures flew back and forth describing
how America's skies have become clogged with traffic, causing
passengers to arrive at family holidays exhausted and frazzled,
miss business meetings or spend whole days or nights waiting in
noisy airport terminals.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1999, flight delays increased 58 percent, according
to the Federal Aviation Administration. Cancellations grew even
more, by 68 percent, in the same time period, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cleland, the air traffic glut has become critical,
and because of that, he offerred an invitation Thursday to Slater
to come to Hartsfield International Airport, the world's busiest
air terminal, after the November general election to discuss
speeding up plans to build a fifth runway by 2005. The new runway
would cut back the ever-growing average flight delay time at
Hartsfield from a projected 14 minutes in 2005 down to five
minutes, Cleland said. Slater has not yet responded to the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need that runway tomorrow,'' Cleland said after the
hearing. ``We need the secretary to help expedite things.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussions come at a time when air travel has become
commonplace. Commuter marriages are not unusual and many
businesses, having the means to travel inexpensively, choose to
conduct business with far-off clients face-to-face rather than over
the phone. Today, a trip through the airport is for some as
everyday, and as harried, as a ride on the subway at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin said Delta will try to help relieve the problem with
regional jet service to small- and medium-sized communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increased capacity is the only solution if we are to meet
consumer demand and at the same time return reliability,
convenience and comfort to air travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials were not quite on the same page. Slater said
his initiatives include:
</P>
<P>
   An Airline Quality Service Performance task force that will
draft a report over the next few months on the best way to measure
airline performance.
</P>
<P>
   A report to be completed by Assistant Transportation Secretary
Francisco Sanchez on best practices in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspector general at the Department of Transportation
said federal officials should first figure out how many arrivals
and departures the nation's top 30 airports can accommodate without
delays or risks to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general, Kenneth Mead, said air carriers have
added additional flights to balance out the growing number of
delays and cancellations, but that airports increasingly cannot
handle the growing load. This is why a system of that sets out
``capacity benchmarks'' should be instituted, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without it, our ability to understand the impact on flight
volume on flight delays and cancellations and, in turn, to make
informed decisions, is severely constrained,'' Mead told the
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administrator Jane Garvey, also at the hearing,
said her agency was working toward creating such benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said he strongly supports the idea, and he spent part of
the hearing trying to convince Mullin and Donald Carty, president
of American Airlines, that they should support it also.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of realistic information is what the public would
like to have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, however, said that such benchmarks are not necessary.
Preliminary discussions are under way to build yet a sixth runway
at Hartsfield, he said. And this year, he added, the airlines and
passengers have gotten through the summer - what he called ``the
mean season.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the benchmark system, he said, ``I think it should only be
put forward on a true emergency basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
