<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-HALL0915-COX     09-14 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HALL0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hall a bit mellower, but stays feisty
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY_ Gary Hall Jr. didn't even have to get in the water here
to find himself embroiled in a controversy. Australian star Kieren
Perkins bristled over Hall's quote about the Australia swimmers:
``We'll smash them like guitars.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. men's coach, Mark Schubert, was somewhat taken
aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very ambitious quote,'' Schubert said. ``Of all of
our swimmers he's certainly the showman.''
</P>
<P>
   Same old Gary? For years, Hall has been known in swim circles as
much for his antics and his rebel attitude as his still unfulfilled
talent. Yet others have noticed a change of late.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Walker edged Hall in the 100-meter freestyle in Hall's
comeback at the U.S. swimming trials in Indianapolis in August, and
Hall beat Walker and everyone else in the 50 freestyle when he
broke a 10-year-old record. Walker sees a new Hall, one who has
matured since he was diagnosed with diabetes last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learned from that. He's bettered himself, and he's on a
roll,'' Walker said. ``He's better than the old Gary. He still has
the spirit and the confidence, but he's grown. I compare him to
Lance Armstrong. Lance had to deal with cancer. He conquered that
and then became a better rider. Gary has had to deal with diabetes.
At the trials I think he was probably one of the most scared people
out there. Now, his physique is good. His confidence level is up.
Now, I think he'll do some amazing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 25, is the son of three-time Olympian Gary Hall. To
understand the genetic potential the 6-foot-6-inch Hall had as a
young swimmer, you can go back to the brief time he was a Texas
Longhorn. Hall swam as a freshman at UT in 1994 and first debated
about transferring closer to his family's Phoenix home before
opting instead to turn professional and point for the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was leaving Texas Coach Eddie Reese's program,
Reese, who is an assistant coach for the 2000 U.S. men's swim team,
had this to say about him: ``He will be a record breaker, a barrier
breaker. . . . He's the greatest freestyler we've ever had. And
`we' is the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall made it to the Atlanta Olympics as the American hope
against Russian sprint star Alexander Popov. Hall played the part
of a young gun to the hilt. He strode around in leather motorcycle
pants. He did some furious shadow boxing. Popov just stared him
down. The Russian seemed supremely confident that he would beat the
talented Hall because he trained harder.
</P>
<P>
   Popov took gold in the 50 and 100 freestyles. Hall settled for
silver. Things went downhill from there. In 1998 Hall was hit with
a three-month suspension for testing positive for marijuana. Then
came the real shocker.
</P>
<P>
   In his diary on the CNN/SI Web site Hall wrote, ``My eyesight
was becoming blurry and I experienced excessive fatigue and
dizziness. It wasn't until I collapsed one day that I was diagnosed
with diabetes.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Hall reacted the way many of us would _ badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hopeless void filled my insides and all I could do was sit
in disbelief,'' he wrote. He was ``depressed, dumbfounded,
horrified.''
</P>
<P>
   And angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to lash at the doctor with my teeth,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   He lost interest in training. He packed up and headed for Costa
Rica and the beach. According to his account, he went swimming in
shark-infested waters, hoping for the worst, and actually felt
sharks brush him on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But he regrouped. While in Costa Rica he started reading about
diabetes. He now knows quite a bit about it and writes about it on
his Web site, much the way Austin's Armstrong has done with cancer.
Others with the condition read his Web site and are inspired, with
good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he now has to take insulin as often as eight times a
day, Hall has achieved some remarkable feats. In his ``prime,'' he
could never break 22 seconds for the 50 freestyle. At the U.S.
trials he accomplished that three times and broke Tom Jager's
decade-old record of 21.81 seconds with a time of 21.76. He entered
that meet worried whether he had enough to swim 100 meters and had
qualified only with a slow 51.13 at the Janet Evans Invitational.
Yet he gave Walker a real run and finished second in 48.84 seconds
to make the team in the 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my hope that I've been able to show the world a person
living with diabetes is capable of achieving anything they set out
to do,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was even extremely kind to the rival Australians, praising
their swimming system and wishing them well before observing,
``Good humor and genuine kindness seem a predominant
characteristic. My biased opinion says that we will smash them like
guitars.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the old Gary's not gone. He also has lashed out at the
stodgy way swimming is run in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm an extremist,'' he recently explained to
reporters. ``I'm not extremely left, I'm just left of center and
most of the swimming establishment is so far right, I seem very far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also criticized Speedo, which dropped him after his
marijuana problems. Without specifically naming the company, he has
taken shots at them for taking credit for records that might have
well fallen in an Olympic year no matter what the swimmers were
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's return closed a few spots that would have been open for
other swimmers, but even those he beat seemed to be glad he's on
the U.S. team, which will need all of his talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel proud to be on an Olympic team with him,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
