<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-14 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BEHIND DEBATE REVERSAL, A SHORTAGE OF OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-GORE-DEBATE) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ What Gov. George W. Bush did on Thursday was an
extraordinary turnabout. After weeks of objections to the debate
schedule that the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates had
been proposing, he suddenly agreed to all of it: three encounters
with Vice President Al Gore, on the dates that the commission
proposed, in the locations that the commission specified.
</P>
<P>
   He even agreed to Boston, which his advisers had dismissed as a
Democratic stronghold that stacked the deck against their
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Bush's representatives sat down with the debate
commission's officials on Thursday, they really had no other
choice. They had to cut their losses and stop the regular pounding
that Bush had been taking in the news media for what looked like a
nervousness about formal debates.
</P>
<P>
   And they had to move on, because an ongoing debate over debates
threatened to be yet another distraction for a campaign bedeviled
by too many of them. They knew that for Bush to communicate his
chosen message to voters, he had to put an end to the extraneous
story lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign recognizes that it has to get back on offense,
back on its own agenda, and out of the muck,'' said one prominent
Republican strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's agreement spoke volumes about the change in the Bush
campaign's fortunes over the last several weeks. Before, Bush
enjoyed a considerable advantage over Gore in the polls, and for a
frontrunner, debates always represent more of a risk than an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush now seems to be trailing by a few percentage points,
and for an underdog, debates hold the promise of mixing up the the
dynamic, changing the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush needs debates,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster,
``because with debates, you can shake up the political
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Debates also represent one of the rare times when a candidate
can speak directly to an enormous number of voters, without having
to rely on the conduit of journalists, and for Bush, that is more
attractive than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The last several weeks have demonstrated to him and his advisers
just how unpredictable the 24-hour news cycle is and how quickly
reporters can latch onto a mistake or a surprise that has nothing
to do with what a candidate is peddling, and yank him off course.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened to Bush again and again, and those mishaps
coupled with the realignment of the candidates in the polls,
changed the narratives associated with Bush and Gore. All at once,
it was Bush who could not gain his footing, and Gore who loped with
an unbroken stride.
</P>
<P>
   For the 90 minutes of a debate, however, there is no commentary,
no interpretation: just the candidates saying what they choose and,
if they don't stumble, what they want the voters to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bush's chance to get his message out unfiltered,
uncensored, unedited,'' Luntz said. ``And that's exactly what he
wants. And that's exactly what will get his campaign back on
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had wanted debates that were less formal, and shorter. His
aides had proposed having only one 90-minute commission debate, and
two 60-minute ones on television news programs. The news program
debates would not have been carried by all the major networks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's communications director, Karen P. Hughes, insisted on
Thursday that he might still get his wish for a more spontaneous
exchange between the candidates. As the candidate played
hard-to-get, she said, the debate commission grew agreeable to
talking about creative, spontaneous formats for the debates.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign has not received any firm agreement along
those lines.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush and his advisers appear to be taking something of a
gamble, worth it to them now because the holdout had not worked to
their advantage, any further holdout may bring only them more
grief, and they need to move the focus of the campaign to ground
where they can put Gore on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of weeks have not been pleasant, and I think
there was a desire not to allow this cloud to linger any longer,''
said Scott Reed, who managed Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush campaign adviser said that while events had clearly been
moving toward an agreement on debates, Thursday's deal may well
have been sealed by the emergence of newly critical appraisals of
Gore's fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   At last, the Republican official said, Gore was on the hot seat.
And Bush's advisers knew that if they did not reach an agreement on
debates on Thursday, they might help Gore out of that uncomfortable
spot by keeping Bush in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision was locked in by the fact that Bush finally got
some traction, after weeks of no traction,'' the official said.
``They don't want to take that away.''
</P>
<P>
   And with less than two months to go before Election Day, they
may not be able to afford to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
