A5804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM15-COX     09-14 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swimmers ready to take on world
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ During training camp up the coast in Brisbane, the U.S.
swimmers enjoyed seeing their sport get the type of media coverage
that's reserved for football, baseball and basketball in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always saying that Australia is swimming heaven,''
sprinter Jenny Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian team, however, wants to make them.The Aussies
will try to wrest swimming dominance away from the Yanks, who won
26 medals in Atlanta four years ago compared to 11 for Australia.
Last year, the United States narrowly prevailed at the Pan Pac meet
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. women's coach Richard Quick and men's coach Mark Schubert
have stressed that this isn't a dual meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to race the world,'' Schubert said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brooke Bennett, the defending champion in the 800
meters, is the only U.S. woman to top the world rankings this year.
The U.S. men's team features three world-record holders: Lenny
Krayzelburg (100 and 200 back), Tom Dolan (400 IM) and Tom Malchow
(200 fly).
</P>
<P>
   Mark Spitz, who won seven gold medals in 1972, has predicted
that the U.S. women will not win any golds.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper it looks that way,'' said Thompson, who has five
golds and a silver yet is still seeking her first individual gold.
``But I think we're all swimming really well in our preparation,
and I think we'll have some amazing swims.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``You have to actually swim the meet, so that's why
we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team arrived in Sydney on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all kind of itching to get this meet on and
start racing, and that's the fun part,'' said Dolan, who is the
defending Olympic champion in the 400-meter individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team features veterans, including 33-year-old Dara
Torres, the first American swimmer to appear in four Olympic Games,
and rookies such as 15-year-old Michael Phelps, the youngest U.S.
male to make the team in 68 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youth of the team has revived the team a little bit and
lightened up the atmosphere,'' said Malchow, who won a silver in
'96. ``I don't think they know to be scared of this meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgians with the best medal chances are Kristy Kowal in
the 200-meter breaststroke and Courtney Shealy, who will swim a leg
on the 400-meter freestyle relay as well as the 100 backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic trials last month, the U.S. team set several
American records but shattered no world marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt from the performances we saw at the training
camp that our team is better than it was at the trials,'' Schubert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
