<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WINGING IT IN BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Lazio, the New York Senate Republican nominee, was supposed
to be the likable candidate. Then this week, at a debate in
Buffalo, the congressman morphed into a political predator. Darth
Vader with dimples. A suburban Stone Cold Steve Austin. The Long
Island Lex Luthor. Richard Hatch with clothes on.
</P>
<P>
   We're getting carried away. As did Lazio. He called Hillary
Rodham Clinton ``shameless,'' and invaded her space, stalking
across the stage waving a campaign finance pledge. When a question
about her husband's affair with Monica Lewinsky left her looking as
if she'd had the wind knocked out of her, Lazio eagerly piled on
with a verbal kidney punch.
</P>
<P>
   Now this is a guy who's supposed to be romancing the suburban
women voters. People, how many times do we have to point out that
women do not like men who yell? This is the cardinal law of modern
American politics, not to mention modern American life. Why do you
think the Republicans nominated George W. Bush? Why is Al Gore
spending so much time hanging around Joe Lieberman? It's because
they are non-yell guys. (Dick Cheney does not generally raise his
voice, but he always looks as if he wants to.)
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has got to know all this. But perhaps he feels he's so
puppylike, no one will notice he's been gnawing away on Clinton's
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The debate began really well for the congressman, whose mission
was to show that he had some gravitas. He seemed aggressive, but
not, you know, crazed. Clinton was so much on the defense that at
one point she resorted to saying that Lazio had ``chutzpah,'' a
word that Midwestern Methodists should really try to avoid. She
kept monotonously invoking Newt Gingrich. If the Clinton campaign
were into subliminal advertising, all the footage of Lazio would be
interrupted by pictures of a small salamander.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio turns out to be one of those politicians with no
thermostat. Having started hot, he just got louder and louder. By
the end, he had charged over to Clinton's lectern and thrust a
no-soft-money pledge under her nose, demanding ``Sign it! Right
now!''
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic point in the debate came when the moderator,
Tim Russert, replayed Clinton's ``Today'' show interview in 1998,
the one where she assured the nation that her husband had not had
sex with that woman. Russert asked if she regretted ``misleading
the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   All of us have moments in our lives that we prefer not to recall
even while cowering in a darkened closet. Clinton's just happens to
be stored in the files of every news bureau on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Russert's tape, she looked as if she had been
sideswiped by a truck. This is a woman who delivers off-the-cuff
remarks in long sentences filled with perfectly conjugated
dependent clauses, none of them dangling. Her answer to Russert's
question, however, contained 23 ``um's'' along with several ``you
know's.'' The gist of it was that she had trusted her husband, who
lied to her and then let her hang herself, on camera, during
morning drive time.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was invited to respond, giving him an excellent
opportunity to say something like ``Tim, let's go back to that
great point I made about health care a few minutes ago.'' Instead
he piled right on, accusing Clinton of ``blaming others every time
you have a responsibility.'' (When it comes to finding a scapegoat
for anything relating to the Lewinsky episode, the president seems
like a really excellent choice.)
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign has bought into the Clinton theory that
Hillary wins if the race becomes about issues. But the congressman
was actually doing fine when he was attacking her record on health
care and education reform in Arkansas. The truth is that Clinton
wins if the race is about her marriage, and loses if we wind up
arguing about the success of the Little Rock school system.
</P>
<P>
   But New York is a land of many great traditions, one of which is
that our big Senate races should be very, very fierce battles that
wind up focusing with laserlike intensity on something utterly
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the town meeting but, you know, we make do with what we
have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
