<SLUG> BC-FILM-FAMOUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALMOST FAMOUS' IS ROCK SOLID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming as it does on the heels of the most intensely raunchy and
witless summer in Hollywood history _ a season Variety editor Peter
Bart feared might ``kill the art of movie comedy forever'' _ the
timing of Cameron Crowe's ``Almost Famous'' could hardly be better.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only the most gentle and effortlessly funny movie so
far this year, it's a film with a style and sensibility that
wonderfully harkens back to Hollywood's golden age of sophisticated
comedy, and in particular to the masterpieces of Crowe's filmmaking
idol, Billy Wilder.
</P>
<P>
   Without a major star in its cast, it may not prove to be as big
a hit as Crowe's 1996 ``Jerry Maguire,'' but it's every bit as good
a movie. If there's any justice in the world, it should earn the
Seattle-based director a third Oscar nomination, and establish him
as the industry's comedy filmmaker to beat.
</P>
<P>
   The film (which, until within weeks of its completion, was
called ``The Untitled Cameron Crowe Project'') is his
autobiographical, coming-of-age memoir, playing off his legend as a
rock journalist in the early '70s, when he was Rolling Stone's
youngest staff writer and editor.
</P>
<P>
   His surrogate character is William Miller (Patrick Fugit), an
awkward, withdrawn, 15-year-old San Diego rock fan who, in 1973, is
inspired to become a music journalist after meeting with pioneering
rock critic Lester Bangs (Philip Seymour Hoffman).
</P>
<P>
   One day after school, he gets a phone call from Rolling Stone
editor Ben Fong-Torres, who's impressed by Miller's unsolicited
submissions, assumes he's an adult and hires him sight unseen to
cover rising rock band Stillwater on its ``Almost Famous'' tour of
America.
</P>
<P>
   From this setup, the movie follows Miller's inside point of view
through the circus of a '70s rock tour, with its glamour, groupies
and ego clashes, all the time with him trying to dodge the endless,
cautionary phone calls from his mother (Frances McDormand) and to
disguise the fact that he's a kid.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the movie segues into an offbeat love triangle
involving the boy journalist, a beautiful 16-year-old groupie (or
``band-aid,'' as she calls herself) named Penny Lane (Kate Hudson)
and Stillwater's charismatic, self-destructive guitarist, Russell
Hammond (Billy Crudup) _ all of whom learn a valuable lesson in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially what the movie is ``about,'' but the
description doesn't really give any indication of the pleasure it
engenders: the ingratiating charm of the characters, the delicacy
and spice of the dialogue, or the warmth, wit and honesty that
manages to shine through in every scene.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's study of Billy Wilder that culminated in his landmark
1999 book, ``Conversations With Wilder,'' constantly displays
itself not just in small tributes to individual Wilder films, but
in its distinctly Wilderesque staging and compositions. With its
high-polish scenes and unpretentious camera work, it looks and
feels like a classic comedy from the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Also, like the best of Wilder, there's a perfection to the
casting and subtlety in the performances that's rare in modern
comedy. Hudson, who lights up the world with her smile, and Crudup,
who took the rock-star part after Brad Pitt unwisely stepped out at
the last minute, are so magnetic they should both ride their parts
to bona fide stardom.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected from a personal memoir by a major rock
journalist, Crowe's film is also a valentine to the music of his
formative years, and his numerous musical collaborators (including
musical supervisor Danny Bramson, and rock artists Nancy Wilson and
Peter Frampton) have done an extraordinary job of evoking the era
with a musical environment that uses pieces from 50 classic (and a
few new) songs.
</P>
<P>
   In his interviews, Crowe has strongly maintained that he did not
set out to make a genre ``nostalgia'' movie, but _ like it or not _
``Almost Famous'' is a '70s nostalgia movie par excellence. It is
the most good-natured and visually epic of all the many recent
movie bows to that more innocent and optimistic time when
mainstream rock was a coalescing force that bound a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ALMOST FAMOUS
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Cameron Crowe
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Billy Crudup, Kate Hudson, Patrick Fugit, Frances
McDormand, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Anna Paquin
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 120 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: R, for drug and sexual references
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
