<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday Sept. 15, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-FAA (Seattle) _ It will take at least three years to
design, manufacture and thoroughly test a new 737 rudder control
mechanism before it is ready to go into the first airplane, the
Boeing Co. said. And it could be 2008 before the entire U.S. fleet
of some 1,500 737s can be hauled into maintenance facilities and
retrofitted, the Federal Aviation Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DUETS (Undated) _ Since Gwyneth Paltrow is the hottest
actress in Hollywood and her father, Bruce, is far from an A-list
director, their teaming in the low-budget drama, ``Duets,'' has an
air of nepotistic charity about it that has generated mostly
negative advance buzz. Actually, the movie is not all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FAMOUS (Undated) _ Cameron Crowe's ``Almost Famous'' could
hardly be better. It's not only the most gentle and effortlessly
funny movie so far this year, it's a film with a style and
sensibility that wonderfully harkens back to Hollywood's golden age
of sophisticated comedy. Without a major star in its cast, it may
not prove to be as big a hit as Crowe's 1996 ``Jerry Maguire,'' but
it's every bit as good.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
