<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-DEBATES-ART     09-14 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-DEBATES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, LAZIO CAMPS CONTINUE DEBATE DIALOGUE OVER SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Let's just get this deal done right now,'' Rep.
Rick Lazio told Hillary Rodham Clinton at their debate on Wednesday
night, trying unsuccessfully to persuade her to sign a pledge
barring the use of so-called soft money in their Senate race. With
a stroke of the pen, Lazio declared, the two could alter the
landscape of modern-day politicking.
</P>
<P>
   But as with other issues debated, like health care, the
thrusting and parrying over soft money obscured a more complicated
reality. To begin with, while Clinton and Lazio insist that they
favor a ban on soft money in their contest and have issued
proposals to to adopt one, they cannot even agree on what soft
money is.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides presumably realize that an informal ban with no legal
force, drawn up by the very political consultants who have mastered
the art of injecting soft money into elections, would be difficult
to police.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be enough for the two candidates to forswear
raising soft money in the New York race: They would have to
persuade dozens of other politicians to do so as well, from state
party leaders to senators in Washington. Not to mention other
political groups, some of which are secretive about their
activities.
</P>
<P>
   So the calls for a ban are seen by some experts as a tactic
meant to paint the opposition as corrupt. ``I've seen a lot of
these pledges, and they are about political advantage, not about
results,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, an
advocacy group that lobbies for tighter campaign finance
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Wertheimer said the only way to rid the campaign finance system
of soft money would be to approve legislation pending in
Washington, which both candidates favor.
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns continued their maneuvering Thursday, with
officials holding news conferences and issuing statements to
declare that their standard-bearer was the real reformer. But there
seemed no movement toward a deal.
</P>
<P>
   To many advocacy groups unhappy with the campaign finance
system, soft money is a major culprit because it essentially allows
politicians to circumvent the donation limits for federal races:
$1,000 for a primary and $1,000 for a general election.
</P>
<P>
   Political parties can raise soft money in unlimited amounts from
anyone, including unions and corporations. The parties can legally
spend it only on so-called party-building activities, like voter
drives, not on items that help candidates' campaigns. But the
parties have sidestepped the restriction by using soft money to buy
commercials that promote or criticize candidates without directly
mentioning the elections.
</P>
<P>
   In alliance with Democratic leaders, Clinton has raised several
million dollars in soft money _ it is hard to pin down amounts
because the donations are channeled through different committees _
in addition to the nearly $22 million in so-called hard dollars she
has collected for her official campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has taken in $19.2 million for his campaign committee, and
has so far not collected soft money, but he has benefited from
spending by Republican committees and outside groups independent of
the political parties, like the Republican Leadership Council,
which backs moderate Republicans. Technically, this outside
spending is not soft money because it is not done by parties, but
it is effectively the same.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has repeatedly called on Clinton to forgo the use of soft
money. She has responded that she would if Lazio could persuade the
outside groups to stay out of the race. The Clinton campaign says
it considers outside spending in its definition of soft money. The
Lazio campaign has usually referred to soft money as that spent
only by parties.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lazio's campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, wrote to his
counterpart on the Clinton campaign, Bill de Blasio, that if
Clinton agreed to a ban, Lazio would send letters to these outside
groups asking that they ``immediately cease and desist from any
political activities designed in any way to influence the outcome
of this election.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many of these groups would oblige.
</P>
<P>
   De Blasio responded with a letter in which he called on the
Lazio campaign first to obtain signed pledges from 14 groups that
the Clinton campaign believes are trying to defeat Clinton,
including the American Conservative Union and the Conservative
Leadership Political Action Committee.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, the candidates also tangled repeatedly over
health care, often relying on the same technique they employ in
their commercials: taking the other side's votes or positions and
casting them in the worst possible light.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio charged that Clinton had done nothing to stop her husband
from vetoing money for New York's hospitals, and Clinton said that
Lazio had backed Newt Gingrich's plan to cut $270 billion from
Medicare, the health program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was referring to billions of dollars in financing for
Medicaid, the health program for the poor, which the president
removed from the federal budget in 1997 using his line-item veto
power. Lazio did not mention that the Clinton administration later
tried to return most of the money, and that all the money was
restored after the Supreme Court overturned the president's
line-item veto power.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in describing the Medicare proposal, repeated a
frequent Democratic contention: that the Republicans wanted to
sharply reduce financing. In fact, the Republican plan would have
reduced the projected rate of growth of Medicare by $270 billion,
not cut existing allocations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also suggested that Lazio has opposed efforts in
Congress to approve a patients' bill of rights that would give
people more authority to sue their health maintenance
organizations. She did not note that Lazio favored an HMO bill
presented by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
