<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WAGES-ART-$ADV17-     09-14 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WAGES-ART-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INCOME GAP, ON A NEW MAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite all the talk about prosperity in this Digital Age, tax
return data indicates that the rising tide of bits and bytes is
lifting the yachts much more than the rowboats.
</P>
<P>
   From 1986 through 1997, the latest year for which detailed
figures are available from the IRS, the average income of the
richest 1 percent of Americans soared 89 percent, to $517,713 from
$273,562.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are after federal income taxes have been paid, and
are given in constant 1997 dollars to eliminate the effects of
inflation. To be counted among the top 1 percent in 1997 required
an after-tax income of $268,889, suggesting a pre-tax income of
about $440,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the incomes of those at the top did not rise steadily over
the 12 years. The average declined from 1989 to 1991 because of a
mild recession. And it dropped again in 1993, but that is probably
a fluke, attributable to significant numbers of wealthy people who
had cashed in deferred bonuses and the like in anticipation of an
increase in the top income tax rate to 39.6 percent, a rate paid
only by the top 1 percent of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   During those same 12 years, the bottom 90 percent of Americans,
meaning everyone who took home $79,598 or less after federal income
taxes, did not fare nearly as well.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the average income for the bottom 90 percent was
$23,815, up a scant $364, or 1.6 percent, from 1986. This average
also fluctuated during the 12 years, but the changes up or down
were smaller than 2 percent in 11 of those years. The fluctuations
were so tiny that in the chart accompanying this article they
disappear, and the line appears flat.
</P>
<P>
   These figures were computed from an IRS statistics-of-income
report by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a nonprofit
Washington group that advocates policies that it says will benefit
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an interesting fact that was not in the center's report:
From 1996 to 1997, the increase in average income for the top 1
percent _ a gain of $69,009 _ was nearly triple the total average
income of the bottom 90 percent. That the increase at the top alone
would dwarf the total average income for the bottom 90 percent
illustrates the sharp divergence between the fortunes of the
economic elite and the rest of America.
</P>
<P>
   Over nine years of economic expansion, the question of whether
the fruits of the boom are being distributed fairly has become a
central one in American politics. Competing policy proposals from
Democrats and Republicans on issues ranging from taxation to health
care to retirement savings are often based on fundamentally
different interpretations of the available data, and the quality
and reliability of the data itself is often hotly disputed by
advocates in each camp.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to measure income, none of them perfect. Tax
return data like that studied by the center has the advantage of
coming from documents that all taxpayers sign under penalty of
perjury, and of being subject to comparison with W-2 and 1099-form
reports from third parties listing payments of wages, dividends,
interest and royalties. Rent and capital-gain income, which goes
mostly to the affluent, depends on self-reporting by those
receiving the income.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Wolff, a New York University economist who studies the
wealthy, said tax return data gives a reliable picture of those
with the highest incomes. But for the bottom 90, percent, he said,
``the figures are biased downward'' because a substantial amount of
Social Security and other income is not picked up on tax returns.
Another kind of income, from tax-free bonds and the like, is also
omitted from tax returns, but that type of income goes almost
entirely to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Another widely used measure of income, the Census Bureau survey
data on median household income, also shows little change in
overall income from 1986 to 1997. Adjusted for inflation, the
median income rose just 1.5 percent during those years, to $37,005
in 1997 dollars. Unlike the tax data, the Census Bureau's survey
figures tend to understate incomes at the high end, because of the
methodology used to record large incomes. For example, the bureau
puts a cap on all income components, no matter how large, and for
example caps salaries at $999,999 as $999,999 for survey purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Those who report the greatest share of the nation's income also
pay the greatest share of income taxes. In 1997, the IRS data
shows, those with incomes of $100,000 or more, about 5.9 percent of
all taxpayers, made 34.5 percent of all the money and paid 53.7
percent of the income taxes collected that year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
