<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FIRESTONE0915-COX     09-14 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allied Holdings blames tire recall for downturn
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Allied Holdings' third-quarter loss will be more than
double analysts' earlier estimates because of fallout from
Firestone's tire recall, the Decatur, Ga.,-based car hauler warned
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus estimate was for a $2 million loss, or 24 cents a
share, for the quarter ending Sept. 30, according to First Call and
Nelson Information/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   But Allied Holdings said it expects to report a loss for the
quarter of 50 to 60 cents a share, or about $4 million to $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Holdings said it has transported 39,000 fewer Ford
sport-utility vehicles and light trucks than expected because of
Ford's decision to shut down three plants to make more tires
available during the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Allied transports vehicles from all three of the plants in St.
Paul, Minn., St. Louis and Edison, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The hauler gets about $95 for each vehicle it transports from
plants to dealers, said Kevin Feeney, an Allied Holdings vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The company said revenue also will be lower than expected
because of extended plant shutdowns by other automakers. Allied
Holdings' shares closed Thursday at $5.88, up 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone recalled about 6.5 million tires on Aug. 9 after
receiving complaints of blowouts and peeling treads involving its
15-inch Firestone ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT tires. The tires
were installed on Ford's Explorer SUVs, light trucks and other
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has received
more than 1,400 complaints about Firestone tires, including reports
of 88 deaths. The agency also issued a safety warning on up to two
dozen other Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recall's impact on the third quarter, Allied
Holdings expects to meet analysts' earnings estimates of 77 cents a
share for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Holdings Chief Executive A. Mitchell Poole Jr. said he is
``confident that our strategic initiatives and corporate
realignment have positioned the company to achieve the positive
earnings we expect in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's projections are based on Ford resuming production
at the three plants by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ford plans to decide this weekend whether to extend the closing
of the three plants. The closing freed up about 100,000 tires for
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
