<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-CHUCK-SMITH15-COX     09-14 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHUCK-SMITH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A moment with Chuck Smith
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolina defensive end Chuck Smith called the other day to talk
about the Falcons, past and present. He spewed minimal venom.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he spent most of a 15-minute teleconference laughing,
rhapsodizing about former teammates and philosophizing about
Atlanta left tackle Bob Whitfield, his dear friend.
</P>
<P>
   The two men stood in each other's weddings earlier this year.
Sunday in Ericsson Stadium, they might stand in each other's way.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield, the only player Atlanta selected before Smith in the
1992 draft, started Thursday's odd exchange when he talked about
Smith, whose 58 1/2 sacks (1992-99) are second in franchise history
to the 62 1/2 of Claude Humphrey (1968-74, 1976-78).
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck's probably putting chicken bones in a bag, shakin' em
all up, and putting a voodoo curse on me,'' Whitfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith cackled loudly in reply. His trademark sound was heard
rarely in Atlanta last season, when he battled a sprained right big
toe and right knee, boomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That boy is sick,'' he said. ``I'm worried about Bob. He'll
take a personal foul just to rattle you. I taught him that; I got
to watch out for it. He's my dog, and we're going to go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Smith's right knee and Carolina coach George Seifert will
decide whether the old dogs go at it Sunday when the Falcons (1-1)
play at Carolina (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   That knee played a role in the Falcons' decision not to bring
Smith back once he became an unrestricted free agent in February.
</P>
<P>
   He tore the anterior cruciate ligament in a game in 1994, and he
has had degenerative arthritis in it since. He had arthroscopic
surgery a few months ago and still is re-gaining strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are talking about signing people, everything comes
into play,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``There was no secret
he had problems with his knee.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons never called Smith's agent, Jimmy Sexton, with a
contract offer ``because they would never give us a figure,''
Reeves said last offseason. ``You had to think they were thinking
of a huge number.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to a deal came when Sexton called general
manager Harold Richardson last September after the team gave
defensive tackle Travis Hall a seven-year, $51.5 million extension.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton asked: Why extend a guy who has three years left on his
contract before Chuck?
</P>
<P>
   Richardson told Sexton that Smith could have the same deal,
complete with the $5.1 million signing bonus, that day.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Sexton held out, mindful that the Colts in 1999 gave
defensive end Chad Bratzke a $9 million signing bonus and that
Tampa gave end Chidi Ahonotu a five-year, $30 million contract with
a $6 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Smith performed, ailments and all. He led the team with 10
sacks, 27 quarterback pressures and six fumbles caused. He added 84
tackles and finished second in the point system that coaches use to
grade defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   But the free-agent market was not kind.
</P>
<P>
   He passed on a nice offer from Green Bay to sign a five-year,
$21.5 million deal in Carolina, with a $4.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in the end, the fact he'll get to play against
Atlanta twice a year was important,'' Sexton said in February.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said: ``In the beginning, I guess I was more disappointed
that no one ever said, `Hey, Chuck, we're not going to be able to
mess with you, or we don't think your knee is good, or the money's
not right.' Instead, I was just kind of left to the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, I started thinking of the good times,'' he said. ``Dan
was cool. (Defensive-line coach) Bill Kollar, (offensive-line
coach) Art Shell, I attribute a lot of the stuff I learned to those
guys. I don't have (any) hard feelings. I was proud to be a
Falcon.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield was asked if Smith is angry
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``(Smith) would have loved to have
stayed here his whole career, but _ things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith talks regularly with former teammates, including Patrick
Kerney, who helped bump Smith and former Falcons defensive end
Lester Archambeau out of work. Kerney was Smith's neighbor at Lake
Lanier, where both own homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, my house is just two minutes from the new complex,''
Smith said. ``Tell one of those cats to buy my house. I keep
telling Pat, `Keep playing hard, and then you can get a big
contract and upgrade to my house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to (kicker) Morten Andersen's house all the time,
about five minutes on my jet ski. Those guys are my dogs. I want
`em to win every week, except this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has not seen the last of Chuck Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers visit the Georgia Dome on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Atlanta,'' Smith said. ``I'm coming down there after
football, and I'm going to get one of those radio or TV jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
