<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-HUMMER0915-COX     09-14 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney perfect Games venue
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ A bloke pauses in mid-alfresco-mouthful. A moment is
upon him on this night as perfectly chilled as the Australian wine.
</P>
<P>
   The grilled rudderfish would wait. A mental image is begging to
be stored. Check the copper moon pasted above the skyline. Freeze
Darling Harbor as it catches the lights to jewel its surface.
Remember the surprising burst of fireworks competing with the
stars.
</P>
<P>
   And the bloke can't help thinking: Looks like it will be another
four years before Atlanta gets the chance to look any better by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   A bloke goes to work each morning _ leaving the asylum that
required only minor renovations to house sportswriters _ and passes
an aviary stocked with squawking, garishly colored native birds.
When he gets back at night, he makes out the faint forms of
kangaroos hopping about in the next pen.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon. It's just not fair. Between the Old World beauty of
Barcelona and the emerging exotica of Sydney there sits Atlanta, a
soccer mom outflanked by divas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this same bloke can imagine few places on the planet he
would rather live than Atlanta. At the same time, he knows there
are several cities better to visit for 16 days of sport that don't
involve Southern youth meeting at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of new experiences is just too great. It overwhelms
even the stoutest provincial sort.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are all about competition. How, then, is Atlanta to
compete against the terrain of Sydney, a place where it seems the
Creator has pressed a hand into the shore and the prints since have
been so gratefully adorned?
</P>
<P>
   How perfect is this: They have an opera house that you don't
have to go inside to enjoy. No need to endure a single aria. The
experience is over before the fat lady sings.
</P>
<P>
   Just above the Opera House, a bloke wanders into a bar, not an
uncommon Australian experience. His party is joined by a local
worker in a floppy hat and a ZZ Top-standard-issue beard. He is
asked to be part of a simple photo.
</P>
<P>
   Hang on a sec, the gent says. He turns away, as if to fix his
makeup. But when he swings back, he has combed his beard up over
his face, anchored the effect with a pair of sunglasses and stuck a
smoldering cigarette into the thicket, risking a major brushfire.
Australia's Cousin It. These people are just too eager to please.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you'd wish a disaster on anyone. But maybe Athens could
stage enough logistical problems _ a brownout here, a phone outage
there _ in 2004 to boost the memory of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The real work of the current Summer Olympics begins Saturday.
Before then, a chance to play. First a trip by the Rosehill Gardens
Racecourse, where the nags run clockwise on turf while Sinatra
plays overhead, more challenges to the American eye and ear. Then
on to the Star City Casino, a huge, Vegas-style place in the back
pocket of downtown. A bloke watches them gather round a small pit
and loudly wager on the toss of two coins. He gets more serious at
the blackjack tables and manages to lift a bit of yellow and purple
money from the place.
</P>
<P>
   It might just all come together for the Sydneysiders, darn them.
They get to put on their Games in their spring, when the air is
clean and fresh. The U.S. dollar is strong and the value high.
Their citizens seem in a mood to make this work.
</P>
<P>
   A cavernous Olympic Stadium awaits the real business of the
Games. Radiating outward is a couple city blocks of gleaming
facilities that promise a matchless concentration of energy and
excitement. They'd really have to make an effort to blow it from
here.
</P>
<P>
   There's a long way to go before the 2000 Games are safely in the
books. Still, upon entering, a bloke from another venue that would
be worldly, kicks himself for thinking it, but think it he does:
Just as every Super Bowl should be in New Orleans, every Olympics
should be here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
