<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-GRASSROOTS-COLUMN-980     09-14 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASSROOTS-COLUMN-980&AMP;ADD-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS BUSINESS: A FINE PLACE TO WORK, BUT CAN YOU FLY
THERE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By JOEL KOTKIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nevada _ Like a modern-day conquistador, Roger Norman
surveys a vast expanse of open brush and sage, and dreams of El
Dorado.
</P>
<P>
   He has plans to turn his 104,000 empty acres here into the
Tahoe-Reno Industrial Center, the largest industrial park in North
America, with 120 million square feet of industrial and warehouse
space, power plants, movie studios and even a racetrack. He is sure
that he could fill it with new-economy tenants, as he has done at
South Meadow, a smaller project closer to Reno that is near
completion.
</P>
<P>
   Only one ingredient is missing, he said: A sky filled with
planes heading toward Reno's modern airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't build things fast enough here,'' said Norman, 37.
``But without the air traffic, how do we accommodate the growth
that wants to come here?''
</P>
<P>
   Before November 1998, there were plenty of flights to Reno, most
of them flown by Reno Air, an independent carrier that had grown to
serve a large chunk of the West. Then AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, acquired Reno Air for $124 million and began reducing
service. Despite complaints from business and political leaders,
the number of nonstop flights on all airlines to Reno _ 127 daily
from 28 cities in 1997 _ has fallen to just 88 daily from 12
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons lie in the economics of the hub-and-spoke route
systems operated by American and other large carriers, according to
Dale Morris, a spokesman for the airline. Most passengers are
routed through a few high-volume hub airports, like American's at
Dallas-Fort Worth, where they catch connecting flights to their
final destinations. Away from the hubs, only the most popular
routes have nonstop service, and according to Morris, ``secondary
markets'' like Reno ``don't have the lift'' to warrant many direct
flights.
</P>
<P>
   Reno is a conservatively minded, pro-business city, and people
here acknowledge the capitalist logic of American's stance. But
they had grown used to the broader service that their hometown
airline had provided, and its disappearance leaves them fearing for
Reno's long-term ability to compete with other cities in the
region, most notably Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Developers like Norman worry that demand for ambitious projects
already in the pipeline will be undercut if prospective tenants
find it a nuisance to get in and out of town by air.
Gaming-industry executives worry that making Reno less accessible
will further widen the gap between Reno's casinos and those in Las
Vegas, and perhaps make Reno more vulnerable to competition from
new Indian-owned casinos springing up in California.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns are increasingly commonplace in ``second-tier''
cities, said John Kasarda, president of the Kenan Institute for
Private Enterprise at the University of North Carolina. The
hub-and-spoke air traffic system leaves even rapidly growing cities
like Reno feeling marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a matter of tourism. For a city that wants to keep
growing, being an easily accessible air hub _ what Kasarda calls an
``aerotropolis'' _ is crucial to attracting high-technology and
Internet businesses and investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic commerce companies in particular, with their emphasis
on speed as a competitive advantage, have come to understand that
warehousing and handling goods in places where they can be rapidly
and efficiently distributed is just as vital to their success as
having plenty of bandwidth and server capacity: More than 70
percent of e-commerce sales are shipped through express delivery
services, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesspeople in the technology sector travel more than their
counterparts in the traditional economy, Kasarda said _ in some
studies, up to four times as much.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that even cities with everything else
going for them _ from land to tax rates to infrastructure _ can
find their growth threatened by a lack of direct air service.
Metropolitan areas like Tulsa, Okla., and Raleigh-Durham, N.C.,
have wrestled with perceived air-service shortfalls in recent
years, and have galvanized political and business leaders to find
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrations over the paucity of flights to Wisconsin in the
early 1980s even prompted Kimberly-Clark, the paper products giant
then with headquarters near Milwaukee, to lease a Boeing 737 and
begin running its own airline. The service was opened to the public
in 1984 as Midwest Express, and has since been spun off as a
separate company.
</P>
<P>
   What the Renos, Tulsas and Raleighs care most about are nonstop
flights to major business centers like New York, Chicago, Los
Angeles and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many midsized cities have become preoccupied about this,''
Kasarda said. ``They see it as key to their economic development.
Businesspeople hate to change planes and listen to the music at
O'Hare. Time is money for these people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Reno, business and political leaders are casting about for
ways to entice other airlines to expand service to Reno and replace
the flights that American has trimmed. American, Southwest Airlines
and other carriers have been visited by officials here, but to date
the lobbying has not paid off.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Randolph Townsend, who represents the city and is the
chairman of the legislature's commerce and labor committee, said
the state is considering incentives ranging from state contracts to
reductions in fuel taxes and landing fees to obliging airlines,
including start-up regional carriers like Allegiant Air, based in
Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that such proposals run counter to the free-market
ideology that dominates politics here; loss of direct air service
could ``really hurt in the long run,'' Townsend said, even though
job and income-growth statistics in the Reno area have yet to show
definite signs of weakening.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But a harbinger of losses may be visible in the recent decision
by Reno's largest manufacturer, International Game Technology, to
keep its 300-person sales and marketing operation in Las Vegas,
where executives and technicians have access to a much wider array
of flights to places around the county and, increasingly, the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the company, Tom Butler, said that operating
from Reno with its current level of air service meant adding up two
extra days to every trip to the East Coast or overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to locate today,'' he said, ``we'd put everything
in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler became head of the company, whose plant is in Norman's
South Meadows industrial park, in 1996, before American acquired
Reno Air.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``it bugs customers when we have to bring them
here, and it takes away one of the things that would help bring
sophisticated employees here.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller businesses smart at the loss of service, too. Addi
Gallery has exhibition space in Reno, Maui and most recently Las
Vegas; it also has a new Internet-based art business called
GalleryRow.com. Winifred Addi, the company's chief operating
officer, said that the loss of Reno Air's former direct service to
Orange County, Calif., and San Diego kept potential customers away
from her Reno location, and that cutbacks in flights to San Jose
had hampered development of the Web site part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a meeting with 25 top representatives of Bay Area and
Orange County tech companies, and people just didn't want to wait
around,'' she said. ``They were all worrying about how to catch a
flight to get themselves home. If the meeting had been in a place
like L.A., we could have started earlier and gone into the evening.
It really hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest potential losers are the casinos, which remain the
bulwark of the region's economy. Glen Carano, marketing director
for the Silver Legacy Casino in downtown Reno, said the loss of
convenient service to Orange County, San Diego and other markets
threatened to depress an important category of business _ bookings
for large conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge when it's tough to get here, and I am going
to have a hard time getting them to come,'' Carano said. ``We sit
here and think we are at the center of the world, but you've got
travel planners with thousands of markets and hundreds of airports
to look at. We are just a little pimple to them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
