<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BURNING-MAN-$ADV1     09-14 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BURNING-MAN-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT ON THE ROAD TO BURNING MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 17) 
 By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't yet seen a Burning Man sticker on a Cadillac. But when
I do, it won't surprise me. That is because Burning Man, the annual
weeklong festival of arts, music and ``radical self-expression'' in
the Nevada desert, is rapidly seeping into mainstream American
culture _ or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   Like many other things countercultural and groovy, Burning Man
started in the Bay Area, when Larry Harvey built and burned an
effigy on a San Francisco beach in 1986. Publicized by word of
mouth and on the Web, the event caught the imagination of the
digerati and took on a life of its own. Sequels grew so big that
Harvey had to move the pyrotechnics to somewhere a bit less
populated _ a desolate stretch of federally owned desert 100 miles
north of Reno. This year's event culminated on Labor Day; about
28,000 people participated in the ephemeral makeshift community,
Black Rock City, that materializes for the annual torching of a
40-foot-high wood and neon figure.
</P>
<P>
   Burn Heads are loath to make the comparison, but the festival _
which draws so many people from Silicon Valley that it could easily
be called Burn Rate Man _ has much in common with a Grateful Dead
concert: Young and formerly young people camping out, enjoying
performance art (and maybe various levels of undress and altered
states of consciousness) and raging against the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, Burning Man is anti-corporate, anti-consumerism,
anti-establishment; people cover over the Ryder logos on their
trucks and wear handmade outfits that reflect the Inner Them of the
Day. Hard currency will get you only coffee and ice at the
festival; you have to bring other supplies along with you, or
barter for them. Think ``Survivor'' without the lush foliage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burning Man co-opts people out of their rut and shows them a
different way of living, working, playing and communicating,'' said
Larry Smith, 32, the executive editor of Yahoo Internet Life
magazine, who has made the pilgrimage six times.
</P>
<P>
   I attended last year, and for all my skepticism, I have to say
that I had a hilarious, if slightly dehydrating, time. But what I
found there wasn't a digital-age Woodstock. It was more
fascinating: The Internet made flesh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got your communities of affinity, viral marketing,
information pricing, users-provide-the-content approach, branding,
and Larry Harvey is the very essence of today's iconoclast-savant
CEO,'' said Brad Wieners, 32, editor of the book ``Burning Man''
(Hardwired, 1997). ``All that's missing is the IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   There are certainly enough dollars involved to go public.
Depending on when you buy your ticket, Burning Man can cost $95 to
$250. Multiply that by 28,000 and, well, you do the math. And how
anti-establishment can an event be when the managing editor of Time
magazine makes an appearance? Or when the Green Tortoise travel
company advertises package trips to the ``wildest experience you've
ever had''? Or when law firms send squads of employees in rented
RV's? What's next, a ``Let's Go: Black Rock City'' travel guide?
</P>
<P>
   Aly Eisenhardt, 22, a junior at Humboldt State University in
California who had attended Burning Man twice before, didn't go
this year. ``It's gotten too commercial, too big and too
hypocritical,'' Eisenhardt said. ``It's outside the value system of
what Burning Man was really about.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything underground and successful eventually becomes
commercial and overdone. Each generation has had its its own
counterculture jamboree; images of the Beats, Haight-Ashbury,
Monterey, the Dead, Nirvana, mosh pits and techno raves come to
mind. Before long, everyone else comes piling in and spoils the
fun. So, too, with the Web, some would say.
</P>
<P>
   But not with Burning Man. The dynamic is different. Most
participants are not rebellious teen-agers, but people in their 20s
and 30s with jobs and even companies of their own; more than a few
are stock-option millionaires. This generation may not openly
condone ``selling out,'' but it certainly doesn't frown on
capitalism and getting rich. By past counterculture standards,
``them'' equaled ``us'' from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Wieners, who has seen seven Men burn, said that while the
festival has been ``legitimized by the establishment,'' that
doesn't mean that it is being destroyed. ``There are a lot of
paradoxes,'' he said. ``The guy who's the main instigator is making
his living off Burning Man, but has he sold out? It's not brought
to you by Budweiser. It's kept certain parameters. This year, some
of the art had a much higher production value, because artists are
getting grants from Burning Man. Is this bad?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's discovering that play, folly, make-believe, the
way you spent afternoons in the early grades, is a valid thing for
an adult to do. It's what a whole lot of companies strive for.
Realizing that innovation comes from play, they want to encourage
it _ to a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But if play breeds innovation, and innovation breeds
productivity, and productivity breeds sales, one thing is clear:
Bumper stickers can't be far behind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
