<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-HNS &LR;      09-14 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore spends star-studded evening on campaign trail in New York
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore, who
earlier this week bashed the entertainment industry for marketing
sex and violence to children, taped a show with David Letterman
Thursday, then spent the evening at a multimillion-dollar
fund-raising extravaganza featuring such talent as Bette Midler,
Jimmy Buffett and Paul Simon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is faking his criticism of the Hollywood elite,''
Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson said at a
sidewalk news conference outside the fund-raiser at Radio City
Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore and (running mate) Joe Lieberman are cozying up with
them,'' he said, adding that criticizing Hollywood while taking its
money shows ``hypocrisy characteristic of Al Gore's career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane fired back that unlike Republican
nominee George W. Bush, Gore is capable of accepting financial
support from his friends and still stand up to them when he
believes they are wrong. He cited Bush and running mate Dick
Cheney's ties to the oil and health insurance industries and
campaign promises Lehane said are aimed at protecting them.
</P>
<P>
   Gore tried to emphasize that point earlier in the day, telling
students, teachers and parents at a middle school in Manchester,
N.H., that he will fight companies that aggressively target minors
with advertising for adult music, movies and video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wrong and it has to be stopped,'' Gore said. ``It's
hard enough to raise a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated the message at Thursday evening's fund-raiser,
expected to bring in $5 million to $7 million for the Democratic
National Committee. It was produced by Miramax Films' Harvey
Weinstein, Rolling Stone publisher Jann Wenner and VH1 president
John Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Michael Douglas was emcee.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Granata, spokeswoman for Miramax, issued a statement
saying that even before Monday's release of a Federal Trade
Commission report critical of the entertainment industry's
advertising practices, Miramax had voluntarily developed new
guidelines to give parents more information for judging what films
are appropriate for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax films include Academy Award winners ``Life is
Beautiful,'' ``The English Patient'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,''
in addition to the ultra-violent ``Pulp Fiction'' and the
controversial ``Kids,'' which portrays a group of New York
teen-agers whose lives revolve around riding skateboards, having
sex and abusing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Among other performers Thursday night were Sheryl Crow, Lenny
Kravitz, Jon Bon Jovi, k.d. lang and Crosby, Stills and Nash. Actor
Harrison Ford was listed as a special guest.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gore and Lieberman attended a fund-raising
barbecue in Boston where singer James Taylor performed. That
dinner, along with a luncheon earlier, netted $2.5 million for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Gore and wife Tipper attended an $800,000
fund-raising concert in suburban Philadelphia with Cher, Michael
Bolton, Luther Vandross and Sister Sledge.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday's show, Gore walked onto the set of
``Letterman'' to the Prince song, ``Kiss,'' and joked about the
now-famous big kiss he gave wife Tipper Gore on the stage of last
month's Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been surprised at the amount of commentary and reaction
to it because to me, that was just a little peck,'' Gore joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al, how long have you been on the road?'' Letterman responded.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also shook hands with an audience member featured earlier
in the show. The cowboy hat-wearing man identified himself as
``Craig'' and said he runs the hardware store in Lampasas, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, wearing a gray suit, white shirt and blue tie, also
answered several serious questions from Letterman, commenting on
the release from jail of Los Alamos scientist Wen Ho Lee and a Gore
aide's receipt of a package containing debate preparation materials
from the campaign of Republican opponent George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight of the show was Gore's reading of Letterman's
trademark Top 10 _ this one listing rejected Gore-Lieberman
campaign slogans. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vote for me or I'll come to your home and explain my
191-page economic plan in excruciating detail.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Remember America: I gave you the Internet and I can take it
away.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``With Gore-Lieberman, you don't have to worry about
pork-barrel politics'' and ``With Lieberman on the ticket, you get
all kinds of fun new days off'' _ both references to Lieberman's
strict observance of the Jewish Sabbath, holidays and dietary
rules. ``Vote for us,'' Gore added to that one. ``We're gonna work
24-6.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We know the microphone is on,'' alluding to Bush's off-color
characterization of a reporter that was picked up by a live mike.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 1: ``I'll be twice as cool as that president guy on `The
West Wing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
