<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AD SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Television stations around the country are expected to benefit
from this year's bounty of political commercials to the tune of $1
billion, according to a Washington group that pushes for better
campaign coverage by the news media. The Alliance for Better
Campaigns, which is headed by Paul Taylor, a former political
reporter, released data showing that as of July 31, local
television stations in the top 75 media markets had already taken
in $211 million from the broadcast of 286,737 spots. The bulk of
the commercials appear in the final months leading up to the
November election. At a news conference, Taylor, joined by Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., called on local stations to devote five
minutes of their news programs to issues and discourse by the
candidates on each of the last 30 days of the campaign, as
recommended by a presidential commission. Thus far, the alliance
said, only 42 stations, or 3 percent of the industry, have said
they will try to meet that standard.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNING WITH A LAUGH TRACK
</P>
<P>
   He'll keep his day job, but for a frustrated comedian like Sen.
Joseph I. Lieberman, appearances Thursday on NBC's ``Late Night
with Conan O'Brien'' and Comedy Central's ``The Daily Show with Jon
Stewart'' were a fantasy come true. To prepare for the vice
presidency, Lieberman told Stewart: ``I've been watching old Carson
reruns to learn from Ed McMahon what I should do. `Yes, sir, I
never thought of that, that was brilliant.''' Does the vice
president get a house, Stewart asked. ``A small trailer,'' the
senator said. ``No, actually, it's the Naval Observatory. Naval as
in Navy. I don't want you to think _'' ``That was the last
administration,'' Stewart shot back. Lieberman, the first Jew on a
major party's national ticket, told O'Brien that he and Vice
President Al Gore are considering new slogans, like
``Gore-Lieberman: no bull, no pork'' and ``With malice toward none,
but a little guilt for everyone.'' O'Brien coaxed the senator into
singing ``My Way.'' When he came to the line ``Regrets, I've had a
few,'' he added, ``Here's one right here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO BOB JONES
</P>
<P>
   By loudly criticizing Hollywood for its glorification of
violence and sex, the Republican and Democratic presidential
tickets have stolen one of the issue horses that Pat Buchanan has
ridden in his many campaigns. Not to be outdone, Buchanan, who now
appears to be the official candidate of the Reform Party, has
scheduled a speech for Monday on ``Hollywood and the Cultural
War,'' which a press release described as a ``battle cry.'' The
location of the speech is almost as telling as the subject: Bob
Jones University in Greenville, S.C., a favorite conservative
audience of Buchanan's and one that Gov. George W. Bush addressed
this year before the South Carolina primary. Bush was criticized
for that appearance because of certain university policies, but
those have never bothered Buchanan. ``It'll be a good one,''
promises Buchanan's press director, Brian Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ San Diego and Albuquerque
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH I. LIEBERMAN _ New York
</P>
</TEXT>
