<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RETIRED-TEACHERS-N     09-14 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RETIRED-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BACK-TO-SCHOOL OFFER FOR RETIREES: FULL SALARY AND FULL
PENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a stark concession to the seriousness of New
York state's shortage of qualified teachers, the Board of Regents
said Thursday that it would ask the Legislature to approve a
measure allowing retired teachers to return to the classroom and
draw a full salary while continuing to receive their pension
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers who accept the offer must agree to teach in a
low-performing school or in a subject area, like math or science,
where schools are having a difficult time attracting qualified
teachers. The program is aimed at attracting teachers to the 173
districts and up to 1,000 schools that the state classifies as
low-performing or high-need, and includes the roughly 100 schools
that are in danger of being closed for their poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   The increased costs of hiring the more experienced teachers
would be borne by the school districts, although the state has been
allocating more funds in recent years for special recruitment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is likely to enjoy bipartisan support among
legislators and the governor's office, government officials said
Thursday. The Republicans in the Senate introduced a similar
measure last spring, but it was ultimately dropped from an
education package signed into law by Gov. George Pataki in May.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Conway, a spokesman for Pataki, said in response to
Thursday's developments that the governor ``is very pleased that
the Regents share the governor's belief that teacher recruitment is
a major issue. We welcome their support in the ongoing effort to
attract and recruit qualified teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the state's 230,000 teachers will need to be
replaced in the next few years, according to the Regents. And there
is an immediate need for at least 16,000 certified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the proposal remain to be worked out, but such a
program would substantially increase some retired teachers'
incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the legislation is written, a returning teacher
could earn anywhere from the money he or she was earning upon
retirement to some lower level on a teacher's pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   Under the most generous scenario, a teacher who retired at the
age of 55 after 25 years of service from a job paying $70,000
would, by returning to the classroom, continue to earn that amount
plus $35,000 a year in pension benefits, bringing his annual income
to more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law that limits a retiree's earnings, that teacher
could only earn $17,000 beyond his pension if he went back to work
in his own district. The Regents will also ask the Legislature for
up to $39 million to support mentoring programs of beginning
teachers by older, more experienced ones and for $5 million more in
grants to colleges to increase programs that train teachers in
math, science and other key subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents' proposal comes after several school districts
across the state, including New York City, struggled to fill
teaching positions in the weeks leading up to the start of school.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, state officials say that more than half of current
teachers will be eligible to retire in this decade. The situation
in New York City may be even worse, with the teachers' union
maintaining the city will need to fill 54,000 jobs in the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of teacher recruitment have forced school districts
around the country to try new incentives to attract and retain
qualified teachers, including offering low-interest loans for
housing and offering signing bonuses to teachers who move from
other careers. Last year, the Texas Legislature approved a similar
pension measure to the one proposed by the Regents to entice
experienced teachers out of retirement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In May, Pataki signed into law a program, called ``Teachers for
Tomorrow,'' that included extra pay for teachers who agreed to work
in areas of shortages and tuition grants for teachers to complete
licensing requirements. However, in New York under current law,
retirees lose $1 of their pension benefits for every $1 they earn
beyond $17,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Levy, the chancellor of the New York City school system,
where current and predicted teacher shortages are the worst, said
he welcomed the Regents proposal. But, he warned, ``it doesn't help
in adequate numbers to solve the problem, and it is expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how expensive the program will be is not clear. Among the
uncertainties are whether principals and superintendents would be
free to choose which retired teachers they wanted to hire and and
whether retirees would receive priority over younger uncertified
teachers who want the jobs. By 2003, all newly hired teachers in
the state will have to be certified.
</P>
<P>
   Also unknown is whether retired teachers would have to be hired
in order of seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every teacher who is retired might not be appropriate to come
back,'' said Steven Sanders, a Manhattan Democrat who is chairman
of the Assembly Education committee and who said he supports the
Regents' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In the program outlined by the Regents, teachers would have to
be retired for at least one year before enrolling, and they could
participate for up to five years. Richard Mills, the education
commissioner, said he believed the cost of the program to school
districts would be minimal because the retired teachers would be
hired for positions that otherwise could not be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hayden, chancellor of the Board of Regents, said that New
York State trains about 10,000 more teachers each year than it
hires, with many of the state's education graduates opting for
other professions or choosing to teach in other states. In
addition, large numbers of New York City teachers, including many
of the best prepared, leave teaching within a few years after
starting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of details, the proposal was lauded by
officials of teachers' unions and by legislative leaders Wednesday.
Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of Teachers,
the New York City union, commended the Regents for their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Regents and Commissioner Mills have realized very quickly
that in order to get standards higher, the quality of the teachers
in the classroom becomes absolutely imperative,'' Weingarten said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
