<P>
   (NYT28) TANGIER ISLAND, Va. -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- Adv. for Sun.,
Sept. 17 -- TANGIER-ISLAND-COX-3 -- Tangier Island has changed more
in recent decades than it did during several centuries following
its discovery in 1608 by Capt. John Smith, the leader of Jamestown.
This remote island in Virginia that didn't have phones until 1966
now has cable TV and computers. Tangier Island is actually three
ridges divided by marshes and tidal canals and linked together by
small bridges. Islanders use golf carts to travel between Main
Ridge, West Ridge and Canton Ridge. (Bob Dart/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TANGIER ISLAND, Va. -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- Adv. for Sun.,
Sept. 17 -- TANGIER-ISLAND-COX-2 -- Tangier Island has changed more
in recent decades than it did during several centuries following
its discovery in 1608 by Capt. John Smith, the leader of Jamestown.
This remote island in Virginia that didn't have phones until 1966
now haS cable TV and computers. Opportunities are very limited.
Since 1950, the population has fallen by more than half to about
650. Sandy Dise, 15, Kim Lewis, 15 and Justin Landon, 16, squeeze
into the front seat of a golf cart while a couple of young tourist
hitchhikers peer in from the back. (Bob Dart/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TANGIER ISLAND, Va. -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- Adv. for Sun.,
Sept. 17 -- TANGIER-ISLAND-COX-1 -- Tangier Island has changed more
in recent decades than it did during several centuries following
its discovery in 1608 by Capt. John Smith, the leader of Jamestown.
This remote island in Virginia that didn't have phones until 1966
now haS cable TV and computers. As its fishermen suffer dwindling
crab catches and tightening environmental regulation, the Tangier
economy is turning toward tourism. The Swain Memorial United
Methodist Church is the center of the island's spiritual and social
life. (Bob Dart/Cox News Service)
