<P>
   (NYT43) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- GORE-FUNDRAISER-3 --
Democratic presidential candidate, Vice President Al Gore pushed
celebrity politicking to dizzying heights Thursday as he traded
laughs with TV's David Letterman and later in the evening attended
a star-studded fund-raiser at Radio City Music Hall set to bring in
about $5 million for the Democratic National Committee. Gore making
a joke about working 24-6, a reference to running mate Joseph
Lieberman's following the Sabath which prevents him from working on
Saturdays. Lieberman. Lieberman's wife Hadassah, left, Lieberman
and supporters laughing on stage at the gala event at Radio City
Music Hall. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) YENIDOGAN, Turkey -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- TURKEY-SCHOOL-2
-- About 14 million children started the new school year across
Turkey this week, donning uniforms and filling overcrowded
classrooms. But a million other children were not there. Instead,
most were working in factories, fields, shops and the streets. Many
of these children are needed to earn money for their families, or
to stay at home and take care of siblings while their parents work.
Others come from families that do not value formal education. Murat
Kilic, 14, center in plaid shirt, toils 10 hours a day in a
metal-fabrication shop in the village of Yenidogan. Kilic standing
with four friends who still attend school. (Douglas Frantz/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) YENIDOGAN, Turkey -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- TURKEY-SCHOOL --
About 14 million children started the new school year across Turkey
this week, donning uniforms and filling overcrowded classrooms. But
a million other children were not there. Instead, most were working
in factories, fields, shops and the streets. Many of these children
are needed to earn money for their families, or to stay at home and
take care of siblings while their parents work. Others come from
families that do not value formal education. Fifty first graders,
three to a desk, crowd their classroom in the village of Yenidogan.
(Douglas Frantz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- NY-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN --
At the direct urging of the first lady and one of her closest
advisers, James Carville, Hillary Rodham Clinton has opened a ``war
room,'' though her aides decline to use the term. Whatever it is
called, it is a high-pressure boiler room of about twelve people
devoted to constant examination of Clinton's opponent in the race
for the U.S. Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio and his record. Howard
Wolfson, center, Clinton's director of communications, speaks with
Karen Finney, the campaign's press secretary, Thursday inside the
room. (James Estrin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
