<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- AUTHOR-BUSHNELL-BOS --
Candace Bushnell, 41, author of ``Sex and the City,'' and now, ``4
Blondes,'' is annoyed because people keep mixing fact and fiction.
Bushnell complains, that people confuse her and the ``Carrie
Bradshaw'' character from the HBO series, ``Sex and the City,'' as
the same person. They may share a passion for writing but
Bushnell's sex life is not an open book. She is determined to let
people understand that her writing is fiction written as
journalism. Bushnell walking up Beacon Street in Boston. (John
Tlumacki/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOSTON -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- HOME-CYBER-CLUTTER-BOS --
The wires from computer monitors, keyboards, speakers, printers,
faxes, scanners, and phones are, for some, a visual nightmare. Some
label it cyber clutter. According to a recent Microsoft survey, the
furniture, interior-design, and industrial-design industries are
tackling wire management and techno-clutter problems. Using large
cup hooks, duct tape, nylon ties and Velcro are all inexpensive
ways to bind groups of wires together. (Pam Berry/The Boston Globe)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SANTA ANA, Calif. -- Sept. 14, 2000 --
BUSH-DEMS-ISSUES-3 -- George W. Bush greets children from Heninger
Elementary school gathered outside the Santa Ana High School,
Thursday. Speaking to students at Santa Ana High School, Bush
reiterated his plan to make schools more accountable for student
performance and to give local and state governments more
flexibility to spend education money as they wish. Students of this
heavily Hispanic school peppered him with questions on other
topics, such as whether he supports the teaching of sexual
abstinence. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- CHILDHOODREVEALED-3-HNS --
More than 100 pieces in the book and exhibit of the same name.
``Childhood Revealed,'' a touring exhibit, opened in Houston this
week at the Museum of Health &AMP; Medical Science and runs through
Oct. 15. The art in the exhibit and the book was created by
children ages 4 to 18 with developmental, psychological and
physical problems ranging from learning differences, abuse and
depression to divorce, psychosis and chronic illness. One of the
artworks,''Camouflaged,'' 1996, oil stick, by an 18 year-old. The
artist said: ``This piece is about me! It was the first time I ever
used art to express my feelings, I would always close up and not
talk about my feelings, but not this time. It helped me express my
pain and loneliness. I am grateful to be seen and heard.''(Harold
S. Koplewicz, Harry N. Abrams, Inc./Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- CHILDHOODREVEALED-2-HNS --
More than 100 pieces in the book and exhibit of the same name.
``Childhood Revealed,'' a touring exhibit, opened in Houston this
week at the Museum of Health &AMP; Medical Science and runs through
Oct. 15. The art in the exhibit and the book was created by
children ages 4 to 18 with developmental, psychological and
physical problems ranging from learning differences, abuse and
depression to divorce, psychosis and chronic illness. One of the
artworks, ``Madness,'' 1997. Felt markers by a 14 year-old male.
The artist said he selected the name ``because it shows anger
inside the character in the picture.'' (Harold S. Koplewicz, Harry
N. Abrams, Inc./Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 2000 -- CHILDHOODREVEALED-1-HNS --
More than 100 pieces in the book and exhibit of the same name.
