<HEADLINE>
HERTA MAKES MOST OF FORSYTHE DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Valencia's Bryan Herta got his chance to defend
his title at Sunday's Grand Prix of Monterey and nearly pulled it
off.
</P>
<P>
   In a race with few accidents and even fewer mistakes, Herta
finished where he started, in fourth, in an impressive run for a
driver and a team with only eight days to prepare for a race.
</P>
<P>
   Herta, racing for the first time this season for owner Gerald
Forsythe, who signed him at the start of the 2000 CART FedEx season
to race for Forsythe Championship Racing, had to overcome fuel pump
problems and an inexperienced pit crew at Laguna Seca Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Herta's team, which was mostly funded by Forsythe, went from not
turning a lap on the first day of practice to qualifying on the
second row to finishing in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   But Herta said while fourth place made for a productive weekend,
it wasn't where he wanted to end his day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a little disappointed we didn't win,'' said Herta, a
Hart High graduate. ``But looking at the fact that we had a group
of guys who hadn't worked together before, it was pretty amazing.
Considering the circumstances, I'm pretty happy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Herta's future with Forsythe, things are very much up in
the air. He will definitely not race in St. Louis, for the Motorola
300 at Gateway International Raceway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not enough spares and not enough time turn the car
into an oval car,'' Herta said.
</P>
<P>
   However, there has been talk from team sources that Herta may
race in the Grand Prix of Houston on Oct. 1 and possibly in the
season finale at California Speedway in Fontana on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Boone hanging on to lead: In one of the most tightly contested
title chases in USAC Western Midget racing history, Bobby Boone of
Palmdale holds a three-point lead over Danny Ebberts in the series
standings with six races to go. Third-place driver Wally Pankratz
is 13 points behind Boone.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Boone's season even more amazing is that he has been
running consistently and successfully near the top of the series
without the benefit of corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Boone, a 19-year-old Littlerock High graduate, has been entirely
funded by his family and friends. His mother, who also doubles as
his financial manager for the team, says about $40,000 has been
invested in Boone's season. The total championship purse for all
the series drivers is expected to be around $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'd really like to have a big ol' points lead
right now,'' Boone said. ``I am just concentrating on finishing
races.''
</P>
<P>
   The tightest race in Western Midget history happened in 1989
when Robby Flock beat out Sleepy Tripp by 16 points. It was Flock's
second Western Midget championship. He also won in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Boone credits his family for keeping him financed throughout the
season and engine builders Dan and Dwayne Esslinger of South El
Monte for putting him atop the Western Midget standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without them, we wouldn't be where we're at,'' said Boone of
the Esslingers. ``They helped us find problems, heating problems,
and get the bugs out of the engine.''
</P>
<P>
   If Boone holds on to win the Western Midget crown, he will
become the youngest driver to do so. Ricky Shelton, who was 19
years and 11 months when he won his title in 1997, is the youngest
driver with a Western Midget crown. If Boone holds on to win the
championship, he will have done it at 19 years and nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Boone finished ninth in the Western Midget feature Saturday
night at Santa Maria Speedway. The Western Midgets head for Madera
Speedway next for a doubleheader with the USAC Sprints. The Madera
Speedway race is on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lyon takes Madera race: Bob Lyon of Agua Dulce, driving the
Northridge Rentals/LTR Eng./Ramada Express Chevrolet, won for the
first time this season on the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series
on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Lyon took the Food 4 Less MDA 100 by leading for the last 54
laps of the race and winning by a .2-second margin over Eric
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   M.K. Kanke of Frazier Park was fourth; Greg Pursley of Newhall
was ninth; Frank Maronski Jr. of Quartz Hill was 13th; and Sean
Woodside of Saugus was 18th.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Southwest Series is Sept. 23 at Las Vegas
Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Dotter wins for third time on Winston West: Bobby Dotter of
Charlotte, N.C., won for the third time this season on the NASCAR
Winston West circuit by taking the Sept. 4 Bank One 250 at Rocky
Mountain Raceways in Salt Lake City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sedgwick of Acton, a two-time Winston West Series champion,
finished second in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Dotter, driver of the People Against Drugs Chevrolet, also won
at Laguna Seca Raceway and Irwindale Speedway this year. He is
second in points and trails series leader Brendan Gaughan of Las
Vegas by 185 points.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Winston West schedule is the Spears
Manufacturing 250 at Mesa Marin Raceway in Bakersfield on Oct. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
