<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE IS `TROUBLED' BY HANDLING OF SCIENTIST'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Rewrites first 2 grafs to emphasize `stinging and highly unusual
rebuke')  
(See also LEE-RELEASE-ASSESS) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a stinging and highly unusual rebuke of his
Justice Department and the FBI, President Clinton said Thursday
that he was ``quite troubled'' by the government's actions in the
Wen Ho Lee case.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came a day after a federal judge in New Mexico
harshly criticized the Justice Department for its tactics in the
case, and as Attorney General Janet Reno rejected calls for her to
apologize to Lee, a former Los Alamos scientist. He was freed on
Wednesday after pleading guilty to a single count of what had been
a 59-count felony indictment that accused him of illegally putting
at risk vital atomic secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In comments to reporters, Clinton said he had long questioned
whether prosecutors had adequate grounds to keep Lee in jail for
nine months awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had reservations about the claims that were being
made denying him bail,'' Clinton said. ``So the whole thing was
quite troubling to me and I think it's very difficult to reconcile
the two positions that one day he's a terrible risk to the national
security and the next day they're making a plea agreement for an
offense far more modest than what had been alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can justify in retrospect keeping a person
in jail without bail when you're prepared to make that kind of
agreement,'' the president said, speaking with reporters outside
the White House after a speech. ``It just can't be justified and so
I too am quite troubled by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if would consider a pardon for Lee, Clinton was
noncommittal but expressed sympathy for Lee, saying the scientist
had been detained for ``a bailable offense, and it means he spent a
lot of time in prison that any ordinary American wouldn't have and
that bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said the attorney general would not
respond publicly to the president's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier, Reno expressed no regrets over the government's
tactics even though the judge in the case, James A. Parker of U.S.
District Court in Albuquerque, said the nuclear scientist deserved
an apology for harsh treatment that had ``embarrassed this entire
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said, ``I think Dr. Lee had the opportunity from the
beginning to resolve this matter and he chose not to and I think he
must look to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with reporters, Reno said she wished ``with all my
heart and soul'' that Lee had agreed earlier to provide
investigators with information, which he must do as part of the
plea agreement, about seven missing computer tapes onto which he
transferred nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Lee, Mark Holscher, said in an interview that Lee
had offered in December to cooperate as part of plea deal, a point
Parker also made in his scathing comments about the prosecution.
But, Holscher said, the government never responded.
</P>
<P>
   Neither White House or Justice Department officials would say
whether Clinton and Reno ever discussed the logistics of Lee's
confinement or other legal aspects of the case, although there was
no indication that White House officials ever complained to the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Some law enforcement officials said that they had sought to keep
Lee confined to pressure him into pleading guilty or to confess to
what a number of officials believed, but could never prove _ that
he was a spy for Beijing. The officials now acknowledge that those
tactics were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, suggested Thursday that
the president would order a review of the government's handling of
the case. ``He'll be looking for some answers to how this came
about,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lockhart seemed to soften Clinton's words,
saying later that the president's comments were not intended ``as a
blanket criticism of anyone.'' He also said in an interview that
the president retained confidence in Reno.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The president's blunt remarks on the Lee case seemed certain to
heighten the furor over a case that, with its sudden collapse, has
turned into a major embarrassment for Reno and other officials who
favored the indictment, including FBI Director Louis J. Freeh and
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said Thursday in a statement, ``While there are some
regrettable aspects about the way the case unfolded, the bottom
line remains that Dr. Lee committed very serious security
violations involving our nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   While Reno was named to her post by President Clinton, any
direct involvement by the White House in discussions about whether
and how to prosecute Lee would have been unusual. The department is
supposed to operate independently from White House in prosecutorial
matters, and Clinton's aides stayed out of such matters, since they
had been criticized for involvement in an inquiry that followed
death of Vincent Foster Jr., a deputy White House counsel who took
his own life in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, national security officials at the White House did
know in advance about the lengthy felony indictment of Lee without
raising apparent objections.
</P>
<P>
   Several days before Lee was charged in December 1999, Reno,
Richardson and Freeh met with senior intelligence officials at the
White House to discuss the security implications of the case, among
them Samuel R. Berger, President Clinton's national security
adviser, and George J. Tenet, the director of central intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress, some of whom once complained that the
government had moved to slowly in the case, shifted gears in
aftermath of the plea bargain to urge an inquiry into the
government's conduct. Senate hearings will begin later this month
chaired by Arlen Specter, a Republican Senator from Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The government's decision to abandon a case that prosecutors had
once compared to nuclear espionage shattered an uneasy calm that
had settled over the Justice Department and the FBI in the waning
months of the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Freeh, whose once close relationship has frayed over a
series of internal battles, many of them involving questions over
the need for independent prosecutors in cases involving the White
House, were forced once again to close ranks and defend their
actions. Freeh, in Moscow on Thursday to attend meetings with
Russian law enforcement officials, refused to discuss the Lee case
when asked about it by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI is expected to conduct a review of the case. Law
enforcement officials said Thursday that Freeh, a former federal
judge, had instituted a policy of conducting internal inquiries
when its agents are criticized by federal judges.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released after the guilty plea, Freeh said Lee
had pleaded guilty to a serious offense. Freeh said much of the
information that Lee removed from Los Alamos was highly sensitive,
disputing some weapons experts who have said the government vastly
exaggerated the sensitivity of the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some of the information was not classified,'' Freeh's
statement said, ``the government was prepared to prove that much of
it was highly classified nuclear weapons information.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lee had to concede in his plea deal that the
government had been justified in investigating the downloading, he
has also decided to take legal action against the government, Brian
Sun, one of his lawyers, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, will revive a civil suit he filed against the Energy
Department, accusing the department of violating his privacy by
releasing a large amount of confidential information on his
background and its investigation of suspicions that he had spied
for China.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed last December in U.S. District Court in
Washington, but the judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, decided that it
would have to wait for the end of Lee's criminal case, a common
practice. Sun said that, with the criminal prosecution concluded,
the family wants to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is trying to win monetary damages from the government , but
perhaps more important, Sun said, the family hopes to use the suit
to obtain documents from the government on why Lee was singled out
for prosecution in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers had claimed that Lee had been unfairly singled out
for prosecution largely because he is Asian American. In one of the
most important successes scored by the defense, the federal judge
handling the case, James A. Parker, ordered the government to hand
over most of the documents so he could decide whether to give to
the defense so they could try to prove their claim.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting Lee's guilty plea Wednesday, Parker suggested that
he felt it was unfortunate that he would not be able to review the
documents because the criminal case was over.
</P>
<P>
   Sun said that he was exploring whether he could seek the
documents in the civil suit, since Lee's plea said he ``waives any
right to additional disclosure from the government in connection
with the guilty plea.'' The judge in the civil case will probably
have to decided whether the documents are connected to the plea.
</P>
</TEXT>
