<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5923 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-A     09-14 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN-ART-465(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLINTON CAMPAIGN, A TESTED TECHNIQUE: A WAR ROOM, BY ANY OTHER
NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT40 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a windowless, unmarked room on the third floor
of an office building across the street from Madison Square Garden.
The shabby office, five flights down from Hillary Rodham Clinton's
campaign headquarters, is scattered with desks, computer terminals,
televisions, hanging cable wires and telephones. There is at least
one campaign official posted there 24 hours a day, monitoring the
television news, wire services, newspapers, the Internet and,
ultimately, the campaign activities of Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   At the direct request of Clinton and one of her longtime
advisers, James Carville, the signature campaign tactic that helped
President Clinton win the White House has quietly found its way to
the campaign for Senate in New York. Clinton has opened what in
1992 was called a war room by Clinton's advisers, though her aides
this time have pointedly declined to use that name, because it
might remind voters of what some consider an unseemly side of the
Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is called, the result is a political boiler room
teeming with about a dozen people who research Lazio's background
and record, write Clinton's policy pronouncements and, most
important, seek to influence the news coverage of Clinton's
campaign for Senate, mostly through an insistent barrage of e-mails
intended to advance the first lady and undercut Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked that it be created after her campaign was engulfed
for three days in July by a charge that she voiced an anti-Semitic
slur against a former colleague in 1974, and Clinton's aides
debated how to deal with publicizing her denial.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, who had been Clinton's ubiquitous spokesman and
who is an advocate of aggressive and fast-paced politicking, was
dispatched from the eighth-floor headquarters to run the operation
with Neera Tanden, the campaign's policy director.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, standing outside a diner in South Buffalo where
Clinton was greeting voters, Wolfson could be heard on his cellular
phone overseeing the production of a ``debate scorecard'' that
compiled newspaper reports on voter reactions to the Senate debate
on Wednesday, in an effort to show that some viewers thought that
Clinton had won.
</P>
<P>
   The, um, whatever room _ ``Well, it's not a peace room,''
Wolfson said archly _ had the scorecard in reporters' e-mailboxes
before lunch, when the campaign calculated that reporters were
making judgments about post-debate articles.
</P>
<P>
   For a campaign that has been criticized by Democrats for being
factionalized and as slow as an ocean liner (her decision to visit
a diner in South Buffalo Thursday morning was arranged only 12
hours earlier), the war room has emerged for many Democratic
leaders as a model of efficiency and, they hope, ruthlessness.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And it has prompted Lazio to step up his own rapid response
operation, which he put on strong display at the debate. Although
it is not as concentrated or intense as Clinton's, it took the art
of response to a whole new level Wednesday night. It fired off 10
e-mails, offering a running rebuttal of Clinton's remarks to
reporters, many of whom were online during the debate. (``False
Clinton Charge: At 7:17 p.m., Hillary Clinton claimed Rick Lazio
voted to cut 100,000 police,'' one of the e-mails announced,
proceeding to offer evidence to the contrary.)
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, who is intensely competitive, reacted glumly upon
learning about Lazio's high-tech operation. He noted that Clinton's
campaign had managed to get a response out to Lazio's debate
performance before the candidates even walked into the studio. It
was called a pre-buttal edition.
</P>
<P>
   This is, in truth, more than a matter of games that campaign
consultants play. There are some implications that are broader than
the efficiency of both candidates in getting out their positions
and undercutting their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates tend to benefit when the public _ and, not
insignificantly, other politicians and the news media _ perceive
that they are running a strong, confident campaign. Until the
debate on Wednesday, Republicans were raising questions about the
competence of Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Lazio's aides took issue with the notion that his
campaign was not as nimble as Clinton's. ``Let's put it this way:
We have an operationally very tight campaign, and we have a big
room with desks in it,'' said Mike Murphy, Lazio's senior campaign
consultant. ``But we don't go around having to call it a war room
and trying to make ourselves feel good about ourselves.'' He mocked
the Clinton effort as ``lots of people high-fiving each other and
towel-snapping and feeling really good about themselves while Rome
burns.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Clinton's advisers were wary of drawing too
much attention to the operation, for fear that it would underline
the Clintons' reputation of being bellicose. Carville, in
particular, has written the book on the war room _ or, more
precisely, the movie, since the one he set up with George
Stephanopoulos in 1992 was the subject of a documentary. He even
set one up in Israel when he served as consultant to Ehud Barak
when Barak was elected prime minister in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The War Room has become sort of a trademark,'' Carville said
Thursday, discussing its latest incarnation in New York. ``We
needed a way to get things out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hillary Clinton campaign, Carville said, ``was small-d
democratic. And in a democracy, autocratic campaigns work better
than a democratic campaign. You can notice the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there have been several instances when the work of the
war room has shaped the daily flow of the campaign. There is, on
one wall of the room, a blow-up of a Daily News headline that
reads, ``Lazio Tax Plan Doesn't Add Up.'' It is, in effect, a
testament to what Clinton's aides view as one of their bigger
accomplishments: within two hours of Lazio's offering up his tax
plan, Tanden prepared a detailed response that used congressional
cost estimates to argue that he was drastically understating its
cost. That assertion was backed up by a number of critical
newspaper and magazine articles.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Clinton's aides were visibly relieved on Tuesday
night when the primary returns showed that Clinton had won 82
percent of the vote over an unknown challenger, Mark McMahon, a
Manhattan surgeon. A double-digit showing by an unknown challenger
could have been seized by Lazio as evidence of Clinton's
unpopularity even among New York Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   However, the war room, as part of its daily procedure, monitored
interviews that Bill Dal Col, the Lazio campaign manager, gave to
small radio stations upstate. In one of those interviews, Dal Col
made the offhand observation that Clinton would be in trouble if
her primary opponent got 30 percent or more, a generous prediction
that would surely have been lost had Clinton's aides not made sure
to share that particularly high number with any reporter writing a
story on the race.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible edge of the effort is the use of e-mail. On any
given day, the two campaigns dispatch a dozen e-mail messages each,
spotlighting negative information about the opponent, or
highlighting some new proposals about each campaign. In a sort of
political incarnation of ``Spy vs. Spy,'' both campaigns have
managed to sneak their way onto their opponent's e-mail list _
aides to Lazio and Clinton declined to reveal how, or what address
they were using _ which guarantees an even faster and more furious
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me how much everything has changed since 1998
because of e-mail,'' said Michael Marr, a spokesman for Lazio who
worked for Gov. George E. Pataki's re-election campaign. ``Now
 &UR; everything &LR;  is e-mail. This is a cycle where e-mail has both
defined and changed things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
