<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE'S RESULTS FOR QUARTER BEAT ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oracle Corp. posted fiscal first-quarter results
Thursday that handily surpassed Wall Street estimates. The company
also announced a 2-for-1 stock split, the 10th since Oracle's
initial public offering in March 1986.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Aug. 31, Oracle reported earnings of $501
million, or 17 cents a share, more than double the $237 million, or
8 cents a share, it posted in the period a year earlier. Revenue
grew 14 percent, to $2.26 billion. Sales of database software beat
projections, while those for applications software grew less than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Oracle to earn 13 cents a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Before Oracle announced its results, its shares closed at
$84.94, up $3.13. In after-hours trading, shares slipped as low as
$82.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strong quarter, spectacular in margins, very
strong in database and a little lighter than hoped in
applications,'' said Robert Austrian, an analyst with Banc of
America Securities. He said the best of the fiscal year was ahead
and that ``investors will be pretty pleased.'' He added that
``investors with just a little bit of memory will recall'' that
last year's first quarter ``was pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter has historically been weak for Oracle, based
in Redwood City, Calif., and the company fell short of estimates
last year. Facing numerous hostile questions from securities
analysts, Larry Ellison, Oracle's chairman and chief executive,
said at the time: ``One quarter does not make a trend. Place your
bets, gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison sounded a different note Thursday after a year in which
the growth of the Internet bolstered sales of both the company's
core database products and its suite of business applications.
Oracle has also used Internet applications internally to trim $1
billion from expenses. First-quarter operating profit margin
increased 11.7 percentage points _ to 29.1 percent from 17.4
percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are off to our fastest start in six years,'' Ellison said.
``The spectacular growth in our database business demonstrates that
we are continuing to take market share from IBM and Microsoft.
We're not losing any deals to Microsoft at all, and very few to
IBM.''
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said sales of its applications software increased 42
percent, to $156 million, while database software sales grew 32
percent, to $585 million. Oracle no longer breaks out application
sales by category because it is trying to sell most customers the
complete suite, although customers pay only for the portions they
use. Total software license revenue was up 28 percent, to $807
million, while total service revenue increased 8 percent, to $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions about the slower-than-expected growth in
applications, Ellison said the sales cycle of the applications
suite was longer than for the database software and required
approval from a higher level of management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not close as much of it as we thought'' in the first
quarter, ``but we have tremendous momentum'' going into second
quarter, he said, adding that the second quarter would be
``spectacular.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
