<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBLICAN-AD-MAKER-N     09-14 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-AD-MAKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTER OF GOP POLITICAL ATTACK ADS IS UNDER ATTACK HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even in the spike-elbowed world of political
consulting, Alex Castellanos, the chief advertising architect for
the Republican National Committee, stands out as a uniquely bad-boy
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these highlights from his long resume:
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, at the age of 30, Castellanos produced campaign spots
for Sen. Jesse Helms, the conservative North Carolina Republican,
that political scientists still consider trend-setting in their
harsh tone and ominous sound tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he created for Helms what is widely viewed as one of
the most racially charged political commercials ever, with white
hands crumpling a job rejection letter while a narrator criticizes
Helms' black opponent, Harvey Gantt, for supporting ``racial
quotas.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1996, Bob Dole's presidential campaign canceled
commercials produced by Castellanos because campaign officials
considered them overly caustic in accusing President Clinton of
lying.
</P>
<P>
   Now Castellanos' work is under sharp scrutiny again. This week,
Democrats attacked the Republicans for running a commercial
produced by Castellanos that fleetingly featured the word ``rats''
in large, white letters. The image was a fragment of the word
``bureaucrats'' in a commercial criticizing Vice President Al
Gore's prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
   The episode created a major distraction for the party's
presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who was
repeatedly questioned by reporters about the spot over two days.
And it nearly cost Castellanos his job. (Republican Party officials
now say they believe he did not intentionally use the word, and he
will continue making hard-edged commercials for them. The
commercial is no longer running.)
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Thursday evening, a clearly agitated
Castellanos again asserted that the word ``rats'' was an accident
and bitterly complained that someone _ he would not say who _ was
out to get him fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone's decided I need to be brushed aside, and they've put
a bull's eye on my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Castellanos was little known to the broader public before
this week, he has long been viewed by political professionals as a
master of brass-knuckles campaigning. And this week, many of those
professionals said they were not surprised to hear that Castellanos
was under scrutiny again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he probably has less restraint than most people in
this business,'' said David Paletz, a professor of political
science at Duke University who has studied political
advertisements, including those produced by Castellanos. ``It's not
a profession of gentlemen. But he seems to me to be more willing to
go for the jugular than most, and to slit a few other veins along
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Castellanos has defended the value of attack
advertising, once saying, ``The truest spots, most factual spots,
are the negative and comparative.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, he again defended advertisements that draw sharp
contrasts, saying, ``At the end of the day we have an obligation to
let voters know the differences.'' He added, ``If I can help people
understand that, it's a good day for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Castellanos came to America when he was 6 years old when his
family fled Cuba and settled in North Carolina. He often tells
people that his conservatism and dislike of government regulation
are rooted in his experiences growing up in a Communist country.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of North Carolina,
Castellanos came under the tutelage of Arthur Finkelstein, a
prominent New York media consultant known for hard-hitting
campaigns, who recruited Castellanos to work on campaigns for Sen.
Alfonse M. D'Amato, Helms and other conservative politicians.
Working with Michael Murphy, another young strategist, Castellanos
produced commercials for Helms in his 1984 re-election campaign
against Gov. James B. Hunt Jr. of North Carolina that political
scientists say pioneered attack techniques for a new generation of
consultants. Among the the techniques: Using dark colors, harsh
sounds, sinister music and strong words, particularly ``liar,'' to
paint a threatening picture of an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a leader in what I called hard-sell negative
advertising,'' said Montague Kern, a journalism professor at
Rutgers University who devoted a chapter in her 1989 book,
``30-Second Politics,'' to the Hunt-Helms race. ``There was a time
in the 1970s when people thought negative campaigning didn't work.
The 1984 Helms-Hunt race disproved that.''
</P>
<P>
   After helping on George Bush's 1988 presidential campaign,
Castellanos returned to Helms' payroll in 1990 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But early in the 1996 campaign, Helms released Castellanos and
pulled one of his spots off the air after a Democratic candidate,
Charlie Sanders, challenged its veracity. The advertisement had
accused the Democrat of supporting affirmative action and gay
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Castellanos said that he was fired because he opposed attacking
Sanders. And he defended the advertisement's accuracy. ``I fight
hard but I fight fair,'' he said. ``And sometimes I've lost because
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That would not be the last time a Castellanos commercial would
be canceled by one of his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bob Taft's campaign for governor in Ohio pulled an
advertisement produced by Castellanos after the Ohio Elections
Commission determined it had falsely accused the Democratic
candidate of cutting crimefighting employees while serving as state
attorney general. It was the first time the commission had
reprimanded a candidate for governor for violating state election
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Bush intervened to kill a Republican Party
advertisement developed by Castellanos because he thought the spot
used misleading quotes to attack Gore's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Castellanos devised a commercial for then Sen. Lauch
Faircloth, R-N.C., that attacked the Democratic candidate, John
Edwards, for being a high-paid trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a version of the commercial that was recorded off the
television by the Edwards campaign and provided to The New York
Times by Democratic officials, a woman's voice can be barely heard
in the background saying, as if on a telephone answering machine:
``Valerie? It's mom. Are you all right?''
</P>
<P>
   Edward's most famous case involved a young girl named Valerie
Lakey who was seriously injured after being trapped on a swimming
pool drain. The Edwards campaign took the tape to a television
station, only to find that its version of the commercial lacked the
background voice. So they dropped the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Castellanos suggested that the Democrats had
doctored the video, saying, ``I have never made a spot with
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School of
Communication at the University of Pennsylvania, said that
Castellanos used a technique she called ``priming'' in his 1990
``white hands'' commercial to incite racial fears.
</P>
<P>
   In the spot, the job rejection letter has a black mark in the
margin that viewers in a focus group Jamieson conducted interpreted
as a black hand, she said. Jamieson said her analysis of the 1990
advertisement has led her to conclude that Castellanos purposely
inserted the word ``rats'' into his recent spot. ``He's done it
before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Castellanos replied, ``Kathleen Hall Jamieson, bless her sweet
heart, is overanalyzing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000914.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-14 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-340&AMP;ADD-     09-14 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MOVES TO REVIVE MIDEAST TALKS BUT PLAYS DOWN PROSPECTS FOR
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Clinton administration moved Thursday to
reopen peace talks between Israelis and Palestinians at an informal
working level in New York, but Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright played down prospects that progress would be substantial
enough to lead to an accord in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discussion will continue, and we will pursue the same
agenda that we have been pursuing, fully aware of the fact that
time is short,'' Albright said. She spoke at a news conference at
the United Nations, after a working lunch with representatives of
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we have learned is that the talks are moveable,''
she said, implying that they would be convened wherever there was
any prospect of success. She stopped well short of saying what the
United States would propose to narrow the gap in this new session.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the Palestinian senior negotiators, Saed Erakat
and Muhammad Dahlan, had just arrived in New York and were meeting
with Dennis B. Ross, who handles complex Middle East negotiations
for the administration. And she said she was meeting the Israeli
foreign minister, Shlomo Ben Ami, separately.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made an all-out attempt in July to bring Prime
Minister Barak and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, together
in the seclusion of Camp David to hammer out the framework of a
peace agreement. But for all the displays of good will, the talks
broke down when the two sides could not agree on the future of
Jerusalem and, to a lesser extent, the fate of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Albright said Thursday: ``Camp David was a watershed. We
started to talk about issues that were never talked about before.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to salvage the momentum of the Camp David meeting,
Clinton held a new round of talks last week in New York, where
Barak and Arafat were attending a summit meeting at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location I don't think is the issue,'' Albright said
Thursday. ``I think we're taking advantage that people are here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, the administration has been unable to make visible new
headway in suggesting new formulas for mutual compromise; in fact,
some officials said the positions on each side had slipped since
Camp David. But Barak and Arafat pledged separately to keep the
talks alive.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have said another Camp David meeting
would be worth convening only if the two leaders appeared close to
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after Arafat returned home, the Palestinian Central
Council agreed to postpone a declaration of a Palestinian state
that they had threatened to make if no progress was achieved with
Israel by Sept.13.
</P>
<P>
   Albright noted with some relief that that deadline had come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian postponement, she said, ``provided some
breathing space for negotiations at a time that we will use very
well in a variety of venues and in a variety of combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reference to time growing short referred to January, when
the Clinton administration steps down. Clinton hoped to cap his
eight years in the White House with a Middle East peace agreement,
a goal that is fast slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also concerned about the political
survival of Barak, who, after defections from his slender majority
government, confronts the possibility of having to call a new
election when the Israeli Parliament returns at the end of October.
Progress in the peace talks would reinforce his claim to stay on as
Israel's leader.
</P>
<P>
   The talks in New York could be moved, Albright said, if ``it's
more a matter of where the critical mass of people is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will obviously be deeply involved in them at the appropriate
times,'' she said. ``And we'll be continuing to meet with one or
the other side in the course of these talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering a question today about the emotional deadlock over the
holy site in Jerusalem that Jews call the Temple Mount and Arabs
call Haram al Sharif, Albright said ``there is a great deal of very
imaginative work going on'' to make both Israelis and Palestinians
feel their needs have been met.
</P>
<P>
   On the broader goal of a Middle East peace accord, she
reiterated her contention that ``neither side can have 100 percent
of what it wants, and we can't come out of this where one side
feels that it has won and the other lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
