A5929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISIN     09-14 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON DENIES REWARDING DONORS WITH WHITE HOUSE STAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton acknowledged Thursday that
supporters of her Senate campaign had spent the night at the White
House and at the Camp David presidential retreat, but she denied
that the visits were rewards for political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have friends and supporters come and spend time with us and
spend the night with us that we are getting to know and who like
spending time with us,'' Clinton said Thursday morning at a
campaign stop in Buffalo, N.Y. ``I don't see what's news about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady shook her head to indicate ``no'' when asked
directly if she or her Senate campaign fund-raisers had offered a
stay in the Lincoln Bedroom or at Camp David as a reward for a
contribution or an enticement to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the White House declined to provide a list of
overnight guests in response to a request from The New York Times.
Officials said Thursday they were preparing a list of overnight
guests, but that it was not yet ready for release.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic fund-raisers have told The Times in recent
days that the Clintons had used overnight stays at the White House
to reward contributors to Clinton's Senate campaign. They said that
Clinton, alarmed by the recent financial success of her Republican
opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, had ordered an acceleration of
fund-raising efforts during a meeting late last week with top
fund-raisers in New York. The meeting was also attended by
President Clinton, fund-raisers said.
</P>
<P>
   A false report by Matt Drudge, the Internet gossip columnist, on
Tuesday night that The Times was suppressing a report on the
overnight stays prompted several media inquiries at the White House
news briefing the following day. Clinton was first asked about the
matter Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio raised a stunning $10.7 million in a 45-day period this
summer, a period in which Clinton raised only $3.3 million in
direct contributions. As of Sept. 1, Lazio had $10.2 million in the
bank; Clinton had $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is totally freaked out about Lazio's money,'' said one
longtime Democratic fund-raiser, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``She wants to make sure there is enough to get us
through November.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold M. Ickes, an adviser to Clinton who is the former White
House deputy chief of staff, declined to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The president has stepped up his efforts on Clinton's behalf as
well, phoning donors to thank them, appearing at several recent
fund-raising events and signing a letter soliciting contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and the first lady, over the last seven and a
half years, have always welcomed their friends and supporters and
political officials from around the country, prominent members of
the arts community, to stay at the White House,'' said Joe
Lockhart, the White House press secretary. ``Within that group,
there certainly have been people who, as their friends, have
supported them financially.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said overnight stays at the White House had never been
promised or given as compensation for a political donation.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly sensitive because President Clinton
was widely criticized for inviting donors to White House coffees,
overnight stays in the Lincoln Bedroom and rides aboard Air Force
One.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lincoln Bedroom was never sold,'' the president said in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
