<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-CONOCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LOOKS INTO WHETHER CONOCO VIOLATED IRAN SANCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Treasury Department is investigating whether a
U.S. oil company, Conoco, violated sanctions in dealing Iran,
Clinton administration officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Conoco helped analyze information collected last year by the
National Iranian Oil Co. in its exploration of the Azadegan field
on the understanding that Conoco would be given priority in
developing the field if it became legal to do so, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of the company, Archie Dunham, has met
Iranian officials on visits to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined to discuss the nature and
scope of the investigation, which The Financial Times reported
Thursday. Conoco has acknowledged its interest in doing business in
Iran but denied that it had violated U.S. law by advising the
Iranian company about its geological discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conoco is mindful of restrictions under U.S. sanctions law and
has at all times fully complied with the law,'' said a spokesman
for Conoco, Carlton Adams, in a statement. ``Conoco would be
delighted to one day help NIOC develop this giant field and
believes it would be in the best interest of the United States for
American companies to be involved. This is why the company has been
outspoken in its opposition to unilateral sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams confirmed that a British subsidiary of Conoco had worked
with Iran on analyzing the Azadegan field, which is estimated to
hold oil reserves of 20 billion to 25 billion barrels. Adams also
said Iran had offered to share the information with Conoco because
``they considered us to be a potential participant in the
development of the field if U.S. sanctions were lifted.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Clinton administration responded to an announcement
that Iran had given Conoco a contract to develop an offshore gas
field in the Persian Gulf by barring the company from proceeding.
Shortly after that, Clinton announced an executive order that
imposed unilateral sanctions on Iran and prohibited U.S. companies
from doing business there.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, the administration has eased some minor
sanctions, allowing, for example, the U.S. purchase of food and
carpets and Iranian purchas of food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential
nominee, nor Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican candidate, has
expressed any intention of lifting economic sanctions against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   When Dick Cheney, the Republican vice-presidential candidate,
was chief executive of Halliburton, the oil-services company in
Texas, he endorsed lifting sanctions against Iran to let U.S. oil
companies conduct business there.
</P>
<P>
   But after Bush had chosen him as his running mate, Cheney told
ABC News that he now agreed with Bush's saying he would leave
sanctions in place. ``If I sign on as his No. 2, so to speak,'' he
said, ``I would expect to make my views known, to express my
thoughts to him privately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
