A5936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FALN-CLEMENCY-NYT &LR;      09-14 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FALN-CLEMENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR LATER, GIULIANI CRITICIZES CLEMENCY FOR PUERTO RICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying that he was noting the first anniversary of
the release from prison of members of a Puerto Rican nationalist
group, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani criticized President Clinton, Vice
President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton for their positions on
the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to point out that this is the one-year anniversary
of one of the most disgraceful things that has happened in the last
100 years by a president of the United States,'' the mayor said
Thursday at a news conference arranged with the Republican National
Committee in City Hall Park.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani criticized Clinton for granting clemency to members of
the group, the FALN, who were released last September 10, and for
trying at the same time to boost Gore's standing with Puerto Rican
voters. He criticized Gore for not taking a position on the issue.
Then he criticized Clinton for changing her position. Last year, in
what the first lady later called an early campaign stumble, Clinton
broke with her husband and said his clemency offer should be
withdrawn. The resulting outcry from Puerto Rican voters went on
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear why Giuliani felt the need to hold a news
conference more than a full year after members of the group had
been released from prison. Rep. Rick Lazio did mention the group in
his debate with Clinton on Wednesday night, in a discussion about
clemency, but did not link his opponent directly to the group.
Democrats happily speculated Thursday that the mayor was eager to
get back into the good graces of the Senate campaign of Lazio, who
replaced Giuliani in the race. On Monday, Giuliani criticized Lazio
for heartily shaking Yasser Arafat's hand during a visit to the
Middle East. Lazio's campaign was not pleased, but Clinton's was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Rudy Giuliani,'' a senior campaign adviser to Clinton
said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that the mayor's criticism of the Clintons and
Gore Thursday had nothing to do with his statements on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy Giuliani's a good Republican,'' said Bill Pascoe, a
spokesman for the Republican National Committee. Both the mayor and
Republican officials said the mayor had long ago offered to speak
out on the issue. Giuliani, a former prosecutor, has been one of
the most vocal critics of Clinton's clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue I felt very strongly about when I was running
for, considering running, involved in the race for the Senate,
whatever you want to describe it, whatever I was doing,'' Giuliani
said. ``So some time ago I said to them, at an appropriate time, I
would like to speak out on this.'' Gore, the mayor noted, was
campaigning in the city Thursday. He added that Republicans ``felt
that this was an appropriate time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
