<HEADER>
A5939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-LEE-RELEASE-INVESTIGA     09-14 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-RELEASE-INVESTIGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION OF LEE HAMPERED BY FEUD BETWEEN THE JUSTICE DEPT. AND
THE FBI
</HEADLINE>
   (With LEE-RELEASE-CLINTON, LEE-RELEASE-ASSESS) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Assailed by President Clinton and the federal judge
who presided over the nuclear secrets case of Wen Ho Lee, Attorney
General Janet Reno and the FBI director, Louis Freeh, are once
again under the hot glare of criticism for their handling of an
important criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his remarks Thursday, and Judge James Parker, in his
comments on Wednesday, focused their complaints on the government's
demands that kept Lee in pretrial detention for nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism of federal authorities comes after years of
conflict and tension between the Justice Department and the FBI
about how to obtain evidence in a case that began as an
investigation into suspicions that China had obtained atomic
secrets through espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said neither Reno nor Freeh was
directly involved in the decisive early phase of the investigation,
an absence that some officials said had contributed to the problems
that led to the collapse of the case against Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints also come at a time when battles over other
issues, like campaign finance, have driven a wedge between Reno and
Freeh, who deeply embarrassed the attorney general by urging the
appointment of an independent counsel to investigate possible
violations of political fund-raising laws.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton said he was ``quite troubled'' by Lee's
detention in light of the government's willingness to accept a
guilty plea to a single count of mishandling classified material.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the government's actions were a national
embarrassment. ``I feel I was led astray'' by federal prosecutors
and the FBI, he said at the hearing on Wednesday, when Lee was
freed.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said they had portrayed Lee as ``a danger to the safety
of this nation'' who should not be released.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the Justice Department had feuded over the Lee case
for years, but it was the bureau's suspicion that Lee was a spy for
Beijing that drove the inquiry forward as an espionage case. The
bureau's hand was strengthened by Energy Department officials eager
to counteract the impression that the agency had failed to impose
strict security procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Agents focused on Lee in May 1996 after an internal review at
the Energy Department determined that he was a chief suspect among
a dozen people who might be responsible for China's presumed theft
of a design for the highly advanced W-88 thermonuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, Justice Department officials refused to authorize
an application for a warrant to monitor Lee electronically under
the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act. The department refused
to seek a wiretap on grounds that FBI agents had produced only
sketchy information that the scientist had engaged in spying.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the FBI and the Justice Department said the dispute
over the wiretap was a crucial disagreement, but one in which
neither Reno nor Freeh became involved, even though serious
espionage cases involving U.S. citizens are almost always brought
to the attention of the attorney general and the FBI director.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after some law enforcement officials said that the
warrant would have enabled them to prove or disprove the
allegations against Lee, Reno complained that she was not advised
of the dispute over the wiretap and said that Freeh should have
discussed the matter with her. But FBI officials said Freeh was not
aware of it either.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to tap Lee's phones, the bureau resorted to other
tactics. An agent posing as a Chinese intelligence officer
approached Lee, but the scientist rebuffed the overture to spy for
Beijing. Suspicions lingered, however.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, FBI agents searched Lee's office computer, finding that
he had downloaded from a classified to a unclassified computer
system thousands of lines of secret computer codes _ the
information that he was finally charged with mishandling.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to charge Lee with multiple felonies in what became
a 59-count indictment was agreed upon by officials at the Justice
Department in Washington, prosecutors in New Mexico and the FBI.
Freeh supported the indictment, which was ultimately approved by
Reno.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2251EDT &QL; 
