<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COLGATE-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      09-14 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLGATE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLGATE SHARES DROP 16 PERCENT AFTER REPORTS BY ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Colgate-Palmolive tumbled nearly 16 percent Thursday
after analysts expressed doubts that the company would meet sales
targets, citing the yearlong plunge in the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbornly high petroleum prices, meanwhile, are expected to
limit Colgate's ability to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent quarters, Colgate, the maker of America's best-selling
toothpaste and dishwashing liquid, has been a bastion of strength
in the consumer products industry, consistently meeting and
exceeding analysts' forecasts at a time when some of its principal
competitors _ including Procter &AMP; Gamble, Clorox, and Dial _ have
repeatedly warned of lethargic sales. As a result, investor
enthusiasm for Colgate has surged, propelling its stock price to 35
times earnings as of Wednesday, up to 60 percent higher than others
in the category, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But after Colgate executives discussed operations with several
analysts on Wednesday, they began predicting that sales would fall
short.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Shore, an influential analyst with Deutsche Banc Alex.
Brown, said that the company's third-quarter results ``will signal
a reversal of fortune.'' Shore downgraded the company's stock from
``buy'' to ``market perform,'' unleashing a sell-off that clipped
nearly $5 billion from Colgate's market value before lunch. Shares
of Colgate dropped $8.81 to $47.38, and other consumer products
stocks fell, as well, on word of the downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Mark, Colgate's chairman and chief executive, issued a
midday statement saying the company expected to meet analysts'
earnings expectations, but that did little to reverse the stock's
slide. Though Colgate may report high earnings this quarter,
analysts fear that the company will have to tap into its reserves
and cut back on expenses like advertising to do so, moves that
would hurt its future prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated that, even if temporary, the company's
dip in stock price could make it an acquisition target for overseas
companies looking to break into the American market. Both Henkel,
the giant German consumer products giant, and Kao, Asia's
powerhouse in the industry, are seeking a foothold in the United
States. Marketing their own products here would be futile, analysts
say, because Americans are fiercely loyal to the brands they
recognize, so a takeover of a momentarily rattled company might be
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Thursday's decline, Colgate's stock price is high
enough to dissuade a potential acquirer, some analysts said. Yet
the challenges facing Colgate appear to be long term, so Colgate's
stock could remain under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Like its rivals, Colgate is hurt by high fuel prices, which
increase shipping costs. Colgate also uses oil-based resins in
packaging for its products. But the company has a difficult time
passing rising expenses on to consumers, because increasingly
powerful retailers like Wal-Mart and Costco tend to compete on
price. Moreover, the big retail chains are bringing out more
products of their own, presenting yet another set of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Colgate has managed to use aggressive marketing to
withstand industry pressures, and even gain on its rivals. Colgate
toothpaste now outsells Crest, and Palmolive dishwashing soap beats
Dawn in sales, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Colgate-Palmolive has also been buffered by the dominant market
position of its Hill Science Diet pet food, a high-end product
found in specialty retail stores like Petco and Petsmart. But
analysts fear Hill Science's sales growth will reach a plateau now
that Procter &AMP; Gamble has started selling its premium Iams pet food
in supermarkets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
