A5942 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-AIKMAN-INJURY-TEX     09-14 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AIKMAN-INJURY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' AIKMAN REMAINS IN LIMBO FOR REDSKINS GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A ``frustrated'' Troy Aikman practiced in pads
Thursday, looked sharp on his throws but remained in limbo about
his playing status for Monday night's Cowboys-Redskins game at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' 33-year-old quarterback cited what he called
``still some concern'' about his medical progress, 12 days after
receiving the eighth known concussion of his NFL career. Aikman
said Monday that he planned to play and that he expected to have a
medical OK before today.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman practiced the past two days, mindful that the team had an
extra day to prepare this week. He worked for two hours with the
starters and took as many reps or more Thursday as backup Randall
Cunningham and third-stringer Clint Stoerner combined.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J.R. Zamorano, team physician and internist, was on hand to
observe Aikman. Owner Jerry Jones, personnel director Stephen Jones
and Zamorano conversed throughout practice.
</P>
<P>
   After practice, Aikman went inside for 10 minutes, then returned
to tell local media: ``I've gotten some good work in the last two
days. We're still evaluating exactly where I am \Rmedically\S. This
evaluation process is obviously the reason why we haven't come to a
clear-cut answer yet. ``I thought I would've had an answer for you
today. It just has not been quite that clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who has had three known concussions in his past 10
starts, wouldn't say if he is still experiencing headaches or any
post-concussion symptoms. He has agreed to keep medical details
between himself and his doctors for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being honest with the doctors and trying to be honest with
myself,'' said Aikman, who admitted to being unsure what he should
do Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones said, ``We're continuing to evaluate and look at
Troy's symptoms ... not his play, but his symptoms. No decision has
been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was sacked four times and knocked down four other times
during a frenzied 15-play sequence against the Philadelphia Eagles
on Sept. 3, before leaving the game in the second quarter. On
Sunday, he dressed in street clothes and watched from the sideline
in Arizona as Cunningham made his first start in a Cowboys uniform.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the Cowboys would be
better-served not tipping their hand as to which quarterback will
start Monday, especially with Aikman and Cunningham having such
dissimilar styles.
</P>
<P>
   Why give the heavily favored Redskins a hint on which one to
prepare for?
</P>
<P>
   At one point Thursday, Aikman said: ``I'd like to be a little
more committal. But, I don't know, it's something we're taking a
lot of time in making a decision on. It's not easy. It's not
clear-cut. It's not real black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the nature of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Since November, Aikman has visited neurologists on both coasts,
specialists in sports-related head trauma. In learning about
concussions, Aikman has been told that the human brain is the
``last frontier'' in medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who turns 34 in November, pointed to back-to-back
concussions last season (Oct. 31 at Indianapolis and Nov. 8 at
Minnesota), after which he sat out the next two games, and said:
``What took place last year is why there is extra precaution now.
My age and this stage of my career probably has instigated this as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, said Aikman, ``in the past, I recovered much quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only the second time in his career that Aikman has
missed a game or more after a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating not getting to play,'' said Aikman, referring
to an 0-2 start and high expectations for an offense that was
derailed in the opener and _ adding injury to insult _ lost Joey
Galloway to a season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard,'' Aikman said of his own situation. ``The fact
that there is some concern has made this week even more
frustrating. I'm trying to make as informed a decision as possible.
I appreciate that the organization is approaching it in the same
manner.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
