<HEADLINE>
FORWARD COMMITS TO USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The player at the center of NCAA and Pacific-10
Conference investigations into allegations of wrongdoing within the
USC basketball program has given the Trojans an oral commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Dupree, a 6-foot-7 forward who played at College of
Southern Idaho last season, committed to USC after receiving a
scholarship offer provided he can academically qualify to the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree - now attending San Bernardino Valley College - probably
won't know until next spring or summer whether he will be
academically accepted into USC.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree gained notoriety last month, when College of Southern
Idaho coach Derek Zeck claimed USC assistant Dave Miller offered
Zeck money to help recruit Dupree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'll write you a check to donate to your booster
club to recruit and get Jerry,' '' Zeck said. ``I said 'I don't do
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Dupree both denied any offer was made, and USC coach
Henry Bibby has termed the allegations ``totally false.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators from the NCAA and Pac-10 have
interviewed Bibby, Miller and USC assistant coach Silvey Dominguez
regarding the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ongoing at this point,'' Pac-10 assistant commissioner
Jim Muldoon said regarding the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dupree is the fourth player to commit to the Trojans, and would
take their last available scholarship. USC has also received
commitments from twin brothers Errick and Derrick Craven of Bishop
Montgomery High in Torrance and 6-11 center Rory O'Neil of
Burroughs in Ridgecrest.
</P>
</TEXT>
