<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DEION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COWBOYS, DEION FADE, REUNION LOSES ITS LUSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If Deion Sanders is involved, it's never simple.
</P>
<P>
   Five glorious and sometimes controversial years with the
league's preeminent cornerback/punt returner/self-promoter taught
the Cowboys as much.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas running back Emmitt Smith makes sense when he maintains
that Monday night's matchup pitting the Cowboys (0-2) and Sanders'
Redskins (1-1) ``ain't got nothing to do with Deion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't add anything,'' Smith said. ``He is just playing
for the team we are playing against. Period. Our focus is getting a
win against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But this game isn't about level-headed logic.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Prime Time'' in prime time against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It's Sanders against his former teammates for the first time
since Dallas dropped him in the off-season because of salary-cap
constraints and injury concerns. He promptly signed a seven-year,
$56 million contract with hated rival Washington, predicting doom
for the Cowboys and triumph for the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make comedian Dennis Miller's melodramatic
presence in the broadcast booth redundant.
</P>
<P>
   So, while many in the Cowboys organization agree with Smith's
reasoning, they also can't deny Sanders' impact on Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion has been a big part of the Cowboys, and he's been a big
part of us winning a Super Bowl and having a good team with him
here,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``I think he brings a little
bit of excitement to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   All week, the Cowboys have watched film of Sanders'
self-described career-worst performance in the Redskins' 15-10 loss
to the Detroit Lions on Sunday. Detroit quarterback Charlie Batch
completed seven passes for 75 yards against Sanders, including four
first downs.
</P>
<P>
   While some saw the performance as evidence of Sanders' declining
athletic ability _ and justification for the Cowboys' decision to
drop him and his exorbitant salary _ Campo said the Cowboys still
have a lot of respect for Sanders. He said they won't be naive
enough to think they can throw to his side of the field with a lot
of success.
</P>
<P>
   However, Campo said the Cowboys won't shy away from him. They
plan to spread the ball around the field.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receivers Wane McGarity and James McKnight can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight said he idolized Sanders growing up _ so much so that
he wore No. 2, Sanders' number at Florida State, in high school.
McKnight, who suffered a season-ending knee injury in training camp
in 1999, never got a chance to face Sanders in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' McKnight said. ``I was a big Deion fan. It was
a disappointment last year with me not playing. It's going to be a
challenge, but I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity faced Sanders in practice and said Sanders helped him
become a better receiver by teaching him what cornerbacks look for.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, I looked forward to going against him
in practice,'' McGarity said. ``I knew it was going to make me
better. I'm definitely looking forward to playing against him. He
taught me a lot. You remember those things when you are out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also remember that Sanders is most dangerous when he
feels he has been slighted. Safety Darren Woodson, who considers
himself one of Sanders' closest friends, said the Cowboys' decision
not to re-sign Sanders will likely fire Deion up as much as last
week's poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably feels he got rubbed a little wrong because of the
way he left,'' Woodson said. ``He's going to give us his ``A''
game. He will put on a show if he gets a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety George Teague agreed, saying ``any dance he has he will
dance a little harder. Any words he wants to say, he will say a
little harder. He's going to be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Cowboys want to see Sanders dance, but they would
happily trade a jig from the NFL's showboat king for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating him doesn't mean as much to me now,'' Teague said.
``We haven't won a game. We just want to win. Being 0-2 takes away
from beating any individual.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
