<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS' SILENCE, AND DEPARTURE, ARE GOLDEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The football gods work in mysterious ways. From season to
season, or even week to week, the gods giveth, or taketh away. Far
be it from me to question their weird whims and strange behavior.
NFL honchos show disrespect to a higher authority by calling what
goes on in the league ``parity.'' You won't hear that here.
</P>
<P>
   Like, how in the heck did the St. Louis Rams win that last Super
Bowl? Because the gods bestowed a blessing upon one of the feeble,
that's how. Maybe they were just bored, and having a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   As you've noticed, however, Valley Ranch hasn't been a godly
destination in some time now. The gods left Irving at about the
same time as The Jimster. Mere coincidence? Don't know, and I also
don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   But this has actually been a week for all of us, and
particularly the Valley Ranch contingent, to count our football
blessings. The gods met among themselves and made the decision to
throw us a small bone. From a football standpoint, the Cowboys
couldn't be worse after two games. Then again, this could have been
a much more miserable week.
</P>
<P>
   Notice how quiet it is up there in Washington?
</P>
<P>
   No loud chirping at all from underneath the do-rag.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are coming, flying into D.C. on Monday night with
both wings on fire and a prayer on all lips. But still, nary a
told-you-so word has been uttered from the normally noisy lips of
Deioness.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what's been observed lately, Mr. Sanders and the
Cowboys have actually been reunited. Both parties have become
shadowy football caricatures of their former selves.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Deion's performance against the Detroit Lions
labeled him, at least based on that game, as the worst $8 million
upfront cash investment in the history of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions sent waves of receivers right at Nine-Toed. Detroit's
game plan was to treat the Wonderful One as if he were, well,
Phillippi Sparks. And they toasted Sanders over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   It was so bad that Deioness was forced to take drastic postgame
measures. How's this for a first: Sanders fingered himself for an
awful game and also for the Lions upsetting the Washingtons.
</P>
<P>
   I loved this self-evaluation from Deioness:
</P>
<P>
   ``When they smell something dead, the buzzards circle.''
</P>
<P>
   In five years with the Cowboys, it was unheard of for Sanders to
even remotely share in the blame for games or seasons gone sour. It
was always the fault of others.
</P>
<P>
   Deion got by on nothing more than reputation his last two
seasons here, something which slipped right past Little Danny
Snyder, boy owner of the Redskins. Snyder just had to have Deion,
even for $8 million upfront.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it was amazing last season, even to Cowboys coaches,
to watch opposing teams purposely stay away from Sanders' side of
the field based on his what-once-was status. Those few clubs who
did attack his corner prospered, but the trend never developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, however, have opened a new sack of snakes for
Sanders. That was too easy last week. Detroit simply went out and
took what they wanted from Sanders, when they wanted it. Lions
quarterback Charlie Batch said afterward that the damage should
have been worse, citing how he twice overthrew open receivers who
were behind Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   It's those mysterious ways again of the football gods. With a
pathetic Cowboys bunch coming to town, Deion could have been
enjoying a feast of words. Instead, the lips are zipped. In fact,
the once famous ``Dallas Week'' in Washington has been reduced to
no more than just another football game. The noncompetitive nature
of the Cowboys could have something to do with that, but mostly
there is sudden panic over the poor play of the Redskins in the
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, had been proclaimed a Super Bowl season in D.C.
Little Danny said so himself.
</P>
<P>
   What the Lions game did indicate was that, while every other
off-season move has exploded on owner Jerry Jones, at least his
decision to part ways with his beloved Deioness was correct and
profitable. Are the Cowboys desperate at cornerback? Yes, at least
at one corner. But their other corner, Ryan McNeil, is holding up
very well, simply because no one throws his way. Even a Ryan McNeil
is ``taking away half the field,'' which used to be what the Deion
apologists would crow about.
</P>
<P>
   Jones listened to his medical reports and his coaches _ instead
of his wayward heart _ in allowing Sanders to walk. The word,
particularly from the medical side, was that Deioness had a
wear-and-tear problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a question about us wanting to bring back
Deion,'' said Jones, ``but what we had to answer was the cost
factor. Seven and eight million dollars \Ron a signing bonus\S just
wasn't right for our salary-cap situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After his Detroit performance, Sanders has all of Washington now
wondering if Jones took the smart way out.
</P>
<P>
   For us, however, all is quiet. Thank you again, football gods.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
