<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-NORTHWESTERN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRED-UP TCU SAFETY SET FOR NORTHWESTERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Linebacker Shannon Brazzell said: ``Don't
know where that came from.'' Many other TCU players thought the
same.
</P>
<P>
   They had just seen the unthinkable. Normally reserved and
level-headed Curtis Fuller, the senior free safety who is the
quarterback of the Horned Frogs' defense, stepped, or more like it,
pranced out of character Saturday against Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   After charging into the Nevada backfield, Fuller chased down
quarterback David Neill and recorded the first sack of his TCU
career. Fuller then got up, walked slowly in large, exaggerated
steps toward the Wolf Pack crowd in the end zone and, like a
helmet-toting librarian, brought his extended index finger to his
face mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just excited,'' Fuller said, laughing. ``You never know
how you're going to react. I think we were a little down at the
time. We needed a little excitement on the defense, something to
talk about, something to get riled up about, so it really wasn't
anything special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little pointing and a `shhhh.' It just said, `We're
here to play. Sort of like saying we're going to silence this
crowd, let's play some defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the sack set up Nevada in a third-and-32, the Wolf Pack
scored its only touchdown two plays later. Regardless, Fuller
thought the Frogs picked up their defensive intensity after his
move. Nevada would score only another field goal, and Neill would
end up being sacked a TCU-record 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who received his psychology degree in May and is
pursuing a master's degree, said the show of emotion was not meant
to show up Nevada. He is just trying to follow coach Dennis
Franchione's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not a vocal guy,'' said Fuller, a Fort Worth
Christian graduate. ``Coach Fran has asked me to be more vocal and
more enthusiastic and do those things on the field. So I'm trying
to take a step in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller figures to be all over the field Saturday against
Northwestern. The Wildcats defeated TCU, 17-7, last year, and
Fuller expects a better Northwestern team for the 11 a.m. kickoff
at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to try to spread us out a little bit more and
try to throw the ball a little better than they did against us last
year, which would allow them to run the ball a little bit better
against us,'' he said. ``They're going to try and be balanced with
their attack, throw the ball to keep us honest and not let us stack
the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it would seem revenge would be on his mind, in addition
to a chance to beat a Big Ten team on national television, Fuller
said: ``I don't put more emphasis on one more than another. I
really don't. It's a big game for us, but yet last week was a big
game for us, and the following week will be a big game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, cognizant of the spotlight of the 20th-ranked
Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will look at us on national TV and see what TCU is
about and how we play football,'' Fuller said. ``I still think
there's a lot of people out there that don't know how we play
football at TCU. It'll give us a little limelight and it will be a
good game, a four-quarter ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   And with more than 30,000 fans in the stands and viewers around
the country watching, does Fuller plan on a new move to get his
troops riled up?
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably won't do anything like that again. A one-time
wonder from Curtis Fuller.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
