<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-SUZUKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS DOUBLES ITS STAKE IN SUZUKI MOTOR TO 20 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKI TANIKAWA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The General Motors Corp. doubled its stake in the Suzuki
Motor Corp. to 20 percent Thursday and GM's top executive joined
Suzuki's board.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced by the two automakers in Tokyo, expanded a
close relationship between them that goes back almost 20 years,
when Suzuki first began supplying small cars to GM, the world's
largest automotive company.
</P>
<P>
   GM is hoping that Suzuki will help increase its share of the
market in Asia, where the automotive industry is expected to grow
the fastest in the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to build on that history of relationship with
General Motors,'' said Osamu Suzuki, chairman and chief executive
of Suzuki, who appeared at a news conference with his GM
counterpart, John F. Smith Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to name Smith as a nonexecutive director of Suzuki,
Suzuki said: ``We wanted someone who could advise us on areas of
strategic importance. We are grateful to get an excellent person.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suzuki-GM deal is the latest in a series of transactions by
foreign automakers to gain a greater presence in Japan.
DaimlerChrysler AG has arranged to take a 34 percent ownership
stake in Mitsubishi Motors.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. has control of the Mazda Motor Corp., and
Renault of France holds a 37 percent interest in the Nissan Motor
Co.
</P>
<P>
   GM also holds stakes in Isuzu Motors Ltd. and Subaru, a unit of
Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. But the GM-Suzuki alliance is
characterized by unusually close personal relations between the two
chairmen, who have known each other since GM and Suzuki first
entered into an alliance in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Takaki Nakanishi, an automotive analyst with Merrill Lynch in
Tokyo, said the choice of Smith as a board member ``showed GM had
no intention to control'' Suzuki management.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki also differs from several of its larger Japanese
competitors in that it is financially strong, unencumbered by heavy
debts or sluggish sales. Digging deep into the small-car niche, it
has carved a firm presence in Japan and overseas markets and has
not lost money since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki and Smith said they considered the relationship a
strategic partnership and that Suzuki would remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a small-car manufacturer like Suzuki was now more
important to GM than ever in its strategy to build a greater
presence in Asian markets, especially after the company lost in a
bidding war with Ford over the acquisition of Daewoo Motors of
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future depends on the success in Asia,'' said Rudolph
Schlais, president of GM's Asia-Pacific operations, who attended
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In an important step toward working cooperatively to expand in
Asia, Suzuki will start manufacturing YGM-1, a jointly developed
minicar between GM and Suzuki, in a plant in Kosai, a city near
Mount Fuji west of Tokyo, in September 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, 70, has been chief executive of Suzuki Motor since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which side first proposed raising the GM stake to 20
percent, Suzuki responded, ``That was done by `a un no kokyu' with
Mr. Smith,'' using a Japanese expression that roughly translates
into they ``knew each other's thoughts without using any words.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
