<HEADLINE>
W. PAGE THOMPSON, 73, FORMER EXECUTIVE IN PUBLISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ W. Page Thompson, an executive in the publishing
industry, died on Sept. 10 in New York. He was 73. The cause of
death was cancer, said his son Page.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson became publisher of American Home magazine in 1972. Two
years later, he became publisher and president of Girl Talk, which
he owned with a partner, Bernice Kennedy. After Girl Talk ceased
publication in 1980, Thompson spent three years at Teen Magazine, a
Scholastic publication, as its advertising director. He started a
media consulting business when he left Scholastic in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson began his publishing career as an advertising director
at Ladies Home Journal in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Pat, of Manhattan, three sons and a
daughter from a previous marriage and five grandchildren. In
addition to his son Page, of Weston, Conn., his children are Steve,
of Barrington, R.I.; Charles, of Carmel, N.Y.; and Mary Embree of
Winnetka, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
