<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM H. PITT, 73, REAL ESTATE EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Conn.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   William H. Pitt, a real estate executive and philanthropist,
died on Sept. 9 at his home in Greenwich, Conn. He was 73 and also
lived in Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He died after a brief illness, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt was born in Stamford, Conn., and established William Pitt
Real Estate Co. there in 1949, after selling theater tickets and
cars. He assisted large companies like GTE, Xerox and Schweppes in
moving to Fairfield County during the 1970s. His company, which is
privately held, now has 18 sales offices around Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   As a philanthropist, he was especially interested in education.
His donations included $3 million in 1996 to Sacred Heart
University, which was one of the largest gifts ever given by an
individual donor to a college or university in Connecticut. The
gift helped build the William H. Pitt Health and Recreation Center
on the university's principal campus, in Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   His other donations included $1 million to Trinity Catholic High
School in Stamford, in memory of his first wife, Theodora Ward
Pitt, who died after 45 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Pauline Baker Pitt and four
stepdaughters, Sandra Pine Doubleday of Hobe Sound, Fla., Hope Pine
Kelly of Darien, Conn., Serena Boardman of Manhattan and Samantha
Boardman, also of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
