<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA POWERS METS OVER EXPOS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For the New York Mets to go deep into the postseason,
Robin Ventura knows that much of the burden will fall on him. No
matter how Mike Piazza is hitting _ and right now, he is not
hitting at all _ Ventura will have to drive in runs because he bats
behind the Mets' cleanup hitter. Teams would rather make Ventura
beat them than let Piazza do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos proved this Thursday night. In the seventh
inning, when Edgardo Alfonzo reached second base on a wild pitch
with Piazza batting, Expos manager Felipe Alou ordered Piazza
intentionally walked.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, whose team trailed by two runs, called for a rookie
left-hander, Sean Spencer, to face Ventura. On Spencer's first
pitch, Ventura rifled a three-run homer to right-center, sending
the Mets and Glendon Rusch to a 10-4 victory that increased their
lead in the National League wild-card race to five games over the
idle Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets remain two games behind the Atlanta Braves in the NL
East. The Braves beat the Florida Marlins Thursday by 5-3, and play
at Arizona this weekend before a three-game series with the Mets in
Atlanta starting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who had two days off this week, partly to work on his
swing, has hit in each of his last three games. Thursday night's
performance was his best: He scored twice and went 3 for 5, just
his third three-hit game of a trying offensive season.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch has received about 3.5 runs per start, and considering
that luck, it is remarkable he does not have a losing record. He
evened his mark at 10-10 Thursday night, and if he wins two more
times this year, he will equal his career victory total over parts
of three seasons with Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was the dark-horse entry in a four-man derby for the fifth
starter's job in spring training, but now the Mets may have to
consider him for a start in the playoffs, should they qualify. The
fourth starter, Bobby J. Jones, has been effective, with a 9-5
record, but Rusch, a left-hander, could match up better against
certain opponents. Rusch, who worked 7 1/3 innings Thursday night,
also has been more consistent, with a 2.70 earned run average over
his last five starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
