<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOME-ARSENAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME SEARCH YIELDS HUNDREDS OF GUNS AND EXPLOSIVES, POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT WORTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOBBS FERRY, N.Y. _ Police officers investigating a burglary
complaint at a home here discovered more than 160 guns, a variety
of explosives and fuses, rocket engines, and at least 150 pounds of
gunpowder, the Westchester County district attorney, Jeanine Pirro,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   James G. Neff, a 38-year-old machinist living at 85 Myrtle
Avenue with his parents, was arrested Thursday and charged with
criminal weapons possession and intent to sell. Both charges are
felonies punishable by up to seven years in prison, and further
charges are expected, Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   The police discovered a book on how to build an atomic bomb,
along with books on building conventional bombs, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was apparently a munitions factory,'' Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   Neff pleaded not guilty at an arraignment in Village Court.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons, which were found throughout the house, included
grenades hollowed out to hold explosives, pipes of various sizes
that had been welded and drilled for use as bombs, fuses, timing
devices, magnets, commercial-grade chemicals, gunpowder and
thousands of rounds of ammunition, including armor-piercing
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Chief George Longworth of the Dobbs Ferry Police Department said
the Westchester County bomb squad was testing the explosives in
Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   The guns included more than 130 rifles and shotguns and 30
handguns. Pirro said they appeared to be unlicensed. Seven
silencers were also found, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember a cache as large as this,'' Pirro said.
``What is unusual is not just the guns but the fact that he was
making guns, silencers, pipe bombs, and hand grenades. There were
chemical explosives that you need only add sugar to that would have
blown up an area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
