<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S DEBATE TACTIC SHAPES NEXT DAY'S CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MRSCLINTON-CAMPAIGN) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULTON, N.Y. _ Fresh from their contentious first debate, the
Senate candidates on Thursday continued firing at one another _
from a distance _ as they sought to capitalize on the momentum they
both claimed from their encounter Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, who embarked on a four-city swing through
western and central New York, defended his televised challenge to
Clinton to sign a pact against the use of unregulated campaign
contributions known as soft money. Pictures of Lazio approaching
Clinton and brandishing a slip of paper emerged as one of the
debate's enduring images, featured prominently in television news
segments and on the front pages of morning newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after greeting patrons at a Buffalo diner Thursday
morning, called Lazio's actions a stunt and belittled him, saying
it reminded her of dealing with her two younger brothers. ``You
just sort of say, `Well, that's fine, but now let's talk seriously
about what we're going to do today and how we're going to get it
done.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made no apologies for his tactics in the debate, brushing
aside complaints from debate organizers that he had violated a rule
against using props. ``The only person who violated the rules was
Mrs. Clinton by not agreeing to what she said she was going to do,
a ban on soft money,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   He also defended his aggressive manner. ``People expect plain
talk,'' Lazio told reporters in Buffalo before beginning his bus
trip, one of several planned in the coming weeks as he steps up his
campaign schedule amid talk from some party leaders that he has had
a lackadaisical pace lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can't take the high horse and then take the low
road,'' he said. ``If you fire at me, you're going to have to
expect to get fired back at.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, his communications director, promised more verbal
warfare. ``This isn't high tea,'' he said. ``It's the Senate race
in New York, and New Yorkers want someone who will fight for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's senior advisers said Lazio may have helped them with
particularly competitive voting blocs. They contended that people,
especially women, saw Lazio's aggressiveness as a form of bullying
that he would not have carried out against a man. ``It just
backfired,'' one adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio rejected that assertion Thursday night after speaking to
dairy farmers near Syracuse, saying that his treatment of Clinton
was meant only to demonstrate the force he would bring to debates
in the Senate. ``You have got to stand up when you are in the
Senate,'' Lazio said. ``No one is going to care if you are a man or
a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Even children, it seemed, paid notice to his style in the
debate, as Lazio discovered during one of his stops, at a new
charter school in Rochester. Lazio, in a speech on education
earlier this week, called for allowing parents more options to
choose schools for their children, including charter schools, which
are public schools given wide latitude from local board regulation.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit to the Charter School of Science and Technology
Thursday, a second-grader asked him: ``Why were you fighting
against Mrs. Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio responded, ``Last night we were on TV and were talking
about different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Fagan, a second-grader who said she had watched the
debate with her father, asked, ``Did you expect her to sign that
paper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really, really did,'' Lazio replied, seated on a child's
chair and leaning toward his questioner, ``and I still do.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are to meet Oct. 8 for another debate, sponsored
by WCBS-TV in New York City; they are negotiating the possibility
of a third encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lazio began his day receiving endorsements from three
Hispanic organizations in Buffalo. He went on to the school, then
to a campaign rally here. He planned to end the day talking to
farmers in Cazenovia, near Syracuse, and to campaign on Long Island
on Friday and upstate again over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after her visit to the diner, flew to New York City to
attend a fund-raiser at Radio City Music Hall with Vice President
Al Gore. On Friday, she plans her first campaign appearance with
Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, the Democratic vice
presidential nominee and someone she is counting on to shore up
support from Jewish voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
