u a BC-NY-BUFFALO-TEACHERS-4     09-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUFFALO-TEACHERS-405&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TEACHERS IN BUFFALO WALK OUT FOR 2nd TIME IN A WEEK  
 By KATE ZERNIKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New York state judge ordered Buffalo's public school teachers
back to their classrooms Thursday after they announced a strike in
the hour before school started for the second time in a weeklong
and increasingly bitter dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 4,000 teachers in the Buffalo school system, the
state's second largest, had returned to classes earlier this week
as a good-faith gesture while strike negotiations continued, and
the school district believed that the two sides were within
whispering distance of a settlement late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But after hundreds of students had already boarded the buses to
school, the Buffalo Teachers Federation announced at 7 a.m.
Thursday that it would strike again; the same timing it used last
Sept. 7, when administrators scrambled to cancel school after the
day had effectively begun for about 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Bus drivers served their routes as usual to tell parents waiting
with their children that school was canceled, and to pick up
children waiting alone to deliver them to school, where officials
called parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the teachers' union to make this decision after the
children were on the buses, and without any warning, it's just,
it's just unbelievable,'' said Marion Canedo, the schools
superintendent and herself a picket-line veteran of a bitter
teachers' strike in 1976. ``The distance we were apart was so
small.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Kevin M. Dillon ordered union officials into state
Supreme Court at midday, then issued a restraining order requiring
the teachers to return to work and the union to return to court on
Monday, when he would hold a contempt hearing. The judge, who said
he grew up in a union family, blasted the union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a father,'' he said, ``I ask how would a Pepsi-Cola worker
on Walden Avenue feel dropping off a child at the bus stop at 7 in
the morning and getting out to work, only to discover the strike
had started?''
</P>
<P>
   There have been relatively few teachers' strikes in New York
state over the last two decades, largely because of the Taylor Law,
which makes it illegal for public employees to strike. But even for
Buffalo, a city with a long history of lawsuits and strikes by the
teachers' union, this dispute has become particularly fierce, with
the city's mayor Thursday accusing the union of ``unconscionable
and selfish'' behavior and the union accusing school officials of
reneging on salary offers made at the negotiating table.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``In the interests of our community and at the request of the
state mediator, Buffalo teachers have gone more than the extra mile
to keep schools open,'' the union said in a statement. ``Because of
the broken assurances of the district and their apparent lack of
authority to negotiate, we have no choice but to request that
Buffalo teachers picket in the Buffalo public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Canedo vehemently denied pulling back any proposals. ``There is
nothing, never, ever, that has been reneged on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The union has been working under an expired contract since June
1999. The primary dispute in negotiations is over salary increases.
But according to the district, the two sides were a mere half
percentage point apart Wednesday night, with the district offering
a 16.5 percent pay raise over four years, and the teachers pushing
for a 17 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the district is asking teachers to accept a
reduction in retirement benefits. Buffalo schools now provide
retiring teachers with lifetime health insurance, at an annual
expense of $10.3 million, but that cost is expected to double over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Maddigan, a spokesman for the district, said the district
was now asking teachers to assume part of those costs, by paying
$675 a year after retirement for health insurance for the first
four years of a new contract, and $1,000 a year after that.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Masiello, who has two children in the schools,
accused the union of striking over petty differences; the last
major strike, in 1976, was over sweeping layoffs and budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect negotiations to be bumpy and difficult, but to
take the kind of action they have is totally inappropriate and
uncalled for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers risk being cited for contempt of court, which could
involve fines or jail time. In addition, school district officials
said, the district now stands at risk of losing $2 million in state
aid for the two strike days.
</P>
<P>
   The district must hold 180 school days as a condition of
receiving state aid, but according to a contract provision that is
not subject to change, Buffalo teachers cannot work more than 42
weeks past Labor Day. With several snow days likely, school
officials said, they may not be able to squeeze in those 180 days
before the teachers' clock runs out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-00 2333EDT &QL; 
