u k BC-EDIT-TV-OLYMPICS-NYT &LR;      09-14 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TV-OLYMPICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TELEVISED OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Sept. 15:
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic Games were first broadcast live, from Cortina
D'Ampezzo, Italy, in the winter of 1956, the final torch-bearer at
the opening ceremony tripped and fell over a television cable laid
across the stadium. There is something deeply emblematic in that
moment. It captures what has been, at times, an awkward synergy
between television and the Olympics. And yet for nearly all of us,
the Olympic experience is fundamentally a television experience,
and it is television revenue that has driven the expansion of the
Games, as it has driven the expansion of all sports.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, CBS paid $50,000 for the American television rights to
the Winter Games in Squaw Valley, Calif., and offered 15 hours of
coverage. For this year's Sydney Olympics, NBC has paid $705
million _ in rights only, not production costs _ and will, with its
cable stations, televise 441{ hours of coverage. That is just
slightly less than the total of all American televised Olympics
coverage between Squaw Valley in 1960 and Sarajevo, Yugoslavia, in
1984. And then there is Internet coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Olympiad after Olympiad, we watch the Games with the mingling of
sophistication and naivete that television always elicits from us.
The intimacy and familiarity one often feels by the third or fourth
night of watching the Olympics is really a measure of the intimacy
Americans feel toward their televisions. The Games have changed in
almost every respect over the past 30 or 40 years. Far more
countries participate. New sports have been added and old ones
dropped. Technology has transformed the Games, changing the way
athletes dress to compete, how they prepare, and the manner in
which they are timed and measured and televised. Yet for many
Americans, the changes in the Olympics are best summed up in the
evolution from Jim McKay to Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   This year, because of the great time difference between
Australia and the United States, there will be no live coverage of
the competition. That will mean a real loss in transmitting the
natural excitement of the Games. What we will get instead from
Sydney is a seamless package of events and features, an oscillation
between tight focus on contests and tight focus on individuals and
their lives _ up close and personal, as ABC taught us to say.
</P>
<P>
   It will be easy to believe that we are learning a lot about
Australia, about team handball, about Marion Jones and her American
and international colleagues. But as always when television is at
the center of our attention, we will mostly be observing events in
a repackaged form that television executives believe caters to the
American taste for celebrity and high drama. Some games, like
baseball and soccer, contain an inherent narrative of their own.
But most Olympic events lack that kind of integral narrative. There
are heats and finals, winners and losers. There is mostly the
extraordinary effort of individuals. What television will bring us
night after night is what it believes we most crave: reality shaped
into one story after another.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
