<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AIRLINE COMPETITION OVER CHINA
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Sept. 15:
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate takes up permanent normal trade relations with
China, the Department of Transportation is on the verge of awarding
an additional U.S. carrier the valuable right to fly to that
nation. Lamentably, the aviation deal negotiated by President
Clinton and Zhu Rongji, China's prime minister, in April 1999 does
not reflect the spirit of the trade agreement. It is so restrictive
that the Transportation Department, for the first time ever in such
a bilateral route-awarding proceeding, is being forced to pick
between cargo and passenger carriers. Chinese negotiators refused
to differentiate between the two.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting apples-or-oranges lobbying fight for the 10 new
weekly flights has been both intense and bizarre, even by
Washington standards. The Teamsters union, while opposing the trade
deal with China, has aggressively lobbied members of Congress and
the White House on behalf of the bid by United Parcel Service. The
company employs some 200,000 Teamsters, and the union is keen on
benefiting from the anticipated explosion of trade that it opposed.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel makes a strong case, because at present FedEx is
the only all-cargo carrier that flies directly from the United
States to China. By contrast, there are six such carriers
authorized to operate between the United States and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Among passenger airlines, Delta's bid to provide daily nonstop
service from New York City to Beijing has the most merit. Delta
would join United, Northwest and three Chinese airlines in
providing service between the two countries, but would be the first
to fly nonstop from the Northeast. Such a route is long overdue.
New York, the world's financial capital and the American city with
the largest Chinese-American community, has 11 weekly direct
flights to Singapore, but none to Beijing or Shanghai. At present,
travelers to Beijing must change planes in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department has been weighing these strong
competing bids for months, and must now decide which company to
give direct access to China, a great asset to a carrier with global
aspirations. The New York Times editorial page has no view on which
bid should prevail, and finds the awarding process an unsettling
reminder of the benefits of deregulating air travel. The fewer such
routes the government awards by decree, the better.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, the restrictive bilateral treaty forces the
government to choose between a second U.S. cargo carrier and a
third airline to China. That is unfortunate. With the advent of
normalized trade relations, the Clinton administration should
revisit this issue and clamor for greater access to China for both
cargo and passengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
