<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DENY WELLS BUT ALLOW CRUZ TO HOMER IN THE 11TH
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If David Wells is going to pitch one game in a
three-game series in New York, some of his old teammates reasoned
Thursday, they would prefer he pitch the last game if they were
trying to beat him. For that would give Wells two days to fully
indulge in some of Manhattan's best liquid cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   But Boomer is unpredictable, David Cone said, grinning. Wells
loves the city, loved playing for the Yankees, and no question,
he's got many friends here willing to buy a round and toast him.
</P>
<P>
   This week was not the best time for Wells to hoist a few, what
with him just one victory shy of collecting his 20th victory for
the first time and with the Toronto Blue Jays teetering on the edge
of the wild card race.
</P>
<P>
   Wells pitched splendidly Thursday night before allowing a homer
to Derek Jeter that tied the game at 1-1 in the eighth. Then, in
the 11th, Jose Cruz Jr., slammed a two-run homer off the
left-hander Randy Choate, and Toronto hung on for a 3-2 victory at
Yankee Stadium that prevented the Yankees from sweeping the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, leading Boston by eight games in the American
League East, open a four-game series here with Cleveland Friday
night still having not allowed three or more runs in an inning
since Aug. 29, a streak that encompasses a span of 136 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Andy Pettitte, who allowed one unearned run in 7 1/3
innings, nor Wells were involved in the decision. Pettitte
surrendered just three hits in the first seven innings, walked none
and faced just two batters over the minimum. But Craig Grebeck
banged a lead-off double in the eighth after fighting off a couple
of tough pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Dewayne Wise ran for Grebeck, and when Alberto Castillo bunted
toward the mound, Wise charged toward third base. Pettitte came off
the mound quickly and appeared to have a good chance at nailing
Wise at third, but he whipped the throw wide, so far to the second
base side of the bag that the third baseman Scott Brosius never
moved. Wise scored the game's first run and Castillo moved to
second on Pettitte's error.
</P>
<P>
   As Chuck Knoblauch stepped in to bat with one out in the eighth,
Jeter turned to a boy in the second row of the stands near the
Yankees' on-deck circle and chatted, perhaps checking with the
youngster to see whether he should swing at the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter got ahead in the count three balls and no strikes, and
with the count 3-1, he swung hard and smashed the pitch to
straightaway center. The ball disappeared beyond the 408-foot sign,
the fans exploded and Wells grimaced.
</P>
<P>
   The old school rules regarding decorum among competitors will
never apply to Wells, who rarely passes on an easy chance for
conversation. The Yankees catcher Jorge Posada jogged out to left
field to stretch before Thursday night's game and at first, he
tried to keep his distance from Wells, with whom he shared a
perfect game at the Stadium in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lying on his back and stretching, Wells shouted something to
Posada, and Posada burst out laughing, and they continued to
banter. Wells began throwing in a part of the outfield usually
inhabited by the Yankees pitcher and catcher.
</P>
<P>
   When Pettitte marched past, he glanced at Wells before moving on
sternly to the bullpen. Pettitte would have been a perfect hall
monitor in high school, completely trustworthy. Wells assuredly was
a hall monitor's worst nightmare at San Diego's Point Loma High.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells is as serious about competing as Pettitte is. When he
embraces a challenge, Wells challenges hitters, pounding them with
fastballs, spinning his curveball for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To challenge him makes him a better pitcher,'' Torre said
before the game. ``I hope we beat his brains in, but that doesn't
diminish the respect I have for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
